<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHENS GIVES BRUINS A SAFETY NET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At first glance, Jason Stephens appears an
unlikely answer to UCLA's most pressing problem. He lacks the size
and experience to fill the ever-expanding hole at strong safety
alongside All-American Larry Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Whitfield, Tod McBride and DuVal Hicks _ all tried and
faltered. Either they were improperly aligned or they missed
tackles or they blew coverages. It was so bad against Oregon that
Atkins played both positions at the same time, which meant he
played neither.
</P>
<P>
   One option remained. A 190-pound redshirt freshman from
Redlands, Stephens is wide-eyed and lanky. In his first career
start, against Cal, he had eight tackles and a sack. He provided
ample run support. He was properly aligned. He did not blow
coverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the strong safety, you have to force the run,'' Stephens
said. ``That was the No. 1 thing I emphasized. I don't have the
size, so I want to be tough. Once I got my first tackle (on Cal's
opening possession), I got my groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Can he keep it up? The Bruins are optimistic; Stephens has
superb instincts and loads of athletic ability. But they are
cautious, as well, because he had a chance in training camp and was
outplayed by Whitfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``All last year I was thinking I'd be starting at free safety as
a redshirt freshman,'' he said. ``It got to the point that I felt
myself timid during spring with (first-year defensive coordinator)
Nick Aliotti and the changes and fighting for the position. It
discouraged me a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, after learning the system and switching from
free to strong safety, he's a different player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing with more confidence,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
``He's learning through experience to do things better. When he was
given the opportunity, he didn't take advantage of it. He didn't
prove to be better than the others. But it got to the point we
said, `We'll give you a chance.' And he has responded very well.''
</P>
<P>
   More BCS: UCLA's No. 1 ranking in the Bowl Championship Series
poll is based, in part, on its strength-of-schedule. UCLA's six
opponents have a combined winning percentage of 62.7, while Ohio
State's seven opponents have a winning percentage of 54.
</P>
<P>
   Each time Miami, Texas and Houston win, it helps the Bruins. And
in case you haven't noticed, the Hurricanes upset West Virginia
last week and are 4-2, while the Longhorns have won four in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford stat of the week: The Cardinal is one of two teams in
Pacific-10 history to allow at least 30 points in seven consecutive
games. Oregon, in 1986, is the other.
</P>
<P>
   Short and sweet: With a plethora of minor injuries, Toledo ended
Tuesday's practice 15 minutes early. The Bruins will practice in
helmets and shoulder pads today and forgo their full-contact work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do alignments and assignments,'' Toledo said. ``With
daylight (standard) time, it's getting cold and late. I don't want
to beat them up. We need to teach.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the depleted practice roster, only one regular, tailback
DeShaun Foster, won't play Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers: The Bruins have excelled in two of the most
important categories: They lead the Pac-10 in turnover margin
(plus-1.5), and they have scored on 85 percent of their red zone
opportunities (inside the 20-yard line).
</P>
<P>
   Top 10: Toledo is one of 10 finalists for the Football Writers
Association Coach of the Year Award.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Toledo are: Missouri's Larry Smith, Oregon's Mike
Bellotti, Arizona's Dick Tomey, Tennessee's Phil Fulmer, Arkansas'
Houston Nutt, Wisconsin's Barry Alvarez, Kansas State's Bill
Snyder, Tulane's Tommy Bowden and Georgia Tech's George O'Leary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
