<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Houston won the bathing-suit competition.
</P>
<P>
   Everything in its well-packaged NFL expansion proposal was in
the right place, and the figures were quite impressive.
</P>
<P>
   But Los Angeles group No. 1 _ the New Coliseum Ventures _ won
the talent competition. Despite completely revamping its proposed
stadium design just weeks ago, the group managed to wheel in a
scale model of its stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The model came complete with miniature cars in the parking lot
and miniature people in the grandstands. The group also cleverly
left out the miniature muggers lurking in the shrubs outside.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Los Angeles group No. 2 _ Michael Ovitz's Hollywood
stars _ won the evening-gown competition. Have we mentioned Sharon
Stone is a partner in this group? No further explanation required.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite the impressive day Tuesday at the NFL meetings, but
the search for a leading candidate to become the NFL's 32nd team
was futile.
</P>
<P>
   It merely was a beauty contest. It was three contestants dressed
to the nines, searching for NFL team No. 32 and looking out for No.
1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not any different from Houston,'' Coliseum leader Ed
Roski pronounced.
</P>
<P>
   Responded Houston's Steve Patterson, a partner in Bob McNair's
group: ``Do they have signed documents?''
</P>
<P>
   They don't. Then there was Ovitz, all but demanding a quick
decision from NFL owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not be here next year,'' Ovitz said. ``We cannot sit
on this project for three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, the marketing genius, even tried to pull heartstrings,
apparently unaware that many NFL owners have been accused of not
having them.
</P>
<P>
   ``My 11-year-old son never has watched an NFL game in Los
Angeles,'' Ovitz said, all but wiping a tear from his cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone postured. Everyone posed. And at the end of the day,
NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue even played the role of master of
ceremonies, all but telling the potential NFL owners, ``You're all
winners in my book.''
</P>
<P>
   But nobody handed out the latest NFL crown or even told the NFL
hopefuls when they might expect an expansion decision from the
judges. Today? Next month? At the Super Bowl meetings in January?
At the NFL meetings next March?
</P>
<P>
   The owners simply sat there in the hotel ballroom, watched the
three presentations and walked away doing more sidestepping than
Charles Durning in The Best Little Whorehouse In Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh Steelers owner Dan Rooney: ``I was impressed with
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver Broncos owner Pat Bowlen: ``They all look good.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Vikings owner B.J. ``Red'' McCombs: ``Houston was
fantastic but I wouldn't say anyone was better than the other.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what it would take for one of these three potential
NFL groups to distinguish itself, Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones
actually said the following: ``That's the answer. And I don't know
the answer. Hopefully, it will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh? If it was an answer to Houston's NFL dreams you were
looking for, you had to look hard. But finally, Buffalo Bills owner
Ralph Wilson stripped this beauty contest down to what it's really
all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of money,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course. The owners spent most of Tuesday playing one group
off the next and off the next. And they will continue to do so
until the price for expansion is right and pretenders fall out of
the contest like so many Miss South Dakotas.
</P>
<P>
   It is the reason a decision on expansion did not come Tuesday
and probably won't for a long while. The longer owners can force
these contestants to keep posing and primping for the judges _ and
keep pulling promises from their cities' leadership _ the more
likely the eventual expansion fee will keep rising.
</P>
<P>
   Had owners agreed Tuesday that an expansion group distinguished
itself, that there was a clear leader in the race, they might have
cost themselves about $100 million. The expansion price to play the
game would have been locked at about $350 million to $375 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the longer all three candidates look good, the longer they
strut and posture and politic, the more likely they will keep
digging deeper and doing more. Eventually, the expansion fee could
reach $400 million or even $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Only then will a decision be made and an expansion crown handed
out. Clearly, most NFL owners want Los Angeles to get the eventual
expansion team, but they wouldn't mind if Houston won or if another
team landed in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Like Patterson said, ``Los Angeles is Los Angeles, but we're not
exactly Dime Box or even Old Dime Box.''
</P>
<P>
   And this isn't a penny-ante game. Tuesday's shows were
impressive, but they were simply cosmetic. All the Houston group
can do is keep smiling, keep wooing the judges with high-dollar
promises, keep waiting, keep playing the game. And keep their
checkbooks open.
</P>
</TEXT>
