   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RIGHTS (Beijing) _ Only weeks after signing a global
covenant calling for freedom of speech and assembly, China has
taken new steps to suppress political organizations and debate. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-U.N. (United Nations) _ AIDS is cutting the life expectancy
in many African countries and will effectively reduce their
populations, according to a new U.N. report. By Youssef M. Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-POLITICS (Toronto) _ Profile of Jean Chretien: Whether it
is candor, or insensitivity, Chretien's five years in office have
been marked by a directness uncommon among world leaders. At a time
of obtuse diplomacy and executive legalisms, he can be outspoken
and blunt to a degree that frightens and frustrates his handlers.
By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-REGULATORS (Undated) _ As fast as the gambling business
has spread across the country, a fast-spinning revolving door has
also developed, creating a world in which a state senator with no
casino experience has in an instant become president of a major
casino, a law enforcement official from a state attorney general's
office has gone on to become chief executive officer of the
nation's most profitable casino, and where top gaming officials
from one state after another have resigned to pursue lucrative
casino careers. By Brett Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV.: Photo [NYT15) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHUTTLE-NOSTALGIA (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ There must be
something here that invigorates the likes of John Glenn and T.J.
O'Malley. Thomas J. O'Malley, known to missile colleagues as T.J.,
was the man who on the morning of Feb. 20, 1962, pressed the black
button to start the Atlas booster's engines and send Glenn on his
way in a Mercury capsule to be the first American to orbit the
planet. He is 83 now, still full of sass and gruff charm, and
brimming with stories of the old days. Like O'Malley, many of those
who shared the anxiety, thrill and glory of the first Glenn flight
in 1962 are gathering here again to sip at the fountain of their
youth. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT19) has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT grpahics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-GAYS (Ft. Collins) _ Fort Collins, which just experienced
the death of openly gay college student Matthew Shepard, is about
to vote on a municipal hate crimes law that was placed on the
ballot before Shepard's death. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT17,18) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
