   NY-VALLONE-PROFILE (New York) _ A profile of Peter Vallone,
speaker of the N.Y. City Council and the Democratic challenger to
Gov. George Pataki. By Abby Goodnough.
</P>
<P>
   EDUC-GRENADA-MEDSCHOOL (True Blue, Grenada) _ Seen from the
campus here, the Caribbean Sea appears so serene and breathtakingly
beautiful that it may be hard to remember that just 15 years ago
this month the United States fought a sort of war to save St.
George's University. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT grpahics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MD-GOV-RACE (Bethesda, Md.) _ By most ordinary reckoning, Parris
Glendening should be a shoo-in as he seeks re-election as governor
of Maryland. He is a moderate-to-liberal Democrat in one of the
nation's most reliably Democratic states. But Glendening is in the
race of his life, an election that seems even closer than the one
in 1994, when he won by fewer than 6,000 votes, or four-tenths of 1
percent, over the Republican candidate, Ellen Sauerbrey, who is his
opponent again this year. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   VOTER-ISSUES (Moreno Valley, Calif.) _ Four years ago, people
interviewed in this bedroom community of stucco houses, strip malls
and independent-minded voters expressed deep disappointment with
President Clinton and complained vehemently about declining wages,
rising taxes and worsening crime. Two years ago, the bitterness
about Clinton had receded as voters raised concerns about
Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole and said his party was too
extreme. Now, dozens of random interviews on the eve of another
election show that the outlook of voters here had shifted yet
again: They do not seem exercised about anything. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos [NYT11,12,13) have been sent to NYT photo
clients.)
