</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-BRONCOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL COLUMN: BRONCOS TALK OF A PERFECT SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There is an aura enveloping the Denver
Broncos, an invincibility, a feeling that this Bronco season could
be as special as last year's. Maybe even more so.
</P>
<P>
   Denver toppled Jacksonville, 37-24, on Sunday afternoon at Mile
High Stadium, and that made the Broncos 7-0. They saw one of their
own, Jason Elam, boot a record-tying 63-yard field goal, and
another, Terrell Davis, reach 1,000 yards rushing in his seventh
game, matching more league history. The quarterback, John Elway,
made his 7,000th pass attempt, a mark reached previously by only
Dan Marino. The team won its 20th consecutive regular-season home
game.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, Mike Shanahan, is keeping his players hungry and
focused, and he is staying a step ahead of the National Football
League coaching curve.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Pat Bowlen, here among his peers at the NFL's annual
fall meeting, is feeling good. He is unmistakably noticed now. So
is his team.
</P>
<P>
   How about an unbeaten regular season? How about 16-0?
</P>
<P>
   ``People are talking about that, but it's all but impossible,''
Bowlen said of his team's chances of joining the 1972 Miami
Dolphins, who went 14-0, as the NFL's only unbeaten team. ``What I
worry about is being undefeated in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Really, though, he does not look worried at all. Neither do his
defending Super Bowl champions.
</P>
<P>
   The team has this look we have seen before. That swagger, that
look-you-in-the-eye persona. That feeling of confidence that the
49er teams with Joe Montana used to always exhibit, or the strut of
those Cowboy Super Bowl teams. The old Halas Bears, the old Jim
Brown Browns. Those scary teams that made opponents feel as if they
were at a disadvantage well before kickoff. Teams that made others
feel as if they were battling history and destiny as much as the
present.
</P>
<P>
   We know that in Davis, the Broncos have a special running back.
If he maintains his current pace, he will finish with 2,288 rushing
yards this season, an NFL record. We know that Elway is Elway. That
the Denver defense can rush the passer and stop the run and make
enough plays to keep the team's big-play offense front and center.
We know that Shanahan mixes his play-calling and he attacks
weaknesses as well as any coach today. We know that with
special-team players such as Vaughn Hebron, the Broncos can beat
you there, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings are also 7-0. But what separates Denver
from most teams, maybe even the Vikings, is its offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   This is the team's wheel in the middle of the wheel. This is the
juice. The glue. The pedal. The engine and the energy.
</P>
<P>
   Elway says about this Denver line, about this offense, ``It's
nice to know that we can pretty much do whatever we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   This line _ with Tony Jones at left tackle, Mark Schlereth at
left guard, Tom Nalen at center, Dan Neil at right guard and Harry
Swayne at right tackle _ is big and mobile. It can smack you in the
face and pull and sweep and trick. It is a treat to watch.
</P>
<P>
   This group excels at setting up cut-back running lanes, and it
is as adept at protecting Elway. It seems to gain strength as the
game goes along.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not even the same group that knocked the Green Bay
Packers backward in Super Bowl XXXII. Left tackle Gary Zimmerman
retired after last season. Right guard Brian Habib left as a free
agent for Seattle. Actually, entering this season, the offensive
line was the team's biggest question. It was supposed to be the
weak link that prevented Denver from being a serious contender to
repeat as champions.
</P>
<P>
   This is when you know you have a special team: When your
supposed weak link becomes your strength.
</P>
<P>
   This line is coached by Alex Gibbs, with Barney Chavous as an
assistant. Gibbs, 57, is in his fourth year in Denver and his 15th
in the NFL as a coach. He is a crusty fellow, a guy who is
respected throughout the league and admired by most in the Broncos'
organization. The guy is a guru at offensive line play. He knows
when to push a player and when to embrace him. He knows that
football is won in line play and makes sure that the Broncos'
offensive linemen understand that, too.
</P>
<P>
   All of the owners here at the league meetings congratulated
Bowlen months ago. They slapped him on the back and told him how
great he was and how great his team was. Now they all chase him and
his team.
</P>
<P>
   In a very short time, the Broncos have raced to the head of the
class, and they are steamrolling toward more glory. They are in a
tussle at home, hoping that financing to help build a new stadium
will be approved, but who believes that ballistic Broncos fans
won't comply, that they would let their beloved team leave? Unheard
of. They have Cincinnati and San Diego next, and then come to
Kansas City for a Monday night game against the Chiefs. Later they
play at the Giants (Dec. 13) and at Miami (Dec. 21).
</P>
<P>
   The Miami game will be intriguing if the Broncos are unbeaten
then, because it was Miami that toppled the 12-0 Bears in 1985 in
Miami. Denver will be 15-0 if it hasn't lost by the time it leaves
Miami. Unbeaten? Is it possible?
</P>
<P>
   ``We won the Super Bowl, the first time in four tries,'' Bowlen
said. ``The thing about that is, making the playoffs or winning the
AFC championship is not good enough anymore. You set out at the
beginning to win that Super Bowl again. However you win it,
unbeaten or with losses, does not matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure it does to men and teams of style. Sure it does to history.
It is that kind of season being built in Denver. A Super Bowl
victory and then 7-0. A team and owner with a big, bright balloon
that each franchise wants to pop. A team laying it on the line.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line. Not a bad place, at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 0012EST &QL; 
