<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0426 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-D'AMATO-370     10-28 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-D'AMATO-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO ADMITS HE MISSED VOTES DURING '80 SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION WARNING: The following story is also being transmitted
with an ``a'' category code) 
 (bl) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last 27 days, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., has hammered
at a single theme, attacking his Democratic challenger, Rep.
Charles Schumer, for skipping votes in the House to tend to his
Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You haven't been there to vote,'' D'Amato scolded Schumer in a
debate Saturday. ``Chuck Schumer always puts politics over
people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, a week before the election, the senator's campaign
acknowledged that when he was the vice chairman of the Nassau
County Board of Supervisors, D'Amato had done much the same thing
when he first ran for the Senate, in 1980. The board held six
meetings during that fall election season, and D'Amato, then the
presiding supervisor of Hempstead Town, was absent for five of
them. County records show that he stopped attending board meetings
altogether after Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   The information about D'Amato's voting record was released
because the Schumer campaign had aggressively and enthusiastically
circulated minutes of the board meetings to newspapers and
television stations Tuesday in an attempt to set the tone for the
final week of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The D'Amato campaign countered that D'Amato's attendance at
county board meetings almost 20 years ago was peripheral to this
contest. ``I suppose he also missed a few days of school in
elementary school,'' said his spokesman, Robert Bellafiore.
</P>
<P>
   But in this case, the disclosure about D'Amato's lax attendance
record in 1980 would appear to go directly to the heart of each
candidate's campaign: D'Amato's criticism of Schumer's absences
this year, and Schumer's attacks on D'Amato's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, it would appear to give Schumer, who until
last week seemed beleaguered by D'Amato's attacks, ammunition to
counter the charges that D'Amato has made the central part of his
campaign. Beyond that, Schumer's aides, said the disclosure
bolstered Schumer's attempt to portray D'Amato as hypocritical.
</P>
<P>
   It also could mean that D'Amato, who spent last week responding
to criticism that he used an offensive Yiddish expression to
describe Schumer and then denied having done it, may now have to
spend the next few days discussing his own attendance record.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   D'Amato was asked about the disclosure as he traveled across the
state with Gov. George Pataki after Schumer's aides tipped off
reporters about the information and after word had spread that The
Village Voice had posted an article on D'Amato's attendance on its
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Although political campaigns, particularly ones as well financed
as D'Amato's, typically examine the background of their own
candidate to anticipate any attack, the senator and his aides
seemed unprepared for this. On the very day that the information
surfaced, D'Amato released a new television advertisement attacking
Schumer's attendance record, this one illustrated with a desk
covered with cobwebs.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, who grew slightly testy as he responded to questions
about the subject throughout the day, accused Schumer of raising
the issue to divert attention from his own attendance record in
Congress. Schumer had an attendance record of about 77 percent this
year, and has a career attendance record of 92 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 18 years, I've delivered for the people of New York,''
D'Amato told reporters as his chartered plane flew from Rochester
to Niagara. ``I've performed my duties, day in and day out. Whether
it is campaign time or not. I think what we find is that Schumer is
engaged in a desperate attempt to divert attention from his failed
record for the last two sessions, the last two years of the
Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in Buffalo, when asked by a television reporter to
elaborate on the differences between his missed votes and Schumer's
absences, D'Amato snapped: ``I wasn't in the Congress, son.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's campaign seized gleefully on the incident. ``Al
D'Amato lives in a glass house and for the past six weeks he's been
throwing stones,'' said Howard Wolfson, the Schumer campaign
spokesman. ``Today, Al D'Amato's glass house shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   It also seems likely that Schumer's campaign will quickly
spotlight these developments in a television advertisement.
Tuesday, one of Schumer's advisers easily ticked off examples in
which D'Amato had appeared before the cameras discussing how
important it was for legislators to tend to their governmental
duties before their political interests _ the kind of clip that
might lend itself to an advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, it now seems increasingly likely that this
campaign, no matter what the outcome, is going to be remembered for
the fighting over attendance records.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer campaign manager Josh Isay said the congressman's
organization _ which had at first appeared flummoxed in trying to
respond to D'Amato's attacks _ has been actively investigating
D'Amato's attendance record for some time, but declined further
comment. He credited The Village Voice with being the first to
report the disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato began using the attendance issue against Schumer in a
television advertisement Oct. 1, and has not dropped it since. The
senator's advisers have looked at the missed-votes issue as perhaps
the key to the senator's re-election, and returned to the theme,
virtually to the exclusion of all others, through the last month.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato's advisers said that their polls had showed that the
attacks were working. However, a series of recent public polls,
including a New York Times/CBS News poll, have shown the race in a
dead heat, and suggested that the issue had not yet taken hold. The
latest Times/CBS News poll, conducted Oct. 21 through Oct. 25,
found that most respondents considered the attacks to be politics
as usual. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 0018EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0428 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     10-28 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOARING MARKET COULD PRICE M'S OUT OF CONTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Citizens of Marinerville did not need Mike Piazza and
the Mets to tell them they're out of luck when it comes to keeping
up with the Joneses, which in baseball are the Yankees, Orioles,
Atlanta and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   These are baseball's heaviest hitters _ teams willing to cough
up more than $60 million in annual payroll or commit huge contracts
to single superstars.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have accomplished that by bequeathing $91 million over
seven years to Piazza, who is going to save the Mets in the box
score and at the box office, or else.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the Piazza deal is being heralded as a prudent
business decision. The Mets are not just competing against the
National League East for a playoff berth. They also have to worry
about competition from that nice little team in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   And now it looks likely that the Piazza deal will also help
dissolve the relationship between the Yankees and their center
fielder, Bernie Williams, whose heavy-hitting agent, Scott Boras,
can smell blood.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have accomplished the most significant thing a pro
sports franchise can do in these days of spectacular risk and
reward: they have altered the market. They have made every single
baseball club in the land look around, look at its own roster and
wonder how the heck they are going to make this puppy work.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners should be among the top head scratchers now, since
they are still grappling with how to sustain the expectation of
fielding a World Series contender with a middle-class budget.
</P>
<P>
   As one Mariner player recently told me, the M's give the
appearance of ``wanting to be like the Yankees, but they act like
the Pittsburgh Pirates.'' This is a bit of an exaggeration since
the M's well exceeded the Pirates' payroll, and Ken Griffey Jr. at
$8.5 million a year did once sit on top of baseball's salary
mountain. But he makes his point: the M's aren't wheeling and
dealing at any cost for a ring.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, it did not take ``Piazza money'' to show Marinerville
citizens that the M's are not willing or able to jump whenever the
free-agent market salary jumps.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1997, when Randy Johnson was all better from
back surgery and throwing smoke again, the Mariners got their dose
of smelling salts from Ted Turner's juggernaut when Greg Maddux
signed a deal worth $11 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, everyone understood what was coming for Johnson
and the M's. Even before the infamous November 1997 announcement
that there would be no deal for Johnson, the handwriting was on the
wall. The M's were not going to pay ``Maddux money'' to their
34-year-old, franchise-saving pitcher, no matter how great a draw,
no matter how much Johnson all but guaranteed 18 or 20 wins a
season.
</P>
<P>
   This may all seem like ancient history now, but there is a point
to bringing it up again. If ``Maddux money'' killed the Mariners'
resolve to re-sign Johnson (or made him unwilling to sign), does
``Piazza money'' destroy the Mariners' willingness or ability to
re-sign both Alex Rodriguez and Ken Griffey Jr., whose current
contracts expire after the 2000 season?
</P>
<P>
   Not many teams could stomach locking 40 percent of their payroll
in two players, even two future Hall of Famers. So who would be
surprised if the M's have a very tough time resolving this issue,
especially since their Japanese-led consortium of owners is a hard
sell.
</P>
<P>
   This is a bittersweet dilemma, trying to find a way to keep two
of the game's most gifted and attractive young stars and still
field a competitive team in this day of the $13 million man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intent is to keep both of them here,'' Lee Pelekoudas, the
M's vice president of baseball operations, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't always point to one signing and say that is now the
market. There's always an odd signing, although it's hard to tell
if this $13 million-a-year-deal (with Piazza) is an aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   These are harsh times in pro sports. The greater the financial
glory for the players, the greater the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Fans can't begin to account for a market that all but demands
the dismantling of good teams, the separation of superlative
talent. And it's not much easier for club presidents or general
managers.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, before the Mariners are forced to tackle this
franchise-defining decision on Griffey and Rodriguez, they will no
doubt find the Johnson debacle staring them in the face.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers, with their deep pockets and will to succeed,
will make a run at Johnson. Texas will try to lure the Big Unit to
an American League club that already promises to be a contender. If
they are successful, the Rangers will no doubt have a fantastic
chance of haunting the Mariners for all of 1999, at least.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to commend the Rangers if they get him because it
means they are committed to winning,'' Rodriguez said Tuesday from
his home in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Johnson is the guy we should go after. He's the No. 1
guy out there. Say what you want about Randy, he's going to win. We
have a small window of opportunity. We're not the youngest team,
but we have a $400 million stadium, and we are drawing big crowds.
It's a shame. A guy like that should play the rest of his career
here.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, heaven forbid, we all might be saying the same thing
about our A-Rod.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 0019EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
