A0431 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-IRWIN-NYT &LR;      10-28 0259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-IRWIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM IRWIN, 91, PIANIST AND CONDUCTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ky., N.Y., Ill.)   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William C.K. Irwin, a pianist and conductor, died
Oct. 23 at the Jewish Home and Hospital for the Aged in Manhattan.
He was 91 and had lived for many years on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin spent much of his career in musical theater. He was
introduced to George Gershwin by composer Vernon Duke in the 1920s
and was a regular dinner guest at Gershwin's Manhattan apartment,
where he would sit in on impromptu piano improvisations with
Gershwin and pianist Oscar Levant.
</P>
<P>
   Gershwin introduced Irwin to Irving Berlin, starting a musical
relationship that lasted six years. Irwin worked alongside Berlin,
writing melodies as they were composed, and often had to hurry over
to Berlin's studio in the middle of the night to write down a new
tune that had popped into the composer's head.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s Irwin was music director for the national tours of
``Oklahoma!,'' ``South Pacific'' and ``The King and I.'' He became
choral director for Radio City Music Hall in the 1960s and later
was the staff composer and musical director for the music hall. He
retired in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Born in San Francisco, Irwin grew up in Louisville, Ky. As a
teen-ager, he studied piano in Chicago with the composer Percy
Grainger and then moved to New York to continue his studies at the
Manhattan School of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin's wife, Helen, died in 1984. He is survived by a son,
Dean, a producer for ABC News.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 0020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHONE-FEE-NYT &LR;      10-28 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-FEE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE FEE QUIRK BENEFITS NEW PROVIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As new local phone companies have taken on old communications
giants, some of the upstarts have come to rely on a quirk of
negotiation and technology that has grown into a cash cow. It goes
by the name of reciprocal compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Reciprocal compensation, which is meant to make up for some of
the new carriers' expenses, is costing the regional Bell companies
and GTE Corp. hundreds of millions of dollars a year, so it is not
surprising that they think it is little more than an unfair
loophole. By the end of this week, the Federal Communications
Commission will almost certainly begin heading down a regulatory
road that could mean the cash cow's demise.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are regulatory jurisdiction over the Internet and the
ways in which companies will be allowed to profit from it. In the
battle over reciprocal compensation, old phone companies, new phone
companies and regulators have entered a new stage in figuring out
the structure of a communications industry based on data, rather
than voice conversations.
</P>
<P>
   When new local phone companies began to emerge a few years ago,
they negotiated deals with the incumbents to determine how to share
costs for local calls. When a customer using Acme Phone Co., for
instance, calls someone who uses Bell Atlantic, Acme pays Bell
Atlantic a small fee to compensate Bell Atlantic for carrying its
end of the call, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   In those negotiations, the incumbents often held out for higher
rates, up to eight-tenths of a cent a minute, according to people
close to the commission. The incumbents thought that higher rates
would hurt the new carriers because, naturally, there would be
proportionally more traffic flowing from the new carriers' small
customer bases to the incumbents' big rosters of customers than the
other way around.
</P>
<P>
   But the new companies outsmarted the giants. They began to focus
sales efforts on Internet service providers, with their thousands
of phone lines. The beauty of that strategy is that phone calls for
Internet providers are almost entirely incoming. At the same time,
most of the people making the calls use the incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   One result is that the Bells and GTE are on track to pay more
than $500 million in reciprocal compensation to new local phone
companies this year. Another result is that for the upstarts as a
group, the fees provide 26 percent of their earnings before
interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization, a benchmark for
small companies, according to Daniel Reingold, a Merrill Lynch
analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The incumbents say they should not have to pay the fees for
Internet calls, because calls to cyberspace are long distance, not
local. Twenty-three states have disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   But the FCC has not given concrete guidance on that question,
leading to a patchwork of reactions. BellSouth, for instance, is
refusing to pay the fees for Internet calls and is fighting in
court while Bell Atlantic is paying. SBC Communications is paying
into an escrow account in California while the question remains
unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a tariff filing from GTE for a high-speed data service,
digital subscriber lines, is forcing the issue. If the FCC, which
generally has jurisdiction only over interstate matters, approves
GTE's prices, it could be interpreted to have affirmed that
Internet communications are inherently long distance. And
long-distance communications are not eligible for reciprocal
compensation. Such confusion is almost sure to lead to more
explicit guidance from the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond all this, most of the contracts between new and old phone
companies are to expire over the next two years anyway, prompting
new negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   That could leave the commission some wiggle room. It could, for
instance, support the current contracts but try to force down
future fees.
</P>
<P>
   The haggling and debate continued at the commission yesterday,
with some regulators hoping to lower the fees while not wounding
the new carriers. Some sort of official action is expected by this
weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
