<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STANFORD-LEONARD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEONARD SITS OUT SEASON ON THE FARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a week Matt Leonard wouldn't eat. Couldn't eat. He lost 12
pounds and vomited until his stomach muscles strained and ached.
Trainers thought it was a virus, but a week of testing offered no
scientific conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   It was homesickness and as homesickness goes, this was
insufferable. Intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   And it came during two-a-day football workouts at Stanford but
happened much more than twice a day. Leonard had no family near, no
friends at Stanford and no cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not fully back as far as strength is concerned,''
Leonard said. ``I was really, really homesick. But I never thought
about leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, a 6-foot-4, 290-pound defensive end, was the Daily
News' Defensive Player of the Year at Palmdale High last fall. He
was also expected to push for a starting spot at some point this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Then he took ill. Violently ill. And that, more than being a
freshman, has kept Leonard out of the Pacific-10 trenches this
season.
</P>
<P>
   If Leonard was healthy in training camp, he would be playing
this week against No. 2 UCLA at the Rose Bowl on Saturday. Instead,
he'll be inactive as he finishes up his redshirt season.
</P>
<P>
   ``All things being equal, he would have had a chance to do a
lot,'' Stanford defensive-ends coach Phil Zacharias said. ``It was
tough for him. The one thing about going somewhere new is you don't
know anybody, and he ran into that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be a good player. He was very raw in terms of
what we do, but he's learning, just like every young player we've
got.''
</P>
<P>
   As it's worked out, redshirting this year hasn't been all
terrible for Leonard. He admits to having the excitement of game
day muffled and feeling too far removed from the team when the
Cardinal takes road trips.
</P>
<P>
   But other sides exist. While at Palmdale, Leonard dominated
opposing offenses with sheer speed and athleticism. Then he started
practicing against experienced offensive linemen at Stanford and
wondered how the heck he ever made a play at Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high school I got by because I was bigger and stronger than
anyone else, but here you're going on technique more than anything,
and I'm just learning that,'' Leonard said. ``I had no technique,
no nothing.... This year I was not mentally prepared to play. It
was like a year of prep school.''
</P>
<P>
   And Leonard isn't just talking about the ABCs of using his hands
to fend off blockers or reading gap assignments. Leonard is also
speaking of Stanford's academics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to all the lectures and it seems like I have a good grasp
on what's going on,'' said Leonard, who hasn't declared a major.
``Then I get the exams and see the (instructors' comments) and it's
like, `Say what?' `Where did this come from.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even through the sickness that zapped his strength and his
admitted unpreparedness, injuries to Stanford's defensive line
forced the coaching staff to contemplate playing Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   But during the past few weeks, when the Cardinal defensive line
was most desperate for healthy bodies, the overwhelming variable in
not playing Leonard was Stanford's standing. The Cardinal is 1-6,
0-4 in the Pacific-10, and going nowhere but to spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You only have four games left so you'd have to be in a train
wreck to suit somebody up who's redshirting, and then you might
forfeit the game instead,'' Stanford defensive coordinator Bill
Harris said jokingly. ``You don't know how much he could have
helped, but the way we've played he couldn't hurt. He seems to have
a lot more athleticism than what we usually get here. I'll be
looking for him in the spring.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
