u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-PANTON-595&AMP;ADD-N     10-28 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PANTON-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERNER PANTON, 72, DANISH DESIGNER AND ARCHITECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Verner Panton, the Danish industrial designer and architect
known for his radical molded-plastic chairs, op-art-inspired
textiles and lighting, died at his home in Copenhagen, Denmark, on
Sept. 5. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, according to his office in Basel,
Switzerland, where he also had a residence.
</P>
<P>
   Panton was in the forefront of postwar European and American
designers who were exploring new materials and their potential for
mass production.
</P>
<P>
   Like Charles and Ray Eames and Eero Saarinen before him, Panton
focused on the marriage between organic form and new technologies,
adding his own imaginative twist, which made his designs pop icons
of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Verner Panton was born on Feb. 13, 1926, in Gamtofte, Denmark.
He studied at the Odense Technical School and at the Royal Danish
Academy of Fine Arts in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   From 1950 to 1952, Panton worked for Arne Jacobsen, Denmark's
premier designer, and in 1955 he established his own architecture
and design office, first in Denmark and later in Binningen,
Switzerland, where he moved in 1963. In 1964, he married Marianne
Pherson, who continues to work in his design studio.
</P>
<P>
   Panton's most significant design contribution was his 1960s
curved and cantilevered plastic stacking side chair, also known as
the Panton chair. It is credited with being the first single-piece
molded plastic chair to succeed in production.
</P>
<P>
   Panton prepared for the design by visiting factories that made
crash helmets and plastic buckets. For at least seven years he
could not find a manufacturer able or willing to take it on.
Finally, in 1967, it went into production in Switzerland at the
Vitra factory, where it is still being made.
</P>
<P>
   The sinuous Panton chair was quickly lauded as a breakthrough
and was acquired by the most important design collections,
including the one at the Museum of Modern Art in New York in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the first to give form to the aspirations of a
whole generation that had some ideas about a new kind of living and
a new kind of society,'' said Terence Riley, chief curator of the
department of architecture and design at the Museum of Modern Art.
``Verner was there before anyone else and put his personal stamp on
that vision.''
</P>
<P>
   With designs like a 1963 inflatable plastic stool, a wire-frame
cone chair with pivot joint in place of legs, and op-art-patterned
rugs, Panton's work had more in common with that of leading Italian
designers than with the designs of Scandinavians who were working
in fine, hand-crafted wood.
</P>
<P>
   Not all his experiments were conducted on a small scale. In
1960, he designed two buildings, called the Cardboard House and the
Plastic House.
</P>
<P>
   With a philosophy that revolution was, or ought to be, a sensory
experience, Panton wielded color with boldness, from the glossy
stacking side chair that came in violet, turquoise, red, orange,
beige, black and white to the orange and red cafeteria he designed
for Der Spiegel magazine (1969).
</P>
<P>
   His exhibition installations were usually intended to startle.
For the 1968 Cologne Furniture Fair, he created a surreal interior
with the images of gigantic lips, feet, arms, hands, eyes and ears
printed on textile walls stretched like a tent, and colorful rubber
balls covered in toweling tossed onto the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``By experimenting with lighting, colors, textiles and
furniture, and utilizing the latest technologies, I try to show new
ways to encourage people to use their fantasy and make their
surroundings more exciting,'' he once told an interviewer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Panton's furniture, lighting and textile designs are in many
important design collections, including those of the Metropolitan
Museum of Art, the Georges Pompidou Center in Paris, the Denver
Museum of Art, and the Industrial Art Museum in Copenhagen.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, he was overseeing a retrospective of
his work at the Trapholt Museum in Kolding, Denmark. In addition to
his wife, Panton is survived by his daughter, Carin von Halem of
Basel, and his brother, Ole Panton of Charlottenlund, Denmark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
