<SLUG> BC-LA-NFL-BIDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. TEAMS MAKE PLAYS FOR NFL SLOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``a'' national news file.) 
BY ERIC NOLAND  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The door vibrated with the bass track as NFL
owners inside the hotel conference room took an aerial video tour,
via computer animation, of a mythical opening day at an equally
mythical football stadium in L.A.'s industrial suburb of Carson.
</P>
<P>
   And Michael Ovitz, according to observers, pitched his plan with
all the enthusiasm of one of those ``Saturday Night Live''
cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   When a group championing a renovated Los Angeles Memorial
Coliseum had the stage, an enormous scale model commanded the room,
Charlton Heston narrated the video and developer Edward Roski Jr.
exhibited images of concrete going up for the Staples Center.
(Implied message: I'm not all talk; I can get it built.)
</P>
<P>
   After viewing these presentations _ and a third by a group from
Houston _ at their fall meeting Tuesday, several NFL owners said
they were impressed with everything they saw.
</P>
<P>
   About all that's left, they added, is fleshing out a few of the
details behind the L.A. gleam _ and deciding exactly when they will
choose their 32nd franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they answered a lot of questions,'' Pittsburgh
Steelers President Dan Rooney said at the conclusion of three
one-hour programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Houston showed they have everything going. As they
said, they have all their ducks in the water. I thought L.A. showed
great designs for both stadiums. They talked about the benefits of
the different locations; they all said they had it financed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All the presentations were very focused and had a lot of
energy,'' added owner Jerry Jones of the Dallas Cowboys. ``The
principals are very impressive. The dilemma in my mind is how to
get a franchise in both places.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't going to happen, at least from an expansion
standpoint. The NFL, which will be at an awkward 31 teams when the
Cleveland Browns start anew next fall, have only one prospective
expansion slot. And Commissioner Paul Tagliabue seemed hopeful that
the dazzle of the presentations will spur owners to make the choice
``within the first quarter of next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Both the Ovitz and Houston groups insist they are operating
under a deadline, with Ovitz even pressing for a decision by the
end of this year. But an NFL insider dismissed that as
``gamesmanship'' and predicted that if the league shows it is
making progress toward a resolution, the former Hollywood agent
won't be issuing any ``drop-dead dates.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue adjourned the day's meeting moments after Ovitz's
show, the last on the agenda, thumped to a halt in the late
afternoon. The commissioner said the owners would be asked for
feedback when the fall meeting reconvenes this morning.
</P>
<P>
   What he is likely to get are more questions about specifics _
particularly on the L.A. projects _ which likely will prolong this
process well into next year.
</P>
<P>
   An NFL executive privately cited the gray areas still evident in
both L.A. proposals:
</P>
<P>
   _ Carson: ``The public money just came in last week (a pledge of
$180 million in bonds by Carson). How is that really delivered to
the project? Is that cash upfront or is that revenues just taken
off the stadium? And is there going to be any public challenge to
that?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Coliseum: ``You're assuming you can sell suites for this.
You're assuming you can do PSLs (personal seat licenses), club
seats. You're assuming that the total project costs this much ($357
million). But this design just came along in the last two months.
Have they really priced it out?''
</P>
<P>
   However, Tagliabue said, ``I would say both (L.A.) presentations
were quite specific in terms of financing and how the financing
would be nailed down.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston, meanwhile, drove its nails in deeply long ago. It
already has a special-purpose tax, on hotel occupancy and
short-term car rentals, that has been in place producing income for
a baseball stadium for a year.
</P>
<P>
   But there's that pesky issue of Los Angeles having the
second-largest TV market in the nation, while Houston lags behind
at 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Broncos owner Pat Bowlen insisted that would not
influence his decision when the time comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it would be difficult at all'' to choose Houston
over Los Angeles, Bowlen said, ``because they're both great
markets. Houston is not exactly a small city, or a small area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at them both being equal at this point. ... It comes
down to two things: ownership and stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Which maintains the mandate for the Los Angeles groups to be
ever more convincing that they're solid in each respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to go; we're ready to start construction,'' said
Roski, who admitted that he was questioned after his presentation
about the interest of the market and his projected revenue streams.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz said his presentation focused on ``why football should be
back in Los Angeles and why this group is the one to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' Jones said: ``There are some bright lines between
both groups in L.A. _ different stadium approaches. You've got some
decisions to make there.''
</P>
<P>
   By building strong cases on such issues as stadium design and
ownership strength, it appears all three bidders did nothing to
hurt their causes in the latest round of lobbying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
