<HEADLINE>
STUMPEL'S INJURIES PROVE FRUSTRATING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ It will be difficult to accurately evaluate
the Los Angeles Kings offense until they get their best offensive
player back. But exactly when center Jozef Stumpel, the Kings' top
scorer last season, will be able to return remains uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel suffered a hip-flexor strain in the Kings' exhibition
finale at Bakersfield on Oct. 4. He then was scoreless in the first
four regular-season games before revealing his injury and heading
into rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, following the Kings' skate before their game
against the New York Islanders, trainer Pete Demers acknowledged
that in addition to the hip injury, Stumpel has experienced ``a
little abdominal pain which has eased up significantly.'' Stumpel
did not skate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel was examined by a doctor when the Kings were in Tampa
last week, and is scheduled to be seen by Kings physician Dr.
Ronald Kvitne on Thursday, ``to see if there's something we're
missing,'' Demers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's slow right now,'' Demers said. ``He's just not coming
along the way we expect him to. We're continuing to treat him and
we're trying to keep his (conditioning) up and have him skate every
few days. It's frustrating for us. We want to get him back in the
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   On the farm: General manager Dave Taylor toured Canada to scout
Kings prospects before joining the Kings in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor scouted left wing Matt Zultek at a junior game in Ottawa,
center Justin Papineau at a junior game in Belleville, Ontario, and
several Kings prospects during two AHL games involving the
Springfield Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   At the Springfield games, winger Greg Phillips had three goals
Friday, two assists Saturday, and center Olli Jokinen had a goal
and five assists in the games, earning AHL Player of the Week
honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked the way he played over the weekend,'' Taylor said.
``He has excellent vision on the ice, moves the puck well and does
a lot of smart things. Where he has to adjust is being more
forceful as far as getting the puck and being more physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Springfield prospect, center Donald MacLean, is expected
to be sidelined a month after spraining an ankle playing
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Winger Josh Green returned after missing three
games with a shoulder strain, and winger Craig Johnson returned
after being a healthy scratch for one game. Defenseman Garry Galley
was a healthy scratch for the sixth time in eight games, but coach
Larry Robinson said he may play tonight at New Jersey.... Goalie
Stephane Fiset is expected to return to action tonight after
missing nine days with a groin strain. Fiset, however, was not the
backup Tuesday against the Islanders. That job went to Ryan Bach.
The Kings didn't want to risk the possibility of having to suddenly
stick Fiset into a game if starter Manny Legace got hurt or was
ineffective.... Taylor said that when the time comes for Bach to be
assigned to the minor leagues, there's a chance he will be sent not
to the team he was with, the Utah Grizzlies of the IHL, but to the
Long Beach Ice Dogs. Jamie Storr (groin strain) also may play some
games in Long Beach before rejoining the Kings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
