<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-KINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS DEFEAT KINGS, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ While their coach was in Vienna seeking to get
their leading scorer to rejoin the team, the New York Islanders
barely got enough scoring to beat the Los Angeles Kings, 1-0, at
Nassau Coliseum on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sacco got the goal, early in the third period, and Tommy
Salo got his third shutout of the season as Lorne Henning ran the
team in Mike Milbury's absence.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury, the Islanders' coach and general manager, left Long
Island late Monday with a contract proposal for Zigmund Palffy, who
has been a holdout for seven weeks. The 26-year-old right wing is
the Islanders' best player and a restricted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, Milbury will return on Thursday without
Palffy's signature on a contract. Palffy, who led the Islanders in
scoring the last three seasons, rejected the team's latest offer of
a two-year deal worth $7.8 million, plus incentives. He is seeking
$6.8 million a season.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed contract would have paid Palffy $3.45 million this
season and $4.35 million next season, the Islanders said.
Incentives for goals, assists, total points and awards would have
made the offer worth more than $10 million over two years. The
Islanders' latest proposal came less than a week after the team
withdrew its offer of a three-year, $12.75 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike went there in a serious way about getting Ziggy to play
hockey this season,'' the Islanders' president, David Seldin, said
on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury had said, ``My goal in meeting with Zigmund Palffy face
to face is to bring this issue to a conclusion.'' He wanted a
resolution, whether it meant signing Palffy, trading him or letting
him sit out the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy and his agent took Tuesday's offer as an insult.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone offers you less than what they offered
previously, that tells me they are not interested in negotiating
seriously,'' said Paul Kraus, Palffy's agent, who did not attend
the meeting in Vienna, sending an associate, Petr Svoboda, in his
place. ``We are interested in making a deal; they obviously are
not.''
</P>
<P>
   According to an Islanders official, the team's offer was
identical to the contract signed by Edmonton's Doug Weight last
week. The Islanders have compared Palffy to Weight during the
negotiations, according to Kraus. Weight scored 256 points over the
past three seasons, which is comparable to Palffy's 264 points over
that time.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I were a general manager, would I trade Zigmund Palffy for
Doug Weight?'' Kraus said. ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   During the negotiations, Kraus has repeatedly compared Palffy to
Mats Sundin, the standout Toronto center who earns $6.8 million a
season.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he expected another offer from the Islanders, Kraus
said: ``Nothing is final. Nothing is absolute with them. Honestly,
I don't know what they are thinking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 0031EST &QL; 
