<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0465 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-     10-28 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERSKOWITZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
MickeyHerskowitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THIS is not a knee-jerk nostalgia thing. But when it comes to
picking the top college football teams, I believe I liked the old
system better. Do you remember how it used to be, as much as 48
hours ago, when you had two polls, one picked by the writers and
one by the coaches?
</P>
<P>
   Rating the teams was an industry in itself, with its own rote
and ritual. The system was invented in the 1920s by two legendary
sportswriters, Sam Rote and Joe Ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the process has just gotten a whole lot more complicated
because of something called the Bowl Championship Series, which
rates the teams according to their records, strength of schedule,
opponents' schedules and a compendium of ratings gleaned from the
writers, the coaches, the New York Times, the Seattle Times and a
math scholar named Sagarin.
</P>
<P>
   When they fed all the numbers into a computer named Albert, UCLA
was atop the list and Ohio State was second, a reversal of their
positions in the two most widely circulated polls. How the teams
are seeded has taken on a new, cosmic importance because at
season's end One and Two will meet in the Fiesta Bowl to play for
all the treasures.
</P>
<P>
   For now, we have Tennessee and Kansas State, also undefeated,
looking for ways to run up the score. In the final five weeks, the
Volunteers play three teams that are not ranked in the top 100,
which is akin to scrimmaging their coaching staff. Of course, the
Wildcats opened the season against three teams that rated no higher
than 131 (Northeast Louisiana). This is akin to playing opponents
whose jerseys and helmets don't match.
</P>
<P>
   Among the schedule-makers, this is known as ``pianissimo,'' or
soft touches, a convenient way to inflate the record.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so complicated in 1924, when the first national
championship was awarded. Unbeaten in 10 games, with no math police
checking out its schedule, Notre Dame was crowned by the Helms
Foundation and the Dickinson System. Historians say there was
little argument among the few who paid attention. People were
preoccupied with striking for a 50-hour work week and wondering
where Khartoum was.
</P>
<P>
   The 1924 Irish featured the backfield Grantland Rice
immortalized as the Four Horsemen. The team had one other
distinction. It was the first to win the championship
retroactively. The polls came into existence in 1926, but Knute
Rockne persuaded the people who developed them to predate their
choices by two years. Thus Rockne was able to honor his most famous
team. Notre Dame has always had a lot of ways to win.
</P>
<P>
   The latest formula is designed to squeeze out human error and
leave the serious matter of trophy-giving to science. All of which
gives us this oddity:
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska and Texas A&AMP;M boast identical records (7-1). The Aggies
are playing a meaner schedule, the country's eighth-toughest
compared to 15th for the Cornhuskers. And when they teed it up, the
Aggies won. So we check the BCS rankings and find Nebraska ranked
No. 6 and the Aggies eighth. What could the computer possibly be
thinking?
</P>
<P>
   It is at roughly this time every year that those in amateur
football discover what a vampire they have created in the national
polls. To the teams expected to compete for the national title, the
rankings have come to symbolize a great boiler, into which they
have been lowered to cook like Maine lobsters.
</P>
<P>
   You can go all the way back to 1966, and many people do, for an
example of the craziness this process has inspired. That year, Ara
Parseghian, then the coach of top-ranked Notre Dame, ran out the
clock and settled for a tie against No. 2 Michigan State, keeping
the Irish undefeated. And this is what transpired:
</P>
<P>
   Parseghian argued that if you're No. 1 and you don't lose, you
can't be dislodged. Duffy Daugherty, the Michigan State coach,
countered by saying that if you're second and you tie the team
ahead of you, then you become No. 1 and the other guy becomes 1A.
</P>
<P>
   And Bear Bryant, the coach at Alabama, the only undefeated and
untied team left among the major powers, said, waving the flag,
that he just hoped if any of his Alabama seniors got drafted and
had to go to Vietnam that they would not play for a tie.
</P>
<P>
   But later, Bryant made the truest observation of all: ``Ara had
the last laugh because he wound up with most of the awards. Playing
that old tie must have been smart.''
</P>
<P>
   There are clearly a few clinks in the computer still to be
ironed out. The bowl poll seemed like a good idea at the time. It
may yet turn out that way. But for now, it just gives another
reason to grumble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
