<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0469 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMPIONSHIP     10-28 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMPIONSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ For the first 60 years of its existence, East Lake Golf
Club claimed a tradition unlike any other _ it was home for Bobby
Jones, who epitomized golf during the sport's formative years in
the United States.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The place had staying power. Its tradition was as revered as
that of any course in the South, at least any of them outside
Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   But East Lake's reputation as a monument to golf peaked in 1963,
when it hosted the Ryder Cup. Since then, East Lake might as well
have been the Crater Lake of the golf scene. For most of the past
35 years, it went through a sad deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   But when the top 30 PGA Tour players step onto East Lake for the
season-ending Tour Championship starting Thursday, they might want
to give thanks for the concept of urban renewal. If not for Atlanta
developer Tom Cousins taking this run-down portion of town and
implementing a revitalization plan for the past few years, East
Lake might never have gotten this chance.
</P>
<P>
   It's a story not unlike that of Houston's Memorial Park. A
classic course designed decades ago had suffered from neglect for
years. Now, Memorial Park is a jewel in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for East Lake in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really nice to see what's transpired at this golf
course,'' Mark O'Meara said Tuesday. ``This is my first visit here,
but to hear about what has happened over time, it's quite an
achievement for all of Atlanta and for Tom Cousins and all the
businesses here to have put the support behind this development and
brought it back to an incredible stature. My hat's off to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The rejuvenated East Lake will provide an incredibly stiff
challenge this week to the best golfers on the tour. Even though
the course had to be tweaked to accommodate the pros (two par-5s
were changed to par-4s), it should hold up nicely under their
assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like a major, and I think scores will be similar to a
major,'' Phil Mickelson said. ``Definitely single digits under par,
and probably 4- or 6-under-par, will win. With a par-70, 6-under is
really like 14-under. I think it's set up better than most of the
majors we play as far as fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   What the PGA Tour has done is give the course, tucked in the
eastern neck of Atlanta's inner-city sprawl, a combination of
Augusta National finesse with U.S. Open muscle. The greens aren't
like putting on a tabletop, as they are at the Masters at times.
But they are faster than your average PGA Tour stop.
</P>
<P>
   And the rough looks as if it hasn't been cut since Jones
traipsed around the joint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rough is very, very deep,'' O'Meara said. ``With the
pressure and everything, it's set up like a U.S. Open. The rough is
that deep. If you're an inch off the fairway, you're going to take
out your wedge or 9-iron. That grass is very thick and very tough
to play out of.''
</P>
<P>
   Which would seem to favor the straight hitters this week. But
then you look at the course length (6,980 yards) and the speed of
the greens and realize this is a tract that favors nobody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it favors any one person,'' Jim Furyk said.
``It's not real long. It's not real short. The fairways are
probably the best we've played, and the greens are real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the greens. They will level the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they'd want to get the greens much faster,''
Jeff Sluman said. ``I would think they'd want to keep them right
where they are. The place is really something special. The course
is perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather is expected to be perfect, too. And that won't hurt
East Lake's chances for getting into the Tour Championship
rotation. There is talk of rotating the tournament among Champions,
East Lake, Pinehurst No. 2 and the Olympic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Because the event always will be in late October or early
November, it must be in an area where weather concerns will be
minimal. It's dicey enough coming to Houston at this time of year.
Atlanta, while chamber-of-commerce brilliant this week, can get
nasty in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it appears East Lake is destined to regain its
spot among the elite golf courses in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Bobby Jones is smiling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
