r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASHERIFF-2takes-LADN     10-28 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASHERIFF-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. COUNTY SHERIFF'S CAMPAIGN CONTINUES DESPITE UNCERTAINTY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Sheriff Sherman Block slowly showed signs of
``alertness'' Tuesday after surgery for a brain clot, the politics
of his re-election campaign played out on a variety of stages.
</P>
<P>
   Some well-known political leaders _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein, Mayor
Richard Riordan and county Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky _ reaffirmed
their support for Block, while prominent political analysts said
challenger Lee Baca was all but assured of victory because of the
seriousness of the sheriff's illness.
</P>
<P>
   Baca, who retired as a regional chief in the Los Angeles County
Sheriff's Department to run against Block, initially suspended his
campaign appearances and his advertising that had heavily
emphasized the sheriff's age and poor health.
</P>
<P>
   But the cease-fire did not last long, as the Block campaign
stepped up its attack on Baca's competence to run the massive law
enforcement agency, and the Baca campaign struck back with renewed
emphasis on Block's physical inability to serve another term.
</P>
<P>
   Block was listed in serious condition at USC University
Hospital, and Dr. Srinath Samudrala, who performed the four-hour
surgery, said it was too early to determine whether the sheriff
would fully regain consciousness or be able to talk and function
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is in serious condition. His level of alertness continues
to improve,'' Samudrala said. ``Obviously we'll need to allow
several days of recovery to see how the patient is going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He would not answer directly a series of questions about whether
Block was conscious and responsive or what the prognosis for
recovery is.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff ended up in the hospital Saturday night after
falling and hitting his head, requiring 10 stitches. His condition
worsened, and doctors now say he suffered a blood clot in the brain
before the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Block campaign spokesman Joseph Scott expressed frustration that
Block's health had overshadowed other issues and that Baca's
ability was escaping attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is Baca?'' Scott asked. ``There's a large undecided vote
out there, I think'' and several factors could help decide it, he
said, including Baca's lack of visibility during much of the
general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Block campaign manager John Shallman added: ``To give up or quit
is against the man's character. I do not need a reconfirmation from
this sheriff to continue this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``His opponent is someone who is too risky.''
</P>
<P>
   While Baca avoided jumping into the fray, his campaign
counterattacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been many issues in this campaign, one of them
being the sheriff's health and ability to lead the department,''
said Jorge Flores, a campaign consultant for Baca.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now more than ever, the voters of Los Angeles County
understand that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry that the Block campaign does not recognize the
genuine act of compassion that this (campaign suspension) is,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Block, who has overcome two bouts with cancer and must get
dialysis treatments for kidney failure three times a week, has
insisted he was healthy enough to lead the department for an
additional four years and campaigned vigorously after being forced
into a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Baca has said Block's health was 99 percent of the reason he
entered the race. He feared that if Block was elected again, he
might have to quit midterm because of health problems, meaning the
choice for replacing the sheriff would fall to the Board of
Supervisors rather than the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   The supervisors received a closed-session briefing from County
Counsel Bill Pellman on provisions of the law governing what
happens in the event the sheriff dies or is incapacitated.
</P>
<P>
   By law, the undersheriff runs the department when the sheriff is
not available. If the sheriff should die, the supervisors can
appoint a new sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's new term will start at noon Dec. 3, so any
appointment now to replace him because of death, resignation or
incapacity would be effective only until then.
</P>
<P>
   If Block wins the election but dies, resigns or is found unable
to stay in the position afterward, the appointed successor would
stay in office until the November 2000 election and would have to
run in that election to continue. The winner of that election would
serve a two-year term.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's incapacitation would have to be determined in
court. Under state law, the county would need to ask the attorney
general to bring a lawsuit in Superior Court to obtain such a
ruling or could have the attorney general delegate that
responsibility to the county.
</P>
<P>
   Two findings are necessary for a court to rule that an elected
official no longer is capable of holding office, Pellman said. The
official must be found physically or mentally incapacitated and
there must be reasonable cause to believe the incapacity will
remain in effect for the remainder of the official's term.
</P>
<P>
   In the political arena, many questioned whether the issue would
ever come to that because Baca is regarded as an all-but-certain
winner now.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, it's over,'' said consultant Joe Cerrell. ``For
people who didn't know Sherman Block from Gen. Sherman,'' he's now
being splashed across newspaper front pages and television news
because of his health.
</P>
<P>
   ``People without a clue about which one was ill'' _ Block or
Baca _ ``now know it. I don't see how Baca can lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Added consultant Rick Taylor: ``The campaign's over. Mr. Block
and his people have to understand it's not going to be him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Block supporters gathered Tuesday evening at a private
home in Brentwood for a previously planned fund-raiser for the
sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   A broad cross-section of elected officials from both major
political parties at the fund-raiser helped his campaign raise an
estimated $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Block has backing from Democrats such as Feinstein, Yaroslavsky,
District Attorney Gil Garcetti, Supervisor Yvonne Brathwaite Burke
and from Republicans such as Riordan, Councilman Hal Bernson and
former District Attorney Robert Philibosian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sherman Block has been one of the best sheriffs in the United
States,'' Feinstein said. ``I know it's hard for people at this
time, but I believe that he will improve and come back better than
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan recalled Block's 42 years in the Sheriff's Department,
serving the past 16 as sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has always served with pride, energy and wisdom,'' the
mayor said. ``Sherman Block will come back and serve that way for
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky added: ``If this had happened two years ago, he
would have had time to recover and it wouldn't be an issue. But,
the fact is, it happened seven days out from the election. If you
were going to vote for Sherm Block last Saturday, you should vote
for him next Tuesday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
