<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-SABRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TIE SABRES, 0-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The game ended in a double shutout, 0-0, between Mike
Richter's New York Rangers and Dominik Hasek's Buffalo Sabres on
Tuesday night at Madison Square Garden. The verdict extended the
Rangers' undefeated streak to five games, but the bad news involved
an injury to Aleksei Kovalev, who will miss about three weeks with
a separated left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to hurt our offense any,'' said Ranger Coach
John Muckler, with a grimace of a smile. ``We have to find a way to
score some goals.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth consecutive time that Hasek has shut out the
Rangers, who have tied their last two games and are undefeated in
five at 2-0-3.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's result could be submitted as a good argument for
a shootout, the penalty-shot contest that is used to decide Olympic
games and is occasionally discussed in the board rooms of the
National Hockey League. Although several rules have been changed to
increase scoring, neither goalie last night seemed interested in
extending the reforms to a post-buzzer series of one-on-one
confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fun for the crowd and it would be fun to
participate in,'' said Richter, who had 24 saves and got his first
shutout since the 1996-97 season. ``But it kind of takes away from
the orientation of a team game.'' As it was, many of the fans
grumbled and groaned with a few boos at the final buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek prevailed in such a shootout for the Czech Republic in
last winter's Olympics, defeating Team Canada on the way to the
gold medal. But he said on Tuesday night he doesn't want to use it
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say no,'' Hasek said. ``I'm not a big fan of
shootouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it would be a mistake to allow such a display with these
two teams on a night like this. Imagine if both kept sending
skaters in alone on each other's goalies without scoring. Imagine
if the Rangers could not even put a shot on goal under these
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   They managed only 16 in 65 minutes on Tuesday night, only eight
of them after the first period. During the third period, they
enjoyed four power plays. On three, they got no shots.
</P>
<P>
   All this is not to say that the game _ the Rangers' first 0-0
tie since Feb. 28, 1995 _ was boring or poorly played. It was not,
really, for fans who enjoy technical strategy laced with malice and
effort. But it is the kind of final score that might worry the NHL.
Last season saw the lowest scoring, on average, in four decades.
</P>
<P>
   Among many players paying a physical price was Wayne Gretzky. He
twice was hit hard by Jay McKee, the big defenseman, and Vaclav
Varada jousted with him.
</P>
<P>
   Usually the first Ranger to shower, dress and speak to
reporters, Gretzky remained in the team's private quarters for
almost 45 minutes after the game. In the last three outings,
Gretzky has been hit hard and knocked over several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little sore tonight,'' he said. ``Been banged up a little bit
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovalev was injured in the first period. ``He's going to be in a
sling and rest it around three weeks,'' Dr. Barton Nisonson said,
adding that surgery was not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kovalev has no goals this season, he plays an important
role as right wing for Gretzky on the Rangers first line. He also
gets ice time on the power play. Mike Knuble, right wing on Todd
Harvey's line, was promoted to Gretzky's line with the start of the
second period. One change might be to move Harvey back to his
regular position of right wing and use the rookie Manny Malhotra at
center.
</P>
<P>
   Checking was so tight that it seemed at times as if the teams
were playing with 12 men a side instead of six. Both teams also
used variations of the neutral zone trap to stifle each other's
attacks. Within this framework, there was much hard hitting and
animosity. On the game's first shift, Buffalo wing Michal Grosek
clobbered Ranger defenseman Ulf Samuelsson into the corner in the
Ranger end. Several other Sabres also targeted Samuelsson, who is
playing with a full face shield to protect a fractured cheekbone.
</P>
<P>
   This seemed to energize Samuelsson, who is one of the league's
roughest players. With the Sabres on the power play near the end of
the first period, Samuelsson came across the ice laterally to
flatten Grosek with a hard, clean check in open ice. In the second
period, Samuelsson had several altercations with Matthew Barnaby,
the Buffalo terror. They collided, knee to knee, and went at it
moments later in front of the Rangers net. Whenever Samuelsson
skated by the Buffalo bench, the Sabres taunted him. With a
fraction of a second left in the second period, Barnaby, Curtis
Brown and Grosek all ganged up on Samuelsson in the corner, and
Barnaby was penalized for elbowing.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
