<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEITER IS NEXT ON MENU FOR METS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two days after signing Mike Piazza for $91 million to
be the cornerstone of their offense for the next seven years, the
New York Mets plan to announce Wednesday that they have agreed to a
four-year, $32 million deal with their pitching ace, Al Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   Mets general manager Steve Phillips and Leiter's
representatives, Alan and Randy Hendricks, completed the agreement
_ which has been in the works for over a month and a half _ late
last weekend, a person with knowledge of Leiter's negotiating
stance said.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter's deal, which includes a large signing bonus and no
deferred money, was expected to be announced at a 2 p.m. news
conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the Mets had been reluctant to give a four-year deal
to Leiter, who won 17 games this past season. But as was the case
with Piazza, the Mets apparently were more reluctant to let Leiter
test the free-agent market, where he would have been the most
coveted pitcher after Randy Johnson and Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   In the span of three days, the Mets will have agreed to spend
$123 million to keep their best hitter and their best pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' next move could be reacquiring Bobby Bonilla. The Mets
were believed to be willing to send Mel Rojas to the Los Angeles
Dodgers for Bonilla in a deal that could also include Butch Huskey
for Eric Young, a person with knowledge of Phillips' thinking said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That would give the Mets a potential lineup of Young leading off
and playing second base, followed by third baseman Edgardo Alfonzo,
first baseman John Olerud, Piazza behind the plate and Bonilla in
right field. Left field is an unsettled position, Brian McRae would
be in center field and Rey Ordonez at shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   That question mark in left may be answered when the Mets trade
Todd Hundley, who has become an extra body now that they have
signed Piazza. The Cubs, Diamondbacks and Cardinals are understood
to definitely be interested. The Cardinals would presumably be
willing to part with left fielder Ron Gant. Or the Mets could
simply make a run at the free-agent outfielder Brian Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips reiterated Tuesday that his main priority now was
shoring the offense. After Luis Lopez agreed to a two-year deal
worth $1.35 million Tuesday ($575,000 in 1999 and $775,000 in
2000), the players the Mets have under contract for next season are
Piazza, Leiter, Rick Reed, Bobby Jones, John Franco, Willie Blair,
Rojas, Jorge Fabregas, Olerud, McRae and Hundley. The Mets also
have an option to pick up the final year of Greg McMichael's
contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Met players who are eligible for arbitration are Alfonzo,
Huskey, Ordonez, Todd Pratt, Hideo Nomo, Turk Wendell and Jason
Isringhausen. Phillips seemed to indicate Tuesday that the Mets
would also like to re-sign two of their pitching free agents:
Armando Reynoso and Masato Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have pitching depth and a catcher that we can trade from,''
Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips also has a lot more money in his budget. The Mets'
co-owners, Fred Wilpon and Nelson Doubleday, have indicated their
willingness to spend more to make a run at the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' payroll at the end of last season was $57 million, the
sixth-highest figure in the league. With the 12 players they have
signed at the moment, their payroll currently stands at just under
$50 million. But that includes the $5.325 million Hundley will make
this season and he will almost certainly be traded, although
Phillips said he was not in a rush to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   When asked Wednesday whether he felt his payroll would approach
$70 million _ or near what the Yankees spent to win the World
Series this year _ Phillips said: ``I don't think we'll be exactly
at that number. But we will have a competitive payroll.'' And
Phillips added that he had no complaints about the budget his
owners had given him to work with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take some work,'' Phillips said. ``But I think
we're going to have a good team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
