<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-LAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAILED-OUT HEDGE FUND CUTS 18 PERCENT OF STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital Management Inc., the hedge fund that a group
of banks and brokerage firms rescued last month, laid off 33
people, or about 18 percent of its 178 employees, on Tuesday,
according to people close to the firm.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs mostly involved people in the fund's offices in
Greenwich, Conn., and London and affected several senior
researchers and traders. They were concentrated in businesses that
the fund is seeking to wind down, like investments in developing
countries, and in the firm's equity trading, according to the
people close to the firm. These people spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   There are also a few layoffs in Long-Term's Tokyo office, they
said. No partners lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, a group of big banks and brokerage firms _
including Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.; Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.; Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter &AMP; Co. and J.P. Morgan _ invested $3.6 billion to shore
up the Greenwich hedge fund as it came close to running out of
money after falling under pressure from huge borrowings.
</P>
<P>
   That rescue, which resulted in the investing companies'
acquisition of 90 percent of Long-Term's capital, was organized by
the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, although it involved no
public money. The Fed and the rescuing institutions were
particularly concerned that at a time of great fragility in many
financial markets, a failure of Long-Term Capital might have had
severe market consequences that might have even threatened the
integrity of the financial system itself.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital, which is now overseen by a committee made up
of its new shareholders, is believed to be trying to reduce its
risks and improve its returns. It is operating in a more favorable
climate since the financial markets have recently calmed.
</P>
<P>
   Those laid off by Long-Term Capital were paid through the end of
the year, and they will also receive additional severance payments,
according to an executive involved with the fund's business who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The layoffs are expected to result in a charge for the
management company estimated at $1 million or $2 million. They were
approved at a meeting of Long-Term Capital's oversight committee on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Capital was set up in 1993 by John Meriwether, a
former vice chairman of Salomon Brothers Inc., along with several
other senior Salomon executives.
</P>
<P>
   The hedge fund, a lightly regulated pool of capital, began
trading in 1994 and produced big returns in 1995 and 1996. This
year it stumbled badly, particularly after Russia defaulted on its
debt in mid-August, causing steep losses in markets around the
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 0057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0481 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERCOMPUTER-NYT &LR;      10-28 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERCOMPUTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASTEST SUPERCOMPUTER: U.S. OUTDOING ITSELF AGAIN AT LIVERMORE
LAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department will take delivery Wednesday
of what the government says is the world's fastest computer,
capable of a peak performance of 3.88 trillion calculations, or
teraflops, a second.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials said Tuesday that the
supercomputer, which is being assembled at Lawrence Livermore
National Laboratory in California, is about 15,000 times faster
than a 350-megahertz personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   The computer, built by the IBM, uses 5,800 processor chips, each
slightly more powerful than the widely sold Pentium II chip made by
Intel Corp., said people involved in its development. Livermore, a
nuclear weapons lab, will use it for simulations that determine,
without detonation, whether aging nuclear weapons are still
operable.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks prepared for delivery Wednesday, Vice President Al
Gore says that beyond weapons research, the technology of the
computer, known as massively parallel architecture, ``will lead to
advances and greater understanding of weather patterns, global
climate change, medicine, manufacturing and aviation safety.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Energy Department, the computer, called Pacific Blue, is
part of a program to advance supercomputer technology rapidly to
the stage where it can model nuclear warheads. Pacific Blue takes
the speed title from Sandia Red, a computer at Sandia National
Laboratory built by Intel that was finished in December 1996 and is
about half as fast. Mountain Blue, a computer being built by
Silicon Graphics Inc., is expected to deliver about four teraflops.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-2000, Energy Department officials hope to have a
10-teraflop computer, also built by IBM, running at Livermore,
followed in 2004 by a 100-teraflop computer. The 100-teraflop model
would allow high-fidelity simulation of an H-bomb detonation, as a
volleyball-size mass of nuclear fuel is compressed to the size of a
walnut, setting off the explosive chain reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they were trying to retire Moore's
Law, which holds that chip makers will be able to double the number
of transistors on a given sliver of silicon, and thus its speed,
every 18 months. The Energy Department wants to triple computing
speed in about the same time frame by combining the power of many
processors instead of increasing the speed of each.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Donofrio, senior vice president for technology and
manufacturing at IBM, said that in building Pacific Blue, ``we
pretty much used commercial-grade stuff'' from the IBM. commercial
product line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
