<HEADER>
A0484 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBO-ARIZONA-8-MAN-AZR     10-28 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-ARIZONA-8-MAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8-MAN FOOTBALL GETS SACKED BY LONG TRAVELS, FEW PLAYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is homecoming at Arizona Lutheran Academy. Family and friends
have come from as far away as Tucson and the White Mountains.
</P>
<P>
   And the football team at the southwest Phoenix school is
determined not to inflict the 42-point mercy rule on its guests,
the Clifton Trojans, before the king and queen are crowned at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   With his team ahead, 36-0, eight minutes into the game, Coach
Doug Meyer sends in sophomores and freshmen against a team with
only eight reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going for a two-point conversion after its seventh
touchdown, Arizona Lutheran kicks the extra point to make the score
49-8 with three minutes left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Homecoming festivities go on as planned, accompanied by the roar
of engines from Manzanita Speedway, a mile or so away.
</P>
<P>
   The game ends shortly after halftime with an Arizona Lutheran
touchdown, leaving Clifton with a five-hour trip home and lots of
time to ponder the declining state of eight-man football.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, the eight-man game was established in sparsely
settled areas to give boys a chance to play football. But lack of
numbers, high travel costs and the disparity between weak and
strong teams have left it on life support in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically dead,'' said Meyer, coach and athletic director
at Arizona Lutheran, which petitioned to move into Class 2A to play
11-man football against teams closer to home next fall. ``There is
no competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Four of Arizona Lutheran's seven victories this year ended
prematurely because of the point spread. Its only loss was a mercy
ruling to No. 1 St. David. Meyer said he can count on one hand the
number of competitive 1A football teams: St. David, Orme, Heber
Mogollon, Arizona Lutheran and Joseph City, all among the eight
teams starting the playoffs Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Lutheran opens at home against Joseph City.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will be a great game,'' Meyer says. ``The rest will be
halftime, mercy-rule games.''
</P>
<P>
   And this, according to some, is one of the more competitive
eight-man seasons. &QL; 
Opting for 11-man
</P>
<P>
   The eight-man game is played on an 80- by 40-yard field. It is
wide-open, high-scoring and quite often one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Mogollon Athletic Director Rocky Nelson said.
``You don't want to totally humiliate the other team, but you want
to give your starters time to get in a rhythm and feel good, then
put in your JV kids, your younger kids. You know they're going to
go all-out.''
</P>
<P>
   Some wonder whether eight-man ball will survive through the next
two-year realignment.
</P>
<P>
   Nine schools recently appealed out of 1A, which has an
enrollment cutoff of 200 students. Next fall, 21 schools will be in
1A, with maybe nine playing eight-man football.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Interscholastic Association executive board will
consider a proposal on Nov. 16 that could create an 11-man 2A-1A
football conference for schools falling into the 249-150 enrollment
range. The rest of 2A, those schools with enrollments between 250
and 449, would play in it own league. The schools with fewer than
150 students would continue to play eight-man ball, but there could
be so few that there may not be a state tournament.
</P>
<P>
   A season still could be played, but the title would be a
mythical one. According to bylaws, the AIA can't sanction playoffs
for classifications that have less than half of its team involved
in football.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the AIA isn't giving up on the eight-man game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to make sure every kid at every school has an
opportunity to play,'' said Glen Treadaway, assistant director of
the AIA. ``I'd hate to see it go.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 15 1A schools with football teams, barely enough for a
state tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Salome Frogs had to drop football midway through last season
because injured and ineligible players made it impossible to field
a team.
</P>
<P>
   Salome, about 90 miles west of Phoenix, takes pride in finishing
this season, but the team can look back at four mercy-rule defeats,
including a 92-50 loss last week to St. David.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard when you have eight seniors who never played a down
before,'' first-year Coach Rich Metcalf said. ``There is no tackle
football this side of the state for seventh- and eighth-graders.''
</P>
<P>
   Routs are common, but coaches and administrators agree that the
mercy rule is needed to keep scores from getting really ugly.
</P>
<P>
   It also gives visiting teams a head start on the long bus rides
home, so players can be in bed before sunrise. &QL; 
Bus trip nightmare
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tiniest towns in the most remote outposts in Arizona
attempt to field eight-man high school football teams.
</P>
<P>
   Bowie, a high school with 25 students in far southeastern
Arizona, for years combined with neighboring San Simon to field a
football team. But Bowie broke away two years ago, and this year it
had enough players for just a JV team.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Lutheran and Phoenix Day School for the Deaf are the
last of the Valley schools with eight-man programs. To reach their
competition, five-hour bus trips, one way, are typical. And
sometimes frightful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bus breaks down a lot, for some reason,'' Arizona Lutheran
junior quarterback Zack Stam said. ``We might have broken a state
record for flat tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last season, Meyer was driving the bus for Arizona Lutheran
en route to a game in Clifton. A tire blew just east of Apache
Junction. There was no spare, and Meyer had to call for another
bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally roll into town, five hours from home, and halfway
through the first quarter, our best player gets a freak accident
and breaks his ankle. The parents are taking him to a hospital in
Morenci.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get slaughtered, 50-12. We have to hop on the bus and drive
back and get home at 3:30 in the morning. Whatever could have gone
wrong, did.''
</P>
<P>
   Next season, Arizona Lutheran will will play in a league against
schools closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest Community Christian and Scottsdale Christian recently
moved into 2A and into a league made up of Valley schools.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a smooth transition for Northwest, which won the 1A
title two years ago and now is 6-2 and ranked third in the state in
2A.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved eight-man football,'' Northwest Coach Charlie Bell
said. ``It was exciting. But it's my opinion that if all schools
played 11-man football, it would help tremendously. Scheduling
would be easier. You don't travel as much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are some 1A football teams that could play
against 3A schools and not be disgraced.'' &QL; 
An appreciation
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody looks forward to seeing an end to eight-man
football.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Gilmore left San Jose, Calif., to start the football program
at Tesseract, an exclusive private school of about 90 students in
north Scottsdale that starts at ground zero next year with an
eight-man team.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore attended Arizona Lutheran's homecoming to see his first
eight-man game. He saw the numerous Clifton turnovers fueling the
rout by the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore enjoys the nature of the smaller game, but he can see
the horizon, the long bus rides ahead. He puts a positive spin on
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if they let it die, it will die,'' Gilmore says. ``You
have to appreciate what they're doing, what they're going
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer of Arizona Lutheran recalls those trips to Clifton and
Fredonia, he remembers the flat tires and he craves a new era. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
