<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0492 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-WILL     10-28 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-WILLIAMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS SET PLAN FOR WILLIAMS TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service  clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the same day that Bernie Wil liams' agent said in a published
report that the free-agent New York Yankees center fielder probably
will earn more than Mike Piazza's $91 million, Diamondbacks General
Manager Joe Garagiola said a visit with Williams has been lined up,
although not finalized.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola also said the Diamond backs will contact pitcher Randy
Johnson, but won't have to bring him here. Johnson already lives in
the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to talk to them and find out what their thinking
is and go from there,'' Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola said Williams and his agent, Scott Boras, will come
here in November, probably shortly after Williams returns from his
home in Puerto Rico ``sometime around the fifth or sixth.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite what appears to be an outlandish asking price for
Williams, who led the American League in batting last season,
Garagiola said it never hurts to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think whenever we can have somebody, particularly someone
from the American League who doesn't know our ballpark . . . it's a
tremendous plus when they can see the community and the
facilities,'' Garagiola said.
</P>
<P>
   It also helps that Williams has a relationship with Diamondbacks
Manager Buck Showalter, who man aged Williams and the Yankees from
1992 through 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks already have an established center fielder,
Devon White, who was the team's most valuable player last season.
White also has declared for free agency, but he has a home in the
Valley and would prefer to stay here. Williams conceivably could
play right field next to White.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' agent, Scott Boras, said that Williams is a better
player than Piazza and should expect to make more money because
several teams will be bidding. The New York Mets on Monday made
Piazza the highest-paid player in the game with a seven-year deal,
even though Piazza did not file for free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Piazza's contract represents what what team was willing
to pay Piazza,'' Boras told Bloomberg News. ``It doesn't represent
what free agency was willing to pay Piazza. We don't know what the
market is for a premium player who's competed for by multiple
teams. I think that's a very different market.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite missing 34 games because of a knee injury, Williams, 30,
hit .339 with 26 homers, 97 RBIs and 101 runs for the Yankees, who
won their second world championship in three years. He also won a
Gold Glove.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, traded from the Los Angeles Dodgers to Florida and then
to the Mets, hit .328 with 32 homers, 111 RBIs and 88 runs. But
defense is not his strong suit, which Boras was quick to point out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie Williams is a complete player. Mike Piazza is a
slugger,'' Boras, who represents Andy Benes and Jay Bell on the
Diamondbacks, told Bloomberg. ``In Bernie's case, you get the same
offense as Piazza, but you get premium, Gold Glove-type defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, since 1993, when both players became regulars, Piazza
has better hitting statistics in virtually all the major
categories.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean the Diamond backs wouldn't love to have Wil
liams. The question is whether he is too expensive, even though the
club is awash in revenue streams that puts it among major league
baseball's most profitable franchises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we get the opportunity, as I think we will, to sit
down and talk to him about Phoenix, about our team and how we're
putting it together and talk about the good things we hope to
accomplish, it's a good thing,'' Garagiola said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
