A0493 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-SWANN-A     10-28 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-SWANN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWANN DECIDES SURGERY NEEDED ON RIGHT KNEE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eric Swann, who is scheduled to undergo another arthroscopic
surgery on his right knee this morning, has had cartilage problems
and arthritis in both knees his entire career.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were aware that Swann might miss work because of
the problems when they re-signed him in February to a five-year
deal worth $25 million, including what then was a team-record $7.5
million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   He is the anchor of a defensive line that was expected to carry
the team, a star among stars in a group that includes three former
first-round draft picks. Swann, a two-time Pro Bowler, can be one
of the league's most menacing defensive left tackles when healthy,
as his team-leading five tackles for loss and co-leading four sacks
bear evidence.
</P>
<P>
   So there was pressure on Swann, 25, to play and perform, even
after his knee flared up unseasonably early. The decision to opt
for surgery was Swann's, Coach Vince Tobin said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one who has to determine whether he can play or can't
play,'' Tobin said. ``What we hoped we could do is nurse him
through the season even if we had to sacrifice some practice time,
let him practice a little bit at the end of the week so he'd know
what to do and be able to play on Sunday. We did that the last
couple of weeks, and he played pretty well. It's disappointing that
he couldn't continue to go that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Swann could not be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A team source said arthroscopic surgery was considered three
weeks ago and then dropped when Swann's knee began to feel better.
He practiced very little during the weeks leading up to the past
two games.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the bye week. Swann practiced on Wednesday. On
Thursday, the knee flared up again. He is scheduled to have what
team medical personnel term ``arthroscopic flush and joint
inspection'' of the right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Warren King, a member of the Association of Professional Team
Physicians, comprised of team physicians from the NFL, NBA, NHL,
Major League Baseball and WNBA, said that in such cases, the
recovery time is dictated by the advancement of the arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be good in anywhere from one week to a very long
period of time,'' said King, who consults for the San Jose Sharks,
San Francisco Giants and Oakland Raiders in the Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   Arthritis is damage to surface cartilage that covers the bone at
a joint. It starts as a softening of firm cartilage, then becomes
rough and fissured, then thins, eventually disappearing so the
underlying bone is exposed. King said any roughening or damage to
the cartilage surfaces on a joint, such as the knee, can be
smoothed or removed and flushed out, resulting in ``significant
pain relief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If a player is having trouble playing or performing, it is a
very reasonable thing to do,'' King said. ``If there is lost
meniscal pad, it could lead to quite an aggressive form of
arthritis at a relatively young age. It is not uncommon at all
among linemen who are carrying a lot of weight.''
</P>
<P>
   After Swann (6 feet 5, 315 pounds) had meniscus cartilage
removed from the right knee on Sept. 12, 1995, he missed four
weeks. After he had meniscus cartilage cleaned out of the same knee
on Nov. 10, 1993, he missed the final seven games.
</P>
<P>
   He has had two surgeries on his left knee, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin wouldn't second-guess the timing or the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I never look back,'' Tobin said. ``You make
determinations as you go, and you make decisions when you're forced
to make decisions. Last week, he practiced on Wednesday and felt
pretty good. On Thursday, it got sore and he didn't practice. This
week, it would not have been such that he could do what we'd
planned on doing, which was to practice at the end of the week and
play on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always satisfied that a player is going to do what he
thinks is best for him and the football team. Nobody can get into
anybody's mind and tell the level of pain he's going through, or
the level of his ability to play. . . . I'm satisfied that if Eric
thinks he needs surgery in order to continue to play, that that's
the course he should follow.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
