A0497 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CASSTEVENS-RANKIN     10-28 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CASSTEVENS-RANKINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BCS POLL RAISES MORE QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ohio State University is unbeaten and ranked No. 1 in both
college football polls. But OSU isn't the nation's best team
according to the Bowl Confusion System rankings released this week.
UCLA is No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State is No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Buckeye A: ``We don't get any respect, man.'' Buckeye B: ``Yeah,
the computer's dissin' us.''
</P>
<P>
   After his team beat Northwestern last week, Ohio State coach
John Cooper spoke for most Americans when he said, ``I couldn't
tell you what the BCS poll is.''
</P>
<P>
   The BCS is a complex statistical formula devised by the Internal
Revenue Service and leaked by the White House to confuse the public
and direct our attention away from the pending presidential
impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Between now and December the BCS is guaranteed to produce many
heated arguments, and an occasional stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   I have spent hours studying the new ratings, which will identify
the teams that will play for the national championship Jan. 4 in
the Tostitos Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Best I can tell, the Byzantine formula is based in part on the
data from three computer rankings:
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sagarin; Hester &AMP; Anderson/``Seattle Times; The New York
Times''. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Who's who? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who is Jeff Sagarin?
</P>
<P>
   You can find him on the internet. Pictured on Sagarin's ``home
page`` is an intense-looking young man with dark eyebrows and a
shaggy head of dark hair. Jeff looks like Engelbert Humperdinck,
the singer.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a T-shirt and khakis, Sagarin is standing outdoors
alongside a young woman identified as Earth Goddess Nan. A white
dog is dozing at the couple's feet.
</P>
<P>
   Sagarin is a mathematics graduate from the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology _ MIT for those in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Sagarin's national rankings (he ranks ASU No. 56, just ahead of
the Texas Christian Horned Frogs) will help determine which teams
will be coming to Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   Ever met him?
</P>
<P>
   Spoken with him?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I haven't,'' said John Junker, executive director of the
Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   How about Chris Hester?
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Anderson?
</P>
<P>
   Junker laughed softly, the healthy sign of a busy man who hasn't
lost his sense of humor. ``I don't know them either,'' he said,
``but I enjoy their work.''
</P>
<P>
   Sagarin ranks UCLA ahead of Ohio State. So does Hester/Anderson.
But who ``are'' they? And why is a Seattle newspaper involved in
all of this? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Judging reliability &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Click your mouse and you'll find more than 70 college football
power ratings and rankings. Gary Hawley's Pigskin Index. Dr. Ono's
NCAA Football Rankings. Chad Hansen's Ultimate College Football
Ranking System. What makes one more reliable than the others?
</P>
<P>
   Junker defends the BCS rankings, calling the formula a
``credible and reasonable system.'' He favors computers determining
who is No. 1 and No. 2 over a person in a ``yellow jacket'' _ a
Fiesta Bowl official _ deciding which teams are worthy to play for
the championship, and by doing so risk having his house burned down
by those who most passionately disagree.
</P>
<P>
   And really, it's not that complicated. According to the system,
an average of the three rankings are utilized to calculate points
in one component of the formula. A maximum adjusted deviation of no
greater than 50 percent of the average of the two lowest computer
rankings will be utilized in the calculation.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, if a team is ranked third and fifth in two of the
computer systems and 12th in the third computer system, the highest
ranking of 12 would be adjusted to six before calculating the
average points for the computer component (3+58 divided by
24x50%2+46).
</P>
<P>
   The average of those three rankings would be calculated for the
points of this component (3+5+614 divided by 34.67.)
</P>
<P>
   Have a nice day. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 0114EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
