r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-TEXAS-FLOODS-TEX     10-28 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-TEXAS-FLOODS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS WOMAN'S TEAM AIDS FLOOD VICTIM _ THEIR TEAMMATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the aftermath of last week's South Texas floods, members of
the Texas Woman's University basketball team opened up their hearts
to assist one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   With an off-day from the drudgery of practice, the players drove
from the school in Denton, Texas, to Seguin, Texas on Saturday to
help teammate Laura Kolenozsky, after her family's home was
destroyed during flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that speaks highly of these players as individuals,
and it tells you a lot about their character,'' Texas Woman's
basketball coach Beth Palmer said. ``We have some athletes who have
high integrity and character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laura was real apprehensive about all of us wanting to help
her, because she didn't want anybody feeling sorry for her. But
after it was done, she was real appreciative.''
</P>
<P>
   The home where Kolenozsky grew up was located on the banks of
the Guadalupe River in Seguin. Now, Palmer said ``there's nothing
there but a slab.''
</P>
<P>
   The floods were ``similiar to a tornado,'' Palmer said. ``We
went down there to help Laura and her family try to find personal
belongings, and we were also there for moral support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would dig, dig and dig, and we'd find a fork. Then, we
would dig, dig and dig, and we'd find a pot. Laura's sister said
whatever we did find is more than what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolenozsky would not comment, but her teammates were more than
happy to be there in her time of need.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it shows how close we are as friends and as
teammates,'' guard Angie Land said. ``We're not just going to get
together on the basketball court and play, but we're also going to
help each other out on all situations on and off the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it meant a lot to all of us, especially Laura. It shows
how much we all care for each other, and that when hardships come
we'll help each other out.''
</P>
<P>
   For the team, witnessing devastation happening to strangers on
TV is one thing. But seeing it happen to someone they know was a
sobering experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``To actually walk in and see where someone's house is totally
gone, that hurt me because Laura's a teammate of mine. But not only
that, she's a human being,'' junior guard Shamika Wilburn said.
``To be able to help out, it made me feel better. It was just a
great team effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Denton stores aided the cause. Kmart gave the team a
discount on cleaning supplies, and Wal-Mart donated the wading
boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we were down there, we also helped one of the neighbors
whose home also was affected by the floods,'' Palmer said. ``It was
emotional, and mentally and physically draining.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Laura is family in a way, because she's on our team. We
were shoveling and digging all day long.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior forward, Kolenozsky led Texas Woman's in scoring last
season with 13.6 points per game. But her accomplishments on the
court pales in comparison to what her teammates and coach did for
her and her family off the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just proud of my team, and proud of the ladies who went
down there,'' Palmer said. ``We had them off last Saturday, and
they could have taken that day and done whatever they wanted to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the players said, `We'll think about this day a lot
longer and remember what we did by helping out the flood victims.
But we won't remember what we did if we would have gone home and
sat in front of the TV.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The team did rally around Laura, and were able to rally around
something negative and make it work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 0114EST &QL; 
