<HEADER>
A0524 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-LECHLER     10-28 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-LECHLER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M'S LECHLER STARS IN PUNT, PASS, KICK DUTIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Strange-but-true fact: The most
accurate passer on the Texas A&AMP;M football roster actually earns his
keep with his feet.
</P>
<P>
   But that does not prevent punter Shane Lechler from branching
out into other areas of the Aggies' offense or special teams.
During the 1998 season, Lechler is the only player at A&AMP;M who has
kicked off, punted, attempted a field goal, held for a field goal
and thrown a touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   That final achievement became a topic of discussion during a
Monday afternoon hunting trip with quarterback Randy McCown.
</P>
<P>
   Lechler said he lost track of how many touchdown passes McCown
threw during the eighth-ranked Aggies' 17-10 victory against Texas
Tech and requested an update. McCown, of course, had none. A&AMP;M's
lone touchdown toss against Tech came from Lechler on a fake field
goal, making the quarterback-turned-punter 2-for-2 in the passing
department this season.
</P>
<P>
   In McCown's estimation, that also makes Lechler hard to live
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept saying, `It only took me two passes to throw for a
touchdown. How many did it take you?' '' said McCown, who has
thrown for three touchdowns in 69 attempts. ``He's constantly
giving me a hard time. Just once, I'd like to punt and have it roll
about 80 yards so I could have something to hold over him.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't look for that to happen any time soon, said coach R.C.
Slocum. He doesn't want anyone but Lechler, a junior from East
Bernard with All-America credentials, handling the punting duties
when the Aggies (7-1, 4-0) head to Stillwater, Okla., for
Saturday's 6 p.m. game against Oklahoma State (3-4, 2-3).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Slocum likes to let Lechler handle as much of the
special-teams load as he is willing to shoulder. When he is not
holding for kicker Russell Bynum, Lechler is attempting the
long-distance field goals deemed out of Bynum's range. The past two
weeks, Lechler has completed a 29-yard pass on a fake punt and an
8-yard touchdown toss off a fake field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the versatility, Lechler's biggest asset is his ability
to win the field-position battle with rival punters. Lechler
averages 45.2 yards per punt, best in the Big 12 and sixth
nationally. He has killed 14 punts inside the opponents' 20-yard
line.
</P>
<P>
   Most telling, perhaps, is the fact A&AMP;M's average starting point
for drives this season is its 35-yard line. For opponents, it's
their own 27. Over the course of 103 possession exchanges, that's a
field-position gain of 824 yards, much of it attributable to
Lechler.
</P>
<P>
   That 824-yard figure exceeds the season totals produced by the
Aggies' leading rusher (Dante Hall, 750 yards), passer (McCown, 639
yards) or receiver (Chris Cole, 418 yards).
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it, to drive 80 yards against our defense is
next to impossible,'' Lechler said of a ``Wrecking Crew'' unit that
ranks eighth nationally in total defense (271.4 yards per game).
``The farther I can put them down there, the more I help out out
the defense.''
</P>
<P>
   He's helped to the point that Hall said, if forced to list the
team's three most valuable players, he would rank Lechler behind
linebackers Dat Nguyen and Warrick Holdman. Slocum takes it a step
further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shane Lechler has been the most valuable player on this
football team, by far, for a couple of years now,'' Slocum said.
``If you graded all his plays, he'd have very few minuses. He's a
great weapon for us that most teams don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, he accepted his role grudgingly. Lechler played
quarterback in high school, completing an eye-popping 87 of 101
passes (86.1 percent) during his senior season. But he played for a
Class 2A team that ran the option and never was asked to read
defenses until he arrived A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   That limitation proved too great to overcome, so Lechler stopped
attending quarterback meetings in 1997 and focused his attention on
punting. Last year, he set A&AMP;M season records for punting average
(47.0) and net punting (41.5). His career marks in those
departments, 44.6 and 41.5, also are school records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to hate punting. I didn't want to settle for that. I
wanted to be involved all the time, instead of six plays a game,''
Lechler said. ``Some times, it's still tough to watch Randy and
those guys out there having fun on every play. But I know if I'm
ever going to get to the NFL, this is what I've got to do. And I've
gotten to the point that I love kicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Lechler loves it even more when he gets to fake a kick and show
off his passing prowess, just to remind opponents _ as well as
McCown _ that he remains the most accurate passer on the A&AMP;M
roster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
