<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GONZALEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SECURE GONZALEZ FOR '99
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers exercised their option for 1999
on the contract of right fielder Juan Gonzalez and will consider
discussions regarding a extension, general manager Doug Melvin said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin informed Jim Bronner, who represents Gonzalez, of that
decision before the Rangers exercised their option worth $8.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're focusing on putting the team together for next year and
then we would consider sitting down,'' Melvin said. ``I'm not
saying we would, but we would consider it at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   The escalation of major-league salaries this decade likely will
dictate Melvin do so despite the fact the Rangers also possess an
option for the 2000 season on Gonzalez's contract worth $7.5
million. Both option years represent a bargain considering Gonzalez
is possibly the game's best run producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that salaries are escalating,'' Melvin said.
``You just try to take each contract individually and do what you
can do from a team concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirby Puckett became the game's first player to average $3
million per year when the Minnesota Twins signed the center fielder
to a three-year contract worth $9 million before the 1990 season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, New York Mets catcher Mike Piazza _ who Monday signed a
seven-year contract worth $91 million _ ranks as the game's
highest-paid player at $13 million per year less than a decade
later. It also should be noted that Piazza never tested the market
by filing for free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``His market value might have been five years at $12 million,''
Melvin said. ``He didn't sign for market value. He signed a deal
that the Mets gave him. He didn't go out in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Bernie Williams likely will, and it remains to be
seen what the 30-year-old outfielder will receive. Williams filed
for free agency Monday, and Scott Boras, who represents the player,
seeks a seven-year contract with a no-trade clause.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin will watch with interest, but the general manager said
that cannot dictate the Rangers' approach with Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't worry about where the market is and all that,''
Melvin said. ``You try to work out a deal that fits your
ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision yesterday gives the Rangers 10 players signed for
1999 at $39.5 million, and many questions remain.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton, right-hander Todd Stottlemyre and
reserve catcher Bill Haselman have filed for free agency, and first
baseman Will Clark and right-hander Xavier Hernandez likely will.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Aaron Sele, center fielder Tom Goodwin, designated
hitter/first baseman Lee Stevens and designated hitter/outfielder
Mike Simms will be eligible for salary arbitration, and the Rangers
expect right-hander Rick Helling will be eligible, too.
</P>
<P>
   Those 10 players earned $22,644,000 this past season, and with
10 players already signed at almost $40 million illustrates
Melvin's task. The Rangers' Opening Day payroll this past season
was $54,142,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always uncomfortable when you get that high, but you
just work and try to put the best team together that you can,''
Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   The scenario could leave the Rangers vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you make a mistake or players get injured,'' Melvin said,
``you've got a chance to have a disastrous year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
