<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SULLIVAN'S ACT DIDN'T PLAY AT TCU, BUT MIGHT AT AUBURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From his sweet home of Alabama comes the news that Pat Sullivan
has long been preparing to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   He's tanned. He's rested. He's ready to be the next head
football coach at Auburn.
</P>
<P>
   One full year after he submitted his resignation at TCU _
winless at the time and under fire _ Sullivan is being mentioned
prominently as a candidate to replace the abruptly departed Terry
Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a loyal Frogs fan, you probably find the news (A)
predictable, and (B) the silliest thing you've heard all month.
</P>
<P>
   To most observers here, TCU was never more than the Stuckey's on
Sullivan's highway back to the Southeastern Conference. He never
talked about it much, but his feelings for Auburn, his alma mater,
and for the down-home religion that is SEC football were always
there.
</P>
<P>
   One scene comes to memory, ironically from Sullivan's last night
of work at Amon Carter Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs were quasi-celebrating the conclusion of their ghastly
1-10 season, chortling at upsetting rival SMU. In the TCU locker
room, running backs coach Bud Casey, whose ties with Sullivan went
back more than 10 seasons, greeted a visitor with a frank synopsis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell ya,'' Casey said. ``We came here, not expecting to stay
all that long. We thought we were all going to LSU, but Pat screwed
that up. But now it's over and we're going back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Yep. That much pretty much sums up the Pat Sullivan Era at TCU.
</P>
<P>
   From out here on the prairie, it's seems unfathomable that
Auburn could have chased away a head coach who, in six years, was
30 games over .500. But then again, this is Texas and we know the
drill.
</P>
<P>
   In his private thoughts, back when Patrick was sharing them with
some media people, Sullivan would confess that he wasn't a fan of
Bowden. He put it much more colorfully, of course. And he was dead
right.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden was cocky and manipulative. He was stubby in stature but
left a wide footprint.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, his 20-0 start as a head coach was both the best
thing and the worst thing. It immediately stamped him, rightly or
wrongly, as a winner in the mold of his famous father.
</P>
<P>
   But the young Bowden never could assuage the Auburn expectations
left after those first two seasons _ who could? In 16 games against
top 25 foes over the past four seasons, Bowden was 4-12. His
overall record during that span was 18-15-1.
</P>
<P>
   More damning, though, was that the Auburn family never knew
whether to hug him or distrust him. With the school's worst start
in 46 years (1-5) staring him in the face, Bowden slipped into his
martyr's robe and walked out, leaving others to be blamed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people that Bowden has insinuated were responsible:
supporters of Pat Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   But know this _ no kid of Bobby Bowden is ever going to play the
fool. Terry gets $625,000 in severance pay and the chance to leave
before that 1-5 record got a lot worse. He could end up being the
next Oklahoma coach.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn, it appears, will let longtime assistant Bill Oliver
finish the season on an interim basis. And if he proves to be the
next Phillip Fulmer, who made Tennessee forget Johnny Majors,
Auburn might stop right there.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, however, those ``supporters of Sullivan''
will get their say. Patrick is certain to emerge as a serious
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm interested in the job,'' he told the
``Birmingham Post-Herald.'' ``I'm not going to sit here and lie to
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Auburn needs someone to rally the Auburn people, recruit and
coach. I feel like I'm good at those things.''
</P>
<P>
   In this part of the football world, alas, we never could
understand that about Pat Sullivan. But he was revered back in
Auburn after taking the Plainsmen to three bowl games and winning
the Heisman Trophy in 1971. He was Auburn's Earl Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the worst of TCU times, media friends from Alabama would
call us to check up on Sullivan. We would tell them one more time
about the LSU saga, when Sullivan talked his way out of the job in
1994 by demanding a Steve Spurrier-sized contract and someone to
pay his TCU escape clause.
</P>
<P>
   We would tell them how things changed abruptly after that '94
season, how Sullivan had decided he wanted to take control of the
offense and how the players had steadily lost faith in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to coach somewhere next year,'' Sullivan, who is 48,
told the Birmingham paper. ``Those were the plans back in January.
I just used this year to recharge my battery.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU fans will probably chuckle when they read that.
</P>
<P>
   At Auburn, Pat Sullivan is a golden oldie. A Heisman legend.
</P>
<P>
   Here, he was a dead battery.
</P>
<P>
   Godspeed, Auburn, from all the folks here at Stuckey's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
