<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN WANTS RAMOS, ARNOLD TO STAY BUSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cal State Northridge's Anthony Ramos had three
offensive touches in Saturday's loss to Montana State. Aaron Arnold
had two catches.
</P>
<P>
   Considering how exciting and electrifying both wide receivers
can be, that's not nearly enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I saw was that we only completed 16 passes,''
CSUN offensive coordinator Rob Phencie said. ``I looked and they
didn't come close to touching the damn thing as much as they should
in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   When CSUN's coaching staff met Monday to discuss what worked and
what failed during the last week, the inability to get Ramos and
Arnold more involved in the offense came up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   That should change Saturday when CSUN travels to No. 23 Weber
State, which has the Big Sky's top-rated defense. The coaching
staff is under the belief that CSUN settled for four field goals
against Montana State because Ramos and Arnold weren't involved in
the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ramos goes (well), we go,'' CSUN coach Ron Ponciano said.
``When he's had good games we've won. He's an exciting player who
makes big plays in a lot of different facets of the game. We have
to get the ball in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the same thing with Arnold. If he gets shut down, our
offense gets shut down. That's what we have to solve. How to get
them the ball more.''
</P>
<P>
   There are ways.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold has been moved to kick returner, and when Ramos was being
his most destructive to defenses earlier this season, he did it in
a variety of ways. He's thrown a touchdown, is third in rushing for
CSUN and has 19 receptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the week we always have stuff prepared, but come game
time we have to run sight adjustments,'' Ramos said. ``Last week
our practice plan, we were doing a certain thing, and they gave us
a different look so we did something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Jamming Welch: CSUN has already faced Division I-AA's top rusher
(Sacramento State's Charles Roberts) and next week the Matadors
host the No. 7 runner, Charles Dunn of Portland State.
</P>
<P>
   However, this week's focus is Weber State's Morgan Welch, who
has run for 1,310 yards and eight touchdowns. He's fifth in the
country in rushing (163.8 ypg) and is 69 yards from a single-season
school record but has been held to fewer than 100 yards in each of
the Wildcats' past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Welch) breaks some tackles, I think the offensive line is
very good and they have the one thing that kills us,'' Ponciano
said. ``They have the two tight ends and H-back.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are bad combinations for a defensive line that's been
mediocre lately. The Matadors are eighth in the conference in
rushing defense, allowing 202 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   All-you-can-eat buffet: Periodically, injured linebacker Cos
Abercrombie stops by practice, which he did Tuesday. His jaw is
wired shut after being broken at Northern Arizona on Sept. 19, but
he's scheduled to have the wiring taken off Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I ate real food was Sept. 19, when I had chicken
and spaghetti at Sizzler,'' said Abercrombie, who's lost 10 pounds
since being hurt. ``Just talking about it makes me hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Now this is ridiculous: The Matadors' injury situation has been
well-documented, but now it's getting out of hand. CSUN radio
analyst Ron Foster limped to practice with a hamstring problem
after injuring his leg during a commercial shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was high-steppin' it like Deion Sanders and felt
something,'' Foster said. ``(Play-by-play man) Gary Cruz is
healthy. Foster is probable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
