<HEADLINE>
PUSH IS ON FOR NATIONAL FINALS RODEO BERTHS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association heads into the
final two weekends of the regular season, cowboys such as Mike
Johnson are entering every rodeo possible, trying to secure a
National Finals Rodeo berth.
</P>
<P>
   Using come-from-behind tactics during a small show last weekend
in Del Rio, Johnson placed first in calf roping, earning $2,241.
The Del Rio victory boosted Johnson from 18th to 15th place in
today's world calf roping standings, a slim $689 ahead of New
Mexico roper Shawn Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   Only the top 15 in each event qualify for the $4.2 million
National Finals Rodeo, scheduled Dec. 4-13 in Las Vegas. The
regular season ends Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 34, attempting to gain his 16th NFR berth, has high
hopes of staying among the elite 15 for the next 1 1/2 weeks. If he
can ride out the bubble and qualify for the NFR, he'll earn a spot
in the record books with the second-most calf roping qualifications
behind former world champion Roy Cooper, who has 18.
</P>
<P>
   If I were a gambler, I'd bet on Johnson. The Henryetta, Okla.,
cowboy has had continued success since turning pro in 1982. The
next year, at 19, he qualified for his first NFR and finished sixth
in that year's world calf roping standings.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next 14 years, he was a permanent fixture at the NFR,
and although he has never won a world championship, Johnson
finished as runner-up in '89 to Rabe Rabon. In 1998, Johnson joined
an elite group of cowboys, reaching the million-dollar mark in
career earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Another on-the-bubble-bet might be Aaron Semas, who is
attempting to qualify in bull riding. Semas, 32, from Auburn,
Calif., has a good chance of qualifying for his seventh NFR thanks
to an impressive late-season push at last weekend's Casper (Wyo.)
Season Finale Rodeo. Semas vaulted to 13th in the Crown Royal world
bull riding standings with a $1,552 victory in Casper after scoring
80 points aboard Burns Rodeo Company's Pounder.
</P>
<P>
   Semas has devoted most of his time to competing on the
Professional Bull Riders circuit. But he has placed in enough PRCA
shows, mostly larger rodeos, to gain a top-15 spot.
</P>
<P>
   North Texans who are on the bubble, their rankings and events
include: Ty Murray, Stephenville, 15th, saddle bronc riding;
Gilbert Carrillo, Stephenville, 15th, bull riding; Brian Hawk, Fort
Worth, 15th, bareback riding and Vic Morrison, Bowie, 16th, team
roping heading.
</P>
<P>
   In the season's 11th hour, competitors hope to cash in at bigger
rodeos, such as the Grand National Rodeo at San Francisco's Cow
Palace, scheduled Friday through Sunday and Nov. 4-8, to earn a
berth in the 40th National Finals Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco show traditionally ranks in the top 10 in
prize money among the PRCA's 750 annual shows. A sure bet: During
finals night on Nov. 8, rodeo competitors on the bubble will learn
their fate.
ON THE CIRCUIT
Courting college rodeo
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth might be in the preliminary stages of roping next
summer's College National Finals Rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   The June championships have been staged in Rapid City, S.D., the
past two years. But the National Intercollegiate Rodeo Association
has elected to look for another home after attendance waned.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NIRA officials met with some of Fort Worth's
prominent rodeo officials, including W.R. Watt Jr., Southwestern
Exposition and Livestock Show Rodeo president and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Watt said a committee will approach Fort Worth government
officials next month and ask for financial backing in case the
finals are not profitable in its first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that we have to have somebody in place to
cover a shortfall,'' Watt said. ``However, I don't think we'll even
need to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Watt, who exuded confidence the CNFR can turn a profit in Fort
Worth, said the decision must come soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a lot of time,'' he said. ``Within the next
month, we'll know whether we have it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   If the college finals move to Fort Worth, officials will have
about seven months to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Will Rogers Equestrian Center has a date open in June _ I
understand it's not the exact week that the NIRA would prefer, but
they would be willing to hold it then,'' Watt said.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth's drawing cards are its state-of-the-art Will Rogers
Equestrian Center and its central location. Fort Worth officials
are courting the championships, knowing that finals were successful
in the remote city of Bozeman, Mont., its home for more than two
decades before it moved to Rapid City last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it can be successful in Bozeman, it sure can be successful
in Fort Worth,'' Watt said.
Fund-raiser scheduled
</P>
<P>
   Former Rangers pitcher Nolan Ryan, PRCA commissioner Steve
Hatchell and bootmaker John Justin are scheduled to appear tonight
at Billy Bob's nightclub for a fund-raiser. The gala will benefit
the Justin Cowboy Crisis Fund, which offers financial assistance to
rodeo competitors who have experienced hardship.
Headed to the Hall
</P>
<P>
   Helen Groves, billed as the Grand Dame of the National Cutting
Horse Association, is scheduled to be inducted into the National
Cowgirl Hall of Fame this weekend. Other inductees are Alice
Van-Springsteen, Coronado, Calif., trick rider; Cindy Walker,
Mexia, western song composer; and Mary Nan West, Batesville, stock
show organizer. Posthumous inductees areMaria Martinez, Native
American potter; and Cynthia Ann Parker, Old West pioneer.
THE BUZZ Women's rodeo
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville's J.J. Hampton is expected to enter this weekend's
Women's National Finals Rodeo in Fort Worth leading four
world-title races.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, a multiple title holder, will enter the championships
with an all-around race lead over Dolli Lautaret, $6,093 to $4,250.
Hampton also leads in team roping heading, calf roping and
break-away roping.
</P>
<P>
   The finals, scheduled Friday through Sunday at Cowtown Coliseum,
will help determine the 1998 world champions in the Professional
Women's Rodeo Association. Title races are determined by prize
money earned during the regular season and the finals.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call (817) 625-1025.
PRCA
</P>
<P>
   The Badlands Circuit Finals Rodeo ended Sunday in Rapid City,
earning its champions qualifications for the Dodge National Circuit
Finals Rodeo in March. The DNCFR, held in Pocatello, Idaho, is the
crowning event of the PRCA's circuit system, which comprises 12
geographic regions. Year-end circuit champions and circuit finals
average winners in each of PRCA's 12 circuits qualify to compete at
the DNCFR.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the average titlists at the Badlands Circuit Finals
Rodeo included Ken Lensegrav (Piedmont, S.D.), bareback riding, 218
points on three head, $1,731; Troy Pruitt (Minatare, Neb.), calf
roping, 29.5 seconds on three head, $2,309. In saddle bronc riding,
Red Lemmel of Mud Butte, S.D., and T.C. Holloway of Eagle Butte,
S.D., tied for the average win with 218 points on three horses.
Lemmel earned a rodeo total of $2,021 and Holloway garnered $1,691.
Bull riding
</P>
<P>
   Troy Dunn of Stephenville is among 10 competitors claiming a
North Texas residence who have qualified for the Nov. 6-8
Professional Bull Riders World Championships in Las Vegas. The
others include Ty Murray, Stephenville; J.W. Hart Gainesville; Cody
Hart, Gainesville; Gilbert Carrillo, Stephenville; David Fournier,
Stephenville; Adam Carrillo, Stephenville, Luziano Da Costa, Fort
Worth; Charles Litchfield, Bluffdale; and Tracer Hand, West. Tuff
Hedeman of Morgan Mill qualified, but has declined to compete
because of a neck injury sustained earlier this season.
Colleges update
</P>
<P>
   After competing in three National Intercollegiate Association
Rodeos in the Southern Region, Hill College leads both men's and
women's team title races. Last weekend, Hill's men's team finished
first and it's women finished third at the region's third of 10
rodeos at Uvalde.
Appaloosas
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 800 Appaloosas are expected to compete in the 37th
World Championship Appaloosa Horse Show, Friday through Nov. 7 at
Will Rogers Equestrian Center. Highlights include Sunday'scutting
futurity and the Nov. 6 freestyle reining class.
High schools
</P>
<P>
   After winning the break-away roping title at the Texas High
School Rodeo Association Region III show last weekend in Decatur,
Mindy Elrod leads the title race with 29 points. Kory Gant leads
the bareback riding title with 27.5
</P>
<P>
   after finishing second at Decatur, the third of 10
regular-season shows.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing first at last weekend's Richland High School
Rodeo in Saginaw, Northwest leads the North Texas High School Rodeo
Association team title race over Boswell, 2,447 to 2,250.
Northwest's Brandon Henderson leads the steer wrestling race after
finishing second last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley Harter's boys all-around victory at the Richland Rodeo
helped the Aledo cowboy take the lead in the race over Clint Akins,
975.5 to 965. Mary Margaret Richter has a commanding girls
all-around lead over Mansfield's Karly Newborn, 1,209 to 800.
</P>
</TEXT>
