<HEADLINE>
QB SAYS QUICK EXIT AFTER HOOK NOT TRUE 
</HEADLINE>
  ST-NOTEBOOK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chad Elliott said he didn't go away mad, he just went away.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott started at quarterback for Arizona State last week
against Stanford, then came out for the guy he replaced, Ryan
Kealy. That much is known. Not so certain is what happened after
the game. Allegedly, Elliott was so upset that he quickly left the
field instead of celebrating the Kealy-led, 44-38 overtime victory.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people got the wrong impression,'' he said
Tuesday. ``I was taken out of the game, and I think people tend to
look for negative things. They saw me running off the field,
thinking I was upset or mad or whatever. That's not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``What actually happened was, I walked over and talked to Randy
Fasani, their quarterback who lived close to me in Sacramento. I
told him he played a good game. He actually caught a pass against
us, playing tight end. I congratulated Ryan, gave him a hug, went
to the locker room and took my shower. People tend to make things
out of situations that aren't really there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elliott did concede that he was steamed over being taken out
late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I should have been pulled at that time,'' he
said. ``Obviously, I wasn't playing that good, but I don't think I
was playing bad enough to be taken out. But that's what the coaches
decided to do, so you have to live with that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first collegiate start, Elliott, a redshirt freshman, was
8 for 17 for 92 yards and an interception. But Coach Bruce Snyder
said he was not disappointed in the way Elliott played. Kealy, who
will start Saturday at Washington State, was 8 for 15 for 153 yards
(two of the incompletions were spikes) and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott, who changed high schools to give himself a better
chance at a scholarship, said he plans to remain a Sun Devil.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are rumors, just like the thing about me running off the
field,'' he said. ``But I'm going to stay around. I'm just happy
the team's back on track and focusing on Washington State.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott said he and Snyder met to discuss ``where each other
stood,'' and things are fine between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked each other some questions because we were a little
iffy on some areas,'' he said. ``But I think it worked out good.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Trying out the turf &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because Washington State's Martin Stadium has artificial turf,
this is the first week the Sun Devils are using their new,
Astroturf practice field. It came in handy earlier in the week,
when it rained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Sunday it was wet and windy with the storms that went
through, and it gave us perfect conditions to practice in for this
game,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the weather, we wouldn't have gotten as much
accomplished with the turf. We became much more comfortable with
the turf shoes and the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   But not without a footwear adjustment. The team came out in the
wrong kind of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The plastic grass also served another purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also saved our grass fields, because in the wet and muddy
weather, we really would have torn them up,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I like Astroturf on a regular basis? That's another story.
But so far, it has really served its purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The 70-yard field, located southeast of the two grass fields at
the Bill Kajikawa practice facility, cost $400,000. It was a gift
from an anonymous donor. &QL; 
 &QL; 
J.R. hurting &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If Tuesday was any indication, it doesn't look good for tailback
J.R. Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, nursing an ankle sprain, rode the bike and ran a
little, but did not participate in drills during what is usually
the most intense practice day of the week.
</P>
<P>
   He is second in the Pac-10 in rushing and third nationally in
all-purpose yardage.
</P>
<P>
   Another starter, safety Christon Rance, also was limited during
practice and is questionable for the game. &QL; 
 &QL; 
National leader &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Redshirt freshman Stephen Baker leads the nation in punting with
a 47.4-yard average. That ranks as the second-highest average in
conference history. ASU is eighth in the nation in net punting,
with a 40.5-yard average. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
