<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-FUTURE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON A NO-SHOW AT LOCAL GYM  
 BOXER'S TRAINING SCHEDULE INTERRUPTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Tyson has fights in court but none in the ring on his
schedule, which did not include an expected resumption of training
Tuesday at Phoenix's Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson left his equipment at the downtown gym 13 days ago amid
plans of returning for an extended stay in preparation for his
first fight since biting Evander Holyfield's ears on June 28, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The equipment is still there. But there's been no word from
either the former heavyweight champ or his ever-changing entourage
about his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard anything,'' said gym owner Richard Rodriquez,
who said he was told by Tyson that he would return not long after
the Nevada Athletic Commission agreed to re-instate his license.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ricardo, also of Madison Square Graden, said he been told
by Tyson that he would return Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Without a firm date for a fight, however, there's little reason
for Tyson to begin serious training. His absence Tuesday would seem
to eliminate any possibility of a bout Dec. 5, which had been
widely speculated throughout his five-day stay in the Valley and
during his re-licensing hearing 10 days ago at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   He probably would need six weeks to two months to prepare for
his first bout in nearly a year and a half. If he had begun working
Tuesday for a Dec. 5 bout, he would have had five weeks and three
days to get ready.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tyson's legal problems continued to mount. On Monday,
he was sued in Las Vegas by a police officer, Thomas Moyer, who
charges Tyson hit him during a melee seconds after his
disqualification for biting Holyfield. Moyer, an off-duty member of
a security team at the time, alleges Tyson struck him in the chest.
The suit asks for unspecified damages for physical pain and mental
anguish.
</P>
<P>
   The Moyer suit is on top of a potentially more serious legal
problem for Tyson, who already owes the Internal Revenue Service
$13 million and at least $7 million to former trainer Kevin Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Maryland has decided to proceed with misdemeanor
assault charges against him in a trial Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is alleged to have assaulted two middle-aged men after an
auto accident Aug. 31. A Tyson attorney said an out-of-court
settlement with the two men was likely. But the state decided to
proceed with charges because of Tyson's criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   He is on probation through March on a rape conviction. If he is
found guilty Dec. 1, he could be sent back to prison. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 0141EST &QL; 
