<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_RONNING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RONNING SOLIDIFIES 2ND LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ When Cliff Ronning checked into the Hilton Hotel in
San Jose last March, his name was swirling amid trade rumors that
proved to be bogus.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say his comfort zone was much improved on Tuesday,
when the team checked into the hotel for tonight's 8:30 meeting
with the Sharks at San Jose Arena on the heels of a 5-1 win over
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   He finished last season third on the team in scoring with 55
points, including a team-leading 44 assists, despite bouncing
between the second and third lines, depending upon whether Jeremy
Roenick played center or wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy I'm getting an opportunity to help us win
games,'' said Ronning, 33. ``It's definitely more satisfying when
you feel that you're really a contributor on a winning team.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, with Roenick firmly entrenched as the first-line
center and Craig Janney shipped off to Tampa Bay, Ronning is
centering the No. 2 line with Greg Adams and Rick Tocchet as his
wings.
</P>
<P>
   The team can't complain about the production it is getting from
the top two lines. The Coyotes have five players tied for the team
scoring lead with six points. All are members of the top two lines,
including first-line mates Keith Tkachuk, Roenick and Dallas Drake,
plus Ronning and Tocchet, both of whom have two goals and four
assists.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of top-six production the Coyotes are going to
need if they hope to better last season's 35-35-12 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is we're just starting to develop
cohesiveness as a line,'' Ronning said. ``We're getting used to
each other's habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is that we come out and be steady in every
game. We can be a backbone for the first line if we can just remain
consistent.''
</P>
<P>
   The only missing element at the moment, at least in terms of
scoring production, has been that of left wing Adams, a consistent
20- to 30-goal scorer during his career who has just one assist in
the first six games.
</P>
<P>
   Ronning, however, said there is no reason to doubt Adams'
production.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing hard,'' Ronning said. ``In fact, Gus (Adams'
nickname) does a lot of the dirty work that nobody really sees.
It's Gus who is digging out the puck and getting it to me and Rick
and setting up our shots or passes. I've been in the league long
enough to know before long it will be me or Rick who is down there
digging and getting the puck to Greg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only a matter of time. Greg's the kind of guy who will
start scoring goals in bunches when he gets going.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronning, like the Coyotes, returns to a city where he has
enjoyed great success. He has scored 44 points against the Sharks,
topped only by the 50 he has scored against Los Angeles and 45 he
has against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have a 7-1 record against the Sharks in their past
eight games, outscoring them, 34-14, with Tkachuk (17 points) and
Ronning (11) leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix was 4-0 against San Jose last season, with Tkachuk
scoring eight points and Ronning five.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Jose hasn't won yet (0-4-2) and will be fighting for its
life,'' Ronning said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
