<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 03:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0602 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NG-VIDEO-SFCHRON(WITH     10-28 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NG-VIDEO-SFCHRON(WITH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS CLIP FROM NG TRIAL SHOCKS SURVIVORS 
</HEADLINE>
 NG-TRIAL)   By HARRIET CHIANG  
 and JONATHAN CURIEL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard and Sharon O'Connor turned on the local news Monday
night to find out what had happened in the trial of Charles Ng,
charged with murdering their daughter and grandson in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   What they saw was a videotape of their daughter, Brenda, bound
to a chair, terrified and helpless, as her captors threatened to
rape and murder her. No one _ least of all the prosecutors in Ng's
trial _ had warned them it was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my God,'' Richard O'Connor cried as he and his wife
collapsed into tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were shocked,'' O'Connor said Tuesday from his home in
Coldwater, Mich. ``Not seeing your daughter all those years and
then seeing her in the chair. Here it comes on at 11 o'clock and
(Ng) is cutting the blouse off my daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge at Ng's trial allowed the media in for opening
statements, so the videos of Brenda O'Connor and another victim,
Kathleen Allen, were fair game for TV stations to show. Whether
their decision to do so was ethical or moral was a subject of much
debate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda O'Connor was 20 years old when she disappeared with her
husband and 2-year-old son in 1985. In the tape, shown in Orange
County Superior Court and on television stations across the
country, Ng's alleged partner, Leonard Lake, tells her, ``You will
work for us, you will cook for us, you will f _ for us . . . or
we'll take you outside, rape you and shoot you.''
</P>
<P>
   The O'Connors' shock at seeing their daughter quickly turned to
anger. They complained to the local station in Kalamazoo and were
no more happy with the Ng prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have shown a little decency in calling us up and
saying, `Mr. O'Connor, there's going to be something on the 11
o'clock news,' '' O'Connor said.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Dan Lungren, whose office is part of the
prosecution team, did not respond to phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible intrusion on the surviving family
members,'' said Peter Arenella, a criminal law professor at the
University of California at Los Angeles, who has written about
television distorting the criminal justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Arenella said a responsible news station could have given a
brief description of the videotape without showing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me this is being done purely for the shock value and the
appeal to people's prurient interest,'' Arenella said. ``It's
unhealthy and adds to this trend that we now have in using criminal
trials as entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Television news directors said it was a hard call to make. Some
stations showed only portions of the tape or blurred victims'
faces.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Francisco Bay Area, KPIX-TV decided to broadcast
excerpts because they ``are germane to what the prosecution was
saying, which was whether or not Ng could be connected to the
killings,'' said the station's news director, Daniel Webster.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to that,'' Webster said, ``even though it's not
pleasant, it demonstrates the severity and horrific aspect to the
crime. . . . We're about putting out good, accurate, truthful
information. Sometimes, that isn't always terribly pleasant
information. It's the definition of news.''
</P>
<P>
   Webster said the station had received some calls voicing concern
about its decision.
</P>
<P>
   KRON-TV did not show Ng cutting away O'Connor's shirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of discussion about it,'' said Dan Rosenheim,
KRON-TV's news director. ``Someone in our news department said that
it was almost like showing a snuff film on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we even showed less than what normal prudence would
dictate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   KGO-TV did not broadcast any of the tapes, calling them
``objectionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even veteran journalists who staunchly defend freedom of the
press anguished over the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm torn that this video exists where people, through no fault
of their own, are seen in horrifying circumstances,'' said Joe
Saltzman, associate director of the University of Southern
California's School of Journalism. ``But as a journalist, I don't
like anyone telling me what I can and what I can't see.''
</P>
<P>
   Saltzman, who has produced award-winning documentaries for CBS
and covered the Vietnam War, said matters of taste become ``a
minefield of disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why blame the news media?'' he said. ``Blame this horrible
rapist killer.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Keane, the chief attorney in the San Francisco public
defender's office, who is defending Ng on a separate murder charge
here, said there is no reason to show such powerful scenes to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing someone in that kind of distress with a total
sense of hopelessness, terror and anxiety,'' Keane said. ``And you
combine it with her anxiety for her baby _ it was gut-wrenching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To show that is to exploit the most poignant aspect of human
terror,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
