<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FONG-SNUBBED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAYS, RIGHT SNUB FONG'S UNITY TACTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLA MARINUCCI  
 and JOHN WILDERMUTH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    Attempts by GOP Senate candidate Matt Fong to ``unify'' gay
groups and the religious right backfired Tuesday as groups on each
side accused him of selling out to the other.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fong's unprecedented decision to sign a written pledge of
support for gay issues, reported in Tuesday's Chronicle, drew angry
responses from some conservative Christian groups over his
``apparent sellout of family values.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think that a person like Matt Fong would stand on
his principles and not have been forced to bend down and sign a
statement that goes against his beliefs,'' said Randy Thomasson,
political director at the conservative Capitol Resource Institute
in Sacramento. ``It seems pretty obvious that Matt Fong has either
changed his beliefs _ or is now showing us what he really
believes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike German, who heads the San Francisco Log Cabin Republicans,
was equally unforgiving of Fong's $50,000 donation to the
conservative Traditional Values Coalition, headed by the Rev. Lou
Sheldon, who has railed against the ``immoral homosexual agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps Matt Fong should find refuge in the Bible, if he's
going to use it as a source,'' said German. ``A man cannot serve
two masters.''
</P>
<P>
   With less than a week before the election, Fong's attempt to
appease both sides on one of the nation's hottest political issues
is a setback in his campaign to unseat Democratic Sen. Barbara
Boxer. The controversy battered his carefully crafted image as a
moderate and undercut his argument that _ unlike Boxer _ he is ``a
unifier, not a divider.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong, in San Francisco for a Chinatown fund-raiser, did not talk
about Sheldon Tuesday, but an aide dismissed the complaints from
conservative religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to a lot of conservative leaders today, and they're
all with Matt down the stretch,'' said Steve Schmidt, a spokesman
for Fong. ``They know that Matt Fong is a man of principle . . .
who wants to listen to both sides before he makes a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP strategists agreed that the Sheldon flap is unlikely to send
Republican conservatives fleeing to Boxer, whom they have been
anxious to send packing for six years, but they expressed concern
about the effect it will have on Fong's campaign plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that keeps you from getting your message out is a
problem, and this is a distraction,'' said one Republican
consultant. ``It's a real fluid race, and anything could change the
way it's going.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy began during the weekend, after Fong
acknowledged his $50,000 gift to Sheldon's anti-gay, anti-abortion
organization which, among other things, has advocated quarantine of
AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   The angry response from GOP gays and lesbians prompted Fong on
Monday to sign an unprecedented written pledge to support the
California Log Cabin Republicans on a wide range of gay issues,
including AIDS research, domestic partnership and
anti-discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   That pleased national and state Log Cabin Republicans, who said
Fong had proved himself to be a peacemaker and ``big tent''
Republican, but it failed to soothe the activist San Francisco
chapter, which has clashed often with Sheldon.
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps far more damaging to Fong's election hopes, it was
received badly by conservative Republicans who support family
values legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly has stirred up Christians, as far as
disappointment is concerned,'' said David Spady, executive director
of the California Christian Coalition. ``These are people who
worked very hard to gather signatures for the Defense of Marriage
Act, and certainly our organization is opposed to special rights
for sexual orientation.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to contact Sheldon were unsuccessful, but Thomasson of
the Capitol Resource Institute said his nonpartisan family values
advocacy organization was ``deluged'' by angry conservatives who
were ``shocked, angry and disappointed at this apparent sellout of
family values.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of the candidates is supporting traditional family
values. Both support the homosexual agenda,'' he said. ``And that
goes against what people want for their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservative voters, he said, ``are today almost as disappointed
with Matt Fong's pro-homosexual ideals as we are with Barbara
Boxer's loud and vivid pro-homosexual agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomasson said that if Fong's strategy was to court gays and
lesbians at the expense of conservative and evangelical voters _ a
block of several hundred thousand crucial state voters who are
unlikely to defect to Boxer, he has made a critical mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``No candidate can afford to take California families for
granted,'' Thomasson said. ``We do have principles that are
obviously higher than many of the candidates'.''
</P>
</TEXT>
