 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 408 - October 28, 1998  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY -- No. 408 -- Oct. 28, 1998 We are
offering the following articles for sale. Please contact us for
availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. ANNETTE BENING : DOING STARDOM HER WAY Actress Annette Bening
is also the wife of Warren Beatty and mother of his three children.
As she prepares for the opening of her new film ``The Siege,''
Bening talks about the film's controversial plot (involving Arab
terrorists and a hardline U.S. Army general,) how she manages to
juggle film stardom and motherhood, and why she thinks Hollywood's
obsession with age is unfair to women and to movies themselves. By
Ian Spelling. 1,400 words + photo. 2. PHIL COLLINS INTERVIEW : ``MY
LIFE AS A MOLE'' Pop singer Phil Collins discusses abuse from
critics, the worldwide success of his songs and the reasons why he
lives in Switzerland. By Wolfang Hoebel and Christoph Dallach. From
Der Spiegel. English translation available. Q&AMP;A format. 1,400
words. 3. OPERA'S DYNAMIC DUO Even for La Scala in Milan, home to
the world's most zealous opera fans, the booing suffered by soprano
Renee Fleming and tenor Marcello Giordani was remarkable. Here is
how two of opera's shinng stars survived the performance of
``Lucrezia Borgia'' and how they intend to scale the heights this
autumn. By Kevin West and Alessandra Ilari. From W magazine. 1,000
words + photo. 4. HECTOR ELIZONDO : KEEPING 'HOPE' ALIVE Hector
Elizondo has been nominated for four Emmys (winning one) for his
hit television show, ``Chicago Hope,'' and is as popular as ever in
movies, making him arguably America's most visible Hispanic actor.
Elizondo talks about the series, how fame has changed his life, why
he's about to begin his 11th film with director Garry Marshall and
what we should look for when he co-stars with Julia Roberts and
Richard Gere in ``Runaway Bride,'' (the not-quite-sequel to
``Pretty Woman.'') By Andrew Ryan. From Canadian TV Guide. 1,000
words + photo. 5. STAN TUCCI INTERVIEW ``As soon as somebody says,
``Don't do it the way you want to,'' I say, ``See you later,''
actor Stanley Tucci explains in his mellifluous voice that helped
make him so creepily convincing as suspected murderer Richard Cross
on television's ``Murder One.'' Tucci's roles have ranged from
Italian villain to the dogcatcher in ``Beethoven,'' Demi Moore's
husband in ``Deconstructing Harry,'' and an assassin in ``The
Pelican Brief.'' In this interview he talks about his two latest
starring roles. By Louise Farr. From W magazine. 1,600 words +
photo. 6. JOHN FRANKENHEIMER INTERVIEW According to John
Frankenheimer, the career of a Hollywood director goes through
three distinct phases : ``You go from the stage when people say,
'Who is John Frankenheimer?' to 'OK, we'll take a chance on
Frankenheimer' to 'Get Frankenheimer!'' Finally, however comes a
fourth : ``Get me a younger John Frankenheimer.'' The veteran
director (responsible for such major films as ``Birdman of
Alcatraz'' and ``The Manchurian Candidate,'') now returns with
``Ronin.'' Filmed in France, it is a suspense thriller that follows
a band of former Cold War operatives. ``The movie is about
betrayal, which in today's society is a very important subject,''
Frankenheimer says. By Natasha Fraser-Cavassoni. From W magazine.
1,000 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
ANDREAS VOLLENWEIDER'S HARPS OF MANY VOICES Swiss harpist Andreas
Vollenweider is on his first solo tour but takes with him enough
instruments to supply a large orchestra, including gothic harp,
Celtic harp, kora (African harp,) cheng (Chinese harp,) wind
chimes, gongs, piano, accordion, flute, saxophone. This New Age
pioneer even plays tuned salad bowls. By Steve Morse. From The
Boston Globe. 700 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
TODD SOLONDZ'S PRESCRIPTION FOR 'HAPPINESS' ``Happiness'' may be
the most ironic movie title of the '90s. This controversial film is
a bleak, unsparing and yet relentlessly comic look at several
citizens of New Jersey whose lives are defined by sexuality.
Director Todd Solondz says he prefers the expression ``sad comedy''
to ``black comedy,'' but ``Happiness'' is about as dark as they
come .... By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words + photo. 9. SHARON
STONE: UNGLAMOROUS IN 'THE MIGHTY' For her newest film, ``The
Mighty,'' Sharon Stone agreed to appear as an unglamorous
working-class mother, so enchanted was she by the story of two
handicapped boys who share a love for the King Arthur legend. Stone
discusses the film, (which she produced,) as well as her marriage
to San Francisco journalist Phil Bronstein. By Ivor Davis. 1,000
words + photos. (N/A Great Britain and Australia.) Please fax to
Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81 I am interested in story
no. ______ from summary 408 Name : ____________________________
Publication : _________________________ Country :
___________________ Fax : ___________________ Tel : ______________
email
________________________________________________________________
