<SLUG> BC-THE-BIG-APPLE-TOUR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S DOING IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact one of the following sales
representatives:
 &HT;    (_ U.S. and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
 &HT;    (_ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (_ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at (310)
996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
 &HT;    Two color slides are available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
 &HT;    ---------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By AMY WALDMAN 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    The runners of the New York Marathon may be masochistic, but
they are not stupid: They run in the fall. After all, if you are
going to see the five boroughs as a blur while gasping for breath,
you might as well do it when the colors are crisp and the air
brisk.
 &HT;    Attitudes are brisk, too: When the heat leaves, the locals
return, their hunger to master the universe recharged.
 &HT;    The roaring '90s continue in New York, and in an appropriately
fin de siecle paradox, the city is both prospering and
deteriorating.
 &HT;    The proof is in the number of buildings going up _ witness the
construction boom around Times Square _ and the number falling
down, as suggested by a recent report calling for $90 billion in
infrastucture fixes in the city (and by the bricks peeling off old
buildings and onto the streets below).
 &HT;    The one adjective that does not apply to New York is static.
Neighborhoods molt and acquire new identities so fast that you can
blink and miss the metamorphoses.
 &HT;    The downtown commercial art scene is moving to Chelsea, while
young designers are forsaking SoHo for NoLIta, north of Little
Italy. Brooklyn and Queens, too, have taken on new cachet, as
places both to live and to visit.
 &HT;    After summer's lazy dress rehearsal, fall is when the show
begins, literally, with a new cultural season. There is a
head-spinning selection of art, theater, music and dance.
 EVENTS  
 &HT;    Two of the 20th century's greatest Abstract Expressionists are
the subjects of big retrospectives this fall.
 &HT;    Mark Rothko's early Surrealist works and color-saturated
canvases are on view in ``Mark Rothko: A Retrospective,'' at the
Whitney Museum of American Art, 945 Madison Ave., at 75th Street,
through Nov. 29.
 &HT;    This year the Whitney also opened 11 intimate galleries focusing
on art from 1900 to 1950. Open Wednesday, Friday, Saturday and
Sunday from 11 a.m. to 6 p.m., and Thursday from 1 to 8 p.m.
Admission is $9; (212) 570-3676.
 &HT;    ``Jackson Pollock: A Retrospective,'' from Nov. 1 to Feb. 2 at
the Museum of Modern Art, at 11 West 53d St., is the first
retrospective of Pollock's work since 1967, and covers his entire
career. Open daily except Wednesday 10:30 a.m. to 6 p.m., and to
8:30 p.m. on Friday. Admission: $9.50; (212) 708-9400.
 &HT;    So far, this Broadway season offers no new spectacle like the
``Lion King'' or must-have ticket like ``Cabaret.''
 &HT;    At Lincoln Center's Vivian Beaumont Theater, Harold Prince is
directing ``Parade,'' a new musical based on the true story of Leo
Frank, a Jewish factory worker accused of murdering a 13-year-old
girl in Georgia in 1913. Previews begin Nov. 12. Tickets: $50 to
$75; (212) 239-6200.
 &HT;    Dance assumes center stage in several productions.
``Footloose,'' the 1984 movie about the standoff between a
small-town preacher and a high-stepping outsider, is now a Broadway
musical, co-written and directed by Walter Bobbie, who won a Tony
for his direction of ``Chicago.'' It's at the Richard Rodgers, 226
West 46th St. Tickets: $20 to $75; (212) 307-4100.
 &HT;    And ``Swan Lake'' came to Broadway this month in a version by
Matthew Bourne, the British choreographer and director, at the Neil
Simon Theater at 250 West 52d Street. The production won raves in
London and Los Angeles. The twist: all the dancers are men _
wearing feathery pantaloons, not tutus. Tickets: $15 to $75; (212)
307-4100.
 &HT;    The most controversial ticket of the season promises to be
``Corpus Christi'' by Terrence McNally, starring an as yet unknown
actor, Anson Mount.
 &HT;    The play centers on a gay Jesus-like figure and was briefly
called off earlier this year after protests by the Catholic League
and anonymous bomb threats. A Manhattan Theater Club production, it
is at City Center, 131 West 55th St. Tickets are $50; (212)
581-1212.
 &HT;    In early December, the Brooklyn Philharmonic performs a
semistaged version of ``Powder Her Face,'' a new opera by the
English composer Thomas Ades about the life of Margaret, Duchess of
Argyll, whose sensational divorce rocked England in the 1960s. At
the Brooklyn Academy of Music's Majestic Theater, Dec. 8, 10, and
12. Tickets: $20 to $45; (212) 307-4100.
 &HT;    On Nov. 12 and 14, at Alice Tully Hall, Jazz at Lincoln Center
presents ``Blues Up and Down: A Battle in the Bucket,'' with jazz
elder statesmen like Teddy Edwards and Al Grey trying to outdo
younger talents like Cyrus Chestnut and Nicholas Payton. Tickets:
$37.50; (212) 721-6500.
 SIGHTSEEING  
 &HT;    The Lower East Side Tenement Museum offers one-hour historical
walking tours of a neighborhood that is gentrifying faster than a
New York apartment rents.
 &HT;    The tours leave from 90 Orchard St. and run weekends at 1:30 and
2: 30 p.m. through December; tickets $8. The museum also offers
frequent tours of its Tenement House, an 1863 building with
recreated apartments as they would have been during the 1870s,
1916, and the 1930s; (212) 431-0233.
 &HT;    There is no better time than fall to explore Fort Tryon Park,
which is also home to the rich medieval offerings of the Cloisters,
the upper Manhattan branch of the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
 &HT;    The only thing missing is the Unicorn tapestries, which have
been removed until January while the museum undergoes renovations.
Open Tuesday to Sunday, 9:30 a.m. until 5:15 p.m. through October,
to 4:45 p.m. after November. Admission: $8; (212) 923-3700.
 &HT;    The Wollman Rink in Central Park opened for ice skating on Oct.
15. With buildings rising like castle spires behind the trees,
there are few more magical settings for exercise _ north of the
entrance at Central Park South and Avenue of the Americas.
Admission: $4; (212) 396-9203.
 &HT;    In Chelsea, the West 20s between 10th Avenue and the Hudson
River have filled with dozens of galleries. You can start an
informal walking tour at the Dia Center for the Arts, at 548 West
22d St., now showing works by Robert Irwin and Joseph Beuys, and
then meander through the surrounding blocks.
 &HT;    The shops of NoLIta, the surreally quiet, oddly self-contained
blocks of Elizabeth, Mulberry and Mott between Spring and Houston,
seem made as much for looking as for buying. Stores include a glass
blower (Michael Anchin, at 250 Elizabeth St.), a milliner (Kelly
Christy, at 235 Elizabeth St.), and nearly two dozen eclectic
clothing stores.
 WHERE TO STAY  
 &HT;    Many hotels offer weekend specials or even discounted regular
rates, but occupancy rates in New York are so high _ 83 percent
this year _ that reservations are important. These hotels are
either new or recently renovated:
 &HT;    One look at the green carpet and the portrait of Mary McAlees,
the president of Ireland, on the wall, and you'll get the theme at
the Fitzpatrick Grand Central Hotel, which opened in August at 141
East 44th Street; (212) 351-6800, fax (212) 818-1747. The rooms are
not green, but tastefully decorated with canopied beds. Doubles
start at $325.
 &HT;    The Roger Williams, 131 Madison Ave., at 31st Street, was built
around 1928 but was thoroughly renovated last fall. Its sleek,
modern lobby includes a 20-foot atrium, and its 209 minimalist
rooms are done in white and beige with blond wood, and equipped
with CD players and VCRs. Doubles from $245; (212) 448-7000; fax:
(212) 448-7007.
 &HT;    The Algonquin, 59 West 44th St., (212) 840-6800; fax (212)
944-1419, finished a major renovation this year with an accent on
nostalgia. The lobby has been darkened to evoke an air of
antiquity, and the halls have been wallpapered with New Yorker
cartoons, a self-conscious reminder of the hotel's history as a
literary gathering place.
 &HT;    The Rose Room has been absorbed into the lobby, but the Round
Table remains. Guest rooms retain an old New York feel, with pewter
blue and cream decor, antiques, and headboards carved of dark wood.
Doubles: $329.
 &HT;    Budget: The Bentley Hotel, 500 East 62d St., (212) 644-6000, fax
(212) 207-4800, near the Roosevelt Island tram, has made the
transformation from office building to hotel with admirable grace.
It has a small reading library in the lobby, and its 229 rooms are
modern, spacious and simple. The higher floors have sweeping views
of the city. Doubles start at $195.
 &HT;    The New York Marriott Brooklyn, 333 Adams St., (718) 246-7000,
fax (718) 222-6535, is the borough's first new hotel in nearly 70
years, and a convenient base for exploring either Brooklyn or
Manhattan. It is a short walk from six subway lines and the
Brooklyn Bridge. The 374 rooms are comfortably furnished, with
unusually high ceilings, and there is a health club and pool.
Doubles start at $229.
 &HT;    Luxury: Even a grand dame needs an occasional make-over. The
Waldorf-Astoria and Waldorf Towers, 301 Park Ave. at 50th Street,
has just completed a renovation that, among other things, uncovered
original mosaics and murals in the Park Avenue lobby, transformed
Oscar's from a coffee shop into a softly lighted Art Deco bistro,
and created a new lounge in the Towers. Doubles start at $295 main,
$425 Towers; (212) 355-3000, fax (212)872-7272.
 WHERE TO EAT  
 &HT;    Park View at the Boathouse: the Loeb Boathouse in Central Park
has a new restaurant featuring Asian-influenced American cuisine to
complement its bucolic lakeside setting. It will stay open all
year, offering outdoor dining (with heaters) until Nov. 1, then
moving inside, where fireplaces have been installed. Dinner for two
with wine is about $150; (212) 517-2233.
 &HT;    Occupying the Coach House's former home, at 110 Waverly Place in
Greenwich Village, is Babbo, a modern Italian restaurant both
elegant and casual that combines unusual ingredients in unorthodox
ways; specialties include such pastas as mint love letters with
spicy lamb sausage, spicy ``Sicilian lifeguard'' two-minute
calamari, and saffron pannacotta with poached peaches and lemon
balm. Dinner for two, with wine, is about $130; (212) 777-0303.
 &HT;    If you want to sample the ``new'' Lower East Side, try Torch, a
supper club and lounge, at 137 Ludlow Street, which features South
American-influenced French cuisine, including a well-spiced
hamburger and popcorn-topped ceviche.
 &HT;    Along with the banquettes and sultry lighting, the attraction is
the array of torch singers who perform jazz standards nightly.
Dinner for two with wine costs about $90; (212) 228-5151.
 &HT;    After a hike over the Brooklyn Bridge (breathtaking even with
traffic rumbling below _ and, of course, free), warm up at
Grimaldi's, on 19 Old Fulton St. a cobblestone's throw from the
bridge. In the endless debate over the city's best pizza,
Grimaldi's is a front-runner; acolytes line up outside. Dinner for
two with wine is $30; (718) 858-4300.
 &HT;    At Gabriela's, 685 Amsterdam Ave., a casual, friendly Mexican
restaurant, you can get a savory roasted half-chicken _ with ample
side dishes like rice, beans and guacamole, for $6.50. It offers
traditional dishes like baby cactus salad and pozole, the filling
Mexican soup made with hominy. Dinner for two, with margaritas:
$25; (212) 961-0574.
 &HT;     (Amy Waldman is a reporter on the metropolitan desk of The
Times.)  
