</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Thursday, October 29, 1998 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   CERABINO-COLUMN _ What would the real Moses say? He'd probably
be embarrassed. After all he'd done. To end up like this: a shill
for the National Rifle Association. Maybe you've heard the radio
ad. It begins with NRA front-man Charlton Heston's voice, saying
``As Moses, I led my people to the promised land . . .'' But it
doesn't hit the high harmonics of nonsense, until Heston wraps back
to: ``I can part the Red Sea, but I can't make criminals pay for
their crimes without your help.'' Somewhere, the real Moses must be
cringing, and begging his boss, ``Please, let me smite this actor!
Please! Just this once!'' Heston's gone far with his Moses movie
role. But tying Moses into gun control is, well . . . too far.
(Cerabino, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ MONTE CARLO, Monaco _ I sit in the outdoor cafe
in the shadow of the Casino du Monte Carlo surrounded by the
beautiful people of Monaco. If I am ever to stand out in a crowd,
this is the crowd. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ Editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel)
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ Does Round Rock already have too darned many
things for vacationers to take in as it is? Or is there room for
growth in Round Rock's tourist industry? I say there's space to
squeeze in a baseball team among the other highlights. Look at the
top 10 tourist attractions in Round Rock, and make up your own
mind. (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ The headline on the story about political
contributions the other day really struck me. It siad, ``Georgia
'fat cat' contributors only make a small meow.' Add my family to
that small meow list. We always put a political contribution in the
budget, along with a tithe for the church. But looking at today's
contributors I am woefully embarrassed. The Home Depot chairman and
his wife, $52,500, for goodness' sake! (Sibley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ SESTRIERE, Italy _ In the march of time armies
commanded by Roman rulers, Celtic kings, European nobles, Christian
crusaders, Napoleon I, Nazis and others have come this valley. To
those bygone warriors, the surrounding mountains looked dangerous
and forbidding. To me, lounging in the morning sun in front of an
Alpine cafe amid the smells of cappuccino and fresh-baked Italian
bread, the same scenery looks postcard perfect, which you can buy
for about 1,000 Italian lira on postcards all around the village.
The Italians ought to do something about their money. I nearly get
a heart attack when my lunch bill says I owe 40,900. (Nethaway,
Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
