<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0935 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRGINITY-CHECK-PASTO     10-28 0445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRGINITY-CHECK-PASTOR29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pastor who performed `virginity check' on teen faces prison
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A pastor who performed a ``virginity
check'' on a teenage member of his Delray Beach church was found
guilty Tuesday of felony sexual activity with a child and faces 12
years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Pastor Joseph Millien, 51, sat erect and motionless as the
verdict was read. He undid his tie and calmly passed it to his
attorney when the judge revoked his bond and ordered him jailed
until sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   The charge is a first degree felony because the jury found found
Millien was acting in the role of a pastor and custodian of the
girl when she was molested in church offices. The pastor was
acquitted of another count of disrobing and rubbing against the
17-year-old girl in a second encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Church members said virginity checks on girls is a cultural
practice in Haiti, where Millien lived before moving to Delray
Beach in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Haiti it's not against the law,'' said Marie Rodriguez, a
member of Millien's Full Gospel Assembly Church. ``All the parents
do that to their children.''
</P>
<P>
   In a confession he later retracted, Millien told Delray Beach
detectives in 1997 that he tested the girl's virginity even though
he had no medical expertise. He denied having any other sexual
contact with the girl.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors, who asked to re-hear the taped confession during their
two hours of deliberation, reached verdicts that matched Millien's
own words as to what he did and didn't do to the girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jury obviously listened to the statement,'' Assistant
State Attorney Andy Slater said. ``I am pleased with the verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   The felony carries a maximum 30 years in prison but sentencing
guidelines call for six to 12 years for first-time offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Millien's attorney, Richard Lubin, said he was disappointed
Circuit Judge Howard Berman would not allow him to bring witnesses
before the jury to say that the charges against Millien were
motivated by a group seeking to take control of his 250-member
church.
</P>
<P>
   Lubin said the witnesses would have testified they were offered
money by Millien's enemies if they accused him of sexual
misconduct. Three females testified in court that the pastor
sexually abused them, but two of the incidents were in the late
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge denied our defense,'' Lubin said. ``We feel we have
an excellent (case for) appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman ordered Millien to jail until sentencing in about 30
days. Lubin said he will request a bond hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
