   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   NEWS-QUESTIONS _Q&AMP;A on the news, in two takes. (Bessonnette,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) (l, a). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-SIZES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ How clothing sizes are
revamped to fit our expanding selves. WITH BOX comparing sizes at
the mall. (Anna, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WILD-EYES-CONTACTS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ WildEyes are
contact lenses with attitude. They'll make your eyes look like
8-balls, or like cats eyes, or like the whited-out eyes of a fiend.
(Benarde, Palm Beach Post). 10. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BILLY-GRAHAM _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The fiery oratory that
once scared us into believing is gone. Now, a grandfather's
soothing voice urges the faithful to confess Christ. Billy Graham
has grown old. That was clear at his latest crusade last weekend in
Tampa. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post). 15. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-KID-BIRTHDAY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ My daughter has
leukemia. Doctors have warned us that the worst might happen, but
my wife, Judie, and I try not to think about that. Instead, we talk
only about the best-case scenario: After three years of
gut-wrenching chemotherapy treatments, Nicki will be cured. Even
so, it's hard. (Neal, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOSONETTO-COLUMN _ At this time of year airlines offer seemingly
perpetual airfare sales to Europe. Most sales have ticketing
deadlines, but they are often extended from week to week through
March. (Bosonetto, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HEATHER _ ATLANTA _ She's already blown away the critics in
``Elaborate Lives: The Legend of Aida.'' Now actress Heather
Headley talks about her trek to star in the Elton John-Tim Rice
musical. The 24-year-old Trinidad native was plucked out of
Northwestern for ``Ragtime,'' then had Disney fighting Livent to
get her out of her contract for ``Lion King.'' Though dealing with
``Sybil,'' the glitchy ``Aida'' pyramid was tough, it was nothing
compared to two sprained ankles and stress fractures in both legs
for ``Lion King.'' But her biggest worry was this: After getting
used to standing ovations every night for ``Ragtime'' and ``Lion
King,'' she had to get ready for the first ``Elaborate Lives''
public performance, wondering if this would be the first time she
ended a show... and the first time she would see an audience still
sitting. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOO _ ATLANTA _ We examine the trend of trick-or-treating in
malls. Seems to have begun in the '80s; now it's well-established.
All the local malls, and even grocery stores, do it. (Hill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15. MOVED
</P>
