<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0948 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-1029-C     10-28 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-KOSOVO-1029-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: FOR KOSOVO REFUGEES, SIMPLEST NEEDS TOUGH TO COME BY
 &HT;    With photo mug of Roughton available in International folder on
the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Oct. 29 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VRAGOBIL, Yugoslavia _ I watch the villages of central Kosovo
pass by from a Yugo driven by a guy I hired in Pristina, the
province capital.
</P>
<P>
   We're traveling a main road through hilly farmland. It's
familiar scenery, reminding me of the pretty rolling country around
the Ozark or Appalachian mountains back home. It's sunny and warm,
even hot in the car.
</P>
<P>
   It's an eerie place with no people, as if there has been some
terrible germ warfare that wiped out the humans but spared the
cattle, chickens and dogs.
</P>
<P>
   I've spent the morning trying to assess how things are going for
the thousands of people who have abandoned these villages for fear
of being caught in the wicked fighting between Yugoslavia's Serb
forces and the ragged soldiers of the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA).
</P>
<P>
   My assessment is pretty simple: These people need to get home
and make ready for winter while they still have good weather.
</P>
<P>
   On a day such as this, you could climb up on a roof and put some
plastic or canvas over the shell holes, and get something to cover
the windows. You could set aside some food from the relief
organizations, maybe even store some drinking water. You could get
the kids in some kind of decent shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that isn't happening. Kosovo's ethnic Albanian
refugees, frightened and exhausted by months of struggle, are
digging in where they are -- three and four families in dark
airless rooms in the few houses in the few villages overlooked in
the fighting. The rooms, though kept neat by constant maternal
labor, are breeding places for house flies and other bugs. There is
always the faint smell of feces and urine. Always.
</P>
<P>
   When you pull up to these houses, the first people you see are
children. They get as close as they can without touching you. They
seem fascinated by the look of the foreigner, with his clean jeans
and shiny boots, scrawling notes. They study his color photo mug on
a plastic card dangling by a chain from his neck.
</P>
<P>
   They wear dirty Chicago Bulls sweatshirts, My Little Pony
t-shirts and New York Yankees caps. I wonder if these things came
in donated packages, the former play outfits of some American kids
who tossed them in the bottom of their closets only to be delivered
by their mothers to some charity.
</P>
<P>
   I feel a pang from the flashback of the trash bags of clothes,
shoes and such that I hauled to my curb in Atlanta last summer
before moving to London. I'd give anything to see my boys' barely
worn things on these sweet-faced children.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hard thing when you are used to having children around.
It's normal to play with them, dress them, feed them and doctor
their wounds. These children need these things too, but where do
you start?
</P>
<P>
   You could go a lifetime in America without struggling with such
a question, clicking past the faces of starving children on the way
to HBO. You want to tune them out so that you can live your life
with only your own burden to carry.
</P>
<P>
   We have become a soft people, unhardened by war and want, so
just looking at these faces causes despair, a helpless feeling that
is abhorrent to someone so comfortable. It hurts too much.
</P>
<P>
   And places like this war-torn province in southern Yugoslavia
are thankfully easy to ignore. The politics are too messy to sort
out when you're already up to your neck in worrying about how
you'll pay for a good college or the many other pressing matters of
American life. And there's plenty of misery in America should the
spirit ever move you.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for me, there's comfort in the limitations of being
only a newspaper reporter. My job sets a limit on what is required
of me, which is no more than telling people like you about places
like this.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I've done that.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
