<HEADER>
A0957 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CERABINO-COLUMN29-COX     10-28 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bringing Moses into gun control fight a step too far
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would the real Moses say?
</P>
<P>
   He'd probably be embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   After all he'd done. To end up like this: a shill for the
National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've heard the radio ad.
</P>
<P>
   If not, don't worry. There'll be plenty of other opportunities
before Tuesday's election.
</P>
<P>
   It begins with NRA front-man Charlton Heston's voice, saying
``As Moses, I led my people to the promised land . . .''
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't hit the high harmonics of nonsense, until Heston
wraps back to: ``I can part the Red Sea, but I can't make criminals
pay for their crimes without your help.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, the real Moses must be cringing, and begging his
boss, ``Please, let me smite this actor! Please! Just this once!''
</P>
<P>
   Heston's gone far with his Moses movie role. But tying Moses
into gun control is, well . . . too far.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of the ad is a Florida constitutional amendment
aimed to keep crooks and lunatics from buying firearms at gun
shows, the ubiquitous weekend flea markets of unregulated mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   A loophole in the state law exempts gun shows from complying
with any county laws requiring background checks and
three-to-five-day waiting periods on gun sales.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional amendment would close the loophole.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of law that makes sense, unless you happen to
stake out the position that practically any form of gun control is
immoral and unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the NRA does.
</P>
<P>
   And so does the group's candidate for governor, Jeb ``Burning''
Bush, who's planted himself on the fake-Moses side of this issue.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA thinks defeating constitutional Revision 12 on Tuesday's
ballot is important enough to unleash Heston on us and spend at
least $150,000 in radio ads.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't know what Revision 12 was about, you'd never know
from listening to the Heston ad.
</P>
<P>
   He never mentions the words ``gun show'' or ``gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he talks about how ``crimes that are now felonies under
state law could be reduced to mere misdemeanors, putting many
dangerous criminals right back on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   I think the real Moses returned from the mountain with a
commandment that addressed statements like that.
</P>
<P>
   As for gun control, it's hard to say exactly what the real
Moses' position would be. The Old Testament is silent on the
subject of the registration of firearms at Florida gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   But upon further inspection and study, I've come to the
conclusion that the real Moses would be opposed to the position
staked out by Heston and the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   In Moses' day, they didn't have guns. They had ``rods.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Old Testament is full of advice about how rods should be
used.
</P>
<P>
   In Numbers 17:2, the Lord tells Moses: ``Write thou every man's
name upon his rod.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like centralized registration of firearms to me.
</P>
<P>
   And consider this, from Exodus 4:2
</P>
<P>
   ``And the Lord said unto him, What is that in thine hand? And he
said, A rod. And he said, Cast it on the ground. And he cast it on
the ground, and it became a serpent; and Moses fled from before
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rods turning into serpents.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't sound very pro-gun to me.
</P>
<P>
   And while we're in Exodus, there's that bit about ``three days
journey into the wilderness, that we may sacrifice.''
</P>
<P>
   Three-day sacrifice?
</P>
<P>
   Three-day waiting period for guns.
</P>
<P>
   It's all starting to make sense.
</P>
<P>
   The real Moses wouldn't agree with Heston, at all.
</P>
<P>
   He'd be mortified.
</P>
<P>
   So I feel sorry for the real Moses.
</P>
<P>
   To be reduced to a pawn in the broken-promise land of politics
is a horrible way to end up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
