<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's space to squeeze in stadium at Round Rock
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does Round Rock, Texas, the Gateway to Hutto, need yet another
tourist attraction?
</P>
<P>
   The question is becoming important because on Tuesday, Round
Rock voters will go to the polls to decide whether to use $7.3
million of their hotel-motel bed tax money to help build a $13
million minor league baseball stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Does Round Rock already have too darned many things for
vacationers to take in as it is? Or is there room for growth in
Round Rock's tourist industry?
</P>
<P>
   I say there's space to squeeze in a baseball team among the
other highlights. Look at the top 10 tourist attractions in Round
Rock, and make up your own mind.
</P>
<P>
   Here are my picks for the top 10 things to see and do in the
Round Rock O Plex.
</P>
<P>
   Hairy Man Road: Get off northbound Interstate 35 at exit 253,
cross the highway, then head west on Sam Bass Road until you get to
Hairy Man Road. A beautiful drive with trees drooping over the
road, some say Hairy Man Road is named after a legendary hairy man
who came out of the bushes after dark to scare the bejeepers out of
people.
</P>
<P>
   It's kind of like Austin's Sixth Street thing, except Hairy Man
Road is out in the country. So, unlike in Austin's entertainment
district, the hairy guy along Hairy Man Road won't hit you up for
spare change.
</P>
<P>
   Garden Ridge Pottery, northwest corner of I-35 and FM 1325,
I-35's Exit 250:
</P>
<P>
   A 140,000-square foot crafts store filled with women looking for
such items as Beanie Baby Bunk Beds, Garden Ridge Pottery offers a
selection of lovely concrete yard statuary, including toadstools.
</P>
<P>
   Also available are decorative four-foot-high metal suits of
armor for $48.88 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are just tin; we just call them our tin men,'' said
Dalton Roberts, the general sales manager.
</P>
<P>
   You're probably wondering why anyone would buy one of these
hollow knight suits, since they're too small for most people to
squeeze into. They're for home decoration, Roberts explained. Just
the ticket, one supposes, if you're fixing to put a moat and
drawbridge around your house.
</P>
<P>
   The Tap, Exit 252B:
</P>
<P>
   Located downtown, just off the intersection of Main and Mays
streets, this tiny beer joint has a message on the front door that
reads, ``Men only. 11-10.''
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean women don't get to come in until after 10 at
night, or what?
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they leave the seat up on the toilet, they're all
right. They can stay,'' joked Frankie Brown, one of the bar's
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Best sign in town, on a wall at The Tap:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I die, I want to go peacefully in my sleep like my
grandfather, not screaming in terror like the other people in his
car.''
</P>
<P>
   The water tower downtown:
</P>
<P>
   Looming in the sky across the street from The Tap, the old
unused water tower has very little water in it. It has been left
standing for aesthetic reasons, said Jim Nuse, director of public
works.
</P>
<P>
   Nuse added that a man named Boxey Elam who now lives in Lampasas
was the only person in town who would climb the water tower to
change the light bulb on top. Elam, Nuse says, is about 80 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that light goes out, I keep telling him he's got to get his
climbing shoes on,'' Nuse said.
</P>
<P>
   Impromptu car show, Renaissance Square strip mall, in front of
the Antique Mall of Texas, Exit 251:
</P>
<P>
   Every Saturday night, says Round Rock Mayor Charlie Culpepper,
you can find a bunch of auto enthusiasts gathered in the parking
lot here to look at each others' classic cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh man, you've got the Chevies and the Fords and the
Studebakers,'' Culpepper said. ``It's just everybody comes out
there and pops their hoods. It's been going on for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The markers on Main Street, Exit 252B:
</P>
<P>
   In 1878, outlaw Sam Bass died in a Main Street shootout here.
The eight numbered metal markers, set into the bricks of the
sidewalk, identify various critical spots in the event. They were
once part of a Chamber of Commerce walking tour.
</P>
<P>
   The actual rock for which the town is named, in Brushy Creek on
Chisholm Trail Road, Exit 252B:
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead and laugh, if you want, at a town being named for a
rock. But look at it this way. At least it's not one of those deals
where the town is named after something that doesn't exist, like
Lake City, Iowa. The town motto there is: ``Everything but the
lake.''
</P>
<P>
   To get to the table-shaped rock, take RM 620 west, then turn
right at the light at Chisholm Trail Road and go to Brushy Creek.
</P>
<P>
   You'll know it when you see it. It's the round, table-shaped
rock sticking out of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star Bakery, 106 W. Liberty St., downtown, Exit 252B:
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only bakery in the world that sells great orange
doughnuts from a drive-up window.
</P>
<P>
   The frame house where the horror classic ``The Texas Chainsaw
Massacre'' was filmed, on Quick Hill Road:
</P>
<P>
   Robert Burns, art director for the movie, says he's not sure if
the house is still standing. He says it was pretty dilapidated the
last time he saw it a couple years ago. But you couldn't get to it
anyway, since the part of old County Road 172 that led up to it is
now closed, Culpepper said.
</P>
<P>
   So let's play ball.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
