<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Funny money needs fixing in Italy
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SESTRIERE, Italy _ In the march of time armies commanded by
Roman rulers, Celtic kings, European nobles, Christian crusaders,
Napoleon I, Nazis and others have come this valley.
</P>
<P>
   To those bygone warriors, the surrounding mountains looked
dangerous and forbidding.
</P>
<P>
   To me, lounging in the morning sun in front of an Alpine cafe
amid the smells of cappuccino and fresh-baked Italian bread, the
same scenery looks postcard perfect, which you can buy for about
1,000 Italian lira on postcards all around the village.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians ought to do something about their money. I nearly
get a heart attack when my lunch bill says I owe 40,900.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in lira, right?'' I ask the waiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   People everywhere can say ``OK,'' ``Coca-Cola'' and ``no
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a very big problem if my American Express bill shows
that my lunch cost as much as a new luxury car. It was good, but
not that good.
</P>
<P>
   I can see my ``no-problem'' waiter and his girlfriend slicing
through the Alps on their new flame-red Ducatis, bought with my
lunch money.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of motorcycles, this is motorcycle heaven. Here, you
are guaranteed to wear out sides of your tires first.
</P>
<P>
   A young man I met at breakfast said Sestriere is included in a
three-valley loop that motorcycle riders out of Turin like to ride.
</P>
<P>
   They usually ride in groups. They wear full-faced helmets and
multi-colored race leathers. No Harley Davidsons here. These bikers
ride race-replica crotch rockets and tear through the mountains
like they are chased by demons.
</P>
<P>
   Like racers, they lean off their bikes into the turns, often
dragging a knee. They pass on hills and curves and split lanes
between traffic on narrow roads.
</P>
<P>
   The first day I encountered these Alpine road racers, I had been
concentrating on throwing my rented 5-speed Renault into the curves
when the first of a string of motorcycles screamed past only inches
from my left ear.
</P>
<P>
   I nearly wrecked trying to watch them and keep my car on the
road at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't a lot of motorcycle riders get killed around here?'' I
asked my young breakfast companion, who also rides a motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   He thought a moment as though he was trying to give me an
accurate estimate of the fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``Not in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   This, I felt, added weight to of my theory about America's
obsession with safety laws.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than allow Americans to assume responsibility for our own
safety, and thereby develop the skills needed to avoid injury, the
United States relies on safety nannies and spineless politicians
who heap safety laws on top of safety regulations to keep people
from hurting themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Americans are a danger to themselves and others
whenever they are forced to deal with life outside the tight,
little safety cocoon constructed for them by suffocating government
safety nannies.
</P>
<P>
   I saw an occasional speed limit sign in the Alps. Only farm
tractors and cows obeyed them.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding wrecks and fender-benders in Europe has more to do with
confidence in your fellow motorists and blending in with the
surrounding traffic rather than with posted signs, rules and
regulations that substitute for common sense and driving skill in
America.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude pumps money into government coffers as a result of
excessive fines and even more money into the pockets of personal
injury lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Europe has good scenery, good bread, good coffee and good
drivers. Next time, I'm bringing my motorcycle
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
