<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLY-GRAHAM29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Graham keeps the faith, if not the brimstone
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The fiery oratory that once scared us
into believing is gone. Now, a grandfather's soothing voice urges
the faithful to confess Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Graham has grown old.
</P>
<P>
   That was clear at his latest crusade last weekend in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   The sermon was the same, Graham's conviction was obvious, but
his sense of urgency was no longer palpable.
</P>
<P>
   He once paced a mile or more back and forth across the stage to
drive home his sermon calling sinners to repent. He preached a
simple _ his few critics say simplistic _ version of Christianity
for more than 60 years to hundreds of millions of people.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the 79-year-old evangelist has Parkinson's disease. He
walks with a cane and sits on a high stool behind the podium to
preach. His voice is calm, almost pleading; his demeanor gentle and
self-effacing.
</P>
<P>
   In Tampa, he reminisced about earlier crusades. He told personal
stories and invited people to join him in a faith that has given
him peace. There was none of the hell fire and brimstone of the
younger Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you remember anything from these meetings,'' Graham urged
Friday night, ``remember that God loves you.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowds still come. More than 50,000 people gathered on each
of four nights at the Raymond James Stadium that is home to the
Tampa Bay Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 80,000 overflowed the 65,000-seat stadium at the last
meeting on Sunday. Extra seating with remote television was set up
in a parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham was preaching to the choir. Most of the audience
seemed already converted. They came to be part of history. They
came to be with an evangelical icon of enormous stature in a tribal
celebration of Protestant Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   A Billy Graham crusade is a form of evangelical fervor that he,
almost alone in the universe of preachers, made respectable.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 bay area churches worked together for nearly a
year to bring this one to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The well-oiled efficiency of the Graham organization will
continue to mount crusades long after his extraordinary run comes
to an end. But no one is likely to surpass his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Graham has preached to more people than any other person in
history. And that may be the least of the remarkable benchmarks
this profoundly humble man of God will leave as a legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina farm-boy-turned-preacher transformed the
oft-ridiculed country tent meeting into popular middle class urban
rallies. More than 200 million people came to hear him.
</P>
<P>
   He preached his old-time religion using every high-tech tool he
could muster including radio, television, satellite downlinks, and,
last weekend for the first time, the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Graham accomplished the nearly impossible. He reduced or
eliminated the distrust that various Christian groups have
historically had for one another. Multi-church cooperation is the
theme _ and the reality _ of every Graham crusade.
</P>
<P>
   He was raised a Presbyterian, ordained in the Southern Baptist
tradition and claims to feel a part of the Anglican and Christian
Missionary Alliance church.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, his sincerity converted countless Roman Catholic
churches from opposition to his crusades into eager participants.
</P>
<P>
   But arguably his greatest gift to both evangelical ministry and
to Christianity is his personal integrity. He brought honor to a
profession known as much for the sleaziness of Elmer Gantry as the
purity of the Gospel.
</P>
<P>
   In a era of questionable televangelists such as Pat Robertson
and Benny Hinn _ not to mention the disgraced Jimmy Swaggart _
there has never been a hint of scandal around Graham or his
organization.
</P>
<P>
   His few critics argue that despite his extraordinary statistics,
the world has not much changed since Graham began crusades after
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   They suggest his preaching has been great theater, classic
evangelism charged more with emotion than content and like much of
its ilk, ineffective in changing lives.
</P>
<P>
   Graham admits that cities look much the same after his crusades
as before. But he would say that saving the world was not his task.
</P>
<P>
   Simply preaching the Gospel and preaching the Gospel simply were
his marching orders.
</P>
<P>
   And he has been faithful to that task beyond anyone's
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   His well-deserved epitaph _ like that of St. Paul _ might be
found in the second New Testament letter to Timothy:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have fought the good fight. I have finished the race. I have
kept the faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
