A0961 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHOPRA29-COX     10-28 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOPRA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some say he's a guru, he says `just a regular guy'
 &HT;    By Charlise Lyles
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the telephone, Deepak Chopra does not exactly sound like
the deep baritone, all-knowing mythical prophet.
</P>
<P>
   But a prophet he is, say devotees and detractors alike.
</P>
<P>
   Followers have declared him a guru, come to heal sick bodies and
souls with his teaching of mind/body harmony.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors denounce Chopra as a ``profit prophet,'' whose advent
is just in time to cash in on the New Age-spiritual craze and baby
boomer angst and affluence.
</P>
<P>
   In the past eight years, both camps have purchased Chopra's
sutras, best sellers such as Ageless Body, Timeless Mind, The Seven
Spiritual Laws of Success, The Return of Merlin and The Path to
Love , contributing to his phenomenal success as a master of
personal transformation and alternative medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Since the early 1990s, Chopra, with a halo of jet black hair and
shiny let-me-empower-you eyes, has traveled the globe, preaching
his metaphysical message of inner renewal about 140 days each year.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview last week, over the telephone lines from St.
Louis, the man who has been called the harbinger of pre-millennial
enlightenment sounded nasal, placid, somber. ``. . . just a regular
guy writing books on topics that he's interested in,'' Chopra said.
``I have absolutely no guilt about being successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Endocrinologist Dr. Deepak Chopra, 52, is the former chief of
staff of the Boston Regional Medical Center. In the 1980s, as he
treated internal ailments and taught at Tufts and Boston
universities, Chopra began to call on the ancient wisdom of his
native India to inform his practice of Western medicine.
</P>
<P>
   His unorthodox teaching took hold, even in pretty orthodox
places like the American Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Tussing of Cincinnati tuned in to Chopra three years ago.
``I was in a marriage and job that were both very unhappy and
unfulfilling for me. I was so sad,'' said Tussing, who describes
her age as 24 ``with 18 years experience.''
</P>
<P>
   She read Chopra's Seven Spiritual Laws of Success . She attended
his lectures, meditated, changed her diet, studied. She became a
``certified mind/body educator'' and teaches the Chopra technique
at area hospitals and places such as the Yellow Springs Center for
Spiritual Journeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this knowledge, renewed confidence, a knowingness and
putting his principles into practice, I've had major
life-transforming events in my life and personal relationships,''
Tussing said.
</P>
<P>
   How does Chopra explain his melding of quantum physics, Hindu
text and other Eastern philosophies, the Bible and Western
medicine?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that we see around us, including our bodies, is an
expression of information and energy. Even our thoughts are
clusters of photons. Where does this all come from? And what is it
that organizes the information and energy into a very orderly
universe, including a very intelligent biological system? That
domain of awareness, which is the source of all creativity, is
spirit. To befriend this force is to find a sense of meaning and
purpose in life, which is the basis of true success.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, said Chopra, people come back to his $25 to $200
seminars, lectures or classes as many as 20 times ``before they get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chopra does not dismiss traditional medicine. Still, approach
him with caution, say some physicians wary of his ``healing''
remedies for persons battling serious illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deepak is part preacher, part salesman, part philosopher. We
hear an awful lot of things from his lips and writing,'' said Dr.
John Renner, a family physician in Independence, Mo., who is
president of the National Council for Reliable Health Information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people need to be very, very skeptical before they buy
into that kind of thing. I'm not against all alternative medicine.
We have to be careful about what we call alternative and what we
call sales talk. When he talks warm, fuzzy stuff, that's one thing.
But when you talk about cancer. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Chopra-ism challenges traditional organized religion with the
notion that spirituality and consciousness, the true keys to
happiness and health, transcend religious doctrine and ritual.
</P>
<P>
   At the Healing Arts Center on the River in Mishawaka, Ind.,
director Sister Judian Breitenbach combines some of Chopra's ideas
with other mind/body spiritual integration therapies such as
reflexology, aromatherapy, healing touch and herbal body wraps.
Chopra serves as an adviser to the center, which opened three years
ago as part of Ancilla Health Systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we initiated this we did focus groups, and it was
well-received. There was some concern expressed on the part of the
diocesan leadership and fundamentalist-based groups,'' Breitenbach
said. ``It is a very delicate situation and it will be for other
dioceses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But the public is pushing this,'' she said. ``They are
searching for a spiritual element in their healing process that has
not been present in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Chopra calls mainstream skepticism and rejection predictable.
``It is an expression of fear,'' he said. ``God is no longer a dead
white male in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a perceived threat. That has always been the history
of organized religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the universe within that Chopra urges us to tap into, his
enterprise is vast.
</P>
<P>
   He employs about 65 people, from public-relations specialists to
physicians and massage therapists. Some staff the Chopra Center for
Well Being in La Jolla, Calif., near San Diego, which opened about
four years ago. A massage appointment costs $55. The five-day
``creating health-ayurvedic-detoxification program'' is $2,550. But
it comes with a guarantee: a ``life transforming and healing
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Chopra says the retreat center has yet to turn a profit. It is
supported by the proceeds from his 21 books and 30 audio, video and
CD-ROM programs. He won't say how many millions of dollars this
means. And still, his enterprise grows with seminars, a line of
herbal products, movie scripts and possibly a spiritual television
channel.
</P>
<P>
   Chopra also has a reputation for filing lawsuits _ against the
Weekly Standard , a Rupert Murdoch paper, the Journal of the
American Medical Association and Britain's Daily Mail .
</P>
<P>
   Though he offers healing to the burned-out, the divorced, the
cancer-stricken, the grieving and the otherwise disheartened and
despairing, Chopra himself has suffered few life crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 6 years old, we got a telegram from my daddy in
England saying he had just been inducted into the Royal College of
Physicians. My grandfather, whom I loved very much, was absolutely
proud. He took us to the roof of the house in Bombay and took a
rifle and fired some rounds. Then he took me and my little brother
to the movies . . . He took us home and kissed us goodnight, and he
died. I couldn't figure out where he went. . . . It was like he
suddenly disappeared. Did I solve the crisis? No. I haven't
still.''
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, he says, ``There have been minor things. Nothing
major.'' His marriage to wife, Rita, is stable. His daughter is 25
years old and a graduate of Brown University. His 21-year-old son
sometimes works with Chopra.
</P>
<P>
   And no self-destructive traits have gotten the better of this
guru. ``Criticism, things like that make me angry for a little
while, then I let it go,'' Chopra said. ``And maybe I'm a little
self-righteous sometimes.'
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
