<HEADER>
A0963 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-SIZES29-COX     10-28 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SIZES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Having a fit in the dressing room
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Lenda Jo Anderson wears a size 4. She
thinks.
</P>
<P>
   Sirvart Mellian has sizes 12 through 18 in her closet, and they
all fit her.
</P>
<P>
   How's that? ``The problem is, women's wear is based on numbers
that mean nothing,'' says Anderson, an associate professor of
consumer affairs at Auburn University(Ala.).
</P>
<P>
   Both women are working on national projects to make some sense
of it all.
</P>
<P>
   In today's stores, those 12s and 14s you hunt through vary from
designer to manufacturer. A Donna Karan size 4 is not necessarily a
Banana Republic size 4, or even a size 6.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the government stepped away from mandatory size
standards in 1942, after basing those numbers on a young and fit,
uniform-wearing World War II population. Since then, some designers
have become more generous with their sizing, squeezing more space
into smaller numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more interesting to say you are a size 2 to
friends,'' Anderson says.
</P>
<P>
   And smiles make sales.
</P>
<P>
   Groups such as the American Society for Testing and Materials,
which does quality control in the clothing industry, have suggested
new standards to reflect our expanding waistlines. And some simply
want to replace sizes on all tags with key measurements, such as
waist and hips.
</P>
<P>
   With help from the aerospace, auto and furniture industries _
which also need to know how big we are _ the group plans to take
body measurements of thousands of American women.
</P>
<P>
   Working with women 18-55, they plan to measure in 60 different
ways, from wrist to waist and beyond, says Mellian, a design
engineer for the U.S. Navy Clothing and Textile Research Facility
in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Combine those findings and interviews with each woman, and out
comes the first real database on sizing since the 1940s. They hope.
</P>
<P>
   The first part of the ASTM survey, on women 55 and older,
already is complete. The group looked at more than 6,000 women from
38 states and found, as was expected, that body types change. If
you compare the average measurements for a mature size 6 with the
1942 standard, you now have 4 more inches of waist and 2 more of
hip room.
</P>
<P>
   This should mean a new sizing standard after the two-year study
is complete.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no way to enforce it, Mellian says.
</P>
<P>
   She has had some success, at least with her branch of the
military. She has talked the Navy into putting waist and hip
measurements on its women's uniforms, sort of a women's version of
menswear sizing.
</P>
<P>
   She asks why designers can't do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say women don't know their measurements,'' she says.
``But I refuse to believe that men are smarter than women, because
men know their measurements.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, a lack of strict standards gives those who make
clothes some room to play. And that's important to the creative
types.
</P>
<P>
   Designers don't want to be told what to do, says Jack Morgan,
director of communications for the American Apparel Manufacturing
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the designer going to have to produce clothes along exact
numbers, like uniforms?'' he asks. ``Our feeling is, we would be
very concerned if undue restraints were put on designers.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you replace sizes with measurements, you constrain the
designer's creativity, he says. (His solution? ``We suggest people
try on the clothes.'')
</P>
<P>
   The AAMA is not entirely unsympathetic, though. For one thing,
Morgan says, they have developed a program called Suitable
Solutions, which may make the swimsuit buying process a bit easier.
</P>
<P>
   The program features color-coded tags that correspond with
different body types. Want a suit that de-emphasizes the tush? Look
for the right tag.
</P>
<P>
   The AAMA is now sending information to retailers, Morgan said.
But this system, too, is voluntary. And Morgan said there are no
plans to expand the tags to other kinds of clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Another program in the works involves the National Textile
Center, a group of colleges working with the U.S. Commerce
Department. The group wants to first sit down with focus groups,
probably in Atlanta and in North Carolina, to talk fit with women
ages 22-55, says Auburn's Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   They will go beyond measurements and discuss ease _ who likes
what to be loose where. Manufacturing representatives will sit in a
sound booth nearby, taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the group will mail questionnaires to a random sampling of
women across the country, asking similar questions about size and
fit.
</P>
<P>
   The goal: Come up with a program where women can say, ``Here are
my measurements and here is how I want this to fit.''
</P>
<P>
   So Anderson can order her fitted dresses and looser jackets,
just the way she wants them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I like,'' she says. ``You can't fool me.''
</P>
<P>
   2-4-6-10? WHAT SIZE DO I FIT IN?
</P>
<P>
   HAVING A FIT IN THE DRESSING ROOM
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone offers khaki pants.
</P>
<P>
   A Cox writer, with a 26-inch waist and 35-inch posterior area,
shopped around this week and snuck into fitting rooms with a tape
measure. Turns out she is a size 2, and a size 4, and a size 6, and
a size 8.
</P>
<P>
   The results:
</P>
<P>
   Lizsport, by Liz Claiborne _ Size 4 (26 waist, 38 fanny)
</P>
<P>
   Lauren, by Ralph Lauren _ Size 4 (26 waist, 36 fanny)
</P>
<P>
   DKNY, by Donna Karan _ Size 2 (28 waist, 38 fanny)
</P>
<P>
   Tommy, by Tommy Hilfiger _ Size 2 (28 waist, 39 fanny)
</P>
<P>
   Gap _ Size 8 (27 waist, 38 fanny)
</P>
<P>
   Limited _ Size 2 (28 waist, 38 fanny)
</P>
<P>
   Lerner New York _ Size 6 (27 waist, 37 fanny)
</P>
<P>
   Ann Taylor _ Size 4 (27 waist, 36 fanny)
</P>
<P>
   Banana Republic _ Size 8 (28 waist, 38 fanny)
</P>
<P>
   Talbots _ Size 4 (27 waist, 39 fanny)
</P>
<P>
   And the most unusual _ a size 26 at the Guess? boutique.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
