<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0964 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISSUEADS29-COX     10-28 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISSUEADS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deluge of political issue ads flows from major parties
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Back in June before the fall campaign was in full
swing, lawyers for the two major political parties appeared in
federal court here to demand an end to restrictions preventing them
from spending unlimited amounts of unregulated ``soft money'' on
political issue advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Though they generally agree on little else, the two sides argued
together that without such an unfettered entitlement they would
become footnotes in the November elections, swamped in a flood of
political spending from third parties who face no restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Nov. 3 elections less than a week away, the
lawyers' predictions have proved flat wrong. Issue advocacy is
indeed flooding the airwaves in many states, but it is the major
parties themselves that are responsible for the deluge, not
third-party special interests.
</P>
<P>
   With several dozen House seats and perhaps eight Senate seats up
for grabs, the two parties are pouring millions into unregulated
issue advertising in California, Nevada, New Mexico, Illinois,
Kentucky, New York, North Carolina, Ohio and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans alone, under the leadership of Rep. John
Linder (R-Ga.), are spending $25 million on issue advertisements
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   State parties have been big players, too, using their own ``soft
money'' accounts to fund issue ads in gubernatorial campaigns and
congressional races. In Georgia, for example, the Democratic Party
spent $500,000 on issue advertising attacking Republican Sen. Paul
Coverdell on funding for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of most issue advertising that voters are seeing around
the country, the Georgia ad does not tell voters to vote for
Michael Coles, Coverdell's Democratic opponent, or against
Coverdell, so the spending does not count against the federal
limits on what parties can spend on behalf of their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In some instances, the amount the parties are spending in issue
advertising far exceeds what they could spend in direct
contributions. In North Carolina, for example, the Democratic Party
is spending nearly $1.5 million on issue ads to attack the record
of Republican Sen. Lauch Faircloth, the GOP's most vulnerable
incumbent next to Sen. Alfonse D'Amato of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The amount is more than twice what the party can contribute in
so-called coordinated party expenditures under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Under Federal Election Commission rules that the parties are
challenging, the parties must mix unregulated soft money with
regulated ``hard money'' _ funds collected under contribution
limits _ to finance their issue advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has turned into a major river of soft money which is
flowing into federal campaigns,'' said Don Simon, director of
Common Cause. ``They spend this money on candidate-specific ads run
right before the election and claim that these ads are doing
nothing but discussing issues and have nothing to do with
campaigns. It's a joke.''
</P>
<P>
   The parties, spending an estimated $30 million to $40 million,
also are responsible for fueling the harshly negative tone of many
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got one of the worst attendance records in the Senate,''
intones one recent ad against Faircloth. ``And when Lauch Faircloth
has shown up for work? He voted to cut Medicare $270 billion, the
largest Medicare cut in history. Voted against Head Start for our
kids _ eight times. ... Call Lauch Faircloth. Tell him to put North
Carolina's working families first for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads have helped make the race competitive, said Michael
Tucker, a spokesman for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, which helped pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go in there and tell North Carolina voters that Lauch
Faircloth voted against Head Start eight times ... it makes a
difference when voters hear that,'' Tucker said.
</P>
<P>
   In Kentucky, a Republican Party ad tells voters that Democratic
Rep. Scotty Baesler, running for the Senate, ``voted to export
thousands of Kentucky jobs to Mexico.'' To the sound of the Mexican
mariachi, a Mexican actor says, ``Muchas gracias, Senor Baesler.''
</P>
<P>
   Issue advertising came under intense scrutiny in the 1996
elections after the two parties spent tens of millions of dollars
on ads that appeared to bolster the candidacies of President
Clinton and former Sen. Bob Dole. The Justice Department is
examining whether spending by the Democrats illegally exceeded the
spending limits imposed on presidential candidates who accept
federal matching funds.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party special interest groups also were active in 1996.
Organized as tax-exempt social welfare organizations in many cases,
these groups poured more than $135 million to $150 million in
unregulated donations into specific races.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Annenberg Public Policy Center in Washington
estimated that special interest groups have spent $260 million to
$330 million on issue advertising. But the 1998 figures are skewed
by the huge sums several of the largest groups poured into trying
to influence legislation, such as the $40 million spent by the
tobacco industry to fight an increase in cigarette taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party groups that wanted to influence candidates and
elections appear to have spent most of their money during the
primaries, said Douglas Rivlin, Annenberg's director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been the massive, coordinated effort we saw in
1996,'' Rivlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO, which spent $35 million in 1996 in the districts of
vulnerable House Republicans, scaled back its issue advertising
campaign this year to $5 million. This year, the labor union has
spent more money on organizing its grass-roots constituencies to
increase voter turnout, said AFL-CIO spokeswoman Denise Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to us that the party spending is the one place issue
advertising is increasing,'' Mitchell said. ``Other than that, I
think it's playing a diminished role.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, the AFL-CIO ran ads against 14 senators, including
Coverdell, criticizing them for opposing the patients' bill of
rights, which would subject health maintenance organizations to
liability lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, the ad prompted a response from the Washington-base
Business Roundtable, which just completed a $500,000, two-week ad
campaign across the state defending Coverdell's record on health
care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to set the record straight,'' said Jennifer
Litchman, the Roundtable's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The Roundtable, a tax-exempt trade association comprised of
chief executive officers from the nation's largest corporations,
developed a relationship with Coverdell when the Georgia senator
coordinated efforts to defeat Clinton's proposed health care
reforms in 1993. Coverdell has remained a staunch opponent of HMO
reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted people out there to know that Coverdell is
doing some good work out there on some of these issues,'' Litchman
said. ``We wanted to say thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   The parties, meanwhile, are continuing to press their claim in
federal court that FEC rules requiring them to match some regulated
hard money with soft money to produce issue ads is illegal. David
Leland, chairman of the Ohio Democratic Party and a party to the
lawsuit, said the case is still important even though third-party
advertising has not developed as they argued in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we want to do is play by the same rules as everyone
else,'' said Leland. ``Whether these (third-party) groups choose to
engage or not is irrelevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
