<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUFFETT-MACKAY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jimmy Buffett to strum in support of MacKay campaign
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Parrotheads will get a chance to hear
Jimmy Buffett Thursday when he makes a surprise visit to Clematis
By Night to campaign for Lt. Gov. Buddy MacKay.
</P>
<P>
   While Buffett is strumming in South Florida for the Democrats,
the Oak Ridge Boys will be touring the Florida Panhandle Thursday
with Republican Jeb Bush.
</P>
<P>
   If music is an important issue for voters picking a governor in
Tuesday's election, they'll have to decide: Is your heart on fire
for Elvira? Or would you rather be wasting away in Margaritaville?
</P>
<P>
   Buffett, who will be joined on stage by Gov. Lawton Chiles and
other Democratic leaders, will sing a few of his most popular
songs. Buffett, who has been active in politics for years, has long
supported Democratic candidates and will endorse MacKay during a
press conference in Titusville today.
</P>
<P>
   The Oak Ridge Boys, riding in their tour bus, will join Bush at
several stops in the Panhandle where their country and gospel music
is very popular.
</P>
<P>
   These star wars are not being limited to singers.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay will spend most of Thursday with President Clinton
attending a money-raising dinner in Palm Beach and watching U.S.
Sen. John Glenn return to space aboard the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   After the dinner, Clinton, if his schedule permits, may show up
on the stage in downtown West Palm Beach with Buffett, MacKay,
Chiles and other Democratic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Bush comes to West Palm Beach on Friday to
attend a rally at Rooney's Public House, a downtown Irish pub and
restaurant with New York's best-known Italian, Mayor Rudy Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, who was campaigning in West Palm Beach Tuesday night,
was asked whether the Oak Ridge Boys or Jimmy Buffett was more
popular with Florida voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take Jimmy Buffett every time,'' he said with a laugh.
``I think he's a proven winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
