<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0969 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-2000-PRESIDENT29-COX     10-28 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-2000-PRESIDENT29-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Bush adviser: It's about 2000 now
</P>
<P>
   By Ken Herman
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's top adviser on Tuesday
declared the gubernatorial race over and said the battle has turned
into the beginning of the 2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove blamed the Democrats _ not Bush _ for the White House
overtones. And, in nonspecific terms, he dismissed Democratic
challenger Garry Mauro as generally unworthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you're right, the governor's race is over,'' Rove said
after fellow panelists expressed the sentiment at a meeting of the
Texas Taxpayers and Research Association. ``And it really is
astonishing commentary on the decline of the Democratic Party that
they've got this guy running as their candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mauro campaign was unimpressed with Rove's commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dream on Karl Rove,'' said Billy Rogers, Mauro's campaign
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the campaign, Bush has declined to publicly make any
derogatory comments about Mauro, though he has aggressively
challenged the challenger's ideas and proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has said he has not decided on whether to enter the
2000 presidential race. In San Antonio on Monday, he said he does
not even want to talk about it until after Tuesday's election.
</P>
<P>
   But Rove said the Democrats are turning the gubernatorial race
into a preseason presidential contest. He pointed to Saturday's
possible trip to El Paso by Hillary Rodham Clinton, whose
appearance at a Mauro rally would mark the 14th event that she,
President Clinton or Vice President Al Gore have attended on
Mauro's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said the White House has not yet said whether the first
lady will attend the El Paso event.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said the Mauro campaign's ``closing endgame'' is an effort
to keep Bush from hitting his goal of running well in the Hispanic
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about trying to deny George W. Bush 40 percent of
the Hispanic vote, which has nothing to do with 1998 at all, and
all things to do with future fears on the part of the Clinton-Gore
White House,'' Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, even before polls showed Mauro running a distant
second to Bush, political gossip said Mauro's mission was to see
what kind of issues worked against Bush, who could wind up in a
head-to-head battle for the White House with Gore in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Rogers said the Clintons' interest in the Mauro campaign
stems from their long-term friendship with him. Mauro met Clinton
in 1972, when they worked in Dallas for the George McGovern
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro and Bush worked West Texas on Tuesday, with the Democrat
continuing to criticize the incumbent for not saying if he is going
to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to choose at a time that is more convenient to him,''
Mauro said in Lubbock. ``My position is that we have full-time
problems and I plan to be a full-time governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, also in Lubbock, repeated his position:
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that I have not decided whether I will run for
president,'' he said. ``If that is a problem for some people, then
they should take that into account when they go to the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pre-election polls, Mauro insists he will be the
next governor. Like Rove, he said the outcome is not in doubt,
though he sees a different outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully expect to win the election next Tuesday,'' Mauro said
Monday in Austin. ``Absolutely, 100 percent convinced of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove on Tuesday also served up a colorful view of the race
between Democrat John Sharp and Republican Rick Perry for
lieutenant governor. Rove, though involved with the GOP's
coordinated campaign, is not a consultant to the Perry campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the campaigns' television ads, Rove jokingly
dismissed Sharp as ``Mr. Green Eye Shades. Hire me to be your
accountant. Got tax problems? Call John Sharp, tax preparer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And here is Rick Perry talking about kids and looking good
and, 'If you agree with me, I want to be your lieutenant governor,'
exuding charisma,'' Rove said. ``One is Mr. Bland White Guy . . .
and the other is `Hey, I'm your next-door neighbor, and I may not
be as smart as the other guy, but you'd rather have me over
Saturday night for dinner wouldn't you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' was the one-word response from Kelly Fero, spokesman for
Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   This article includes material from The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
