<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0970 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELL-EXEC-GIFT29-COX     10-28 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-EXEC-GIFT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell executives give $13 million for art museum
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney and Michael Barnes
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ In the largest single cash gift to the arts
in Central Texas, five Dell Computer Corp. executives and their
wives have pledged $13 million to help build the Austin Museum of
Art on West Third Street in downtown Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The gift, which will be announced today, is a significant boost
to the museum's efforts to raise an estimated $35 million for
design and construction of the museum and at least $15 million to
endow it.
</P>
<P>
   It also signals that Dell, which has grown from its 1984 start
in a University of Texas dormitory to the region's largest private
employer, will be more active in shaping the region's cultural and
philanthropical landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Dell continues to grow, we are presented with a unique
responsibility to partner with greater Austin to shape the kind of
world-class community we need as we move into the 21st century,''
Chief Executive Michael Dell said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same basic quality-of-life issues that affect the future
of our company and our employees are directly relevant to Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Michael and Susan Dell, the donors are Mort Topfer, vice
chairman, and his wife, Angela; Kevin Rollins, vice chairman, and
his wife, Debbie; Tom Green, senior vice president for legal
affairs, and his wife, Deborah; and Tom Meredith, senior vice
president and chief financial officer, and his wife, Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Kirk Watson welcomed Dell Computer's multidimensional role
in Central Texas as the region evolves from a government-driven
economy to a technology center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a 13-million-star demonstration of generosity to the
community,'' Watson said. ``It assures that a part of this
transition of the city will occur in a high-class way.''
</P>
<P>
   Museum officials called the gift a huge boost to the entire arts
scene in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been much talk throughout the United States that the
high-tech community was not coming to the table in this way,'' said
Elizabeth Ferrer, director of the Austin Museum of Art. ``I think
that was a premature assessment. The high-tech community will play
an incredibly important role in the arts and other philanthropic
endeavors in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   While the gift has been in the works since spring, its
announcement depended in part on the filling of key positions at
the museum, said Tom Green, who has been working out details of the
gift for several months. The museum was without a chief executive
officer until June, when former IBM executive Bill O'Brien got the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Dell officials hope the timing of the announcement, one week
from the Nov. 3 election, boosts support for Proposition 4 among
Austin voters. The $46.4 million proposal includes spending for
libraries, museums and cultural centers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dell urged support for Proposition 4 and other measures,
noting that voters approved an $11.4 million bond issue for an art
museum in 1984 _ which coincidentally is the year he started his
company in his dorm room at UT.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next week's bond election gives us another, rare opportunity
to reinvest in important cultural assets that benefit us all,
including the Mexican-American Cultural Center, the Carver Museum
and the Palmer Performing Arts Center,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it to be a wonderful coincidence,'' said Watson.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot does not ask approval for bonds to renovate Palmer;
$50 million is expected to be raised privately. Propositions 11 and
12 release the City of Austin to rent Palmer to Arts Center Stage
and to raise money through taxes on car rentals in order to build a
parking garage, a landscaped park and a new community events center
to house current Palmer users.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Dell donation should hearten those Palmer backers who
question whether Arts Center Stage can raise $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gift proves there is money here in the community for the
arts,'' said museum board Chairman David Gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been saying that this kind of philanthropy is
possible in Austin,'' said Jessie Hite, director of UT's Blanton
Museum of Art. ``But this is the first time we have seen it. This
is very positive for everyone in the arts in Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   Running on parallel tracks, the new Blanton, planned for the
intersection of Speedway and Martin Luther King Boulevard, is
estimated to cost $50 million for design, construction and
endowments, about the same as the municipal museum. University
fund-raisers have secured $37 million so far. The Houston
Endowment, headed by Houston oilman and former UT Regent Jack S.
Blanton, gave $12 million, while Blanton and his wife, Laura Lee,
personally pledged $5 million. The late novelist James Michener and
his wife, Mari, left $10 million to the museum, as well as their
collection of American art, valued at $16 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Dell gift, however, is the largest single cash pledge to an
Austin arts group.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin Museum of Art, which will concentrate on 20th century
art in its new building, emerged from the reorganized Laguna Gloria
Art Museum in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The old museum had first sought a downtown presence in the early
1980s with a bond election to raise money for a building designed
by architectural superstar Robert Venturi. The project fell apart
in 1989, victim of a sour economy, political infighting and the
loss of the original land on Fourth Street.
</P>
<P>
   Die-hard backers revived the dream in the early 1990s by
creating a board of directors more broadly inclusive of Austin's
diversified communities. The City Council endorsed the new
management in 1996, and, a year later, retired doctor Ernest Butler
and his wife, Sarah, jump-started the renewed campaign for the
downtown museum with a gift of $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since $11.4 million in bond money remains for the project, the
addition of the Dell gift brings the project close to the halfway
mark in a fund-raising campaign expected to seek at least $50
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we've taken several giant steps forward,'' museum
chairman Gold said. ``We are within hailing distance of our (1998)
targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Gold said Dell representatives have worked closely with the
museum board on the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Dell Computer Corp., its executives and
employees and the 3-year-old Dell Foundation have given several
million dollars to cultural and charitable organizations.
Executives say the company's presence will be felt more in the
months and years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are all the things you need to do to become a
world-class company,'' said Topfer, a vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the gift is more significant for Austin's arts
institutions, which, for decades, rarely received any donations of
more than six figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am already beginning to schedule the first year or two of
exhibitions in the new building,'' Ferrer said. ``These are the
shows that are going to put Austin on the map, in terms of an art
center.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This represents a sea change in the cultural life of Austin,''
Gold said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
