<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small-business owners blast Southwestern Bell
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Several Austin small-business owners criticized
Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. on Tuesday for lack of local
competition and high in-state long-distance charges.
</P>
<P>
   Their press conference at the Capitol Marriott Hotel was
organized by a local public relations company, JRG Communications,
on behalf of the Partnership for a Competitive Texas, which was
started by AT&AMP;T and other long-distance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman was the Rev. Frank Garrett, who lives in Austin
and is pastor of Bethel St. Paul Baptist Church in Giddings. He
focused his criticism on the 12-cent-a-minute ``access charge''
that long-distance companies must pay local phone companies to
complete long-distance calls made between points within the state.
</P>
<P>
   Garrett is also a radio talk show host and said he has expensive
long-distance bills trying to develop his Black Talk Broadcasting
Network of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   As have the long-distance companies, Garrett said that it
actually costs the local companies _ in Texas, primarily
Southwestern Bell _ about 1 cent a minute to complete the calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It amounts to little more than corporate welfare,'' Garrett
said of the 12-cent charge, ''welfare paid for by our families and
businesses and we want reform.''
</P>
<P>
   He was joined by Joseph Villarreal, a jeweler; Ying Li, a
consultant for people who do business in China; Russel Anders,
whose Data One company installs telecommunications equipment; and
Eugene Bailey, a landscaper.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Maddox, a spokesman for Southwestern Bell, said the access
charge _ frozen by state law until Sept. 1, 1999 _ was set that
high to keep the monthly charge for local service low.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're asking Texans to increase local rates when they (ask
for lower access charges),'' Maddox said. As for local competition,
he said competitors have almost 650,000 local lines. Southwestern
Bell has about 9.3 million lines in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
