<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Malloween: Treats the focus in safe settings
 &HT;    WITH BOO-BOX
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Traffic at the mall will be a nightmare this Saturday.
Thousands of frightening-looking kids will pack the doorways of
stores in search of sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Trick or treating at the mall has become a tradition for many
metro Atlanta children since the tainted-candy scares of the
mid-1980s, when malls got into the candy business to provide a safe
haven on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a natural fit that we give kids a safe place
that's well lit,'' said Cindy Gilmer, marketing director at
Northlake Mall. ``You don't have to worry about being hit by a car
or the weather. Every year, we're mobbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sybil Moore of Forest Park has always taken her two sons
Malloweening. They've trick or treated at the Mall West End,
Southlake Mall and Greenbriar. The family hasn't decided which mall
it will hit this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generation grew up running wildly into the night, going
door to door. It was fun and safe then,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now you don't know whose door they're knocking on. People
move so frequently. And you get hit with eggs because of the
roughness of the teenagers. My kids like the mall because they can
be cute in their costumes and feel safe with mom's hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the free festivities are just for a day, mall managers
and store owners hope the business benefits last longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merchants love it,'' Northlake's Gilmer said. ``They don't
do a lot of business that night, but the parents are going to
remember the store that gave their child candy and, hopefully,
they're going to come back and shop there.''
</P>
<P>
   For serious trick or treaters who want to fill their goodie bags
to the brim, the malls can be a better deal than walking around the
neighborhood. Youngsters can get treats at more than 100 stores
before they call it a night.
</P>
<P>
   Greenbriar Mall expects to pass out more than 40,000 pieces of
candy.
</P>
<P>
   The Cobb Galleria Centre will have a semi-trailer loaded with
sweets to hand out during its annual Trick or Treat Street. More
than 11,000 children attended last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wild day. It's just insane,'' said Annie Miners, (cq)
event producer for Game Inc., the company that helps coordinate the
program at the Galleria.
</P>
<P>
   Not all malls participate. Some say unruly teenagers
overshadowed the under-12 set, for whom the events were targeted.
Cumberland Mall stopped passing out candy a couple of years ago. So
did Gwinnett Place.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do all parents embrace Malloween, with its sometimes long
lines and absence of neighborliness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to do trick or treating at the mall anymore.
It's just too much of a line,'' said Sandra Dawson, a Norcross
mother who used to take her 5-year-old daughter, Ashley, to a mall.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Finley's two girls wouldn't think of trick or treating
outside their Tucker neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what our kids enjoy,'' Finley said. ``We live near a
couple of cul-de-sacs, so we know almost all the neighbors.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
