<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEATHER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Aida' star Heather Headley sees her winning streak continue
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Heather Headley says she doesn't get recognized too
much on the streets of Atlanta. That's hard to believe, given the
catlike grace and sly almond eyes of the star of ``Elaborate Lives:
The Legend of Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, creating the role of Aida, the Nubian princess in
Disney's Elton John-Tim Rice musical at the Alliance Theatre,
Headley doesn't have a whole lot of time to stroll around the city
and attract notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show takes over your life,'' she says, tackling a salmon
steak during lunch at a Midtown restaurant, near the apartment
where she and other ``Lives'' members are living. ``You have to
plan your day backward.''
</P>
<P>
   She gets to the theater at 6:30 p.m. That means she watches
``Jerry Springer'' (a guilty addiction) at 4. At 3 she has to stop
talking to rest her vocal cords. At 2 she tries to hit the gym.
``All of a sudden you realize, `OK, I need to wake up at 5 to get
all this done,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Headley doesn't get up at 5 a.m. She can't: Aida keeps her up
too late, as the actress mentally runs through the night's show,
critiquing her own performance and the evolving production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I go to sleep with Miss Aida,'' she says with a
shake of her head. ``And I'm like, `Let me go! Go back to your
pyramid and stay there.'''
</P>
<P>
   A pop variation on the Verdi opera, ``Elaborate Lives''
elaborates on the love triangle that develops between the enslaved
Aida, her Egyptian captor Radames (Hank Stratton) and his
betrothed, the princess Amneris (Sherie Scott). Like her co-stars,
Headley has spent much of her time in Atlanta adjusting to rewrites
and new choreography and, of course, finessing John's songs.
</P>
<P>
   At a casual get-together with the songwriter and other cast
members, Headley remembers being amazed when John asked if she'd
like any changes in her ballads. ``I was just there to ask his
blessing,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the show that needs a blessing of its own is the
temperamental, hydraulically operated pyramid, which the cast has
dubbed ``Sybil.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had maybe one or two nights where my heart would
break,''Headley says, recalling the early times when the set
element would crash. ``You're already trying to remember lines or
where you go next. But on top of that, I was stressed wondering,
`Is Sybil going to make it tonight?' By the fourth or fifth time, I
was getting really upset, because it wasn't fair for the
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when the director came in and reblocked the show, so it
could continue smoothly with or without the pyramid. Headley, whose
voice even offstage is a rich mix of caramel and honey, is quick to
praise the technicians, who have worked very hard trying to solve
the mechanical glitches.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Sybil's erratic behavior has generated spending
money for some of the actors, who bet on her nightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe Sherie (Scott, who plays Amneris) and Rich (Hebert, who
plays Zoser),'' Headley says of two of her co-stars. She'd been
betting the machine would crash, but Sybil performed flawlessly for
a week. ``I come offstage, and Sherie's there with her hand out,
waiting for her money.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the show has been physically demanding, Headley is used
to it. It's the second time she has created a role for Disney,
having originated the part of Nala in ``The Lion King'' on
Broadway. By comparison, ``Elaborate Lives'' is cake.
</P>
<P>
   ```Lion King' wore my body down,'' Headley says. She went from
the corseted Edwardian world of ``Ragtime'' in Toronto, in which
she understudied three-time Tony winner Audra McDonald, into Julie
Taymor's spine-bending, athletic stage vision for the Disney
adaptation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Arnold Schwarzenegger could go in there and die after
three weeks,'' Headley says. ``It's a rough show. I got two
sprained ankles and stress fractures in both legs.'' She pauses,
then laughs. ``Disney will be very happy that I'm saying this.''
But it's clearly said with affection; she hopes to return to the
show for a few weeks in December, while the next stage for
``Elaborate Lives'' is being decided.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Trinidad to a minister father and teacher mom, Headley
moved to the States as a teen when her father was assigned to a
church in Fort Wayne, Ind. ``That was a slap in the face,'' she
recalls with a smile. ``The weather, the culture, everything.''
</P>
<P>
   A churchgoer all her life, Headley has found it hard to make it
to Sunday services following two-performance Saturdays. But once,
Alliance artistic director Kenny Leon took her to his church,
Cascade United Methodist. And the pastor recognized her. ``He was
screaming `Aida' from the pulpit,'' she says with an embarrassed
giggle. ``It was so funny. I wanted to say, `No, I'm just here to
worship. There's no Aida here today _ I'll be putting her on in
about two hours.'''
</P>
<P>
   Most young actors struggle with rejection. Only 24, Headley's
big struggle has been with success. She was in her third year at
Northwestern University when her agent told her to audition for the
producers of ``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Headley mimics her agent's world-weary voice: ``She said, `Go.
They'll say you're too young, finish school. They'll call you next
year. You won't get it!'''
</P>
<P>
   She got it. She wasn't sure she wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not an easy decision, because my whole point in life
was never to leave school,'' she says. So she ran up $300 in phone
bills, calling her teachers, seeking advice. ``I was waiting for
the first `no,''' she says. ``The first `no' was going to keep me
in school. But they all said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Headley calls her six months in Toronto with ``Ragtime'' her
first true love, ``like your first boyfriend,'' she says. ``I still
warm up (vocally) to it every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Disney came calling, looking for a Nala.
</P>
<P>
   Headley's agent said, ``Go. Sing for them. They'll tell you
you're too young. You won't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   She got it. She wasn't sure she wanted it.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that she originally thought the idea of ``Lion
King'' onstage sounded silly and she'd never heard of Julie Taymor.
``I had a week or two of intense pressure,'' she remembers. ``No
sleep, I lost weight. Both sides were telling me, `Are you
crazy?''' Ultimately, Disney bought her out of the ``Ragtime''
contract, and she sees the decision as the best possible choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a quick three years, but it's my life, so I don't
see it as something phenomenal or great,'' she says. ``People are
like, `You've done two of the biggest musicals of the century in
one year.' But I don't see it like that. For me, it's just, `My
ankle hurts. This is killing me!''' She stops to laugh. ``But I do
consider it a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, she's spoiled. She admits it.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers feeling nervous when she was getting ready to
perform ``Elaborate Lives'' in front of an audience for the first
time. ``I say this with all humility, but after `Ragtime' and `Lion
King' I did not know what it's like to see a -- itting house at the
end of a show. I had to remind myself, not everybody's show is sold
out, and not everybody gets a standing ovation every night.''
</P>
<P>
   But in her case, with standing-room-only performances of
``Elaborate Lives,'' Headley's record is now three for three.
</P>
<P>
   Most actors have rituals they perform each night. Headley's is
simple. ``I have to go center stage, to the center curtain, and
pray,'' she says. ``If I don't, I feel like Sybil will break down _
which she has. So I do it right before the curtain goes up. The
kids are always asking, `What are you doing?' But it only takes
half a second. I do it and go off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not calling all the gods,'' she says with a smile. ``Just
the one, the main guy.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
