A0982 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-BIZ-COLUMN29-CO     10-28 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-BIZ-COLUMN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Small businesses face big threat from Y2K
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ While government agencies and major corporations
have been plowing millions into addressing Year 2000 computer
problems, many small-business owners are just beginning to look
into whether their companies will have disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 5 million small businesses are at risk of Year 2000 _ or
Y2K _ computer glitches, according to Wells Fargo &AMP; Co., which
commissioned a Gallup Poll survey of 500 small-business owners
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate how pressing some people think it is: Last week,
the U.S. Small Business Administration and the Internal Revenue
Service began sending letters to 6.5 million companies warning them
of possible Year 2000 problems as part of the SBA's Y2K Action
Week.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the Technical Business Network hosted a conference with
100 people in attendance that explored the legal, insurance and
business issues of the problem. The business group announced plans
for the Austin Year 2000 Alliance, a forum to allow Texas
businesses to exchange information on solving Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've somehow managed to avoid any discussion about the
the Year 2000 problem, here's the crux: Some personal computers are
programmed to record only the last two digits of the year for any
date they encounter. If they're not fixed on or before Jan. 1,
2000, their automatic clocks will reset to Jan. 1, 1900. The fact
that 2000 is a leap year may complicate matters even more.
Obviously, this could cause devastating problems for any company
that uses computers _ now fixtures in 78 percent of small
companies. But it can also affect cash registers and telephone or
elevator systems that use time- or date-dependent microchips,
according to the SBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very concerned about it,'' says Pedro Filipowsky, whose
company develops custom database software for small businesses.
``Once you start looking into all the different areas that can go
wrong it's just mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   He says a preliminary check of a small-business's computer
system takes about three to five hours, plus another couple of
hours per computer to identify what files or software applications
contain a date-related problem. If the database software needs to
be examined, a business owner may have to hire a professional at
$75 to $100 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all they have is a hardware problem, that can usually be
fixed in a few minutes. Beyond that it depends on how extensive
their date-related problems are,'' Filipowsky says. ``It can be
anywhere from a few hours to a few weeks of work.''
</P>
<P>
   He says if small-business owners delay exploring their computer
systems too long they may find it difficult to get help before the
date changes to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you have to do is not bury your head in the sand;
approach it rationally, but do approach, do address the issue,''
Filipowsky says.
</P>
<P>
   GartnerGroup a high-tech consulting company, recently found that
23 percent of businesses and government agencies haven't started
any Year 2000 effort. But the proportion is far greater among what
GartnerGroup considers small companies _ 83 percent of those
waiting were businesses with fewer than 2,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The consulting group predicts at least half of all small
businesses will experience at least one serious system failure and
10 percent of these failures will last more than three days.
</P>
<P>
   Bernardine Bering, co-owner of Barton Springs Nursery, is one of
those who has looked at the consequences. She says her company
recently bought a computer-driven cash register that is
Y2K-compliant and Bering says she also has been assured by the
developers of its Counterpoint accounting software that the latest
version has taken care of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Some small businesses say they are being asked to give
assurances to their clients that they won't have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ginny's Printing and Copying, for instance, has had to assure
client Dell Computer Corp. that the problem won't disrupt Ginny's
new service center at Dell. Michael Martin, president of Ginny's,
says he has gotten promises from Xerox, which supplies his copy
machines, that it is addressing any Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Dell is focusing on the impact of Y2K on Nov. 19 in a Webcast
from 10:30 to 11:15 a.m. at www.dell.com/breakfast. Experts from
Dell, the SBA and Microsoft Corp. will advise small businesses on
what they can do to prepare. The Webcast is expected to include
videos of small-business owners talking about how they are
addressing the Y2K problem and a question-and-answer session.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Ronay, who has a small financial consulting company in
Austin, says he found free software on the Internet to test his
system and discovered his 1994 computer's ``clock chip,'' or BIOS,
had a date problem. ``I didn't think I had a problem, but I did,''
Ronay says. ``My calculation is I need to replace either the
components of this computer or buy a new one before it gets too
close to the year 2000. If I had waited until August 1999, like
most people will probably do, there could be a run on computers or
parts.''
</P>
<P>
   One small business that has not yet tackled the chore of taking
on the Year 2000 issue is Garden-Ville of Austin Inc., a nursery
that specializes in native plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have thought about it. We now know what 2YK means . . . oh
yeah, it's Y2K,'' says Kathryn Stevens, assistant to the owner. ``I
have a file on it, but I'm not going to be able to do a lot of it
because I'm not computer-literate enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tyson writes Wednesdays on small-business issues. Send
information to her at P.O. Box 670, Austin, 78767 or by e-mail at
ktysonstatesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
