<HEADER>
A0983 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-KID-BIRTHDAY29     10-28 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-KID-BIRTHDAY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Happy Birthday, My Sweet Baby
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Dan Neal
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ My daughter has leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have warned us that the worst might happen, but my wife,
Judie, and I try not to think about that.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, we talk only about the best-case scenario: After three
years of gut-wrenching chemotherapy treatments, Nicki will be
cured.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it's hard. Despair dogs your every move when your child
has cancer, clawing just beneath the surface. Then it gnaws into
your consciousness when you least expect it. When you're driving to
work, making dinner, or just when you thought you were going to
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But happiness peeps through as well. Like it did last week.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was Nicki's 7th birthday, and she celebrated it in the
children's cancer ward at St. Mary's Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   She wouldn't have had it any other way. All her friends were
there.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse Janet was there. She's the one who calls her
``girlfriend'' and ``Sweet Cheeks.'' The one who does her spinal
taps and other heavy-duty treatment procedures. The one she trusts
almost as much as Mom.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dave was there. He's the pharmacist who orders up those
drugs with the cold, cruel names _ Vincristine, Daunomycin,
Methotrexate. Drugs so vile the nurses have to wear rubber suits to
start the kids' intravenous lines. But to Nicki, Dr. Dave has only
one job that matters: He'll make faces, dance or tell her jokes _
anything to make her laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse Pam was there. She's the one who never hurts her when she
taps into the IV port in her chest.
</P>
<P>
   Even Dr. Hector was there. He's the one who's funny because he
talks with that funny accent. He's the one her parents are trusting
with her life.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, the other cancer kids were there _ her best buds
Daniella and Shardai and little Brooke, and Rachel, Anel, Alyssa,
Audrey. The ones Nicki plays Uno with, and works jigsaw puzzles
with and gets into trouble with whenever they are in the hospital
at the same time and aren't too sick to fool around.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't your typical kid bash. Most of the revelers were in
wheelchairs or trailing IV poles, so rowdy games were out. And most
of the chatter among moms centered on their children's absolute
neutrophyl count _ an immune system measurement that determines
when the kids can venture out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also the usual kid stuff: a stack of presents, a
big, messy cake, and lots of noise.
</P>
<P>
   Too much noise, in fact, for a boring old dad who had dashed
over in the middle of the work day. I stepped out into the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding Room 2512
</P>
<P>
   Been there a hundred times and the place still gives me the
creeps. At the far end of the hall I saw that little table where
the doctor gave us the leukemia speech back in June, when Nicki was
diagnosed. The different kinds. How it wrecks the blood. How the
chemo works. Any questions? Only one, but we dared not ask.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, the fish tank. Destination No. 1 for the child
just learning to walk while pushing an IV pole.
</P>
<P>
   And across the hall, Room 2512.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't looked in since June and couldn't look in now. It's the
room where Judie and I spent the two worst days of our lives _ a
brutally long Saturday and Sunday waiting on test results that
would show Nicki has cancer.
</P>
<P>
   That Monday, I would sit on the floor of that room and tell
Nicki that she had a bad germ called leukemia. As I talked, she
picked up the pieces to a stamp set she had been playing with and
put them in a plastic bag. ``All right,'' she said, sealing the bag
and handing it to me. She climbed into bed _ and into a dark,
furious funk that would last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And it was in 2512 that Monday night that Judie _ a rock of
strength and optimism all weekend _ collapsed in my arms as our
precious baby lay sleeping, the first bag of chemo dripping into
her veins. ``It hurts so much,'' she cried, her body heaving, her
sobs broken by vicious, stabbing gasps for breath. Her grief broke
my heart.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it's home
</P>
<P>
   But there was no grief Friday. Now my wife was laughing,
hollering for me to come back in the playroom. Nicki was opening
her presents.
</P>
<P>
   Bald as an egg, she flashed the same old snaggle-toothed grin
I'd seen at the 7th birthday parties of our three older children.
Four-year-old Brooke was her helper, toting packages from an
enormous pile of gifts to her friend, who sat enthroned on a
plastic chair. Rugrats dolls! An Ants-the-anteater Beanie Baby! A
Winnie-the-Pooh shirt!
</P>
<P>
   The scene of our horror now felt like home _ at least to Nicki.
</P>
<P>
   Happy birthday, my sweet baby
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
