<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYT-UT-DONATION29-COX     10-28 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYT-UT-DONATION29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New York Times gives UT its 20th-century archives
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ To the college student who is more comfortable
staring at a computer screen than an old gray page, a recycling
center might seem to be the best place for four truckloads of
newspaper clippings.
</P>
<P>
   But the Center for American History at the University of Texas
is thrilled to be the new home to the New York Times morgue, the
old gray lady's enormous file of clippings that covers 80 years of
20th-century history. The donation will be officially announced at
a dinner tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here are the extremely well-indexed articles of
comprehensive coverage of all the major events of U.S. history as
they occurred during the major portion of the 20th century,'' said
Don Carleton, the center's director. ``It's quite a coup.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the newspaper's archives were transferred to electronic
databases, Times reporters and editors used the morgue as their
primary source of information on people, places and events. The
Times kept complete files of its articles sorted by subject from
1908 to 1989.
</P>
<P>
   But with all of those stories online now, the Times realized it
did not need the morgue and could not afford to maintain it. The
newspaper originally offered the voluminous archive to the New York
Public Library, which didn't have room for the 22 million clippings
and more than 2,500 linear feet of paper.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the center's reputation for storing huge media
archives, the Times asked UT to take it on. The clip files of the
New York Journal-American and the New York Herald-Tribune, two
Times rivals that are now defunct, are already housed there, as are
the papers of CBS News legends Walter Cronkite and Andy Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted UT,'' said Linda Amster, director of research at the
Times. ``The center is known for having morgues and knowing how to
store them. Our concern was for the preservation of the clips.''
</P>
<P>
   The clips include large files on many Texas topics, including 25
cubic feet of clippings on Lyndon Baines Johnson. ``This gives the
center really one of the great newspaper collections in the
country,'' Carleton said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
