<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROAST29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Livestock industry rallies around roast to up beef sales
 &HT;    By John Keilman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ With the livestock business taking a pounding,
beef producers are hoping a new savior will come from an old
standby.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the roast?
</P>
<P>
   Steakhouses may be hotter than jalapenos, but the meat they use
accounts for only one-quarter of the cow. The rest, known as the
chuck (the front end) and the round (the back end), isn't nearly as
popular.
</P>
<P>
   The chuck and round is carved into thick roasts, the kind
millions of families once teamed with carrots and potatoes and
tossed into crock pots and Dutch ovens.
</P>
<P>
   But as more women took jobs outside the home, slow-cooking
dishes such as roasts gave way to quick and convenient foods.
What's more, beef's regal place in the American palate has eroded
over the years: Per capita beef consumption has dropped 12 percent
since 1980, while chicken and turkey have soared by 52 percent and
77 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   When roasts don't sell, processors usually turn the chuck and
round into ground beef. While that may be good for hamburger
lovers, it's bad for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``A whole muscle pot roast will sell from $1.29 to $2 a pound,''
said Mary Adolph, a marketing executive for the National
Cattleman's Beef Association. ``When we grind it, the value goes
down substantially.''
</P>
<P>
   So now, with steer prices at a 12-year low, industry promoters
plan a new approach to return the roast to its former glory.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a cue from the poultry business, which introduced such
easy-to-make foods as the chicken nugget and the turkey cutlet,
beef producers are coming out with new products.
</P>
<P>
   One item being tested is a precooked pot roast that takes seven
minutes to microwave. Another is a ``rotissaroast,'' beef's answer
to the rotisserie chicken craze.
</P>
<P>
   The Cattleman's Beef Association also plans to push the idea of
cooking a roast instead of a ham or turkey for holiday meals.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the group's efforts, prospects for a roast renaissance
appear limited. Doug Randolph, the meat buyer for Cub Foods, said
the cuts have always been seasonal items.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, when grills beckon and people don't want to use
their ovens, roast sales plummet while steaks leap. The trend
reverses itself in colder months.
</P>
<P>
   Randolph said beef has the added handicap of intimidating
customers. Many cuts can seem difficult to prepare, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear a lot of questions from customers in front of the beef
case as opposed to poultry and pork,'' he said. ``We need to do our
job helping them figure out what to prepare for dinner and figuring
out how to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
