<HEADER>
A0989 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUDENT-TESTS29-COX     10-28 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-TESTS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Comprehensive achievement test scores high with officials
 &HT;    WITH GRAPHICS
 &HT;    By Mary Ellen Flannery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Try this: Denise and Nona play soccer.
Denise scored four goals this year and Nona scored five, and
together they scored half of the goals scored by the team.
</P>
<P>
   How many goals did the team score?
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the more challenging questions posed to
fifth-graders on the new Florida Comprehensive Achievement Test.
It's likely that if it was asked of Palm Beach County students,
many would have answered incorrectly. Students here and across
Florida got more questions wrong on the FCAT than right when they
took it this year.
</P>
<P>
   But state and district officials like the FCAT, in a way that
only testing officials can truly appreciate a test, partially
because it is hard and their students aren't expected to do well at
first. One state official calls it ``an evolutionary step
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We get excited about new tests that have the impact of
improving student performance,'' said Marc Baron, director of the
school district's research and evaluation department.
</P>
<P>
   The FCAT is different and better than fill-in-the-bubble
standardized tests such as the Comprehensive Test of Basic Skills
or the High School Competency Test _ both of which the FCAT
eventually will replace _ because it makes students think, said Tom
Fisher, director of the state Department of Education's testing
department.
</P>
<P>
   It was developed in response to Florida's Sunshine State
Standards that raised the expectations for students. For example,
the standards for math for all fifth-graders say they should be
able to identify number patterns and ``make predictions'' using
those patterns. A major function of the FCAT is to measure how a
student is doing in relation to the standards, rather than to other
students.
</P>
<P>
   Using the test results, the state DOE can also identify schools
that aren't performing well, and district officials can determine
which teachers are doing effective jobs, Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   On the math section, which is given to fifth-, eighth- and
10th-graders, not all of the questions are multiple-choice.
Fifth-graders have to understand a concept and from that draw bar
graphs or finish patterns. On the reading section, given to
fourth-, eighth- and 10th-graders, students have to explain in
writing the lessons they learned from it. That is judged on
accuracy and detail.
</P>
<P>
   These are not questions that students typically see on a
standardized test, said Patricia Ordonez-Felicia, a math teacher at
John F. Kennedy Middle School who reviewed questions for the state.
But they are the type of questions that a regular eighth-grader
should be able to answer, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't try to make it fancy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the FCAT does not compare a student's achievement to other
students, parents will not get a percentile score.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the parents will get a number between 100 and 500, and
that score will be placed into one of five achievement levels.
Children who score in Level One haven't mastered basic reading and
math skills. A Level Five score would be best _ it means a child
could answer the more challenging questions correctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be nice to have clear, statewide standards on what it
means to be proficient in reading and math,'' Baron said.
</P>
<P>
   The students took the test in January; the results were released
in May. Statewide and locally, students scored an average 300
points of a possible 500. At the time, the numbers didn't mean
much. But last week, each student's score was explained using the
newly defined achievement levels. Those achievement levels may be
adopted by the state in November.
</P>
<P>
   Most Palm Beach County students scored in the two lowest levels.
No more than 7 percent of Palm Beach County students scored in the
top level in reading or math. Black students scored worse than
white students, but many white students also brought home low
scores.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity among white, black and poor student scores isn't
unusual _ most tests show an achievement gap _ and it raises a
familiar question: Is the test biased against black or poor
students? Does it ask questions about bouillabaisse or lacrosse, or
any subjects that might be more familiar to white or more affluent
students?
</P>
<P>
   Fisher says no. The test is ``not a vehicle causing the
problem,'' but it is part of the solution, he said. It reveals the
disparity so that teachers and school officials can do something
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Are testing officials disappointed by the dismal showing? Not a
bit, Fisher said. They would have been disappointed if students had
scored very well. Great scores are the sign of a poor test, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the scores) get high enough, it's time to throw the test
in the trash. The whole idea is to set standards and move forward,
set standards and move forward again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, state officials want all students in the top three
levels, but most in Level Three _ like half of a bell curve, Baron
said. And as hard as the FCAT is supposed to be, he said that's not
an impossible goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be amazed at what (students) can do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
