<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UT-FRESHMAN-PROGRAM29     10-28 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-FRESHMAN-PROGRAM29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT implements program to ease freshman fear
 &HT;    By Angela Shah
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A problem that has dogged the University of
Texas for years slapped freshman Cristina Maas in the face when she
walked into a philosophy class of 160 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first week, I was, like, scared to death,'' Maas said. ``I
walked into class and there were all those faces that I didn't
recognize. It was a really intimidating situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Auditorium-size classes have long been the standard freshman
fare at UT _ the nation's largest university _ and are believed to
be one culprit keeping students from graduating. They also have
thwarted the school's efforts to attain a stellar ranking
nationally. On a campus with almost 50,000 students, UT's 6,744
freshmen often get lost in the shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   But UT administrators hope a new program started this fall and
designed to better assimilate freshmen into university life will
change that. Freshmen Interest Groups, or FIGs, aim to make UT feel
smaller by grouping students in similar majors in the same set of
classes. The program would be one of the university's largest
efforts to solve its freshmen retention problem on a grand scale.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the groups, Maas said, she quickly became as
comfortable on campus as in her hometown neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I walk in and I see at least 20 people I know,'' she said.
``I have a better sense of home.''
</P>
<P>
   That comfort level is key to keeping freshmen in school and,
more important, to helping them succeed. Only 30 percent of UT
freshmen graduate in four years. In five years, that number rises
to about 63 percent. Administrators say that's not high enough.
''The biggest complaint we get is that UT doesn't feel like a
home,'' said Nina Bhatia, a humanities and English senior who
volunteers as a peer mentor for a FIG on campus. ``This is a way to
show them that they belong to the university.''
</P>
<P>
   The university's focus on freshmen arrives as research
universities are being scrutinized for not paying enough attention
to undergraduate education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to help students adjust to life at the university by
giving them a small cohort of people with whom they share their
experiences,'' said Jim Vick, UT vice president for student
affairs. ``We have the potential to reach out to a lot of
students.''
</P>
<P>
   Maas, like so many other students, had attended UT's summer
orientation, where freshmen get nickel tours of UT, learn a
smattering of the school's traditions and register for fall
classes. During the orientation sessions, students in the Liberal
Arts, Engineering, Natural Sciences and Fine Arts colleges were
told of the FIGs and encouraged to apply. Maas took UT up on the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was going to take these classes anyway,'' Maas said of the
humanities courses offered in her Traditions and Beliefs FIG.
``This way I get to meet people, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In the program, 30 groups of up to 25 students each take three
related courses that are linked to students' majors. Some of the
groups' offerings have catchy names such as The X-Files (psychology
and astronomy), The Bold &AMP; The Beautiful (classical mythology and
American photography) and Law &AMP; Order (sociology/juvenile
delinquence and English/crime and punishment).
</P>
<P>
   Each group has a volunteer peer adviser like Bhatia, an
upperclassmanwho is the students' liaison with administrators and
faculty. Once a week, these advisers meet for an hour to give tours
of the libraries or simply to socialize. As a result, many UT
freshmen say they have formed a community tethered by classes and
reinforced with e-mail and phone lists of classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was worried about being a number,'' said Casey Meyers, a
freshman government student, who is in the Changing Face of
Medicine group for pre-med students, ``but this took care of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Maas, the liberal arts freshman, joined a dozen or so
of her FIG classmates at the Texas Union. Sitting around a table
savoring scoops of Amy's ice cream, the multiracial student group
resembled an archetypal Bennetton ad sculpted by Madison Avenue.
The gregarious group members drew out the wallflowers, razzing each
other like old friends. Soon, they hope to get a weekly dinner
group going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think that the students have bonded faster than
usual,'' Bhatia said. ``To use the most cliche(accent)d word at the
university, they have established a greater sense of community than
I think freshmen normally do.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar interest groups have flourished at other state
institutions such as University of Oregon in Eugene, where they
were created in 1982 and involve one-third of incoming freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Though Oregon only has 13,000 undergraduates, just one-fourth of
UT's student population, Jack Bennett, director of Oregon's FIG
program, said both institutions ``have the same issues of
connecting students to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   About 1,100 students at Oregon are enrolled in FIG programs that
include a College 101 class, tours of campus libraries and other
student resources and seminars on alcohol abuse and sexuality.
Students are even expected to write a four-year college career
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program creates an attitude of curiosity,'' Bennett said.
``It begins with a group of peers that take ideas seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   The proof, Bennett added, is in graduation rates. About 45.3
percent of freshmen who participated in Oregon's program graduated
in four years, compared with 34.7 percent of non-FIG students.
</P>
<P>
   UTprofessors said they are optimistic about their FIGs. Billy
Wood, who teaches FIG students in mechanical engineering and is
also the undergraduate adviser for the College of Engineering, said
test scores this semester are the highest ever.
</P>
<P>
   Al Martinish, Maas' philosophy professor, regularly has lunch
and coffee with the FIG students in his class.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of banter going on,'' Martinish said. ``They're
very comfortable debating with each other even though they have
very different attitudes on the things we cover.''
</P>
<P>
   Some professors are already finding ways to improve the program.
Tommie Meyer, an assistant instructor of American Studies who
teaches in the Project Planet groupfor natural science
students,said he had to reconstruct his class plans because the
freshmen were ill-prepared to handle a seminar course. His students
were unable to openly debate discussion topics. He admits he's
frustrated that he was left to do most of the talking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent all this time preparing for this class and then . . .
I threw out my entire syllabus,'' Meyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, FIGs not only help students learn and stay in
school, they provide invaluable college experiences that will serve
students well after they leave the university, Oregon's Bennett
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Oregon, FIG students have moved out and gotten apartments
together (after graduation),'' Bennett said. ``They remain pretty
good friends. Some have even gotten married.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
