<SLUG> BC-NETSOLVE-OFFERING29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NetSolve plans stock offering
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ NetSolve Inc. of Austin is hoping to defy the
odds by selling stock to the public in the worse environment for
such sales in a decade. The company, which sets up and manages
large computer networks, plans to raise up to $51.75 million with
the stock sale, according to its registration statement filed with
the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   NetSolve's chief executive said the company realizes that it's a
tough market for public stock offerings. ``We're going to have to
see what the market conditions are,'' said Craig Tysdal. ``Clearly,
the market conditions haven't been supportive of pricing tech
IPOs.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Austin Internet company Vignette Corp. withdrew its
IPO filing citing the volatile stock market. PcOrder.com, an Austin
electronic commerce company, is still hoping to raise $35 million
through an offering.
</P>
<P>
   According to the investment firm Morgan Stanley Dean Witter,
about 75 companies have pulled their IPOs since August, and 15 have
gone public in that period.
</P>
<P>
   NetSolve, founded in 1987, has about 125 employees in Austin.
The company lost $2.2 million on revenue of $14.5 million in fiscal
1998. For the first six months of fiscal 1999, the company lost
$96,000 on revenue of $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   NetSolve would use the proceeds for general business purposes,
according to the filing. It may use some money to acquire
technology or other businesses. Underwriters are BancBoston
Robertson Stephens and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. Legal work is being
handled by Worsham, Forsythe &AMP; Wooldridge of Dallas and Foley, Hoag
&AMP; Eliot of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
