u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-BRAUNFELS-NEWSPAP     10-28 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-BRAUNFELS-NEWSPAPER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Braunfels newspaper doing business in a strip mall
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ The sign seen from the road still says
``A Cut Above,'' as in a haircut, as in what used to be produced in
the strip mall that is the new home of the New Braunfels
Herald-Zeitung, flood victim.
</P>
<P>
   Above the door, there's a sign noting the shop's new tenant, but
people still ask if they're in the right spot when they come in to
buy a classified ad or pay for their subscription.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this the right place?'' one woman asks, clearly confused.
``Is this the Herald?''
</P>
<P>
   The strip mall is the third unlikely home for this
circulation-10,000 newspaper since six feet of water surged up from
the Dry Comal Creek and swamped its red brick office. Like most of
their neighbors, the newspaper's employees have been busy salvaging
valuables, cleaning up and getting on with their lives after one of
the worst floods in Central Texas history roared through town.
</P>
<P>
   They've also been back at work every day since, putting out the
city's only local newspaper without missing an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how proud I am of them. I just felt it was
too important for a community that had been devastated so bad not
to have their newspaper come out,'' says Doug Toney, the Herald's
editor and publisher, who along with five others waded through
several feet of water Oct. 17 to salvage the computers that are the
brains of the newspaper. Nearly everything else at the
award-winning 146-year-old paper was lost in the deluge.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Bill O'Connell showed up for work early on the day that
18 inches of rain fell, ready to file a quick story on some
scattered road closings and get back home.
</P>
<P>
   He kept an ear to the police scanner, updating his story when
another road was closed, not thinking that his workplace was in
danger. By the afternoon, water outside the building rose high
enough to seep in around the doors.
</P>
<P>
   p
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you looked outside, you'd thinart of that,'' said
Margaret Edmonson, the Herald's managing editor. ``For us, there
was never really any question. That's what we were supposed to do,
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   It will take at least a year to repair the old building, still
strewn with notebooks and negatives and soggy from the flood. Toney
estimates the newspaper suffered at least $2 million in damage,
only about half of which was covered by flood insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But, the plain-speaking publisher said, don't make too much of
that victim business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is this isn't our home,'' he says. ``The fact that
people lost their homes is a hell of a lot more significant. We're
just doing our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
