<HEADER>
A0993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILD-EYES-CONTACTS29-     10-28 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILD-EYES-CONTACTS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jeepers, creepers, unearthly peepers!
 &HT;    By Scott Benarde
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Earlier this month, WIRK's morning drive
man J.D. Pelletier walked into a Winn-Dixie, approached an
employee, tapped her on the shoulder and asked for something for
his aching eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The employee screamed.
</P>
<P>
   This happened on the air, of course. But J.D. was just having
fun with his WildEyes, contact lenses with attitude.
</P>
<P>
   With eight styles available _ including the living dead-looking
White-Outs which J.D. wore, Hypnotica (think Vertigo-like spirals),
Pool Shark (they look like eight-balls), Wildfire and Cat Eyes _
customers are buying the lenses to enhance Halloween costumes and
amuse family, friends and co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted a pair of contacts like this for a while,'' says
20-year-old Alex Gentry of Delray Beach. Gentry was influenced by
the villain in the film The Last Action Hero. ``It was cool,''
Gentry says, how the guy's eyes kept changing color and design.
</P>
<P>
   He opted for White-Outs, the most popular design until the Cat
Eyes lenses (think Michael Jackson in his classic Thriller video)
hit stores in early September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were the best ones,'' says Gentry. ``They made
me look more sinister than the other ones. Also, Halloween's coming
and I want to be a zombie.''
</P>
<P>
   He also plans to wear them to work _ he's an assistant engineer
_ and to the Art Institute of Fort Lauderdale, where he takes
computer animation classes.
</P>
<P>
   WildEyes hit stores in February after a year of development by
Wesley Jessen, a company that has been making contacts since 1948.
In the late '80s, the company began making special effects lenses
for films such as Wolf, Interview With The Vampire, Death Becomes
Her as well as the Star Trek movies.
</P>
<P>
   Patients noticed the oddball eyeballs in films and well-heeled
customers began paying specialists $800 to $2,000 to have
special-effects lenses custom made.
</P>
<P>
   Contact lens maker Wesley Jessen figured a way to mass produce
them and lower costs. Its Halloween ad campaign features WildEyes
for $99 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the sales are to people who don't even have a
prescription,'' says Brad MacLeod, a spokesman for Wesley Jessen.
``They're just wearing them for fun.'' (He emphasizes, though, that
the lenses are not toys and wearers shouldn't trade lenses.)
</P>
<P>
   What happens after Halloween, or when the novelty wears off?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' says Alex Gentry, ``I still have my glasses.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
