<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1007 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MARATHON-THUGWANE-     10-28 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MARATHON-THUGWANE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUN-THUGWANE.)  
 THIS RUNNER OPENED A DOOR AND HELPS TO KEEP IT OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds, adding photo note; story moved Tuesday night as (ART ADV: Photo of Thugwane is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(bl) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As he crossed the finish line as the 1996 Olympic marathon
champion in Atlanta, Josia Thugwane of South Africa found his life
undergoing the same tumultuous change as his country's political
system.
</P>
<P>
   In that instant, everything was different. Nothing would ever be
the same.
</P>
<P>
   An athlete consigned by apartheid to living in a tin shack, a
man who did not read or write, was soon able to command an income
of half a million dollars a year. An unknown before the race, he
was now the first black in his country ever to win a gold medal. He
was greeted by President Nelson Mandela and was elevated into a
galvanizing symbol of a new, democratic South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a nation still grappling with unity and reconciliation,
Josia was not a hero for blacks, he was a hero for all South
Africans,'' said Banele Sindani, the executive director of the
South African track and field federation. ``He was someone we could
all rally around. After something like that, you don't go backward.
It has contributed to healing the wounds of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But, upon his return home, there seemed to be as much concern as
celebration regarding Thugwane, (pronounced tug-WANNE) who has said
that he grew confused. Would this tidal wave of change capsize his
career? Would unsavory people try to exploit him? Could he hold
onto this money and his motivation? Would the vestiges of apartheid
suck at him insidiously, like an undertow?
</P>
<P>
   Not everything has gone as smoothly as the Olympic marathon.
After the Atlanta Games, Thugwane was beaten at home in a traffic
scuffle after he inadvertently cut off another driver; this
followed a scary incident before the Olympics when he was carjacked
and shot, a bullet grazing and scarring his chin.
</P>
<P>
   And in a country that has been slow to fulfill its promises of
houses and jobs, Thugwane has found that people wanted his money,
whether he wanted to give it to them or not. Some were beggars, he
said; others attempted to rob his wife when he left home to train
for races.
</P>
<P>
   His incipient efforts at reading and writing ended after two and
a half months when a South African company that promotes literacy
seemed more interested in using his name for promotion than real
education, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, by all accounts, his life has remained on a steady course.
</P>
<P>
   Thugwane, who is 27, has run his fastest races since Atlanta,
winning the Fukuoka Marathon in Japan last December and setting a
South African national record. With a personal best of 2 hours 7
minutes 28 seconds, he enters Sunday's New York City Marathon as
the fastest competitor in a deep field of Kenyan, Mexican, Moroccan
and Spanish challengers.
</P>
<P>
   He has quit his custodial job at a coal mine to become a
full-time athlete. A member of the Ndebele tribe, he has learned to
speak English. He has moved his family from a squalid township,
first to a house bought for him by the mine and then into a
comfortable suburb of Johannesburg, where an alarm system and
private security guards protect against intruders. He bought
another house for his parents. Where once he lived without
electricity and running water, he now has a cellular phone, a fax
and a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``More money can mean more problems, but there are a lot of poor
people with empty stomachs at home,'' said the 5-foot-2-inch,
99-pound Thugwane, who has been training for two months at altitude
in Albuquerque, N.M. ``People see me making money from running and
now they think they can make money, too.''
</P>
<P>
   After Atlanta, Thugwane settled on an American-based agent, Luis
Posso, of Tampa, Fla., who works with a South African associate,
Jaques Malan. Posso said that Thugwane, his wife, Zodwa, and their
four daughters are set financially for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, he was always worried, about money, about the safety
of his family,'' Posso said. ``Now I see him as a happy guy with no
worries.''
</P>
<P>
   Thugwane has signed a shoe contract with Nike, and has another
endorsement deal with Coca-Cola to conduct grass-roots clinics in a
country where apartheid left only one all-weather running track for
all of black South Africa. Once he could not afford his own running
shoes; now he hands them out free to children, Posso said.
</P>
<P>
   While some of his other clients go through expensive cars like
socks, Posso said, Thugwane wants nothing more exotic than a Toyota
Camry. It is this life of simple humility that has kept his running
from detouring into the potholes of sudden wealth and fame, Sindani
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Josia has not lost his humility,'' Sindani said. ``I believe
that will take him to an even higher level. I'll say it now, I
won't be surprised if he wins the Olympic marathon a second time in
Sydney'' in September of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Thugwane would like to be included more often in clinics given
by the South African track federation, which he said sometimes
ignores him. Posso said there would be a renewed effort to teach
him to read and write. For now, though, Thugwane is concentrating
on New York. He ran here in 1995, but dropped out after 18 miles
because of the bitter cold.
</P>
<P>
   Heat doesn't bother him, as he showed in the suffocating air of
Atlanta. And now he has apparently also conditioned himself against
the cold. On Oct. 4, he won the Great Northern half marathon in
1:02:32 on a chilly, rainy day in Newcastle, England. The forecast
for Sunday in New York is for temperatures climbing through the
50's with high clouds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know now I can run in the cold,'' Thugwane said.
</P>
<P>
   He injured a calf muscle days before the London Marathon last
spring and dropped out after 10 miles. ``Everything is fine, so I
don't talk too much,'' said Thugwane, who has paid for two training
partners in Albuquerque, where he said he has prepared for New York
by running for two hours six days a week.
</P>
<P>
   He longs to return home after the race, but at least he can feel
reasonably certain that his family will be protected in his
absence. When he lived near the Koornfontein coal mine east of
Johannesburg, he said, people would read in the newspaper or see on
television that he was out of town, training for a marathon, and
they tried to rob his wife. Others left animal parts and other
things on his lawn, as if to bring him bad luck, Posso said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided it was not safe,'' said Thugwane, who moved to
Johannesburg early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Posso has broached the idea of moving to Albuquerque
permanently, but Thugwane has so far declined. He wants to stay in
South Africa. And now that he has opened the door for others,
Thugwane is delighted to hold it open while his countrymen walk
through. He declined to run in the 1997 world marathon
championships, he said, giving his spot to another runner who had
not had the same exultant opportunity to compete against an
international field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gold medal opened many doors; I can go anywhere,''
Thugwane said. ``Other young men haven't had that chance. I want to
give them the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-28-98 0100EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1110EST &QL; 
