<HEADER>
A1025 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON     10-28 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Microsoft Hopes New Name Will Jazz Up Software  
 By Benny Evangelista   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an effort to extend the Windows brand even further, Microsoft
Corp. yesterday said it is changing the name of its operating
system for businesses from Windows NT to Windows 2000 and
introduced an operating system for smart cards.
</P>
<P>
   The name change, announced by Microsoft officials in San
Francisco, is aimed at creating the same consumer awareness for the
more powerful NT operating systems that Microsoft now has with its
Windows 95 /98 PC operating software.
</P>
<P>
   And at a Paris trade show, Microsoft launched its first
operating system for smart cards _ which contain microchips that
store personal or financial information.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will compete in the chip card market with systems
based on Sun Microsystem's Java software. The worldwide market for
chip cards will jump from $1.4 billion in 1997 to $6.8 billion in
2002, according to Dataquest Inc. of San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Elgan, editor of Windows magazine, said the two
announcements get rid of a ``bad name'' (NT was short for new
technology) and signal a further move by Microsoft to create one
standard in the minds of all consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming increasingly clear that Microsoft really does
want to put a Microsoft operating system on anything that is even
remotely computerlike,'' Elgan said. ``They want to be the center
of the universe. They want to be the ocean that everyone swims
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which is on trial in Washington on federal antitrust
charges that it misused its monopoly position with Windows 95 and
98, announced it is changing all of its business operating software
to Windows 2000, with specific products taking on the name of the
markets they serve.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Windows NT Server becomes Windows 2000 Server,
while Windows NT Workstation becomes Windows 2000 Professional. The
company also announced a new product called Windows 2000 Datacenter
Server, aimed at bigger corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Beilinson, Microsoft's Windows 2000 product manager, said
company research showed business customers didn't fully understand
Windows NT and confused it with alternative operating systems like
Unix.
</P>
<P>
   The new Windows 2000 name brings the old NT more in line with
Windows 95/98 in the minds of consumers and businesses, he said.
Beilinson added that future versions of Windows 98 might be called,
for example, ``Windows 2030 Consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Elgan said the name change may also mean a future ``Windows 2003
Home, or Windows 2003 Family or Windows 2003 Kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The name change is purely perception manipulation,'' Elgan
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum, Microsoft unveiled a Smart
Card for Windows, an operating system with a memory capacity of 4.5
kilobytes. The smart card system is smaller than Windows CE, which
runs on 300 kilobytes of memory.
</P>
<P>
   During an announcement at the Cartes '98 smart card trade show
in Paris, Microsoft also said 20 hardware companies now make smart
card products that will use the system, including two of the
biggest, France's Gemplus and Schlumberger Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said it will cost $2 to $5 to produce a card using
Smart Card for Windows, compared to $15 for Java-based cards.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the smart card market is in now Europe, where they are
used as prepaid phone cards and bank cards. But analysts have said
Microsoft's entry may hasten development of the smart card market
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another facet of Microsoft's long-running campaign to
make Windows omnipresent,'' said analyst Christopher Galvan of
Hambrecht &AMP; Quist.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-27-98 2138EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
