<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETRATINGS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 NetRatings Joins Nielsen to Track Web Audiences  
 By Carol Emert   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NetRatings Inc., the underdog in the Web-ratings business, is
teaming up with Nielsen Media Research, the well-known television
ratings company, to track Web audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The companies' announcement of a strategic alliance yesterday
came just two weeks after Media Metrix, the top Web
audience-measurement company, announced a merger with No. 2 ranked
Relevant Knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   All of the companies use panels of computer users to project
which Web sites receive the most visitors. They also identify key
demographic information about surfers such as their age, gender and
household incomes.
</P>
<P>
   NetRatings of Milpitas has been criticized for its research
methodology, particularly its small panel size, which includes
3,500 people, compared with 40,000 for Media Metrix. Nielsen of New
York, meanwhile, has been trying to launch a Web measurement
service for about two years but has not gotten it off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The new alliance will combine Nielsen's methodology and
NetRatings' tracking technology into a service called Nielsen
NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen will take a ``significant equity position'' in
NetRatings, and two Nielsen executives will join NetRatings' board.
However, the companies will remain separate entities. Financial
details were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Monahan, of the San Francisco interactive ad agency Left
Field, said there appears to be enough Web business to support both
Media Metrix, which is headquartered in New York, and Nielsen
NetRatings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We subscribe to Relevant Knowledge and to NetRatings'' because
they offer slightly different services, said Monahan, a media
supervisor. ``It's almost going to be a question of personal
preference.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-27-98 2138EST &QL;
</P>
