<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEAPER THINKPADS STILL CLASSY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   This is the first installment of a new column by Peter H. Lewis. 
Each week he will write about new products and developments in the
electronics industry of interest to consumers. 
 By PETER H. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After spending nearly two years interviewing consumers about
their computing desires and habits, IBM has created a very
impressive new line of notebooks designed for people who spend
their own money on computers.
</P>
<P>
   Best known for selling hardware to the expense-account crowd,
International Business Machines has learned that individual
consumers have different desires than corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, IBM discovered, wanted a high-quality notebook not so
much as a traveling companion but as a substitute for a desktop
computer at home. And by the way, it had to cost less than $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's response is a trio of Thinkpad notebooks _ called the i
Series _ that will have base prices of $1,499, $1,999 and $2,499
when they arrive in stores next month.
</P>
<P>
   I've been testing the momma-bear version, the $1,999 Thinkpad
1450. It is about twice the size of the older Thinkpad 560X, the
slim four-pound model that I carry on business trips, but it is
also half the cost, and it outperforms the smaller machine. For a
desktop substitute, the added heft is actually an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   (But when I carry the external disk drive, CD-ROM drive, AC
power adapters, port replicator and other attachments, the 560X
actually weighs eight pounds, slightly more than the Thinkpad
1450.)
</P>
<P>
   The new Thinkpad has a big, bright display that outshines
anything offered by competitors in the price range, respectable
performance from its 266-megahertz Pentium MMX processor and lots
of features that make it more friendly to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The new Thinkpads arrive in what has already been a delightful
season for portable PCs. Earlier this year, a resurgent Apple
Computer Corp. introduced the impressive line of powerful G3
Powerbooks. Dell Computer offered a high-end Inspiron notebook
featuring a Texas-sized 15-inch active-matrix display.
</P>
<P>
   Sony broke new ground with a powerful yet super-skinny
subnotebook computer, its magnesium-hulled Vaio 505. And we are
just beginning to see a new crop of ultraportable computers that
weigh a couple of pounds and cost less than $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Either because of price or features, however, none of these
computers seemed ideal for consumers who wanted an all-in-one
portable PC that could serve as a replacement for a desktop
computer at a reasonable price. (An all-in-one portable includes a
floppy drive and a CD-ROM drive in the main body along with the
hard disk, instead of forcing them onto the desktop as tethered
external devices, octopus style.)
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, prices for Pentium-class notebooks with
active-matrix thin-film transistor color displays _ the best in
terms of brightness and sharpness _ were above $5,000.
Expense-account customers quickly made Thinkpads the most desired
Windows notebooks in the airlines' first-class sections.
</P>
<P>
   But when it came to buying a computer for personal use, even
corporate executives had to think twice about Thinkpads. With
prices for desktop computers dropping every week, in some cases
below $1,000, it did not take a chief financial officer to figure
out that one could buy two, three or more desktop computers for the
price of one high-end Thinkpad.
</P>
<P>
   The i-Series Thinkpads narrow the price gap between desktop and
portable computers.
</P>
<P>
   The one I've been using has the characteristic solid feel and
finish of a Thinkpad. In performance, it is still at least two
generations behind comparably priced Windows-based desktop
machines, but it holds its own with other laptop competitors in its
class. It wins hands down for cachet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get on a plane, it's still a status symbol to pull out
a big black IBM computer,'' said Andrew M. Seybold, editor-in-chief
of Andrew Seybold's Outlook, a newsletter about mobile and wireless
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   He forecasts success for the lower-cost i-Series Thinkpads.
``It's like when BMW or Mercedes came out with lower-priced
models,'' he said. ``People are waiting to buy them when you drop
the price.''
</P>
<P>
   There are three new i-Series Thinkpads. The least expensive is
the model 1410, which comes with an Intel Pentium MMX processor
humming at 266 megahertz, 32 megabytes of system memory, a
3.2-gigabyte hard disk, a 20-speed CD-ROM drive, and a 12.1-inch
thin-film transistor screen. The cost is $1,499.
</P>
<P>
   The model 1450, which I tested, will have an estimated street
price of $1,999. It also had a 266-MHz Intel Pentium MMX processor,
but it came with 64 megabytes of RAM, a 4.3-gigabyte hard disk and
a 13.3-inch screen that was exceptionally good.
</P>
<P>
   The poppa bear is the 1710 model, which steps up to a more
powerful Intel Pentium II processor, a 24X CD-ROM drive and an
extra bay that allows the use of a second battery or some sort of
removable data storage. Based on specifications alone, the 1710
model appears to make the most sense as a desktop replacement,
worth the extra money.
</P>
<P>
   The new consumer notebooks share several new features, including
at least 2 megabytes of video memory and a 56K modem. Most
impressive is that they all sport thin-film transistor displays,
which yield brighter and sharper images than the lower-cost passive
displays found most often on low-cost portables.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said it had decided to use the costlier but superior
displays as a result of ``exit poll'' interviews with recent
notebook purchasers. The most common regret among people who had
already bought notebook computers, IBM found, was that they did not
get a bigger or better display, despite the higher cost.
</P>
<P>
   In the category of little things that make life better, IBM made
the new notebooks much better suited to playing audio compact
disks. Working with the audio company Altec Lansing, it created a
speaker system that fits in the left and right margins of the
computer's display, creating a wider than normal notebook with a
bit of an overbite on the lid.
</P>
<P>
   Other laptops, like the Compaq Presarios, sometimes place the
speakers where they can be muffled by the palms of the user.
</P>
<P>
   The i-Series Thinkpads have the CD controls _ including a
liquid-crystal display, a volume control dial, forward and reverse
track selection, and eject buttons _ on the outside of the
computer, so a person can play music disks without having to boot
up the computer.
</P>
<P>
   For those who resist headphones and think that their mission in
life is to share their musical taste with the folks in adjoining
seats, the speakers in the lid are cleverly positioned to pump out
decibels to either side when the case is closed.
</P>
<P>
   There are cheaper alternatives if a consumer simply wants a
portable audio CD player, of course.
</P>
<P>
   IBM also clearly listened to people who wanted to become
productive with their laptops without having to get a degree in
computer science.
</P>
<P>
   The company's research revealed a list of questions that new
users often have, including such common stumpers as these: How do I
send a fax from my computer? How do I send and receive electronic
mail? How do I download files from the Internet? What the heck is
power management, and how do I do it? How do I write a letter or
make a business presentation?
</P>
<P>
   So IBM has answered the questions by creating shortcut
instructions for each task (available on the 1410 and 1450 models).
IBM also added four color-coded function keys to the keyboard that
can be set up to perform common tasks, like connecting to the
Internet (the computer comes with an offer of 100 free hours of
Internet time through American Online), gathering e-mail and so on.
</P>
<P>
   What don't I like? It seems a shame not to show off such
beautiful screens with a DVD drive, which would let travelers watch
movies as well as play audio CDs. An external DVD add-on is the
only option. The new Thinkpads are too big to use on airline
seat-back trays.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentium MMX processor poses a dilemma for students: It keeps
the cost down and is fine for e-mail, Web browsing and term papers,
but it is a lousy chip for serious game players.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is that the i-Series Thinkpads are a good
value, and the only question is whether IBM can produce them fast
enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-21-98 1615EDT &QL;
</P>
