 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Internet provides guide for ghouls 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is difficult to write about Halloween sites on the
World Wide Web without using any puns. But don't be spooked.
There's not a ghost of a chance you'll be left with haunting
memories of bad jokes here.
</P>
<P>
   We'll start our tour of the frightful sites with one called
Halloween at http://www.4halloween.com/ that can furnish all the
necessities for a traditional Halloween. You will, of course, want
to copy the recipe here for fake blood and follow some of the links
to the traditional scary stories that should be told on this
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   You'll also get hints here for making (or buying) a trick or
treat costume. And don't leave this site without reading up on the
various methods of carving a jack-o'-lantern pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've mastered that art _ and assuming you still have the
usual number of fingers left so you can operate the computer
keyboard _ let's move to Jody's Haunted Halloween Page at
http://www.netwide.net/users/lightner/halloween.html. Even if you
are unmoved by the most lifeless zombie and do not have a burning
desire to dress as a witch, you may enjoy this page.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there are recipes with a Halloween theme. You can,
for instance, prepare Tuna Spooks, or Bloody Devil Dogs, or
Gingerbread Ghosts with a little help from the recipes you find.
Or, if you lean more toward conventional fare, you'll find a good
recipe that will let you use the remains of your jack-o'-lantern to
cook up some pumpkin bread.
</P>
<P>
   But there's still more. You will find links to many other pages
with a Halloween theme as well as recommendations and designs for
trick-or-treat costumes. You'll also get some safety tips that help
make your own ghosts and goblins stand out in the dark to avoid
traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Halloween wouldn't feel right without a trip to a haunted house.
You'll probably find several near where you live, tours of the
awful with the admission price going to a charity.
</P>
<P>
   But if you'd like to take a tour of a virtual haunted house,
complete with sound effects and music, wander over to The Haunted
House at
http://members.aol.com/harley101/private/hween/hween1.html. You'll
also find a selection of Halloween sound files you can download.
</P>
<P>
   Next we'll stop in at a place that will give you ideas for
Halloween costumes. It's a page called Halloween and is sponsored
by McCall's Patterns. It's way too late to order the patterns from
this page at http://www.mccall.com/funstuff.html but the full color
photographs will spark some good ideas if you're planning to make
your costume this year.
</P>
<P>
   We've saved the sweetest of the sites for last. It's Hershey's
Halloween 1998 at http://www.hersheys.com/(tilde)hershey
</P>
<P>
   /halloween/. Since the site is sponsored by the famous chocolate
maker, as you would expect, there is some commercial content here.
However, as you might not expect, most of the page is used for
nifty Halloween screensavers you can download, a Halloween Handbook
that offers everything from safety tips to costume ideas, and a
really nifty feature called a Pumpkin Carving Planner.
</P>
<P>
   To use the planner, simply move the jigsaw puzzle like pieces
around. The notion is to try out various designs for a carved
pumpkin before you make the first cut. Even if you never carve a
jack-o'-lantern yourself, it's a lot of fun to use the designer.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
