 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Action Files carries on tradition 
By Charles Haddad  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the early days of Apple Computer, Now Utilities was
among the most successful and innovative enhancers of the software
that gave the Mac its distinct look and feel.
</P>
<P>
   Now Utilities was so successful Apple Computer added many of its
innovations to the Mac operating system. Things such as
point-and-click navigation through folders, hierarchical pop-up
menus and lists of recently used files and folders began with Now
Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere in the mid-1990s Now Utilities lost its way. It
failed to come up with new innovations and has not released a
version compatible with OS 8.
</P>
<P>
   The company was sold a couple of times and finally ended up in
the hands of a hot new upstart, Power On Software. Power On is
updating Now Utilities and incorporating it into its own popular
Action Files Software.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Action Files is the modern day successor to Now in
both function and spirit. It's a simple but powerful enhancement to
the Mac's open and save dialogue box.
</P>
<P>
   That's the window that pops up anytime you highlight and release
the open command in any menu. It lists files by name and lets you
navigate through a file or folder to a particular item.
</P>
<P>
   Action Files, like Now's SuperBoomerang utility, greatly
enhances this window. For starters, it adds a menu bar with lots of
new headings along the top. Those headings include not only a
file's name but also the size, kind, label and modification date.
</P>
<P>
   You can also sort files in this window, turn off column headings
and resize an Action File's window, something you can't do in the
Mac OS.
</P>
<P>
   But the best part of Action Files is its navigational tools. It
lets you save in a list your favorite files and folders. Just
highlight the item you want to add to your favorites list and hit
the space bar.
</P>
<P>
   The item now appears every time under either the document or
folder heading in the menu bar. To jump to any particular item,
just highlight it in the menu. This is a great timesaver.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find Action Files all over the Internet, from which a
trial copy can be downloaded. Among the sites are http://www
</P>
<P>
   .actionutilities.com and http://www5.zdnet.com/mac, the Mac
homepage of ZDNet.
</P>
<P>
   The price of Action Files is $39.95 for a downloaded version and
$49.95 for a CD version.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-26-98 1620EST &QL;
</P>
