<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNOBUDDY27-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Reboot your life _ give away your old computer 
By Bill Husted  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Computers can figure your taxes, connect you to the
Web so you find a good place to board your dog for the weekend, let
you pass a slow Saturday killing space aliens, and make your
spelling resemble English more when you write your Aunt Vera Mae.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing a person can do with a computer is give it
away.
</P>
<P>
   Now that prices are so low and new computers are so powerful
compared to last year's model, many people will be buying a new
machine. Today, I'm suggesting a fine use for the old machine. Put
it in the hands of someone who needs a computer but can't afford
one.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way to write a column like this without being corny
and sentimental. But some of the world's greatest moments are corny
ones. If you've gone a week or so without blushing, then maybe I
can help you find a way to reboot your life.
</P>
<P>
   When most people think about giving a computer away, the
practical side takes over. Before you know it, you are considering
IRS rules and tax-deductible ways to use that donation to shave a
tax bill. If that approach appeals to you, then there are plenty of
excellent organizations that could use that old clunker of yours. I
can even recommend a place here in Atlanta called Freebytes that
will even take in defective computers (it's also delighted to have
working models).
</P>
<P>
   It qualifies as a tax-deductible charity and has a Web site at
http://www.freebytes.org that will give you all the details. Even
if you live far away from Atlanta, the Web site can be valuable
since it has links to similar organizations in other areas. There's
nothing wrong with saving on your taxes and helping someone else at
the same time. That's real multitasking.
</P>
<P>
   But some of you may believe charity begins at home. And plenty
of my old machines have found places within my own family _
extended and otherwise. There's even an old 8088 machine _ if it
was a car it would qualify for antique plates _ that's happily
writing letters in Jonesboro, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of opportunities in most families. Maybe your
parents aren't properly wired. Think of the money you'll save on
phone bills if Mom and Dad can use e-mail to keep in touch and _
with a computer _ you'll be able to send them e-mails with
electronic images of the latest family happenings. Or perhaps there
is a niece or nephew that could use a computer.
</P>
<P>
   All these are fine uses for an old computer. But none of them
have the true blush value of giving a computer away to a total
stranger. If you really want to stammer and blush, think about
using your computer to change the life of a school kid.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, being able to log on to the Internet to get homework
help; or to simply fire up a computer to write a school report, is
almost as important for a kid as having access to books. But a lot
of families have enough trouble buying groceries. While computer
prices are lower than ever, even one of those $600 PCs that seem so
inexpensive to you represent a financial mountain for others.
</P>
<P>
   Most schools and churches can help you find a kid who needs a
computer. Or your own children may have a nomination to make. And,
if you have time, set up the computer and even give an hour or so
of instruction.
</P>
<P>
   If you take this route, you won't get a penny's worth of
deduction on your taxes. But my guess is it'll make you richer than
you ever dreamed possible. And your computer will have performed
one last fine task for you _ it may make you blush.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Husted writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
