r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEW-WITCHES-HNS &LR;      10-28 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-WITCHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITCHES PRACTICE THEIR CRAFT WITHOUT TOIL AND TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RENE A. GUZMAN  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ As a young girl, Sarah Unsworth MacMillan spent
many a Halloween in the black garb of a witch. But it wasn't until
her 30th birthday that she realized the costume was an extension of
her true self.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came into witchcraft through my studies,'' said MacMillan, a
Yale University graduate, former high school English teacher and
self-initiated witch who lives in San Antonio. ``I was even
encouraged by a Catholic nun at Yale to study more about the
feminine aspect of my god.''
</P>
<P>
   MacMillan and other modern witches prescribe to Wicca _ commonly
called ``witchcraft'' _ which celebrates seasonal and life cycles
with rituals from pre-Christian Europe. Unlike most patriarchal
religions, Wiccan worship recognizes a higher being as the
``Goddess,'' a pre-Christian god that is as much feminine as
masculine.
</P>
<P>
   Halloween, or Samhain (pronounced ``sow-en'') on the Wiccan
calendar, is like New Year's Day to a witch _ welcoming what
Wiccans contend is life's rebirth through the divine Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   And whether you attribute it to millennialism or author Anne
Rice, a new undercurrent of witchcraft is subtly bewitching the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's showing up like crazy in pop culture,'' said Phyllis
Curott, a Wiccan high priestess in New York City and author of
``Book of Shadows,'' which recounts her journey from Civil Rights
attorney to witch. ``Goddess spirituality is the fastest growing
spirituality in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   The entertainment industry has certainly hopped on the
broomstick, so to speak. Perhaps inspired by ABC's ``Sabrina the
Teenage Witch,'' the WB network recently added ``Charmed,'' a
television series starring Shannen Doherty and Alyssa Milano as
sisters in the craft. And Sandra Bullock and Nicole Kidman play
another pair of spell-casting sibs in the motion picture
``Practical Magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers are dabbling in witchcraft, too. Cover Girl makeup
has models Tyra Banks and Niki Taylor casting lavender magic
makeovers in an enchanted forest, while Camel cigarettes recently
ran print ads with three fetching smokers encircling about a table
of arcane items and rings of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Gone is the image of the old crone with hooked nose hunched over
a bubbling cauldron as she cackles incantations. The modern witch
looks shockingly contemporary. Save for occasional intricate
jewelry and floral headdresses, witches typically prefer a power
suit or jeans to black cloaks and pointy hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to dress extremely corporate,'' said Dorothy Morrison,
a Wiccan High Priestess of the Georgian Tradition who lives in the
Midwest but did not want her hometown to appear in this story. ``I
think it's better for the image. Flowing robes have their place but
I think we would have more credibility if we looked like normal
people because we are normal people.''
</P>
<P>
   And while men may be warlocks, most new Wiccans are young women
searching for an identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hugely popular with young teens and women in their 20s,''
noted Curott, who became a witch when she was 25. ``Women need an
image of the divine that reflects themselves. They haven't had it
for 2,000 years. Goddess spirituality and witchcraft affords the
image of the divine feminine.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said she ``stopped praying to Jesus when I was 5
because I realized Mary was the all powerful one, and no one would
dare disobey their mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Curott said the Goddess in Wiccan lore is the sacred life force
_ Mother Nature within the body _ an ever-present energy that
connects all things.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for a belief system that dates back hundreds of years (it's
commonly called ``the Old Religion''), witchcraft's fresh, New
Age-like philosophy still has clouded origins.
</P>
<P>
   The word witch actually stems from the old Anglo-Saxon word
``wicce,'' meaning ``wise one,'' such as a seer, priestess or
shaman who is able to work with unseen, divine forces.
</P>
<P>
   Wiccans contend their craft was founded by the people of Old
Europe who attuned their psyches and daily lives to the cycles of
nature. It was practiced for centuries in southern Italy and in
small villages of Britain. Later, witchcraft made its way to
colonial Virginia and New England.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian crusade to suppress the Old Religion resulted in
many deaths (mostly women) during the Inquisition of the 13th and
14th centuries, as well as the infamous witch trials in
17th-century Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Modern Wiccans still use much of the old terminology (many still
prefer to be called ``witches''), but they want to dispel the
historical misconceptions associated with their craft.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, witches stress they do not worship the devil or
cast spells to harm people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Witches do not acknowledge the existence of a Christian devil
or hell,'' MacMillan said. ``Some pentagram users call themselves
Satanists. They may call themselves witches but the pagan community
in general wants nothing to do with Satanism or any kind of
relationship between Satanism and witchcraft. I wouldn't want my
kids to be involved in that or anywhere near it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Wiccan pentagram is often confused with the
baphomet used in Satanism, which is the pentagram turned upside
down to resemble a horned goat.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Wicca's acknowledgment of God (albeit a duel god) and
determined stance against Satanism still haven't won the affections
of some Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church has not changed its position that witchcraft is not
acceptable,'' said the Rev. John A. Leies, chairman of the theology
department at St. Mary's University of San Antonio. ``It is a
violation of the virtue by which we honor God.''
</P>
<P>
   Leies said the Roman Catholic Church was aware of the difference
between witches and Satanists but added that Wicca's
``superstitious elements'' are not accepted by the church. Nor will
it condone Wicca's defying of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't hear anybody in the church instituting a crusade
against witches,'' Leies said. ``In one sense, there's a greater
tolerance of Wicca, or white witchcraft, but the church is more
worried about the alliance with Satanism. The church says to accept
the reality of the devil.''
</P>
<P>
   But witches don't believe they will be condemned to hell for
doing or saying things ``deemed negative by someone else,'' said
Lori Christensen, a San Antonio witch who also teaches psychic
development. ``Wicca has no right or wrong. It's you and your
higher self that you face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
