<SLUG> BC-CANDY-CORN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDY CORN REMAINS THE KING OF SWEET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANIEL J. VARGAS  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Time to fess up. Candy corn is one of your guilty
pleasures.
</P>
<P>
   You love it. Say it. Again, this time with some semblance of
sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   You're not alone. The concoction of honey, sugar and corn syrup
is a Halloween staple. Americans will buy 20 million pounds of the
tri-colored, triangular treat this year. So say the number
crunchers at the National Confectioners Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candy corn sales are kind of a fall thing,'' said the NCA's
Sheila Heath (not to be confused with the candy bar, she added).
``There is some red and green candy corn around Christmas time, but
it's primarily Halloween.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Halloween without it. While you are at it, imagine an
Easter basket missing marshmallow chicks, Christmas without candy
canes, Valentine's without those chalky little hearts bearing mushy
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Candy corn's significance is undisputed, but how did this
corn-craving craze come to be?
</P>
<P>
   Candy historians say the fall treat evolved in the 1920s, but
they aren't sure who produced the first sweet kernels. Even
professors who are experts in food culture couldn't answer the
question.
</P>
<P>
   Call it little orphan candy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit on the public relations board of the National
Confectioners Association, and I've brought it to their attention
but no one knows,'' said Gwen Stansu, spokeswoman for Favorite
Brands International in Chicago. Favorite Branks owns Farley's and
Sathers, both of which churn out several billion kernels per year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll continue our search for an answer. Someday someone will
own up to it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its mysterious origin, candy corn's place in the candy
universe was clear from the beginning. Its hues of yellow, orange
and white destined it to become Halloween's soul mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``With its fall colors, it was a perfect fit,'' Stansu said.
``You can put the candy corn in a bowl on the table and it just
says `Halloween.' The whole experience just caught on.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 70-plus years later, it remains a thriving relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Candy corn spooks all other nonchocolate treats in sales this
time of year, helping make Halloween the biggest candy holiday. It
rakes in about $1.8 billion, leaving Valentine's Day, Easter and
Christmas in a cloud of, um, corn.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the recipe for candy corn, but don't try this at home:
</P>
<P>
   Fifty thousand pounds of corn syrup, honey and sugar are mixed
in a giant beater and then heated in bathtub-sized kettles until a
creamy syrup, called ``slurry,'' forms.
</P>
<P>
   The slurry is poured into silver vats, into which the yellow and
orange colors are added.
</P>
<P>
   The white portion (tip) of the candy corn is mixed in a special
vat. It receives special ingredients to make it firmer, hence, the
different taste you may have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Next step is to add the slurry to triangular-shaped molds made
of cornstarch. First, the yellow band is poured, then orange and
white. Once done by hand, this process now uses machines.
</P>
<P>
   The kernels dry for 24 to 36 hours. Then they are removed from
the molds, dropped into a sifter to shake off any excess cornstarch
and get a shiny glaze.
</P>
<P>
   Candy corn is touted as a fat-free snack with 4.4 calories per
kernel. (Be warned, if you eat enough, your body will store any
excess calories as fat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
