<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONATION BRINGS OUT THE REAL MATT FONG 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If Matt Fong were the ``unifier'' he claims to
be, these are just a few causes the Republican candidate for Senate
could have given $50,000 to:
</P>
<P>
   _ How about a Matthew Shepard scholarship fund at the University
of Wyoming in honor of the young gay man beaten to death by thugs
two weeks ago?
</P>
<P>
   _ How about a child care center in San Francisco's Chinatown or
East Los Angeles?
</P>
<P>
   _ How about an agency that makes adoption easier for working
families?
</P>
<P>
   No, Fong didn't give the leftover campaign funds from his state
treasurer's race to any unifying charitable cause like those, a
cause he'd be proud to mention in campaign speeches and ads in his
race for senator against the incumbent, Barbara Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   While advertising himself as a moderate, Fong gave the $50,000
to right-wing extremists, the Rev. Lou Sheldon and his Traditional
Values Coalition, a group that's against women's right to abortion
and has fought to keep gays out of teaching, marriages and
ambassadorships.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition even fought to put people with AIDS in urban
concentration camps, euphemistically called ``cities of refuge.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican National Convention in 1996, Sheldon told me
he was sure there must be good moderate Republicans, ``just as I'm
sure there are heterosexuals in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the most dangerous kind of right-winger, smart, savvy
and often witty, unlike the witless Fong who handed the man his
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, in answer to your question, he could have given it
to a day care center in Chinatown or some other charitable
organization,'' said Joseph Remcho, a Democratic lawyer who has
dealt with leftover campaign funds before. ``It's pretty clearly a
massive statement about where his heart is.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong's heart is with the heartless. I don't know where his head
is, or if there is anything in his head.
</P>
<P>
   After the San Francisco Examiner revealed Fong's June donation
to the Traditional Values Coalition, Fong was left sputtering about
how the donation was intended to change the group's more extreme
positions.
</P>
<P>
   You bet, Matt, and the NAACP should give money to the Klan to
change its more extreme positions.
</P>
<P>
   If by any slim chance Fong is elected senator, maybe he'll vote
to send millions to Serbian and Iraqi leaders so they'll change
their more extreme positions.
</P>
<P>
   If only Fong had said something credible, like he gave the money
to Sheldon in order to get an endorsement in the primary, he'd be a
lot better off.
</P>
<P>
   The people Fong hired as spin doctors have been reduced to
barely rotating quacks. Fong's campaign spokesman, Steve Schmidt,
who referred to Sheldon as ``Rev. Lou,'' said the money was meant
to help the Traditional Values Coalition with its ``voter education
efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   I've seen some of the Traditional Values Coalition's educational
materials, and they were pretty sleazy. They were effective,
though, and aimed at the U.S. Senate, the 100 most important voters
in the land.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon helped demolish the Senate confirmation of James Hormel
_ the gay philanthropist from San Francisco _ as ambassador to
Luxembourg by spending two days in the gay and lesbian room of the
San Francisco public library. Sheldon and his daughter Xeroxed
about 10 pounds of mostly raunchy and erotic material for each
member of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   As Kenneth Starr knows, they love receiving thick volumes of the
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon's idea was to convince senators that if Hormel helped
fund the library, he must approve of every book in it _ you know,
like Andrew Carnegie and all his libraries.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? Fong now says his donation was only earmarked for
survey research to oppose gay marriage, but maybe it's paying off
Sheldon's Xerox bill.
</P>
<P>
   In endorsing Fong, the San Francisco Chronicle said he is a man
who ``talks with passion about making the Republican Party more
inclusive to minorities and gays.'' The Los Angeles Times described
Fong as ``a low-key Republican moderate.''
</P>
<P>
   They look almost as foolish as Matt Fong does.
</P>
<P>
   If they don't retract their endorsements, the only thing they
can say is that they endorsed Fong to make him more moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, that works. And making Fong senator will make him smarter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
