<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZING SURVIVAL INSTINCTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Whenever I think of mazes, my mind immediately dredges
up ``The Shining.'' Not the book, the movie _ Jack Nicholson
murderously chasing Shelley Duvall and the little kid who played
Danny through the snowy maze in the mountains of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   I could have used Danny the other day, when I visited the Maize
(it's in a cornfield, get it?) at Alma School and Queen Creek
roads. Although his particular psychic gifts may have given him a
propensity to talk to invisible friends and scream ``Redrum!
Redrum!'' at the top of his lungs, Danny was invaluable in the
maze, nearly a human compass.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, I wasn't in that big a hurry. The temperature was
near 90, so freezing to death wasn't a problem. And, as far as I
know, I didn't have a crazed ax-wielding writer chasing after me.
Although some editors might have liked to have had a crack at it. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   I tackled the maze in the early afternoon, and pretty much had
the 6-acre place to myself.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as you walk down the dirt path, you're bordered on
either side by cornstalks held back by plastic chicken-wire
fencing. The stalks are 6 or 7 feet tall, so once you make your
first turn, you are immersed in corn, causing you to immediately
lose your bearings. Causing me to, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the point, after all. Mazes are funny things. When
you're solving one with a pencil on a children's menu at a pizza
parlor, you see everything from above. When you're down in it,
well, you're down in it.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain freedom, so they say, to willingly getting
yourself lost. They are wrong. They just have a poor sense of
direction. Unfortunately, so do I. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fight of the navigator
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I hugged the perimeter for a while, and not on purpose. I have
such a poor sense of direction and spatial relations that I don't
learn anything. I'll go over a path again and again before I
realize it's the same one _ the wrong one. Three times I tried
different paths, and three times I wound up back in the same place.
There are gates you can use as shortcuts, but at first I thought
that would be cheating, and soldiered on.
</P>
<P>
   Soon I decided that, yes, I would use the shortcuts. But by then
I was so lost I couldn't find one.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I ended up atop a bridge, where a man in a yellow
shirt (that's how you know it's him) offered help. Just tell me
generally where the center is, I asked him, pointing in the
direction I suspected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right over there,'' he said, and pointed directly behind me.
</P>
<P>
   Aha. So I glanced at the aerial map he had, and, in a few
minutes, wound my way to the center. Magellan, I ain't.
</P>
<P>
   The way out was a little simpler, although I didn't just retrace
my steps. The only way I know that is because on my exit I saw a
blue Pepsi cup someone had jammed onto a cornstalk. I don't know if
this was Hansel-and-Gretel-style cheating or just plain littering,
but, either way, it was wrong. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Professional concession
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It took me about 45 minutes to get in and out, which wasn't a
bad time. Most people take about that long, Dale Herbst told me
from his post in the trailer that serves as a concession stand. His
son, Brett, designed and built the Maize.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there was the person who wandered around for 3{
hours. I'm sorry, but that's when I'd whip out my Swiss Army knife
like it was a miniature machete and hack my way to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had to help people out,'' Dale said. ``A lot of people
get a little bothered.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale himself gets a little mixed up sometimes, when he's tilling
the paths.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get in there on that Roto-tiller you pay attention to
what you're doing and not where you're going, so much,'' he said.
``I'm going around and around. It's hard for me to find my way
through, I will admit.''
</P>
<P>
   No shame in that. The Maize can throw you off, and the feeling
lasts. When I was done, I headed south on Alma School toward home.
It took me almost five minutes to figure out the problem.
</P>
<P>
   I live north. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
