<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOXER VS. FONG: A DILEMMA FOR AN ASIAN-AMERICAN LIBERAL 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM WONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More than other political contests, the
Boxer-Fong U.S. Senate race has caused a battle between my head and
my heart. It is a tussle between the rational and irrational.
</P>
<P>
   For most California voters, a decision on the fascinating
face-off between incumbent Democrat Barbara Boxer and Republican
Matt Fong will be relatively simple. They will vote for the person
they like better _ who most closely stands for what they stand for.
For me and for other Chinese-American liberals, the choice is more
complicated.
</P>
<P>
   When Boxer first ran for the Senate in 1992, the choice was
simple for me. Her opponent was a right-wing Los Angeles television
personality named Bruce Herschensohn. Boxer was a feisty Marin
County liberal who espoused feminist and environmental positions.
It was easy pickings: Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, this year's race is no different because Boxer
still represents liberal causes, ones that I generally subscribe
to. It should again be an easy choice for me. But it isn't, and the
reason is Fong's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   At one level, my waffling is itself irrational. Fong's stances
on issues such as abortion rights, gun control and the environment
are ones I generally disagree with. A responsible voter, you might
say, would support a candidate who shares his views on significant
public issues.
</P>
<P>
   No argument there, except that Fong represents something
intangible that may not be apparent to most Californians. He is the
rare Chinese-American politician who has risen to the level of
potential national visibility.
</P>
<P>
   In a state with a long and sometimes troubled history regarding
its ethnic Chinese population, Fong standing on the precipice of
national political power is a potent symbol. It is ethnic pride
that causes my civil war of conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese-Americans are energized by Fong's candidacy, and
not all of them are conservative Republicans. Just take my own
relatives. One sister, not particularly active politically, is a
friend of one of Fong's aunts _ so she is helping Fong raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Another sister, more liberal and more politically active, says
she's voting for Boxer even though she doesn't care much for Boxer
personally. She can't see voting for Fong and what he stands for.
Her husband, however, has both centrist and iconoclastic political
views. He's going to vote for Fong because the Republican, as a
Chinese-American man, embodies what my brother-in-law believes has
been a missing or invisible element in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese-American Democrats clearly are divided on the Boxer-Fong
race. Some liberals have expressed support for Boxer with complete
certitude. Some centrist Democrats say they are crossing the line
to work for Fong.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons vary. Some express disappointment with the
Democratic Party for not embracing Asian-Americans more. They
didn't like how the party abandoned a handful of Asian-American
party fund-raisers during the campaign-finance scandal. They view
Boxer as insensitive to Chinese-Americans and issues of particular
importance to them.
</P>
<P>
   One pro-Boxer Asian-American told me that she does not have our
community in her heart. The feeling among a lot of California
Chinese-Americans, and perhaps other Asian-Americans, is that Fong
does have their interests in his heart, despite his moderate to
conservative stances.
</P>
<P>
   For me, Fong's $50,000 contribution to the Traditional Values
Coalition, a right-wing Christian group, is troubling, if not
defining. But as the election grows close, I just might wait until
I am inside the polling booth before I make my final decision.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
