<SLUG> BC-UTILITY-DEREGULATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHTING CALIFORNIA PROPOSITION 9 WITH YOUR MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARVEY ROSENFIELD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Proposition 9 is one of those rare ballot
measures that exposes the pervasive reach of cash-register politics
in California.
</P>
<P>
   The odd alliances organized against the ballot initiative
include three environmental groups lined up with utility companies
in support of nuclear power. Big labor standing side-by-side with
big business. Republicans and Democrats hand-in-hand.
Self-described ``low-income'' groups opposing rate reductions. What
unites so many groups? The answer, of course, is money _ your
money.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 9 is a referendum on a 1996 legislative deal that
requires ratepayers to pay off $28 billion in bad debts incurred by
Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric, Southern California Edison and San Diego
Gas &AMP; Electric. The arrogance of these giant monopolies pushed the
cost of electricity to 50 percent above the national average.
Deregulation was supposed to give ratepayers the right to choose
among competing electricity suppliers. But competition threatened
the three companies.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the Legislature. Its bailout of the utilities appears on
utility bills as ``CTC.'' This charge has destroyed competition.
Every power supplier that competes with PG&AMP;E must collect the
bailout charge from its customers and send the money to PG&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   To hide their thievery, the utilities agreed to give small
ratepayers a 10 percent rate reduction for four years. But
residential and small businesses are required to repay the rate
reduction bonds with interest for 10 years. (Look for the ``Trust
Transfer'' charge.)
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 9 prohibits utilities from taxing us to pay for
billions of dollars in obsolete and inefficient power plants. It
will lower our electricity rates by 24 percent to 37 percent,
according to the California Energy Commission. That's at least $250
per year per family.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is supported by the League of Women Voters,
Consumers Union, Consumer Reports magazine, the Sierra Club, Ralph
Nader and the Public Media Center.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities already have spent $30 million trying to defeat
Proposition 9. But you won't ever see their faces. In a remarkable
display of cash-register politics, the utility companies have
recruited a vast number of surrogates.
</P>
<P>
   The Planning and Conservation League, an ostensible
environmental group, got $70,000 in donations from the three
utilities (some of the most notorious polluters in the state) to
send out anti-Proposition 9 mailings.
</P>
<P>
   David Horowitz, the former television reporter now campaigning
against Proposition 9, got $106,000. The author of a supposedly
independent study critical of Proposition 9 got $100,000. The San
Francisco Greenlining Institute claims Proposition 9's rate cuts
aren't important for the poor. (It got $300,000 from the
utilities).
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the utility food chain: the state Republican and
Democratic parties, which each got $500,000. In ads and mailings,
these pigs at the utility trough threaten us with higher taxes,
litigation and ``chaos'' if we dare pass Proposition 9.
</P>
<P>
   Independent experts, such as the state legislative analyst, have
dismissed their claims. Indeed, the courts have already thrown out
the utilities' legal challenge to Proposition 9. A question for
after the election: How much of the tab for the utilities'
campaigning will ratepayers be forced to pay?
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the citizen-backed Proposition 9 has no money for
slick advertising. The people Proposition 9 will help the most
can't afford commercials. Instead, citizen volunteers _ members of
the new California Oaks Project _ are spreading the word. So the
campaign for Proposition 9 will determine not only whether
Californians will pay less for electricity, but also whether the
initiative process belongs to the people, or to the arrogant and
corrupt establishment that dominates our state.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harvey Rosenfield, president of the nonprofit Foundation for
Taxpayer and Consumer Rights, is co-author of Proposition 9.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
