<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-HNS &LR;      10-28 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D'AMATO FACES QUESTIONS ABOUT HIS WORK HABITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in the national news, ``a,'' category and political
news, ``p,'' category)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENVILLE, N.Y. _ Amid a spirited, blue-collar work force
cheering his speech, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato on Tuesday declared
himself a working man who shows up day in and day out to do his
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those men and women, they go to work every day, just like the
rest of Americans,'' D'Amato, speaking from a flatbed truck, told
many of the 370 men and women employed by locomotive manufacturer
Super Steel. ``And if you send me to Washington and I was too busy
to show up for work, then you should replace me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki earlier credited his fellow Republican,
D'Amato, for being on the job when the state needed him.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, D'Amato, who has relentlessly attacked his
Democratic rival, Rep. Charles E. Schumer, for missing dozens of
votes in Congress this year, was called on to explain why he, as a
Nassau County supervisor running for the Senate in 1980, missed 966
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Records released by the Schumer camp Tuesday showed D'Amato
routinely missed votes in 1980, when he was supervisor of
Hempstead, Long Island, and running against Jacob Javits in the
Republican primary and Democrat Elizabeth Holtzman in the general
election.
</P>
<P>
   The D'Amato data, which first appeared Tuesday on the Internet
version of today's edition of The Village Voice, shows:
</P>
<P>
   When he ran for the Senate the first time, in 1980, D'Amato
missed 10 of his final 11 county board meetings _ a 91 percent
absentee rate.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato missed 966 votes on ordinances and resolutions that
election year, including measures similar to those he has
criticized Schumer for missing. D'Amato did not show up for votes
on the county budget, tax rates and on funding for education and
senior citizen services. D'Amato skipped five of the six bimonthly
board meetings before the November 1980 election, starting in
August of that year, and all of the sessions after the election,
even though he remained on the public payroll.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has criticized Schumer the past six weeks for putting
politics before public service, even though both candidates have an
18-year congressional attendance average of more than 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Schumer campaign turned the tables on D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today Al D'Amato's glass house shattered,'' said Howard
Wolfson, Schumer's spokesman. ``Al D'Amato's whole campaign has
been a fraud. This shocking revelation is definitive proof that New
Yorkers can't trust Al D'Amato.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato, through a spokesman, said Schumer is desperately
seeking to divert attention from his own record.
</P>
<P>
   The senator has said Schumer missed 90 percent of the House
Judiciary Committee's votes this year and 99 percent of the Banking
Committee's. Schumer's staff has not disputed the numbers, but said
that most of the measures were procedural or that most of the bills
passed by overwhelming margins rendering his vote meaningless to
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has had a difficult several days on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, D'Amato was caught in an apparent lie when he first
denied referring to Schumer as a ``putzhead'' and then admitted
using the Yiddish slur. ``Putz'' literally means penis, but is
often used as a synonym for ``fool,'' and it was in that context
that D'Amato eventually said he used the term.
</P>
<P>
   As the contentious and close race _ some polls have D'Amato and
Schumer in a statistical dead heat, while others give the Democrat
a slight lead _ moves into its final days, the revelations about
D'Amato's prior record are damaging to the incumbent senator,
according to pollster John Zogby.
</P>
<P>
   ``He raised the issue, and he keeps hammering and yammering on
the issue of attendance,'' Zogby said. ``And now it's going to come
back and haunt him.''
</P>
<P>
   Marist College pollster Lee Miringoff said D'Amato has a problem
explaining why it was OK for him to miss votes when he was
campaigning, but not OK for Schumer. Marist is an independent
college polling organization in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, (D'Amato) cannot overlook one and not the other. I
would suspect this would require some backpedaling on D'Amato's
part ... I would suspect because of the close connection between
Pataki and D'Amato, it may require some explaining as to why `A' is
OK and `B' is not. Most voters would think there is a similarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, a check of state Legislature voting records
Tuesday found that Pataki, a former state senator and D'Amato's
handpicked choice for governor in 1994, also missed Senate votes
during his gubernatorial campaign. Pataki, who has attacked
Schumer's voting record, missed 123 votes in Albany while
campaigning to unseat Democrat Mario Cuomo, according to records
released by Senate Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
