<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRONAUT-PARAZYNSKI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `SCIENCE FICTION' JOURNEY FOR YOUNG ASTRONAUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KENNETH C. CROWE II  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ When Friendship 7 astronaut John Glenn
orbited the Earth three times on Feb. 20, 1962, Josephine
Parazynski followed the flight from her market in this upstate New
York town.
</P>
<P>
   She never considered that her only grandson, Scott, then just 7
months old, would be an astronaut. Even farther from speculation
was he would be traveling on the space shuttle Discovery when Glenn
returned to space 36 years later.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday afternoon, Parazynski, 87, will be sitting with
family and friends in her living room watching her grandson, Glenn
and their fellow crew members lift off from Cape Canaveral aboard a
space craft far more roomy and sophisticated than Friendship 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very nice to Scotty. They're very friendly. Scotty had
him over for dinner,'' Parazynski said about the relationship
between her grandson and Glenn, who is now 77 and the senior
senator from Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scotty's very protective of him. He's always guiding him,''
she said, pointing to her arm to show how her grandson, who is a
physician and will be monitoring Glenn in space, touches the
senator.
</P>
<P>
   Scott E. Parazynski, 37, spent summers and vacations visiting
his grandparents and relatives in Saratoga Springs, where his
father, John E. ``Eddie'' Parazynski, had grown up. Much of his
time was behind the register at Pepper's Market, the family
business next door to his grandparents' home.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Parazynski attended high school in Iran and Greece while
his father was working overseas for the Boeing Co. He graduated
from Stanford University and Stanford University Medical School and
now lives in Houston. He joined NASA in 1992, has flown on two
previous shuttle missions and has walked in space.
</P>
<P>
   On Josephine Parazynski's living-room wall hangs a picture of
6-year-old Scotty standing in front of a large building bearing a
NASA insignia. He's clutching a plastic toy rocket popular among
boys his age during the height of the space program. It's about
that time when he decided to be an astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview posted on the NASA Shuttle Web site, Scott
Parazynski spoke about flying with Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, my initial response was this is too good to be true,
this is science fiction,'' Parazynski said.
</P>
<P>
   ``John certainly was one of my role models, and one of the
inspirations for me being here today. Of course I don't remember
his pioneering orbital flight because I was only 7 months old at
the time, but my father worked on the Apollo program,'' Parazynski
said.
</P>
<P>
   Josephine Parazynski doesn't expect to speak to her grandson
until he returns from space.
</P>
<P>
   The most difficult moment of the 10-day mission for her will
come when Discovery is launched, scheduled Thursday at 2 p.m.
Eastern. She saw her grandson's two other launches in person. But
she worries and prays as the shuttle lifts off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll be able to cope better at home,'' she said. ``I'm
not going to miss it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1338EST &QL; 
