<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-OAKLAND-A'S-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GROUP SAYS IT MAY BUY THE OAKLAND A'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Just days after officials here hired a Boston
financial firm to find local buyers for the Oakland Athletics, a
group of sports and business figures has emerged with a plan to buy
the baseball team and a promise to keep it in the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball Hall of Famer Joe Morgan; Andy Dolich, a former A's
vice president; and George Zimmer, whose bearded, beaming face
appears in ads for his Men's Wearhouse clothing chain, say they are
assembling a team of investors to buy the A's once the team's worth
has been determined.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth partner would be Advantix, parent company of BASS
Tickets, for which Dolich is vice president for sports marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not made an offer,'' Dolich said Tuesday. ``We are
still out actively talking to additional investors. The group as
it's presently constructed will not be the final group.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Vice Mayor Ignacio del la Fuente said it was ``too early
to tell'' whether Dolich and his team would make a viable offer for
the A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they have any juice behind them. We'll see,''
he said, adding that other potential buyers were ``waiting in the
wings.''
</P>
<P>
   Current owners Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann have put the A's on
the block for $135 million plus $20.3 million in deferred player
compensation, a price officials consider to be inflated.
</P>
<P>
   John Russo, an Oakland City Council member, has accused the
owners of trying to price themselves out of the local market and
sell to investors who will move the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are successful in breaking the community's heart, they
will sell the team to the highest bidder,'' Russo said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland-Alameda County Joint Powers Authority, which
oversees the Oakland Coliseum, has demanded arbitration to
determine the value of the A's.
</P>
<P>
   Dolich said his group, if successful in buying the A's, would
restore the team's fan-pleasing performance and keep it in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be the intent of our group to move the A's to the
level that they had in their glory years of 1987 through 1992,''
Dolich said. ``You have to give the fans a team that they believe
has a chance to compete for the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   The team has had three losing seasons since the current owners
took over, and attendance has dropped from 2.5 million a year to
about half that number.
</P>
<P>
   Dolich said he and his partners wanted to keep the team where it
was, even if that meant remaining in the multipurpose Oakland
Coliseum rather than getting a baseball-only park of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it is folly to believe that this community would
look at building a new stadium,'' Dolich said. ``In the future, if
the economics makes sense to do that, sure, we'll consider it. But
right now the focus is in Oakland at the Oakland Coliseum.''
</P>
<P>
   Russo said the potential new investors were ``a very impressive
group. They've got baseball background both on the field and in the
front office, and they've got at least one prominent businessman
who has got a high profile.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to Zimmer, the Men's Wearhouse founder,
chief executive and company icon, who appears in all of his own
advertisements to tell viewers, ``I guarantee it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolich served as the A's vice president of operations from 1980
to 1991, and as executive vice president from 1991 to 1994. He then
spent one year as president and chief executive of the Golden State
Warriors National Basketball Association franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who owns a beer distributorship in Alamo, played for
Houston, Philadelphia, San Francisco and Oakland but was best known
for his stellar years with Cincinnati's Big Red Machine. He is a
member of baseball's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   As for Zimmer's ``I guarantee it'' slogan, Russo said: ``I'd
like to hear him say he's going to guarantee a World Series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
