   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-COCKTAIL (Undated) _ Two attempts to simplify the
burdensome schedule of medications prescribed to suppress HIV
infection have failed, allowing resurgence of the virus,
researchers are reporting in studies involving nearly 600 patients.
The two studies were designed to test an idea on which many
scientists and patients had pinned their hopes: that therapy
combining three powerful antiviral drugs, the ``cocktail,'' might
diminish HIV infection to such a low level that the virus could
then be kept in check by fewer drugs and the body's own immune
system. That way, instead of having to take the triple combination
for life, as some experts had predicted would be necessary,
patients might be able to back off and escape some of the side
effects, inconvenience and expense. By Denise Grady. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ All looks smooth a day
before the launching of the shuttle that is to carry John Glenn
back to space. By John Noble Wilford. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo) _ Brazil's finance minister, Pedro
Malan, announces details of Brazil's austerity measures, including
tax increases and spending cuts. A central feature is a tax on all
financial transactions, from checks to bank withdrawals to stock
market investments. The plan would raise the tax paid on those
transactions to 0.38 percent from 0.2 percent now. A tax on
corporate earnings will rise to 3 percent from 2 percent. The most
sensitive measure would raise the social security tax paid by
government employees and _ for the first time _ collect the tax
from retired civil servants. The extra revenue is expected to come
to $2.2 billion. The actions are expected to slow the economy and
increase unemployment. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 32
points, or 0.4 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 9 points, or
0.5 percent. Elsewhere, prices were down 2.2 percent in Tokyo and
there was no stock trading in Hong Kong. Stocks fell 2.5 percent in
Frankfurt, dropped 0.7 percent in London, rose 2.6 percent in
Brazil and gained 0.7 percent in Mexico. On the American debt
market, the long bond was down 22/32 point at midday, with the
yield at 5.12 percent. By Robert D. Hershey.
</P>
<P>
