<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1325 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSROOM-RAGE-ART-3T     10-28 1428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-RAGE-ART-3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKA SCHOOL MURDERS: A WINDOW ON TEEN RAGE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 First of three parts  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, Alaska _ One pitch-dark morning last year, 16-year-old
Evan Ramsey boarded the yellow school bus on Napakiak Drive with a
three-foot shotgun stuffed into his baggy black jeans.
</P>
<P>
   Classmates noticed he was walking with a limp but never said
anything. Two minutes before the 8:50 bell Evan walked into the
lobby of Bethel Regional High, removed his hat and coat, pulled the
gun to his hip, and shot sophomore basketball player Josh Palacios
in the stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys better run,'' he yelled as students ran for cover. A
school secretary described Evan's expression that morning as
``gleefully evil.'' For several minutes, he roamed the hallways,
firing randomly into the ceiling and the metal lockers before he
was confronted by the principal, Ron Edwards, a 50-year-old former
Marine.
</P>
<P>
   Evan pointed the black gun at Edwards. As the principal turned,
Evan shot him behind his left shoulder from about 10 feet away. He
then pulled another shell from his pants pocket. ``This one's for
me,'' he announced.
</P>
<P>
   He raised the gun to his chin but couldn't bring himself to
fire. Police shot at Evan twice before he finally yelled ``I don't
want to die'' and threw down the shotgun on a staircase.
</P>
<P>
   Josh and Edwards lay dying, the student holding his gold
crucifix, the principal cradled in the arms of his wife, a
substitute teacher, on the floor of his own office. The spray of
birdshot that killed Josh also wounded two other students, the
second shooting incident in a 16-month wave of multiple murders
committed by children at schools in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The frightening odyssey that led Evan to kill _ pieced together
from dozens of interviews, court transcripts, and Alaska
child-welfare records _ illustrates how the hidden culture of
severely troubled children can produce the kind of explosive
violence that has flashed in seven school shootings the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Just off the radar screen of most adults, growing numbers of
teenagers move in a world where violence is an option in resolving
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The glorification of violence has spread from inner cities to
places like Bethel, a lonely rural town on the Alaskan tundra where
residents still leave their keys in the car. And the presence of
weapons, combined with common teenage problems _ untreated
depression, substance abuse, suicide ideation, even teasing _ has
made the melodrama of adolescence more dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think growing up basically is hard,'' said Brock Rapoza, 16,
who was standing near Palacios when his friend was shot. ``I think
it would be real easy _ with a combination of hormones, the
problems you have growing up, and around here there's so much
alcohol abuse _ for a kid to just snap.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of bringing a gun to school ``popped into my head one
day,'' Evan said recently during three days of interviews inside
the Cook Inlet Pre-Trial Facility in Anchorage, where he is
awaiting sentencing Dec. 1 for what is expected to be a life term
in state prison. His face soft, his wrists and legs shackled, Evan,
who turned 18 in July, said he ``didn't really feel anything'' as
he killed his classmate and principal.
</P>
<P>
   Evan (pronounced E-van) lived with the superintendent of the
Lower Kuskokwim School District, who first took him in as a foster
child when he was 7. Slight, goofy, with brown curly hair and acne,
he wore winter hats in summer, was tough to beat at chess, and was
known at school as ``Screech'' _ a geeky character he was said to
resemble on the television show ``Saved by the Bell.'' He counted
the school's brightest students among his closest friends, but he
was frequently picked on by stronger, more popular boys. He was
polite to adults and carried his neighbors' groceries. In a region
where guns are as prevalent as screwdrivers, he had little
experience with weapons, including the 12-gauge shotgun that hung
unlocked near his front door.
</P>
<P>
   To most adults who interacted with him, Evan seemed like a boy
who was maturing after struggling for years to control his
explosive temper. But in reality, he was slipping badly. Two years
earlier, depressed about his home life and harassment at school, he
took down the shotgun and threatened to ``blow my brains out''
before his best friend, Wilson Naneng, talked him out of it. At
night, unable to sleep, he wandered his neighborhood for hours, he
said, amusing himself by tossing rocks at dogs.
</P>
<P>
   One night, 10 days before the murders, Evan received an
unexpected call from his father, Don Ramsey, 53, who told him he
had just been released from prison. An infamous figure in Alaska,
the elder Ramsey had served 10 years for storming the state's
largest newspaper, The Anchorage Times, with an AR-180 assault
rifle, a .44 magnum revolver, three smoke grenades, and a string of
firecrackers, and for briefly taking the publisher hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son, I'm out,'' Ramsey told Evan, who had seen his father just
three times since that incident. ``And I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan began to hang out with two new friends, both 14-year-old
boys. The three spent hours after school walking the boardwalks
that range across the area. They smoked unfiltered Camels and
marijuana together, and played violent video games on a Sony
PlayStation that one of the boys, James Randall, had in his room.
For hours, after school and during frequent sleep-overs, Evan and
James sat in the dark, immersing themselves in simulated killing.
</P>
<P>
   One day after being picked on, Evan recalled, he told James he
wanted to ``go out with a bang.'' He said he'd like to bring the
shotgun to school ``to scare the hell out of everybody and kill
myself.'' At first James didn't believe him, Evan said, but slowly
became convinced that his friend was serious. Evan said that James
and his other friend, Matthew Charles, began to egg him on. The two
boys even suggested several teachers and students he could kill,
including Ron Edwards, the principal, Evan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``James said, `Don't kill yourself,''' recalled Evan. ``He told
me: `You got to live the fame and the fortune.'''
</P>
<P>
   James, currently on trial for two juvenile counts of first-and
second-degree murder as an accomplice, acknowledged in an interview
that he showed Evan how to load the shotgun the day before the
murders. But he said he hadn't been sure Evan was serious about
taking the gun to school.
</P>
<P>
   The third boy, Matthew, told investigators he had offered to
``back up'' Evan with a .22-caliber revolver he kept at home. But
he couldn't, he said, ``because I'm only 14.'' Instead, he brought
a camera to take pictures of the shootings, which, according to
Evan, Matthew had hoped to hang on his wall. Matthew, who was
initially charged with first-degree murder as a juvenile, later
pleaded guilty to a juvenile charge of criminally negligent
homicide, and is in the custody of his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Evan told other friends that ``something big is gonna happen,''
that he was plotting ``an evil day.'' He told them to gather in the
library that morning, Feb. 19, 1997, on a mezzanine above the
lobby, out of harm's way. At least 10 students were there _ some
completely in the dark, others with a vague foreboding of what
might occur, and at least one apparently aware that Evan intended
to show up with a gun. But none alerted an adult.
</P>
<P>
   When the first shot was fired, Wilson Naneng and his girlfriend,
Cynthia, came racing down from the mezzanine in a panic. Both had
received calls from Evan the night before. Cynthia hadn't been
home. But Wilson talked to his friend for an hour and got the
impression Evan was planning to fight a student who had been
teasing him. But as they waited in the library, it occurred to
Wilson and Cynthia that Evan, as he had two years before, might be
planning to take his own life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed to make sense,'' Cynthia recalled later. ``He was
hurting so bad, you know, why not show everybody how much he was
hurting. But we thought that he would kill himself, not other
people.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the thought occurred to them, however, it was too
late. ``Evan was our friend, and to do something like that, it
totally destroyed all the trust I had,'' said Cynthia, a
16-year-old junior who asked that her last name not be used. ``You
just think, `Couldn't one of my other friends have done this,
too?'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (end of 1st take; 2nd take begins ... Inside Bethel
regional...)
</P>
</TEXT>
