 ART ADV.: Photos are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service
subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories from its
three-part series,  &UR; ``Killing in the Classroom,''  &LR; for use by N.Y.
Times News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   The series describes the frightening odyssey that led a
16-year-old Alaska boy to open fire at his school, killing a
classmate and the principal and wounding two other students. The
articles, by  &UR; Steve Fainaru &LR;  of the Globe staff, also detail how
the hidden culture of severely troubled children can produce the
violence exhibited in six other US schools the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about the series, contact  &UR; Roy Greene  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator and move under (a)
coding.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CLASSROOM-RAGE-ART-3 TAKES (Bethel, Alaska) _ Two minutes
before the 8:50 bell, Evan Ramsey Evan walked into the lobby of
Bethel Regional High, removed his hat and coat, pulled a gun to his
hip, and began shooting. A school secretary described Evan's
expression that morning as ``gleefully evil.'' 6000 words. Photo
showing Evan Ramsey awaiting sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CLASSROOM-TEEN-DEPRESSION (Undated) _ Rates of clinical
depression among teenagers are as high as they have ever been, and
the recent spate of multiple murders in American schools has led to
nationwide efforts to detect children at risk for violence and
suicide. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSROOM-PLOT-ART-3 TAKES (Bethel, Alaska) _ Rumors, not books,
drew Evan's friends to the Bethel high library. As it turned out,
he wanted his friends out of the line of fire. 6000 words. Photo
showing mother of slain classmate holding crucifix. w/
</P>
<P>
   CLASSROOM-GAMES-IMPACT (Anchorage, Alaska) _ Researchers fear
that the violent video games like the ones Evan played are giving
children a dangerously skewed perspective. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSROOM-AFTERMATH-ART-2 TAKES (Bethel, Alaska) _ ``I think we
no longer have that innocence where school is the safest place in
the community,'' Alaska Governor Tony Knowles said. ``We have lost
that.'' 4000 words. Photo showing muddy basketball court at home of
slain player.
</P>
