<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1332 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSROOM-RAGE-ART-2N     10-28 1704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-RAGE-ART-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BETHEL, Alaska: ... ``have done this, too?'''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inside Bethel Regional High, a rectangular mass of dark brown
wood, heads of moose, muskox, brown bear, and caribou are mounted
on the wall, testimony to the region's hunting culture. That year,
454 students _ mostly Caucasians, Eskimos, and mixtures of both _
were enrolled. Bethel (pop. 5,277), a hub for dozens of fishing
villages in the Yukon-Kuskokwim River Delta, is inaccessible by
car, so the high school basketball team, the Warriors, flies to
away games in a 10-seat plane.
</P>
<P>
   Before Alaska became the 49th state in 1959, the delta existed
in isolation. Many villages lacked telephones until the 1970s.
Television arrived shortly after. Today, most everyone has cable,
and the school district, which covers 10,000-square miles and
includes 25 schools, uses the most advanced technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here 19 years. The kids used to be incredibly
naive,'' said Gary Baldwin, director of personnel for the school
district. ``They had no experience with the media, or with exposure
to violence, or with video games... But things are changing here
really fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The region has one of the highest rates of alcoholism and child
abuse in Alaska. In 1992, the Bethel office of the Division of
Family and Youth Services (DFYS) received 428 reports of harm to
children; by 1997 that number rose to 1,361. The high school has
become more unruly, teachers and students say. The year of the
shootings, Bethel Regional registered 2,496 disciplinary
infractions, an average of 5.5 per student, and issued 108
suspensions. The major infractions included abusive language,
defiance, and disruptions (45 percent); smoking, alcohol, and drug
use (25 percent); fighting and rough horseplay (19 percent);
harassment (9 percent); and carrying of weapons (4 percent).
</P>
<P>
   A student showed up at a junior varsity basketball game that
year with a 9mm Glock pistol, which he threatened to use against a
visiting student who had pulled a knife on him. Girls informed
their parents, who in turn informed administrators, that drugs were
being sold in the school bathroom. Boys were caught on campus
filling soda cans with beer. Midway through the year, the school
board met to consider using a drug-sniffing dog to search lockers.
</P>
<P>
   In a safety survey that year, 55 percent of all Bethel Regional
students reported seeing drug and alcohol use on campus; 70 percent
said they knew students who came to school high on drugs or
alcohol. ``Kids will come to school stoned; they'll go out during
lunch time, during classes, and smoke pot,'' said Cynthia.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting beside her, Cynthia's parents, Marty and Jean, said
little. Both are nurses who moved to Bethel from Anchorage,
Alaska's largest city, to raise their children away from the urban
maw. Scholastically, Cynthia is thriving: Her grade-point average
is 4.05, better than perfect because of an A she received in honors
biology. She reads Hemingway and Nabokov.
</P>
<P>
   But socially she sometimes has struggled. In seventh grade, she
briefly dated Evan Ramsey. The two broke up but remained friends.
They hung out in a clique of students who, she said, ``were not
really wanted by anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia said many of her friends have struggled with the kind of
depression that seemed to gnaw at Evan. ``A lot of them have tried
to commit suicide or mutilate themselves in various ways,'' she
said. ``One of my friends was taking bottles of aspirin and had to
be taken into Anchorage for a day or two. My friends carve
themselves up with razors, burn themselves, pierce themselves. One
of my friends has slit her wrists several times, unsuccessfully.
There's probably something with every single one of my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiral of troubles began after father's rampage &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five feet 4 1/2 inches tall and built like a small kiosk, Don
Ramsey sometimes refers to himself as ``Yoda.'' He lives in
Anchorage in a sparsely furnished two-bedroom apartment with his
youngest son, William, 14. He lives with the shades drawn,
surrounded by computer equipment and thousands of documents
detailing his criminal history and his sons' experiences in the
Alaska foster-care system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, a fire destroyed Ramsey's apartment. A cab driver at
the time, Ramsey blamed the incident on local politicians. He sent
his wife Carol and their sons, John, Evan, and William, to live
with relatives in Fairbanks, then declared ``war'' against ``The
System,'' as he described it in an open letter to an Alaska senator
for which he bought advertising space in The Anchorage Times.
</P>
<P>
   Upset when the Times pulled the ad, saying it was in poor taste,
Ramsey walked into the newspaper's offices, chained the door, set
off smoke grenades and firecrackers, and made his way upstairs to
meet the publisher, Robert Atwood. After spraying the ceiling with
the assault rifle, he held Atwood hostage for several minutes
before the 79-year-old man and his 46-year-old daughter subdued
him. Ramsey claims he gave up when he heard Atwood's daughter cry,
``Daddy!''
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time they pulled me out of there it looked like the
last scene in `The Blues Brothers,''' joked Ramsey, who was called
``Rambo'' in prison.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 10 years, Carol Ramsey said, her husband had been
``the kind of person I was looking for: loving and caring. On
weekends we'd go for rides down the highway, celebrate the kids'
birthdays at home or at Chuck E. Cheese.'' When her husband was
convicted of attempted kidnapping, three counts of felony assault,
and two counts of reckless endangerment for the attack on The
Anchorage Times, she unraveled. ``That's when I started drinking,''
she said recently. ``I didn't know what else to do. From 1986 until
about two years ago, everything I did depended on alcohol. Every
morning I would have beer for breakfast and drink all day.''
</P>
<P>
   DFYS took away her children on Dec. 14, 1987. Tipped off by her
sister Ida, authorities found Carol too drunk to speak, her boys
huddled inside an unheated home with temperatures of 22 below zero
outside. Evan was 7. For the next four years, he and his brothers
moved between foster homes and their mother's, always returning to
state custody when Carol resumed drinking.
</P>
<P>
   One February evening, one of Carol's boyfriends punched John
Ramsey in the chest. John, who was 9, waited until his mother and
her boyfriend had passed out, put coats on his two brothers, and
set out in subzero weather. The boys made their way to their
principal's house, where Janna Hulse, his wife, found them huddled
in an enclosed porch at 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard a noise and thought it was a dog, but I went to take a
look and it was the three boys,'' she recalled. ``They had their
jackets, but no hats or gloves. So we gave them breakfast and in
the morning washed them and called DFYS.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol, a tiny, soft-spoken woman, lost her two front teeth a few
years back when a lover punched her in the face. She lives in a
small Anchorage apartment decorated with scenic jig-saw puzzles and
photos of her children. She is part Eskimo, part Athapascan Indian,
and when she speaks, it is difficult to imagine the horror that
seems to surround her when she drinks. ``When she's sober she's the
type of person you wouldn't mind hanging around with,'' said Evan.
</P>
<P>
   Even while he and his brothers were in foster care, Evan visited
his mother every summer. ``He always wanted to come stay with me _
a momma's boy, I guess you'd call it,'' said Carol.
</P>
<P>
   Evan's psychologist: `It hurts when he cries'
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, three months after DFYS first took custody of the
Ramsey boys, a state psychologist warned that Evan was ``beginning
to develop a real depression. He has no nice dreams. The only
beautiful thing he can think of is his cat, which died; and it
hurts when he cries.'' Evan was almost 8. The psychologist
recommended therapy and placement in a ``long-term, safe, and
affectionate home.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan lived in 10 homes over the next three years. In 1990, DFYS
received reports of abuse and discovered an older boy in his foster
home had caused bruises to Evan's face and neck. Evan later said
the boy urinated in his mouth. In a letter to the foster parents, a
case worker wrote, ``I'm sure that you readily agree children
cannot live in an environment where there is fear of being `thumped
on' by another child stronger than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan never received counseling. But later that year, DFYS found
a stable home for him and William with school superintendent Sue
Hare. (John had been sent to a relative in Anchorage.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the most prominent figures in the region, Hare oversaw a
school district roughly the size of Ohio. She held a master's
degree in public school administration. Fired after the shootings,
her 13-year tenure was the longest of any school superintendent in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   Hare grew up in Georgia and came to Alaska after seeing pictures
in a travel brochure. She never left. She married a local Yup'ik
Eskimo and settled down to a career in public education. One day
her husband David took a group of boys fishing on the Kuskokwim
River. His nephew fell in and when David went to rescue him, both
drowned. ``You always think the thing that's bad is the worst thing
that'll ever happen,'' said Hare, laughing mordantly. ``And then
you live a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hare was alone and already had two adopted children, a boy and a
girl, when DFYS asked her to take in Evan and William Ramsey. She
was traveling to schools throughout the district and often was busy
with work into the night. The state paid her $1,424 a month for the
care of both boys, but she said money was not a consideration. ``I
just felt so sorry for them,'' she said. ``You have two kids
turning up on somebody's porch and it's below freezing outside? And
DFYS says, `Will you take them; there's no other place?'''
</P>
<P>
   Elena Franks, the DFYS social worker who handled the case, said
Hare was chosen because ``she was licensed and she had the space.''
Hare had cared for 21 previous foster children, including a child
with leukemia who had died in her arms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ( &UR; End of 2nd take; 3rd take begins ... But many people in Bethel
...) &LR;
</P>
