<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1334 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSROOM-RAGE-3RD &LR;  &UR; T     10-28 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-RAGE-3RD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BETHEL, Alaska: ... died in her arms.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But many people in Bethel now second-guess the decision to place
the boys with Hare. In July 1992, according to Bethel court
records, Hare's adopted son, 27-year-old Sam, pleaded no contest to
sexual abuse of a minor, a felony. State law prohibits sex
offenders from residing in homes where foster care is provided. The
agency was aware of the allegations against Sam during a review of
Hare's guardianship that year, agency officials acknowledged. No
action was taken because Sam never molested Evan and was not living
at home at the time, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sue Hare and Evan said that Sam lived with the boys for
several years before and after his conviction. Worse, both Sue and
Sam Hare acknowledged in interviews that the shotgun used in the
shootings belonged to Sam, an apparent violation of his probation
and of federal law. Sue said she bought the gun long ago and had
given it to Sam to hunt ducks, geese, and ptarmigan. The gun sat
for years on a rack nailed next to the front door. ``William liked
to play with the gun,'' said Sam. ``William was just 13; he liked
looking at things. I'd tell him that as long as it's in the home,
it's OK. But Evan never picked it up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, you don't even think about it as an issue until
something like this happens,'' said Sue Hare. ``And then you go,
`Well, I would never have a gun in the house again.' But it's so
normal here to have access to guns. It wasn't anything that was at
any kind of level of my consciousness. It was a bird gun. I don't
think I even connected the fact that you can kill a person with a
gun that you use to shoot birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks, of the DFYS, said the gun never was an issue because
hunting is a way of life in Bethel and to question its presence
``would be unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   The first years of life at Hare's, Evan recalled, were ``like
the `Brady Bunch.' We went on our little outings. We went to the
playground, did things at home. We'd go out to the park, go to
restaurants to eat, go rent movies.'' But as he grew older he
struggled. He often fought with Hare's adopted children. In 1996,
police were called to Hare's home after Evan allegedly threatened
her daughter Pam and kicked a hole in the wall, but no charges were
filed. With Hare constantly traveling, she often sent the children
to stay with friends.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson Naneng's mother, Agnes, said Evan came running down the
street one day, crying. ``He asked if he could live with us,'' said
Agnes, who has 10 children, six still at home. ``I said, `Evan, we
don't have room, but anytime you need a place to go you're welcome
here.' He was the kind of kid who needed hugs, you know, people who
showed him they cared. I tried to do that for him when I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Agnes said she called DFYS and asked what it would take to place
Evan and his brother in a home where there was more adult
supervision. ``They said nothing could be done because Hare was his
legal guardian,'' she said. DFYS said it has no record of the call.
</P>
<P>
   Growing sense of tension, malaise in student body
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1996, a boy at Bethel Regional Junior High,
located on the same campus as the high school, told a 13-year-old
seventh grader that if he came to school the next day he would beat
him up. The youth went home, pulled a rifle from the hall closet,
and shot himself to death.
</P>
<P>
   Later, during one awful week, two other Bethel students lingered
on life-support systems before dying. One was a gifted student
athlete whose own house crushed him as he was lowering it with his
father, a physical education teacher. The other was a troubled
16-year-old who had gotten drunk and shot himself in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Between those crises and mounting discipline problems,
uneasiness began to grow among the faculty over what seemed to be a
growing sense of tension and malaise in the student body. None of
that concern, however, focused on Evan. Around school, teachers and
classmates were vaguely aware of his troubled life, but few knew
the details. He was known mainly as Sue Hare's foster son, a quiet
underachiever who often ran to Hare's office when his temper got
him in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Morris, who as dean of students was the school
disciplinarian, said Evan had trouble during junior high because
classmates ``knew how to push his buttons.'' He often would
explode, throwing trash cans, books, and other debris before
storming out of school. As a freshman, he tossed a chair in the
library, brushed aside a teacher who tried to restrain him, and ran
crying across the street to Hare's office. He received a two-day
suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, he got into a fight with Josh Palacios, the boy he
later killed, at a sandpit outside school. There are several
versions of what happened. Brock Rapoza said Josh, who was half
black, half Mexican-American, actually fought a friend of Evan's
who used a racial epithet against him. Claudia Palacios said she
was told by her son it was Evan who used the racial slur and that
``Joshua kicked his ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan said he had first hit one of Josh's friends ``and (Josh)
didn't like that so he beat my ass.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of letting it end there, Evan left for a few moments and
came back with a metal pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna kill you,'' he yelled, waving the pipe as Josh
scattered with his friends. ``He was freaking out,'' said Brock,
who witnessed the outburst. ``It was like he snapped or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan said Josh was one of several students who ``seemed to feel
that (messing) with me was one of the jobs that was meant for
them.'' Josh sometimes called him ``a punk'' and other names, he
said. When he passed Josh's locker on his way to class, students,
including Josh, sometimes pelted him with wads of toilet paper.
</P>
<P>
   His nickname, Screech, was given to him good-naturedly by Wilson
Naneng's sister, and most of his friends used it interchangeably
with his real name. ``I didn't like it,'' said Evan. ``From what I
understand, that kid is thought to be the dork of the show.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead of continuing to lash out, Evan turned to teachers
and administrators for help. This was taken as one of several signs
he was maturing. After a conversation with Morris one day, Sue Hare
recalled thinking, ```You know, he's had a hard time and he's
really using good judgment.' This was just a month or so before
(the shootings) and I thought, `It's going to be all right, it's
going to come together for him. He's going to be OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   Evan's grades, though still poor, were improving. And after 12
disciplinary infractions the year before, including two suspensions
for smoking, he had received just five minor detentions. ``I would
put my arm around Evan and tell him how much better he was doing,''
said Morris. ``I guess that's why I'm alive today.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Evan felt no one was listening. ``The response I
always got from all these people was to ignore it, it will go
away,'' he said. ``I got tired of people telling me it will get
better. I think that if Sue would have put me in counseling, maybe
it would have helped, just to talk to somebody. But it seemed that
nobody really did anything about it. Nobody did anything until it
got out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   One cold February evening, the school board gathered for a
special meeting to discuss discipline at Bethel Regional. Students
had been showing up in class wearing colors, pretending to be gang
members. A Bethel police officer told the board about drug busts in
the parking lot and said he frequently smelled pot in the
bathrooms. Pat Martin, a social studies specialist with the
district, recalled: ``It was lots of little things that when you
added them all up it made you say, `We have a problem here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Edwards, the principal, had just returned from the state
basketball tournament in Anchorage. He told the board he had heard
harrowing stories about violence and a growing need for metal
detectors to reduce gunplay on school grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Exasperated, Edwards pounded his fist on the table. ``I do not
want my school to be like that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 24 hours later he was dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
