<HEADER>
A1336 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSROOM-TEEN-DEPRES     10-28 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-TEEN-DEPRESSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY DETECTION SOUGHT FOR DEPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rates of clinical depression among teenagers are as high as they
have ever been, and the recent spate of multiple murders in
American schools has led to nationwide efforts to detect children
at risk for violence and suicide, which also has risen dramatically
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute of Mental Health in Washington estimates
that 1.5 million children under 18 suffer from serious depression,
a treatable mood disorder. Other studies put the numbers much
higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's one of the saddest things in our society, that
we're not doing anything about this,'' said Kevin Dwyer,
president-elect for the National Association of School
Psychologists. ``If we don't address the needs of these children,
it's a short-term gain for a long-term loss. I sound like a
politician, but I'm tired of talking to reporters about death.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, there has been no systematic analysis of the eight boys
who killed 21 people and wounded 48 in seven nationally publicized
school shootings since 1996. But mental health experts familiar
with the cases said most of the attackers suffered from some form
of clinical depression or other psychological disorder. Alone, even
severe depression is unlikely to lead to violence, the experts
added. But depression can become dangerous when it serves as the
psychological foundation for other risky behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Ramsey, a 16-year-old who killed the principal and a
sophomore basketball player and wounded two other students in 1997
at Bethel Regional High School in Alaska, suffered from dysthymia,
a form of depression, ``so ingrained in the personality it becomes
a part of you,'' said John R. Smith, a pyschiatrist who examined
Evan on behalf of the Alaska Public Defender Agency.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, when Evan was almost 8, a psychologist determined that
he was beginning to develop ``a real depression'' and recommended
treatment. But Elena Franks, a social worker with the state
Division of Family and Youth Services, said the local health
corporation in Bethel did not have a child therapist available at
the time. Evan, it now appears, showed signs of severe depression
throughout adolescence. But both he and his legal guardian, Sue
Hare, said he never received treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This boy had a treatable illness,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   A guide to early warning signs for school violence, released in
August by the US Department of Education in response to the seven
school shootings, lists many of the same characteristics found in
children with symptoms of depression. Those characteristics
include: social withdrawal, excessive feelings of isolation and
rejection, and patterns of impulsive and aggressive behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   Richard W. Riley, the secretary of education, said in an
interview that some children ``don't feel like they've ever been
connected.'' The situation can become explosive, he said, when
combined with other factors, such as guns and exposure to excessive
media violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that a child turns on the television and sees several
horrendous murders, then has a loaded pistol in the drawer and then
goes to school and is mixed up, disturbed, or troubled, anyone who
thinks those things aren't connected I don't think has thought it
out,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   The high depression rates overlap with a number of risky
behavior patterns that have made adolescence more dangerous and, at
times, lethal.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of 1,558 middle and high school students sponsored by
Harvard University and the Metropolitan Life Foundation, published
last week, indicated that large numbers of teenagers live in a
climate of uncontrolled anger and violence. In polling that crossed
geographic, racial, and socio-economic lines, one-third of students
agreed with the statement: ``When I am really angry, there is no
way I can control myself.''
</P>
<P>
   In the highly combustible atmosphere described in the survey, 43
percent of all boys said they had been in a physical fight in the
previous year, and 18 percent of all boys said they had been
threatened with a weapon. ``This means that these high-profile
shootings that we read about are just the tip of the iceberg'' in
terms of school violence, said Jay Winsten, a co-author of the
study.
</P>
<P>
   For the 1996-97 academic year, 6,093 students were expelled for
bringing a gun to school, according to the Department of Education.
That figure is believed to represent a small fraction of the
weapons that actually make their way into American schools.
</P>
<P>
   In an August report by the Centers for Disease Control, nearly
one-fifth of high school students reported carrying a weapon in the
previous 30 days, 8.5 percent onto school property. The figures
were just slightly lower than the CDC's last Youth Risk Behavior
survey, released in 1995. In addition, nearly one-third of all high
school students said they had been offered, sold, or given an
illegal drug on school property in the past year. One-in-four
students said they had smoked marijuana at least once in the past
month. Nearly half of all students said they had drunk alcohol at
least once in the past month. Those figures also were largely
unchanged since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Margot A. Welch, who heads the Collaborative for Integrated
School Services, a Harvard University support network for school
counselors, said the recent school shootings ``are evidence that
the pot is boiling faster than ever and that things are getting
worse. And when I talk to educators, people are almost afraid to
talk about them, because they can happen anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, depression was considered primarily an adult
disorder, and child mental-health experts say it still often goes
untreated or misdiagnosed. However, the most-convincing evidence
that it is rising among teenagers is suicide rates, which have
tripled since 1960 and are rising even faster at younger ages.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC survey offers a glimpse at how teenagers view suicide.
Nationwide, 20.5 percent of high school students said they had
seriously considered suicide in the previous year and 7.7 percent
had actually made an attempt. In 1995, according to the CDC, 2,227
children ages 10 to 19 killed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Although juvenile crime in schools, like crime nationwide, has
decreased, violent school crime is rising. In public schools, the
number of students who were victims of violent crime, including
physical attacks with weapons, robberies, and threats, rose from
3.4 percent to 4.2 percent between 1989-95, according to a joint
study published in April by the Justice Department and the
Department of Education. Last year, one in five public middle and
high schools reported at least one serious violent crime, including
murder, rape, and armed assault.
</P>
<P>
   Dwyer, of the National Association of School Psychologists,
said, ``It's only a matter of time when you find out that no
community in the country is immune from this epidemic. And I call
it an epidemic: It is an epidemic of violence in the country
generally that is now manifesting itself in our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Poland, who chairs an emergency-assistance team that has
provided counseling services to most of the communities where the
school shootings occurred, said the crimes have demonstrated the
need for ``broadening the missions of the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make our schools more like an airport,'' he said.
``Does anybody b.s. about guns, violence, and weapons in an
airport?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1409EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
