<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1339 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSROOM-PLOT-ART-3T     10-28 1482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-PLOT-ART-3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY WAS PRECEDED BY MANY OVERLOOKED SIGNALS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 Second of three parts  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, Alaska _ Rumors, not books, drew Evan Ramsey's friends
to the Bethel Regional High library that morning last year.
</P>
<P>
   The students were gathered on a landing, uncertain exactly why
they were standing there amid the computers, books, and maps. One
girl had heard vaguely of an impending disaster that would make
people want to leave town. Others had heard that ``something really
big'' was about to happen. The rumors focused on Evan, who had
warned one boy he was plotting ``an evil day,'' and who had told
his younger brother that he was planning to shut down school for
the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Evan wanted his friends out of the line of
fire. He came to school that morning with a loaded 12-gauge shotgun
concealed in his jeans. He shot and killed a 15-year-old sophomore
and the principal, wounded two other students, then surrendered to
police on a flight of stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Evan, 16, plotted the rampage in his bedroom, with the
assistance of two 14-year-old friends. To retrace their steps
before the murders, which occurred on a cold Wednesday, Feb. 19,
1997, is to explore the chasm that often divides teenagers and
adults, obscuring impending trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The signs were there,'' said Bob Herron, the school board
president. ``But for whatever reason, we didn't hear them. We were
in a comfort zone where we thought, `That can't happen here.'''
</P>
<P>
   To many adults, the seven multiple murders in American schools
since 1996 seem like screams from a distant culture. Yet in their
words and actions, the young killers sent out unsubtle signals of
their deadly intentions. Their warnings slipped through the cracks
of adolescence, where teens are afraid to ``narc'' on their
friends, teachers often lack full information about their students,
and parents are sometimes too busy to notice.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Bethel Regional High _ even inside his own home _ adults
perceived Evan differently than he perceived himself. To most
adults, he was a polite and likable boy, rapidly maturing after
years of acting up. But to himself, he was an outcast, under
constant harassment from other, more popular classmates, his pleas
for help ignored by adults who had the power to end the abuse.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Evan and his friends plotted the murders as if they
were playing a board game, while his legal guardian _ the school
superintendent _ slept across the hall. At school, in hurried phone
calls, they dropped tantalizing hints and whispered dark secrets to
their friends. Evan told one girl he planned to bring a shotgun to
school, then lied when she made him promise not to. One afternoon,
he abruptly walked out of class, causing his anxious teacher to
notify other faculty. But none of the teenagers warned an adult,
and none of the adults picked up signals that a tragedy was
brewing.
</P>
<P>
   Evan had been jolted by a series of events _ some exceedingly
small, but significant given his state of mind and the peer
pressure he was experiencing. The teenagers around him either were
egging him on, didn't believe him, or had just enough information
to gather in the school library to see what might happen next.
``It's the audience: He sent out invitations to the shooting.
That's what it amounts to,'' said Renee Erb, who later prosecuted
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The total effect, said Wilson Naneng, Evan's close friend, was
``like shaking a soda and finally opening it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Wilson, a college-bound junior, disclosed that Evan
had picked up the same shotgun once before. Two years earlier, Evan
had called him and said, ``You've got five minutes to get over here
or I'm going to shoot myself.'' Wilson took away the gun and
comforted his friend. But he never told Evan's legal guardian, Sue
Hare, who first heard about the incident when a reporter recounted
it to her recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really tell anybody about that because of how friends
are,'' said Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   (AT)5Gun ownership common in hunting culture
</P>
<P>
   (AT)7 James Randall killed his first moose when he was 13, his
first bear a year later. Like many children in this region, he was
responsible for helping his family gather food. He hunted and
fished with his father, James Sr., a former public-safety officer,
and he owned several of his own guns. ``I have maybe three .22s, a
.410 shotgun, a .30-30 (rifle), an SKS (semiautomatic rifle) and a
.306 (rifle),'' James said. ``I think that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   James and Evan are distant cousins. They had known each other
for years, but they started to hang out the summer before James
entered ninth grade and Evan entered 11th. The two boys walked the
slim wooden boardwalks that connect Bethel's subdivisions. They
went to the sandpit, rode bikes, smoked cigarettes and dope, and
hung out in James's bedroom, where a dozen speakers culled from
garage sales were hooked up to his stereo, a VCR, and a video-game
unit.
</P>
<P>
   The two boys played video games for hours, taking breaks only
when James's mother would arrive with snacks, or when his father
would burst into the room. ``He'd go, `Enough!''' said Evan. ``He'd
tell us to get off our asses and help him clean up the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   James said Evan sometimes called him up and told him he was
depressed about his home life and that he was being picked on at
school. Evan would come over and play and ``then he would go back
to normal,'' said James.
</P>
<P>
   To most adults, Evan appeared to be coming into his own that
year. ``I commented to him a few times,'' said Dit Hoffman, a
school secretary. ``I would compliment him on his good behavior and
the fact that he'd grown up a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   But Evan saw his situation differently, and in many ways it was
changing dramatically. Without notice, his father, Don Ramsey, had
come back into his life after spending 10 years in prison. In 1986,
armed with several weapons, Ramsey had stormed into the offices of
the state's largest newspaper, The Anchorage Times, and had briefly
taken the publisher hostage following a dispute over how the paper
had handled a political screed for which he had bought space.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey called up his son 10 days before the shootings and told
him he had been released. ``It was just, `You know I love you,
don't you, son?''' said Ramsey. ``And he told me, `I love you, too,
dad.' He gave me no indications that anything was wrong up there in
Bethel.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan also was having problems with his love life. For months, he
had dated a girl who, like him, had spent years in foster care and
``could relate to some of the things that were happening in my
life,'' he said. ``Then, all of a sudden, she said no more,
(expletive) you, and left town. It was a pretty depressing
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, the week before the murders, Bob Morris, the dean of
students, confiscated a portable compact disc player from him in
the hallway at school. Evan said he had taken the Discman from Hare
and had been scared she would find out. ``I just thought it was a
retarded reason to take it away,'' said Evan. ``I wasn't listening
to it and I never got it back. I was supposed to get it back
sometime in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just was one of the things that was on my mind at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   `I figured I'd scare everybody'
</P>
<P>
   The Saturday night before the murders, James and another
14-year-old, Matthew Charles, slept over at Evan's. They invited
Matthew's sister, Theresa, who James was dating at the time, and
the four climbed beneath the house to smoke marijuana from a pipe
they had fashioned from aluminum foil.
</P>
<P>
   Evan said he does not recall the exact moment he got the idea to
bring a gun to school. ``It just popped into my head,'' he said.
``It came out of the blue.''
</P>
<P>
   The original idea, he said, was to commit suicide in the school
lobby. ``I figured I'd go into the high school and scare everybody,
scare the holy crap out of them, and kill myself,'' he said. ``But
James had some strong disagreements on that. He said that my face
and name would go across the world. He said I'll become famous. He
said lots of people will know about me. He said I should live the
fame.''
</P>
<P>
   The three boys fantasized about whom they would kill, Evan said.
``They made some suggestions, `Why don't you shoot this person,
kill that person, kill that person.''' Someone brought up the name
of Ron Edwards, the principal. ``Matthew was telling me, `Shoot
him, shoot him, shoot him,''' said Evan. ``He's an
(expletive)...he's this, he's that.'''
</P>
<P>
   Evan went downstairs, pulled the shotgun off the rack and
brought it up to the bedroom. Matthew borrowed a camera belonging
to William Ramsey, Evan's younger brother, and took pictures of
Evan holding the gun.
</P>
<P>
   ( &UR; End of 1st take; 2nd take begins... The three compiled ...)
</P>
</TEXT>
