<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1343 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSROOM-PLOT-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     10-28 1730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-PLOT-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BETHEL, Alaska... holding the gun.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The three compiled a rough hit list that included Edwards, a
sophomore basketball player named Josh Palacios, and other students
and members of the faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a list up here,'' Evan said, pointing to his head.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe it was the confiscated Discman that
ultimately triggered the murders. Evan said the Discman incident
``was one of the things. And this girlfriend (who) said
`(expletive) you' and disappeared. And everybody constantly coming
at me and messing with me and messing with me. And I don't know who
my parents are; that was another thing that hurts. It seemed like
all my friends knew their fathers. And James and Matthew were
getting me all riled up: `Yeah, it would be (expletive) awesome.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``James told me, `You can't go back, everybody would think
you're nothing. Everybody would just have one more reason to mess
with you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Later, William said, ``I knew something was going on because
James kept saying `Wednesday is going to be the happiest day of my
life. Wednesday is going to be a cool day.'''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for James and Matthew said neither boy believed Evan
would actually go through with the plot.
</P>
<P>
   Hints of shooting intimated to close friend
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Evan called Carol Rodgers. She was two years older, but
they had become friends. Occasionally, the two rode snowmobiles
together on the tundra and walked the town, but mostly they hung
out, smoking cigarettes and talking. Evan frequently told her how
unhappy he was.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, she said, Evan seemed agitated and serious. ``At
first he goes, `Carol, I got to tell you something really
important, but I don't know if I should.' It took me 10 minutes on
the phone to get it out of him. I'm like, `Evan, you better tell me
now.' He goes, `Why?' And I said, `Because I'm getting scared of
what you're going to tell me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Carol, do me a favor. Don't come to school
(Wednesday) morning.' I'm like, `Why?' And he goes, `Because.' And
I said, `Why?' He kept saying, `Because.' And finally he told me.
He said, `I'm thinking about bringing a gun to school on
Wednesday.' And I'm like, `Don't do it. You're going to suffer the
consequences if you do it and I don't want to see that happen.' And
then he goes, `I don't care about consequences.'''
</P>
<P>
   Carol said she made Evan promise not to bring the gun to school.
``And before we hung up, he goes, `Carol, I promise.'
</P>
<P>
   ``See, I expected him to keep that promise. That's the only
reason why I didn't say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Evan walked out of seventh-period yearbook class. The
instructor, Reyne Athanas, had asked him what he intended to do
about his assignment, a series of photos on special needs students.
``I don't know,'' he said. When Athanas turned to help another
student, Evan grabbed his backpack and disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Athanas, 47, was more informal than most teachers: She looked
younger than her age, wore jeans to class, and allowed students to
call her by her first name, pronounced ``Renee.'' On Halloween she
painted faces, including Evan's. When he walked out of class she
became concerned. ``He wouldn't respond to me that way,'' she said.
``It was just a total indifference to what I was saying. He didn't
care. In a normal everyday classroom situation we would have talked
about it. He had never left my class like that.''
</P>
<P>
   She waited a few minutes to see if he returned, then went to
find a guidance counselor. The counselor, busy with another
student, sent her to Bob Morris, the dean of students. Morris
checked the bathrooms but couldn't find Evan, so Athanas went to
the school social worker, Jacqueline Volkmann, and later told
Evan's guardian, Hare, the district superintendent, when she bumped
into her at the public library.
</P>
<P>
   Volkmann cornered Evan in the hallway before school the next
day. ``Oh, that's no big deal,'' Evan told her. Lying, he said he
had gone to the computer room to work, and that he would assure
Athanas everything was fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem was I wasn't even sure who he was; I had to have
someone point him out to me,'' said Volkmann, who had arrived at
Bethel Regional that year. She said she believes the faculty
assumed she must have known him ``but the sad part is I really
didn't. The teacher had some insight but the problem was I didn't
have enough information to pick up on it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she has been afraid to admit that she didn't know Evan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I haven't talked about,'' she said. ``Number
one, I didn't want to take the fall for that. Number two, I didn't
want the school to take the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan learned to fire shotgun from a friend
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the day before the murders, Evan, James, and Matthew
skipped school. They wandered around Bethel, ducking into a hideout
beneath an apartment complex to smoke cigarettes. They visited with
friends and, after school let out, returned to Evan's house, where
James showed Evan how to use the shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Evan, who unlike James had almost no experience with weapons,
pulled the gun off the rack, carried it up to his room and handed
it to James. ``He showed me how to load and unload it,'' Evan said.
``Then he gave it to me to load and unload. He showed me everything
about the shotgun except how to fire it. He told me I'd have to be
a (expletive) moron if I didn't know how to fire a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   James told him that ``after I fired the first time I wouldn't
want to stop,'' Evan said. ``He said it'll become a normal thing.''
</P>
<P>
   James said Evan, while holding the gun, began to talk about Ron
Edwards, the principal. ``I don't know if he was saying he was
going to kill him but I know he was calling him names and saying
stuff,'' he said. ``I kind of thought (Evan) was serious. I think I
shouldn't have started this whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   James went home but Matthew stayed for dinner. Hare arrived from
work, tired and ill. She already had heard from Morris that Evan
had skipped school. ``You know, I expect you to go to school,'' she
scolded him. On other occasions, Evan had lost his $10-a-week
allowance when he skipped, but this time Hare chose not to punish
him. Shortly after dinner she went to bed.
</P>
<P>
   According to James, Evan called him later that night, crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was going to kill himself,'' said James. ``Then he
told me, `It's either them or me.' I remember that like it was
right now. I was like, `Why? Why are you so mad?' I was just trying
to talk him out of it. I just told him, `Don't do nothin'.'''
</P>
<P>
   James said he never told an adult because he didn't believe Evan
would actually go through with it.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew, apparently unaware he was incriminating himself,
volunteered in a witness statement that he had offered to ``back
up'' Evan with a .22-caliber revolver he kept at home. He couldn't,
he said, because ``I'm only 14.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he borrowed a camera from Evan's younger brother
William. ``He wanted to get pictures to hang on his wall and
remember everything,'' said Evan. ``He just thought it was really
cool that I was going to kill these people. I really don't think he
was all there.''
</P>
<P>
   That night, Evan and Matthew sat in Evan's room. They played
music and drew cartoons. They drew pictures of the rabbit from Trix
breakfast cereal commercials. ``You know, `Silly rabbit, Trix are
for kids,''' Evan said. ``We changed `Trix' to `trips' and made the
rabbit look like he was on some kind of drugs, and we drew some
marijuana leaves.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan called his friends. Several weren't home that night. Wilson
said he spoke with Evan for about an hour but never learned
specifically what his friend was planning to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Go up to the library, something really bad is gonna
happen tomorrow,''' Wilson recalled. ``I asked him, `What do you
mean something bad's going to happen?' He said he would let people
know on the bus and let them know out loud in the lobby. I said,
`Is it going to be like a fight and he said, `Yes.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said Evan told him that ``somebody was going to get hurt.
He said, `I'd like to tell you more, but I just can't.' Then Sue
told him he had to go to bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that night, Evan sat down with a notebook and wrote two
notes.
</P>
<P>
   Excerpts from one, found crumpled and discarded, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have thought to myself, what kind of damage can a 12 gauge
slug do to a human's internal organs or their head? Well today I
found out, and so did everyone else that is in school .... No, I am
not on drugs...ciggerettes, that's all. I am not really depressed
just that the fact that I want people, the world, or maybe just
Bethel, to know how (expletive) and cruel the world is or can be.
This school has got to get its (expletive) together 'cause there
are too many deaths this past 2-3 years. Well I can tell you that
the Superintenant Sue Hare has been the nicest person I've ever met
cause she took both William and I in and didn't get any money for
it, and she like was a mother for William and me. But anyway I'm
dead you guys are living, you should be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The second note, folded and placed on his desk, read in part:
``Hey Every body!! I feel rejected, rejected, not so much alone,
but rejected. I feel this way because the day-to-day treatment I
get usually it's positive but the negative is like a cut, it
doesn't go away really fast. I figure by the time you guys are
reading this I'll probably have done what I told EVERYONE I was
going to do. Just hope 12 gauges don't kick too hard but I do hope
the shells hit more than 1 person because I am angry at more than 1
person. One of the Big (expletive) is Mr. Ron Edwards, he should be
there, I was told this will be his Last year, but I know it WILL BE
HIS LAST YEAR. The main reason that I did this is because I'm sick
and tired of being treated this way everyday .... By the way every
one allways told me ``Don't Judge A Book By It's Cover.'' This
saying is true because I was told that my teachers say that ``He's
Such A Good Kid.'' But they Say that About everyone. I don't think
I'm a good-Hearted person. LIFE SUCKS in its own way, so I killed a
little and killed myself. Jail isn't and wasn't for me, ever.''
</P>
<P>
   He requested that Sue read the note to friends and family. ``I
was not crazy (I think),'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (End of 2nd take; 3rd take begins ... By February)
</P>
</TEXT>
