<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1348 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSROOM-PLOT-3RD &LR;  &UR; T     10-28 1751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-PLOT-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BETHEL, Alaska... he wrote.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By February, Bethel is covered in snow and darkness. The
temperature hovers around zero. The sun rises at 10:30 and sets
around 4. Many students arrive at school and leave in total
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as Evan prepared for school, he found himself alone.
Hare was ill and had stayed in bed. William had taken a cab to
school early to see what might happen.
</P>
<P>
   Evan had traded his lunch money, $5, for William's baggy black
pants. He already had loaded the shotgun with shells from a box
that he said sat on a shelf below the unlocked gunrack. He spilled
some extra shells into his pocket. He took down the shotgun and
stuffed it into his pants and covered himself in a black parka that
went down to his knees. ``The reason I chose that color of clothes
was that the shotgun was black,'' he said. ``I figured I needed
that in order for me to get on the school bus without anybody
wondering what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   He walked stiff-legged out the door. Instead of waiting at the
bus stop in front of his house, he walked down the street to
``where most of my friends were at. Just to b.s. with everybody.''
The bus stop was in front of Carol Rodgers's house on Napakiak, so
he stopped to chat with her. ``I didn't notice anything,'' she
said. ``I mean, it was chilly out that day and I noticed he had a
trench coat. But I didn't notice the way he was walking.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just like, `What's up?''' Rodgers recalled. ``Then he
bummed a smoke off me, like he does every morning. It was just our
normal morning conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   With the gun in William's jeans, Evan rode the bus to school and
limped across the boardwalk. A few students later said they noticed
he was walking strangely, but no one said anything, according to
Evan.
</P>
<P>
   At school, several students had arrived early. Wilson waited
near the front door for his girlfriend, Cynthia. While he was
waiting, he said, James and Matthew came up behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``James specifically stated to me, word for word, `Don't try to
stop him, don't be a hero,''' said Wilson. ``That's when I started
thinking, `There's something wrong here.'''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia arrived and Wilson met her. ``He (Wilson) said go to
your locker, we have to go to the library,'' she recalled. ``So he
walked me to my locker and I put my stuff away. I went up to the
library and I was like, `What's going on?''' By then, at least 10
students had gathered, most of them friends of Evan. Cynthia asked
Matthew's sister Theresa what was happening. ``She said, `Evan told
me to tell everyone to go up to the library because he's got
something really important to tell us.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson thought about Evan's threat to commit suicide two years
earlier and began to panic. ``I kept asking Theresa, `What did Evan
say to you? What did he say to you?' I said, `Is Evan going to kill
himself? Is he going to kill himself?' She said, `I don't know. I
don't know. I don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   Joking bet about death became all too real
</P>
<P>
   Downstairs, Josh Palacios was sitting where he sat every
morning: in the center of the lobby. He and his friends had come
from playing basketball in open gym. Sweaty and disheveled, they
were gathered on couches and lunch tables, the most popular boys in
school joking and talking and preening in the middle of the noisy,
crowded room.
</P>
<P>
   One of Josh's friends, a heavy-set boy named Brock Rapoza, came
running up out of breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, you're gonna die of heat stroke,'' said Josh, ribbing his
friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever, punk, you're gonna die first, I'll bet you money,'''
said Brock. ``African-American males, you know what the statistics
are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, let's make a bet,'' said Josh.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, $100.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear to God,'' Brock said later. ``Everybody was laughing.
It was like everyday conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   The group looked up and saw Evan standing in front of the
secretary's station with the shotgun in his hands. ``He was kind of
crouched a little bit and he had this really odd look on his face,
like he was gleefully evil,'' said Dit Hoffman, the school
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Evan held the gun low to his hip, almost to his thigh, and
pointed it at Josh. Few students panicked at first, believing he
was carrying an ROTC rifle, which does not fire. Josh was one of
the first to realize the gun was real. ``Hey, what do you have that
gun for?''he asked Evan, who had moved about 10 feet away from him.
Evan didn't answer. Josh started to walk away slowly, then returned
to his seat, then got up again.
</P>
<P>
   As he rose, Evan shot him in the stomach. ``My head was thinking
weird things,'' said Brock. ``In sixth grade we had this mock
emergency, you know, and my mind was thinking that this was a big
emergency and we were just practicing how to exit the building.''
Evan then fired into the ceiling and yelled: ``You guys better run.
Run, (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   Two students who had been near Josh, Shane McIntyre and Russell
Lamont, both were struck in the arm by pellets from the first shot.
Raul Sanchez, one of Josh's closest friends, crawled beneath the
lunch table. ``Paco, don't look,'' said Josh, using his nickname
for his friend as Raul glanced at the wound beneath Josh's T-shirt.
Josh asked Evan: ``Why did you shoot me?'' He asked Raul to hand
him his gold crucifix. Raul, who later received the Alaska Student
Hero of the Year award, held Josh's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Reyne Athanas emerged from the teachers' lounge and saw Evan
standing in the middle of the room, waving the shotgun. She slowly
approached him and asked him to put down the gun. ``I kept
thinking, `I've got to get him to give up the gun,' but he just
couldn't stop,'' she said. ``I don't know how to describe it. He
looked like he wasn't even there.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan said he remembers little of what happened inside the
school. ``I don't know what happened that day,'' he said. ``I don't
know what was asking me to go this way or go that way. It was like
this feeling, `Walk here, walk there.' In the high school I didn't
know who I shot or where they went to....It was like it got really
confusing. I didn't really know what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Athanas asked Evan for the gun. ``He said:
`Do...you...want...this...gun,''' she recalled. ``And I told him,
`Yeah, if you'll give it to me, I'll take it if you'll give me the
gun.' And I stepped toward him to take it and he swung it at me
like he was going to shoot and I said, `You don't want to do this
Evan.'
</P>
<P>
   ``What went through my mind was, `Would I fly backwards when it
hit me?' I don't know where that came from. Isn't that weird? And
then I thought, `What would my boys do?'''
</P>
<P>
   Gale Power, a physical education teacher, set off the fire
alarm. Kids screamed and ran everywhere; some were still arriving
at school and teachers tried to head them off. Up in the library, a
boy named Mark Patzke laughed, and seemed to be counting off the
shots: ``That's one, that's two....'' (His family moved away
shortly after the shootings.) Evan ran off down the hall.
Investigators said they believe he was looking for other students
on the mental list that he, James, and Matthew had prepared. He
fired into a metal locker and the ceiling. He walked down another
hall, went outside, crossed the boardwalk, then walked through the
front door, completing a circle that brought him back to the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   He was met by Edwards, who had emerged from his office, hoping
to somehow get the gun away from him. Evan pointed the gun at the
principal. Edwards turned and tried to make it back to his office,
but Evan shot him in the doorway from behind. The mass of pellets
struck behind Edwards's left shoulder, perforating his lung, heart,
and aorta. ``I really didn't know I hit the principal,'' said Evan.
``I could have sworn I hit that wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Athanas tried again to persuade him to give up the gun. Evan
reached in his pocket and held up another shell.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not going to take me alive,'' he told Athanas. ``This
one's for me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept thinking, `grab the gun, grab the gun, grab the gun.'''
Athanas said. ``Then he put it up to his chin. I was like, `Don't
do that. Please don't do that. You don't have to do that Evan. Put
it down.' I knew he had absolutely no control at that point. He was
definitely not there then. He couldn't stop. It's like you get
going in something and you don't know how to get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan said one of the main reasons he went to school that day was
to kill himself.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he didn't, he said: ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officers began to creep in through the front door. Evan
saw them and ran up a flight of stairs toward the library. He
reached the top of the stairs, but the gate had been locked by
Bruce Wegner, the school librarian. Chris Walker, a Bethel police
officer, shouted at Evan to drop the gun. Walker later said Evan
pointed the gun at him. He fired at Evan twice with his own
shotgun. The first shot, a slug, lodged in the wall behind him. The
second shot glanced off the railing of the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Expletive) this,'' Evan said. ``I don't want to die.''
</P>
<P>
   He threw down the shotgun on the stairs. It broke into two
pieces and tumbled to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Accomplice couldn't believe Evan had actually done it
</P>
<P>
   In the school cafeteria, Sue Unin, a teacher at the elementary
school, sat with one of her children. She had rushed over when she
heard what had happened, and, now that it was all over, police and
state troopers were fanning through the building, organizing
students and teachers to take statements.
</P>
<P>
   A 14-year-old boy sat down beside her. ``He was talking and
talking and talking,'' she said. ``He was talking about how he
couldn't believe it had happened, that Evan had actually done it.
He reminded me of a motor that wouldn't stop. And then he told me
that he was supposed to take pictures. I can still see him bringing
that camera out of his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just about died,'' she said. ``I couldn't believe it. After
I got myself together, I went and told someone. It was like, `Um,
this kid over here said he was going to take pictures.'''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Charles was questioned several times. He told state
troopers he had gotten so excited he forgot he had the camera, and
by the time he had charged the flash it was too late. An
investigator asked him if he had thought about warning anyone.
``No, I didn't want to warn anybody,'' Matthew said. ``I wanted to
see if he was bluffing.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``It was kind of cool when he shot Mr. Edwards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
