<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1351 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSROOM-GAMES-IMPAC     10-28 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-GAMES-IMPACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENT VIDEO GAMES COLOR OUTLOOK FOR KIDS AT RISK, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU
 &HT;    c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   ANCHORAGE _ ``This is where I think he got his strategy,'' said
Don Ramsey as he guided his mouse across the pad. The mouse
controlled a hand. The hand held a gun as it negotiated a maze of
animated carnage: blood-drenched corpses, mutants obliterated and
the ultimate killing machine, the B.F.G. 9000, which stands for Big
Fragging Gun.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey believes his son, Evan, was emulating the popular
computer game ``Doom'' when he raced through the corridors of
Bethel Regional High with a shotgun last year. Evan ducked behind
corners and blew holes in the ceiling. He killed a 15-year-old
sophomore, then killed the principal by firing into his shoulder
from a few feet away.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, most children who use fantasy guns never kill in real
life. The $5.1 billion video-game business, which has grown larger
than the film industry, sold 115 million units last year _ more
than one for each US household. Most titles are nonviolent and many
are educational.
</P>
<P>
   But like Don Ramsey, many researchers fear that the most violent
games are giving some children a dangerously skewed perspective.
Most troubling, they said, are ``first-person'' or
``point-and-shoot'' games, estimated to represent 5 percent of the
market, where the primary aim is to kill _ randomly, constantly,
often for hours on machines not unlike simulators used by the
military and law-enforcement agencies to train their people to
shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about a hundred rounds a year, which is what
you need to get soldier- or police-qualified,'' says Lieutenant
Colonel David Grossman, a former West Point professor of behavioral
sciences and author of a 1995 book on how people learn to kill.
``We're talking about tens of thousands of rounds, every single
time, and there are never any repercussions. It's nothing but kill,
kill, kill, kill, kill.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman retired recently as a professor of military science at
Arkansas State University in Jonesboro where, coincidentally, two
11- and 13-year-old video enthusiasts killed four classmates and a
teacher last year. The perpetrators of other recent school
shootings in West Paducah, Ky., and Springfield, Ore., also
reportedly played the ultraviolent games.
</P>
<P>
   In Alaska, Evan Ramsey and an alleged 14-year-old accomplice,
James Randall, spent evenings playing games like ``Doom,'' the
``Die Hard'' trilogy, and ``Resident Evil'' in James's room,
according to both boys and their parents. The two turned off the
lights and played for hours on a Sony PlayStation hooked up to ``12
or 13 speakers,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like action and shooting,'' he said. ``You start out with
something cheap, like a handgun. You'll keep shooting and the
higher you get you find weapons on the way and then you use them. I
had my `surroundsound' hooked up and it'd be dark and it'd just be
the screen and we'd have fun. We had everything: We had chips, Dr
Pepper, and we'd just sit there. We'd start around 11 and we'd play
until 3 or 4. If we really got into it, we'd play until maybe 6 or
7 in the morning, until he had to go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan, who had almost no experience with real guns, now says the
games mistakenly taught him ``you can get shot a whole bunch of
times before you die.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like with `Doom,' you have a `health factor,''' said Evan.
``You start at a hundred health. When you get shot it drops to
something like 15. You get shot with different types of weapons and
your energy gets taken off. Now I know it's not like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Evan, ``I think I played video games too
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Lowenstein, president of the Interactive Digital Software
Association, said blaming video games for mass murder amounts to
``very simplistic scapegoating.'' Jeanne B. Funk, an associate
professor of psychology at the University of Toledo, who has
studied the effects of video games on children, acknowledged that,
despite her own uneasiness about their possible impact, research so
far is inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want parents to think that because kids take up
violent video games they end up shooting their classmates,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Lowenstein, ``that's not to say I would be willing to
bring all these games into my home. I wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The real danger, most experts believe, is the potential
influence on children like Evan who are more predisposed to
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this stuff is a huge, huge problem, except when
you get to the extremes of the culture,'' said Eugene F. Provenzo
Jr., an education professor at the University of Miami who has
written a book about children and Nintendo. ``This is really bad
stuff to give to our most-troubled kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In the niche world of ultraviolent gaming, gore is a marketing
tool. The game ``Re-Loaded,'' for example, is advertised as ``the
most deranged, psychologically brutal, senselessly violent,
over-the-top, insane bloodbath ever created.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman said the ``point-and-shoot'' games produce the same
effect as strategies long used by the military to break down a
soldier's aversion to killing. After World War II, the military
found that just 15 to 20 percent of all soldiers fired their
weapons in battle. Using repetition training with man-shaped
targets, the military was able ``to make killing a reflex action,''
Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   More alarming, said Grossman, there is evidence the games have
made some children better marksmen. He said he witnessed this
phenomenon while commanding an ROTC battalion of 500 cadets at
Arkansas State. ``What we're seeing is more and more kids who have
never handled a gun in their lives, whose parents hate guns and
never allowed a gun in the house, the kid comes in and puts a gun
in his hand and starts to fire expert,'' he said. ``Why? They all
know: `It was all the video games that I played.'''
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Johnston Beach, professor of psychology at West Point,
said he is unaware of studies showing that video games have led to
better marksmanship. ``It would be kind of scary if it's true,'' he
said. But he agreed with Grossman that violent video games provide
the same kind of repetition training without the discipline
enforced by the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think kids have adapted themselves to a much higher level of
stimulation,'' he said. ``They have to do more to get excited,
which just makes it more likely that people will go out and do
stupid things.''
</P>
<P>
   James, Evan's alleged accomplice, disagreed that the games give
children an unrealistic view of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so, but that's from my view,'' he said. ``I
mean, I'm a kid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
