<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1354 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSROOM-AFTERMATH-A     10-28 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-AFTERMATH-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY STRUGGLE TO PUT THEIR WORLD TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 Last of three parts  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, Alaska _ Overcome with guilt, Wilson Naneng for months
he should have prevented his friend Evan Ramsey from bringing the
shotgun to school.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of at least 10 students who had gathered in the
Bethel Regional High library that morning, following Evan's
suggestion that ``something really big'' was about to occur. He
then stood by in horror as Evan killed 15-year-old Josh Palacios
and principal Ron Edwards, wounded two other students, then
surrendered under fire from police in the school lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Wilson, a promising junior, began to find ways to
injure himself. He bit his hands raw, drew knives across his arms.
Finally, during the state academic decathlon meet in Anchorage, he
strung up his belt in a hotel room and attempted to commit suicide
before friends and supervisors intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt betrayed by Evan and I felt some guilt that I should
have stopped it,'' said Wilson, now an 18-year-old freshman at the
University of Alaska at Fairbanks. ``I felt as if I had been shot
myself. When I talked about Evan, it was like he was dead. I felt
like I had lost a brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson hardly recognized Evan that morning _ Feb. 19, 1997 _
``all raged, full of his hate that he had.'' His soul-searching was
shared by others in Bethel, and, in many ways, throughout the
state, as people sought to understand how such a crime could have
been committed in the sanctuary of a public school, by a boy whose
life was so embedded in his community.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that two 14-year-old friends had helped Evan plot the
murders, and that other students had failed to act on the dark
hints that emerged beforehand, made the crimes all the more tragic
and perplexing. The case provoked fundamental changes in the way
the school district addressed its most-troubled students, changed
the way Alaska looked at juvenile crime, and foreshadowed a
national debate about school violence as the shootings,
grotesquely, seemed to repeat themselves across the country in six
other nationally publicized episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we no longer have that innocence where school is the
safest place in the community,'' Alaska Governor Tony Knowles, who
spoke at Ron Edwards's memorial service, said in an interview. ``We
have lost that.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan, who was 16 when he committed the murders, is now 18. Tried
as an adult, convicted in February of two counts of first-degree
murder, and awaiting sentencing Dec. 1, he alternated between
convincing remorse and callous indifference during a series of
interviews inside the Cook Inlet Pre-Trial Facility in Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at one point if he wished he had committed suicide in the
school, as he said he'd intended, Evan said: ``I do, but I don't. I
do because I wouldn't have to deal with this: with the chains, with
having to worry about getting (stabbed) or having somebody sodomize
me. But then, this also gives me an opportunity to get a message
out: that what I did ain't right. All these teenagers in the Lower
48, for whatever reasons they pulled their killings, I don't think
that it is really right.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to his early child abuse and the harassment he endured
at school, he said: ``What I did was (expletive) up. I mean, I
killed two people. But then, there's also some (expletive) up
things that happened to me. I tried to go get help and nobody would
help, so I felt I had to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was less apologetic when asked about the effect of the
crimes on friends and relatives of the victims: ``I think I've
(expletive) these people's lives up _ temporarily. And if they're
not (expletive) morons they'll get on with their life. What
happened was really screwed up, but that don't mean that they
should just stop living and stop doing what they were doing
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he &UR;  &LR; was angry at Edwards, Evan, sitting in shackles
and his red prison jumpsuit, said: ``I don't remember. I think it
was one of those little things. I thought he was a (expletive) but
not the kind of (expletive) that you'd really want to hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the losses of Edwards and Palacios are still felt
deeply in Bethel. A veteran educator, Edwards, 50, was so
passionate about Bethel Regional High and its students that, had he
lived, ``I think this would have devastated him,'' said Les
Daenzer, a district administrator who became interim principal
after the shootings. ``I think he would have quit.'' Friends find
it hard to believe that Edwards, a former marine and National
Guardsman who had served in Vietnam, was killed in his own school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to describe Ron in one word it would be `solid,'''
said Daenzer. A champion bodybuilder from Kalispell, Mont., Edwards
had risen through the ranks of the Lower Kuskokwim School District.
Before Bethel, he was principal in Kongiganak, a Yup'ik Eskimo
village of about 200 people. Conditions were so basic that Edwards
and his staff took showers at school. But within a few years he had
created one of the best-run programs in the district.
</P>
<P>
   At Bethel Regional, Edwards seemed to be everywhere at once:
running the lunch line, sitting in on classes, pushing papers,
picking up spare change, attending every sporting event and fawning
over his wife, Cindy, who was studying for her teaching certificate
and often substituted at the school. One of his unfulfilled dreams
was to see Ron Jr., the youngest son among his four children, play
baseball. His daughter, Meagan, was valedictorian the year after
his death.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards loved to hunt moose and pan for gold. He intermittently
worried about his weight: When friends cleared out his desk, they
found rice cakes and tuna in one compartment, mounds of candy in
another. At home, he would curl up in his favorite chair, announce
``the captain is in the command module,'' and watch Monday Night
Football. He was perhaps the biggest booster of the Bethel High
sports program, of which basketball, as in most schools in
hoops-crazed Alaska, is king.
</P>
<P>
   To many, Josh Palacios was the future of that program. A
sophomore, he already had made the eight-man varsity traveling
squad. He was 5 feet 4 inches tall and growing, dribbled well with
both hands, and was solidly built: He loved to flip up his T-shirt
to reveal his ``six-pack'' stomach to anyone willing to look or
touch. Half black, half Mexican-American, he was an exotic presence
in Bethel and girls found him attractive. His mother Claudia, a
women's health-care provider, put condoms in his Easter baskets. A
gifted artist, Josh once replicated a Van Gogh painting, which, he
wrote, ``symbolized a man sittin' and chillin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudia had moved her two sons, Josh and Corey, from Dallas to
Bethel after her marriage broke up in 1988. She wanted to be closer
to her mother, Linda, a nurse who had moved to escape inner-city
violence. Linda reached her breaking point one day when she pulled
a gun on a man who was tailing her on a Dallas freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the climate change, Josh's love of sports only deepened
in Bethel. He set up Nerf hoops all over the house to amuse himself
when it was too cold to play outside. ``In Bethel we had a rule
that the boys couldn't play outside if the wind-chill was minus-10
or below,'' said Linda. ``They'd be at home by themselves and
they'd call me up at work: `Grandma, it's only minus-9!' Josh would
get snow in his boots and his socks would freeze to the soles of
his feet. We had to put him in the bathtub with warm water to get
his feet out of his boots. And he had this short, nappy hair and
the snow would melt on his head and then it would freeze. It made
an ice cap on his head and he'd come in and you'd have to crack it
off his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated at an Anchorage restaurant, a few blocks from Josh's
grave, Linda and her daughter Claudia laughed, then cried. Josh had
so many friends that they all pitched in one year to send him to
basketball camp when it looked like he might not be able to afford
it. ``I can't tell you how many kids he brought over to our
house,'' said Claudia. ``It was never stray dogs, it was always
stray people.'' Josh, whose favorite NBA player was David Robinson
of the San Antonio Spurs, was buried in his Bethel Warriors
uniform. Claudia only wishes he had brought home Evan Ramsey one
day.
</P>
<P>
   Climate of harassment given intense scrutiny
</P>
<P>
   After the shootings, there was an outpouring of grief for both
Josh and Edwards. But those seeking change at Bethel Regional also
focused on the climate of harassment in which the murders took
place. Once the grief settled, the school board held a series of
emergency meetings. Task forces were assembled on everything from
cultural awareness to alcoholism to family values.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, meetings of the ``School Issues'' committee
were the most heavily attended. The committee looked at harassment,
violence, security, dropout rates, substance abuse, truancy, and
other issues. It made several recommendations, some of which were
implemented immediately. Bethel Regional added an unarmed security
guard who patrols the halls with a radio. The school repainted the
walls a brighter color, and stationed teachers in the hallways as
extra eyes and ears during class changes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (End of 1st take; 2nd take picks up ... The new principal)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1417EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1363 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSROOM-AFTERMATH-2     10-28 2048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-AFTERMATH-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BETHEL, Alaska... during class changes.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new principal, Ron Magee, a former member of an elite Marine
unit and a black-belt in karate, championed a ``zero tolerance''
discipline policy. The school set up discipline guidelines for
offenses ranging from cutting classes and truancy to weapons and
drug possession, robbery and extortion. Students caught bringing a
gun or knife to school would be expelled immediately. Possession of
drugs or alcohol would result in a 5-day-suspension and counseling
for the first offense, a 15-day suspension for the second offense,
a 45-day suspension for the third offense. Students caught selling
drugs or alcohol would receive a 45-day suspension for the first
offense, then face expulsion for a second infraction.
</P>
<P>
   The school district set aside $125,000 for an alternative
boarding school to ``provide a new start for students who have left
school, or are not experiencing success.'' The school was designed
for ``at-risk'' students, many of whom had problems with substance
abuse and violence.
</P>
<P>
   The school, which accepted about 30 students this year, provides
both classroom instruction and three hours daily vocational
training at a paying job in Bethel. Before enrolling, students
submit to rigorous interviews in which they are asked about past
drug and alcohol use. The school also forces students to take drug
tests and makes them sign a waiver stipulating that the school
maintains a zero-tolerance policy on drugs, alcohol, and violence,
and that ``if I violate this policy I will be sent home.''
</P>
<P>
   The district has yet to implement a violence-prevention
curriculum that was promised after the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most serious concern of many teachers and parents is
that the issues that led to the shootings extend far beyond the
walls of Bethel high, that the problems are so big as to be
insurmountable. ``It's a mess, but it's all a mess,'' said
Jacqueline Volkmann, who served as the school's social worker the
year of the shootings and now works as a social services
coordinator for the local health corporation. ``To say otherwise
would be to remain in denial.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyne Athanas, a former art teacher who tried desperately to
persuade Evan to put down his weapon, said the incident has left
her emotionally torn. ``How can you care for someone, who you think
you know, and then they do a horrendous thing like this, and you're
appalled by the act but you don't know how to feel?'' she said,
crying quietly at the school one afternoon. ``Do you hate him? Do
you despise him? Do you feel sorry for him, what?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got tons of different battling emotions,'' she said.
``I mean, I really liked Evan. I really liked Josh. And I'm angry
at Evan for doing this to me and everybody else that has had to go
through it. I mean, how could he do this? It's too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Palacios said she was torn sitting in court listening to
testimony about Evan's troubled life before he shot her son. ``I'm
sitting there, listening to all this, and as a mother I felt so bad
for him,'' she said. ``Part of me wanted to get up and hold him in
my arms and just tell him it'll be all right. And he killed my
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   But others see strict punishment as the key. ``As a friend of
the family, I wish we had the death penalty,'' said Nancy Brown, an
education specialist with the district who worked with Edwards in
Kongiganak and led the search for a violence-prevention curriculum
after the murders. ``I guess this is the anthropologist in me
talking but, you know, cull the herd.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere are the issues more confused than in the
criminal-justice system as it tries to mete out fair punishments to
adolescents who may or may not understand their crimes. Evan, who
had turned 16 less than four months before the murders, fell under
a recent Alaska law that says any juvenile 16 or over can be tried
automatically as an adult for certain felonies, including murder.
His attorney, the assistant public defender, launched a ``suicide
by cop'' defense. He argued that Evan had hoped to draw police to
the school to shoot him, but he never intended to kill anyone. That
defense was weakened by the judge's decision to limit testimony
related to Evan's horrific upbringing and by the fact that he had
shot two people at nearly point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   But the fates of his two alleged 14-year-old accomplices is less
clear. Both were initially charged with first-degree murder _ but
as juveniles. Matthew Charles, who brought a camera to school to
take pictures of the shootings, pleaded guilty to a lesser charge
of criminally negligent homicide. His attorney, Sidney Billingslea,
said he remains in ``24-hour custody of a network of parents,
treatment providers, and education people who monitor the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the systems are old and they don't work anymore,''
said Claudia Palacios. ``(Matthew) sits down with his family at the
dinner table every night, and in my family there's an empty chair.
He'll celebrate holidays and birthdays with his family, and in my
family there will always be something missing. It just doesn't make
any sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew, in tears, apologized to Claudia Palacios last week
during the trial for James Randall, who admitted to showing Evan
how to use the gun the day before the murders. After testifying
against James for more than 40 hours, Matthew, who was receiving
treatment for ``pervasive depression,'' according to Billingslea,
ingested large quantities of cold medicine and Tylenol in an
unsuccessful effort to kill himself. He remains hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   James was first tried _ also as a juvenile _ on charges of
conspiracy to commit murder and accomplice liability. He was
acquitted of conspiracy, but after the jury became hung on the
second charge the state, armed with new evidence, chose to try him
again for first- and second-degree murder. A verdict is expected
any day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Central to James's defense is his adolescence: that he neither
believed Evan nor understood the seriousness of what they were
doing. Evan himself said of James: ``I think if he was thinking he
wouldn't have shown me'' how to use the gun. ``I think if he was
thinking straight he would have realized, `Hey, people are going to
die and get really hurt. He don't know how to load it or unload it,
so if I don't show him how to use it properly nothing will
happen.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchel Schapira, James's lawyer, said Bethel's hunting culture
should be taken into consideration. ``My kid showed Evan how to
fire a gun,'' he said. ``Up there, that's like when you're 14 years
old and somebody shows you how to start a car.'' He said it is
inconceivable James truly believed Evan would use the gun to kill.
He said the legal standard to which James is held is that of ``a
reasonable person in the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But what is the situation? I say his situation is
adolescence,'' said Schapira. ``His situation is being a
14-year-old, and hearing how 14-year-olds talk, this plethora of
issues that adolescents go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall's father, James Sr., a former Village Public Safety
Officer, said: ``I think J.R. might have been involved in the way
that 14-year-olds think: just blowing smoke. Like me, when I was
young, I might talk about a teacher and I might say I'd like to
kick their ass, and maybe even shoot them, but to the point of
believing it and actually doing it, no. I don't even think Evan
believed it until he walked in with that shotgun.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he's found guilty of murder, James, who turns 16 on
Sunday, cannot be held past his 19th birthday. Evan is facing over
300 years in state prison. If he spends 70 years of his life
incarcerated, Alaska will spend an estimated $2.1 millon for his
care. ``Evan's as good as dead,'' said Sue Hare, his legal guardian
at the time of the murders. ``I've told other people: Evan killed
two people and he killed himself at the same time. That's what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Renee Erb, who prosecuted Evan, said: ``I'll tell you the
scariest (stuff): Evan is not that different than a lot of kids;
he's not much worse than a lot of kids. Maybe that is the scary
thing: that they're not different. They're not different enough so
that anyone could pick them out. Not different enough for teachers
who spend seven hours a day with kids to pick them out. They're not
necessarily detectable. And that is what should scare the pants off
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Healing interrupted by similar shootings
</P>
<P>
   In Bethel, the difficult days of recovery after the murders have
been interrupted by terrifying images from other rural American
towns that experienced similar school shootings. ``It was like this
nightmare going on and on,' said Cynthia, a 16-year-old junior who
asked that her last name not be used. ``It just seemed so odd that
what happened in Bethel, Alaska, was going on all over the country.
And it got me mad when people would say it's just a southern
problem. Because I know it wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   On the one-year anniversary of the shootings, the school held a
``Celebration of Life'' in the gym. Brock Rapoza, one of Josh
Palacios's best friends, sang ``I'll Be Missing You,'' the tribute
that Sean ``Puffy'' Combs dedicated to his best friend, Christopher
``The Notorious B.I.G. /Biggie Smalls'' Wallace, after the rapper
was shot dead in Los Angeles last year. The school compiled a book
of student poems and writings about the shootings. In one poem,
titled ``Unexpected,'' a student wrote:
</P>
<P>
   The shock is that the one that murdered these
</P>
<P>
   Is the one we trusted, laughed with just as well as the ones
that died.
</P>
<P>
   Just an ordinary person like us,
</P>
<P>
   He talked, laughed, cried, just as we did.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Yummy, not Evan,'' said John Ramsey when asked for his
reaction to the shootings. Evan's 20-year-old older brother is
serving 3 1/2 years at the Central Arizona Detention Center for
holding up an Anchorage porn shop five days before Evan committed
murder. John Ramsey was referring to his younger brother William,
who bears the family nickname ``Yummy'' because as a toddler Evan
would call out, ``William, William, Yum, Yum, Yum.''
</P>
<P>
   William, 14, the only one of the Ramsey boys not in prison,
currently lives in Anchorage, in a two-bedroom apartment with his
father. Don Ramsey, 53, served 10 years in prison for bursting into
The Anchorage Times with an arsenal of weapons in 1986, briefly
taking the publisher hostage. He took custody of William last year
from Sue Hare, who had been William's as well as Evan's guardian in
Bethel.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Don Ramsey spent seven years in a wheelchair. He
underwent open-heart surgery in July. He plans to have William
schooled at home, but so far the program has not begun.
</P>
<P>
   William spends much of his time in his room, using the
PlayStation he purchased recently. ``I like playing Golden Eye,''
he said, referring to a computer game. ``It shows it like real
life. They got real pistols, and you can aim at the head and go
pop.... They got shotguns and you could shoot 'em and blood will
come out.''
</P>
<P>
   To William, what happened to his brother is ``like a violent
movie, a killing movie. That's how I see. I can't see it as real.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson Naneng, who once considered killing himself over his
friend Evan Ramsey, is feeling better now. He said a talk with his
uncle made him realize that everyone's life is difficult at times.
``You must try to understand each aspect of the accident,'' he
wrote in a poem called ``Life's a Rugged Road.'' By the end of the
summer he was ready to move on to college.
</P>
<P>
   At Bethel Regional High, the days go on. Still, many teachers
wonder whether they'll ever look at their students the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Elliott, a special education teacher, had been near the
principal's office the day of the shootings and saw Ron Edwards as
he was shot. She stayed with him, trying to reassure him on the
floor of his office as he whispered to her, ``Nancy, I'm going to
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, on the first day of school, Elliott was forced to
admonish one of her students over his refusal to complete an
assignment.
</P>
<P>
   The student responded with a warning, which earned him a
three-day suspension: ``I'm gonna to do to you what Evan did to Mr.
Edwards.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
