<HEADER>
A1365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUILT-SHOW-HNS &LR;      10-28 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUILT-SHOW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUILTS 
 
 
QUILT ARTIST WILL RECEIVE COVETED 1998 SILVER STAR AWARD, THE
QUILTING WORLD'S ANSWER TO THE OSCAR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: Photos available on New York Times photo service, sluggedBy MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Quilts.
</P>
<P>
   It's a cozy word that calls to mind a gaggle of grannies sitting
in a circle, sipping tea and sharing gossip as their fingers fly
across pastel-tinted squares of cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Quilts.
</P>
<P>
   Soft, warm things you snuggle under on a cold winter's night,
the fabric equivalent of a mother's hug or a warm glass of milk.
</P>
<P>
   With her brash ``oeuvre,'' Yvonne Porcella explodes these
notions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't call myself a quilter,'' she says earnestly, her blue
eyes magnified behind bifocals. ``I make quilts as art. I make
wearables as art. But it took a long time for me to verbalize
that.''
</P>
<P>
   A long time because Porcella went the conventional route. Wife.
Mother. Operating-room nurse. Never went to art school, never
earned a fancy art degree.
</P>
<P>
   What she did instead was fall hopelessly in love with color.
With image and design, hue and pattern. With the beauty of the
natural world, and the way it can be grasped and transformed
through cloth.
</P>
<P>
   Porcella, 62, is a pioneer in the Art Quilt movement, a
burgeoning subgenre that takes the homespun craft of quilting and
elevates it to the level of fine art. In Houston to attend the
International Quilt Festival, which begins Thursday and runs
through Sunday at the George R. Brown Convention Center, Porcella
will receive the group's coveted 1998 Silver Star Award, the
quilting world's answer to the Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Her quilts are dazzling, alive things. Meant to hang on a wall,
not lie across a bed, they burst with movement and unorthodox color
combinations. Her art quilts, like her wearable art and artful
kimonos, have hung in museums around the world; in the Smithsonian
Institution's traveling exhibit, they shared space with works by
Auguste Rodin and Pablo Picasso.
</P>
<P>
   Her work has been exhibited in far-flung locales, from Kyoto,
Japan, to Lodz, Poland. She's traveled the world to teach and
lecture. She founded Studio Art Quilt Associates, a group that
promotes quilting as a legitimate art form. The latest of her eight
books, ``Art &AMP; Inspiration,'' traces her evolution from a simple
weaver to a maker of elaborate quilts.
</P>
<P>
   In the quilt world, Porcella is regarded with something akin to
reverence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her quilts are just breathtaking _ so bold, so dramatic, so
unlike anything that anyone else does,'' says Karey Bresenhan,
founder and director of the International Quilt Festival. ``They're
totally recognizable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Art Quilt movement began about 20 years ago as part of a
larger effort, in tandem with the women's movement, to gain new
artistic respect for traditional ``women's crafts.'' Porcella, who
divides her time between Modesto, Calif., and Arnold, a small town
in the Sierra Nevada mountains, is viewed by many as ``the mother
of art quilts,'' says Bresenhan.
</P>
<P>
   Pausing in a convention center meeting room days before the
festival to discuss her quilts, Porcella looks like an artist, with
wavy, bohemian hair and a silver belt studded with turquoise and
lapis. She wears a handmade black jacket trimmed with bold checks
and a hand-painted tangerine silk shirt. Even her speech is
tactile: She uses her hands and fingers (also studded in turquoise)
in describing fabric and the magic it can weave.
</P>
<P>
   So how is an art quilt different from a quilt quilt?
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is in the terminology,'' Porcella says. ``All
quilts are art, but art quilts were never intended for the bed.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, art quilts bring ``the discipline of fine art'' to
an otherwise homey craft. ``It's about looking at quilts as a
painting or mixed media,'' she explains. `` `Collage' is a good
term. We attempt to use fabric as collage.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, people from outside the traditional quilting
world _ people with formal art training _ have increasingly been
drawn to the medium. This influx has further ``broadened the
boundaries'' of art quilting, Porcella says.
</P>
<P>
   Her own entree into the textile world was accidental. A young
mother of four married to a physician, she was teaching herself to
weave and paint in her cramped laundry room. One day, one of her
kids knocked over an oil painting. It was ruined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two mediums just didn't work together, so that was it. I
switched to fabric,'' she says. ``That was my first love anyway _
the joy of it, the feel of it.'' She rubs her fingers together.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, Porcella (who has never made a traditional
quilt) progressed from making her own fabric to weaving, to
collecting and weaving from ethnic textiles, to making wearable art
and kimonos. In 1979, she attended a quilting convention and left
inspired. What if I made art flat? she asked herself. Her first
quilt, titled ``Takoage,'' was full of unorthodox strips and
triangles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought to myself, `People are going to think some lunatic
put this together,' '' she says, smiling. `` `This is like no quilt
ever seen.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The piece now resides in the Smithsonian's Renwick Gallery at
the Museum of American Art in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Her art quilts have evolved as well, moving from primarily
color-based creations to quilts based on themes drawn from her
travels, memories or events. Some make political statements, such
as her work based on the Persian Gulf War, full of hearts
representing her grandchildren. (``Which heart do we send off to
war?'' she asks.)
</P>
<P>
   Her quilts bear recurrent motifs _ black-and-white squares,
polka dots, calla lilies, wild geometrics, striding figures. An
inveterate Polaroid picture-taker, Porcella also relies on ``visual
data,'' whether it's corrugated siding on an old building or a
field of flowers. She works from hand-drawn sketches, projecting
them onto a wall, then tracing them onto cloth. She cuts fabric to
fit, then sews the pieces in place by hand and machine.
</P>
<P>
   Porcella was thrilled when an issue of Time magazine devoted to
American art opened with an image of an Amish quilt. Recognition is
coming, but slowly, she says. The problem is that quilting is
traditionally regarded as ``soft art'' _ that is, the craft of
kaffeeklatsches.
</P>
<P>
   As an antidote, Porcella, through her Studio Art Quilt
Associates, urges peers to regard their quilts as art so that
others will, too. Art quilts are art, she says. They do what art
does: evoke an emotional or spiritual response from the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feed the soul,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Her hope is that a major museum will soon mount an art-quilt
exhibit. It's ``the next logical step, when you look at the breadth
of what's being done,'' she says. Other art quilters are pushing
the envelope even more _ painting their quilts, studding them with
``found objects,'' sewing X-Acto knives into the fabric as a
tactile joke.
</P>
<P>
   This boundary-stretching has produced its conflicts, she says.
Traditional quilters were slow to embrace the work of their more
revolutionary sisters. Porcella recalls a major quilt show in 1986
when a bus load of conventional quilters confronted a wall of art
quilts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a slap across the face to them,'' Porcella says.
``They were saying things like, `How can this be here? She didn't
even trim her threads!' or, `She must be on LSD!' It wasn't
acceptable to their sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, a new unity has emerged, she says, with quilters of
all stripes giving one another equal respect.
</P>
<P>
   And Porcella has evolved once again. She unfurls two samples of
her latest work, a stunning series of heads resembling African
masks. (They go for $950 each; her other art quilts can sell for
thousands of dollars and are available exclusively through the
Connell Gallery in Atlanta. Her quilts are part of an exhibit and
will not be for sale at the festival.) The new series reflects
Porcella's urge to capture more ``spontaneity'' in her art, which
by its nature is time-consuming and labor-intensive.
</P>
<P>
   And, for her, painful. For years she's struggled with carpal
tunnel syndrome, even undergoing surgery for it. But she just can't
stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is in me, driving me to do it,'' she says, sounding
very much like an artist. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
