<HEADER>
A1369 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEEN-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS     10-28 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEEN-MUSIC-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT EARL KEEN FAVORS THE OLD OVER NEW 
 
RICK MITCHELL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Three songs into his concert Saturday night at the
Aerial Theater, Robert Earl Keen introduced a new song called
``Feelin' Good Again.'' With its delicate finger-picked guitar and
a warm and fuzzy lyrical perspective, the song represents a mellow
change of pace from the rock-edged direction of his last album,
``Picnic.''
</P>
<P>
   Keen's new album, ``Walking Distance,'' is due in stores
Tuesday. The album is his second for the Arista Austin label, after
several releases for the independent Sugar Hill label.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 15 years ago, it was all I could do to get out of bed
and order a pizza,'' Keen told the not-quite sold-out house
Saturday night. ``It's a big step, from ordering a pizza to putting
out an album.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone could accuse him of excessively hyping the new
release. Unless I missed something, the set list included only one
other new tune; ``That Buckin' Song,'' a rodeo ditty that gets
maximum mileage out of its clever rhyme scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Keen's Texas cult-hero status has come at a certain price. Like
Willie Nelson, he balances two separate careers as a touring act
and a recording artist.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Nelson, however, Keen still considers himself first and
foremost a songwriter. And ``Walking Distance'' contains some of
the most personal and poignant compositions of his recording
career.
</P>
<P>
   The problem Keen must contend with is introducing his more
thoughtful and laid-back material to boisterous frat-guys eager to
bellow along on ``Swervin' In My Lane'' and raise a toast to
``Corpus Christi Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That Buckin' Song'' is destined to become an in-concert
favorite. But Keen didn't take many chances with his set-list. Even
more up-tempo new songs such as ``Travelin' Light'' and ``New Life
In Old Mexico'' were bypassed in favor of proven crowd-pleasers
such as ``Five Pound Bass'' and ``It's the Little Things.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the set did include a number of serious songs. The
melancholy opening tune, ``I Wonder Where My Baby Is Tonight,''
evokes an atmosphere of barely restrained desperation. ``Gringo
Honeymoon'' is a modern border town masterpiece, as well as an
unusually subtle love song.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to setting a mood, Keen has few peers among the
current generation of Texas songwriters. His approach has spawned a
growing legion of collegiate emulators, none of whom has come close
to equaling his knack for inventive melodies and non-cliched
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Keen's road band is perhaps the tightest of its kind in the
state. It includes Keen's childhood friend Bryan Duckworth on
fiddle, Rich Brotherton on lead guitar, Bill Whitbeck on bass and
the newest member, Tom Van Shaik, on drums.
</P>
<P>
   Brotherton, who also plays with Toni Price, is one of Austin's
most underrated guitarists. He's capable of shifting gears from
acoustic bluegrass flat-picking to electric power chords on
``Levelland'' and the searing solo that climaxes ``Dreadful Selfish
Crime.''
</P>
<P>
   If the band sounded less inspired than it did at May's Texas
Uprising concert at the Woodlands Pavilion north of Houston, the
overly loud and improperly balanced sound mix might have had
something to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it was me, waiting impatiently to hear more new
material. After watching Keen duet with Steve Earle on ``Tom Ames'
Prayer'' and Joe Ely on ``Whenever Kindness Fails'' at the Texas
Uprising concert, the versions here inevitably sounded slightly
anti-climactic by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   And while ``The Road Goes On Forever'' will go down as one of
the anthems of our era _ an epic country-rock ``corrido'' in which
the party never ends _ you can only sing along on the chorus so
many times before the party becomes not quite as much fun anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Keen is a Houston native who now lives in Bandera, Texas. His
encore choices _ ``I'm Comin' Home,'' ``The Coming Home of the Son
and Brother'' and ``Merry Christmas from the Family'' _ emphasized
his Houston ties.
</P>
<P>
   The new album features a sequel to the last song called ``Happy
Holidays, Y'all.'' This might have been a good place to introduce
it. Oh, well. Maybe next Christmas, after the frat-guys have had a
chance to learn the words. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
