<SLUG> BC-TV-SWEEPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVEMBER TV PROGRAMMING HAS PLENTY TO OFFER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing to watch on TV? Phooey to that.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not finding stuff to like, you need to look harder.
It's out there aplenty, from ``Ally,'' ``Buffy'' and ``Biography''
to ``Frasier,'' ``Friends'' and ``Frontline.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, there are several new series to like, too, from ``Will
&AMP; Grace'' to ``Sports Night,'' ``Charmed'' to ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you need some extra incentive to turn on and tune in,
television offers it in November, one of the months set aside for
``sweeps.'' (Local stations use sweep ratings to set future ad
rates.) And this year, while there's no history-making event like
``Roots,'' there's a miniseries with a ``Roots'' connection. There
may not be an Olivier or Hepburn in a ``Love Among the Ruins,'' but
there's a determined performance from Christopher Reeve and a
bravura one from Leon, the actor with no last name.
</P>
<P>
   There are things to like this month, and for your viewing ease
and pleasure, we offer up our list, top to bottom, of the
television specials we believe worthy of your attention. As the
sweeps begin Thursday, here is our baker's dozen of November's
best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Temptations'' _ ``War and Peace'' this isn't, but
judicious use of the Temps' music and an Emmy-worthy performance by
Leon as David Ruffin lift this biopic several notches above
standard fare. NBC, Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rear Window'' _ Keep those Emmy nominations coming.
Christopher Reeve proves you can be paralyzed from the neck down
and still act, starring in this updated version of Alfred
Hitchcock's 1954 classic. ABC, Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winchell'' _ Attention, Mr. and Mrs. America and all the ships
at sea: Stanley Tucci (``Big Night,'' ``Murder One'') plays the
celebrated (and feared and despised) gossip columnist and radio
broadcaster. Paul Mazursky directs. Not previewed. HBO, Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``David and Lisa'' _ Lukas Haas and Brittany Murphy play
emotionally troubled teens in this remake of the 1962 film (which
starred Kier Dullea and Janet Margolin). Sidney Poitier contributes
his commanding presence as the teen's compassionate psychiatrist.
ABC, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mama Flora's Family'' _ Alex Haley's follow-up to ``Roots,''
this time from his mother's side of the family. Spanning half a
century, the two-part mini stars Cicely Tyson in the role of Flora,
Mario Van Peebles as the son Flora bears but must give up, Blair
Underwood as the son she raises, Erika Alexander and Queen Latifah.
CBS, Nov. 8 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Story of Jesse H. Jones'' _ A ``forgotten hero from one of the
most important chapters of our nation's history'' is remembered in
this grand, PBS-produced biography of the Houston businessman and
philanthropist (and Houston Chronicle founder). Walter Cronkite
narrates ``Brother, Can You Spare a Billion?'' PBS, Nov. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saint Maybe'' _ ``Hallmark Hall of Fame'' presents a fine
adaptation of Anne Tyler's best seller about a young man under
religious conviction to raise his brother's family on his own.
Thomas McCarthy, Mary-Louise Parker, Blythe Danner and Edward
Herrmann star. CBS, Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't Look Down'' _ In the first of a series of projects for
ABC, horrormeister Wes Craven unveils a thriller about a woman
(Megan Ward) who witnesses her sister's death, then becomes spooked
by visions of herself falling from high places. ABC, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleeping Beauty'' _ This timeless, always watchable Disney
classic has its broadcast television premiere. ABC, Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank Lloyd Wright'' _ This bio on the acclaimed architect
comes from Lynn Novick and the acclaimed documentarian Ken Burns.
PBS, Nov. 10-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knight in Camelot'' _ Whoopi Goldberg plays a modern-day
scientist accidentally sucked into sixth-century England, where
Arthur (Michael York) is king, Guinevere and Lancelot are
(wink-wink) ``friends,'' and Merlin's (Ian Richardson) magic tricks
are surpassed by Whoopi's. Loosely based on Mark Twain's ``A
Connecticut Yankee in King Arthur's Court.'' ABC, Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max Q'' _ A shuttle mission goes awry, leaving a disabled ship
and its crew floating perilously in space. The crew's fate rests in
the hands of people back on Earth. Bill Campbell and Paget Brewster
star. Working the roller-coaster switch: producer Jerry Bruckheimer
(``Armageddon,'' ``Con Air,'' ``The Rock,'' ``Crimson Tide,'' ``Top
Gun''). ABC, Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Garth Brooks: Double Live'' _ In promoting his new live album,
Brooks sings new songs, revisits some old ones and takes questions
from a studio audience. Portions of the show will be live.
Unpreviewed. NBC, Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Also worth noting
</P>
<P>
   ``American Experience.'' America 1900. A look at the forces
shaped the 20th century. PBS, Nov. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antiques Roadshow Jr''. The popular PBS series spawns a
special designed for young people. PBS, Nov. 23.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biography.'' The lives of Walter, John and Angelica Huston are
chronicled in a two-hour edition of the popular cable series. A&AMP;E,
Nov. 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Birdcage.'' Robin Williams and Nathan Lane star. ABC, Nov.
12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cats.'' Television premiere of Andrew Lloyd Webber's
still-running Broadway musical. This fully staged production stars
Elaine Paige. PBS, Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming Home: The Veteran Experience in America.'' What was it
like to travel overseas for years as a soldier in combat, then
return home and find an unfamiliar place? History Channel, Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Death Train.'' Chronicles the plight of Russians doomed to
Gulag camps. HBO, Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exiled: A `Law &AMP; Order' Movie.'' Banished to Staten Island,
detective Mike Logan (Chris Noth) schemes to be given a murder case
that will take him back to Manhattan and his family at the
precinct. NBC, Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Shorty.'' John Travolta and Danny DeVito star. NBC, Nov.
22.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside the Actors Studio.'' Too bad Bravo's gone the
commercial route, so expect interruptions to this fine series,
which during sweeps includes a conversation with Meryl Streep.
Bravo, Nov. 22.
</P>
