<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PUMPKIN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUMPKIN USED IN EVERYTHING FROM APPETIZERS TO ENTREES TO DESSERT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: Photo available on New York Times photo service. &HT;     
with recipies sidebar: FOOD-PUMPKIN-RECIPIES By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Pumpkin wears many disguises for the Halloween table. It can
appear in everything from appetizers and entrees to dessert.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a stellar year for this fall favorite because of the
superhot weather during the growing season, according to one
produce wholesaler. There is an ample supply of jack-o'-lantern
pumpkins, but the quality of cooking pumpkins is off a bit, says
Jerry St. Laurent of Chef's Produce in Houston. Nevertheless, this
is the peak season to enjoy fresh pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Interest has been growing the past few years in white pumpkins,
but you'll see them around, although they're not in great supply.
They also can be used for cooking. A mixture of mini pumpkins and
white pumpkins with a scarecrow figure makes an eye-catching
Halloween centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   A tureen of pumpkin soup or stew makes an elegant entree for a
holiday dinner party or a nourishing meal for trick-or-treaters.
For extra drama, serve the soup from a real pumpkin shell. Pick one
of these versions, add a salad and some hearty bread.
</P>
<P>
   Different types of pumpkins are needed for carving or painting
jack-o'-lanterns and cooking.
</P>
<P>
   For carving, choose large pumpkins. Pick those that are bigger
than 12 inches and from 20 to 40 pounds. Choose the smaller, bright
orange, round, ribbed, sugar or pie pumpkins for cooking. They
weigh 6 to 8 pounds, are 8 to 10 inches in diameter and have a
thick rind.
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin is highly perishable and must be cooked the day it is
cut open. Chill cooked pumpkin immediately. Freeze the pulp if you
don't plan to use it within 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin, a close cousin to squash, may be cooked like squash. It
also has a similar nutrition profile. Pumpkin is an excellent
source of vitamin A (1,320 international units in { cup cooked,
mashed pumpkin; enough for one day's needs); it's high in dietary
fiber (1 gram per { cup); high in carbohydrates (6 grams per {
cup); and negligible in fat (less than 0.1 gram per { cup). Fresh,
cooked, mashed pumpkin provides 24 calories per { cup; canned has
about 40 calories.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to use a pumpkin shell as a serving utensil, use a
cleaned-out raw pumpkin. Pumpkins darken considerably if baked long
enough that the meat softens enough to be scraped out, and
sometimes the shell collapses. Use a medium-to-large pumpkin and
watch carefully. Check at the minimum time listed in the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Following are basic cooking directions and some of the Houston
Chronicle's best pumpkin recipes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Cooking methods: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oven-cooking bag: Cut the pumpkin in halves, quarters or large
chunks. Scrape out the seeds and strings. Place pumpkin pieces, cut
side down, in a 16-by-10-inch or 14-by-10-inch oven-cooking bag.
</P>
<P>
   Close the bag with a twist tie and make 6 ({-inch) slits in the
top near the twist tie. Bake at 350 degrees 45 to 60 minutes, or
until the pumpkin collapses. When cool enough to handle, carefully
remove the peel from the pumpkin meat, and puree the meat in a
blender or food processor.
</P>
<P>
   Range top: Halve the pumpkin. Scoop out the seeds and fibers.
Cut the pumpkin into large pieces, then peel each piece with a
vegetable peeler. Cut pieces into {-inch cubes. Place cubes in a
large, heavy saucepan and cover with about 1 inch cold water.
</P>
<P>
   Bring to a boil, reduce heat and simmer covered until tender, 10
to 15 minutes (larger pieces may take 20 to 25 minutes). Stir
occasionally to prevent scorching. Drain and mash, or process in
food processor with a little cooking liquid to moisten. If desired,
add a little margarine and seasonings (salt, black pepper, dried
thyme, etc.) and heat until margarine melts.
</P>
<P>
   Oven baking: Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Halve pumpkin. Remove
the seeds and fibers. Cut into 2-inch pieces and peel. Put peeled
pieces in a shallow baking dish, and brush with melted margarine.
Sprinkle with salt and pepper. Bake, uncovered, 45 minutes, or
until tender, brushing several times with margarine. Serve as a
vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Microwave: Weigh pumpkin to determine the correct timing (do
this at the store if you don't have a scale). Allow 7 minutes per
pound. For a medium-size pumpkin, cut it in half vertically, then
scoop out the seeds and fibers.
</P>
<P>
   Place one half, cut side down, in a 12-by-8-inch microwavable
baking dish. Microwave on high, uncovered, 18 to 22 minutes, or
until tender, rotating dish once or twice during cooking time.
Repeat procedure for the other half.
</P>
<P>
   Cool until easy to handle. Scoop out pulp and place in a blender
or food processor. Puree at medium speed until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Like prune puree and applesauce, pumpkin puree can serve as a
fat substitute in breads, muffins and cakes, according to Sandra
Woodruff, author of ``Secrets of Fat-Free Baking'' (Avery
Publishing, $12.95). Woodruff says to increase the amount of
pumpkin as you eliminate fat.
</P>
<P>
   For half the butter, margarine or other solid shortening in
cookies, substitute three-fourths as much pumpkin (i.e., if a
recipe calls for 1 cup butter, use { cup butter and 4 to 6
tablespoons mashed pumpkin). Bake reduced-fat and fat-free cookies
at 275 to 300 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If puree is watery, simmer over low heat in a heavy-bottom
pan instead of draining off liquid; draining removes much of the
flavor. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
