<HEADLINE>
FOOD-PUMPKIN-RECIPIES-2TAKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  EDITORS: These recipies are a sider to FOOD-PUMPKIN story for
Wednesday, Oct. 28. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indian Pumpkin Soup Almondine
</P>
<P>
   from Houston Chronicle files &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To serve this soup family-style from a hollowed-out pumpkin,
select a uniformly shaped pumpkin with a level bottom, or cut a
thin slice from the bottom to make it level. Slice the top off the
pumpkin to make a lid. Scrape out seeds and stringy fibers, then
scoop out the meat, being careful not to puncture the sides of the
pumpkin. (The meat can be used for the soup or another use.)
</P>
<P>
   Before serving the soup, warm the pumpkin shell in a preheated
180-degree oven about 15 minutes, or microwave on high 5 to 8
minutes, depending on the size of the pumpkin. Pour hot soup into
warmed pumpkin shell and ladle into bowls at the table. Use hot
pads while handling heated pumpkin. Do not overheat or pumpkin will
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
\ cup butter or margarine &QL; 
2 large onions, chopped &QL; 
{ cup lentils &QL; 
5 cups chicken stock &QL; 
1 { cups canned or cooked pumpkin &QL; 
[ teaspoon each: marjoram and thyme &QL; 
 &QL; 
\ teaspoon coarsely ground black pepper &QL; 
Dash of hot red pepper sauce &QL; 
1 cup half-and-half &QL; 
Salt to taste &QL; 
{ cup toasted sliced or slivered almonds &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in large kettle. Add onions and cook until lightly
browned. Stir in lentils and chicken stock; add pumpkin. Crush
marjoram and thyme and add to soup along with ground pepper and
pepper sauce. Simmer about 1 { hours or until lentils are done. Let
cool, then puree in blender (will have to be done in batches).
</P>
<P>
   At serving time, heat soup to simmer, then add half-and-half and
season with salt. Serve in soup bowls, cups or in a hollowed-out
pumpkin, and top with almonds. Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hearty Golden Pumpkin Soup &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Great Pumpkin Cookbook'' from McNeill Libby Co. (out
of print).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
2 tablespoons butter or margarine &QL; 
{ cup each, chopped: onion and celery &QL; 
2 cups each: chicken broth and sliced fresh mushrooms &QL; 
{ cup raw rice &QL; 
 &QL; 
{ teaspoon each: salt and tarragon &QL; 
1 (16-ounce) can solid pack pumpkin &QL; 
2 cups half-and-half &QL; 
\ cup dry sherry &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in medium saucepan; saute onion and celery. Add
broth, mushrooms, rice, salt and tarragon. Bring to a boil. Cover
and simmer 20 minutes or until rice is cooked. Stir in pumpkin;
continue cooking 5 minutes. Stir in half-and-half and sherry. Heat
thoroughly. Makes 6 cups, 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gingered Pumpkin Soup &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Pumpkin Cookbook,'' edited by Nicola Hill (Hamlyn,
$12).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
2 \ pounds pumpkin, peeled, seeded and roughly chopped &QL; 
1 (1-inch) piece fresh ginger, peeled &QL; 
1 tablespoon sunflower oil &QL; 
1 large onion, peeled and chopped &QL; 
2 teaspoons ground ginger &QL; 
1 teaspoon ground turmeric &QL; 
2 ripe tomatoes, skinned and chopped &QL; 
2 teaspoons brown sugar &QL; 
 &QL; 
\ teaspoon grated nutmeg &QL; 
1 thin strip orange zest (thinnest colored part of peel only) &QL; 
2 { cups chicken stock &QL; 
Salt and freshly ground black pepper &QL; 
1 \ cups plain yogurt (can use fat-free) &QL; 
Garnish: 2 tablespoons chopped parsley, 6 tablespoons pumpkin seeds
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Put pumpkin and piece of ginger in a saucepan; cover with water,
bring to a boil, cover pot and simmer 15 minutes or until pumpkin
is tender. Drain thoroughly and discard ginger.
</P>
<P>
   Heat oil in a clean saucepan; add onion and cook over moderate
heat 2 minutes. Stir in ground ginger and turmeric; cook 1 minute.
Add pumpkin, tomatoes, sugar, nutmeg, zest and stock; bring to a
boil. Cover and simmer 10 minutes. Cool slightly. Discard zest.
</P>
<P>
   Puree pumpkin mixture in a blender or food processor, then
return to the pot. Season to taste with salt and pepper; stir in
yogurt. Heat gently. Taste and adjust seasoning if necessary. Serve
in warm bowls garnished with parsley and pumpkin seeds. Makes 6
servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin Butter
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
6 pounds pumpkin, winter squash or carrots &QL; 
2 tablespoons each, ground: ginger and cinnamon &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 teaspoon ground allspice &QL; 
5 pounds light brown sugar &QL; 
Juice and rind of 5 lemons &QL; 
1 pint water &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peel pumpkin and remove seeds and fibers. Chop pumpkin fine or
put through food chopper. Pour pumpkin into a nonreactive bowl and
add ginger, cinnamon, allspice and sugar with lemon juice and rind
(which has been put through a food chopper). Let mixture stand
overnight. The next day, pour pumpkin mixture into a large stew pot
and add water; bring to a boil over medium heat. Boil gently until
vegetables are clear and soft and mixture is thick. Pour into
sterilized jars and seal while hot. For prolonged storage, keep in
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Microwave Pumpkin Butter
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
\ cup dark brown sugar &QL; 
2 tablespoons granulated sugar &QL; 
\ cup water &QL; 
{ teaspoon each: allspice and cinnamon &QL; 
 &QL; 
\ teaspoon each: ginger, cloves and nutmeg &QL; 
1{ cups cooked pumpkin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugars, water, allspice, cinnamon, ginger, cloves and
nutmeg in 4-cup glass measure. Microwave 3 minutes on high. Add
pumpkin; microwave 5 minutes on high. Cool and refrigerate. Makes 2
cups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin Fudge
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
3 cups sugar &QL; 
} cup butter or margarine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup evaporated milk &QL; 
{ cup canned pumpkin &QL; 
1 teaspoon pumpkin pie spice &QL; 
1 (12-ounce) package butterscotch morsels &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 (7-ounce) jar marshmallow creme &QL; 
1 cup chopped toasted almonds &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla extract &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, butter, milk, pumpkin and pie spice in heavy
saucepan. Bring to boil stirring constantly and continue boiling
over medium heat, stirring constantly until mixture reaches 234
degrees on a candy thermometer, about 10 minutes. Remove from heat
and stir in morsels. Add marshmallow creme, nuts and vanilla; mix
well.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly pour into greased 13-by-9-by-2-inch pan and spread until
even. Cool at room temperature and cut into squares. Store tightly
wrapped in refrigerator. Makes 3 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Pumpkin Seeds &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From ``Holiday Pumpkins: A Collection of Inspired Recipes, Gifts
and Decorations'' by Georgeanne Brennan (Smithmark Publishers,
$14.98).
</P>
<P>
   These crunchy roasted seeds, called pepitas in Mexico, can be
eaten without shelling because the shells crisp nicely during
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
2 tablespoons canola or vegetable oil &QL; 
1 cup seeds from any freshly cut pumpkin, washed and dried &QL; 
Salt to taste &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Heat oil in a skillet over
medium-high heat. When oil is hot, saute seeds, stirring frequently
until lightly browned, about 5 minutes. Using a slotted spoon,
transfer seeds to an ungreased baking sheet and spread in a single
layer. Sprinkle with salt. Bake until crisp, about 15 minutes.
Transfer with slotted spoon to paper towels and let cool. Store in
an airtight container as long as one month. Makes about 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   Separate stringy fiber from pumpkin seeds. Rinse seeds with cool
water and lay on paper towels or newspaper to dry completely. Store
dry seeds in a plastic bag or tightly covered container until ready
to toast.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Spread seeds in one layer on baking
sheets that have been lightly greased or coated with vegetable oil
spray. Bake until lightly browned, about 15 minutes. Sprinkle with
salt if desired. May be stored at room temperature for a couple of
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Microwave Toasted Pumpkin Seeds &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
1 cup fresh pumpkin seeds &QL; 
2 tablespoons butter or margarine &QL; 
Salt or other seasonings to taste &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rinse seeds in water to remove fibers, then pat dry with paper
towels. Place margarine in a 2-quart rectangular dish and microwave
on high 30 seconds. Stir in seeds to coat; spread evenly in dish.
Microwave on high 7 to 8 minutes, or until toasted, stirring every
2 minutes. Sprinkle with salt or other seasonings. Cool before
storing in an airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin Pound Cake
</P>
<P>
   From ``Simply Cakes'' by Elizabeth Alston (HarperCollins,
$12.50).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:  &QL; 
2 sticks butter, at room temperature &QL; 
{ cup granulated sugar &QL; 
} cup packed dark brown sugar &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla extract &QL; 
4 large eggs &QL; 
2 cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
1 teaspoon baking powder &QL; 
 &QL; 
{ teaspoon each: baking soda and salt &QL; 
2 teaspoons ground cinnamon &QL; 
1 {teaspoons ground nutmeg &QL; 
1 teaspoon ground ginger &QL; 
1 cup canned pumpkin &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Topping (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Spray a 9-by-5-by-3-inch loaf pan with nonstick cooking spray
and line the bottom with wax paper; spray again and set aside.
Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Cream butter and sugars until fluffy on medium-high speed in
electric mixer. Beat in vanilla. Reduce speed to medium. Add eggs,
one at a time, beating after each.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate bowl, sift together flour, baking powder, soda,
salt, cinnamon, nutmeg and ginger. Add dry ingredients in two
additions to butter mixture, alternating with pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer batter to pan. Sprinkle Topping over batter. Bake 1
hour or until a tester inserted into center of cake comes out
clean. Cool in the pan 15 minutes before unmolding onto a rack. Let
cool completely. Wrap airtight and store in refrigerator or
freezer.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 slices, each: 361 calories, 5 grams protein, 18 grams
fat, 32 grams carbohydrates, 114 milligrams cholesterol, 352
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Topping
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
2 tablespoons granulated sugar &QL; 
{ teaspoon each: ground cinnamon and nutmeg &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, cinnamon and nutmeg; use as directed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin Cheesecake Bars
</P>
<P>
   From Chronicle files. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
2 cups unsifted all-purpose flour &QL; 
} cup firmly packed brown sugar &QL; 
1 { cups chopped pecans or walnuts, divided &QL; 
{ cup margarine or butter, melted &QL; 
3 eggs, divided &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla, divided &QL; 
1 (8-ounce) package cream cheese, softened (can use light) &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 (14-ounce) can sweetened condensed milk (not evaporated milk) &QL; 
1 (16-ounce) can pumpkin (about 2 cups fresh) &QL; 
2 teaspoons pumpkin pie spice (see note) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. To make crust, combine flour,
sugar, { cup nuts and margarine in a medium-size bowl; mix until
crumbly. Stir in 1 beaten egg and 1 teaspoon vanilla; mix well.
Press onto bottom of 15-by-10-inch baking sheet. Bake 15 minutes at
350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in large mixing bowl, beat cream cheese until fluffy.
Blend in sweetened condensed milk. Add remaining 2 eggs, one at a
time, beating well after each addition. Add pumpkin, pumpkin pie
spice and remaining 1 teaspoon vanilla; beat until smooth. Pour
mixture over prepared crust; sprinkle remaining nuts on top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 30 to 35 minutes, or until set. Cool to room temperature
before cutting into bars. Store in refrigerator. Makes 48 bars.
</P>
<P>
   Note: If you don't have pumpkin pie spice, an approximate
equivalent is 1 teaspoon ground cinnamon, { teaspoon ground ginger
and \ teaspoon ground cloves for this recipe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ann Brinkerhoff's Pumpkin Bread &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This has been a great favorite with Houston Chronicle readers
since it was first published in the '70s. Ann Brinkerhoff is an
active alumna of the University of Texas and contributed this
recipe to ``Cook 'em Horns,'' a cookbook published by the UT
Ex-Students Association in 1981. The recipe adapts well to a coffee
can, large Bundt pan, small cupcake-size Bundt pan or cupcake pan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
3 cups sugar &QL; 
3 { cups all-purpose flour &QL; 
2 teaspoons baking soda &QL; 
{ teaspoon salt &QL; 
2 teaspoons each: ground nutmeg, allspice, cloves and cinnamon. &QL; 
4 eggs &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 cups fresh cooked or canned pumpkin &QL; 
1 cup vegetable oil &QL; 
{ cup water plus { cup apricot or peach brandy (or 1 cup water) &QL; 
1 cup each: chopped pecans and raisins &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Combine sugar, flour, soda, salt,
nutmeg, allspice, cloves and cinnamon in large electric mixer bowl.
In a separate large bowl, mix eggs, pumpkin, oil, water and brandy;
add to dry ingredients; beat until well-mixed. Fold in pecans and
raisins. Bake in large, greased Bundt pan until cake tests done,
about 1 hour and 30 to 45 minutes. Makes 18 to 20 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pumpkin Loaf
</P>
<P>
   This has been a favorite since we discovered it on the label of
Pioneer Flour Mill's French Doughnut (Beignet) mix years ago.
You'll find the mix in the supermarket where bread and cake mixes
are stocked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
4 cups (an 18-ounce box) Pioneer French Doughnut (beignet) mix &QL; 
3 cups sugar &QL; 
2 teaspoons baking soda &QL; 
1 { teaspoons salt &QL; 
1 teaspoon each, ground: cinnamon and nutmeg or allspice &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 cups pumpkin puree (homemade or canned) &QL; 
{ cup vegetable oil &QL;
</P>
<P>
   cup water &QL; 
4 eggs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Generously grease 2
(8-inch-by-4-inch) loaf pans or 4 miniature loaf pans.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine doughnut mix, sugar, soda, salt,
cinnamon and nutmeg. Add pumpkin, oil and water; mix well. Add
eggs, one at a time, stirring well after each addition. Pour into
prepared pans. Bake 55 to 70 minutes, or until bread springs back
when touched. Cool in pans 10 to 15 minutes before removing. Makes
2 loaves. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
