<HEADLINE>
MEXICANS FEAST CELEBRATES DAY OF THE DEAD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Day of the Dead (``Dia de los Muertos'') is one of the most
time-honored customs in Mexico, a festive occasion that celebrates
life, instead of a somber ritual. Mexicans believe the dead yearn
for the things they loved when living and return to share in the
festivities. Photos of the deceased and images of patron saints are
displayed on home altars (``ofrendas'') along with offerings of
favorite foods.
</P>
<P>
   It is customary to construct an altar. ``Ofrendas'' are adorned
with flowers (especially marigolds), herbs, palm leaves and other
greenery, candles, sugar-paste figurines, skulls sculpted in sugar
(``calaveras''), photographs, mementos and Dead Man's Bread (``Pan
de los Muertos'').
</P>
<P>
   Mexican culinary expert and writer Patricia Quintana describes
``Dia de los Muertos'' as a combination of pre-Hispanic Indian
beliefs and the Catholic traditions of medieval Spain. When reborn
into the Mexican culture, the All Souls Day of Spanish-Indian
Mexico became Mexico's Day of the Dead, Quintana says. Instead of
praying for those in Purgatory on All Souls Day, Mexicans
celebrated with those who have gone before, feasted with them and
welcomed them home for a visit.
</P>
<P>
   By tradition, on Oct. 31, festivities begin with parents
welcoming back ``los angelitos,'' the souls of departed children.
The next day the sweets and toys on the children's altars are
replaced by adult treats. On Nov. 2, families gather to ``raise the
dead,'' and food that has decorated the altars is consumed. Typical
of ``Dia de los Muertos'' menus are several kinds of mole, shrimp,
rice, pumpkin in syrup, tamales and fruits.
</P>
<P>
   Lucia Bettler of Lucia's Garden in Houston and a cooking
teacher, Jano Mott, constructed altars this year during cooking
classes for the public and the Houston Culinary Guild, an
organization of women food professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The menu included seasonal foods such as glazed sweet potatoes
with cinnamon and cloves, autumn salad and green pumpkin seeds,
which accompanied cinnamon-roasted chicken and flan.
</P>
<P>
   The Day of the Dead custom has not flourished in modern times
because the food takes so long to prepare and is so laborious, Mott
said. Candied sweet potatoes with cinnamon and cloves, for example,
had to bake in the oven 2 hours, basting every 20 minutes. The
sauce boiled for 2 { hours.
</P>
<P>
   At the Culinary Guild meeting, Dolly Bille added to the altar a
picture of her late mother, a handful of garbanzo beans, which her
mother liked, and an ice cream scoop to symbolize how much her late
father loved ice cream. Mott contributed photos of her former
husband, who died recently, and a photo of a beloved woman who
reared her and gave her an appreciation of home-grown foods.
</P>
<P>
   Heide Vukovic brought a Polish postage stamp (Poland was her
father's home), a photograph of her father-in-law from Yugoslavia
and a doily crocheted by her husband's grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Bettler displayed a picture of her grandfather and his rosary,
which is made of beans, and brought an artichoke, one of his
favorite foods.
</P>
<P>
   Other favorites added included cookies and chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   For more information and recipes for Day of the Dead, these make
good reading: ``Frida's Feasts'' (Clarkson Potter, $35) about
artist Frida Kahlo, who was married to Mexican muralist Diego
Rivera; ``Rosa Mexicano: A Culinary Autobiography with 60 Recipes''
by Josefina Howard (Viking, $29.95); and ``Mexico's Feasts of
Life'' by Patricia Quintana (Council Oak Books, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   In her book, Howard tells about the celebration of ``Dia de los
Muertos'' in Xochimilco and the use of amaranth, a seed or grain
with similar nutritional value to sesame. The Spaniards prevented
the Indians from growing it because of its links to a pagan custom.
Pre-Columbian people traditionally made gods out of amaranth and
honey on the days when they remembered their dead. Afterward they
ate slices of amaranth.
</P>
<P>
   Amaranth seems to have been lost for many years; only the people
of Xochimilco still had it, Howard wrote. But after the Day of the
Dead was ``Christianized,'' it was again used.
</P>
<P>
   Amaranth is now considered ``the best food of vegetable origin
for human consumption'' by the U.S. National Academy of Sciences
and the World Food Organization, Howard writes. Amaranth seeds
heated on a comal, or in a frying pan, puff up like popcorn, she
said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
