<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-DEAD-RECIPIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: These recipies are a sidebar to FOOD-DAYOFDEAD story for
Wednesday, Oct. 28 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quesadillas With Poblanos, Brie and Fruit &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Ann Lindsay Greer in the PBS television series ``Southwest
Tastes: Great Chefs of the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Quesadillas are a traditional fiesta dish filled with meats,
vegetables, cheese, chilies or fruit. Serve them either as an
appetizer or with fruit to end the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: { cup water &QL; 
{ yellow onion, halved and thinly sliced &QL; 
10 tortillas (corn for appetizer, flour for dessert) &QL; 
1 pound Brie cheese, cut into \-inch strips &QL; 
2 poblanos, roasted, seeded and diced &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe fruit (mango, papaya), peeled, seeded and diced or equal
amount of seedless grapes &QL; 
4 tablespoons each: butter and vegetable oil &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heat water in a skillet over high heat. Add onions, cover,
remove from heat and let stand until wilted, about 10 minutes.
Drain and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a well-seasoned skillet or nonstick frying pan. Heat
tortillas 15 seconds on each side to soften. Preheat oven to 200
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Lay one tortilla on a plate, add a few onion strips, strips of
Brie, diced poblano and fruit to half of one side; fold the other
half over. Brush top of tortilla with melted butter and oil, turn
over and brush the other side. Place quesadillas in skillet and
brown; turn and brown other surface; set aside on cookie sheet in
the oven to keep warm. When all are done, remove from oven and cut
each quesadilla into 3 wedges. Garnish with a few extra onion
strips and finely chopped poblanos. Makes 30 wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Note: These may be prepared the night before to the point of
filling. Cover to keep tortillas from drying out. Bring to room
temperature, grill (in skillet) and cut.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Candied Sweet Potatoes With Cinnamon and Cloves
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Mexico's Feasts of Life'' by Patricia Quintana
(Council Oak, $24.95). You may gasp over the amount of sugar, but
it is correct. Adjust to taste.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Syrup: &QL; 
6 cups water &QL; 
4 cups sugar &QL; 
6 (6-ounce) piloncillo cones (Mexican brown sugar cones) or 4{ cups
dark brown sugar &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 (3-inch) cinnamon sticks &QL; 
6 whole cloves &QL; 
1 teaspoon aniseseed and lemon juice to taste (optional) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For syrup, pour water into a medium saucepan. Add sugar,
piloncillo, cinnamon, cloves, anise and lemon juice; cook 2 { hours
or until syrup is thick and the consistency of molasses. Strain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Potatoes
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: 4 large (1-pound) yellow sweet potatoes, peeled &QL; 
{ cup butter, melted &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Arrange sweet potatoes in large
baking dish with lid. Brush potatoes with melted butter; cover.
Bake 1 to 1 { hours or until done. Test with a toothpick or fork
for tenderness. Cool potatoes, slice and cover with hot syrup.
Makes 6 to 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meriemil's Flan
</P>
<P>
   No ``Dia de los Muertos'' altar is complete without a freshly
made flan. This is one of our all-time favorites from a former
Houston Chronicle staffer, Meriemil Rodriguez. She uses an
ovenproof double boiler, but it can be made in a flan pan or other
type of container that will fit in a water bath.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
Sugar &QL; 
2 tablespoons water &QL; 
1 (12-ounce) can evaporated milk &QL; 
6 eggs &QL; 
{ teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
 &QL; 
Few drops lemon juice or { teaspoon lemon extract (optional) &QL; 
Grated lemon peel &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For caramel, combine { cup sugar and water in the top of an
ovenproof double boiler. Place top double boiler pan directly on
burner over medium heat and cook, stirring constantly, until sugar
becomes golden. Do not overcook. Set aside in pan.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Combine milk and 1{ cups sugar; mix
well. Add eggs, one at a time, stirring with an egg beater or
rotary beater until just mixed with milk. Add vanilla, lemon juice
and peel to taste. Pour mixture over caramel. Place double boiler
over simmering water in oven or set pan in a larger pan of hot
water. Bake until flan tests done, about 1 hour or when knife
inserted in the center comes out clean. Remove pan from water bath
and oven and let cool at least 20 minutes. Gently run knife around
edge; turn flan out onto a serving dish.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prosciutto-Wrapped Asparagus With Balsamic Glaze
</P>
<P>
   From chef Jim Mills' class for bachelors benefiting Share Our
Strength (S.O.S).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
Salt &QL; 
8 asparagus spears trimmed to 2 { inches &QL; 
2 ounces prosciutto, sliced very thinly &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces (6 tablespoons) balsamic vinegar (dark, aged Italian
vinegar) &QL; 
\ tomato, julienned &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bring a small pot of water to a boil; add salt. Have ready a
bowl of water with a few ice cubes in it. Plunge asparagus into
boiling water and cook 1 minute. Remove and place in iced water 40
seconds. Remove when cooled; drain well. Divide prosciutto into
2-inch wide strips. Roll around asparagus spears. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place balsamic vinegar in small nonreactive pan such as
stainless steel; reduce 1 minute until it thickens to a syrup. Let
cool. To serve, arrange rolls on a plate, drizzle with balsamic
glaze, top with baby gourmet greens (mesclun) and decorate with
julienned tomato. Makes 2 servings. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
