<HEADLINE>
POP UP FUN FOR GHOULS AND GOBLINS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN STEINER 
and CICI WILLIAMSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which snack do you most often prepare in your microwave? If you
said popcorn, you're on the same wave length as other Americans who
pop their favorite snack in the microwave.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Popcorn Institute, Americans eat more popcorn
than any other nationality. Figures indicate that per-capita
consumption of popcorn in the United States is now 84 quarts
annually, up 11 quarts from just three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   We've been popping corn in the microwave almost three decades.
Before packaged microwave popcorn exploded in the marketplace, we
used popcorn poppers designed specifically for the microwave. Some
people even put popcorn into paper sacks _ which is a big no-no
since these can catch on fire during microwaving.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury introduced microwave popcorn (frozen) about 20 years
ago. Now all microwave popcorn is shelf-stable.
</P>
<P>
   What pops up for selection on supermarket shelves is
mind-boggling. Some of the options are: Movie Theatre Butter, Zesty
Butter, Extreme Butter 2000 for the New Millennium, Butter Lover's,
Blast O Butter, Butter, Butter Light, Gourmet Quality, Natural,
Natural Light, Homestyle and Caramel.
</P>
<P>
   In reading the labels, we found it difficult to make a true
comparison regarding nutrient data. Some brands consider a serving
3 { cups, while others consider 4, 5 or 6 cups to be 1 serving. The
best way to compare calories, fat and sodium is to check the
figures for 1 cup popped corn (which is provided on some, but not
all, labels).
</P>
<P>
   Microwave popcorn is designed to pop 99 percent of the kernels.
Follow manufacturer's directions for popping and carefully open the
bag of popped corn to avoid getting burned from the steam. Don't
try to put the unpopped ones back in the microwave to pop, since
the bag could overheat and catch on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Now, pop into the kitchen, grab a bag of microwave popcorn and
conjure up a treat for your family to enjoy. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Goblins' Popcorn Balls
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: 1(3 {-ounce) bag microwave popcorn &QL; 
\ cup each: chopped sugar-coated orange slice candy, chopped black
gumdrops, peanut butter morsels and toffee-coated peanuts &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 cups miniature marshmallows &QL; 
3 tablespoons butter or margarine &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prepare popcorn according to manufacturer's directions; discard
unpopped kernels and place popped corn in a large bowl. Add orange
candy, gumdrops, peanut butter morsels and peanuts; stir to
combine.
</P>
<P>
   Combine marshmallows and butter in a 4-cup glass measure.
Microwave on high 1 minute; stir until melted. Pour over popcorn
mixture; toss to coat evenly. Butter hands, form into balls and
place in individual paper muffin liners. Refrigerate until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 balls, each: 99 calories, 2 grams protein, 4 grams fat,
16 grams carbohydrates, 1 gram fiber, 6 milligrams cholesterol, 82
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Note: In lieu of orange slices and black gumdrops, substitute
whole jelly beans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Praline Popcorn Crunch
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: 1 { cups pecan halves &QL; 
1 (3 {-ounce) bag microwave popcorn &QL; 
{ cup packed brown sugar &QL; 
\ cup margarine or butter &QL; 
 &QL; 
2 tablespoons dark corn syrup &QL; 
\ teaspoon salt &QL; 
{ teaspoon each: vanilla and baking soda &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Place pecans in a 10-inch glass pie plate. Microwave on high 4
minutes, stirring midway through cooking. Place in a 4-quart
microwave-safe utensil. Prepare popcorn according to manufacturer's
directions; discard unpopped kernels and add popped corn to pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, margarine, syrup and salt in a 4-cup glass
measure. Microwave on high 1{ minutes; stir. Microwave on high 2
minutes. Add vanilla and baking soda; stir well.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately pour mixture over popcorn and nuts; toss to coat
evenly. Microwave on high 2 minutes, stirring midway through
cooking. Turn out onto a piece of wax paper or aluminum foil to
cool. Break into pieces and store in an airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 (1-cup) servings, each: 210 calories, 2 grams protein,
15 grams fat, 20 grams carbohydrates, 2 grams fiber, 223 milligrams
sodium.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Savory Southwestern Popcorn
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:  &QL; 
1 (3 {-ounce) bag microwave popcorn &QL; 
3 tablespoons butter &QL; 
1 teaspoon garlic salt &QL; 
{ teaspoon each: ground cumin and chili powder &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prepare popcorn according to manufacturer's directions; discard
unpopped kernels and place popped corn in large bowl. Place butter
in 1-cup glass measure; microwave on high 45 seconds, or until
melted. Stir in garlic salt, cumin and chili powder. Drizzle over
popcorn; toss to coat evenly. Serve warm or store in an airtight
container.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 (1-cup) servings, each: 55 calories, 1 gram protein, 4
grams fat, 5 grams carbohydrates, 1 gram fiber, 9 milligrams
cholesterol, 208 milligrams sodium. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
