<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COGNAC-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW COGNACS DON'T MEASURE UP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cognac is the mother of all brandies.
</P>
<P>
   There are several things you should know about cognac. It's the
brandy made specifically from the Cognac region of France. It can
age gracefully for decades.
</P>
<P>
   And it's gotten hideously expensive.
</P>
<P>
   What's expensive? Cognacs that used to sell in the $15 range are
now routinely in the $40-$60 range. And those in the three-digit
category are almost commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   The Cognac region is a pie with six irregular pieces. Each piece
is distinct, and their quality, in descending order, is: Grande
Champagne, Petite Champagne, Borderies, Fins Bois, Bons Bois and
Bois Ordinaires.
</P>
<P>
   (Trivia: But some cognacs say ``Fine Champagne'' on the label.
What does that mean?)
</P>
<P>
   You seldom hear about the last two districts, but the first four
are of particular interest and are the ones used regularly for
blending.
</P>
<P>
   And blending has been the key to quality cognacs for several
hundred years.
</P>
<P>
   But there's an undercurrent in Cognac these days to offer
bottlings from single districts of Cognac.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it's all that new. Several firms for years have offered
cognacs from Grande or Petite Champagne. After all, those are the
two finest-quality areas. But more recently firms such as Louis
Royer and Gabriel &AMP; Andreu have offered brandies from other areas
of Cognac, as well, the idea being that each offers special
qualities that hopefully will appeal to those who appreciate the
differences.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Hennessey, probably the largest cognac producer, which
is taking the process a step farther. It is now offering three
single-distillery cognacs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hennessey has 27 distilleries,'' said Hennessey's Arnaud
Monnier. ``We own some; the rest we have under exclusive contract.
This enables our three distilleries to make their separate
products. These cognacs are still blends of different vineyards and
vintages, but from a single distillery.''
</P>
<P>
   Monnier said each of the three new cognacs ``possesses a strong
personality and taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are the three new single-distillery Hennessey cognacs:
</P>
<P>
   Le Peu: The distillery is in, and most of the cognac comes from,
the Grande Champagne heart of Cognac. It's a blend of cognacs from
five to 25 years old, with the younger brandies added for
liveliness and acidity, and the older cognacs for smoothness to
round out the blend. Le Peu (it means ``top of the hill'') _ 3
stars _ is light and refined, with a floral quality. Because it is
so light, I would drink it before a meal, not after.
</P>
<P>
   Izambard is the name of a venerable cognac-making family. Of the
three single-distillery brandies, this has the darkest color.
Izambard _2 { stars _ is heavier, too, with more noticeable oak,
along with what Monnier called ``forest notes.'' Both Izambard and
the following Camp Romain come from Fins Bois, said Monnier. To me,
Izambard is the most distinctive, yet one in search of a
personality.
</P>
<P>
   The Camp Romain distillery dates back almost 100 years, and sits
on the site of an ancient Roman camp; hence the name. Camp Romain _
3 { stars _ is one of the few Cognac distilleries run by a woman,
Betty Lesueur. This is the most complex of the three, and has a
butterscotch nuance, Monnier says. This is the one I'd drink after
dinner, in the cognac tradition.
</P>
<P>
   So what about this single-distillery business. Will it be a
short-lived fad, or is the trend of the future? I mean, Scotch
whisky distillers for years have offered both single-distillery
scotches as well as blends. And while the single malts have enjoyed
an increasing popularity in recent years, sales of the blended
whiskies haven't been so hot. Could this happen to cognac? If these
single-distillery items catch on, will cognac drinkers eschew the
traditional blends?
</P>
<P>
   Monnier said no, that because the production of the
single-distillery brandies was so small, they pose no threat to the
blends.
</P>
<P>
   I think he's right, but for a different reason.
</P>
<P>
   On my way home that day, I bought a bottle of Hennessey's
V.S.O.P. cognac, the traditional blend of which Hennessey makes
probably hundreds of thousands of cases a year.
</P>
<P>
   I did a little taste test at home that night and found that
while each of the three single-distillery cognacs had something to
offer, the Hennessey V.S.O.P. offered me more in the most important
department: pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't as delicate as the Le Peu, it wasn't as complex as the
Camp Romain, but it just offered my comfort to my battered soul.
</P>
<P>
   And while it wasn't cheap _ about $40 _ it was less expensive
than the the new cognacs, each of which is about $48 a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessey may be onto something with their new products, but for
me, I'll stick with the old tried-and-true.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessey cognacs are handled here by Glazer's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the right track: Domaine Carneros, owned by the Champagne
firm of Taittinger and which makes some of California's better
sparkling wines, last year released a table wine, the 1995 Pinot
Noir. I didn't like it; called it clumsy, overripe and too tannic.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the 1996 Domaine Carneros Pinot Noir _ 3 { stars _
which is much better. The fruit isn't as raisiny (that's good), the
wine shows better balance (that's good), but it's still a bit
tannic (that's not so good). A little bottle age could soften those
mouth-drying tannins, though.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's a pleasant wine, and went pretty well with a
marinated pork tenderloin sprinkled with fresh rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   From Republic Beverage. Suggested retail: $22.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fan of single-malt scotch, there's an upcoming
``Scotch Whisky Distillery Tour'' March 20-28 that will originate
in Houston. On the itinerary are trips to various distilleries such
as Macallan, Edradour, Dalwhinnie, Glenlivet, Glenfiddich and
Glenmorangie, plus available side trips to Loch Ness or shopping
expeditions in Inverness and Edinburgh, not to mention at least one
stay in a genuine castle (Dalhousie).
</P>
<P>
   Cost is $2,950 per person (double occupancy), and is being
arranged through All Seasons Travel. Call Betty Feehan at
713-627-9900 or 800-666-5555 for reservations or information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Trivia answer: ``Fine Champagne'' means that the cognac blend
must contain at least 50 percent Grande Champagne cognac, with the
rest Petite Champagne cognac.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to: michael.lonsford at chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
