<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS FEAR LOSING POWER IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in the national news, ``a,'' category and political
news, ``p,'' category)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELK GROVE, Calif. _ For the first time since disco died,
California may become a state controlled by Democrats. It is a
thought that spooks Republicans such as Jerry Hogan, a salesman
from Sacramento who attended a recent GOP rally here.
</P>
<P>
   ``That scares me. That really scares me. It's just too much
control,'' Hogan, 34, said at Sunday's steak-and-oyster barbecue in
Elk Grove, an event that attracted Republican gubernatorial
candidate Dan Lungren and Gov. Pete Wilson, who is barred by law
from seeking a third term.
</P>
<P>
   Although the race is far from over, the Democratic lieutenant
governor, Gray Davis, is favored by voters in poll after poll over
Lungren, and there is unlikely to be a shift toward GOP candidates
elsewhere, including the Democratic-controlled Assembly and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the governor's office and the 120-member
Legislature were run by Democrats, Jerry Brown was governor and
Davis was his chief of staff. That does not escape Lungren, and
he's using it as a tactic on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long do you think it would take a Democratic governor with
a Democratic Legislature to turn back the clock to Jerry Brown
days?'' Lungren asked the Elk Grove crowd, which then groaned.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long do you think it would take to have them repopulate
our courts with judges like Rose Bird, who couldn't understand that
there was a difference between a criminal and a victim? ... I'll
tell you, it wouldn't take much time at all to do that, and we
cannot afford that,'' Lungren said. ``How long would it take for
them to raise taxes?''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lungren did not mention it, another important factor is
terrifying Republicans: After the 2000 census, California officials
must redraw the boundaries of every legislative district in the
state. With Democrats in control, party leaders and the governor
could reconfigure district boundaries in their favor, giving
Democrats a substantial advantage for at least a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats hold a 43-37 majority in the Assembly, and there are
23 Democrats, 16 Republicans and one independent in the Senate.
Although the Assembly was controlled by Republicans in 1995,
Democrats are considered to have a solid hold on the Senate. About
nine Assembly seats are tightly competitive this year, but
Democratic strategists say Davis' campaign is helping them.
</P>
<P>
   Only three Democrats have served as governor of California this
century, and two of them were father and son _ Pat Brown and Jerry
Brown. Culbert Olson served one term starting in 1938. But since
Jerry Brown left office in 1982, Republicans George Deukmejian and
Wilson have done battle with a Legislature mostly controlled by
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans admit they would like to run the
government, they say the issue is ``balance.'' Wilson and
Deukmejian used their powers to counteract the Legislature. Such a
divided government, the conventional wisdom goes, creates a more
reasonable approach to lawmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Republican leader Bill Leonard said he was in the
minority party when Jerry Brown was governor, and ``it was awful.''
Leonard, like Lungren, is worried that the compromises Democrats
made with Wilson in the past eight years could be overturned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be very worried that our welfare reforms would be watered
down and even repealed,'' Leonard said, ``that our movement toward
school accountability would stop, that our building of prisons and
getting tough on violent crime would stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard admitted that being in the minority might energize
Republicans, just as it did when Jerry Brown was governor. Being in
the minority might also allow the GOP to play havoc with the
state-budget process, because passing the spending plan takes a
two-thirds majority of both houses. That means Democrats would have
to compromise with Republicans no matter who is governor.
</P>
<P>
   But Lungren's argument that Davis will take California back to
the Jerry Brown days assumes that Davis is the same as Brown. A
popular GOP bumper sticker reads: ``Gray. Just another shade of
Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two men differ in many ways, not the least of which is
temperament. Brown, ready to take over in January as Oakland's
newly elected mayor, has dropped out of the Democratic Party. Davis
supports the death penalty and other tough-on-crime laws that Brown
does not.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has vowed moderation if he is elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm certainly going to live within the resources that the
economy provides,'' Davis said, ``and I'm going to lead this state
down a moderate path into the next century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
