<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSROOM-AFTERMATH-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY STRUGGLE TO PUT THEIR WORLD TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (retransmitting to correct dropped word in lede)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 Last of three parts  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, Alaska _ Overcome with guilt, Wilson Naneng for months
believed he should have prevented his friend Evan Ramsey from
bringing the shotgun to school.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of at least 10 students who had gathered in the
Bethel Regional High library that morning, following Evan's
suggestion that ``something really big'' was about to occur. He
then stood by in horror as Evan killed 15-year-old Josh Palacios
and principal Ron Edwards, wounded two other students, then
surrendered under fire from police in the school lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Wilson, a promising junior, began to find ways to
injure himself. He bit his hands raw, drew knives across his arms.
Finally, during the state academic decathlon meet in Anchorage, he
strung up his belt in a hotel room and attempted to commit suicide
before friends and supervisors intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt betrayed by Evan and I felt some guilt that I should
have stopped it,'' said Wilson, now an 18-year-old freshman at the
University of Alaska at Fairbanks. ``I felt as if I had been shot
myself. When I talked about Evan, it was like he was dead. I felt
like I had lost a brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson hardly recognized Evan that morning _ Feb. 19, 1997 _
``all raged, full of his hate that he had.'' His soul-searching was
shared by others in Bethel, and, in many ways, throughout the
state, as people sought to understand how such a crime could have
been committed in the sanctuary of a public school, by a boy whose
life was so embedded in his community.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that two 14-year-old friends had helped Evan plot the
murders, and that other students had failed to act on the dark
hints that emerged beforehand, made the crimes all the more tragic
and perplexing. The case provoked fundamental changes in the way
the school district addressed its most-troubled students, changed
the way Alaska looked at juvenile crime, and foreshadowed a
national debate about school violence as the shootings,
grotesquely, seemed to repeat themselves across the country in six
other nationally publicized episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we no longer have that innocence where school is the
safest place in the community,'' Alaska Governor Tony Knowles, who
spoke at Ron Edwards's memorial service, said in an interview. ``We
have lost that.''
</P>
<P>
   Evan, who was 16 when he committed the murders, is now 18. Tried
as an adult, convicted in February of two counts of first-degree
murder, and awaiting sentencing Dec. 1, he alternated between
convincing remorse and callous indifference during a series of
interviews inside the Cook Inlet Pre-Trial Facility in Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at one point if he wished he had committed suicide in the
school, as he said he'd intended, Evan said: ``I do, but I don't. I
do because I wouldn't have to deal with this: with the chains, with
having to worry about getting (stabbed) or having somebody sodomize
me. But then, this also gives me an opportunity to get a message
out: that what I did ain't right. All these teenagers in the Lower
48, for whatever reasons they pulled their killings, I don't think
that it is really right.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to his early child abuse and the harassment he endured
at school, he said: ``What I did was (expletive) up. I mean, I
killed two people. But then, there's also some (expletive) up
things that happened to me. I tried to go get help and nobody would
help, so I felt I had to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   But he was less apologetic when asked about the effect of the
crimes on friends and relatives of the victims: ``I think I've
(expletive) these people's lives up _ temporarily. And if they're
not (expletive) morons they'll get on with their life. What
happened was really screwed up, but that don't mean that they
should just stop living and stop doing what they were doing
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he &UR;  &LR; was angry at Edwards, Evan, sitting in shackles
and his red prison jumpsuit, said: ``I don't remember. I think it
was one of those little things. I thought he was a (expletive) but
not the kind of (expletive) that you'd really want to hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the losses of Edwards and Palacios are still felt
deeply in Bethel. A veteran educator, Edwards, 50, was so
passionate about Bethel Regional High and its students that, had he
lived, ``I think this would have devastated him,'' said Les
Daenzer, a district administrator who became interim principal
after the shootings. ``I think he would have quit.'' Friends find
it hard to believe that Edwards, a former marine and National
Guardsman who had served in Vietnam, was killed in his own school.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were to describe Ron in one word it would be `solid,'''
said Daenzer. A champion bodybuilder from Kalispell, Mont., Edwards
had risen through the ranks of the Lower Kuskokwim School District.
Before Bethel, he was principal in Kongiganak, a Yup'ik Eskimo
village of about 200 people. Conditions were so basic that Edwards
and his staff took showers at school. But within a few years he had
created one of the best-run programs in the district.
</P>
<P>
   At Bethel Regional, Edwards seemed to be everywhere at once:
running the lunch line, sitting in on classes, pushing papers,
picking up spare change, attending every sporting event and fawning
over his wife, Cindy, who was studying for her teaching certificate
and often substituted at the school. One of his unfulfilled dreams
was to see Ron Jr., the youngest son among his four children, play
baseball. His daughter, Meagan, was valedictorian the year after
his death.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards loved to hunt moose and pan for gold. He intermittently
worried about his weight: When friends cleared out his desk, they
found rice cakes and tuna in one compartment, mounds of candy in
another. At home, he would curl up in his favorite chair, announce
``the captain is in the command module,'' and watch Monday Night
Football. He was perhaps the biggest booster of the Bethel High
sports program, of which basketball, as in most schools in
hoops-crazed Alaska, is king.
</P>
<P>
   To many, Josh Palacios was the future of that program. A
sophomore, he already had made the eight-man varsity traveling
squad. He was 5 feet 4 inches tall and growing, dribbled well with
both hands, and was solidly built: He loved to flip up his T-shirt
to reveal his ``six-pack'' stomach to anyone willing to look or
touch. Half black, half Mexican-American, he was an exotic presence
in Bethel and girls found him attractive. His mother Claudia, a
women's health-care provider, put condoms in his Easter baskets. A
gifted artist, Josh once replicated a Van Gogh painting, which, he
wrote, ``symbolized a man sittin' and chillin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudia had moved her two sons, Josh and Corey, from Dallas to
Bethel after her marriage broke up in 1988. She wanted to be closer
to her mother, Linda, a nurse who had moved to escape inner-city
violence. Linda reached her breaking point one day when she pulled
a gun on a man who was tailing her on a Dallas freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the climate change, Josh's love of sports only deepened
in Bethel. He set up Nerf hoops all over the house to amuse himself
when it was too cold to play outside. ``In Bethel we had a rule
that the boys couldn't play outside if the wind-chill was minus-10
or below,'' said Linda. ``They'd be at home by themselves and
they'd call me up at work: `Grandma, it's only minus-9!' Josh would
get snow in his boots and his socks would freeze to the soles of
his feet. We had to put him in the bathtub with warm water to get
his feet out of his boots. And he had this short, nappy hair and
the snow would melt on his head and then it would freeze. It made
an ice cap on his head and he'd come in and you'd have to crack it
off his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated at an Anchorage restaurant, a few blocks from Josh's
grave, Linda and her daughter Claudia laughed, then cried. Josh had
so many friends that they all pitched in one year to send him to
basketball camp when it looked like he might not be able to afford
it. ``I can't tell you how many kids he brought over to our
house,'' said Claudia. ``It was never stray dogs, it was always
stray people.'' Josh, whose favorite NBA player was David Robinson
of the San Antonio Spurs, was buried in his Bethel Warriors
uniform. Claudia only wishes he had brought home Evan Ramsey one
day.
</P>
<P>
   Climate of harassment given intense scrutiny
</P>
<P>
   After the shootings, there was an outpouring of grief for both
Josh and Edwards. But those seeking change at Bethel Regional also
focused on the climate of harassment in which the murders took
place. Once the grief settled, the school board held a series of
emergency meetings. Task forces were assembled on everything from
cultural awareness to alcoholism to family values.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, meetings of the ``School Issues'' committee
were the most heavily attended. The committee looked at harassment,
violence, security, dropout rates, substance abuse, truancy, and
other issues. It made several recommendations, some of which were
implemented immediately. Bethel Regional added an unarmed security
guard who patrols the halls with a radio. The school repainted the
walls a brighter color, and stationed teachers in the hallways as
extra eyes and ears during class changes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (End of 1st take; 2nd take picks up ... The new principal)
</P>
</TEXT>
