<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FRIENDLY SEATTLE, US SENATE RACE GETS MEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This is a city so friendly that strangers inquire if
you've had a good breakfast, and cabbies won't charge for a short
hop.
</P>
<P>
   This is a place so mellow that it created the US version of
espresso bars and made them as common around Puget Sound as salmon
on the menu and Microsoft millionaires.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, this is also the site of one of the season's
meanest Senate races, a bare-knuckles brawl between two diminutive,
middle-aged women with clashing personalities and wildly opposing
views on everything from gay rights to gun control, abortion to
affirmative action, free trade to taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst for such an unlikely confrontation in this
picturesque part of the Pacific Northwest is US Representative
Linda Smith, a two-term Republican from Vancouver in the
southwestern corner of Washington state and perhaps the most
contrarian, in-your-face conservative in Congress. She defied state
party elders and trounced their preferred candidate, a moderate
with lots of money, in last month's primary. Now her sights are
firmly set on denying a second term to Senator Patty Murray, a
liberal Democrat from the Seattle suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who campaigned six years ago as a sweet ``mom in tennis
shoes,'' isn't running scared in the only all-female Senate race in
the nation and just the third such matchup in US history. Neither a
novice nor soft-spoken now, Murray has raised far more money than
Smith to saturate the airwaves with negative TV advertising, and
recent polls show her with a comfortable, double-digit lead going
into Tuesday's election.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith, a former state legislator, has a history of ambushing
complacent opponents and outwitting the oddsmakers. In 1994 she won
the Republican primary as a write-in candidate, and in 1996 she was
declared dead until absentee ballots gave her an 887-vote victory
over her Democratic challenger.
</P>
<P>
   In this midterm contest, clouded by the Clinton scandal in the
other Washington, a combination of low Democratic turnout and a
crusade to go to the polls by Smith's energized army of Christian
conservatives and Ross Perot populists could upset both Murray and
conventional wisdom. The gender war some expected is more a
sideshow than an issue. In this state, which has more women
legislators than any other and a long tradition of electing females
statewide, a woman vs. woman race isn't a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Smith can win,'' said Dale Foreman, state GOP
chairman. ``The woman is a powerful blend of charisma and chutzpah,
and she has always been underestimated.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the gates of the University of Washington's football
stadium on a drizzly homecoming Saturday, Smith worked the
60,000-plus crowd in what any other candidate would welcome as an
easy campaign stop. But just like the hometown Huskies, who eked
out a 35-34 win over Oregon State, the prickly GOP underdog was
here for a fight.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, Smith was debating a young teacher about her plan
to wipe out most of the US Education Department. She shook a finger
at a military veteran who thought Murray had a better record on
protecting his benefits. She argued with an African-American man
about a state ballot initiative she favors that would end education
and hiring preferences for minorities and women. ``You're
competent, I'll bet,'' said Smith, suggesting to the carpenter that
he might not have been hired because of affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   And after several minutes of hurling trade and employment
statistics at a Democrat who disagreed with her opposition to
raising the minimum wage, Smith told the man his views were ``a
bunch of crap.'' ``You've got a philosophical problem,'' Smith told
him, as local TV cameras rolled. ``Why don't you go campaign for
Patty Murray?''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who went straight from high school to marriage and then
into a career running a chain of H&AMP;R Block offices, later
explained, ``You've got to stick your neck out. These people are
going to get me for the next six years, so they'd better know who I
am.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray's aim is also to define Smith, but as an extremist with a
protectionist agenda who is out of step with this socially
tolerant, trade-dependent state. So far, spending records show, the
incumbent has been successful convincing executives at Boeing and
Microsoft that she is the safe choice. Her task this week before
the election seems more daunting: to rally traditional Democrats to
go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a crowded labor-union hall in Tacoma last weekend, Murray
blended in with the audience that whipped into chants of ``Patty,
Patty, Patty'' when she said nothing less than the education of
their children, their Social Security, their abortion rights, and
their jobs were at risk if they sent Smith to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patty isn't glitz and glitter. She is one of us. She
understands working people, families, and people getting by on
$20,000 or $30,000 a year,'' said Pat Hunter, a forklift operator
and a member of the Teamsters local. ``Linda Smith, she has her own
agenda, and I think she is mean-spirited.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray, 48, who grew up in a working-class family and went to a
state college, cultivated a down-to-earth, political outsider image
in her 1992 campaign. A former education activist and state
senator, Murray also capitalized on being a woman in an election
year when many voters were sour on men in the Senate for their
clumsy handling of the sexual harassment allegations against
Supreme Court nominee Clarence Thomas. She won the open seat with
surprising ease.
</P>
<P>
   Constituents who initially thought Murray was very nice but not
too sharp say she has matured into an effective, attentive senator.
Aides tick off a string of legislative achievements _ sponsoring
the bill that just produced federal funds for 30,000 new teachers _
and boast that she can bring home plenty of bacon as a member of
the powerful Senate Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who won't take money from political action committees,
accuses Murray of becoming too cozy with special interests and
pledging her allegiance to liberal leaders like Senator Edward M.
Kennedy instead of state voters.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who has ducked all but one debate, dismisses Smith as
desperate. ``I know who I am _ I'm someone who's grown over six
years, I've accomplished a lot, and I've become a real asset to my
state,'' Murray said after attending services at Seattle's
predominantly black Mount Zion Baptist Church. ``But that doesn't
mean I'm not still a mom in tennis shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   In a state that prides itself on independence _ 25 percent of
the voters backed Perot in 1992 _ Smith wears hers like a badge of
honor. In Congress, she drives House GOP leaders to distraction by
refusing to back their budget and tax bills for fear the measures
won't protect Social Security, and out of human rights concerns she
won't go along with free-trade measures, even when pro-business
Republicans beg. She refused to support Newt Gingrich's reelection
as House speaker in 1997, and she called for the president's
impeachment long before anyone knew about his recent extramarital
affair.
</P>
<P>
   But it was her backing of legislation to overhaul the campaign
finance laws that really got her into hot water with her party. The
Senate Republican Campaign Committee, which could have given Smith
more than $500,000 toward her race, has withheld almost all of it,
Smith said, because its chairman, Senator Mitch McConnell of
Kentucky, is angry at her for calling him someone ``who likes the
laundering of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed when Smith made a media issue of it, the Republican
National Committee last week gave her campaign $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like Linda Smith precisely because people who pull the
strings in the Republican Party don't like her,'' said Mark
Ingersoll, an insurance salesman waving a Smith sign at the
football stadium. ``She's not a lap dog like her opponent. She
speaks her mind, sticks to her principles, and won't buckle
under.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, Smith picked up Ingersoll's toddler, aptly named
Reagan, and planted a kiss on her cheek. The 48-year-old candidate
said she misses her six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, it can't be about who's the best mom in the race,''
said Smith. ``It's about two very different views of how the
country should look, and which woman is best able to move us
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
