<SLUG> BC-RHODEISLAND-KENNEDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRICK KENNEDY HELPS HIMSELF WHILE HELPING OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Representative Patrick Kennedy campaigned earlier this week in
Fort Worth, nearly 2,000 miles and a time zone away from his Rhode
Island district.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is spending the days before the election helping other
Democrats and simultaneously helping himself land a slot on the
powerful House Appropriations Committee and a leadership post as
chairman of the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   A congressman up for reelection usually sticks close to his
district the week before an election, but a recent Brown University
poll showed that Kennedy held a 53-point lead over his Republican
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, by the time he returns home Thursday to East
Providence, he will have completed a two-week campaign swing for 20
different Democrats running for various offices around the country.
In the past year, Kennedy raised $1.5 million for more than 40
Democratic House candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kennedy is basically going prime-time now, which is exactly
what people thought he would do,'' said Darrell M. West, a Brown
University political scientist and pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, 31, the youngest of Senator Edward M. Kennedy's three
children, has emerged as a top contender for the campaign committee
job because of his fund-raising skill and his friendship with House
Democratic leader Richard Gephardt, aides to Gephardt say. He is
one of the most requested speakers on the congressional ``rubber
chicken'' circuit.
</P>
<P>
   While flying from Las Vegas to Fort Worth Tuesday morning, he
practiced saying, ``We need your vote'' in Spanish. After
campaigning for Representative Martin Frost of Texas, the current
chairman of the Democratic campaign committee, Kennedy stumped for
two Hispanic candidates running in San Antonio-area districts,
Charlie Gonzalez, and Ciro Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he began his campaign day at a Mass in Moline, Ill.,
with a Democratic House candidate. He then flew to Chicago,
Philadelphia and Las Vegas. The day before, he campaigned in Green
Bay, Wis., for freshman Representative Jay Johnson. The candidate
resurrected some old ``Kennedy-Johnson'' campaign signs from the
1960 presidential campaign and crowed that the ``ticket'' had been
reunited.
</P>
<P>
   While Kennedy has not ruled out running for the Senate in 2000
if Rhode Island's Republican Senator John Chafee retires, he is
focusing on his role in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the biggest draw we have in the caucus in terms of
campaigning requests,'' said Laura Nichols, a spokeswoman for
Gephardt.
</P>
<P>
   His Rhode Island critics make an issue of his absences from the
state, and Kennedy acknowledges the concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically for me, my life would be a lot easier if I spent
every weekend in Rhode Island,'' he said. ``But I have a feeling
that my district is starting to appreciate what I am doing. They
elected me in some measure because of my last name and the
connections I promised I could make on their behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   His priority for the 106th Congress that begins in January is to
be named to the House Appropriations Committee. But he is also a
front-runner for the high-profile campaign committee job because of
his willingness to stump for Democrats and because of his
friendship with Gephardt, who selects the chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt emerged as his patron soon after Kennedy entered the
House four years ago as its then-youngest member. They formed a
joint fund-raising committee several years ago, and Kennedy has
become one of Gephardt's staunchest supporters.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely combination of conservative Democrats in the House
and labor union lobbyists have floated the idea of splitting the
chairmanship of the congressional campaign committee into two jobs.
Representatives Nancy Pelosi of California and Sherrod Brown of
Ohio are frequently mentioned as candidates, along with Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy would like to head the committee, but he is also willing
to share the spot with Pelosi and would step aside for her is there
is just one chairman and no other women are chosen for House
leadership roles.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials, however, say Kennedy is a strong contender
whether one or two people head the campaign committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick is a celebrity. He was born into that,'' said Loretta
Bowen, an official of the Communication Workers of America, who
favors the double-chairman idea. ``So why not take advantage of
that?''
</P>
</TEXT>
