<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
THE CORRUPTION OF SCHOOL CHOICE 
</HEADLINE>
 JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Annette Polly Williams knew in 1990 that giving
birth to school choice guaranteed a bitter custody fight for her
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew from the beginning that white Republicans and rich,
right-wing foundations that praised me and used me to validate
their agenda would do it only as long as it suited their needs,''
Williams said. ``I knew that once they figured they didn't need me
as a black cover, they would try to take control of vouchers and
use them for their own selfish interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee is the site of one of the nation's most highly watched
school choice programs. It is being watched partly because it is
one of the few programs that originated with African-American
support. Williams, a 10-term Democratic state representative and a
fierce advocate for low-income African-American youth, created
vouchers in an alliance with Republican Governor Tommy Thompson and
a Republican-led state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Williams did so out of frustration with a nationally maligned
public school system where the black male grade average was a D and
parents screamed for change. Williams wrote legislation that
allowed 1,500 low-income students to attend private, secular
schools on state money that comes to about $5,000 per child.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify, a family had to have an income no greater than 1.75
times the poverty line, or about $23,000 for a family of three. In
1995, in a move that has been appealed by civil liberties groups to
the US Supreme Court, the state expanded the program to allow up to
15,000 students to use vouchers for religious as well as secular
private schools. There are 104,000 students in the Milwaukee public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best way I could come up with to give low-income
families the same choices as a middle-class family,'' Williams
said. ``In my mind, this was not abandoning the public schools.
I've always felt that no more than, say, 25 percent of public
school students should have access to vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``More kids are always going to attend public schools. This was
something to put a little power in the hands of parents, the same
power that parents in the suburbs have to decide where their
children can go to school. I had hoped to nudge the public schools
themselves to respond to the challenge and work harder to keep
parents from wanting vouchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever power those low-income families have had is under
threat. In August, Mayor John Norquist set off shock waves by
saying choice should be expanded to all families.
</P>
<P>
   Norquist's director of communications, Jeff Fleming, said the
mayor has no intention of taking choice from low-income families.
Fleming said universal choice would help keep middle- and
upper-class families from fleeing Milwaukee because of the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hearing compelling stories like a woman who was $200
over the income cap but had to spend thousands of dollars to keep
her kids in private school,'' Fleming said. ``We're trying to think
about this in terms of a GI grant for students to use to select
where they feel they will receive a quality education.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said ``universal'' choice means white choice. She said
that wealthier will use their privileges, such as having more spare
time to game the system, to grab the first spots in private
schools. There is evidence for her fear. Cambridge, Mass., has
universal controlled choice, but privileged white families are
disproportionately clustered in the most desirable schools.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said there will be room for all, especially since only
6,000 of the 15,000 slots are expected to be used this year.
Williams does not buy that for the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is why most black groups like the NAACP are against
vouchers,'' Williams said, ``because without the income cap, choice
just becomes a free-market program that keeps richer families happy
and Catholic and Lutheran schools solvent with state money without
any commitment to improve public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   To head off calls for universal access, Williams is considering
raising the cap to $35,000 for a family of four. So far, Governor
Thompson still stands by the income cap. Other legislators say the
voucher system has not been analyzed enough for its effectiveness
to expand it to everyone. The state's black legislative caucus has
urged its colleagues not to lift the cap.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Supreme Court upholds the use of state-funded
vouchers for private schools, Williams is concerned that
middle-class families will press hard to become eligible for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people in the voucher crowd exploit low-income black
children, saying we are creating vouchers for them when what they
really have in mind is bringing in a Trojan horse,'' Williams said.
``They can say what they want, but I've never seen a situation
where low-income people, when they have to compete in education
with people with far more resources, come out equal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1454EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
