<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1439 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-28 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POLITICAL `PLEASANTVILLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Pleasantville'' is not a profound experience,
but moviegoers will likely talk about it. Like ``Forrest Gump'' and
``The Truman Show,'' it serves up digestible philosophical musings
amid seamless special effects.
</P>
<P>
   In this respect, the movie resembles California politics. As 15
million registered voters in the Golden State decide whether or not
to vote, they confront a political landscape that resembles
``Pleasantville.'' The surface is slick and relentlessly pleasant,
but underneath, the plot can be stiff, stark, and anxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, I'm home!'' William H. Macy exclaims throughout the
movie, mocking the signature of black-and-white situtation
comedies. ``The Adventures of Ozzie and Harriet,'' ``Leave It to
Beaver,'' and others graced a pristine landscape in which art
imitated life and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, that much-parodied decade, two cultural and
political forces grew up together. Suburbia and television were
powerful adolescents, and California helped mold them both. The
Hollywood Freeway's opening in 1954 was a cultural and political
event, a plastic festival of crabgrass and conformity. All roads
lead to the Pleasantville that television producers imagine was the
national heart's desire. When American husbands in the 1950s said,
``Honey, I'm home!'' they inhabited a virtual San Fernando valley,
America's dream suburb, where television antennae sprouted like
dandelions.
</P>
<P>
   The major candidates for governor are 1950s archetypes. Democrat
Gray Davis, born in 1942, and Republican Dan Lungren, born in 1946,
are alike in ambition and different in ideology. They are no worse
or better than candidates in most other states, but they confront
the historic antipathy of Californians toward politics.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicious since the Gold Rush of anything that hemmed in people
or curbed their acquisitiveness, Californians have built barriers
to politics. The robber barons of railroad and mining interests
bought the Legislature 100 years ago, leading to the birth of the
progressive movement. Hiram Johnson, the revered governor and
longtime senator, was Theodore Roosevelt's running mate on the
Progressive Party ticket in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was also a glum, un-Californian skeptic who could have
been the political boss in ``Pleasantville,'' brilliantly portrayed
by the late J.T. Walsh in one of his final performances. Johnson
demanded a republic of virtue and used the ballot referendum to
thwart railroad barons.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, special interests can concoct a grass-roots
campaign of instant artificial turf to sway the masses for and
against ballot questions. The grimmest black-and-white tableau in
politics today is the official 127-page voter information guide,
the Pleasantville white pages, a trackless waste of trivialities
and demagoguery.
</P>
<P>
   Californians decide 10 questions Tuesday, including whether ``to
prohibit the sale of horsemeat for food for human consumption.''
What hath Hiram Johnson wrought?
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Goodwin Knight and Pat Brown, genial optimists of
different parties, governed California with a gospel of growth and
built what would later be called ``infrastructure.'' They were
succeeded in Sacramento by Ronald Reagan and Jerry Brown, another
bipartisan duo with captivating personalities whose optimism was
tempered by what the younger Brown called ``an era of limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the economy is roaring loudly enough to mute politics.
Prosperity has banished identity-politics controversy, with no
emotionally divisive ballot questions. This election is not as
exciting as ``Pleasantville,'' which evokes ``Singin' in the
Rain,'' with touches of D.W. Griffith, Leni Reifenstahl, and even
John Madden.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pleasantville, where it never rains, the weather diminishes
the zest for politics that enlivens East Coast Novembers. Election
day forecast for most Californians: sublime. This does not
guarantee a big turnout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
