<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DARKNESS OF LA. PRISON, WRITER SEES REDEMPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A maximum security prison filled with murderers, rapists and
armed robbers would seem an odd place to go looking for God. But it
was precisely his desire to find evidence of the divine in the
grimmest of places that drove Daniel Bergner to spend a year at
Angola, Louisiana's infamous penitentiary. Bergner turned his
experiences into a recently published book.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, after witnessing both the degradation and the
brutish behavior of the inmates, the New York City author and
journalist did not come away with a soothing affirmation of God's
power.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he came away with a more complex appreciation of the
possibility of redemption for even the most heinous acts and the
indomitability of the human spirit in the worst conditions. And
what started out as an article for Harper's Magazine chronicling
Angola's annual inmate rodeo evolved into a book, ``God of the
Rodeo: The Search for Hope, Faith, and a Six-Second Ride in
Louisiana's Angola Prison.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways Angola is the ultimate proving ground of the
human spirit,'' said Bergner, sitting in an overstuffed chair at
the John Jeffries House on Beacon Hill during a recent visit to
Boston. ``This may sound strange, but I was trying to find some
kind of comforting parable within a place that was just so
dispiriting. How did these convicts construct their lives in a
place that doesn't offer them any hope whatsoever?''
</P>
<P>
   Angola, in a remote corner of Louisiana, is a hauntingly
beautiful place, a vast expanse of lush fields home to 2,000 cattle
and hundreds of horses, and surrounded on three sides by the
Mississippi River. It also is a place where 80 percent of the 5,000
inmates will never leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it's not a walled prison, as soon as you drive in
the air feels different. It feels thick with ugliness,'' said
Bergner, 38, dressed casually in a dark sport jacket, black top,
khaki pants and black leather shoes. ``It is a place of
overwhelming destruction. The destruction of the lives of the
inmates' victims and their families. The destruction that the
inmates have done to their own lives. You wouldn't think it's a
place where there could be any possibility of some kind of
mysterious, divine power.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even the inmates' rodeo, which Bergner portrays as a cruel
and even inhumane exploitation of prisoners, had a transcendent
quality.
</P>
<P>
   The annual event, held every Sunday in October, recruits inmates
who have no experience with horses or bulls, to ride bucking
broncos and dodge flailing bull horns in front of a paying public.
Inevitably, there are a rash of injuries _ broken bones,
concussions, bloody gashes. A handful have been paralyzed after
being stomped by a bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeals to our worst instincts and impulses,'' Bergner
says. ``A need to see human beings bashed and broken and to
separate ourselves from `sinners' who we can look down at for
willing to be fools for our entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   But, on the other hand, the more he thought about it and the
more he talked with rodeo competitors, Bergner came to another
view. As he wrote in the February issue of Harper's: ``Get hit, get
stomped, get broken, get gored, bleed. What other means of
redemption had there ever been from the most terrible sins?
</P>
<P>
   ``These men had killed, they had raped, at best they had put
guns to other people's heads. Here was original sin, the loss of
God's spirit in the garden. ... And here, as in some vestigial and
distorted Passion, these men, sin's representatives, had arrived at
the place where they would offer up their bodies for purging.''
</P>
<P>
   So even in a spectacle ugly and vulgar, Bergner says he found
signs of God's grace: redemption.
</P>
<P>
   Bergner, a Jew, is neither pious nor naive. His parents, one a
doctor, the other a sociologist, disdained religion as an obstacle
to progress. Yet perhaps, Bergner suggests, in a sign of
generational rebellion, he is a believer. ``Religion is an
emotional need for me,'' Bergner said.
</P>
<P>
   And it is his constant wrestling with issues of faith, a quest
to discern the divine that permeates Bergner's honest and painful
portrayal of Angola.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't any miracles at Angola, Bergner finds. He does meet
Littell Harris, an armed robber who left Angola after 15 years and
is now a cross-country truck driver. It's one of the few success
stories he discovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of what I took away from Angola is that we may be
absolutely right to take such total control of lives,'' Bergner
says. ``But it is the closest position we take to playing God. If
we're going to take that role we better think of it as sacred, and
we better watch over people the same way we would want God to look
over us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Comments may be sent to The Spiritual Life, c/o Diego
Ribadeneira, Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; or via e-mail to
religion(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
