<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT THE CIVICS LESSON WE'D HOPED FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN McNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is not easy to teach your sons a civics lesson when
they have their fingers in their ears.
</P>
<P>
   My colleague, Joan Vennochi, and I had the best of intentions
when we asked her son, Nicholas, 9, and my son, Patrick, 10, to
accompany us to the last debate of the Massachusetts gubernatorial
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   We had planned to show them democracy in action. Instead, we
took them to a street fight. Who would have imagined that two boys,
one of whom I happen to know mastered his multiplication tables to
the blare of a boombox, would complain not that politics is too
boring, but that it is too loud?
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before the lights dimmed, Senator Edward M. Kennedy had
asked the boys to glance around the hall and to appreciate where
they were: ``Some of the greatest issues in our country's history _
the American Revolution, the Civil War, the right of women to vote
_ they were all debated right here where you are standing tonight.
It is why we are all so proud to be from Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   That was an easier sell at 7 p.m., Senator, than it was at 8
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At a post-debate repast of pasta and Coca-Cola, Nicholas and
Patrick both had pounding headaches and a few reasonable questions
for Paul Cellucci and Scott Harshbarger: Why were you yelling when
you were standing right next to each other? Didn't anyone ever tell
you it's rude to interrupt? Why didn't you answer the questions
instead of saying ``take the pledge,'' ``tell the truth,'' ``our
crumbling schools,'' ``no new taxes'' over and over again?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, and who was Lincoln Douglas, anyway _ a boxer?
</P>
<P>
   An understandable mistake, given the moderator's hands-off
approach to the slugfest Monday night. ``This is the
Lincoln-Douglas portion of the debate,'' shrugged Harvard Law
professor Charles Ogletree, suggesting that the names of the two
political legends were synonymous with anarchy, not oratory.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln-Douglas format means that candidates address one
another directly, without reporters acting as intermediaries. That
bears only a marginal resemblance to what happened in 1858 when
Abraham Lincoln and Stephen Douglas engaged in seven debates during
their campaign for the US Senate in Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas was 45, a two-term incumbent Democrat being challenged
by Lincoln, 49, a Republican former congressman. Lincoln had
prodded Douglas to debate him in a desperate bid to call attention
to his longshot candidacy. He asked only ``perfect reciprocity, and
no more. I wish as much time as you, and that conclusions shall
alternate. That is all.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, time was a different commodity in the 19th century.
Each debate lasted for three hours. An hour-long speech was
followed by a 90-minute rebuttal, which was followed, in turn, by a
30-minute rejoinder. That culture, too, bore little similarity to
our own. Politics was a preoccupation of Everyman. Those who had
the vote, exercised it. The debates took place across Illinois,
often in open fields under threatening skies. Still, thousands
came.
</P>
<P>
   The debates _ all of them about slavery _ occurred one year
after the Supreme Court's Dred Scott decision said blacks could
never be citizens. Douglas argued that each new territory should
decide whether to sanction human bondage; Lincoln argued that
slavery should not be extended into new states. Reprinted by
newspapers across the country, the debates ignited a national
conversation about an issue that would soon divide the nation.
</P>
<P>
   All was not high-minded, however. The debates were entertainment
for the masses, as well. There were picnics and torchlight parades.
Lincoln's supporters escorted him to one debate in a wagon drawn by
six white horses. Douglas's partisans brought a brass cannon to
each debate to fire whenever their candidate ``hit'' his opponent.
Newspapers dubbed the short, squat Douglas ``The Little Giant,''
and the tall, gaunt Lincoln, ``Honest Abe.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln historian Harold Holzer writes in his introduction to
the texts of the debates that audiences hooted and jeered when the
candidates ``attacked each other and defended themselves with
biting humor, bitter sarcasm, and hellish fury...''
</P>
<P>
   That much, anyway, sounds familiar. ``I think I'd rather listen
to Paul Cellucci and Scott Harshbarger yell for one hour than talk
for three hours,'' Nicholas decided. Patrick had to agree.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't exactly the civics lesson their moms had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara is a globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
