<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1455 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERSONAL-ADS-WRITER-B     10-28 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-ADS-WRITER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE LONELY: ADJECTIVES FOR HIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Her own personal ad might read something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Trim, creative, green-eyed WF. Forties. Successful business
owner. Enjoys Paris, hiking, and fine wines. Seeks D/SFs and D/SMs
from late 30s through 60s who desire a lasting relationship but
can't write a personal advertisement that doesn't mention walking
on the beach or sitting in front of a roaring fire. Come to my
place and let's talk.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; And so they do, shlepping up three flights of narrow stairs to
the light-filled top floor of Susan Fox's Boston duplex
condominium. They come in search of Mr. or Ms. Right, and it is
Fox's job to make them sound downright irresistible. As a
professional ghostwriter of personal ads, she will not only
describe most of her clients as trim (a must for the women) or
professional (de rigueur for the men), but will let loose a
fusillade of adjectives that no reader in search of a relationship
could possibly withstand: passionate, witty, romantic, warm,
curious, resourceful, articulate, supportive, sophisticated,
expressive, outgoing, attentive, forthright, sincere ...
</P>
<P>
   Alas, such perfection does not guarantee that someone with
similar traits will reply. ``I tell my clients, `You're gonna have
to kiss some frogs,''' says the 47-year-old Fox. ``Well, maybe not
kiss them. But at least look at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who runs a small company called Personals Work, has been
coaching her single and ``re-singled'' clients for six years. The
majority, she says, are widowed or divorced; they're trying, as she
likes to put it, ``to get back up on the horse.'' They range in age
from their late 30s through their 60s, meaning that a lasting
relationship is more important to them than keeping raging hormones
at bay. About two-thirds of them are women, about 95 percent are
straight. Some have tried personal ads and failed, others are
newbies. Most are professionals, preferring to advertise in the
likes of Harvard Magazine and Cruising World. (It's a sailing
magazine.) And they are willing to pay Fox from $325 to $450 for
her services in addition to their advertising costs.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it's not like they have a lot of options besides
personal ads, the 1960s alternative that has become throughly
mainstream. ``One client who's in her 50s asked me, `What else am I
gonna do? Sit in Star Market and wait for someone to walk by?'''
Fox says.
</P>
<P>
   And, hey, personals worked for Susan Fox. Nine years ago, the
onetime therapist, freelance writer, and independent radio producer
sat down with a couple of friends and wrote an advertisement for
herself (``Something about having lots of frequent flyer miles,''
she recalls). She was divorced, a recent engagement had fallen
through, and she was asking herself if she was desperate enough to
try the personals to the tune of $1,200. Result: meetings with 31
different guys over 10 months, from a taxi driver to an MIT
administrator. She chose the latter, Rick Hill, who is today a
computer consultant and her husband. She found a new career, too.
</P>
<P>
   You might think that anyone could compose a personal
advertisement, but Fox might disagree. She also might recite some
of the cliches found in many ads: pretty, blonde, 39; likes movies,
hiking, beaches, and sitting in front of the fire; seeks
successful, handsome man, 39-45. ``Well, just who is this woman?''
Fox laments. ``We know nothing about her except she likes movies,
hiking, beaches, and fires. We know she thinks she's pretty. And we
know she wants what everybody else wants. There's no meat there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox thinks personal ads should tell a kind a story, and the ones
she writes tend to speak of, say, small-town roots, the love of a
good Bordeaux, or dreams of a second home in Maine. Still, that
doen't mean you can't do it yourself, and she offers five
suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _Start with a list of the qualities you're seeking, as well as a
list of your own qualities. ``If you don't know, ask your
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   _Don't make your ad too brief. ``The whole psychology of this is
that people tend to respond to ads that paint complete portraits.''
</P>
<P>
   _Don't get too cute. ```Juliet seeks Romeo' not only falls flat.
It also brings out the weirdos.''
</P>
<P>
   _Write mostly about yourself, not what you're seeking.
``Unfortunately, most people use about two-thirds of their copy to
describe what they're after, not who they are.''
</P>
<P>
   _Avoid cliches. ``OK, you can say you like beaches. But try to
add some interests with substance. Like philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's clients may have played the dating game in the past, but
the rules have changed since many of them took the field. ``They
never had to face AIDS, for one thing,'' she says. ``Also, women
today have to understand that they're allowed to take a more active
role in a relationship, to be the pursuer instead of being passive.
And they have to realize that going out means going somewhere of
mutual interest, not simply being picked up and taken somewhere. My
mother used to tell me when I went out, `Pretend to be interested
in what he's interested in.' But that's not true anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's apparently someone out there for everyone. Fox
recalls a woman in her mid-40s who came to her with a weight
problem. (``Men are hung up on weight,'' Fox says. ``It's audacious
and it's shallow. But it's true.'') The client also had very
specific demands: She wanted a man who was Jewish, had never been
married, had no children, and had never, ever lived with a woman.
``It seemed impossible, but she found him,'' Fox recalls. ``And he
liked overweight women, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Some folks get what they don't need, however _ like the woman
who received a reply to her ad from her ex-husband. But the real
downside is rejection. ``You really need ego strength for this,''
Fox advises, recalling one client who, after several promising
telephone conversations with a man who had replied to her ad,
finally met him for a day. ``He didn't like her,'' she says. ``She
was devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 60- to 90-minute interview that Fox says she conducts
before she puts word processor to paper, she tells her clients to
separate the ``non-negotiables'' they're seeking from their ``wish
list.'' Pies in the sky should definitely not be on the menu, even
in a world where everyone is described in flawless terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``People looking for the perfect prince or princess,'' says
Susan Fox, ``had better stop looking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1502EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1472 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN UPDIKE'S UN-BETTER ANGEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My writer pal William Novak and I were discussing the reviews of
John Updike's new novel, ``Bech at Bay.'' ``It sounds
irresistible,'' Novak said. I have to admit he was right.
</P>
<P>
   Why irresistible? Well, for one thing here's a Pennsylvania
Lutheran, exiled on the featureless North Shore, kvetching about
the writing life in the voice of a lapsed Manhattan Jew. Updike is
notoriously gracious; his creation Bech is a jerk. Updike is
famously prolific. Bech is generally blocked. While Updike worries
out loud about the promises of the Christian afterlife, the
fictional Bech, now 74, has more down-to-earth concerns: He wants
to know where the next erection is coming from.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Abraham Lincoln (himself paraphrasing William
Seward; that's the kind of faux, showy erudition Bech would
simultaneously abominate and envy), Bech is the un-better angel of
Updike's nature. One could make the case that writers are not very
nice people. Paul Theroux has just written a whole book to settle
some ancient score with V.S. Naipaul. Philip Roth has devoted the
better part of a novel to trashing his ex-wife, supposedly payback.
To argue the writers-as-bad-people case, Henry Bech would be
Exhibit A.
</P>
<P>
   Better than most, Bech can describe the impossible anxiety that
attends a friend's success. A literary enemy's triumph is cause for
apoplexy. An enemy's death is cause for celebration. In the latest
book, the protagonist's 26-year-old lover looks on
uncomprehendingly while Bech revels in the obituary of the
once-powerful critic Lucas Mishner. ``The thought of him dead
filled Bech with creamy ease,'' Updike writes.
</P>
<P>
   Bech can quote verbatim from negative reviews _ what writer
can't? _ and, in the story ``Bech Noir,'' takes steps to eliminate
the authors of ``these insults, these hurled mud balls, these
stains on the robe of his reputation, (these) bleeding wounds.''
Although some writers feign to shun praise, on this subject as on
others, Bech is more unbuttoned than most: ``One appetite that had
not diminished with the years was for unambiguous, blood-raw
superlatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, Updike is asked how much he resembles Bech. He
dismisses the question with a quip and a smile. But he does drop
hints. On the first page of the first of the three Bech books,
written 30 years ago, Bech complains to his chronicler that he has
been rendered as ``something Waspish, theological, scared, and
insulatingly ironical, that derives, my wild surmise is, from
you.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men have been close in the past. In 1971 and 1981,
Updike submitted to lengthy, satisfyingly opaque (from the author's
point of view) interviews by Bech, published in The New York Times
Book Review. They share an interest in sex, ``that hint of eternal
life,'' as Bech calls it, and have both been scorned as
women-haters. Beloved by critics, Bech, like Updike, had to write a
``triumphantly sleazy best-seller'' called ``Couples,'' sorry,
``Think Big,'' to find a mass audience.
</P>
<P>
   Although outwardly cordial, Bech has at least once expressed
reservations about his colleague and creator. ``At bottom, (Bech)
didn't like any of his contemporaries' work,'' we learn. ``O'Hara,
Hersey, Cheever, Updike _ suburbanites all living safe while art's
inner city disintegrated. And that was just the Johns.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week I saw Updike read from ``Bech at Bay,'' and he plainly
delighted in his altered ego's fumbling explorations of life in the
material world. ``The purpose of the writer is to amuse himself,''
Bech once told an interviewer, and he clearly succeeds in amusing
Updike, as well as Updike's readers.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of what reads like the final Bech book, Updike grants
Bech not only the Nobel Prize for Literature, but something even
more valuable _ the secret of life digested down to two tiny
letters. (Hint: They're not ``o'' and ``m.'') You'll have to read
it for yourself; I suspect you'll find it irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
