<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-GHOSTS-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWTOWN GHOST STORIES: WHERE THE QUEST BEGINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Ghosts haunt Texas theaters, restaurants,
old homes and graveyards. The apparitions include dog, weeping
women, treasure guardians, hitchhikers and laughing children, as
well as women, usually in blue, who float in doorways and men who
stomp up staircases, sometimes yelling out the news of their
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   So say two Houston Chronicle reporters, modern-day ghostbusters
of sorts who set out to report just-the-facts, ma'am, on modern-day
horror tales in Texas cities. Richard Stewart, the Chronicle's East
Texas bureau chief, and Allan Turner, a roving state reporter,
applied their skills to the search for specters. What did they
find? That they, too, believe in ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Transparent Tales: An Attic Full of Texas Ghosts,''
scheduled for publication by Best of East Texas Press in
mid-November (with statewide distribution through Eakin Press), the
authors share the firsthand stories of businesspeople and lawyers,
university professors, homeowners, a gravedigger and a mother, all
of whom said they have had close encounters of the phantom kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we specifically set out to do was trace down people who
said these things happened to them, and interview them,'' Turner
says. ``We went in with open minds. We came away convinced that
things occur that defy logical explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of Halloween, Turner and Stewart agreed to share a
couple of Fort Worth ghost stories, condensed from their book:
</P>
<P>
   THE GHOST OF BARBER'S BOOKS: Step into the cool, dim recesses of
Barber's Books in a nondescript brick building over on Eighth
Street, and you could be in the 19th century. Sweetly redolent of
aging paper, the Fort Worth store's interior is a tonic for the
senses. Books stacked in disorderly rows line obscure nooks and
crannies. ...
</P>
<P>
   Presiding over the atmospheric chaos is Brian Perkins, who long
ago decided thaty the way to battle discount megachains was to
retreat from the dog-eat-dog world of new-book sales to a
gentlemanly trade in out-of-prints.
</P>
<P>
   Such a place should have a resident ghost. And it does.
</P>
<P>
   Brian and his wife, Larue, have heard a distinct, loud clomping
on the old wooden stairway leading to the third floor. And so have
their employees. ``I lost one worker over it,'' Brian said. ``It
sounded like a 200-pound man walking up the steps in heavy boots.
It was loud and clear. There's no way it was just the building
creaking.''
</P>
<P>
   When Brian bought Barber's, a venerable Fort Worth institution,
in 1960, he found that the landlord had sealed the door to the
third floor with steel plates. Brian unsealed the door to convert
the third floor to a display area. He found 17 rooms, the remnants
of an old walk-up hotel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For much of the building's life _ it was erected in 1908 _ the
third floor had been a fixture in downtown Fort Worth's flourishing
red-light district.
</P>
<P>
   And it was apparently also the stomping grounds of a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most solid manifestation occurred when I was working alone
in the building at 2 or 3 in the morning,'' Brian said. ``Someone
ran up those steps in the back room. There are 20 steps leading to
the third floor, but I just heard six, seven or eight _ bong, bong,
bong ...
</P>
<P>
   Brian's first ghostly encounter occurred about 1965. The most
recent was in the autumn of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Sunday mornings, there's no traffic downtown, and you can
hear everything. It was a little before noon when I heard the
distinct sound of boxes being shoved around on the third floor.''
Going to investigate, Brian peered up at the top floor's door,
which, fitting loosely in its frame, shed light into the gloomy
stairway at its edges. ``Light was coming from around the door, but
it was being interrupted as if someone were moving around in here.
My hair stood straight on end ...
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
