<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CROSS-UNIFORM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING OF POLICE OFFICER FOR WEARING CROSS STIRS CONTROVERSY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF PRINCE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ National civil rights groups with vastly
different stances are taking interest in an Arlington police
officer who was fired in September for refusing to remove a small
cross from his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The interest could increase attendance at an appeal hearing Nov.
9, when former Sgt. George Daniels is expected to ask for
reinstatement to the Arlington Police Department where he worked 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Rutherford Institute, which has assisted Paula Jones in her
sexual harassment lawsuit against President Clinton, has agreed to
assist Daniels. The institute is prepared to seek court action if
Daniels is not reinstated after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on how that comes down, we will have to make a
decision on whether to file in federal or state court, but we will
be proceeding in court if we have to,'' said Jennifer Schans, an
attorney and regional coordinator for the Rutherford Institute,
which provides assistance in civil liberty and religious
discrimination cases nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   It is no surprise to some observers that the Virginia-based
group, which solicits donations, is pursuing the Daniels incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a law firm that agrees with people like Jerry Falwell
and Pat Robertson _ far to the religious right,'' said Robert
Boston, assistant director of communications with Americans United
for Separation of Church and State. ``It is a greater fund-raising
gimmick than it is a great legal case.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels said he does not wish to discuss the matter with
reporters and has asked attorneys to respond to questions, Schans
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials are referring inquiries to the city attorney's
office, which will represent Arlington in the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara G. Heptig, assistant city attorney, said the Nov. 9
hearing concerns a decision to fire an officer based on city
policy, a decision the city backs.
</P>
<P>
   No one complained about the cross on Daniels' collar, she said.
</P>
<P>
   National groups differ on whether a cross pin violates free
speech rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be offensive if Mr. Daniels starting telling a person
about Christ if someone says, `I don't want to hear about it,' ''
Schans said. ``There is a possibility that there is someone out
there that might be offended by the cross, but that doesn't take
away from Mr. Daniels' constitutional right to wear a cross.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rutherford Institute would also assist a police officer
fired for wearing a symbol of the antichrist, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want to see that, but that is constitutionally
allowed, to wear that pin,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A government official such as a uniformed police officer makes a
declaration of belief and possible bias by wearing a religious
symbol that could intimidate someone with differing beliefs, Boston
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if you were Jewish, Hindu, Muslim or whatever,''
Boston said. ``They might feel uncomfortable. You're not neutral
when your wearing a cross on your collar.''
</P>
<P>
   Events leading to the dismissal can be traced through a number
of memorandums.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels met with Police Chief David Kunkle on July 1 and asked
for permission to wear the cross. Kunkle rejected the request, but
Daniels continued to wear it.
</P>
<P>
   Kunkle wrote in a memo dated Aug. 10 that he had not authorized
nondepartment pins other than ones that promote programs in which
the city or police have participated.
</P>
<P>
   Kunkle offered Daniels several alternatives, including wearing a
ring or bracelet to depict the religious symbol, wearing a pin
under a uniform shirt or on the underside of a collar, or
transferring to a nonuniformed position.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels continued to wear the cross on his uniform. On Aug. 24,
Kunkle wrote another memo stating that he would proceed with formal
disciplinary action ``up to and including termination.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels touts his record with the department in a Sept. 10 memo
to the internal affairs division, including his recognition as
Rookie of the Year and Officer of the Year. He has also served as a
field training officer, patrol supervisor, accreditation manager,
detective supervisor and internal affairs investigator, a
nonuniformed position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to emphasize that I have nothing but the utmost respect
for Chief Kunkle,'' Daniels wrote. ``However, I am subject to a
Higher Authority, the Lord Jesus Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   In his eight-page memo, Daniels includes 143 references from the
Bible, references that he says support his decision to wear a
cross.
</P>
<P>
   Police Department policy states that ``no button, badge, medal
or similar symbol or item not listed in this General Order will be
worn on the uniform unless approved by the Police Chief in writing
on an individual basis.''
</P>
<P>
   An internal investigation ruled that Daniels violated the
department's uniform policy and was insubordinate for not complying
with Kunkle's order to remove the pin.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
