<SLUG> BC-SQUASH-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: squash is tender. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garnish with remaining chopped cilantro and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 130 calories, 2 grams fat, 25
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 2 milligrams cholesterol, 477
milligrams sodium, 16 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The One-Dish Vegetarian'' by Maria Robbins (St. Martin's,
$24.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN SOUFFLE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups pureed cooked winter squash
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper and nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   5 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   7 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   Blend squash with seasoning and butter and beat lightly. Mix in
egg yolks one at a time, beating each in well.
</P>
<P>
   Beat egg whites until stiff but not dry. Fold 1/4 of whites into
puree, mixing carefully. Gently fold remaining whites into puree.
Pour mixture into a well-oiled 1 1/2-quart souffle dish. Bake at
375 degrees for 25-30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 191 calories, 16 grams fat, 6
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 208 milligrams cholesterol,
189 milligrams sodium, 74 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Vegetarian's A to Z Guide to Fruits &AMP; Vegetables'' by
Kathleen Robinson (Fisher Books, $12.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SQUASH GRIDDLE CAKES
</P>
<P>
   Yields 16 (4-inch) griddle cakes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, beaten
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup pureed cooked squash
</P>
<P>
   1 cup low-fat milk or soy milk, or as needed
</P>
<P>
   Whipped butter or natural canola margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   Maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   Combine first 5 ingredients in large mixing bowl. Combine beaten
egg with the pureed squash and milk in another mixing bowl and
whisk together. Pour wet mixture into dry and stir together just
until well-blended.
</P>
<P>
   Heat nonstick griddle or a large nonstick skillet that has been
lightly coated with butter. Ladle on batter in amounts enough to
form the cakes approximately 4 inches in diameter. Cook on both
sides until golden brown. Serve hot with maple syrup.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per griddle cake: 56 calories, 2 grams fat,
9 grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 23 milligrams cholesterol,
63 milligrams sodium, 25 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Great American Vegetarian'' by Nava Atlas (M. Evans, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PIRATE HUBBARD
</P>
<P>
   Equipment: Hubbard squash, bandanna, black felt, acrylic paint
in black and white, black marker, fine-tip paintbrush.
</P>
<P>
   Directions: Turn the squash so the stem becomes the nose. Using
pins, tack the scarf down and tie in the back. Cut out eye patch
and long, narrow piece of felt to secure it. Tack both pieces onto
squash with needles. With the marker, outline a mouth and eyes.
With a fine-tip paintbrush, paint the black lines. Allow to dry.
Fill in with the white paint.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Acorn felines
</P>
<P>
   Equipment: Acorn squash, black spray paint, construction paper,
glue, paper clips, needles, fake fur.
</P>
<P>
   Spray-paint the squash, using masking tape to cover the stems.
It will take more than one coat. Allow to dry thoroughly between
coats. For less than 2 bucks, you can purchase fake fur for the
ears. Trim out ear shapes and attach with pins. For the whiskers,
unbend paper clips or any other malleable wire and trim into
different lengths. Acorn squash are very hard; do not try to
puncture with wire. With large sewing needles and thimble, create
holes near stem for whiskers. Squash will ooze a bit of liquid.
Wipe clean and insert whisker wires. Cut eyes out of construction
paper and glue to face.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Ghostly butternuts
</P>
<P>
   Equipment: Butternut squash, black and white acrylic paint,
paintbrush, black felt-tip marker.
</P>
<P>
   Directions: Spray-paint the squash with white matte paint. It
will probably take a couple of coats _ allow each coat to dry
thoroughly. With a pencil, draw face on squash, then use a black
marker to make the permanent outline. Finish by filling in with
black paint.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
