<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SQUASH-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT GOURDS: THINK OF SQUASH AS THE NEW PUMPKIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scare up a squash for Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the same old pumpkin, try some other vegetables of
the vine-growing sort. Turn a Hubbard into a patch-wearing pirate,
an acorn into a kitty cat and a butternut into a bottom-heavy
goblin.
</P>
<P>
   While you're at it, pick up extra squash for some delightful
fall fare. One to decorate, one to eat. Now there's one-stop
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   SQUASH AND CIDER SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 butternut squash, about 1 1/2 pounds
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable or chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 cups apple cider (approximately)
</P>
<P>
   Fine sea salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   With a vegetable peeler, peel the squash from top to bottom.
With a large, heavy knife, cut it in half lengthwise. Discard the
seeds. Cut the two halves in half lengthwise, and then cut across
to make large cubes. There should be about 4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Swirl olive oil in the bottom of a large, heavy pot. Add onion
and garlic, and cook slowly until soft, about 5 minutes. Add squash
cubes, stock and 1 cup of cider. Cover and cook over medium heat
until the squash is very tender, about 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Uncover, remove pot from heat and let rest 10 minutes. In a food
processor, puree the mixture, in 2 batches if necessary. Return the
mixture to the pot, and whisk in up to 1 cup of the remaining
cider, thinning mixture to desired consistency. Season well with
salt and pepper. Heat again until very hot, divide among 6 soup
bowls and serve. (Soup can be made in advance and frozen, or
refrigerated overnight and reheated before serving.)
</P>
<P>
   Variations: Just before it is served, the soup can be
embellished with a little dry mustard, cayenne pepper, sour cream,
yogurt or creme fraiche to taste. The soup can also be served in a
mug, with a cinnamon stick for stirring.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 115 calories, 2 grams fat, 23
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 0 cholesterol, 10 milligrams
sodium, 20 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   PUREED BUTTERNUT SQUASH WITH GINGER
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds butternut squash, peeled and cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 teaspoons peeled and roughly chopped fresh ginger or 1
teaspoon ground ginger, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon brown sugar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Place squash in steamer above about 1 inch of salted water.
Cover and cook until squash is very tender, about 20 minutes. To
microwave, place squash and 2 tablespoons water in a
microwave-proof plate or shallow bowl; cover with lid or plastic
wrap. Microwave on high for 3 minutes, shake container and continue
to microwave at 2-minute intervals, until squash is very tender.
</P>
<P>
   While it's still hot, place squash in container of food
processor with butter and ginger; process until smooth. Taste and
add salt, pepper and brown sugar if you like. You may prepare
recipe in advance up this point; refrigerate, well-wrapped or in
covered container, for up to 2 days before proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Reheat over low heat or in microwave and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Flavor variations: A seeded jalapeno or other chile; small
handful of fresh herbs, including parsley, cilantro, mint and sage;
maple syrup or honey in place of brown sugar; olive oil in place of
butter; other ground spices in place of ginger, including cardamom,
cinnamon, mace and nutmeg.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 118 calories, 6 grams fat, 18
grams carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 16 milligrams cholesterol, 65
milligrams sodium, 45 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''How to Cook Everything'' by Mark Bittman (Macmillan, $25)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WINTER SQUASH IN GREEN CURRY SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   2 large shallots, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1-inch knob fresh ginger, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 serrano chiles, cut in half lengthwise, seeded and deveined
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canned unsweetened low-fat coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup evaporated skim milk or soy milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon palm sugar or brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2-pound Hubbard, acorn or butternut squash, peeled and cut into
1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   Combine shallots, garlic, ginger, chiles and 3/4 cup chopped
cilantro in bowl of a large mortar or blender. Grind mixture by
hand or in blender, adding up to 3 tablespoons water, to make a
smooth paste. Set aside remaining cilantro leaves for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   In medium saucepan, bring coconut milk to a boil and cook for
3-4 minutes, stirring frequently, until milk thickens slightly.
Reduce heat to simmer, stir in green paste and curry powder and
cook, stirring, for about 3 minutes. Stir in evaporated skim milk
or soy milk, sugar, salt and pepper. Add squash, raise heat and
bring to boil, stirring frequently. Reduce to simmer and cook,
stirring frequently, for about 20 minutes, until squash is tender.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
