<HEADER>
A1496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      10-28 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEIGHBORHOOD HERO; THE ABSENT FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS
 &HT;    c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   By the age of 6 or 7, most children grow heartily sick of
Barney, as evidenced by the wicked parodies my son and his friends
used to sing about the purple dinosaur and his mind-numbing show.
But for some mysterious reason, the same pre-adolescent kids never
seem to make fun of Mister Rogers, who has been inviting children
into his television neighborhood for 31 years and is an anachronism
if there ever was one.
</P>
<P>
   In an ambitious issue on heroes, the November  &UR; Esquire  &LR; attempts
to explain why that is so. Some of the stories fall flat _ how,
after all, do you make a hero out of a vigilante who disarmed a
teenager and then shot him with his own gun? But Tom Junod's piece
on Fred Rogers manages to show, amid some unnecessarily intrusive
glimpses into Rogers's private life, why the 70-year-old public
television icon remains so valued, not only by children, but by
street-smart teenagers and jaded parents alike. Children are often
the first to see through hypocrisy, and as Junod illustrates with a
series of telling vignettes, they know Rogers is the real article.
A deeply religious man, Rogers truly does believe, according to
Junod, that children _ no matter how disturbed, disabled, or angry
_ are close to God. And wearing the same cardigan sweater and
sneakers day in and day out _ in defiance of the neon pulse and
``dizzying'' MTVism of television _ Rogers manages to convey that
message to children of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   A few other hero pieces are worth reading as well, notably the
one about Richard Jewell. Not many of us, at first glance, would
consider Jewell a hero _ he's more a victim of FBI ineptitude than
anything else _ but this article will change that perception and
make readers a lot more understanding of what Jewell, who was
unfairly labeled as a suspect in the Atlanta Olympics bombing, has
gone through. There is one gaping hole: Author Sara Corbett never
reminds us what Jewell, a security guard in Centennial Olympic Park
the night of the explosions, did that made him a hero. He
discovered the knapsack containing a trio of bombs and quickly
moved people away minutes before they exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the article about Conrad Muhammed, a Nation of
Islam minister and prodigy of Louis Farrakhan before he was
unceremoniously dumped, is more thorough. Muhammed, now a
charismatic but penniless student at Harvard Divinity School, does
not come across as your garden-variety hero; the piece, though,
borders on the heroic in the un-PC way it reveals just how far
Farrakhan is willing to go to eliminate those who might someday
challenge his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the issue of growing up fatherless strongly resonates in
the black community, which explains why the November  &UR; Essence  &LR; 
devotes space to it, fatherless families are a heartache that
stretches across every ethnic group. In ``Daddy Hunger,'' Diane
Weathers writes movingly about how she was abandoned ``by the very
first man in my life'' and how it has affected her relationships
with other men.
</P>
<P>
   Weathers also points out that ``a father's presence in a girl's
life doesn't necessarily guarantee that (a father's) love will be
there.'' For that reason, her piece will speak to many women,
regardless of their family or ethnic background. And the magazine's
Q&AMP;A with three specialists is a good follow to Weathers's
first-person piece; it offers solid advice to all women whose
fathers may not have been there for them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While that kind of insight might be expected in Essence, the
most popular magazine for black women, it comes as a surprise in
 &UR; The Atlantic Monthly &LR; , which is not known for its women-oriented
offerings. And although most of the articles in the Atlantic's
November issue are true to form, including its cover feature _ a
disorganized and not particularly compelling look at Jack Kerouac's
papers _ tucked in the ``personal file'' column is a beautifully
evocative piece about a woman whose nonagenarian mother has lost
her mind. The story, by Lynn Freed, encapsules a daughter's attempt
to communicate with her mother across the divide of senility. For
anyone with an aging but beloved mother, it is a powerful, almost
haunting read.
</P>
<P>
   Far more haunting and difficult to read is the piece by
Holocaust scholar and retired Simmons professor Lawrence Langer on
the disturbing trend these days to look for some kind of purpose in
the Holocaust. Doing so, Langer argues, ``leads nowhere but back
into the pit of destruction.'' Langer's thoughtful denunciation of
attempts by Christian theologian Frans Jozef van Beek and artist
Judy Chicago, among others, to universalize the Holocaust is
difficult not only because of his somewhat pompous intellectual
tone, but because of the examples of atrocities he includes to
bolster his point. But his argument is well worth reading even so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Life  &LR; magazine has compiled a surprisingly witty list of 100
things that Americans have to be thankful for, as Thanksgiving
approaches. Items range from the obvious (No.3: We are not at war)
to the trivial (No.38: There is one less Spice Girl now) to the
thought-provoking (No.15: The families of the switched babies _
Callie Conley and Rebecca Chittum _ acted in the best interests of
the children by leaving them in their respective homes). As we head
into the midterm elections and the impeachment proceedings, the
Life piece is positively cheering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1513EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
