<HEADER>
A1499 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CRANBERRIES-BOS &LR;      10-28 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CRANBERRIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILY TREE THAT'S ROOTED IN CRANBERRIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH HARWICH, Mass. _ Standing outside a warehouse once used by
hundreds of local cranberry growers, Alan Hall can hardly finish a
sentence. A pickup truck driving down Depot Street honks loudly as
the driver waves hello.
</P>
<P>
   A minute later, another car honks, then another pickup, and more
and more vehicles, county workers, state trucks, and ordinary
citizens _ all flying down a road flanked by cranberry bogs.
``Guess I pretty much know everyone who drives down this street,''
says Hall with an accent that sounds like northern Maine but that
he insists is typical mid-Cape.
</P>
<P>
   Alan John Hall, 27, grew up on this street and spent his whole
life here, the son, grandson, and great-grandson of cranberry
growers. Since the family's arrival on the mid-Cape around 1650,
every Hall has raised cranberries, and even though some didn't farm
full time, ``it wasn't a big deal to have 10 acres,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His own family lived on 33 acres. All but two are gone now, and
Hall cultivates those. Two acres of cranberry bog that were dormant
for 15 years are rebuilt and flourishing. They are harvested the
old way, mechanically and without water, so that almost every
single berry picked from the bogs is in mint condition and can be
sold fresh. Hall moved his four-year-old business into the
warehouse this fall as its first lessee, set up a collection of
antique equipment to demonstrate cranberry sorting, learned the
names of every major figure in Cape cranberry history, and waited
for customers to come.
</P>
<P>
   The lucky are arriving slowly. Usually they're stopping by on a
ride along the bicycle path that runs behind the old warehouse,
which was once owned by Ocean Spray cranberries and used by its
cooperative growers as a ``screening house.''
</P>
<P>
   The screening process _ removing bad berries by hand from the
thousands of picked berries _ was done by women who sat at tables
for hours at a time. Old photographs suggest a scene ripe for an
``I Love Lucy'' episode, but this was serious work and important to
the locals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This building was a big source of income for people here,''
says Maura McKenna, Hall's girlfriend and partner in this venture.
``If you lived on the Cape, everyone had something to do with the
screening house.''
</P>
<P>
   After Ocean Spray sold the warehouse, it stayed empty for 30
years, in such disrepair that North Harwich fire trucks positioned
themselves there on Halloween night. The old place was an obvious
target for mischievous trick-or-treaters.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Bojanowski, who rehabilitates rundown buildings around the
country, bought the warehouse with a partner for $300,000 and began
replacing all the broken windows, pulling clusters of mushrooms off
the damp wood floors, peeling back the rotting roof shingles, and
posting signs to announce space for rent. The work continues and
Bojanowski still uncovers memories of another time, like the
announcement written with chalk on a wall. ``Quiet,'' it reads.
``Last berry Nov. 10, 1954, 10:20 a.m.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the last berry ever, explains Bojanowski, simply the
last of that year's harvest. In fact, the warehouse continued to
process berries until 1968. Perhaps it was the tradition for the
worker who handled the close of harvest to note that on a wall.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and McKenna watched the place assume some of its old grace.
``I've been watching it all my life,'' he says. Then he saw the
``space for rent'' sign and came up with the idea of a retail
outlet.
</P>
<P>
   The trains are gone from Depot Street. Railroad cars transported
barrels of berries off the Cape. Hall knows exactly where the
station used to be. ``Right there,'' he says, pointing to a row of
pine trees.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving passengers were bound for Chatham Bars Inn in Chatham,
which was a hunting lodge, and the Belmont in West Harwich. ``They
were people who had money,'' Hall says, including Henry Ford.
</P>
<P>
   When Ford once found himself without a room in North Harwich
before his trip to Chatham, &UR;  &LR; says Hall, ``he stayed one night with
my great-great-grandmother, Ida Kay Chase.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall is the bearer of the family legend.
</P>
<P>
   Another legend involves his ancestor Henry Hall, who cultivated
the first cranberry vines in Dennis around 1816. Before that date,
they had only grown wild. ``Hall's role as pioneer of cranberry
cultivation remains unchallenged,'' according to ``Cranberry
Harvest: A History of Cranberry Growing in Massachusetts,'' edited
by Joseph D. Thomas (Spinner Publications, 1990).
</P>
<P>
   So Alan Hall comes to his cranberry business naturally. He was
quite young when his father, Arthur H. Hall, was diagnosed with
multiple sclerosis and 12 when the illness prevented the older Hall
from cultivating berries. He owned some of his 33 acres, leased
others, and held onto some he could give his children. Those are
the 2 acres Hall now cultivates.
</P>
<P>
   An acre of bog yields about 150 barrels of cranberries (100
pounds per barrel), which gives Hall 30,000 pounds total. He sells
a pound for $1.50 retail (about 95 cents wholesale).
</P>
<P>
   Because his berries are dry harvested rather than the more
common water-reel method _ in which the bog is flooded before the
berries are picked _ Hall gets more money. Dry harvest berries,
used for cooking and baking, are in higher demand than wet-harvest
berries, which are processed into juices and other byproducts the
industry created a demand for in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Dry harvesting yields fewer barries. Whatever his harvest, Hall
loses 20 percent of the crop on the bog, berries that drop off the
picking machines. ``It's a natural compost that goes back into the
soil,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't use water because ``I don't have the adequate water
supply, I only have a well. I want to do fresh fruit anyway,'' he
says. That means he doesn't have to deal with processors. Fresh
fruit stays well for 1 1/2 months in a cool, ventilated place.
</P>
<P>
   Hall is miffed that berries grown off-Cape are labeled and
shipped as a Cape Cod product. Off-Cape, explains Hall, encompasses
any town on the west side of the canal. There are major commercial
bogs between Wareham and Buzzards Bay, along Route 28, a road
commonly known as ``cranberry highway.''
</P>
<P>
   You get the feeling that Hall never crosses the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do,'' he says, ``but I don't have to because everything's
down here. I'm from the old school, for a young guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Off-Cape berries taste different, he says. His mother, Carolyn
Hall, agrees. ``They're all good,'' she begins, ``but it's the same
way you get a lobster on the Cape or one from Maine. The ground is
all sand here. The natural climate, the ocean's spray. Here, the
cranberry is tart.''
</P>
<P>
   With only 2 acres, Alan Hall had to keep his day job. He works
as building and grounds supervisor for the Harwich school
department. Even working full time, he couldn't touch the cost of
bog land anywhere on the Cape.
</P>
<P>
   ``An acre of bog costs $30,000 to $45,000,'' he explains, ``and
you should have 5 acres of upland around it. That's land other than
bog land,'' which protects the bog. An acre of &UR;  &LR; upland costs more _
about $55,000 _ because most of it is sold to developers. That
land, he says, ``is getting rare.''
</P>
<P>
   His parcel, which includes upland, comes to 9 acres.
</P>
<P>
   To start his venture, Hall received a $30,000 grant from
Barnstable County Extension Service in 1994. He pays his parents $1
a year plus the taxes on the land. Together they wrote up a 10-year
lease ``to make it legal,'' says Hall. He has to repay only 25
percent of the grant after the second crop, which will be a year
from now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could flood the bog and get 5 to 10 more barrels of
cranberries,'' he says, but that wouldn't give him fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, he went to pick up an old cranberry
separator, in which good berries bounce down a flight of wooden
steps (called ``bounce boards'') and bad berries roll into a rot
box. It seems incredible at first, until Hall explains that a good
berry bounces because it's hollow, while bad berries plop and roll
away.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted the separator so he could show people how it worked.
The new ones, with electric motors, are only marginally more
sophisticated and efficient.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Cleaning out the separator, he found a surprise. Inside the
hopper was the rubber stamp that his father and mother used decades
ago to label the crate of berries they shipped out. Large letters,
crimson from the ink pad it was dipped into for years, read:
``Hall's Cape Cod Cranberries, North Harwich, Mass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, I kept asking you, `Where's the stamp?''' says his
mother. ``I don't know how it got into the separator. I can't
believe it.'' She gazes at the stamp, flooded with memories. ``It's
nice to have it back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
