<HEADLINE>
SOME EQUITIES NO   LONGER SO SPECIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were a quirky collection of small stocks with big plans
assembled by mutual fund manager Michael DiCarlo: One ran
fiber-optic communications networks, another sold cheescakes, a
third helped New York City cabbies finance the buying of their
medallions.
</P>
<P>
   The stocks, about 90 overall, made up the portfolio of John
Hancock Special Equities, a leading small company fund through much
of the 1990s that began to struggle two years ago. But things
changed in a big way after Hancock replaced DiCarlo with Laura J.
Allen as the new lead manager on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Allen decided what she wanted to keep and the rest went on the
block, from the start of July through September. What would have
been a tricky portfolio adjustment at any time turned into a
treacherous trading experience because the market for small stocks
suffered one of its worst quarters of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   When no one wanted small company shares, Special Equities was
putting millions of them up for sale. ``Clearly, this has been very
challenging for us,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   At times, Special Equities appeared to suffer from the shift, at
least in the short run. It lost more ground than even the
pulverized small-stock indexes; three weeks ago, its year-to-date
loss was within a whisker of 40 percent. The loss had been pared to
24 percent as of Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who owned some of the same stocks held by Special
Equities clearly felt the short-term effect of the fund's action.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Infinium Software Inc. of Hyannis had noticed
something odd in July, just after they announced record quarterly
revenue and profits that soared 300 percent: Their stock started to
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' said Daniel Kossman, the company's
chief financial officer. ``We had just reported a great quarter.
They were basically liquidating and it was driving our stock price
down.''
</P>
<P>
   But it turned out to be a good move for Special Equities
shareholders. Infinium couldn't meet forecasts for the following
quarter, and the stock plunged, two months after the fund sold.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock declined to identify individual stocks sold by Special
Equities since the summer. But a review of the fund's publicly
disclosed portfolio as of April 30 and the aggregate investment
changes by all of Hancock's mutual funds during the third quarter
fill in most of the details. Aggregate Hancock figures were a good
proxy for activity within Special Equities during the quarter
because the company's other funds rarely owned the same stocks in
bulk, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Allen appears to have sold at least 20 million shares of small
company stocks in her inherited portfolio during the quarter.
Special Equities eliminated positions in nearly three dozen
companies, most of which counted the fund as one of their largest
institutional investors, according to our estimates. Special
Equities had been one of the three largest mutual fund shareholders
in 31 instances; 15 of those had counted it as their largest fund
investor.
</P>
<P>
   Special Equities seems to have sold all of its 350,000 fixing
chartshares of Infinium Software. The fund also appears to have
eliminated positions in a few better-known companies, like its
million shares of San Francisco brokerage Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Group.
But mostly it sold stakes of 300,000 to 600,000 shares in
less-familiar names like Aviation Sales Co., Correctional Services
Corp., and Guitar Center Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said she and other comanagers targeted stocks that they
considered to have risky profit outlooks. The idea: When small
stocks finally regain investor interest, the companies on the most
solid footing will rebound highest.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said Hancock traders were conscious of the problems posed
by selling large blocks of small stocks, particularly shares of
companies that had just disappointed investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these companies reported earnings in July that were
much worse than we expected,'' she said. ``We were very careful in
disengaging in these positions. We did not want to completely sell
at any price.''
</P>
<P>
   But how do you get out of a 500,000-share position of a stock
that trades 50,000 shares on an average day, even if there is no
bad news affecting the company? With difficulty, sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers for Special Equities began to seek buyers for the fund's
500,000-share block of Affiliated Managers Group of Boston in
mid-August, according to people familiar with the stock's trading
activity. There were no takers right away, and soon it became
widely known that a big seller was trying to move stock. The
shares, which had traded at 24 in mid-August, fell to 15 15/16 on
Sept. 9, the one day trading volume soared and 572,500 AMG shares
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   The stock started to move up the next day and finished Tuesday
at 21 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Allen didn't sell all the old Special Equities stocks. The
cabbie financier, Medallion Financial Corp., is still in the
portfolio. So is Family Golf Centers Inc., CareMatrix Corp., and
American Italian Pasta Co., by our reading.
</P>
<P>
   Special Equities has also added about as many new stocks as it
has sold. Among the new names: Duane Reade, a New York drug store
chain; technology outsourcing specialist Whitmann-Hart Inc.; and
Alkermes Inc., a Cambridge biotechnology company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
