<HEADLINE>
TWO NEW MAGAZINES ON THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The women's version of Sports Illustrated is on hold, and Conde
Nast's Sports for Women has absorbed and then become Women's Sports
and Fitness while cutting back to six issues a year. But that isn't
stopping Amy Love or Nancy Levin from putting two new women's
sports magazines on the launchpad.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary: Because they're willing to start small and
eager to skip the tips on beauty and fashion, both women see their
publications as serving a market that has yet to be tapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not a women's magazine that does some sports, we're a
sports magazine for women,'' says Levin, whose magazine, Wsports,
is expected to debut in March, with two more issues in 1999 before
it goes bimonthly in 2000. ``We're going to be 100 percent about
women's sports, pure and simple. There's a big need for that, a big
demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin, who co-founded and captained the women's varsity soccer
team at Harvard before earning her master's degree in business from
Yale in 1987, has been publishing Women's Sports Connection, a San
Francisco area newsletter, since 1993. Wsports is an outgrowth of
the positive response to that publication, which features lists of
resources and calendars of local events in addition to news and
features.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the real, authentic market: the people who
are participants, the people who are fans,'' says Levin, the
magazine's publisher and editor-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Real Sports, which will publish its inaugural issue
in December before going bimonthly in June and then monthly in
2000, aims at the serious sports market. Where it diverges from
Wsports is in its focus on team sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the growth in the marketplace, that's where
there is a huge groundswell of fan involvement and participation,''
says Love, who holds a master's in business administration from
Harvard and began last year to pursue her vision of a women's
sports magazine.
</P>
<P>
   It was a goal she set even before the breakthrough for women's
team sports at the 1996 Olympics. ``I made the decision while the
passion was there, but I couldn't make the numbers work yet, so I
put in on hold,'' says Love, who will publish out of San Jose. ``I
didn't feel it was time to lay out our playbook.'' But after she
saw the early efforts of Sports Illustrated and Conde Nast, she
felt reenergized. ``They chose to go after different market
segments,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Love has no doubt there is room for both magazines. ``This is a
market segment that has been just painfully ignored,'' she says.
``There is huge potential for a whole host of magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Huebner's e-mail address is huebner(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
