<HEADLINE>
RIGHT THIS WAY FOR WYATT-STYLE CORN-BREAD DRESSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Men. First they won't ask for directions and, apparently, now
they're too shy to ask for recipes.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Mencke writes, saying that he loves the corn-bread
dressing served at Wyatt's Cafeterias.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised eating at Wyatt's at least a couple of times a
week. Whenever they had turkey and dressing, I ordered it,'' Chuck
writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work out in Burleson, and we have a lunchtime caterer who
makes turkey and dressing. When I tasted her dressing, I knew it
was Wyatt's. I asked her about it, and she told me her
father-in-law had worked for Wyatt's for years, and he had taught
her how to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the nerve to ask her for the recipe, but if you
call her,'' Chuck writes, ``I'd love to have the recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   This reminds me of the time my husband and I were lost in
Bavaria. Instead of stopping to ask someone for directions, Mr.
Fluent-in-German stopped the car and sent me up to a farmhouse to
ask directions. Not only could I not ask the questions, I had not a
clue what the kind Herr was saying in response.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Chuck, I did call Dolly Fore, owner of Dolly's
Tamales in Burleson, and she was kind enough to send this recipe.
She learned it as a newlywed from Robert Lee Fore.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLY'S CORN-BREAD DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12-15
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1/2 rib celery, chopped
</P>
<P>
   10-ounce can condensed cream of celery soup
</P>
<P>
   2 10-ounce cans condensed cream of chicken soup
</P>
<P>
   4 cups turkey broth
</P>
<P>
   9-by-11-inch pan unsweetened corn bread, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   3/4 loaf dry white bread, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   6 hard-boiled eggs
</P>
<P>
   4 raw eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons poultry seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground sage
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground thyme
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Saute onion and celery in oil. Add soups and broth and heat
through.
</P>
<P>
   Combine remaining ingredients in large bowl. Add soup mixture
and mix well. Pack into pan or pans. Bake for 45 minutes at 350
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 283 calories, 13 grams fat, 31
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 166 milligrams cholesterol,
970 milligrams sodium, 40 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Happy ending: Turn a simple loaf of bread into a sinful treat
with this recipe sent in by Betty Ayars of Keene, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   SHADY OAKS COUNTRY CLUB'S BREAD PUDDING WITH VANILLA SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10
</P>
<P>
   1 loaf egg bread
</P>
<P>
   6 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   6 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 cup nuts and/or raisins, optional
</P>
<P>
   Heat milk and salt until slightly warm. Soak bread slices in
milk for 15 minutes. Combine remaining ingredients with electric
mixer.
</P>
<P>
   Layer bread in 9-by-13-inch pan, sprinkle with nuts or raisins,
drizzle each layer with some of the egg mixture and some of the
milk left over from the soaking. Bake in a 350-degree oven for 45
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla sauce:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cornstarch and 1/2 cup water; mixed and set aside
</P>
<P>
   2 vanilla beans cut lengthwise or 3 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Slowly beat cream, gradually adding sugar. Don't beat cream to
whipped stage. The mixture should be thick and smooth with sugar
incorporated. Stir in cornstarch mixture. Add vanilla. Transfer to
sauce pan and place over low-to-medium heat. Heat mixture until
slightly thickened. Strain and cool for 15 minutes before serving
with the bread pudding.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with sauce: 615 calories, 28
grams fat, 80 grams carbohydrates, 11 grams protein, 233 milligrams
cholesterol, 352 milligrams sodium, 41 percent of calories from
fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
