<HEADER>
A1524 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-BERNSTEIN-BOS &LR;      10-28 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-BERNSTEIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT CONDUCTOR'S ALLEGRO LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMERICAN MASTERS
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Bernstein: Reaching for the Notes
</P>
<P>
   Director: Susan Lacy
</P>
<P>
   Rated: TVPG
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Leonard Bernstein: Reaching for the Note'' depicts its subject
as composer for Broadway, Hollywood, the opera house, and concert
hall; conductor; pianist; television educator; student; colleague;
teacher and mentor; supporter of Israel and liberal causes; son,
brother, husband, father, lover, friend; conflicted, tormented, and
triumphant self.
</P>
<P>
   That's quite a tall order for two hours of television, and
director Susan Lacy's film sometimes spreads itself too thin, like
Bernstein himself. After a somewhat confusing beginning, ``Reaching
for the Note'' is mostly chronological; presumably in order to get
to the popular stuff first, Bernstein is depicted as a conducting
star and a Broadway composer before we see him as a student at
Tanglewood, Mass. Most of the achievements are there, but there's
no time for anything about his work in the opera house _ yet
everything Bernstein did could be analzyed in terms of musical
theater. The film repeatedly captures him in his most frenzied and
grandiose moments on the podium _ yet he perhaps was a better
conductor of Haydn than of Mahler, genial, earthy, and spiritual.
Most of the major biographical issues also come up _ his conflict
with his father; his marriage and family; his complicated sexual
identity; his reckless living, rapid aging, and death. A few
attempts to read the creative work as pure autobiography are
feeble, but the life really was the work.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the film there are comments by people who knew
Bernstein well, including his brother, Burton, and his three
children, Jamie Bernstein Thomas, Nina Bernstein, and Alexander
Bernstein; with colleagues in his professional achievements (Betty
Comden and Adolph Green from the first carefree musical comedies;
Stephen Sondheim, Arthur Laurents, Jerome Robbins, and Carol
Lawrence from ``West Side Story''; Barbara Cook from ``Candide'');
performers such as Isaac Stern, Christa Ludwig, Jerry Hadley, and
Thomas Hampson; composers Lukas Foss, Harold Shapero, and John
Corigliano; conductors Seiji Ozawa, Andre Previn; Michael Tilson
Thomas and John Mauceri; members of orchestras in Vienna, Israel,
and New York; even a couple of critics. It is touching to hear the
voice of mezzo-soprano Jennie Tourel, one of Bernstein's closest
musical friends, on the soundtrack, even though it is not
identified. The most revealing voice is that of Bernstein himself,
the sound of an irresistible and overwhelming personality, which is
heard not only in rehearsal excerpts, television sequences, and
interviews, but also in an actor's reading of notes and diaries,
and in the memories of his friends (``If you are going to fall off
a ladder,'' Sondheim remembers Bernstein saying, ``fall off a high
rung'').
</P>
<P>
   Only Bernstein's children, Sondheim, and Laurents are permitted
to get beyond the sound-bite level. The involvement of the
Bernstein family also means that some issues are handled gingerly.
It is admitted that Bernstein was always a controversial figure,
but it is never quite clear what the controversies were about, or
that any criticism might have been about anything that mattered.
Inevitably ``Reaching for the Note'' is more about personality than
about music; in a way that is appropriate, because Bernstein
appropriated all kinds of music into his personality, and imposed
his personality on all kinds of music. He knew unreserved adulation
in every area of his activity except the one that mattered most to
him _ his concert music; the tragedy was not that his music was
misunderstood by others but that Bernstein himself understood its
limitations all too well. The film does admit Bernstein's
bisexuality, but does not concede his homosexual side any dignity
or depth.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its limitations in reach, focus, and detail, Lacy's film
is expertly made and often moving. There's some wonderful archival
footage _ original-cast members Carol Lawrence and Larry Kert
duetting in ``West Side Story'' 40 years ago _ and material never
before seen by the public, including a montage of sunlit home
movies of Bernstein frolicking with his family and friends in their
Connecticut summer house, deftly edited to the ``Candide''
Overture. The film opens with slow-motion photography of
Bernstein's funeral procession moving through the streets of New
York, with Beethoven's Seventh Symphony on the soundtrack; near its
close we hear the same music, the work Bernstein conducted in the
last concert of his career at Tanglewood. The final notes of ``West
Side Story,'' ``Somewhere,'' are the last we hear, notes that speak
of tragedy but also of hope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
