r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     10-28 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV01-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPE FOR THE UNDERDOG: 50 YEARS AFTER TRUMAN'S UPSET VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Nov. 1)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ If, in these last hours before voters go to
the polls, underdog office seekers are searching for a shrine to
election-year miracles, they will find it here at 219 North
Delaware Street.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Harry Truman lived, and 50 years ago this week he
confounded the pollsters and upset the prognosticators by winning a
seemingly hopeless race for the presidency. Before the votes were
cast, it was the universal belief that Truman, who had succeeded to
the presidency on the death of Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1945, would
be defeated by the Republican nominee, New York Gov. Thomas E.
Dewey.
</P>
<P>
   Truman himself appears to have been almost alone among 150
million Americans in believing he would win.
</P>
<P>
   But win he did, and in doing so he became for all time a symbol
of the projected loser who becomes the ultimate winner.
</P>
<P>
   Even such Republicans as George Bush in 1992 and Bob Dole in
1996 sought, while trailing Bill Clinton in the public opinion
polls, to identify themselves with the plain-spoken Missourian who,
through perseverance, determination and political bravado,
converted defeat into victory in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Forgotten are Truman's mistakes and gaffes. Forgotten is the
fact that his foes called for his impeachment after he fired
General of the Army Douglas MacArthur in 1951 while Americans were
dying in the flaming cauldron of Korea. Forgotten, too, are the
scandals that tarnished his administration and the cronies who took
advantage of him.
</P>
<P>
   What is remembered _ in addition to the remarkable decisions he
made in the fields of foreign policy and national security _ is the
miracle of 1948, when an average-looking-and-acting fellow from
Independence stunned the nation.
</P>
<P>
   We have had other close presidential elections since then,
especially in 1960 when more than 68 million votes were cast
nationwide and the shift of fewer than 60,000 in Texas and Illinois
would have provided Richard Nixon with victory over John Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   But times and the technique of campaigning have changed
drastically since Truman squared off against Dewey. Television was
not an important factor in the 1948 campaign. The American people
got their information primarily from newspapers and radio.
</P>
<P>
   Candidates traveled more by train than by plane. There were no
debates between the Democratic and Republican presidential
nominees. All of the major public opinion polls forecast a Dewey
victory. One pollster, Elmo Roper, was so certain of the outcome
that he stopped sampling voter preferences two months before
election day.
</P>
<P>
   When Newsweek Magazine asked 50 influential bureau chiefs,
columnists and political reporters who they thought would win, all
50 said Dewey.
</P>
<P>
   But the Truman saga transcends politics and the presidency. It
is a tale that glorifies every man or woman who beat the odds after
being counted out.
</P>
<P>
   When Truman entered the presidency, he was largely unknown
outside his home state of Missouri, despite his chairmanship of a
Senate committee that exposed waste in national defense
procurement. He had served fewer than three months as vice
president and he had a tough act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt, projecting supreme self-confidence and great charm,
had been the commanding figure in America for a dozen years,
guiding the republic safely through the Great Depression and World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Truman, an unpretentious onetime farmer who wore thick glasses
and spoke in a flat, midwestern twang, was no match for FDR _ and
he wisely chose not to try.
</P>
<P>
   He chose instead to be himself, an unadorned, middle-class
American who was reared in a farmhouse near Grandview, Mo. that had
neither plumbing nor electricity. He was the only president of the
20th century who did not attend college. But being a prodigious
reader, he educated himself.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles he faced in 1948 were formidable. The Democratic
Party was split three ways, with former Vice President Henry
Wallace leading a liberal faction opposed to Truman's Cold War
policies designed to contain communist aggression, and then-South
Carolina Gov. Strom Thurmond heading the Dixiecrats who opposed
civil rights for blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Two years earlier, Republicans had won control of Congress for
the first time since the election of 1930. The result was the
conservative 80th Congress, which Truman attacked pungently on the
campaign trail in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The two-story, 14-room Victorian house where he lived here is an
excellent reflection of an earlier America and of the personalities
of Bess and Harry Truman. Built by Bess Truman's maternal
grandfather more than 100 years ago, it is old-fashioned,
comfortable and filled with character.
</P>
<P>
   After all, its most memorable resident was the president who
ordered the atomic bombing that ended World War II, provided the
aid that saved Greece and Turkey from communism, established the
Marshall Plan and NATO and turned back the invasion of South Korea
by North Korea. Mementos of those actions and Truman's stunning
1948 victory, are recalled at the Truman museum and library, about
a mile from the Delaware Street house.
</P>
<P>
   When Truman began his nationwide whistle-stop campaign on Sept.
17, 1948, Kentucky Sen. Alben Barkley, his vice presidential
running mate, was at Union Station in Washington to see him off. As
the train pulled away, Barkley called out, ``Mow 'em down, Harry.''
</P>
<P>
   Truman shouted back, ``I'm gonna give 'em hell.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what he did, and he won. In the Truman legend, there
still is hope for those who seemingly are without hope.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1531EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0203 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1573 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AIDS29-COX     10-28 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AIDS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ANNOUNCES AIDS HELP FOR MINORITIES
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Warning of a ``severe and ongoing'' AIDS crisis in
minority communities, President Clinton announced a $156 million
program Wednesday to combat the spread of the disease among African
Americans and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   The new initiative includes a prevention campaign, improved
access to drug treatments, training for health professionals who
treat the disease and federal ``crisis response teams'' that the
Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) will dispatch to
areas highly affected by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   While overall AIDS deaths have declined for two years in a row,
AIDS remains the leading killer of African-American men age 25-44
and the second leading killer of African-American women in the same
age group. African Americans account for more than 40 percent of
all new HIV/AIDS cases, and Hispanics represent over 20 percent of
new cases of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In many minority communities, ``there's still a misconception
that this is a gay disease and that other people aren't at risk,''
said Sandy Thurman, director of the White House Office of AIDS
Policy. For that reason, she said, part of the new program will be
to explain the wider dangers of infection to people in these
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be targeted prevention efforts'' to ``raise
awareness and erase the stigma'' sometimes associated with the
disease, Thurman said. ``We be making sure the messages are in
language in that people use and understand and that is culturally
sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, for instance, the program will look ``to the
leadership in the African American church community'' to ``talk
openly to congregations about AIDS,'' explained Thurman, 44, a
Georgia native who headed AIDS Atlanta before joining the 1992
Clinton presidential campaign. The program might enlist volunteers
from the sororities and fraternities at the city's historically
black colleges to help get out its message, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The program will also increase access to new drug therapies at
the city's neighborhood health centers and train the health care
providers there in AIDS prevention and treatment, Thurman said. The
most effective response is community based or ``home-grown,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Personifying this community-based activism, perhaps, is Denise
Stokes, an AIDS educational consultant from Atlanta who introduced
Clinton at Wednesday's announcement. Diagnosed with AIDS 12 years
ago, Stokes ``is one of the first people to put a face on
heterosexual HIV infection,'' said organizers of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the funding for the minority AIDS program was
provided in the Omnibus Appropriations Act that Congress passed and
Clinton signed into law last week. The remainder will come from the
HHS budget.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
