<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS JUST WIPE AWAY MUD AND PLOW ONWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody seems to be disgusted with all those negative ads that
have been muddying up the political arena this election season. We
have a right to be disgusted; it's darn near impossible to find a
legitimate issue floating around in the muck.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the campaigns for statewide offices in Texas are no more
negative than usual, but they somehow seem to have a nastier edge
to them _ with the possible exception of the race for governor,
where incumbent George W. Bush has more or less ignored challenger
Garry Mauro, and Mauro has more or less confined his
misrepresentations of Bush's record to issues on which honest pols
can differ.
</P>
<P>
   But the races for lieutenant governor, attorney general and
comptroller? The worst. Listen to some of the TV ads put out by the
Republican and Democratic candidates for those offices, and your
first inclination is to burn your voter's card.
</P>
<P>
   If those people are half as bad as they describe each other as
being, Bush might want to get himself elected president of the
United States just to get away from the lowlife bums he has to deal
with in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ads, the major parties' candidates for the top
state jobs are:
</P>
<P>
   a. crooks.
</P>
<P>
   b. liars.
</P>
<P>
   c. political hacks.
</P>
<P>
   d. incompetent nitwits.
</P>
<P>
   e. all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   It must be disconcerting for voters to be confronted with such
disturbing revelations about previously well-respected public
servants. All but one of the candidates have been elected to public
office in the past. How did they achieve their current stature
without being unmasked as self-promoting, unqualified slugs?
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that the voters have heard it all before and just
don't care?
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that voters don't care if a candidate is a crook or a
notorious scoundrel of some sort; it's just that they've heard
candidates describe each other in the most disparaging terms so
often that the negative blasts have turned into little more than
background noise.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations and counteraccusations begin to roll off the
voters' collective back just as easily as they roll off the tongues
of the faceless, hired-gun announcers whose voices have become so
familiar in political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   With allegations flying everywhere _ and with no way of knowing
which accusations are legitimate and which are unfounded
mudslinging _ many voters simply decide to ignore all the
accusations and base their votes on other criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Some vote for the candidate of their favorite political party.
Some vote for the candidate who best represents their views on
important issues. Some vote for the candidate who seems most
sincere or who looks the best on television.
</P>
<P>
   The great thing about democracy is that voters are allowed to
vote for any candidate they choose _ for any reason they choose.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, voters can sort through the inflammatory
rhetoric, the accusatory advertising and the cheap-shot
back-stabbing that passes for political debate. No matter how deep
the mud, conscientious voters almost always manage to wade through
it and arrive at a responsible decision when they enter the voting
booth.
</P>
<P>
   Negative campaigns do not in themselves erode the electoral
process. What damages the process is some voters' increasingly
common habit of using negative campaigns as an excuse for not
voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pox on all their houses,'' these voters say. ``I've got no
use for any of them. I'm staying home on Election Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, that attitude doesn't punish politicians for
negative campaigns. Somebody will win every race, whether voter
turnout is 1 percent or 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, in fact, will probably be the candidate who
conducted the most negative campaign, because attack ads are
designed not to lure voters to the attacker's side but to
discourage voters from supporting the candidate who is under
attack.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't vote, you actually validate the mudslinging that
you meant to protest by staying home.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't want to do that, would you?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1605EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
