<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLINDMARATHONER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARATHON RUNNER, LEGALLY BLIND, DEPENDS ON ANOTHER'S VISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Marathon runner Ricky Cox hopes to become a
winner in this weekend's New York Marathon by slowing down.
</P>
<P>
   A three-time winner of Fort Worth's Cowtown Marathon, Cox, 39,
said he ran the 1983 Boston Marathon in 2 hours, 17 minutes, a time
bordering on world class. He figures he will be a winner in New
York if he finishes the 26.2 miles in 3 hours.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he will not be just running. He will be serving as a
guide for Mike Royal, a Fort Worth runner who also happens to be
blind.
</P>
<P>
   They run linked at the wrist by an 18-inch shoelace. They also
have verbal signals for things such as potholes and turns.
</P>
<P>
   Royal, 30, hopes that this will be the first step toward
qualifying for the Paralympic Games in Sydney, Australia, in 2000.
The games, for people who are physically challenged, follow the
Olympics by two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have become friends, and so if he achieves what he wants,
that will be my glory also. I will be happy for him,'' said Cox, a
Fort Worth resident and a supervisor for the Fort Worth
Transportation Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said that he and Royal got together this summer through The
T, as the transportation agency is known. One of The T's drivers
knew that Royal was having a problem finding a guide runner who
could keep up with him.
</P>
<P>
   Royal, manager of information technologies auditing for Union
Pacific Resources, said his condition was diagnosed as retinitis
pigmentosa, a degenerative eye disease, when he was 5 years old.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a serious runner for about 10 years and has
completed more than a dozen marathons. Royal said his best time is
3 hours, 10 minutes and 48 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   He said that within the past two years, his sight has rapidly
deteriorated. He is legally blind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably within the last two years that I've had guides,
but I've had them drop out because they were too slow,'' Royal
said. ``Before, when they dropped out, I sometimes could still pick
my way through the crowd or follow somebody right in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Royal said, that is impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've turned my trust over to him completely,'' Royal said. ``I
don't have to worry about running into another runner or taking a
corner too tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Royal said it's much harder for Cox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a challenge,'' Cox said, ``but I also wanted to help Mike
after talking to him, with him telling me what he wanted to do and
his problem with guys dropping out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what he wants to do, being blind. It's hard to do
having perfect vision. This is totally new for me, and and it's
quite a responsibility.'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   It's common for long-distance runners to have periods where the
mind drifts off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a humongous responsibility, to remain focused
and to remember that you are running with a totally blind runner.
I'm so comfortable with him now that I tend to forget he's blind,''
Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Royal said they hope to do the Cowtown and the Boston Marathon
in the spring and other shorter races in preparation for the
Paralympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
