A1674 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-28 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALE MIND BEST LEFT UNEXPLORED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is no secret that women and men view the world differently.
I've read and studied everything I could about men for years and
years, only to conclude that I have no idea how they think. I never
have and I never will.
</P>
<P>
   I don't even try anymore. Men are like calculus to me. All I did
to get through calculus was memorize the formulas, plug in the
numbers and hope for the best. It was never natural or intuitive
for me, like English or science. All I know is that if I do this,
he'll do that eight times out of 10. I can live with that. I don't
think that we're supposed to understand everything. It's OK to have
some mysteries in life.
</P>
<P>
   Even my darling sons are mysteries to me. I grew up with a baby
sister and lots of girl cousins. Girls I understand. Boys'
fascination with bodily functions mystifies me. Why does it matter
who can burp the loudest? How is this a useful skill? Why is it so
amusing?
</P>
<P>
   Why ask why?
</P>
<P>
   I frequently share things with my husband, expecting a certain
reaction, but I can never be sure how he will respond. Like when I
told him about our friend's new baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, guess what?'' I said. ``Cindy had her baby today. It's
a 10-pound little boy!''
</P>
<P>
   ``How much weight did she gain?'' he asked me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know, but the baby is 22 inches long and he has a
head full of curly black hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he wanted to know, ``Does she have a private room?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess. She was only in labor three hours. Imagine that. She
said that it didn't even hurt. I am so envious. You know how much I
suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to that, he asked, ``Do you want a sandwich?''
</P>
<P>
   I keep thinking there's a connection here, but I sure don't know
what it could be. Somewhere in the midst of my confusion, I know
that he's happy for Cindy and her husband. And I know that he loves
babies. I just don't understand the private room thing. How is that
relevant? Is that something I should have asked Cindy? The baby is
in the nursery with 20 other babies. Will he resent his mother's
roommate?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee, I finally get out of that noisy nursery, and now this
chick keeps talking to my mom. Look, lady, I just got here. She's
supposed to be concentrating on me. Put a lid on it, already.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything is bipolar with me and my beloved. If I like the
movie, he falls asleep. If he likes the movie, I think it is too
violent or lacking in redeeming social value. It's 60 degrees in
our bedroom; he's on top of the covers and I'm buried under four
blankets. When I'm all excited and upset, he's calm and rational.
If I say tomayto, he says tomahto.
</P>
<P>
   It used to bother me a lot until I realized that, when it comes
to the things that matter, like our family or his job, he is very
predictable and very reliable. Those other little things aren't
really that important. We accept each other and appreciate each
other for all the times that we've taken different paths to reach
the same conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, what's life without a little mystery?
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1606EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 16:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1694 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-ROSS-SFCHRON &LR;      10-28 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ROSS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MEMORIES OF '50s POPULATE `PLEASANTVILLE`  
 By RUTHE STEIN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ As a screenwriter, Gary Ross is known for his
cleverness, a reputation that should be solidified now that he has
directed his first film, ``Pleasantville.'' While his movies may
seem like flights of fantasy, they're also anchored in things he
knows.
</P>
<P>
   Writing ``Big'' 10 years ago, Ross made the fable about a
13-year-old in a 35-year-old body ring true by drawing on the wish
of every boy to be bigger. His 1993 satire ``Dave'' _ about a dead
ringer for the president who is brought to the White House to
impersonate him _ contains Ross' insider view of politics gleaned
from having been an intern on Capitol Hill and from writing
speeches for President Clinton and other politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ross, 42, only caught part of the 1950s, his memories
of the period permeate ``Pleasantville.'' The film, starring Tobey
Maguire and Reese Witherspoon as contemporary teens who get sucked
into a television and become regulars on a '50s sitcom, finished
No. 1 at the box office last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started with the idea of two kids going through a modern
looking glass, which is a TV set,'' says Ross, sipping bottled
water near the pool of his hotel. ``Then I started thinking about
this hermetically sealed universe where everything was just too
perfect, and what a hell that would be.''
</P>
<P>
   The '50s suburban household depicted in ``Pleasantville'' is
right out of ``Father Knows Best,'' complete with a dad (William H.
Macy) who marches off to work every morning, briefcase in hand, and
a mom (Joan Allen) who is clueless about life outside the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the kind of house Ross grew up in, but it was one he
secretly longed for. The son of a blacklisted Hollywood writer, he
recalls being envious of the fathers he saw leaving for work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some weird way, I longed for that stability,'' Ross
recalls. ``If your dad isn't working because he's blacklisted and
if you're in that kind of world where there is a little bit of
instability and mayhem, a dad who goes to work every day just to
make money with no higher purpose _ that was the most exotic thing
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   His close relationship with his mother, who fled the kitchen to
return to college when Ross was 13, helped him understand the
hidden frustration of many housewives during this period.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad wasn't that comfortable with her going back to school.
He was very liberal, but liberal doesn't mean feminist. I mean he
still wanted dinner on the table.'' The scene in ``Pleasantville''
where the father walks off in a huff after peeking into an empty
oven was inspired by an incident in Ross' house.
</P>
<P>
   When his father, Arthur Ross, was allowed to work, he wrote
``Creature From the Black Lagoon,'' ``The Great Race'' and many
episodes of ``Alfred Hitchcock Presents.'' By third grade, Gary
already was emulating him, polishing off a school play as epic as
its title: ``The Vikings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It got rewritten by the rest of the class. I was severely p_
off the way all writers are when someone else messes with their
vision,'' Ross recalls, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with many Hollywood screenwriters, Ross has been lucky
to have his work brought to the screen pretty much as he wrote it.
Early on, however, he realized directing was the only way to have
complete control.
</P>
<P>
   He served an informal apprenc &LR; ticeship watching Penny Marshall
direct ``Big'' and Ivan Reitman do the same on ``Dave.'' ``Penny
was a first-time director, so it was sort of a very forced
collaboration. But Ivan was tremendously gracious. He had one
monitor and I had the one next to him, and I learned an incredible
amount.''
</P>
<P>
   The visual look of ``Pleasantville'' was planned before Ross
ever stepped behind the camera. ``I had 700 pages of storyboard, so
I knew every shot in the movie,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, he intended to shoot the film in black and
white, like '50s sitcoms. His big inspiration was introducing color
to show characters being transformed by a sexual awakening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `What would happen if they fully began to blossom?'
The first image that came to me was a rose blooming. Then I
realized, I could color the rose and use it to show the
transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your perception at the end isn't that you've seen a black and
white movie,'' Ross says hopefully, ``but that you've seen the most
colorful movie you've ever been to.''
</P>
<P>
