A1757 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOM-BUST-TEXTILES-LA     10-28 3734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOM-BUST-TEXTILES-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPINNING GOLD
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By CLAIRE POOLE, with BRENDAN M. CASE in Mexico City, MERY
GALANTERNICK in Rio de Janeiro and THOMAS LONG in San Salvador 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Much like the Charles Dickens novel, ``A Tale of Two Cities,''
it's been the best of times and the worst of times for Latin
America's textiles industry.
 &HT;    It's been the best of times in places like Mexico, where the
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) has opened up the huge
U.S. market to Mexican-made and -assembled textiles.
 &HT;    It's been the worst of times in places like Brazil, whose free
trade policies have hammered the country's inefficient
manufacturers with cheap imports from Asia.
 &HT;    At the same time, countries in Central America and the Caribbean
fight for NAFTA parity so they can increase their textile
industries as fast as Mexico's.
 &HT;    The times have been mixed for U.S. textile companies as well,
many of whom ship thread, yarn and fabric to Latin America for
assembly into apparel and other value-added products. ``For us, the
northern tier has been a big plus,'' says David Link, chief
economist at the American Textile Manufacturers Institute. ``But
(farther) down, it's unrealized potential.''
 &HT;    To top it off, the Asian economic crisis is starting to take its
toll on many countries' textile industries, which find themselves
competing with lower labor costs and better-made products coming
from China and the Pacific Rim at the same time they're battling a
flood of cheap Asian product coming through their borders.
 &HT;    In mid-July, for example, Venezuelan textile maker Sudamtex de
Venezuela announced it would cut its work force by nearly a third
and shut down its textile-manufacturing operations at Arrowvale in
the U.K. as a result of the Asian financial crisis. The move will
result in US$10.5 million in charges, severance payments and other
restructuring expenses.
 &HT;    Mexico sewn up. For Mexico, however, the textiles industry is
one of the country's great success stories. With open access to the
huge U.S. market guaranteed by NAFTA, which was implemented in
1994, domestic textile companies are flourishing while foreign
firms are flocking to take advantage of Mexico's low wages and
efficient work force.
 &HT;    A few optimists even predict Mexico will become the ``Hong
Kong'' of Latin America, the leader in all aspects of the textile
business from fibers to fabric to clothing. Working conditions vary
greatly. But in a country that needs jobs as badly as Mexico,
worries about the quality of jobs often take a back seat to the
need for more work.
 &HT;    In terms of volume, Mexico exported more textiles to the United
States than China as early as 1996. In terms of dollar value, it
took over the No. 1 spot this year, pushing through $2.9 billion
between January and May, up 25.3 percent.
 &HT;    Bancomext, the government's foreign-trade bank, reckons Mexico's
total textile exports could reach $9.6 billion by the end of the
year _ more than the expected value of the country's oil exports.
 &HT;    ``There has been a very important (transformation) in the
textile sector as companies have invested in new equipment,'' says
Jaime Farell Campos, who tracks the industry at Bancomext. ``Most
recently, the industry has been taking advantage of NAFTA in
finding new markets.''
 &HT;    Mexico is also becoming a primary focus for multinational
textile firms, drawn by the quick and easy access to the U.S.
market and wages that start at about $120 per month for low-skilled
workers. U.S.-based companies like Tommy Hilfiger and Phillips-Van
Heusen Corp. make shirts, while Wrangler and the Gap sew together
jeans. Du Pont S.A., a subsidiary of U.S.-based chemicals giant Du
Pont, makes a range of synthetic fibers.
 &HT;    In the last few months alone, Du Pont and Monterrey-based Alfa
have announced investments of $450 million to boost nylon
production and build a new polyester plant in the port city of
Altamira. U.S.-based manufacturer Guilford Mills is spending $100
million on a knitting, dyeing and finishing plant in Altamira.
Asian companies are also setting up factories.
 &HT;    Most recently, U.S.-based Burlington Industries, which
manufactures textiles, apparel and interior furnishings, announced
plans to invest $80 million over the next three years to build four
garment factories in Mexico. When completed, the new sewing and
cutting operations will add $225 million to the company's $2
billion in annual sales. ``The combination of our U.S. plants and
our Mexican facilities makes us globally competitive and presents
new growth opportunities, '' George Henderson III, chairman of
Burlington, said at the announcement.
 &HT;    All together, the National Textile Industry Chamber expects
textile companies to spend at least $1.2 billion over the next two
years modernizing plants and building new ones.
 &HT;    ``NAFTA is pushing all this growth, and the idea at Du Pont is
to manufacture these products in North America,'' says Horacio
Ojeda, director of business planning in Du Pont S.A.'s fibers
division. ``But it's broader than that. We're also interested in
exporting to markets in Europe, Latin America and Asia.''
 &HT;    There are still challenges left. Paradoxically, Mexico is
strongest in fibers production and the cut-and-sew business, in
which cloth is turned into garments. But it is weaker in the
intermediate stage of fabric production, the transformation of
fibers into cloth.
 &HT;    That might change soon. Late last year, Burlington Industries
announced it would spend at least $200 million on two new fabric
plants and a yarn-making plant in a joint venture with U.S.-based
Parkdale Mills. The three plants, all of which are located in
Morelos state, are near completion. Government officials want more
such facilities.
 &HT;    ``We hope that companies that just assemble will begin to add
more value locally, incorporating more domestic cloth and fibers,''
Bancomext's Farell Campos says. ``The goal is to create more of the
added value in Mexico.''
 &HT;    State governments are also eager for investment. In Morelos,
just south of Mexico City, Du Pont, Alfa, Burlington Industries and
Guilford Mills sponsored the Nustart development, Mexico's first
industrial park devoted exclusively to textiles. Nustart opened in
1997 and is already sold out.
 &HT;    Now states like Guanajuato, Oaxaca and Jalisco _ eager for the
hundreds of low-skill jobs the textile business generates _ are
trying to attract similar developments.
 &HT;    In other parts of Mexico, the textile business has become a
leading economic engine. Torreon, in the northern state of
Coahuila, has become a large denim production center, reviving
local cotton growers in the process. ``My sister is moving to
Torreon and she can't find a house,'' Du Pont's Ojeda says.
 &HT;    Brazil on the mend. While Mexico's textiles industry is
thriving, Brazil's is having trouble surviving, with a substantial
drop in cotton production, wide-spread layoffs and a significant
number of manufacturers that have either gone bankrupt or shut down
altogether.
 &HT;    The crisis began in 1995, when President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso put in force his economic stabilization program, the Real
Plan. While it slashed annual inflation from four digits to one, it
also jeopardized domestic industries that were not prepared to
confront the administration's free-trade policy.
 &HT;    ``It was a disaster,'' says Ricardo Steinbruch, director of
Vicunha Nordeste, South America's largest blue jeans and denim
manufacturer. ``Brazil became the wastebasket for Asian products.
They dropped prices to the bottom line and sent their products
here.''
 &HT;    The government realized its mistake and took some measures to
reduce the impact of the Asian invasion, such as more rigorous
control of export licenses and minimum reference prices for Asian
products.
 &HT;    The textile industry still hasn't regained its grandeur. Less
than 10 years ago, the textile industry was one of the Brazil's
leading employers, accounting for a work force of more than
540,000. That's been almost cut in half to 246,500, according to
the Institute for Studies and Industrial Marketing (IEMI).
 &HT;    That's not all. The number of textile companies has shrunk from
4,938 in 1990 to an estimated 3,638 in 1997. In the city of
Americana, the traditional textile center in Sao Paulo state, more
than 50 percent of 1,300 textile companies and garment plants have
closed or gone broke since 1995.
 &HT;    Cotton production has also fallen, from 1.8 million tons in 1992
to 1 million tons last year, largely because imported product is
cheaper than what's being made domestically. ``Manufacturers prefer
to import, borrowing foreign loans at lower interest rates than
local credit charges,'' says Ana Paula Gorini, a textile analyst
with the government's National Bank for Economic and Social
Development (BNDES).
 &HT;    As a result, textiles are becoming less important to Brazil's
overall economy. The industry contributed only 1.1 percent to the
country's gross domestic product in 1996, the most recent official
figure released by the Brazilian Institute of Geography and
Statistics (IBGE).
 &HT;    The industry's major players include Rhodia and Alpargatas
Santista Textil in Sao Paulo, Coteminas in Minas Gerais and Vicunha
in Sao Paulo and Ceara state. About 13 percent of Brazil's textiles
industry is made up of foreign companies, including U.S.-based Du
Pont and the Netherlands-based Polyenka.
 &HT;    Production stretches from basic fibers _ rayon staples and
polyester filaments _ to denim, twills and designer tailoring.
About 20 percent of Brazil's production is exported largely to
other Latin American countries and Europe.
 &HT;    In this survival-of-the-fittest contest, companies have reshaped
themselves by reducing their work force, installing computerized
machinery and making their plants internationally competitive. Some
have even migrated to Brazil's center west and northeast regions to
take advantage of tax incentives and cheap labor. Northeast garment
laborers, for instance, are paid $3 a day, less than half of the
wages earned by their counterparts in southern Brazil.
 &HT;    Textiles central. While Brazil's textiles industry rejuvenates
itself, Central America and the Caribbean, along with Mexico, are
gradually replacing Asia as the center of textile export production
to the United States, primarily maquiladora offshore assembly.
 &HT;    The countries belonging to the Caribbean Basin Initiative (CBI)
saw their share of U.S. textile imports increase from 16 percent in
1992 to nearly 24 percent in 1997. Last year alone, their exports
to the United States rose 26 percent to $7.7 billion, according to
the U.S. Commerce Department. In the first five months of 1998,
they were up another 12 percent.
 &HT;    A number of U.S. companies have textile plants in the area to
take advantage of lower labor costs, favorable tax treatment and
proximity to the United States.
 &HT;    Sara Lee is one of the biggest, with operations across the
region. Its knit-products division, which makes Hanes and Hanes Her
Way underwear and T-shirts, has manufacturing plants in Costa Rica,
the Dominican Republic and Jamaica, while its Champion division
operates garment manufacturing facilities in Costa Rica. Meanwhile,
Bali, its intimate-apparel division, makes bras in Costa Rica, the
Dominican Republic and Honduras.
 &HT;    While textile business with the United States is up, the CBI
countries have called for NAFTA parity so they can regain the level
of growth achieved before the agreement came into effect.
 &HT;    They've made some headway. U.S. President Bill Clinton promised
some relief during his 1997 trip to Costa Rica. He even included a
plan to expand trade benefits for apparel and textiles from CBI
countries in his 1998 budget.
 &HT;    But last November, a bill that would eliminate all quotas and
tariffs on CBI textile imports went up in flames two days before
the ill-fated fast-track bill was pulled from the floor of the U.S.
House of Representatives.
 &HT;    The U.S. Senate is now considering a similar bill, but this time
only products made with U.S. fabric would be allowed free entry. If
the bill doesn't pass through Congress by the end of its session in
October, which is likely, then it will have to wait until next
year.
 &HT;    Industry leaders in both the U.S. and Central America are
clearly dissatisfied with the new bill. ``The (House) bill was good
because it would have given the CBI nations the same benefits
Mexico enjoys and would lead to more free-trade agreements with the
U.S.,'' says Erik Autor, international trade counsel for the
National Retail Federation, a U.S.-based trade group. Complains
Alfredo Milian Jerez, coordinator of the textile advisory
commission of the Salvadoran Association of Industrialists (ASI):
``The U.S. idea of parity is not parity.''
 &HT;    Even without NAFTA parity, several Central American and
Caribbean countries have managed to become important centers of the
Latin American textile industry.
 &HT;    The textile sector in the Dominican Republic, for example, has
taken off.
 &HT;    Over the last five years, exports to the U.S. have risen almost
50 percent in dollar terms, from $1.2 billion in 1992 to $1.8
million last year. It is now the biggest textile exporter among CBI
countries, with more than 80 companies making everything from
T-shirts and blouses to shorts, trousers and skirts.
 &HT;    It's helped that the country has lowered its trade barriers
related to textiles. Last year, President Leonel Fernandez
eliminated all import taxes applied to raw materials for the
textile industry, including fabrics, yarns, chemicals, machinery,
equipment and parts. They were substantial: According to a U.S.
Commerce Department report, import taxes ranged from 10 percent to
25 percent of the value of the product and an ad-valorem tax for
the transfer of products and services amounted to 8 percent.
 &HT;    Not only did the opening help U.S. producers _ who supply 65
percent of imports _ sell into the Dominican Republic, it also
helped the country's producers, who could now bump up production
and renovate old machinery to improve production.
 &HT;    Honduras is also an important producer. In terms of textile
exports, it ranks No. 5 in the world, second among CBI countries
and first in Central America. Over the 12 months ended in May, it
exported $1.7 billion worth of textiles and apparel, up almost 22
percent over the same period last year.
 &HT;    Companies like Sara Lee and Fruit of the Loom have set up
manufacturing facilities in Honduras, while retailers like JC
Penney, the Gap, Wal-Mart and the Limited have contracted out local
companies to assembly clothing for them.
 &HT;    Next door in El Salvador, the textile industry has been hard hit
by NAFTA and its own government's monetary policies. But it's
managing to eke out some growth.
 &HT;    The country is currently the 10th-largest exporter of textiles
to the United States, pushing through $1.25 billion in 1997
(including non-maquila exports and foreign-source maquila inputs).
Its share of the total U.S. import market increased from less than
1 percent in 1992 to more than 3 percent in 1997.
 &HT;    El Salvador has 240 maquilas that either cut and make or cut,
make and trim textile products. Of those, approximately 30 percent
are foreign-owned-mostly U.S. firms such as County Line Sportwear,
Brooklyn Manufacturing and Sara Lee Intimates and South Korean
firms like Daewoo El Salvador. But they account for about 70
percent of total-sector export volume and about 70,000 jobs. In
addition, El Salvador has some 30 textile factories _ defined as
non-maquila processing and/or full-package plants _ that employ
about 10,000. Another 250 to 300 small plants target the domestic
market.
 &HT;    Besides NAFTA, Salvadoran producers and exporters have suffered
from a narrowly focused government monetary policy, which has
maintained the colon at a fixed exchange rate for the past five
years.
 &HT;    The policy was designed to foster macroeconomic stability and
attract foreign capital. But the country still lags behind all of
its neighbors in direct foreign investment, which was only $25
million in 1996 _ the latest available figure _ according to the
U.S.-based Inter-American Development Bank (IDB).
 &HT;    The fixed exchange rate effectively penalizes Salvadoran exports
and local producers. Exporters are at a disadvantage compared with
countries like Mexico and Honduras, which have devalued their
currencies in recent years.
 &HT;    Industry sources also say the monetary policy subsidizes
imports, which, along with declining import tariffs, are
threatening local producers' position in the domestic market.
 &HT;    To top it off, El Salvador has the highest production and labor
costs in the region after Costa Rica. And while Costa Rica enjoys a
higher standard of education and the image of safety, El Salvador
is considered the most violent country in the hemisphere, according
to a 1997 IDB study. Concerns over public security have kept many
foreign firms away.
 &HT;    Since it started exporting in the early 1980s, Guatemala has
also become a big textile producer in the region. It offers foreign
investors a vast array of tax benefits, mostly through free-trade
zones.
 &HT;    As a result, its apparel exports have mushroomed, from $5.5
million in 1986 to $299 million last year, according to Banco de
Guatemala. In the first four months of this year, Guatemala's
exports jumped 18 percent to $115 million.
 &HT;    NAFTA, however, took the wind out of Guatemala's textiles
industry. Since the agreement has been in force, the country's
textile exports have slowed from 44.2 percent in 1994 to 6.7
percent last year.
 &HT;    Guatemala just got a break. This past May, the United States
dropped a quota restraint on imports of cotton and manmade
fiber-skirts from Guatemala.
 &HT;    This is no small thing: Guatemala is the United States'
fourth-largest foreign skirt supplier, with about 6.3 percent of
the import market after India, Mexico and Taiwan.
 &HT;    The Central American country now wants to offer more
full-package production, which would help the apparel industry
develop more clusters of supporting industries.
 &HT;    The industry employs 54,000 workers at 234 factories around the
country _ 17 of which are owned by U.S. companies _ that make
everything from knit and woven shirts and cotton trousers, shorts
and skirts to wool coats, skirts and trousers.
 &HT;    Like Guatemala, Costa Rica also set up free-trade zones some
years ago that allow duty-free imports of product. The country now
does a bustling business with drawback companies, which import
precut cloth, assemble it into a finished or semifinished garment
and export it to the United States or Europe or sell it locally and
to the Central American Common Market. More than 50 drawback
companies are currently operating in Costa Rica.
 &HT;    But the real boost came in 1995, when Costa Rica signed a
free-trade agreement with Mexico. Modeled after NAFTA, the
agreement eliminated tariffs on $5 million worth of clothing
manufactured with foreign-made materials, rising 15 percent per
year until the end of 1999, when it will be abolished.
 &HT;    More importantly, the pact provided that Costa Rica and Mexico
could export an unlimited amount of non-qualifying apparel to each
other so long as the fabric needed to make the products is not
available in either country at the price or in the quality or
quantity required by the manufacturer.
 &HT;    The agreement enticed many major U.S. manufacturers to set up or
expand assembly or manufacturing operations in Costa Rica. They
include Hanes Tejidos Costa Rica and Manufacturera de Cartago,
divisions of Sara Lee that make ladies and girls intimate apparel;
Centro Industrial Manufacturero El Roble, the Levi Strauss licensee
for Central America; and Warner's de Costa Rica, which makes
women's lingerie.
 &HT;    ``With Wal-Mart and other retailers opening stores in Mexico, it
makes (a) tremendous amount of sense for a U.S. company to operate
in Costa Rica so it has the option of shipping to Mexico as well as
the U.S. market,'' says Jerry Watkins, general manager of Cartex
Manufacturera, a division of U.S.-based Harwood Companies that
assembles men's boxer shorts in Cartago.
 &HT;    The proof is in the numbers. According to Costa Rican textile
association Camara Textil Costarricense (CATECO), the country's
exports of textiles rose 16.8 percent last year to $788.4 million.
In the first half of this year, they amounted to $359.7 million.
Ninety-five percent of Costa Rican textile exports are to the
United States.
 &HT;    Outlook. While some Latin American countries' textile industries
have been hard hit by NAFTA and the fallout from Asia, there's
optimism all around.
 &HT;    Analysts predict Mexico will continue to boost its exports and
bring in new investment. Central America and the Caribbean are
expected to become more developed textile centers while they lobby
to achieve NAFTA parity. And Brazil is working to become more
efficient to combat cheap Asian imports.
 &HT;    Indeed, in this ever-increasing world economy, only the
strongest textile companies in the region are expected to survive.
``We've reached the end of the line,'' Vicunha's Steinbruch says.
''(Those) who were unable to modernize dropped out and those who
remain are ready to compete in a globalized market.'' En garde,
Asia.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
