   SCI-AIDS-COCKTAIL (Undated) _ Two attempts to simplify the
burdensome schedule of medications prescribed to suppress HIV
infection have failed, allowing resurgence of the virus,
researchers are reporting in studies involving nearly 600 patients.
The two studies were designed to test an idea on which many
scientists and patients had pinned their hopes: that therapy
combining three powerful antiviral drugs, the ``cocktail,'' might
diminish HIV infection to such a low level that the virus could
then be kept in check by fewer drugs and the body's own immune
system. That way, instead of having to take the triple combination
for life, as some experts had predicted would be necessary,
patients might be able to back off and escape some of the side
effects, inconvenience and expense. By Denise Grady. (1200 words)
</P>
