<HEADLINE>
A CLIP-ON ANTENNA FOR CELLULAR TELEPHONES  
 `FATAL ERROR' ON ENTRANCE TEST TURNS OUT TO BE NOT SO BAD  
 NEW PROJECTION TELEVISION PROMISES LIGHTER VIEWING  
 WITH SECURITY FEARS FADING, IT IS TIME FOR ONLINE BARGAINS  
 ELECTRONIC COMBINATION LOCK DESIGNED TO KEEP OUT HACKERS  
 FUNK &AMP; WAGNALL'S AVAILABLE ON THE INTERNET, AND IT IS FREE  
 LAWSUIT AGAINST A SPAMMER FILED UNDER NEW OREGON LAW   
 BOY SCOUT HANDBOOK ADDS A PAGE ABOUT THE INTERNET  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y., N.J., Ore., Wash., Va.)  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PCS cellular telephone transmissions would be much clearer if
not for one thing: the cellular telephone user's cranium.
</P>
<P>
   A Silicon Valley company, RangeStar International, contends that
the signals coming from PCS phones _ the latest generation of
digital wireless phones _ radiate through 360 degrees, meaning a
good portion of them run directly into, and are absorbed by, the
user's head. In an effort to find a way around the pesky cranial
protrusion, RangeStar is selling an antenna the company says will
redirect the cellular signal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What our antenna does is redirects signals away from the head
and makes it more of an effective signal,'' said Alan Brune, the
company's director of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The small black device, which costs $29.95, clips onto the
existing PCS antenna and turns it into a high-performance antenna,
RangeStar said. The company contends that, as a result, it can
increase the phone's range, improve the effective battery life by
limiting time lost for dropped calls, and reduce by ``50 percent or
more the signal loss to the head.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Fatal Error' on Entrance Test Turns Out to Be Not So Bad  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no fun time to receive a ``fatal error'' message on
your computer screen, but 400 business school applicants found out
last week that some times are more unnerving than others.
</P>
<P>
   The applicants had just finished taking the three-hour
computerized version of the Graduate Management Admission Test _ a
prerequisite for admission to business school _ at test centers
when the words ``fatal error'' popped onto the screen.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the message was simply a ``display error'' caused by a
computer bug, said Kevin Gonzalez, a spokesman for the
Princeton-based Educational Testing Services, which administers the
GMAT. Gonzalez said that none of the test scores were affected and
that the bug, which affected 400 of 10,000 people who took the GMAT
between Oct. 12 and Oct. 21, has been corrected.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of test-takers, who did not know that the glitch was
innocuous when they finished the test, were unnerved. Andrea
Wilson, a spokeswoman for Kaplan Educational Centers, which offers
test preparation courses, said some of the test takers called
Kaplan in a panic about the glitch.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Projection Television Promises Lighter Viewing  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Samsung Electronics America Inc. says it can make the decision
to buy a television less weighty _ by more than 40 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Samsung is preparing to introduce a new 40-inch television that
weighs only 65 pounds, far less even than some 27-inch models.
Samsung's secret is in what the viewer sees _ no, not lighter
programming _ but a rear-projection screen that the company says
requires less bulky infrastructure than the traditional
televisions.
</P>
<P>
   The picture on the screen is created when light from a 100-watt
halogen bulb is projected onto a 1.4-inch diagonal Liquid Crystal
Device. Mark Knox, a senior marketing manager at Samsung, said that
LCD-based screens require less glass than televisions with
traditional screens, and less space than most big-screen projection
televisions.
</P>
<P>
   Several television manufacturers already offer rear-projection
LCD televisions in several countries in Asia, but the market is
just opening up in the United States, Knox said. Meanwhile, just
because the television weighs less does not mean it will be light
on the wallet. Samsung suggests a price of $1,899 for the 40-inch
television, and $2,799 for the 52-inch version. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Security Fears Fading, It Is Time for Online Bargains  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORk _ A new survey indicates web users apparently need a
better reason to start shopping online than the mere idea of
shopping online. And the survey, from Jupiter Communications Inc.,
indicates that a good way to inspire greater E-commerce is if
online retailers would start offering lower prices, or very
attractive specials.
</P>
<P>
   It seems obvious, but therein lies a noteworthy change in the
thinking of prospective online shoppers, according to Nicole
Vanderbilt, one of the authors of the survey for Jupiter, a New
York market research firm. Ms. Vanderbilt said that, not long ago,
the biggest hindrance to online shopping was the fear that
transactions would not be secure; now, she said, the greater
obstacle appears to be that people simply are not finding the
bargains they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``This marks the next phase of consumer adoption of the online
channel,'' Ms. Vanderbilt said. ``If we did this survey two years
ago, the focus would've been on security. Now it's on incentive.''
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Electronic Combination Lock Designed to Keep Out Hackers
</P>
<P>
   The agency that helped create some of the world's biggest bombs
has now helped create its smallest combination lock _ a bit of
technology aimed at preventing attacks by computer hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at Sandia National Laboratories have invented a
combination lock the size of a button. The reason for its
diminutive size is that the lock is meant to be placed inside a
computer, where it can be used to secure the contents of the hard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Like a standard combination lock, the Sandia invention has
mechanical wheels _ six of them _ that can be turned to the
combination that opens the lock. The wheels are microscopic and are
turned, not manually, but with computer commands entered with a
keypad.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, this class of tiny mechanical devices is
known as a microelectromechanical system. Practically speaking,
this could be an advance in the battle against hackers, said Frank
Peter, a mechanical engineer at Sandia who helped design the lock.
</P>
<P>
   When the device is in place, it essentially ``locks'' the
connection between the hard drive and the rest of the computer. As
a result, a hacker would not be able to gain access to the hard
drive from the network, or even sitting at the computer itself.
</P>
<P>
   Some security experts believe the Sandia scientists may have
locked on to a good idea. ``Certainly something like this, if
deployed properly, could keep you from getting away with''
sensitive information, said Robert Stratton, chief technologist for
Security Design International, a computer security firm in Falls
Church, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Sandia scientists say it will be two years before this device or
a form of it is commercially available. In the meantime, maybe they
can think of a better name for the combination lock, which, is now
simply called the ``recodable locking device.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Funk &AMP; Wagnall's Available On the Internet, and It Is Free
</P>
<P>
   A long-time ago, there was something known as the print version
of the Funk &AMP; Wagnall's encyclopedia, a 29-volume set of the
world's history that sold door-to-door for thousands of dollars.
Here is how much things have changed: the encyclopedia now takes up
zero shelf space and is free.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Versaware Technologies Inc., which licenses the
digital content from Funk &AMP; Wagnall's, plans to publish the entire
encyclopedia on the Internet, for free, and including new
multimedia capabilities like audio and video clips. Versaware also
will publish hourly news updates from Reuters and access to the
Random House Webster's College Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   The move to give away the whole shooting match for free may
inspire some users to wonder whether New York-based Versaware
should itself use the dictionary to look up the word
``capitalism.'' A company spokesman, Mathew Barlow, said that
Versaware is not running a charity, but hopes to use the site to
inspire visitors to buy even more multimedia rich versions of the
Funk &AMP; Wagnall's encyclopedia that come on CD-ROM and Digital Video
Disc. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuit Against a Spammer Filed Under New Oregon Law
</P>
<P>
   In what is believed to be the first lawsuit brought by a state
against a spammer, Jason Heckel of Salem, Ore., has been sued for
violating Washington's law against misleading commercial e-mail.
Heckel, 24, has admitted to sending between 100,000 and 1 million
pieces of e-mail per week soliciting interest in a get-rich-quick
scheme, said Paula Selis, senior counsel in the consumer protection
division of the state attorney general's office. A trial date has
been set for March 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington law, which took effect on June 11, prohibits
sending unsolicited commercial messages _ spam _ to any e-mail
account identifiable as belonging to a Washington resident, if the
messages have misleading subject lines, use a third party's domain
name without permission or misrepresent the message's point of
origin. Heckel's e-mail included the subject line of ``Did I get
the right e-mail address?'' _ the kind of subject line that might
appear on e-mail from a college friend.
</P>
<P>
   The law includes a fine of $2,000 per piece of illegal mail
sent.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get angry about spam,'' Ms. Selis said. ``They don't
like receiving it, especially if it has misrepresentations in it.
Having a law like this on the books gives consumers and the
attorney general's office a tool to protect consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ TINA KELLEY  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boy Scout Handbook Adds A Page About the Internet
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, ``The Boy Scout Handbook,'' that trusty life
guide used by almost 100 million boys throughout the century, will
include a page on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might already be using the Internet for school work,
hobbies, or simply for enjoyment,'' says the handbook, which is to
be released early next year. ``For all of its benefits, though, the
Internet can also present hazards you should know about and
avoid.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11th edition of the handbook _ the first revision this
decade _ cautions users never to disclose personal information like
addresses and telephone numbers. It also urges youngsters to never
agree to meet anyone who has contacted them online unless a parent
or guardian accompanies them. In other words: be prepared.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHEL MARRIOTT &QL; 
 &QL;
