<TEXT>
<P>
   The following stories, from The New York Times Education Life
supplement of Sunday, November 1, will move today.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-TEACHER-STANDARDS (Undated) _ The debate on how to turn
out quality teachers has long bedeviled educators. It happened
after the Civil War, with the rise of industrialization and the
shift in skills needed as American workers migrated from the farm
to the factory. It happened after Sputnik, when the Soviet Union's
launch of the first satellite was taken as a sign of the poor
quality of American math and science education. And it is happening
anew, with test results showing that American students are behind
their peers in other industrialized nations on math and science,
and lagging in literacy. By Randal C. Archibald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Features: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-EARLY-ADMISSIONS (Undated) _ Over the last two or three
years it has become apparent that the college application process
has radically changed, at least at the most competitive colleges,
which are filling more and more of their classes early and leaving
fewer slots for regular applicants. While early decision-making
gives some students the ability to short-circuit a year of
agonizing over applications, for others it means enormous pressure
to pick a school quickly. By Peter Applebome. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-OLEMISS-DIXIE (Oxford, Miss.) _ A century and a half ago,
the University of Mississippi sent its sons off to the Civil War. A
century later, it waged a civil rights battle of its own. But now,
under new pressures, the university is trying to take the dixie out
of Ole Miss. By Kevin Sack. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-HOMESCHOOLING-GRADS (Undated) _ They are pioneers, in a
way: the first wave of the modern home-schooling movement, the
first generation of children to be taught primarily by their
parents. Some 15 years after states began legalizing home schooling
in earnest, these early graduates are starting to make their way in
the world. By Pam Belluck. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-MAILORDER-HIGHSCHOOL (Undated) _ The Independent Study
High School, based at the University of Nebraska in Lincoln, was
founded in 1929 as a correspondence program to educate rural
Nebraskans. The school has one of only a few fully accredited
distance-education programs offering high school diplomas. It
offers an option for the children of diplomats and missionaries, or
those who can't or don't want to go to a schoolhouse every day. By
David M. Herszenhorn.
</P>
<P>
   EDLIFE-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Education notes and news: sweatshirt
sweepstakes; typing classes for third-graders; other items. By
Stephanie Gutmann.
</P>
<P>
   For story questions or repeats call Jack Topchik at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. E-mail: topchik(at)nytimes.com
</P>
