 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Whom You Gonna Call? Bad-Grammar Busters! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Need help positioning an adverb? Having an existential tussle
with ``me'' and ``I''? Elisabeth Piedmont-Marton, purveyor of the
grammar hot line at the University of Texas at Austin, will lend a
sympathetic ear. And she's heard it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``They call to confess, to settle bets, to gather ammunition for
arguments with their bosses and to voice jeremiads about the state
of American English,'' said Dr. Piedmont-Marton, Ph.D., who runs
the university's Undergraduate Writing Center and the hot line.
``But when they have spent hours arguing over whether it is correct
to say, `It is I' or `It is me,' you have to wonder if they
shouldn't be exploring something else about their relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The grammar hot line _ (512) 475-VERB _ will help untangle your
syntax from 9 a.m. to 10 p.m. Central Time, Monday to Thursday, and
to 3 p.m. on Friday. The staff receives several calls a day, a
dozen at midterms and finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine that answering the grammar hot line is a lot like
answering other kinds of hot lines,'' said Dr. Piedmont-Marton, a
former English teacher and textbook writer and editor. ``We aren't
giving instructions for CPR or delivering babies over the phone,
but we do offer a calm, competent response to anonymous callers
buffeted by the shifting winds of grammar and usage.''
</P>
<P>
   _LYNETTE HOLLOWAY
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stark White Paper: Those Were the Days &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There are good reasons to create a personal Web site, besides
having a place to display photographs of your cat and Bon Jovi. It
can also be an electronic portfolio, featuring essays you've
written, scores you've composed, scenes you've acted in.
</P>
<P>
   Schools are beginning to see the potential, encouraging students
to create their own sites, or even requiring them at a few
colleges, like Kalamazoo in Michigan and Coe in Cedar Rapids, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, all incoming students at Coe College are required to
start a site as a kind of journal of their work, adding to it as
they go along. Laura Skandera-Trombley, vice president for academic
affairs, calls the sites a way to ``archive their academic
achievements and to assist advisers in keeping track of student
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the ideal. In these early stages, students'
sites seem directed more toward their wired classmates than their
teachers. Content includes ``my vacation in Europe,'' ``my cat,''
``my mom,'' etc. One Coe student has constructed an
all-football-all-the-time site, offering a ``great link to keep up
to date with the NFL'' and the Green Bay Packers' home page, while
women tend to favor medievalism: unicorns, meadows, Goth fashion,
forest glades.
</P>
<P>
   Important questions to ask as assigned Web sites proliferate: Is
prose enhanced by a background of leaping flames and pulsating
rainbows? When does a personal Web site turn into just one more
seductive cathode-ray screen calling students away from homework?
</P>
<P>
   _STEPHANIE GUTMANN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; At Christie's, Master's in the House &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Education has become the weapon of choice in the war between the
two titans of the art market, Christie's and Sotheby's. Over the
last decade, both auction houses have opened special divisions
offering a range of courses about the history and appraisal of fine
art and decorative objects. Both even offer advanced degrees in
their London headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Now Christie's in New York is touting a sheepskin of its own:
this fall, 30 students began working toward their master's degrees
in connoisseurship and the art market, a program designed for
people who want to work in auction houses, galleries and museums.
The program, accredited by the New York Board of Regents, includes
classes on developments in painting and sculpture from 1850 to the
present; business courses; and field trips to view public and
private collections.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Watson, director of the Downtown Arts Project, an
arts-education umbrella group, explained why education is such a
potent weapon for the auction houses. ``It makes absolute sense in
terms of their marketing strategy,'' said Watson, who keeps tabs on
the scene via his art world newsletter, Simon Says. The auction
houses ``want to be a full-service, fine-arts provider, offering
one-stop shopping for any customer.'' It's all very Viacom, very
Disney, he said. ``They can learn about art there. They can get a
degree in art there. They can buy it. They can sell it and then
they can die there and move everything in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is much more important,'' he continued, ``than those
one-night lectures where you meet groovy people who are collecting,
drink a glass of champagne and maybe see John-John or something.''
When people actually invest in a master's degree, they ``become
troops,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Is Sotheby's threatened? Not really, sniffed Kathleen Martin,
the director of Sotheby's education division. They have been
thinking of adding a master's program in New York, too, she said,
and started ``the original'' master's in London. ``They're the ones
who got nudged,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _STEPHANIE GUTMANN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Style Perennial: Dirty Old Sweats &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Harvard and Yale may be America's most prestigious universities,
pantheons of scholarship and yada yada yada, but as far as
marketers are concerned, they are brands, trademarks that can
really move the merch.
</P>
<P>
   Ivy League cachet has sold everything from Harvard Beer (brewed
in Lowell, Mass.) to Harvard Cigarettes (smoked in India) to
Harvard Eggs (available in Korea; they make you smarter) _ all
unauthorized appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   But now Harvard and Yale, along with their English counterparts,
Oxford and Cambridge, have joined in an agreement, licensing their
names to a line of logo-emblazoned T-shirts, sweats and baseball
caps.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking any old T-shirts, sweats and baseball caps,
mind you. According to Helen Kauder, director of Yale's licensing
programs, this will be ``casual apparel that evokes, or is based
on, archival images of scholar-athletes from the '30s and '40s,''
like ``the ones of George Bush in his 1948 Yale baseball team
uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   The line, to be sold in the United States and Western Europe
beginning this winter, is the brainchild of Lee and Dan Mirman,
brothers and owners of Pangea, which markets European university
T-shirts and sweats on the Continent.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Mirman explained the aura: ``Imagine your great-grandfather
was a scholar-athlete at Cambridge. After three years of playing
rugby, he threw his jersey into his footlocker. Fifty years later
that footlocker ends up in your parents' attic, and you're up there
looking for something and come across this footlocker, and you blow
off the dust and there's the jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   How does this aura translate to T-shirts?
</P>
<P>
   Everything will look ``as if it's been worn 100 times,'' he
said. Cap visors and leather straps will be faded, brass buckles
scratched, cuffs prestretched.
</P>
<P>
   And how do the designs differ?
</P>
<P>
   They don't. Each university will be represented by the same
clothes. Only the logo will distinguish one scholar-athlete from
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just a few institutions that have a history rich
enough to do this,'' Ms. Kauder said.
</P>
<P>
   _STEPHANIE GUTTMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Workshops On Tornadoes And Terrorism &LR;
</P>
<P>
   After fatal shootings over the last school year in Oregon,
Arkansas and other parts of the nation, the mantra among
educational administrators is gun preparedness. The Federal
Emergency Management Agency, noting the prevalence of gangs and
other dangers in schools, has added a segment on violence to its
multihazards training course, which teaches education staff
techniques to evacuate and protect children in the event of an
earthquake, high winds or, now, a gun-toting intruder or student.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Villahermosa, who teaches what he calls the ``man-made
disaster'' component of the program for FEMA and individual state
agencies, said the number of times he has been hired to teach his
workshop on school violence has grown by 25 percent in the last
year. ``In tragedy we learn,'' said Villahermosa, who is also a
deputy sheriff in Pierce County, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Some tips:
</P>
<P>
   1. Take a proactive approach. ``Notice when a kid's behavior
starts changing,'' Villahermosa said, ``when he starts getting
moody, when his friends change, grades drop. In four or five of
these shootings, kids knew something was wrong with the shooters.''
</P>
<P>
   2. Learn hand signals to communicate with other staff members.
Two fingers raised means ``Don't leave me!'' A closed fist
indicates a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   3. Carry color-coded cards to the playground. A child can run to
the office with cards that signify different situations _ red, for
example, for ``Call 911.''
</P>
<P>
   4. Don't duck under a desk. While that strategy may work for
earthquakes and air-raid drills, ``if someone walks into a
classroom and opens fire indiscriminately, there's not one desk
that's going to stop a bullet,'' Villahermosa said. ``It's easier
to hit a nonmoving target. The people who survive run.''
</P>
<P>
   _STEPHANIE GUTTMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Package Deal For College &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In these boom times, with part-time jobs going begging in the
service economy, college students can afford to be picky. That's
why United Parcel Service in Louisville, Ky., the company's busiest
package-processing hub, began its own version of the G.I. Bill this
fall: free tuition at three local colleges _ the University of
Louisville, Jefferson Community College and Jefferson Technical
College _ in exchange for a semester-by-semester commitment to work
20 hours a week on UPS' most-difficult-to-fill midnight shift.
</P>
<P>
   And it's grueling, hefting boxes onto conveyor belts or into
trucks in the middle of the night. But people like Michael Hayes,
20, formerly of Flatwood, Ky., were so elated by the prospect of
free tuition that they moved to Louisville to take jobs. He now
lifts 25 large (up to 150 pounds) packages a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes is one of 850 employees _ 650 new ones lured by free
college and 200 company veterans _ who started school this semester
at what is being called Metropolitan College; 150 young people are
on a waiting list, and UPS expects to eventually put 2,000
employees a year through school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an inkling we could get more students if we could get a
college to offer classes on a schedule that was conducive to
working in the middle of the night,'' says Ken Shapiro, a UPS
spokesman, ``and we were ready to offer some kind of incentive to
get people in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusual deal developed when UPS started talking about
expanding its plant, hiring more workers and, if necessary, moving
to find them _ maybe out of state. At stake were about 21,000 UPS
jobs. After learning of the company's staffing needs, the city
offered to pay 50 percent of the tuition in the program, as well as
provide the usual please-don't-leave tax breaks. (Tuition ranges
from $800 to $8,040 a year, depending on a student's residency
status, the school and the course load.)
</P>
<P>
   To insure that there are appropriate schedules for these special
students, who need to sleep during the day, the three schools added
a total of 78 classes in the hours of 5 to 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   UPS and the city are also constructing a dormitory (it won't be
free) with special soundproofing, heavy blinds and more classrooms,
and offering shuttle bus service between the job, the dormitory and
classes.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, said John Kinney, director of Metropolitan College, is
to ``develop a group who can function with an altered circadian
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   _STEPHANIE GUTTMAN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; See Dick and Jane Type (Photo) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to be afraid, very afraid, of the world's
elementary school children: not only do they lack the grace to act
confused around computers, but an increasing number will also be
able to churn out term papers with the speed of court stenographers
by the time they reach the sixth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the ubiquity of home and school computers, typing
classes, once a backwater for high school students shunted onto the
vocational track, are becoming part of elementary school
curriculums around the country. The Pelham Union Free School
District in New York's Westchester County, for instance, puts all
its third graders into a four-day, touch-typing crash course using
Typin's Cool, one of several child-friendly teaching methods used
in schools from Williamsburg, Va., to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Typing classes in the 1990s are decidedly multimedia, and the
instruction features videotapes, cartoons and music. But most
students have yet to achieve court-stenographer speed. Fourth
graders at Colonial Elementary School in Pelham, N.Y., who began
its immersion course last year at 2 to 6 words per minute, ended up
at only 10 to 15 words _ but after the class, the students had
improved their ergonomic approach and had eschewed the
hunt-and-peck habit, according to Gerald Finelli, the principal.
</P>
<P>
   This is one skill started ``the sooner, the better,'' said
Georgina Hancock, one of the creators of Typin's Cool. Children at
7 or 8 are less reluctant to study a manual skill, she said, and
less phobic about getting stuck in the back office.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just seeing the keyboard as a tool to get their ideas
on the screen,'' Ms. Hancock said.
</P>
<P>
   _STEPHANIE GUTMANN
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
