<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1917 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDLIFE-EARLY-ADMISSIO     10-28 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDLIFE-EARLY-ADMISSIONS-$ADV01-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE EARLY-DECISION BANDWAGON 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Nov. 1) 
(JT) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREAT NECK, N.Y. _ The senior-year obsessing had the quality of
timeless ritual as eight top students at Great Neck South High
School gathered to discuss their college application plans one
morning in September.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone was intent on a designer-label college (three Yale, two
Harvard, one MIT, two still thinking). Everyone said there was too
much pressure. A few voiced dutiful reminders that there were
plenty of great schools and no one should think his life is over if
he doesn't get into Harvard. But the underlying angst recalled
generations of high school seniors and parents in wound-too-tight
New York suburbs, where getting into the right college is the only
game in town.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that most seniors applied to four or five
colleges, usually by mid-January, and got word in March or April.
But every one of the Great Neck students, even those not yet sure
where they wanted to go, was planning to apply through some kind of
early-acceptance program. The plans allow students to apply to one
favored school in early fall, with an answer in mid-December, but
they also obligate them to enroll there if accepted.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago only a handful of students at Great Neck South
applied early. This year, in a class of 226, almost a quarter will.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two or three years it has become apparent that the
college application process has radically changed, at least at the
most competitive colleges, which are filling more and more of their
classes early and leaving fewer slots for regular applicants.
What's less clear is whether what's good for colleges is good for
students. If early decision gives some students the ability to
short-circuit a year of agonizing over applications, for others it
is leading to enormous pressures to pick a school quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some kids who know from the ninth grade where they
want to go,'' said Michael Cheng, a Great Neck senior who was
trying to decide between Stanford and the University of
Pennsylvania. ``But a lot of kids aren't sure where they want to
go, but they feel they have a better chance of getting in early, so
they really have to do it. That's where most of my friends are
right now. Most of them think that even if they're not sure, they
have to apply early.''
</P>
<P>
   The plans are not new. They have existed for decades for the
rare student committed early in the senior year to a single school.
But colleges are now adding programs willy-nilly. Two decades ago,
about 120 colleges and universities, mostly selective, private
ones, offered some form of early admission. Now almost 500 do. The
proliferation of plans and the perception that students will miss
out if they don't apply early are making the admissions process
much more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Studies by the National Association for College Admission
Counseling, in Alexandria, Va., indicate that almost everything _
from application due dates to chances of getting in early _ varies
from school to school.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a third of colleges surveyed use different
standards for early decision than for regular admission. Of these,
half say the early-decision standards are higher, and half say they
are lower. (They give special consideration to these applicants
because they show a strong commitment to the school.)
</P>
<P>
   Some schools, like Swarthmore, Stanford and Smith, now have two
early-decision deadlines, one in the fall and one early in the
winter. Most colleges are willing to defer a final decision on
early applicants who don't get in, rejecting only the weakest and
giving others a second look later. But a few, like Northwestern,
flatly accept or reject all early candidates. Northwestern says it
has the same admissions standards for all students, but other
schools, like Duke and Johns Hopkins, give an advantage to
early-decision applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Admissions experts say that because there are enough slots open
at all schools during the entire process, no one should feel
obligated to apply early. But for many parents and students,
applying early is seen more as a requirement than an option. The
panic is most pronounced in the Northeast and high-dollar pockets
in other parts of the country, where competition to get into top
colleges is most intense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense that the whole process has gotten out of
hand,'' said Joyce Smith, the executive director of the National
Association for College Admission Counseling. ``People, at the
least, expect the process to be transparent; they want to
understand what the deadlines are and what the nuances are and how
decisions are made. I don't think that's the case right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the terminology can be a bit confusing. There are four main
admissions options:
</P>
<P>
   _The traditional process allows students to make multiple
applications, usually due by mid-January, with responses coming in
March or April.
</P>
<P>
   _In early-decision plans, students can apply early _ usually
between Nov. 1 and Dec. 1 _ to only one school. They agree to
enroll if accepted, though if financial aid is insufficient, they
can get out of their commitment. Students can have only one
early-decision application pending at any time, and once accepted,
they must withdraw any regular applications.
</P>
<P>
   _Early-action plans, which are far less common, but are used at
some top schools like Harvard, Brown and MIT, allow students to
apply early to one school. If accepted, they are not obligated to
attend but can go through the rest of the process knowing they got
into their early choice. Applications can be rejected outright or,
more often, deferred until the spring. Although these plans can be
riskier for colleges, top schools usually get a high enrollment
rate from accepted applicants. And since the programs have no down
side for students, they encourage strong candidates to apply.
</P>
<P>
   _In rolling admissions plans, which are also less common,
colleges review applications as they are received, sending out
acceptances and rejections throughout the school year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The more desired schools, in particular, are taking increasingly
big chunks of their classes before most applicants have even
applied.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, last year, for the first time, Harvard accepted
more than half its class early. Columbia accepted 45 percent;
Dartmouth and Yale, more than a third. Officials say the process
varies from year to year, depending on the number and quality of
the applicants, but the trend over the last few years is more early
admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the colleges' point of view, it's great,'' said Tom
Gaines, the guidance office chairman at Great Neck South. ``They
get a lot of first-round draft choices and then they can use the
rest of the process to mold the demographics of the class from
there. If I'm a college administrator, I have to think this is the
way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other advantages. With the crush of applications, it
makes sense to start the process early. Early decision also gives
colleges more financial leverage. Students increasingly shop for
the best aid package, pitting one school's offer against another's.
With binding early decision, there's no such bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, early decision works best for students who are
least reliant on financial aid. It also works well for those who
don't need their senior year to improve grades or show increased
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Among the appeal for students is knowing before Christmas where
they'll go to college, as well as getting the chance to stretch: if
early-decision applicants get special consideration, the process
represents a shot at a school that may otherwise seem out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   So Kevin Hsueh, another Great Neck South senior, figured he'd
apply early to Dartmouth or Williams, and if he didn't get in, he'd
apply as a regular applicant to the University of California at
Berkeley, Wesleyan, Cornell and New York University.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you really know that this is the school for you?'' he
said. ``But I figure this gives me a chance to go for a little bit
of a stretch, so there's nothing lost in trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Others find the strategizing more complicated. Should you apply
early to your second- or third-choice school, to avoid being shut
out of it in the spring if your first-choice college proves too
much of a stretch?
</P>
<P>
   Generally, colleges and high school counselors insist that no
one should apply early unless certain of his or her choice. And the
pressure to narrow those choices can be particularly hard on
students Dr. Gaines refers to as ``throwbacks'' _ those who have
been more interested in learning than in building the right resume
to dazzle the Ivies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had a strong feeling I had to apply one place,'' said
Kyra Jucovy, a student who was trying to decide among a number of
schools, including Harvard, Brown, Swarthmore and Amherst. ``I wish
I had that sensation. I don't know where people get it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other problems. Having so many students already
accepted to colleges can put added burdens on high schools to keep
seniors engaged.
</P>
<P>
   It can also put certain strains on colleges. More than a third
of colleges in the association's survey said students are not
honoring early-decision commitments the way they used to. Though
students must file a nonrefundable deposit at some point, the
system operates on trust, not on anything legally binding.
</P>
<P>
   But since the process generally works for colleges, few expect a
concerted effort to move away from early applications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that the college board, our organization and
others have been grappling with this issue,'' Ms. Smith said,
``because it seems we've moved further and further away from the
traditional understanding and definition of early decision. But I'm
not sure much can be done about it. It feels like the train is out
of the station, and everyone is trying to catch up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Rx for Application Fever: A Dose of Early Acceptance &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Early-decision programs, in which a student applies early to one
school and commits to enrolling if accepted, work for some students
but not all. Carol Loewith, president of the Independent
Educational Consultants Association, an organization of freelance
admissions consultants based in Fairfax, Va., offers a few tips:
</P>
<P>
   _Read applications carefully. Deadlines and details vary.
</P>
<P>
   _Visit a school before applying, and do it early. Campus visits
that used to be made in the fall of senior year should be done in
the previous summer or in the spring of junior year.
</P>
<P>
   _Do your homework. Does the school usually defer or reject early
applicants who don't make it? Is it easier or harder to get in? If
the standards are higher for early-decision applicants, and the
school usually rejects these applicants instead of deferring
consideration, you may want to wait.
</P>
<P>
   _If you've underachieved on grades or SAT's, a good showing
senior year will help your chances. Early decision may not work for
you.
</P>
<P>
   _If you're not sure a particular school is best, consider
early-action plans. Though far fewer schools offer them, they are
the most advantageous for students, assuring them acceptance
without obliging them to attend.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't panic and apply early to a school that may be wrong for
you. Except at the most selective schools, which rely on early
decision to fill more and more slots, the trend is not greatly
changing the admissions equation. No school takes so much of its
class early that a superior candidate doesn't stand a chance of
getting in during the regular admissions process.
</P>
<P>
   _Still, if you're interested in one of the most competitive
schools, give the early-decision option serious consideration. ``In
the past,'' Ms. Loewith said, ``I said early decision is only good
if you absolutely love the school. This year I find myself saying,
`If it's a place you really want, even if there are others you
might like as well, it might be worth doing.' If your best chance
of getting into Yale or Harvard or Columbia is early decision, then
in some cases it might be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
