<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT &LR;      10-28 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDENING QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Birdhouse Gourds
</P>
<P>
   Q. When are birdhouse gourds ready for harvest? Must they age or
dry out after harvesting? How does one make a real birdhouse from
the birdhouse gourd?
</P>
<P>
   A. Think small birds. Like most hard-shell gourds, bottle gourds
(Lagenaria siceraria), which are used for birdhouses or musical
instruments, prefer a long, hot season to grow and ripen. Start
seeds indoors, about three to four weeks before the last frost,
then plant outside in full sun once the night temperatures remain
above 60 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   I know a Northern gardener who helps his heat-loving vines along
by letting them climb and sprawl on an arbor built over an asphalt
driveway. The black asphalt captures heat during the day and
releases it at night, helping the vines to explode with lush, leafy
foliage and fragrant, night-blooming flowers. It also helps the
fruit to mature.
</P>
<P>
   Let the vines grow as long as they can, until light frost
withers the plants. Harvest the gourds, including a couple of
inches of stem. Hang them up to dry at room temperature, spacing
them for good air circulation. Let the gourds dry until you can
hear the seeds rattle around when you shake them _ anywhere from
six months to a year, depending on the size.
</P>
<P>
   If you want homemade maracas, you are done, except for the fancy
painting. For a birdhouse, cut a hole far enough up from the base
for a bird to feather its nest, but not up into the neck area. You
want the birds to be able to get in without banging their heads
against the back wall. The size of the hole depends on the birds.
Chickadees, for example, need a one-and-a-half-inch hole. Larger
birds will need a larger hole, and a larger gourd. Add one or two
small drainage holes in the bottom, clean out the seeds with a
spoon and it's ready. Or don't clean it out, and let the birds have
the seeds as a moving-in gift.
</P>
<P>
   Quick Cover
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you have any information as to which are the fastest
growing evergreens?
</P>
<P>
   A. It really depends on your needs. Most requests for fast
growing evergreens come from people who discover that their new
neighbor collects junk cars. If that's the case, then a fast grower
like white pine might not be a good choice. While it grows as much
as 50 feet in 25 years, it eventually loses some lower branches,
letting the glint from those old hubcaps shine through. It is also
sensitive to salt, making it a poor roadside choice if your
community uses salt in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Is your site wet? The tall, slender Atlantic white cedar
(Chamaecyparis thyoides) will do just fine.
</P>
<P>
   Are you making a hedge? Canadian hemlock works well, but wooly
adelgid attacks mean a high maintenance obligation.
</P>
<P>
   I know you see it everywhere, but Eastern arborvitae (Thuja
occidentalis) does make an effective, quick growing hedge. A more
handsome version _ the Western or great arborvitae (Thuja plicata),
does well from Boston to Cincinnati to Raleigh, N.C., despite the
Western connotation of its common name.
</P>
<P>
   A grouping of three to five tall, pyramidal Japanese cryptomeria
forms a screen, not really a hedge, although it works better as a
single specimen tree. The feathery Leyland cypress (x
Cupressocyparis leylandii) gives a more columnar screen, and grows
in coastal areas from Massachusetts to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   For large, single specimens, Norway spruce (Picea abies) and
Atlas cedar (Cedrus atlantica) grow quickly when young, then slow
down.
</P>
<P>
   Spend a little time looking before you buy. Large evergreens are
a strong presence in the landscape, summer and winter. This is a
great season to go to public arboretums and botanical gardens and
look at mature examples. Do you have the room? Is it as cute at 30
feet, or at 80, as it is in a container?
</P>
<P>
   Growing Cherimoyas
</P>
<P>
   Q. A few weeks ago in Chinatown I bought cherimoyas from a
street vendor. My first exposure to this fruit was 25 years ago in
Venezuela. Since then I've been hooked on its unique flavor, a
mixture of strawberry and pineapple. I have grown many exotics from
seed, but when I scarified and soaked my cherimoya seeds, sprouts
never appeared. I do not think that the fruits were frozen in
transport, nor did I refrigerate them. My only conclusion is that
they must have been irradiated by the Food and Drug Administration.
Is there hope in growing this wonderful fruit in my own backyard?
</P>
<P>
   A. The FDA does not irradiate or require imported food to be
irradiated. Quarantine and inspection are still the methods of
choice for protecting the food supply.
</P>
<P>
   You can grow cherimoyas if your backyard happens to be in a
subtropical, frost-free region that doesn't get too humid in the
summer. Israel would do, or Egypt, Chile, parts of South Africa or
some areas of California.
</P>
<P>
   It's too humid in Florida, but Dr. Jonathan Crane, a tropical
fruit crop specialist at the University of Florida's Tropical
Research and Education Center in Homestead, has experimented with
growing cherimoyas from seed. He found that the seed seems to have
an after-ripening requirement. Seeds that have been well cleaned
(don't want any fungus) should be left to age in a plastic bag at
room temperature for at least three months (six is even better).
Soaked for a day and planted one-half-inch deep in well drained
growing medium and kept moist, they will germinate in three to four
weeks. However, this only works if the pot has bottom heat so the
medium is kept at 80 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   That's the easy part, relatively speaking, and it will result in
a large, full-sun foliage plant. Fruit is another matter. After
three to eight years as a juvenile, your cherimoya may flower, but
the species of beetle that pollinates it will not be around _ the
FDA inspections keep them out of the country. And hand pollinating
is tricky because the male and female flowers bloom at different
times. Well, you've got a few years to figure out how to imitate a
beetle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to:
</P>
<P>
   Garden Q&AMP;A
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times
</P>
<P>
   229 W. 43rd St.
</P>
<P>
   New York, N.Y. 10036
</P>
<P>
   or by e-mail to:
</P>
<P>
   gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished
questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
