<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1933 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUADALAJARA-ARCHITECT     10-28 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUADALAJARA-ARCHITECTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUILDING ON A FIELD OF DREAMS IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ind., Fla., Calif.)   (bl)  
 By PHILIP NOBEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget Bilbao. The future of architectural pilgrimage may be in
Guadalajara, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   With a brand new fortune and an ambition that rivals that of
Walt Disney Co., the Omnilife Group, a Guadalajara-based
vitamin-drink company, is sponsoring a giant new
business-and-cultural center at the edge of that sprawling city.
</P>
<P>
   The imperial-scale project, which could begin construction as
early as February, promises to raise the bar on extravagance for
out-of-the-way places looking to put themselves on the
architectural map. Why settle for a single building by Frank Gehry
when you can afford to hire 10 other star architects as well?
</P>
<P>
   The list of projects for the new satellite city _ on a 750-acre
swath of farmland just beyond Guadalajara's beltway _ reads like a
lifetime supply of dream jobs: In addition to a possible
contribution by Gehry (who remains undecided), plans call for an
entertainment complex by Wolf Prix, a partner in the architecture
firm Coop Himmelblau in Vienna; a contemporary art museum by Toyo
Ito of Japan; a 25,000-seat amphitheater by the New York team of
Tod Williams and Billie Tsien; a hotel and 80 units of housing by
Stephen Holl of New York; a fairground landscape by Carme Pinos of
Barcelona, and a state-of-the-art convention center by Enrique
Norten of Mexico City, who is also overseeing the design of the
site plan and acting as the overall talent coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Libeskind, the American architect living in Berlin whose
first building, the Felix Nussbaum Museum, opened in Osnabrueck,
Germany, in July, is working on what the project's organizers call
a University of Success, to house departments of education,
government and architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Thom Mayne, the impresario behind the Santa Monica firm
Morphosis, is designing a ``palenque,'' a traditional Mexican
cockfighting ring to be used also for bloodless concerts and
sporting events. And on a site near the center of the project, the
French architect Jean Nouvel is to design a new headquarters for
Omnilife.
</P>
<P>
   The mastermind behind this play for architectural immortality is
Omnilife president Jorge Vergara Madrigal, 43. At first glance, he
is an unlikely Medici. Before he founded Omnilife in 1991, he said,
he earned a living by frying pork on the streets of Guadalajara.
Then he went broke. Struggling back to solvency _ and away from
fatty foods _ he became a distributor for Herbalife, a producer of
nutritional supplements, but he quit after becoming dissatisfied
with what he saw as Herbalife's insensitivity to Mexican culture.
</P>
<P>
   When he founded Omnilife, with six distributors and three
employees, Vergara set out to make vitamin-enriched drinks in
flavors, like coffee and cola, that he thought would better appeal
to the Latin American palate. Adopting the pyramidal distribution
structure used by Herbalife and Amway, Omnilife grossed, Vergara
said, $240 million last year in sales of its 52 fortified beverage
products, through the efforts of its reported 700,000 Mexican
distributors.
</P>
<P>
   The company also operates in Guatemala, Costa Rica, Colombia,
Peru, Argentina, Spain and the United States, primarily in
California and the Southwest. In the United States, it has
recruited 12,000 mostly Spanish-speaking distributors to sell its
wares.
</P>
<P>
   Given Omnilife's youth and rapid expansion _ and the fact that a
final construction budget will not be released until January _ many
of the architects involved admitted to feeling wary at first about
Vergara and his project, which is also to include an undetermined
amount of additional housing and commercial space in a projected
second phase.
</P>
<P>
   At a forum sponsored by the Architectural League of New York on
Oct. 8, Ms. Tsien described how she and Williams reacted to the
project: ``We said, `Oh, great, we're going down to Mexico, and
there's this guy who sells vitamins who is somehow going to make
this project work?' It seemed too good to be true.'' Now, after
having worked with Vergara since May and having visited the site,
they are more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   Prix attested to the ``incredible power'' of his client. ``He
has charisma,'' Prix said, ``and I was impressed by his social
thinking. He really believes that when he builds a school it will
improve education for young Mexican kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Gehry's skepticism remains unassuaged. The other architects
are reserving a site for what would be his building, a performing
arts center at the edge of an artificial lake, but Gehry said he
needed to hear more about the feasibility of bringing
infrastructure like water, sewers and roads to the undeveloped
site. ``When I'm convinced it's real,'' he said, ``I'll jump in.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike similar projects, such as those by Cummins Engine Co. _
which turned Columbus, Ind., into something of an architectural
museum, with buildings by Saarinen, Pei, Weese, Meier, Polshek and
Venturi, among others _ or by Disney _ which has amassed a
collection of trophy architects at its theme parks and in
Celebration, Fla. _ Vergara has directed his team to collaborate
very closely on all phases of the design.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent visit to Manhattan, he waved his hand at the
view from his high corner suite at the Four Seasons Hotel. ``Here,
you see all these different buildings, and some of them don't
integrate well with each other,'' he said. ``I want the architects
to be able to join together to plan how to make a more beautiful,
more livable space, and to think how their buildings would
integrate with the other guy's building across the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether this grand vision of architectural harmony is too good
to be true may be apparent soon. The amphitheater and fairgrounds
are expected to be completed by December 1999, in time to be the
site for what Vergara calls a ``millennium cultural event.'' The
rest of the complex is scheduled to be finished by 2003, when the
Pan American Games go to Guadalajara. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1712EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
