<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BRONX-GARDEN-ART-N     10-28 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRONX-GARDEN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTISTRY IN THE GARDEN: A STUDY IN CABBAGES AND KALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There's a proud green serpent of vegetables
undulating over the grass at Wave Hill, the public garden in the
Riverdale section of the Bronx, known for its imagination and
unusual plants.
</P>
<P>
   I had never seen columnar basil before, for instance, until I
saw it last week, marching along the inner curves of an S-shaped
fence that forms the backbone of this garden, where giant heads of
a metallic-blue cabbage named Scarlet O'Hara are set off by the
smaller heads of a green cabbage called Dynamo, and red kale stands
a good four feet over grassy-green oak-leaf lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   The basil is called Aussie Sweetie. ``I hate the name, but it
has a wonderful shape,'' said Marco Polo Stufano, Wave Hill's
director of horticulture. ``It's a woody plant, and it gets taller
than this, but we just shear it like a hedge.''
</P>
<P>
   Aussie Sweetie _ which makes a peppery pesto, by the way _ is
just one of the stars of a vegetable garden that's more like a
living sculpture, with its grand architecture of vine-covered
towers and raised pots full of red and purple chili peppers or
flaming lettuces, flanked by billowing golden amaranth, Swiss chard
leaves as big as canoe paddles, and carpets of curly parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Like many works of art, it began in a hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw this reinforcing wire in a building supply store,''
Stufano said, explaining the bones of his latest piece of
performance art. The sturdy fencing _ 4-by-4-inch squares of wire _
has been used to build cylindrical towers, which vary in height,
from 12 feet at the head of this beast to 5 feet at its tail. The
same fencing forms an S-shaped backbone down the middle, creating a
satisfying horizontal to the vertical towers.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, before all that chlorophyll started pumping away
and these wire cylinders and curving fence were still bare, they
were satisfying in a different way. ``Every stage of design should
feel good,'' Stufano said. ``If it doesn't, the bones aren't
right.''
</P>
<P>
   And now, each vegetable, so beautifully tended, is in itself a
work of art. The swirling leaves of a cabbage head are kind of
astounding, if you take the time to look at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People enjoy seeing vegetables grow,'' Stufano said, ``and
they  &UR; should &LR;  see them. We could have planted them in rows, but
this isn't a farm.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll say. ``Some people have never seen an eggplant growing,''
he continued, ``and they'll stop and say, `Oh! So that's what it
looks like.'''
</P>
<P>
   Sort of like seeing a cow being milked at one of those farms
that has to take in tourists to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I've ever seen that,'' Stufano mused. ``I
don't know if I ever  &UR; want &LR;  to see that. And I have no interest in
drinking warm milk, fresh from the cow.''
</P>
<P>
   But you don't have to tell the man to eat his vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love kale,'' he said, his voice getting cozy as he nodded
toward a diagonal line of curly kale, the plants as high as his
chest. ``I eat it sauteed with garlic, over pasta.''
</P>
<P>
   And although he's disappointed with the color of Bright Lights,
the Swiss chard with the supposedly sunny yellow veins (more like
curdled cream), its hefty leaves inspire a dish his Italian mother
used to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would brown some garlic in olive oil, then add some
potatoes,'' he said. ``When those are half cooked, you add the
cut-up chard and maybe a little chicken stock. It turns into this
sticky, wonderful comfort food.''
</P>
<P>
   It was only 11 a.m., and I was starving.
</P>
<P>
   The vegetables have been planted with Stufano's exquisite eye
for pattern and color. A generous blue-green terra-cotta pot, set
inside a waist-high cylinder of reinforcing wire, is bursting with
the crinkled, dark crimson leaves of a lettuce called Merlot.
</P>
<P>
   The curving fence supports a vine of filigreed leaves and
strange oblong fruits that appear to be covered with blisters.
Balsam pears, as they're called, start out pale green, then turn
orange as they ripen, finally opening at their tips to dangle big
red seeds at gaping strangers. It's sort of a Times Square,
pre-Disney vegetable. When I asked what it tastes like, Stufano
mumbled something about an Indian friend who says you can fry the
skins like potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we bring British gardeners here to design
kitchen gardens,'' Stufano said, referring to garden designers like
Rosemary Verey and Penelope Hobhouse, who have many American
clients. ``Americans have a long tradition of vegetable gardens,
like Mount Vernon and Monticello. And even a farm row has a kind of
beauty, with space between the rows, and between each plant, so you
can see its architecture. The repetition is part of it, too.''
</P>
<P>
   I thought of the pilgrims I had seen in Ms. Verey's kitchen
garden north of London, meticulously copying the patterns and
plants into notebooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A garden shouldn't be a clone,'' he said. ``Or a decoration
for the house. It should be an expression of yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The vines on the towers are a study in contrasts, from the
delicate cardinal vine, with leaves as finely pointed as birds'
feet and little red flowers, to the sturdy leaves as big as hands
that scramble over the tallest cylinder. This is Sicana oderifera;
its common name, cassabanana, must refer to its enthusiastic
fruits, which turn orange-crimson and are quite odoriferous under a
tropical sun. Here, they just stay green.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the cucumber family,'' Stufano said, pointing to two
fruits way overhead that seemed to have forgotten that cucumbers
are not the size of watermelons.
</P>
<P>
   I left the garden wondering who first got this notion of
vegetables as sculpture. The Egyptians painted sheaths of wheat on
their tomb walls. Did Pliny the Younger twiddle with cabbages on
the terrace of his seaside villa near Rome? Was a gardener in
Pompeii admiring her curly parsley when the volcano blew?
</P>
<P>
   I'll get back to you on that. But in the meantime, check out the
works of art at Wave Hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
