NYT-10-28-98 1716EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1953 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABT-BALLET-ART-NYT &LR;      10-28 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABT-BALLET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION AND LAUGHTER AS DANCER MEETS DIVA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cecilia Bartoli does not dance onstage with Angel
Corella every night, but she did on Tuesday when American Ballet
Theater opened its new season. Corella did not break into song.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a perfect match: young Italian mezzo-soprano
superstar (Bartoli) meets young Spanish ballet virtuoso (Corella)
and both knock out audience at chock-full-of-chuckles gala.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, this special opening of Ballet Theater's second
annual season of mixed bills at City Center (131 West 55th St.,
through Nov. 7) was packed. Ms. Bartoli, who also sang four
selections on a Spanish theme, appeared as a guest, exuding both
good humor and just plain humor, in a vignette choreographed by
Kevin McKenzie. Wisely, it was called ``Piece d'Occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the evening was just as lively. A revival of Anton
Dolin's 1957 ``Variations for Four'' made implicit some competition
among four male soloists while Antony Tudor's satiric ``Gala
Performance'' made the competition among three turn-of-the-century
ballerinas more than explicit.
</P>
<P>
   The program was completed by ``Sinfonietta,'' Jiri Kylian's
exuberant paean to mother earth, enhanced by trumpeters letting
loose with fanfares while standing at both sides of the proscenium.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bartoli is a fan of Corella and on this evening, he returned
the compliment she offered by appearing with him. They met on the
same ground, virtuosos in their respective arts and both exhibiting
a love of performance.
</P>
<P>
   Happiness is a performance by Angel Corella, but at the ripe old
age of 23, he has also grown out of his whiz-kid bravura to combine
an astonishing technique with artistic depth.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie, who welcomed the audience in a curtain speech as
Ballet Theater's artistic director, choreographed to Corella's
strength, and ``Piece d'Occasion,'' in its references to Spain, was
a tribute to him. One has never seen him circle the stage or fly
across its diagonals in his jetes or a variety of pirouettes with
such amazing speed. Yet McKenzie also wittily integrated Ms.
Bartoli into a star vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Insofar as Ms. Bartoli can be said to hum anything, she entered
humming the air that introduces the heroine's seduction scene in
Bizet's ``Carmen.'' It was enough to make Corella stop dreaming
about his paella as he lounged at the feet of the onstage pianist,
Steven Blier.
</P>
<P>
   Snaking and whirling her way through a mock seduction dance, Ms.
Bartoli's red-bodiced Carmen took less then 10 minutes to steal
Corella from Ashley Tuttle, a good sport enlisted for the straight
man role.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tuttle had a brief solo on toe during Ms. Bartoli's
exquisite rendering in French of a lover's lament, ``Hai Luli!'' by
Pauline Viardot-Garcia and she was turned upside down in a duet,
accompanied by Ravel's ``Vocalise-Etude (en Forme de Habanera).''
</P>
<P>
   Understandably drawn by the richness of Ms. Bartoli's voice,
Corella sent Ms. Tuttle packing and walked, dazed, toward Ms.
Bartoli. And she became a chattering shrew, thanks to one of the
``Canciones Negras'' that the Catalan composer Xavier Montsalvatge
wrote in what he called a West Indian style.
</P>
<P>
   More fun came in ``Gala Performance,'' which featured Susan
Jaffe's ever-superb performance as the Italian prima ballerina with
a stealthy tread and exaggerated balances on one leg. The
character's marble-like demeanor was only a facade for a lethal
interior, as her hapless rivals found out.
</P>
<P>
   Eleena Melamed may be a corps member, but her debut as the
applause-milking Russian ballerina caught the right mix of pathos
and arrogance. Bent over, thrusting her face toward the audience,
dynamically right in shooting out her legs in a flamboyant display,
she was less a cliche than a case study that Tudor, the king of
psychological ballet, distilled with genius.
</P>
<P>
   Yan Chen's debut as the French ballerina offered some delightful
frills, not the usual fussiness, to describe the character's
flightiness. Vladimir Malakhov, new as her partner, combined his
elegance with some hilarious glowering. Ethan Brown, as Ms. Jaffe's
partner, got the right idea across with terrific comic timing, a
19th-century partner used as the equivalent of stage crew. Tudor's
commentary, set to Prokofiev, is not about a once vital Romantic
style but about its decadence. There is a difference.
</P>
<P>
   What this revival of Dolin's ``Variations for Four'' is about is
not clear. Maxim Belotserkovsky, Jose Manuel Carreno, Ethan Stiefel
and Vladimir Malakhov are major dancers, and each had a solo in
this presumed display of male virtuosity and precision in classical
technique. Dolin choreographed the work in England for Festival
Ballet and two of the company's former stars, Jelko Yuresha and
Belinda Wright, are credited with this less than coherent staging.
</P>
<P>
   The sum is less than the parts. Belotserkovsky and Carreno turn
very well and Malakhov's princely line is seen to fine advantage in
an adagio variation. Stiefel elicits applause in springing up in
diamond-shape jumps and fabulous scissor leaps. But he looks like a
jester, not a dancer, just as this theatricalized showcase now
resembles a classroom demonstration. Failing to ``spot'' at the
same time (the equivalent of keeping your eye on the ball) the men
lost their unison in turning a la seconde with leg extended: the
pinwheel approach, one presumes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
