<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-WEB-WITCHES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITCHES ONLINE: NOTHING NEARLY AS SPOOKY AS YOU MIGHT IMAGINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARJORIE INGALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's perfectly reasonable that you'd be able to work magic over
the Internet,'' said Kristin Spence, a former editor at Wired
magazine. ``It's just another tool. Instead of a cauldron, you're
using a keyboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Spence is a self-proclaimed witch. She's ``out of the broom
closet,'' she said, she's proud, and she's got plenty of company.
There are posting and chatting sites for witches (or Wiccans, as
the more serious devotees prefer to be known) on Usenet
(alt.wicca), Internet relay chat ((NU)wicca) and in online
conferences (America Online's Pagan Board, the Commons at the
Witches' Web, www.witchesweb.com/commons.html). There's an entire
search engine, www.avatarsearch .com, devoted to the occult. The
Witches' League of Public Awareness, based in Salem, Mass., of
course, even has an area devoted to improving witches' image in the
media (www.celticcrow.com).
</P>
<P>
   Fritz Jung, Webmaster of the Witches' Voice (www.witchvox.com),
a clearinghouse of Wiccan information, estimates that there are
2,000 witchcraft-related Web sites. He says his own site receives,
on average, almost 17,000 hits a day. Why does he think there's
such a heavy witch presence on line?
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized the medium's communication and networking
potential early, and embraced it in a major way,'' Jung said. ``You
could also say that we had a stronger need for the Net. The big
religions have long had communication networks in place, but we
were very fragmented. The Net was a wonderful opportunity for us to
connect.''
</P>
<P>
   In his nonwitch life (and please, witches disdain the term
``warlock'' _ ``witch'' is sexually nonspecific), Jung is the
management information systems director for a musical instrument
retailer in Clearwater, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't see any contradiction in the fact that an earth-based
religion thrives in a silicon realm, or that a goddess-focused
faith flourishes in a largely male techie preserve. Some witches,
in fact, find that witchcraft and computers have a lot in common.
``Programming is like alchemy,'' said Ms. Spence, who signs her
e-mail with a smiley emoticon wearing a conical witch hat,  &QL; 
:) .
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like divination, a magical thing. You have a spell
or computer program you want to create, so you find an elegant way
to use a main routine and subroutines that refer back to
themselves. You construct a system of elements that need to work
together in harmony and balance to give the desired outcome.''
Presto.
</P>
<P>
   Witchcraft, or Wicca (both words are probably derived from the
Indo-European root wic, ``to bend''), is a modern take on an
ancient pagan belief system.
</P>
<P>
   Francesca De Grandis, author of ``Be a Goddess! A Guide to
Celtic Spells and Wisdom for Self-Healing, Prosperity and Great
Sex'' (Harper San Francisco, 1998), has a site full of rituals and
spells. Among them is one ``to free oneself from excessive computer
enchantment.'' Her site is
www.well.com/user/zthirdrd/WiccanMiscellany.html.
</P>
<P>
   Carrye De Mers, an editorial assistant at a math publishing
company in Emeryville, Calif., has an off-line coven but uses the
Web to enhance her spiritual practice. She rattled off the courses
she has taken through Pandora's Pagan Web, a site affiliated with a
Wiccan bookstore in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, there's Introductory Tarot, Candle Magick, Urban
Pagan and To Stir a Magick Cauldron _ that's the follow-up to Ride
a Silver Broomstick.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Ms. Spence be celebrating Halloween, the most important
witches' holiday, in cyberspace?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a purist in a lot of ways, so it's hard for me to imagine
that those who practice only in cyberspace are getting the full
hit,'' she said. ``I'd like to wrench people away from their
computers and make them stand on the beach in their bare feet. This
is a nature-based religion. But if on line is the catalyst to make
people feel safe and not alone in their beliefs, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
