<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-STAR-WARS-NYT &LR;      10-28 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-STAR-WARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS: BEHIND THE MAGIC': `STAR WARS' WORLD WITH A SENSE OF
HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: CD-ROM publication notes at the end of review.) 
(js) 
 BY J.C. HERZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A long time ago, in a galaxy far, far away, there was a movie
that was so resonant it became a universe. After a big cultural
bang, it grew and grew and grew to include sequels, novels, comic
books and galaxies of T-shirts, lunch boxes, towels, blankets and
toys. And miraculously, even the little bits of plastic had soul. A
Darth Vader action figure or plastic X-Wing fighter was more than
the sum of its mass-produced parts. It was a relic of the film, a
speck of the original magic. It was a way of connecting to the
``Star Wars'' universe.
</P>
<P>
   Star Wars: Behind the Magic is a multimedia chronicle of that
universe and the process of creating it _ a Baedecker of the George
Lucas trilogy containing 700 cross-referenced glossary terms,
detailed biographies of minor characters and an exhaustive
chronology of the overarching epic (``Star Wars,'' ``The Empire
Strikes Back'' and ``Return of the Jedi'' are only the middle chunk
of the nine-part saga.) Each alien is identified by species. Han
Solo's early history indicates why he became one of cinema's great
swaggering jerks.
</P>
<P>
   And in case you couldn't get enough of Leia in her slave-girl
outfit, there is a fully rotating 3-D model of her in a variety of
costumes, narrated in the plummy British tones of a Christie's
auctioneer: ``For rallying troops on the frozen world of Hoth or
exploring damp asteroid caves, nothing is more comfortable or
stylish than this functional rebel uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Further along the continuum of camp, a 30-second
computer-animated fashion show sends Leia vamping down the runway
in combat fatigues and ceremonial evening gowns as flashbulbs pop
and house music, intercut with dialogue clips, thumps in the
background. ``Star Wars'' meets RuPaul.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the Weapon Comparison Test Bay, where an unlucky storm
trooper suffers everything from Ewok stoning to Death Star cannon
fire, is Monty Python in drag. No doubt this will be heresy to the
true believers. But it's heartening to see the folks at Lucas Arts
spoofing themselves, as if to say, c'mon people, it's only a movie.
</P>
<P>
   That's what separates the Lucas Arts people from the folks at
Star Trek headquarters, who publish excruciatingly earnest CD-ROMs
like the Star Trek Technical Manual, a fully functioning
virtual-reality starship with all the knobs and dials laid out,
deadpan.
</P>
<P>
   Trek fandom revolves around technology because the Star Trek
universe was founded on ham-fisted dialogue and ``Gong
Show''-caliber acting. But the fictional science has always been
brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   The science in Star Wars is nonsense, and everyone knows it. But
no one cares because Star Wars isn't about science. It's epic
drama. It's about those incredibly well-developed characters and
the moral decisions they face. People don't get into debates about
how the second Death Star works. They get into debates about the
ethics of blowing it up, since all the construction workers aboard
were independent contractors with no allegiance to the Empire
beyond their weekly paychecks. Star Wars fandom is about stories
and the kind of wallop stories can deliver on a really big screen.
It's about our fascination with movies.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Behind the Magic is a digital product, it's
really about the particularities of cinema. From the scratchy black
and white 3-2-1 countdown that starts the program to the
scene-by-scene analysis with shot-numbered stills and annotated
screenplays, it's an ode to the filmmaking process. It lays bare
the revisions and the script doctoring, the discarded drafts and
lost scenes, and what happens when a writer-director changes his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, these films appear seamless and inevitable. But
when you see a badly printed outtake, or a rough edit before the
sound is added, it becomes apparent that no, this story did not
spring fully formed from the skull of George Lucas. It may be
mythic, but it's also an object. It was constructed. It is the sum
of 10,000 arbitrary decisions.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, seeing the skin pulled back doesn't compromise the
romance of these films. In fact, it enhances their mystique.
Witness the obsessive Star Wars prequel speculation on Web sites
like The Force (www.theforce.net). Episode one of the Star Wars
saga, ``Shadows of the Empire,'' won't be released until May 1999.
But on the Internet, storyboards, production designs and entire
screenplays are taking shape around the prequels' hypothetical
dimensions, based on crumbs and scraps of information gleaned from
a network of informants and spies: moles inside the Lucas movie
machine, trespassers hopping the fence at Leavesden Studios in
England to root around in the trash for filmmaking offal and media
junkies who trawl the news for cast members' stray remarks.
</P>
<P>
   What you see online is a potential film, a what-if blueprint,
the shadow of ``Shadows of the Empire.'' As information accrues,
the phantom movie grows to resemble its real-life counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   And when the information matches perfectly, when the real film
is released, the phantom film will cease to exist. But its archive
will remain as a document of the process, a record of the films
that might have been, a fan-fiction version of Behind the Magic.
Because if you really love a story, it's not enough just to hear
it. You want to help build it, if only by proxy.
</P>
<P>
   All these digital extensions and outgrowths on the Web only
enhance the aura of the original story, which is to say, the films.
Because the proliferation of small screens _ televisions, computer
monitors, LCD cellular phone displays, personal digital assistants
_ only aggravates our desire for the huge screen in a plushly
upholstered movie palace with three-dimensional symphonic sound.
The more fractured information becomes, the more we long for an
epic story that simply washes over us _ and not over one of us at a
time, but over all of us at once. The world is crawling with sound
bites and gadgets, and everyone's flocking to Imax.
</P>
<P>
   If we can't have The Force, we'll settle for the movies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Lucas Arts; CD-ROM for Windows 95 and 98; $29.95; for all
ages.)
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address: Herz(AT)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
