u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-KIDS-E-BOOKS-NYT &LR;      10-28 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-KIDS-E-BOOKS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)  
 DESPITE TESTS STACKED AGAINST IT, eBOOK PASSES  
 (af)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was 7 years old, my father took me to the public library.
While I browsed the familiar collection of picture books, he
disappeared down another aisle and reappeared carrying something
that looked entirely different from the usual
see-the-pretty-seashells fare.
</P>
<P>
   It was the size and shape of an adult's novel, filled with black
type. But on the front was a picture of a girl my age and the title
``Black-Eyed Susan.'' Excited, I realized this novel must be a
children's book, but in a format that was completely new to me. I
took home an armload of novels that day.
</P>
<P>
   For years I have not thought about ``Black-Eyed Susan,'' except
to wonder once in a while if the story of a Midwestern girl and her
bike was still on the shelf at my hometown library in Elmhurst,
Ill. But then last week an electronic gadget called the Rocket
eBook reminded me just what it is like to discover a new way to
read.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket eBook is the name of the so-called electronic book
that Nuvomedia started selling last week. Frankly, I had been
prepared to hate it. Ever since ``Black-Eyed Susan,'' I have been
shamelessly addicted to the perfection of that simpler medium known
as paper books. How could the gray plastic eBook hope to compete?
</P>
<P>
   As I unpacked the test unit, I muttered something about useless
toys for the nouveaux riches. The Rocket eBook, after all, was just
another computer, roughly the size of a paperback, with a
backlighted screen that displayed text.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, it came with two cords _ how I hate unfamiliar cords,
with confusing sets of prongs that have to be plugged into
previously unexplored ports on my PC. Worst of all, it could not be
as egalitarian as a paper book.
</P>
<P>
   The eBook costs a whopping $499, and that's just for the device.
You will have to pay for the books you download onto your eBook
from Barnesandnoble.com. (Prices will be announced any day, a
Nuvomedia spokeswoman said, and are expected to be roughly the same
as for paperback editions.)
</P>
<P>
   But as I started to poke at the screen with my finger (I
immediately abandoned the flimsy plastic stylus), I grudgingly
began to respect the design. When it comes to gadgets, the last one
that I figured out how to use _ throwing down the manual in
frustration and then whining to a tech support person for at least
an hour _ was a blow dryer. That has become my standard for
user-friendly technology.
</P>
<P>
   So I was amazed that within seconds I figured out not only how
to turn it on and off but also how to call up the text of ``Alice's
Adventures in Wonderland,'' one of three preloaded titles on the
test unit. Lewis Carroll's words and John Tenniel's illustrations
looked clear and crisp, and so of course I got carried away by the
story.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching the bottom of the page, I pressed an obvious-looking
button on the eBook's spine. Immediately, the next page of text
appeared.
</P>
<P>
   I decided to put the eBook to the real test _ the Black-Eyed
Susan test _ and see whether it interested my daughter. I hooked up
the eBook (via those two cords) to both my Windows machine and a
wall outlet, so I could register the unit at Nuvomedia's Web site
and download other books. Ten minutes later, I had ``Charlotte's
Web'' and ``Sarah, Plain and Tall.'' (Unfortunately, ``Black-Eyed
Susan'' went out of print years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   Then the moment of truth arrived. My 7-year-old, Ella, came up
to my office to see if I was ready to go to the library later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Dad say you could play with his Palm Pilot?'' she asked,
eyeing the eBook accusingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something else,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I see?'' Within seconds, she had figured out how to jab
the bookshelf icon to see a list of available titles (the eBook can
hold about 10 books). As I watched, she pressed the line of the
menu that read ``Charlotte's Web,'' and then an Open button below.
</P>
<P>
   She wandered off reading the eBook, and later I saw her fiddling
with the underline function, as well as annotating the text using a
built-in keyboard (``My sister Zoe is trying to take this book away
but I said NO mommmm gave it to me Zoee'').
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if I had actually paid $499, I would not have sent it
off so blithely in the care of the sort of person who would ask, a
few hours later, if it was OK to put the eBook in the bathtub to
see if it would float. But the eBook was going back to its
manufacturer in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   So that night, I let Ella take it to bed with her. The
backlighted screen acted as a night light; she could read in bed
for the first time since we moved her baby sister into her room
last winter.
</P>
<P>
   Will the eBook be a hit with parents? It will if Nuvomedia can
do two things. The first is to make it childproof. Apple has
already proved that this is possible, with its discontinued line of
eMate portables, which could withstand being dropped from a school
desk.
</P>
<P>
   The second would be to get the cost down to what a grandparent
might be willing to spend on a birthday gift _ say, $50. And why
not? Not long ago, handheld calculators cost hundreds of dollars. A
friend of mine got one free last week when he filled his gas tank.
</P>
<P>
   I called Cynthia Mun, Nuvomedia's director of product
management, to tell her what I thought. ``Um, thanks,'' she said.
``In fact, we were thinking it would be fun to have a sports
model.''
</P>
<P>
   The eBook passed another test in my house. Ella's introduction
to electronic reading devices did not supplant her love for good
old paper books; it supplemented the experience. The next day, I
found her old paperback copy of ``Charlotte's Web'' on the floor
next to the bathtub.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
