u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TWENTY-MILE-BOOK-REVI     10-28 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWENTY-MILE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INCIDENT AT TWENTY-MILE': TRYING TO RESCUE THE OLD WEST FROM THE
DUSTBIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can't help thinking of Hannibal Lecter at the start of
Trevanian's new novel, ``Incident at Twenty-Mile,'' his first to be
published in a decade and a half. The year is 1898 and in the
maximum-security wing of the state prison in Laramie, Wyo., Guard
Private John Tillman is touring the special cells to check on the
so-called moonberries, local slang for the criminally insane.
</P>
<P>
   Tillman starts with a man convicted for throwing acid in the
faces of children. `` `If I don't do it . . .,' he had explained to
the judge `. . . who will?''' He passes ``The Politician,'' who is
arguing with the space in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Then he comes to ``the baddest of the bad,'' a brilliant and
literate madman named Lieder who has maimed whole families in the
cause of electing William Jennings Bryan president and saving the
farmer and workingman from being crucified ``on a Cross of Gold,''
but who never kills because he knows he would hang for it.
</P>
<P>
   It's Lecter-like the way Lieder lures Guard Tillman into his
cell by pretending to want to be saved by Christ, and then proceeds
to strangle him to death and escape, taking two other prisoners,
who happen to be sodomites, along with him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet surprisingly enough, there's an overtone of unseriousness
about it too, just as there's an element of playfulness in all that
follows, when Lieder and his gang descend upon and terrorize the
tiny population of Twenty-Mile, a mere stopping-off place for
silver miners looking for Saturday night fun, ``so called because
it was 20 miles from a spot 20 miles away.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieder is sadistic and vengeful. He shoots helpless animals. He
paddles to death a former teacher of his. He tortures the owner of
Twenty-Mile's whorehouse by making him remain in his chair until he
urinates on himself. He threatens to rape the virginal town beauty.
</P>
<P>
   One's outrage with him grows and grows. But there is little hope
that any of the town's mostly defective people will be able to
stand up to him, including Matthew Dubchek, another stranger
recently arrived in Twenty-Mile, who models himself after his
literary hero, the Ringo Kid, but who tells a lot of lies and
lapses into a stupor every now and then.
</P>
<P>
   Although the story holds your attention completely, you don't
take it quite seriously. The author has too much fun with language:
``A susurrous scurry of sliding scree drew his attention to three
men climbing up the slope toward him.'' Too many of the characters
verge on parody, not least the town's three prostitutes: Frenchy,
``a tall, lean, yellow-eyed black woman from New Orleans; Chinky,
``a shy Chinese girl who spoke little English''; and Queeny, ``a
loud, laughing, sloshy-breasted old Irishwoman who was said to be
able to drink anything that didn't eat the bottom out of a glass
before she got to it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the author has to know his story has been told many times
before, from E. L. Doctorow's first novel, ``Welcome to Hard
Times,'' to films like ``High Noon'' and ``Unforgiven,'' to mention
only the most obvious. (``Incident'' even contains what can be read
as homages to its predecessors.)
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly is going on here? In an interview sent along
with the book's publicity material, Trevanian _ recorded in Who's
Who in America as the pen name of Rodney Whitaker, a former
professor at the University of Texas _ talks about his previous
novels, ``The Main,'' ``The Eiger Sanction,'' ``The Loo Sanction,''
``The Summer of Katya'' and ``Shibumi.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his readers have taken these books seriously enough as
entertainment to make them international best sellers, the author
insists they were written as spoofs of different genres as well as
``spoofs of spoofs.'' (In fact, he says, the name Trevanian was
originally intended for only those spoofs of what he calls ``the
derring-do/espionage/crotcharama genre,'' but legal complications
forced him to use it for his subsequent novels.)
</P>
<P>
   Is ``Incident at Twenty-Mile'' intended purely as a spoof of the
western genre, then? Probably not. It is written with too much
evocative detail. Its story holds you too closely in its grip. And
in its concluding pages you discover that the details of its plot
are taken from an actual event, and you learn of the delight the
author took in enriching those details with the juices of his
imagination (although at moments this postscript also reads like a
spoof of a scholar at work).
</P>
<P>
   So what you finally have in ``Incident at Twenty-Mile'' is more
complicated than myth or parody. A piece of found art, it tries to
rescue the western from the dustbin. For all its talk about the
closing of the frontier, it suggests that some of the conflicts of
this classic genre, those between effeminacy and virility, between
escape from the self and self-renewal, are still going on in the
West today.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Lieder's ultimate aim is to form a militia to fight
what he sees as an international conspiracy to people America with
immigrants from all over the world. He might as well be tilting at
black helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incident,'' then, is a blend of classic revenge tale,
nostalgia and parody, written by someone who says he believes that
even the writer's voice and persona have to be confected. Reading
it you can never rest comfortably with any single perspective. The
result is slightly unsettling, but it works.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `INCIDENT AT TWENTY-MILE'
</P>
<P>
   By Trevanian
</P>
<P>
   308 pages. St. Martin's Press/Thomas Dunne Books. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1725EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOUIS-DANCE-REVIEW-AR     10-28 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOUIS-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DANCE TROUPE STEPS LIVELY FROM PAST TO FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Murray Louis surely glanced back with pleasure and
looked forward with confidence as he planned the two-week season of
Murray Louis and Nikolais Dance, which opened on Tuesday night at
the Joyce Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, Alwin Nikolais became dance director at the
Henry Street Playhouse on the Lower East Side and began the
choreographic experiments that eventually made him an
internationally acclaimed master of mixed-media dance.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Louis joined the Nikolais company and soon
attracted attention as a virtuoso performer and talented
choreographer. Forty-five years ago, he founded his own company,
yet continued to be a star of the Nikolais troupe. The groups
merged in 1989 and Louis has directed the organization since
Nikolais' death in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Louis celebrated its achievements with a program that included a
premiere, an old work and two more recent ones.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Millennium Loop,'' to an electronic score composed by
Scott Killian in collaboration with Carol and Lawrence Lipnik,
began with all 10 members of the company carrying objects
resembling small metal fences.
</P>
<P>
   The dance technique Nikolais and Louis developed emphasizes
quick, precise movements and these performers showed their mastery
of it as they darted and hopped in a slightly staccato manner. They
also peered quizzically ahead. Both turmoil and rejoicing awaited
them.
</P>
<P>
   Two women battled. Peter Kyle at one point stood imposingly like
an emperor who had made everyone else on stage his slave. Later,
however, the dancers returned in costumes by Frank Garcia that made
them look like happy country folk going to a square dance. But this
idyll did not last, and the work ended with a man and a woman
staring nervously while the image of an apple was projected on the
backdrop. Presumably Adam and Eve were about to be tempted in a new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of Louis' dances, ``Millennium Loop'' was lively and
inventive. But, like a few of them, it did not develop its ideas
fully. Although one could enjoy its cleverness, the work might have
made an even stronger impression if Louis had revealed more of what
he thought about the problems and the promises of this millennium
and the next.
</P>
<P>
   But Louis can certainly devise eye-catching steps. And he has
been doing so for quite some time, as a revival of ``Bach Suite''
revealed. This festive suite of 1956 to recorded pieces by Bach
proved a delight.
</P>
<P>
   It began and ended with people moving gregariously together, and
there was a duet in which Kimberly Gibilisco and Kyle appeared to
be devoted companions who also preserved a measure of personal
independence. The work's pace was usually brisk, and the shapes
bodies made in space were clear and precise.
</P>
<P>
   Clarity of design was also a virtue of ``Figura,'' which dates
from 1979, and ``Sinners All,'' a group work of 1996 in which Louis
portrayed a man who arose from his contemplations to move with
pattering feet and trembling fingers. Yet ``Sinners All'' involved
more than visual spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   Louis seemed to be trying to comment on the follies of
apprehensive and fallible people, and Alberto del Saz brought a
slightly sinister presence to a few scenes. Nevertheless, as in
``Millennium Loop,'' thematic ideas remained hazy. But when, at the
conclusion, mannequins rose into the air like resurrected bodies
ascending heavenward, the implication was that at least some souls
can be saved. Louis is surely a choreographic optimist.
</P>
<P>
   The company will offer several programs of works by Louis and
Nikolais through Nov. 8 at the Joyce Theater, 175 Eighth Ave., at
19th Street.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
