<HEADER>
A2030 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBETROTTING-DANCER-     10-28 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBETROTTING-DANCER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN MARGIE GILLIS TAKES HER FAMOUS FOOTWORK AROUND THE WORLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Margie Gillis is one of Canada's most notable cultural exports:
a modern dancer who gained international attention for performing
in China and who drew rock-concert-size crowds to a stadium in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a self-described ``problem child'' who disliked
school and still has trouble telling left from right.
</P>
<P>
   Although she is one of the most renowned dancers and
choreographers in the world, Gillis says she had an unusual
childhood. Described as intelligent but with an attention-deficit
problem, Gillis struggled in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I avoided school as much as possible,'' she says. ``I was a
problem child.''
</P>
<P>
   But she excelled as a dancer and gymnast. Although her tone and
demeanor are those of a free-spirited intellectual, the solidly
muscled upper arms bespeak an athletic background.
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, she finally learned that her problem is dyslexia.
But dyslexia may well be one of the elements that gives her dancing
its special quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't dance from technical instruction,'' she says. ``I have
trouble knowing left from right. I can't keep count.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents, Olympic skiers who met while competing, encouraged
their children to take physical risks. Margie Gillis was 3 and her
brother, Christopher, was 5 when they started dance and gymnastic
classes together. Although he eventually went to New York to dance
with the Paul Taylor Company, she remained in Montreal and pursued
her own vision, starting to dance in small theaters and museums
when she was 18.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent van Gogh and Janis Joplin inspired her, but she found
that it was dance, not painting or music, that gave her the
opportunity for expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance involves every part of you,'' she says. ``Dance doesn't
lie. I heard a voice that said, `Dance.' I was afraid, but the
passion was stronger than the fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of her career, Gillis has set all kinds of
music to dance, and a variety of poetry as well. ``I love the sound
of the spoken voice,'' she says. Her unique style focuses on, but
is not limited, to her performances as a soloist in her own works.
</P>
<P>
   She was ``discovered'' at a national dance conference in Canada
in 1977 and remains based in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, she visited mainland China as a tourist and ended up
dancing in theaters there. Since then, she has performed around the
world, appearing for crowds as large as 35,000 at a football
stadium in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of becoming an international dance star, Gillis
also became a Canadian cultural icon. She was awarded the Order of
Canada, the Canadian equivalent of knighthood. She jokes that the
medallion that comes with the honor is so heavy, it makes the
wearer lean to one side.
</P>
<P>
   She is well-known for the performances she presents every other
year at the Joyce Theatre in New York. She also tours and has
become a favorite guest artist for ballet company gala
performances; she is pleased that the classical ballet world has
embraced her form of dance.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother, Christopher, was her soul mate and chief
collaborator for many years as dance partner and co-choreographer.
His death five years ago from AIDS marked a turning point in her
life. Since then, she has sought collaborators with whom she has a
similar feeling of empathy.
</P>
<P>
   That group apparently includes Fort Wort-based dancer and
choreographer Bruce Wood, whom she met years ago in Canada, and
with whom she has collaborated to create a suite of dances, ``I
Came So Far for Beauty,'' set to the music of apocalyptic pop
singer-songwriter-poet Leonard Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Gillis says she intends to continue collaborating with Wood and
has yet another work for the company in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Bruce is doing with this company is astounding,'' she
says. ``I hope the community will support his artistry. This
company could be world-class, and it's 90 percent there.'' .MDNM/
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1740EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
