<HEADLINE>
Q &AMP; A: ANTIDOTES FOR CRASHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Does anti-crash software really help?
</P>
<P>
   A. While the promise of an absolutely crash-free computer ranks
right up there with the Easter Bunny, there is utility software on
the market that is supposed to help avoid crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the more popular anti-crash programs for Windows 95 and
98 are Symantec's Norton Crash Guard Deluxe and Cybermedia's First
Aid. These programs, about $50 each, scan your system for
conflicts, glitches and corrupted files and often fix the problems
found. Crash Guard is also available for Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to scanning on command, this type of program will
also lurk quietly behind the scenes as you work, monitoring your
system for things like software conflicts or damaged system files.
Both utility programs can check the Web for the most recent
anti-virus, driver and bug-fix software and update your system.
</P>
<P>
   Some users say anti-crash programs cause more problems than they
fix, depending on the system configuration and programs used, but
if your computer is heading south more often than it should, you
may want to try one of them. If not, you can help avoid crashes by
regularly defragging your hard drive, running virus scans and
deleting unneeded files (like your browser cache and old temporary
files).
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology
</P>
<P>
   by postal mail to
</P>
<P>
   Questions
</P>
<P>
   Circuits
