<P>
   MARTHASTEWART-PRETENDERS (New York) _ Armed with little more
than a sheaf of recipes, a glue gun, some dried flowers and a
puritanical zeal for modern homekeeping, Martha Stewart has built a
$200 million multimedia empire. Thus, it comes as no surprise that
pretenders are cropping up thicker than sprouts on a chia pet.
Haunted by Ms. Stewart's success and eager to promote their own
domains, seven gurus of the homely arts gathered last week in New
York for a Halloween summit conference, at the invitation of House
&AMP; Home. By James Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUBWAY-PRESERVE (New York) _ In a preservation plan both bold
and unprecedented, the entire New York City subway system will be
nominated to the National Register of Historic Places _
highlighting 48 of its stations, 11 of its substations, 6 signal
towers, four control houses, three yard buildings and one tunnel.
By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN-DESIGN (Undated) _ ``Godjets,'' they've been dubbed: the
household gadgets that Americans love so well as to almost worship.
All those blenders, mixers, grinders and other appliances serve as
gods _ mechanical lares and penates of the American home. Now the
godjets have been joined by another class of quasi-mythical
devices: spoons and spatulas, and salt and pepper shakers that look
like satyrs and nymphs, fauns and elves. Personified pourers and
peelers that are shaped to look animate are dancing and leaping
across the countertops, verging into cartoon characters. By Phil
Patton.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BRONX-GARDEN (Undated) _ There's a proud green serpent of
vegetables undulating over the grass at Wave Hill, the public
garden in the Riverdale section of the Bronx, known for its
imagination and unusual plants. I'd never seen columnar basil
before, for instance, until I saw it last week, marching along the
inner curves of an S-shaped fence that formed the backbone of this
garden, where giant heads of a metallic-blue cabbage named Scarlet
O'Hara are set off by the smaller heads of a classic green cabbage
called Dynamo, and red kale stands a good four feet over
grassy-green oak-leaf lettuce. By Ann Raver.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHPOINT-FURNITURE (High Point, N.C.) _ Report from the
International Home Furnishings Market here. By Liz Seymour.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki
</P>
<P>
   GUADALAJARA-ARCHITECTURE (Undated) _ Forget Bilbao. The future
of architectural pilgrimage may be in Guadalajara, Mexico. With a
brand new fortune and ambition that rivals Disney, the Omnilife
Group, a Guadalajara-based vitamin drink company, is sponsoring a
giant new business and cultural center at the edge of that
sprawling city. The list of projects for the new satellite city
reads like a lifetime supply of dream jobs: There is a possible
contribution by Frank Gehry, an entertainment complex by Wolf Prix
of Coop Himmelblau in Vienna, a contemporary art museum by Toyo Ito
of Japan, a 25,000-seat amphitheater by Tod Williams and Billie
Tsien, a hotel and 80 units of housing by Stephen Holl, a
fairground landscape by Carme Pinos and a state-of-the-art
convention center by Enrique Norten of Mexico City, who is also
overseeing the design of the site plan and acting as overall talent
coordinator. By Philip Nobel.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
