<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR OF THE WOMAN IS A DISTANT ECHO FOR MANY WOMEN CANDIDATES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ The ``year of the woman'' seemed a distant
echo as Barbara Boxer swept through this old farm hub in her
volatile fight for re-election to the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But might an echo be enough for Boxer to stave off defeat?
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, the consummate liberal was one of four Democratic
women who surged into the Senate in 1992, more than doubling the
seats held by females.
</P>
<P>
   The victories resulted from a number of factors, but notably
from the disgust many women felt at the perceived unfairness in law
professor Anita Hill's treatment as she told the all-male Senate
Judiciary Committee about alleged sexual harassment by Supreme
Court nominee Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this moment when people saw a face of the U.S.
Senate that I think they hadn't seen before, which was how white
and how male it was,'' said Debbie Walsh, associate director of the
Center for the American Woman in Politics at Rutgers University's
Eagleton Institute of Politics. ``These men didn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   When some female House members marched across Capitol Hill to
confront the Senate on its treatment of Hill, Boxer was in the
lead. Her subsequent election to the upper chamber was seen, in
part, as voter approval of her outspoken activism on women's
rights.
</P>
<P>
   As the Nov. 3 election nears, there is little sense in
California _ or nationally _ that female candidates enjoy any
special momentum this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot that's different,'' Walsh said, pointing to the
possibility that women will be disproportionately turned off by the
seamy revelations in President Clinton's sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   It would be rich political irony, because another factor in the
1992 success of female Democratic candidates was Clinton's sizable
``gender gap'' as he defeated Republican incumbent George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, wondered Walsh: ``Will they be so fed up with it
they just stay home?''
</P>
<P>
   Her view was echoed by Stephanie Cohen, spokeswoman for Emily's
List, a fund-raising organization for women who support abortion
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women very strongly support Democrats,'' Cohen said. ``But
it's all a matter of will they vote.'' Like many analysts, Cohen
said the Republican takeover of the House and Senate in 1994 was
partly due to women who voted in 1992 staying away from the polls
two years later.
</P>
<P>
   This year, some of the most endangered incumbents are Democratic
women, including Boxer. She has been locked in a statistical dead
heat with her Republican opponent, state Treasurer Matt Fong.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Los Angeles Times poll found Boxer with a 5
percentage-point lead, a reversal of her standing a month ago. But
she still could not claim a clear majority of those surveyed, a
worrisome standing for an incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   If the ``year of the woman'' is to echo in Boxer's race, it is
likely to be in the gender disparity in her support that is
reflected in polls. The Times survey last week of likely voters
found Fong with an 11 percentage point lead among men and Boxer
with 19 percentage point lead among women.
</P>
<P>
   In Illinois, surveys of likely voters show Democratic Sen. Carol
Moseley-Braun trailing Republican Peter Fitzgerald. Things are
apparently brighter for Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., also from the
Class of '92, who holds a seemingly firm lead over another woman,
Republican Rep. Linda Smith. And in Maryland, Democratic Sen.
Barbara Mikulski appears headed for a landslide victory in her bid
for a third term.
</P>
<P>
   Mikulski's easy trot to re-election, Walsh said, proves a woman
``can develop a safe seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Open Senate seats hold slim prospects for women. In the Ohio
race to succeed retiring Democratic Sen. John Glenn, Republican
Gov. George Voinovich has maintained a lead in most polls over
Democrat Mary Boyle.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, women hold nine Senate seats. Six are Democrats and
three Republicans, including Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas. In
California and Maine, both senators are women. Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, D-Calif., was also elected in 1992, but to a partial,
unexpired term. She was narrowly re-elected in 1994 in a race that
saw former Houston energy heir Michael Huffington spend $37 million
of his own fortune roughing up Feinstein's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The varied and shifting landscape for women candidates is
related to more than turnout, argued Susan MacManus, a political
scientist at the University of South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women candidates at all levels are no longer novelties,''
MacManus said. ``Women (candidates) have gotten into the same
campaign mode as men, including negative ads,'' which are generally
considered more objectionable to female voters than men.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer's television ads against Fong generally seek to paint her
challenger as a knee-jerk conservative out of step with
Californians. Fong's ads center more on himself and his vision for
the state. But with Boxer now ahead, his final ads may begin to
mirror the stance he takes in public appearances, where he relishes
jabbing at Boxer as a liberal who is _ yes _ out of step with
Californians.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the final days of the campaign, Boxer has outspent
Fong about 2-1 on television ads and the national Republican
senatorial committee has sent Fong an emergency infusion of about
$1 million. Republican pollster Ed Goeas said Boxer appeared to be
``pulling away'' from Fong based on her financial supremacy.
</P>
<P>
   At a community center in Stockton, Boxer argued: ``This election
is not about me, and it isn't about Mr. Fong.'' But later, a senior
California Democratic strategist countered: ``That's hooey. It's
still all about Barbara. She's the incumbent, and she has had
terribly high negatives (in polling). If she can succeed in making
it about Fong, she has a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer, campaigning in a run-down Stockton neighborhood, was
painfully aware of the battle in which she is engaged. Before
racing off to another stop down the nation's richest agricultural
valley, Boxer said she must be resigned to tight races when ``you
stand up for the things we stand up for: a clean and healthy
environment, sensible gun control, women's right to choose,
education for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Stockton Mayor Joan Darrah seconded Boxer's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very outspoken,'' Darrah said. ``She takes hard stands
on issues that other candidates don't have the courage to take.''
</P>
<P>
   The translation: It's tough in California, as in many states,
for an out-and-out liberal like Boxer to win, and it may never be
with a big margin.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer won with 48 percent in 1992, running 6 percentage points
behind the more centrist Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   For the television cameras inside the community center, state
Sen. Patrick Johnston, a Stockton Democrat, praised Boxer as a
candidate who in 1992 ``promised to help'' and as a federal
official ``has delivered.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the Boxer caravan pulled out, he spoke with a reporter
about what he sees as the problems of ideology and image that his
Democratic colleague faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always going to be tough,'' said Johnston, an 18-year
state legislator. ``She's a liberal candidate in a state that's, on
balance, right down the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's another issue that Johnston said transcends Boxer's
voting record and is reflected in the sizable gender gap that polls
have found in the race. Johnston began by exclaiming: ``White,
middle-aged men ought to grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Barbara's kind of in-your-face,'' Johnston said. ``Men who are
in your face don't seem to offend other men.'' But if a woman
politician is assertive, Johnston said, ``you have a chance of
getting ahead in a man's world, but you also bring out the male
hormonal resentment. Men just have a visceral reaction to Barbara
Boxer, and they don't have that problem with some pushy man.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
