<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2070 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOSELEY-BRAUN-HNS &LR;      10-28 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSELEY-BRAUN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EDITORS: This story is a sidebar to WOMEN-SENATE story for
Thursday, Oct. 29 By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In 1992, when Carol Moseley-Braun became the first
black woman elected to the U.S. Senate, she was a political
supernova.
</P>
<P>
   Now as she seeks re-election, Moseley-Braun is perhaps the most
imperiled Senate incumbent in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a star,'' said Paul M. Green, a political scientist at
Governors State University. ``Now it's gone. It's faded.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are manifold, but the bottom line seems clear:
Moseley-Braun was swept into office with strong support from white
suburban women, many of whom are nominal Republicans. Like other
female candidates in 1992, Moseley-Braun seemed to benefit from a
disquiet among women voters about the way the all-male, all-white
Senate handled Anita Hill's accusations of sexual harassment
against Supreme Court nominee Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need any more arrogant rich boys in the Senate, and
that's what this campaign is all about,'' Moseley-Braun said in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Moseley-Braun is trailing her Republican opponent _ a
really rich white guy, state Sen. Peter Fitzgerald _ by about 10
percentage points because recent polls show many of those women
have deserted her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's disconnected with her base,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the 1992 election, Moseley-Braun became ensnared in
activities that raised doubts about her political judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Under the apparent tutelage of her then-fiance, Moseley-Braun
visited Nigeria for consultations with the government of the
strongman Sani Abacha, whose murderous regime had been condemned by
the State Department. She returned for up to five additional
visits.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley-Braun was investigated for mishandling Medicaid
financial dealings relating to her mother. The Internal Revenue
Service has been delving into her tax filings, an inquiry for which
Moseley-Braun has refused to make public any documents.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the fall campaign progressed, Moseley-Braun's sister was
caught attempting to sell tickets to the senator's fund-raising
events while on her government job in the Cook County prosecutor's
consumer fraud division.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do this, sweetie,'' the senator told sister Marsha
Moseley over the telephone, as a local reporter listened in. ``Your
sister is particularly vulnerable to this kind of (thing). A
mistake like this can be a big damn deal.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the questions have persisted and are at the center of
Moseley-Braun's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has become the issue,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald, who has poured about $10 million of his inherited
banking fortune into the race, has pummeled Moseley-Braun about her
troubles in television ads and has compared her in public comments
to the leader of her party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carol Moseley-Braun is one of the only public officials whose
own scandals eclipse those of President Clinton,'' Fitzgerald said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Until polls consistently showed her trailing Fitzgerald,
Moseley-Braun sought to tough out the criticism. But recently she
has begun to air an I'm-sorta-sorry television ad as part of her
underpowered media campaign. As of Sept. 31, the Democrat had
raised only $3.6 million, less than half her opponent's
self-financed war chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've made some mistakes and disappointed some people,''
Moseley-Braun says in the commercial. ``But I want you to know I've
always tried to do what's best for Illinois.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald laid out $7 million of his own money to win the
Republican primary, without the help of the GOP establishment,
which feared his hard-line views against abortion, federal
involvement in education and other sensitive issues would make it
more difficult for him to take on Moseley-Braun.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley-Braun has kept up the attack on Fitzgerald's affluence
and what she says are his extreme political views.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bring to the Millionaire Boys Club they call the U.S. Senate
a working person's perspective,'' she told a union audience
recently.
</P>
<P>
   As an analysis of the race in the Illinois edition of the St.
Louis Post-Dispatch said recently: ``This is turning out to be
exactly the 1998 the Democrats dreaded since 1992.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
