<HEADER>
A2076 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-VS-SMITH-HNS &LR;      10-28 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-VS-SMITH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN YEAR OF THE WOMAN, THE QUESTION IS `WHICH WOMAN?' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It's still the ``year of the woman'' in Washington
state. But which woman?
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate race, only the third in U.S. history when both
major-party candidates were women, is a contest between:
</P>
<P>
   Democratic incumbent Patty Murray, who won her first term six
years ago on a campaign as ``a mom in tennis shoes,'' a distinct
alternative to the blue-suit image of the predominantly male
Congress. Back on the campaign trail this year, the
moderate-to-liberal Murray still sometimes appears in a windbreaker
or sweatshirt and her trademark Nikes.
</P>
<P>
   Republican challenger Linda Smith, a conservative congresswoman
from a district in southwestern Washington state who once declared:
``God put me in Congress.'' Smith, a favorite of the Christian
Coalition, has made her reputation as a maverick, refusing to
support Newt Gingrich for re-election as speaker and supporting
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates disagree on many major issues, including two
watched closely by female voters: abortion and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Smith opposes Medicaid funding of abortions for victims of rape
and incest, and once said: ``We don't kill children because their
father is a jerk.'' Murray opposes attempts to limit late-term
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Smith supports, and Murray opposes, the initiative on the
Washington state ballot Nov. 3 to abolish almost all state and
local governments' affirmative action programs for women and
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Murray has used a superior fund-raising effort to power herself
to what a recent Seattle Post-Intelligencer poll found to be a 13
percentage point lead.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's internecine battles with party leaders, including Sen.
Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, chairman of the National Republican
Senatorial Committee, have not helped her in generating sufficient
campaign cash.
</P>
<P>
   Smith once said that McConnell was ``one belligerent person who
likes the laundering of political money.''
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, the NRSC belatedly decided to give Smith's
campaign $100,000 _ less than a fifth of the amount it could have
under federal law. Although Smith has refused to take money from
special-interest political action committees, she said she would
accept the donation from the national GOP group, much of whose
money comes from those same PACs.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's campaign immediately labeled Smith's decision the
``ultimate hypocrisy.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray's lead has surprised some of her fellow Democrats. Party
leaders in both Washingtons worried that Murray's profile in her
first term had been too subdued, that her impression on voters had
been so indistinct that a talented opponent would be free to
characterize her in an uncomplimentary way.
</P>
<P>
   But Murray seems to be using the low-key approach to her
advantage for what seems a very conscientious but laid-back
electorate. One of Murray's campaign brochures says she's working
``quietly and diligently'' for her constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Murray is, in the word's of the Seattle Weekly, ``the Senate's
self-designated normal person.''
</P>
<P>
   But in other ways, Murray has played the shrewd incumbent,
rejecting all but one debate with Smith. The single encounter was
taped on a Saturday night (because Smith said her religious beliefs
would not allow her to debate on Sunday) but delayed for broadcast
until low-viewership Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Murray also used her seat on the Senate Appropriations Committee
to wedge $30 million for teacher technology training into a
higher-education bill and was at the White House when President
Clinton signed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's proposal for federal funding to hire 100,000 new
teachers failed by one vote when it was considered separately, but
she worked to get the measure restored in last-minute negotiations
on the massive federal spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that kind of thing that catches the eye of key suburban
swing voters,'' said a Washington state Republican strategist.
``She has played the outsider-insider game very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Smith's record in opposing some federal education
spending, Washington state's Democratic Party has aired television
ads of the Republican wearing a dunce cap. But even a local
Democrat said some of the claims in the ad are overstated or
wrong. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
