<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2089 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-DOCTOR-LISTE     10-28 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-DOCTOR-LISTED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENTON DOCTOR LISTED ON ANTI-ABORTION WEB PAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ During the past two years, Dr. Mary Smith has
grown accustomed to the sight of pickets waving signs and chanting
slogans in front of the Elm Street clinic where she performs about
seven abortions a week.
</P>
<P>
   But that hardly prepared Smith for what she saw this week as she
viewed the Nuremberg Files Web page and found herself referred to
as ``The blood red rose of Texas'' and among the nation's ``Third
Trimester Butchers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's appalling,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Web page, dripping with simulated gore, lists personal
information such as home addresses and telephone numbers for Smith
and other physicians who perform abortions, plus their driver's
license numbers and the names and birth dates of their spouses and
their children.
</P>
<P>
   It also highlights the names of doctors who have been killed or
wounded. After Dr. Barnett Slepian was slain Friday in his Amherst,
N.Y., kitchen by a sniper, a slash appeared through his name on the
Web page.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Christian Gallery Web site, originated by the
Georgia-based Creator's Rights group, are concerned that the
Nuremberg Files could serve as a hit list for the more radical
element among anti-abortionists.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 53, said Tuesday that she refuses to let her prominent
inclusion on the Internet site intimidate her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I afraid for my life? Realistically, no,'' said Smith, who
has practiced in Denton since 1978. ``How can you live your life
that way? I am more afraid for my life driving to Dallas to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tend to think that people realize I'm a nice person,
and that they wouldn't want to shoot me,'' she said. ``My husband
says I'm naive.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who practices in Denton and Dallas, also said that she
has never performed a third-trimester abortion. Those procedures,
she said, are reserved for severe medical emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Creator's Rights Internet site lists abortion providers whom
group members want to face ``Nuremberg trials'' for performing
abortions, which they call ``crimes against humanity.'' The site
asks users to send personal or legal information about doctors who
perform abortions or others associated with abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Horsley, founder of the site, did not return two telephone
messages.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan O'Toole, a member of the Creator's Rights group, told
The Boston Globe this week that the violence will continue until
``Roe v. Wade is reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   FBI officals said this week that they will review what role, if
any, the group played in the circumstances leading to Slepian's
slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Price, president of Texans United for Life, cautioned that
Creator's Rights is ``obviously on the lunatic fringe of the
pro-life movement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole battle that we fight is a battle to win the public
mind and heart on this issue, and when these things happen like
this, it makes that very difficult,'' said Price, who lives in the
Dallas suburb of Carrolton. ``It goes so far against the goals that
98 or 99 percent of the people in the pro-life movement have.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said she suspects that North Texas anti-abortion groups _
particularly the Denton-based Life Dynamics group _ gave her
personal information to the Internet site. She said other, more
prominent, physicians in the Metroplex and other areas are not
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I am, this little doctor with a little practice, and they
can't get rid of me. They are frustrated; and that's why I'm on the
Internet,'' she said. ``It's not because I am well-known or do a
lot of abortions in Denton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why they targeted me.''
</P>
<P>
   Life Dynamics, which lobbies to restrict access to abortion and
assists attorneys on behalf of women injured in abortions, operates
the Susan B. Anthony Women's Center. Last year, the center moved
next door to Smith's Denton Health Services for Women clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Life Dynamics President Mark Crutcher declined to comment on
Smith's assertions unless the Star-Telegram met certain demands.
</P>
<P>
   The National Federation for Abortion, an association of 350
abortion clinics, has asked its attorneys to determine whether it
can take action to remove some of the personal information from the
Nuremberg Files Web site, spokeswoman Stephanie Mueller said. The
attorneys are expected to report back in a week, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it as an invitation to intimidation or harassment or
violence,'' Mueller said. ``There is absolutely no reason to put
personal, private information on a Web site unless it is to evoke
the kind of action that occurred Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven people have died nationwide because of anti-abortion
violence, she said. The victims were three physicians, a client
escort, two clinic staff members and a security guard. Nationwide,
15 abortion-related homicide attempts have occurred since 1991,
Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the protests at her clinic and her listing on the
Internet site, Smith said she has never had negative telephone
calls. First United Methodist Church of Denton, where she sings in
the choir, has been picketed. But church leaders continue to back
her, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never felt so supported,'' Smith said. ``There are a
lot of older women in the choir, and they are really behind me. I
don't think I could do it without the support.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion has been a prominent issue this year in Denton. In
January, Commissioners Court approved an anti-abortion resolution
that condemns the 25th anniversary of the Supreme Court's landmark
Roe vs. Wade decision.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution was sponsored by Commissioners Jeff Krueger and
Scott Armey, Republicans who said it reflects their political,
personal and religious beliefs. Krueger brought up the proclamation
at the behest of resident Tom Cyr, a fellow member of Immaculate
Conception Catholic Church and a Life Dynamics employee.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Krueger called the Nuremberg Files Web site ``totally
outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't approve of the treatment that has been given to Dr.
Smith, although I don't condone what she does for her profession,''
Krueger said. ``That's not the style that I would fight abortion
and abortion laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey said the Web site could create a public safety problem for
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the senseless murder of any individual is completely
condemnable, and if there's anything that we can do through the
county through our Sheriff's Department or through any type of law
enforcement to help protect Dr. Smith, we're going to take whatever
measure we can to do so,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the daughter of a fundamentalist minister, said that she
saw the results of back alley abortions while she was in medical
school and that she considers the role of giving women a choice ``a
mission.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I do, and I will probably do it until I'm 85 or
until I can't see,'' she said. ``The more they picket me, the
longer I'll be here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
