<SLUG> BC-GLENN-EXPERIMENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
80 EXPERIMENTS ON TAP FOR DISCOVERY ASTRONAUTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Discovery's seven astronauts plan to tackle more than 80 science
experiments in disciplines as diverse as astronomy, biotechnology,
entomology and agriculture as well as medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle is scheduled to blast off Thursday at 2 p.m. EST,
climbing to an altitude of 345 miles, more than twice as high as
John Glenn's Friendship 7 capsule soared in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   The large number of activities planned by the six-man, one-woman
shuttle crew will make the flight much more than a joy ride for the
77-year-old astronaut.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was happy to come fly with us, obviously '' said Discovery
commander Curt Brown. ``But he may not be happy after a few days in
orbit. We plan to work him to the bone.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn has trained to participate in 15 or so of the experiments,
stationed in a closet-sized module called Spacehab, which is linked
to the shuttle's crew compartment by a tunnel. He will also likely
be called upon to assist his crew mates in other ways over the
mission's nine days.
</P>
<P>
   One of the shuttle's primary payloads is a reusable satellite
called Spartan that has been equipped with a pair of telescopes.
Using the shuttle's 50-foot long robot arm, the astronauts plan to
deploy Spartan for free-flying, pre-programmed observations of the
sun's corona or outer atmosphere, whose energetic discharges
influence climate and electronic communications on the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery will soar ahead of Spartan, then rendezvous for
retrieval by the robot arm after a two-day separation.
</P>
<P>
   A similar test was aborted last November when another shuttle
crew improperly activated the satellite, then sent it into a tumble
when it made a hasty attempt at recovery.
</P>
<P>
   During Spartan's recovery, the satellite will allow NASA
engineers to test an automated rendezvous and docking system it is
developing for use by cargo capsules traveling to the new
international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's unusually lofty orbit matches that of the Hubble
Space Telescope, permitting the shuttle to test a new cooling
system, data recorder and computer destined for installation aboard
the observatory by astronauts in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The cooling device relies on tiny pumps designed to spin at
400,000 revolutions per minute to circulate neon to chill an
infrared camera on the Hubble. It will replace a less suitable
cooling device that relied on frozen nitrogen.
</P>
<P>
   The infrared camera allows the Hubble to observe the most
distant reaches of the universe as well as peer into the dust disks
that surround prospective planet-forming star systems.
</P>
<P>
   An experiment called Hearts in Space will employ a mechanical
device to demonstrate why the hearts of astronauts shrink in space.
Researchers believe the muscle shrinks because the blood that
courses through it is weightless
</P>
<P>
   A series of biotechnology experiments are designed to improve
the medicines used in the treatment of diabetes, colon cancer,
Chagas disease as well as grass and pollen allergies. Others in the
category will examine potential techniques for improving grain crop
production with the reduced use of polluting fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
   Oysters, toads and fish will serve as subjects in an experiment
that records the impulses between the gravity sensing organs and
the brain as the animals adjust to weightlessness. Initiated as an
experiment to study how astronauts adjust to the absence of
gravity, the results could also prove useful in explaining the
balance disorders of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle will carry eight experiments devised by students
from Argentina and Italy as well as the United States.
</P>
<P>
   One developed by students from a Lanham, Md., high school will
study dozens of roaches, some in the larvae and others in the adult
phase, as they develop in weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   The insects are enclosed in a container in Discovery's payload
bay where they will not come in contact with the astronauts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
