<HEADER>
A2129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-POPCORN-COX     10-28 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-POPCORN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    texture? Either way, the kernel of the matter is that we love
popcorn
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   t was a classic first date. A movie. Some popcorn. But Diane
Pfeifer wanted to make something very clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my date that I wanted my own bucket of popcorn. I don't
share,'' she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine,'' he retorted. ``Then I won't share my secret recipe for
Mexican popcorn.''
</P>
<P>
   Pfeifer, 48, now a married mother of two in Peachtree Hills,
never saw him again, and she didn't get the recipe. But because she
had a daily popcorn habit, she set out to create her own spicy
mixtures.
</P>
<P>
   When she was done, she had concocted more than 100 ways to
season and savor popcorn, which she compiled into a book she
self-published, called ``For Popcorn Lovers Only'' (Strawberry
Patch, $9.95). The book has sold more than 40,000 copies, proving
that there are more partners for this classic snack than butter and
salt.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that the way with popcorn? Once you get started, it's hard
to stop, which is probably why Americans eat 1.1 billion pounds of
it every year, according to the Popcorn Institute.
</P>
<P>
   And fall is the peak period for home popcorn consumption,
perhaps because we're prone to curling up on the couch with a big
bowl of it to watch the new TV shows or piling up the popcorn balls
for the kids' Halloween party.
</P>
<P>
   But popcorn isn't just for the movie theater or living room
anymore. It's a favorite office snack and is even showing up in
some upscale restaurants, such as dish in Virginia-Highland, where
popcorn with rosemary and pine nuts is a popular appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much the taste of popcorn, but the texture,''
declares Andy Smith, author of ``Popped Culture: A Social History
of Popcorn in America,'' to be released by the University of South
Carolina Press early next year. ``It's really just a vehicle for
carrying salt, butter and lots of other things we like.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say there are no differences among popcorns.
Inside each kernel is a bit of moisture, and when that moisture is
heated, it explodes, causing the kernel to pop. Moisture levels can
vary among popcorns, and so can the expansion rate. ``Normal
popcorn expands 30 to 40 times the original size of the kernal,
while gourmet popcorns expand to about 50 times,'' Smith explains.
</P>
<P>
   And the way it's cooked can also make a difference. In fact,
popcorn has probably been around for centuries, but it wasn't until
folks started figuring out a convenient way to pop it that it
became popular.
</P>
<P>
   Smith says the notion that Native Americans ate popcorn
regularly is false, largely because the only way they had to make
it was to throw cobs onto the embers of a dying fire and eat what
few popped kernels they could capture. The first wire popcorn
poppers came onto the scene in the 1830s, but they were often
loosely constructed and the handles would fly off in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Methods of popping corn continued to improve, but the snack was
popular mainly in rural areas until movie theaters, desperate for
profits during the Depression, began to offer it as a sideline.
(Popcorn remains a moneymaker for movie theaters today, with most
selling it for about 10 times what it costs them to make it, Smith
says.)
</P>
<P>
   Popcorn moved from theater to living room with the advent of
television and convenience packaging. But the real popcorn
revolution came with the microwave oven. In fact, popcorn was the
first food that researchers in the 1940s aimed microwaves at,
leading to the development of the microwave oven. Today, sales of
microwave-ready popcorn regularly top $240 million a year, the
Popcorn Institute reports.
</P>
<P>
   Corn popped on the stovetop heats from the outside of the kernel
inward; in the microwave oven, the reverse is true. Smith prefers
stovetop popcorn, because it's crustier. And he likes to use fresh
ingredients for seasoning rather than the shelf-stable and
sometimes fake popcorn flavorings.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeifer likes fresh ingredients too. Her favorite is a mixture
of crushed garlic and fresh, grated Parmesan cheese. Other quick
ways to jazz up popped corn are with a sprinkle of Old Bay
Seasoning mix or taco seasoning mix, adding a few drops of sesame
oil to the cooking oil, or adding a tablespoonful of sugar to the
pan just as the corn begins to pop.
</P>
<P>
   On page H6, we offer recipes for more elaborate seasonings,
including Santa Fe Trail Mix and Cranberry Popcorn. So come on _
there's no better time to get popping!
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
