A2142 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-BLUES-COX     10-28 0223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-BLUES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teenage bluesman awaits seasoning
 &HT;    By Russ Devault
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jonny Lang traded normal teenhood for the touring musician life,
but no one's going to suggest that the 17-year-old
guitarist-vocalist sold his soul to the devil to be a bluesman.
Lang alludes to such deals on ``The Levee,'' one of the strong cuts
on his second album, but he needs seasoning. It would be
inappropriate to suggest that Lang's youth and lack of a
hardscrabble background preclude membership in the authentic blues
fraternity, although such greats as Muddy Waters and B.B. King were
paying their dues in down-and-dirty Delta clubs during their teen
years.
</P>
<P>
   Lang's strength, for now at least, is that he is a great
technician who shuns speed for ringing or wistful notes (``Breakin'
Me,'' ``Leaving to Stay''). His grown-up vocals often belie his
youth to such a degree that you'll look at the liner notes to see
who's singing. But what is readily apparent is that he needs less
production, more consistent songs and some play-for-myself
absorption next time out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wander This World''
</P>
<P>
   Jonny Lang. A&AMP;M. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Teen blues star needs seasoning to match his
technique.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
