<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio Reviews: The latest word on the latest sounds
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Doug Hamilton, and Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``Ghetto Supastar''
</P>
<P>
   Pras. Ruffhouse/Columbia. 18 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Well, this is the thud everyone expected. But at least one
helpful thing can be gleaned: Now we have a pretty good idea of who
contributes to the Fugees and who seems to be along for the ride.
``But what about `Ghetto Supastar?''' ask those who couldn't escape
the Pras/ODB/Mya hit of the summer. Think about it: Can you
remember more than the hook? Exactly. Pras obviously has an ear for
a chorus or an unexpected sample (Weather Report's ``Birdland'' on
``Yeah 'Eh Yeah 'Eh'') that works. What doesn't is this dubious
rapper's one-dimensional delivery of very little that's memorable.
</P>
<P>
   -- SOUNDTRACK
</P>
<P>
   ``Storefront Hitchcock''
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   Warner Bros. 20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   British pop weirdo Robyn Hitchcock's upcoming concert film,
directed by Jonathan Demme (``Beloved,'' ``Stop Making Sense''),
finds its subject still indulging his career-long passion for
affixing surreal images to delicate, folk-based tunes. Live, the
stream of consciousness overflows into Hitchcock's stage routine,
as he chatters on about ``spleens a-go-go'' and churches full of
carcasses. In between these lengthy, sometimes tiresome spiels, we
get efficiently rendered versions of such ``hits'' as ``I'm Only
You,'' from his 1985 masterpiece, ``Fegmania!''
</P>
<P>
   -- BLUES
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of the Madness''
</P>
<P>
   The Derek Trucks Band.
</P>
<P>
   House of Blues. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   One day Derek Trucks will make an album that both equals and
reflects his phenomenal talent as a guitarist. A true prodigy, the
Jacksonville native is part Southern rocker (uncle Butch is a
founding Allman Brother), part traditional blues aesthete _ and
wholly gifted at raw slide wizardry. Yet, at 19, he's still
learning how to forge a musical concept. This sophomore release
lacks the focus to properly show off Trucks' burning solo style.
It's a hodgepodge, needlessly saddled with guest vocals (ex-Allman
guitar pyro Warren Haynes is a decent blues growler, but it's pure
shivery steel strings I'd rather hear recount Son House's ``Death
Letter''). The selection of vintage blues and funk material, and
some jazz-tinged originals, speaks to Trucks' good taste. He just
needs to pare away the trappings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
