<HEADER>
A2145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPCORN-RECIPES-COX     10-28 2400
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPCORN-RECIPES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jazz it up or eat it plain: Popcorn can go from holiday table to
trail
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing quite satisfies like a bowl of piping hot popcorn. And
thankfully, it's also pretty healthy. Popped without oil it's about
27 calories a cup. Using a little oil will bring it up to about 41
calories a cup. And thankfully, there are a number of ways to spice
it up without adding calories and fat.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there are some awfully tasty ways to eat popcorn
that make it less healthful, but oh so delicious.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the basics in mind. If you are popping in the microwave,
simply follow instructions on the bag or the popper.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're enticed to return to the stove top, here's a
little refresher. Heat a 3-quart, covered saucepan over high heat
for 2 minutes; pour 2 tablespoons cooking oil into the pan, adding
more if needed to cover the bottom; lower heat to medium-high and
add 3 to 4 kernels of corn. When they pop, add a 1/2 cup popcorn,
cover and shake pan continuously. Just like with microwave popcorn,
listen. When you hear the popping slow or stop, it's ready. You
should have 9-11 cups.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best oils to use is canola, since it's lowest in
saturated fat and imparts no flavor. But you can also use olive oil
(not extra-virgin), corn, peanut, macadamia and some flavored oils.
</P>
<P>
   And one of the best ways to season popped corn is to put it in a
brown paper bag while still hot. Add the seasonings and shake.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Caramel Corn
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10-12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Weren't caramel and popcorn just made for each other? We
borrowed this recipe from Atlantan Diane Pfeifer's ``For Popcorn
Lovers Only'' (Strawberry Patch, $9.95).
</P>
<P>
   8cups popcorn
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1cup unsalted peanuts, optional
</P>
<P>
   Place popcorn in large greased bowl. Combine brown sugar, corn
syrup, butter and salt in 1-quart saucepan over medium heat. Bring
to boil, stirring constantly. Continue without stirring to
hard-ball stage: When it reaches 250 degrees or when a small amount
of boiling mixture dropped into very cold water forms a hard ball.
Stir in vanilla. Pour over popcorn. Stir to coat evenly. Toss in
peanuts, if desired. Cool and serve. (Hide a secret toy in the
bowl, if you must.)
</P>
<P>
   Microwave method: Combine brown sugar, corn syrup, butter and
salt in 2-quart glass casserole. Microwave on high 2 to 3 minutes
until mixture reaches hard-ball stage. Stir every minute. Continue
as above.
</P>
<P>
   Shortcut: Melt 1 pound caramels with 1/4 cup half-and-half. Pour
over popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   Per cup, with peanuts: 286 calories, 5 grams protein, 13 grams
fat (percent calories from fat, 40), 41 grams carbohydrates, 8
milligrams cholesterol, 85 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Peach Crunch
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5-10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here's another of Pfeifer's recipes, steeped in homegrown
flavors.
</P>
<P>
   8cups popcorn
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons peach preserves
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 275 degrees. Place popcorn in large greased
bowl. Melt butter in small pan over low heat. Stir in sugar and
preserves until melted. Dribble over popcorn. Stir to coat evenly.
Spread popcorn mixture on greased roasting pan. Bake for 10
minutes, stirring every 2 to 3 minutes. Remove and cool before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Microwave method: Place butter in 9-by-13-by-2-inch baking dish.
Microwave on high until melted. Stir in preserves and sugar. Add
popcorn and stir to coat thoroughly. Microwave 3 to 4 minutes on
high until crispy. Stir every minute.
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 112 calories, 2 grams protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 28), 20 grams carbohydrates, 8 milligrams
cholesterol, 32 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Popcorn Balls
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 balls
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Popcorn balls are a classic for Halloween or other holiday
parties. This recipe is from ``James Beard's American Cookery''
(Little Brown &AMP; Co., 1996). One word of caution: while this may
seem a great activity to do with the kids, be very careful with the
hot syrup because it can burn. It's probably best to do with older
children.
</P>
<P>
   16cups lightly salted popped corn
</P>
<P>
   2cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup water
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Place popped corn in a large buttered mixing bowl and put in a
warm oven (110 to 120 degrees.) Put wax paper or aluminum foil on a
countertop. Measure the sugar, corn syrup and water into a 3-quart
saucepan. Bring to a boil and wash down the sides of the pan with a
pastry brush dipped in water, to avoid sugar granules. Cook to
264-270 degrees. Remove from the heat and immediately stir in the
vanilla. Take the popcorn from the oven and slowly pour the syrup
over it while stirring thoroughly with a large, long-handled spoon.
Butter or oil your hands very well and as soon as the mixture can
be handled without burning your hands, take up enough popcorn into
the hands to be pressed into a ball. Space the balls on the wax
paper or aluminum foil until cool. Work rapidly so that the syrup
will not harden before the balls can be formed. Store in freezer
bags or in tightly covered airtight containers or the syrup will
draw moisture and make the popcorn soggy.
</P>
<P>
   Per ball: 205 calories, 2 grams protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 4), 49 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 112
milligrams
</P>
<P>
   sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry Popcorn
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Holiday party bowls will need filling soon, and we can't think
of a better way to bring a little color and flavor to popcorn than
with pretty red cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces frozen cranberry juice concentrate, thawed
</P>
<P>
   12cups popped corn
</P>
<P>
   1cup dried cranberries
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees. In a small saucepan, melt butter
over low heat. Stir in sugar, corn syrup and cranberry juice
concentrate. Bring to a boil, stirring constantly. Lower heat and
simmer until mixture reaches 240 degrees on a candy thermometer.
Place popcorn and dried cranberries in a large bowl. Pour syrup
over popcorn and stir until well coated. Spread popcorn evenly in a
large roasting pan. Bake for about 5 minutes, stirring once or
twice, until mixture just begins to lose red color. Remove from
oven and let cool to room temperature, about 15 minutes. Store in
an airtight container for up to 1 week. Recrisp in a preheated
350-degree oven for a few minutes, if necessary. _ Adapted from:
``Popcorn!'' by Frances Towner Giedt (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15)
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 140 calories, 2 grams protein, 1 gram fat (percent
calories from fat, 4), 34 grams carbohydrates, 10 milligrams
cholesterol, 7 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary-Pine Nut
</P>
<P>
   Popcorn
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: overnight
</P>
<P>
   There's hardly a better way to survive the wait for a table at
dish in Virginia-Highland than munching on a bowl of their yummy
rosemary-pine nut popcorn. Here's our adaptation of that treat.
Sometimes you can find rosemary-infused oil at gourmet food shops,
but we've included the instructions for making your own.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE ROSEMARY OIL:
</P>
<P>
   1cup canola or other vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   84-inch sprigs fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE POPCORN:
</P>
<P>
   5tablespoons rosemary oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup popcorn kernels
</P>
<P>
   1cup pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   For the rosemary oil: In a small saucepan over very low heat,
warm the canola oil, rosemary sprigs and crushed garlic for 20
minutes. If the oil begins to sizzle, remove the pan from the heat
for a moment to cool. Warm, don't brown, the rosemary and garlic.
Remove from the heat and let stand, covered, overnight. Strain the
oil. It will keep, refrigerated, for about one week.
</P>
<P>
   For the popcorn: In a large pot, heat 2 tablespoons of rosemary
oil and 1 kernel of popcorn. When that kernel pops, add the rest of
the popcorn, cover, and pop, shaking the pot often to avoid
burning. In the meantime, in a small saucepan over low heat, stir
the pine nuts in the remaining 3 tablespoons of rosemary oil.
Remove from the heat when the nuts begin to turn light brown, about
5 to 8 minutes. Stir in the salt. Pour the nuts with their cooking
oil over the popcorn, stirring continuously to mix well. As soon as
the popcorn has cooled to room temperature, store in an airtight
container.
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 212 calories, 6 grams protein, 19 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 82), 9 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 75
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Jamaican Ginger
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Ginger, cloves and hot pepper sauce will make you feel like you
are on the islands, mon.
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2tablespoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon dried lemon peel
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon hot pepper sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   8cups popped corn
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, melt butter over low heat. Add ginger and
cook for 2 minutes. Stir in cloves, lemon peel, hot pepper sauce
and salt. Cook for 1 minute. Drizzle over popcorn. Toss to mix
evenly. Store in an airtight container for up to 3 days. _ From:
``Popcorn!'' by Frances Towner Giedt (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15)
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 85 calories, 2 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 52), 9 grams carbohydrates, 12 milligrams
cholesterol, 150 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Jalapeno Pecan
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For jalapeno lovers and a few other brave souls.
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   1cup pecan halves
</P>
<P>
   3fresh jalapeno chiles, seeded and minced
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   8cups popped corn
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, melt butter over low heat. Add pecans and
cook, stirring constantly, for 2 minutes. Add the chiles, chili
powder, cumin, garlic powder and salt and cook for 1 to 2 minutes
more. Pour over popcorn; toss to coat evenly. Store in an airtight
container for up to 1 week. _From: ``Popcorn!'' by Frances Towner
Giedt (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15)
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 197 calories, 3 grams protein, 16 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 74), 13 grams carbohydrates, 15 milligrams
cholesterol, 214 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe Trail Mix
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 6 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is a nice switch from the usual party mix, combining
popcorn with peanuts, corn chips and some spicy flavorings. Happy
trails!
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon grated lime zest
</P>
<P>
   8cups popped corn
</P>
<P>
   1cup dry roasted peanuts
</P>
<P>
   2cups small corn chips
</P>
<P>
   In a small saucepan, melt butter over low heat. Stir in garlic
powder, cumin, hot pepper flakes and salt. Cook, stirring, for 1
minute. Add lime zest. Pour over popped corn. Stir gently to coat
evenly. Add dry roasted peanuts and corn chips; mix gently. Store
in an airtight container for up to 3 days. _From: ``Popcorn!'' by
Frances Towner Giedt (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15)
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 195 calories, 5 grams protein, 14 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 66), 14 grams carbohydrates, 12 milligrams
cholesterol, 97 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Ragin' Cajun
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 11 minutes
</P>
<P>
   If you're a fan of Cajun food, then you'll love this popcorn
treat that combines garlic, hot pepper sauce and cayenne pepper
with other spices for one hot bite.
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon dried minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons hot pepper sauce, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon cayenne pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon crushed dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon crushed dried thyme
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   8cups popped corn
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 250 degrees. In a small saucepan, melt butter,
then add the garlic, paprika, pepper sauce, cayenne pepper,
oregano, thyme and salt and cook, stirring constantly, for 1
minute. Place popcorn in a large baking pan; drizzle butter mixture
over popcorn, tossing well to coat evenly. Bake popcorn for 5
minutes, stirring twice, until crisped. Store in an airtight
container for up to 1 week. _ From: ``Popcorn!'' by Frances Towner
Giedt (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $15)
</P>
<P>
   Per cup: 86 calories, 2 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 52), 10 grams carbohydrates, 12 milligrams
cholesterol, 301 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Popcorn Granola
</P>
<P>
   Makes 11 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The next time you take to the hiking trail, take this
power-packed mixture along and you're sure to climb every mountain
_ with a smile on your face.
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup honey
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   3cups unseasoned popped corn
</P>
<P>
   6cups quick-cooking rolled oats
</P>
<P>
   1cup sweet flaked dried coconut
</P>
<P>
   1cup bran cereal
</P>
<P>
   1cup crushed shredded wheat
</P>
<P>
   1cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup sesame seed
</P>
<P>
   In a 12-by-15-inch roasting pan, combine honey, butter and
vanilla. Place in oven and turn heat on to 350 degrees. Meanwhile,
whirl popcorn in a blender or food processor until finely ground.
When butter is melted, in about 5 minutes, add to pan the ground
corn, oats, coconut, bran cereal, wheat cereal, raisins and sesame
seeds; mix well. Bake, stirring often, until lightly browned, 40 to
45 minutes. Cool; serve. If made ahead, store airtight at room
temperature up to 3 weeks. _ From: Bicycling Magazine, March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 333 calories, 7 grams protein, 12 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 33), 53 grams carbohydrates, 15
milligrams cholesterol, 103 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
