<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: 13 scarifying cinematic versions of `boo'
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Probably the scariest thing at the movies these days is the
success of ``Scream'' and its ilk. Most of these splatter-spattered
goofs are derivative and not nearly as clever as they think they
are.
</P>
<P>
   For some real chills, check out these 13 reasons to be afraid of
the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freaks'' (1932): Tod Browning's legendary film about the
vengeance wreaked by some circus freaks on a selfish and
manipulative trapeze artist who harms one of their own is still one
of the most shocking pictures ever made.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Exorcist'' (1973): The later scenes, with little Linda
Blair spewing obscenities and pea soup, are actually less chilling
than the early ones in which her actress-mother (Ellen Burstyn)
first notices that something's not the same about her little girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Night of the Living Dead'' (1968): It may have become too
familiar and its collection of very '60s flesh-eating zombies too
camp. But that opening in the cemetery still gives you shivers. And
talk about an image of America devouring itself ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Island of Lost Souls'' (1933): The recent remake, starring
Marlon Brando, is horrifying in a totally different way. This
adaptation of H.G. Wells' tale of a mad scientist (Charles
Laughton) turning animals into men will give you the real creeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alien'' (1979): The sequel was more of an action-thriller.
This is like a haunted-house movie set on board a spooky spaceship
with the crew getting picked off one by one. The scene where
something disagrees with John Hurt at dinner remains one of the
most gruesome ever filmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry: Portrait of a Serial
</P>
<P>
   Killer'' (1990): Loosely based on a true story, this starkly
brutal little film helped make Michael Rooker something of a cult
star. The entire cast is quite good (read, squalidly believable),
and a videotape of a family massacre is pit-of-the-stomach
terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brood'' (1979): You could just as easily go with David
Cronenberg's better-known ``The Fly,'' but here's something more
obscure and equally nasty. Samantha Eggar plays a really sick woman
whose inner rage manifests itself in some really, really scary
ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vanishing'' (1988): Not the American remake, which is a
travesty, but the original Dutch version. Something terrible
happens to a young couple while they're on vacation. The
repercussions and ultimate outcome will shake you to your very
toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Silence of the Lambs'' (1991): The multiple Oscars make us
think of Jonathan Demme's thriller in a more upscale way, but
Hannibal Lecter _ incarcerated or on a rampage _ is a nightmare
made flesh. And the other killer isn't such a good guy, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alone in the Dark'' (1982): One of those movies that even the
``cult'' types typically don't know. Four vengeful lunatics _ among
them Jack Palance and Martin Landau _ escape from their mental
institution and head for the home of their new doctor. Worth it, at
the very least, for the final twist, which is worthy of EC Comics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evil Dead 2'' (1987): Along with ``Re-Animator'' and ``Dawn of
the Dead,'' this movie mixes horror and humor (of a sort) on a
Grand Guignol scale. It's the usual
young-people-on-their-own-and-in-peril plot, but Sam Raimi takes it
so over the top that you can hardly believe your own eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``M'' (1931): Never mind ``Lolita'' or ``Happiness,'' the
controversial Todd Solodnz movie opening here Nov. 6. Here's the
movie that makes pedophilia an unspeakable horror. Peter Lorre is
the child molester-murderer whose habit of whistling ``In the Hall
of the Mountain King'' as he stalks his young prey is one of the
most ominous sounds in movies. More ominous still is the silence
when the whistling stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead of Night'' (1945): A horror-themed anthology, with some
segments more frightening than others. The last story _ about a
ventriloquist's (Michael Redgrave) twisted relationship with his
dummy _ remains a classic spine-tingler.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
