<HEADER>
A2150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS29-COX     10-28 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-REVIEWS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINI VIEWS: Short reviews of the latest on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ``The Butcher Boy'' (R) _ A dazzling, dark feat. Neil
Jordan's adaptation of Patrick McCabe's novel takes us inside the
mind of an Irish boy (Eamonn Owens) who uses his imagination first
as a shield against the world, then as a weapon. Owens, in his film
debut, is startlingly good, and he's backed by a strong supporting
cast, including Stephen Rea and Fiona Shaw. Watching the movie on
tape is a plus; you may need to rewind sometimes to penetrate the
thick Irish accents. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Habit'' (R) _ In his insinuating Manhattan thriller,
writer-director-star Larry Fessenden plays an alcoholic wreck who
believes the hot new girl he's dating may be a vampire. Set mainly
in the East Village, the movie creates a creepy, compelling analogy
between vampire myths and substance abuse. And it keeps you
guessing till the very end.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Deep Impact'' (PG-13) _ Mimi Leder's end-of-the-world epic
is as somber as ``Armageddon'' is silly. If you don't think the
apocalypse should play like a video game, that's a good thing. The
movie focuses on a disparate bunch of people: TV reporter Tea
Leoni, a teenager (Elijah Wood) and his girlfriend, and the crew of
the space mission (including Robert Duvall and Blair Underwood)
sent to keep the comet from hitting Earth. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Fear and Loathing in Las Vegas'' (R) _ Johnny Depp and
Benicio Del Toro trash hotel rooms, ingest massive quantities of
alcohol and drugs, and mock poor Christina Ricci's portraits of
Barbra Streisand. Terry Gilliam's proudly insane adaptation of the
Hunter S. Thompson book isn't for all tastes, but it's the latest
fascinating choice in Depp's career. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Clockwatchers'' (R) _ Toni Colette, Lisa Kudrow, Parker
Posey and Alanna Ubach play temps working in the barren wastes of
corporate-land. This comedy-drama about bonding and squabbles among
the cabinet-file sisterhood has its deadpan moments, but it hangs
around too long and becomes a victim of its own stasis. Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Cats'' (Unrated) _ Now and forever, God help us. Andrew
Lloyd Webber's deathless, deadly musical is now on video. If you
like the sight of men and women in fluffy leotards, licking their
wrists like big ol' puddytats, have at it. Priced to buy, $24.95.
Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
