<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celebrate Halloween with ghoulish delights
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cyberspace is haunted. If you are searching for Halloween
inspiration, you will find ghosties and goblins, monsters and
haunts lurking everywhere. List upon list of ghoulish recipes make
you wonder if bobbing for apples and little bags of candy corn are
a thing of the past.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you're looking for a viable alternative to kids'
trick-or-treating on darkened streets, you may want to search out
some of these _ let's face it _ disgusting concoctions and turn the
kitchen over to the generation whose vocabulary is heavy on the
words ``yuck'' and ``gross.'' They are bound to have a memorable
time.
</P>
<P>
   Be prepared to find recipes for such ghoulish delicacies as
chopped up finger pizza, frog's eye salad, dirt pie and on and on,
literally, ad nauseam. The grisly eats sound a lot worse than they
are, though. The recipes are humorously written, easy to follow and
geared to kids. And don't let the names of these deadly dishes
scare you off. You will find that most of the ingredients are as
innocuous as Jell-O, food coloring and Oreo cookies and just as
easy to come by.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Bloody Eyeballs on the Rocks consists of
pimiento-stuffed olives and radishes in tomato juice. The kids can
whip up some Boogers on a Stick using Cheese Whiz, green food
coloring and pretzel sticks; and the main ingredients for Dirt Cake
are crushed up Oreo cookies and gummy worms. In fact Witches Brew
Punch, a blend of juices with the added attraction of a hunk of dry
ice in the bowl, is positively appealing. None of this stuff is
lethal and it's a sure bet that the kids will have a hilarious
Halloween concocting it all in the kitchen _ supervised of course.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some sites to check. Keep in mind that kids can also
have a lot of fun just picking this stuff out before the cooking
party even begins.
</P>
<P>
   -- An all-round good Halloween site is
http://www.meijer.com/web/halloween98/intro.html. Not only will you
find most of the recipes already mentioned but there are costume
ideas, scary stories, decorating tips, pumpkin carving ideas and
more.
</P>
<P>
   -- Another fun site is http://www.excell.net/lily1013/samhain.
Along with instructions on how to whip up Swamp Slime, Caterpillar
Sandwiches, and Slug Guts, there is interesting information on the
origins of this ancient autumnal spookfest as well as safety tips,
haunted houses, games and lots of other stuff.
</P>
<P>
   -- For a huge list of just straight Halloween recipes, some
gory, some pretty appealing call up
http://soar.Berkeley.edu/recipes/new/holiday
</P>
<P>
   /halloween/indexall.html.
</P>
<P>
   -- The old standbys have Halloween-decorated treats, too. Check
for chocolate (including Chocolate Spider Web Cake and Spider Web
Munch, below) at http://www.hersheys.com/new/spidercake.html and
www.tollhouse.com.
</P>
<P>
   -- Recipes lurking at
http://columbialinks.com/halloween/recipes.htm include one for
Frozen Hand (see below) to lend a nice punch to the punch bowl.
</P>
<P>
   -- Creepy sound effects accompany the concoctions at
http://www.geocities.com/EnchantedForest
</P>
<P>
   /Glade/5048/halloween.html, home of the infamous Boogers on a
Stick.
</P>
<P>
   -- Kids will flip over the recipes at
http://www.mountain-breeze.com/halloween/index.html mainly because
the recipes are almost too gross for a family newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   -- Looking for Halloween health food? It does exist on the Net.
Check out http://www.wellville
</P>
<P>
   .com/harvest.html for things like Greenie Beanies with Potato
Heads and Smashing Pumpkin Pie in Your Face.
</P>
<P>
   0 TRICK
</P>
<P>
   Frozen Hand
</P>
<P>
   Red, blue or green food coloring
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   1new disposable plastic or rubber glove
</P>
<P>
   Add food coloring to water until it reaches desired color. Fill
glove with colored water, fastening end with a twist tie or rubber
band. Hang glove from a shelf in the freezer and freeze overnight.
When frozen, remove glove from ice and place ``hand'' in the punch
bowl.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Spider Web Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 40-45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30-35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 2/3cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   2eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups buttermilk or sour milk (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   ONE-BOWL BUTTERCREAM FROSTING:
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons butter or margarine, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 2/3cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   4to 6 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   SPIDER WEB:
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup white chocolate chips or 2 ounces (2 squares) white
baking chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon shortening (do not use butter, margarine, oil or
spread)
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 350 degrees. Thoroughly grease and flour two 9-inch
round baking pans.
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour, sugar, cocoa, baking soda, salt and baking powder
in large bowl; add eggs, shortening, buttermilk or sour milk and
vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Beat on low speed of mixer 1 minute, scraping bowl constantly.
Beat on high speed 3 minutes, scraping bowl occasionally. Pour
batter into prepared pans.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 30 to 35 minutes or until wooden pick inserted in center
comes out clean. Cool 10 minutes; remove from pans to wire racks.
Cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   For the frosting: Beat butter, add confectioners' sugar and
cocoa alternately with milk, beating to spreading consistency. Stir
in vanilla. Frost cake.
</P>
<P>
   Spider web: Place 1/2 cup white chocolate chips or 2 squares
white chocolate and 1/2 teaspoon shortening in small, heavy
seal-top plastic bag. Microwave at high 45 seconds. Squeeze gently.
</P>
<P>
   If necessary, microwave an additional 10 to 15 seconds; squeeze
until chocolate is melted. Make small diagonal cut in one bottom
corner of bag; squeeze mixture onto cake by piping or drizzling 4
or 5 concentric circles on top of cake.
</P>
<P>
   Using a knife or wooden pick, immediately draw 8 to 10 lines
from center to edges of cake at regular intervals to form web.
Garnish with a ``spider'' made from candies.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To sour milk, use 4 1/2 teaspoons white vinegar plus milk
to equal 1 1/2 cups. _ From Hershey's
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 472 calories, 6 grams protein, 20 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 37), 74 grams carbohydrates, 37
milligrams cholesterol, 45xd3 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Spider Web Munch
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2cups (12-ounce package) semi-sweet chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1cup creamy peanut butter, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   3cups toasted rice cereal
</P>
<P>
   In a small, heavy-duty saucepan over low heat, heat chips and
3/4 cup peanut butter stirring constantly until smooth; remove from
heat. Add confectioners' sugar; stir vigorously until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Place cereal in large bowl. Add 1 cup melted chocolate mixture;
stir until all cereal is coated. Place on ungreased baking sheet.
Using small metal spatula, shape into a 10-inch circle with
slightly raised 1-inch-wide border. Pour remaining melted chocolate
mixture in center of circle; spread to border.
</P>
<P>
   For the spider web: Place the remaining peanut butter in a
heavy-duty plastic bag. Cut a tiny corner from bag; squeeze to pipe
concentric circles on top of chocolate. Using a wooden pick or tip
of sharp knife, pull tip through peanut butter from center to
border. Chill for 30 minutes or until firm. Cut into wedges to
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 225 calories, 5 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 60), 22 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 66 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
