<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2153 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECIPE-SWAP29-COX     10-28 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPE-SWAP29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One hot tomato: A salad that's worth savoring
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doris Hall of Monroe, Georgia was the one answering the call
from Frances Allen of Atlanta for this unusual tomato salad. It's
made with canned tomatoes, fresh bell pepper and celery, green
olives and crushed saltines, bound with a small amount of
mayonnaise.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Tomato Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10-15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chilling time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   214 1/2-ounce cans diced tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1bell pepper, cored, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   3-4ribs celery, minced
</P>
<P>
   13-ounce jar green, stuffed olives, drained and sliced
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1(or so) stack saltines, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a large bowl. Chill at least 30
minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 123 calories, 2 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 40), 17 grams carbohydrates, 2 milligrams
cholesterol, 615 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   When Christian Harris of Atlanta asked for a repeat of Triple
Apple Waffles, published in January 1997, it sounded like a brunch
or dessert idea others might want to try with some fresh apples.
Cider and apple butter go into the waffles, and they're served with
caramelized apples.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Triple Apple Waffles
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons double-acting baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   Pinch freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup apple cider
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup spiced apple butter
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream or lightly
</P>
<P>
   sweetened whipped cream
</P>
<P>
   Preheat waffle iron. Preheat oven to 350 degrees so you can
reheat the waffles after they are made.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter; reserve. In a large bowl, whisk together the
flour, baking powder, cinnamon, ginger, nutmeg and sugars. In
another bowl, whisk together the cider, milk, eggs and vanilla
until well-blended. Pour the liquid ingredients over the dry
ingredients and stir well with the whisk. Mix in the apple butter
and fold in the melted butter.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not your iron's grids are well-seasoned or made of a
nonstick material, it is best to lightly butter or spray the grids
of your iron for these waffles; the batter is quite sticky. Spoon
out about 1/2 cup batter onto the hot grids. Spread the batter
evenly with a metal spatula or wooden spoon. Close the lid and bake
until browned and set.
</P>
<P>
   Keep the finished waffles on a cooling rack while you make the
rest of the batch. Right before serving, reheat them, putting them
in a single layer on a rack in the oven, for about 3 minutes. _
From ``Waffles From Morning to Midnight'' by Dorie Greenspan
(Morrow, $15)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving, without ice cream or whipped cream: 239 calories, 6
grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 35), 33
grams carbohydrates, 124 milligrams cholesterol, 268 milligrams
sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Caramelized Apples
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   5or 6 firm Golden Delicious apples, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup apple cider
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons dark rum (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Place the apples in a bowl with the lemon juice. Toss to coat
the slices with juice. Melt the butter in a large skillet over
medium heat; add the sugar and stir. Add the apples and saute,
stirring constantly, until soft, brown, and lightly caramelized,
about 10 minutes. Add the cider and bring to a boil. Add the rum,
if using it, and cook another minute to boil off the alcohol. _
From ``Waffles From Morning to Midnight''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 172 calories, less than 1 gram protein, 8 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 42), 27 grams carbohydrates, 21
milligrams cholesterol, 1 milligram sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for recipes for this column should be sent
to Recipe Swap, Food Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689,
Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone number. E-mail:
mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
