<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BATTLES $10 MILLION GOP CAMPAIGN BLITZ FROM ROSE GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton launched a Rose Garden counter
offensive Wednesday against a surprise $10 million Republican
campaign blitz designed to cast the mid-term congressional
elections as a referendum on his embattled presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the Republicans' ad campaign in 33 states and 56
congressional districts is merely designed to shift voters'
attention away from their day-to-day concerns and instead focus on
the scandal clouding his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he hoped his actions in recent weeks have shown ``a
real commitment'' to dealing with issues afflicting ordinary
citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to sugar coat the fact that I made a mistake
and that I didn't want anybody to know about it,'' Clinton said.
``I hope very much that they have seen that I'm doing my best to
atone for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they can sense the rededication and the intensified
efforts I am making for the cause of peace around the world, for
the cause of prosperity at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton commented during a Rose Garden news conference with
Colombian President Andres Pastrana.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of contested House and Senate elections next Tuesday
will influence the pace and scope of the looming congressional
impeachment inquiry into the White House sex scandal involving
Clinton and former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are working to expand their 11-seat majority in the
435-seat House and their 55 to 45 seat edge in the Senate.
Democrats are hoping to hold down traditional losses in off-year
elections for the party holding the White House in an effort to
stem the GOP-led effort to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The National Republican Campaign Committee (NRCC) began airing
the new campaign ads Tuesday evening. The commercials in 22
congressional districts included direct or indirect references to
the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The voice in one ad says that ``for seven months, he lied to
us,'' adding: ``Should we reward not telling the truth? That is the
question of this election: Reward Bill Clinton. Or vote
Republican.''
</P>
<P>
   A second commercial asks: ``What do you tell your kids?''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the advertising campaign appeared designed in part
to rally the GOP faithful to turn out next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder, R-Ga., the leader of the Republican campaign
committee working to elect Republicans to the House, said the
commercials were an attempt to make Clinton the issue in the fall
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the leader of the party with the wrong ideas,'' Linder
said.
</P>
<P>
   GOP Chairman Jim Nicholson said the advertisements raised the
``unspoken question for voters in 1998... `After all we've learned,
do we trust Bill Clinton's judgment so much that we want to reward
him with a Democrat Congress and complete control of our
government?''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Crawford, spokeswoman for the NRCC, said the ads ``spell
out very clearly for the public what the differences are between
Republicans and Democrats in terms of what direction we want to
lead the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivia Morgan, the spokeswoman for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, said the Republican effort was merely a ``$10
million excuse for their failure to address issues that people
actually care about.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sought to rebut the GOP ads during his Rose Garden news
conference. He challenged Republican questions about whether he had
been ``trustworthy'' by claiming he had kept a higher percentage of
his campaign promises than the last five presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the GOP offensive was intended to persuade
Americans to turn their backs on efforts by Democrats to address
problems that citizens face in their everyday lives.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are ``basically saying to the American people... we
don't want you to think about yourself,'' Clinton declared. ``We
want you to give up everything that could help you. And if we can
distract you and divert your attention, that will enable us to hold
onto our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what people ought to say to their children is that,
`When someone makes a mistake, they should admit it and try to
rectify it,''' Clinton said. The president said his admission of
his 18-month sexual relationship with Lewinsky in a nationally
televised White House address on Aug. 17 illustrates that if people
admit their mistakes, ``they can be stronger in their personal
lives, in their family lives and in their work lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his admission and efforts to atone for his mistake
ought to serve as an example of how people become stronger through
adversity and reassessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that in that sense the lesson is a good one that it
should apply to everyone, from the president on down,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that Democrats would do well next Tuesday if the
election were fought on Democratic and Republican differences over
Social Security reform, medical patients' rights, school
modernization, boosting the minimum wage, restrictions on tobacco
sales to teenagers and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appealed for a large turnout in the off-year election,
saying the contest was ``not an ordinary election because of the
challenges facing our country and we don't need an ordinary
mid-term turnout.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
