   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Boris Yeltsin is said to be suffering an ``asthenic condition,''
meaning weakness. Is it possible for someone eventually to go
vodkaput?
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,500 journalists are covering John Glenn's space flight.
Do they remember how to cover a national story that doesn't involve
sex and lies?
</P>
<P>
   Overheard on our bus: ``Pretty cool. For Halloween this year
John Glenn gets to dress up like an astronaut.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats accuse the White House of hoarding party cash for
Al Gore's 2000 campaign. With Gore the problem won't be funds but
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things that make us happiest,'' says Mr. Clinton, ``are
those things which reaffirm our common humanity.'' Is that what he
was doing with Monica Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   The default rate on student loans has fallen for six straight
years, it's reported. Any statistics on the rate at which students
write home for money?
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch has had winds near 180 mph. The only thing close
to that we can imagine is Congress in its last few hours of a
session.
</P>
<P>
   Fidel Castro has suggested Cuba be allowed to field two
major-league baseball teams. Before the Phillies can field even
one?
</P>
<P>
   Germany's new chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, has taken office.
No word on what Helmut Kohl will do now, but don't people with his
name usually move to Newcastle?
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Ilse from Oelwein says not a lot is going right:
``Washington is a mess, the new TV season is horrible and Art Bell
won't stay gone.''
</P>
