<HEADER>
A2176 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-AD-HNS &LR;      10-28 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-AD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GOP AD PORTRAYS SCHUMER AS FLIP-FLOPPING ON VOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ First they called Rep. Charles E. Schumer a
bleeding-heart liberal, then they attacked his congressional
attendance record. Now, in a new advertisement released Wednesday,
the Republicans claim the man who wants Sen. Alfonse D'Amato's seat
can't make up his mind.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement says the Brooklyn Democrat repeatedly
flip-flops on his congressional votes, changing his vote from yes
to no, or no to yes, sometimes in the span of 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican Chairman William Powers said the latest
advertisement, which cost $750,000, will air in all major media
markets around the state for the duration of the campaign. The
chairman said the ad would probably be the last commissioned by the
state party for D'Amato in this election.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we've seen time and time again with Chuck Schumer.
He puts his finger up to the wind and sees what's the right way to
go, casts a vote ... runs back to switch his vote to be correct,
politically correct,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if D'Amato ever switched a vote, Powers replied:
``Don't know. Don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schumer campaign had not seen the ad as of Wednesday
afternoon and was unable to comment on the substance.
</P>
<P>
   However, spokesman Howard Wolfson suggested the Republicans were
simply trying to recover from Tuesday's revelation that D'Amato,
who has made Schumer's voting record the focus of his campaign for
the last few weeks, skipped hundreds of votes while serving on the
Nassau County board of supervisors in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``His entire campaign was exposed as a fraud,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
<P>
   On another matter, Powers said that in a race in which Schumer
has made trust an issue, the Democrat ``needs to explain why''
federal authorities in 1983 investigated him for allegedly using
government workers to staff his political campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, which focused on Schumer's conduct while he
was in the New York Assembly and running for Congress in 1980, came
to an end when the federal government decided not to pursue
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charges were raised 18 years ago,'' Wolfson said. ``Chuck
cooperated fully. They were completely investigated and they were
dropped.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Powers said that since Schumer brought up the fact
that D'Amato skipped hundreds of votes while serving as a local
elected official on Long Island in 1980, ancient history is fair
game in this campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if somebody raises an issue of things 18 years ago,
well I guess things then become fair game,'' Powers said. ``If you
are talking about things 18-20 years ago, you ought to be prepared
to talk about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers later acknowledged that recalling the past is a
double-edged sword, and ``absolutely'' opens the door to a
discussion of D'Amato's ethics history.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato has been investigated repeatedly throughout his public
career. He was implicated in or connected to the 1 percent Nassau
County kickback scandal of the 1970s and the Abscam congressional
bribery sting. A 1991 Senate Ethics Committee investigation
resulted in a rebuke of D'Amato for the ``improper and
inappropriate'' use of his office to solicit illegal campaign
contributions. And D'Amato still refuses to release transcripts of
his four-day hearing before the Ethics Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al D'Amato is the most investigated senator in New York
history,'' Wolfson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
