A2181 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-TOWER-HNS &LR;      10-28 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-TOWER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS TOWER, SITE OF SHOOTING AND SUICIDES, COULD BE
REOPENED AS EARLY AS MAY 1999 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ The University of Texas tower's 28th-floor observation
deck, off-limits to the public since the mid-1970s after it was
used in a deadly sniper attack and numerous student suicide leaps,
could be reopened by May 1999, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Admission will be $5 or $6 for non-students. Remodeling costs
could approach $500,000, and operating expenses, including
security, are estimated to be $86,000 a year, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The deck has been closed since late 1974 after a series of nine
suicide jumps that spanned several decades, but also in reaction to
the 1966 sniper attack by Charles Whitman, which left 16 people
dead and 31 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, the slaughter ranked as the nation's
worst mass murder _ a crime made easier by unfettered public access
to the deck. After killing his wife and mother, Whitman took three
weapons and 700 rounds of ammunition onto the deck and opened fire
on campus, a rain of bullets that lasted more than 90 minutes
before he was slain by police.
</P>
<P>
   Pending final approval by the UT board of regents at a meeting
in Houston Nov. 11-12, the observation deck will be modified to
preclude the kinds of tragedies that led to its closure, officials
said. The open-air deck will be encased in an ironwork barrier
consistent with the ``historic context'' of the 61-year-old tower,
said UT President Larry Faulkner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my opinion we should use this icon of higher education
in positive ways,'' said Faulkner as he formally asked regents to
reopen the tower deck.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the deck sealed to the public would leave Texans ``with
nothing but the history of unfortunate experiences,'' he said.
Reopened access will serve ``to invite the people of Texas to view
their campus and to renew their sense of ownership in the state's
leading academic enterprise,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner's recommendation came in response to six months of
study prompted by student requests to reopen the observation deck.
The tower itself, known as the Main Building, has remained open,
housing administrative offices and archives.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner's plan to reopen the tower includes a variety of steps
to ensure safety, as well as make the tower accessible to the
disabled. The proposal calls for initially allowing access on
weekends only and limiting tours to escorted groups of 12 people,
who would be allowed about 20 minutes on the deck to take in the
view. Visitors would be allowed to carry only small personal items,
including cameras.
</P>
<P>
   The plan presumes there will be ``extraordinary interest'' when
the deck reopens, possibly in time for the spring commencement in
May, which might result in access times being reserved for
graduating seniors and other students.
</P>
<P>
   UT Student Government President Annie Holand praised Faulkner
for responding to the student body's desire, saying the tower
provides students a ``real connection'' to the university.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner described the tower as ``the most important symbol for
academic aspiration and achievement in Texas. It also is the
strongest image uniting members of the university community.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some former students who attended the university during
Whitman's shooting spree and when suicides were common have
expressed their discomfort with the proposal. One of them, Richard
Kelly of Austin, said he can't go near the tower without re-living
the terror of the sniper attack he witnessed on Aug. 1, 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always looking over my shoulder,'' he said. ``I'll never
forget the swath of blood I saw running down the sidewalk.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, those who have stated such concerns acknowledge there are
ways to make the tower a safe vantage point _ and there will always
be other options for those bent on human destruction. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
