<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2191 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARTIN-DRIVEL-NYT &LR;      10-28 0409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTIN-DRIVEL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: come out.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He does much of his writing at home in Santa Barbara, Calif.
When he is not working, and sometimes when he is working, he
travels. On his trips, he looks at art and buys paintings to add to
his collection. As an art appreciator, he is self-taught, although
he has learned a great deal from dealers. Two years ago, he was the
voice on the Acoustiguide for the ``Picasso and Portraiture'' show
at the Metropolitan Museum, doing it straight except to suggest
that people should not follow his commentary blindly, and collide
with the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   His taste has grown, he said, but there is still a place in his
heart for really terrible paintings, like California landscapes.
``I was talking to a very big collector who has very sophisticated
paintings,'' he said. ``We were in a museum, and he took me aside
and confessed, `You know what I really like, the way moonlight is
reflected on water.''' Martin agrees.
</P>
<P>
   In his collection, along with Picassos, he has Edward Hopper's
``Captain Upton's House,'' a view of the Two Lights Lighthouse in
Cape Elizabeth, Maine This summer there was a controversy about the
planned demolition of the keeper's cottage next to the lighthouse.
If that happens, said Martin, deadpan, ``I would have to have the
picture repainted.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pure Drivel,'' there is a piece called ``Hissy Fit,'' about
a New York writer's sense of dislocation in Los Angeles. As a Los
Angeles writer in New York, he pondered the local reaction: ``Am I
perceived as an interloper or as a comedian who dabbles in
something that's not his business? That's my paranoia.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the variety of his accomplishments in the movies and his
appearance with Robin Williams at Lincoln Center in Mike Nichols'
1988 production of ``Waiting for Godot,'' he still regards himself
as a comedian, not as an actor. ``My pride is in being funny and
writing funny and in doing things I've written,'' he said. Asked if
he felt a need to direct, he answered, ``No, I feel a need not to
direct,'' and added, ``I'm doing exactly what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   During a recent sabbatical from the movies, he was flooded with
ideas for comic essays. Since he has described them as
``after-dinner mints to the big meal of literature,'' it seemed
logical to ask when he would do a big meal, a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Although he seemed tantalized by the possibility, he had to
admit, ``I ate my dessert first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
