<P>
   GOPADS _ Washington _ It what is clearly a gamble, the
Republican Party is pumping $10 million into campaign ads that
blantantly refer to the Lewinsky saga. There are several variations
of the ads, but one of the most controversial is now running in
Georgia Democrat Sanford Bishop's district. Bishop says he is not
concerned because the public will ``see right through the
Republican antics.'' His opponenet Joseph McCormick had no idea
that the ads were going to run and he's a bit surprised since
impeachment has not been an issue in that campaign. Rep. John
Linder, the chairman of the National Republican Congressional
Campaign Committee, which is footing the bill for the ads, said the
the motivation behind the ads is to help the GOP ``ride the wave''
and pick up a dozen more seats. Just last week, Linder said they
would not be running such ads as focus groups told them the public
has had enough on the impeachment front. Political scientists say
the latest batch of ads are a gamble, given the public's disdain
for the impeachment inquiry,but they are also smart as there is no
mention of Monica, rather a focus on honesty and trustworthiness
and balance. But Republican strategist and columnist Arianna
Huffington says the GOP leadership should think twice about running
ads swiping at Clinton's honesty when Gingrich and the GOP deceived
the public last week by caving into the White House budget. ``Let
the best liar win,'' Huffington said. (Carr, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
