 &QL; 
USWEST (Washington) - When a federal audit of USWest and other Baby
Bells is completed in a few weeks, it's expected to show that some
telephone equipment is missing, according to congressional
regulators and US West itself. In fact, a lot of equipment - $5
billion dollars' worth. That means customers in Arizona and around
the rest of the country may have been overcharged by millions of
dollars for telephone service. When he found out about the
discrepancies between inventory and claims, Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va.,
chairman of the House Commerce Committee, fired off a letter to FCC
Chairman William Kennard ordering him to determine whether there
had been ``negligent management or willful misrepresentation'' by
the Bell companies. Meanwhile Sen. John McCain, chairman of the
Senate Commerce Committee, hung back, saying he'd wait for the
results of the full audit. The difference between their reactions
is being blamed on one big thing: money, specifically, campaign
contributions, and even more specifically, donations from USWest,
an aggressive player of the election money game. By ADRIANNE FLYNN.
