<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-DEPOT-FORESTS29-     10-28 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-DEPOT-FORESTS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OLD GROWTH FOREST PROTESTS AN OLD STORY FOR CANADIAN LOGGERS
 &HT;    680&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Timber companies in Canada, source of much of the
``old growth'' wood allegedly sold in Home Depot stores and other
building material outlets in the United States, are scrambling for
ways to give their products an environmentally friendlier image.
</P>
<P>
   A largely successful boycott campaign in Europe already has cut
sales of wood products from British Columbia's huge central coast
forests, David Haley, professor of forestry economics at the
University of British Columbia in Vancouver, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The forests, owned primarily by the province of British
Columbia, contain the largest areas of undisturbed temperate rain
forest left on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The threat that demonstrations and boycotts at Home Depot, now
America's largest forest products retailer, could have the same
effect in this country at a time when Asian sales are depressed
because of the economic downturn in Japan has had a seismic impact
in timber company offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``These activities in the United States are viewed very, very
seriously indeed,'' Haley said Wednesday in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our larger companies are making major changes in
their land use policies'' in order to blunt environmental concerns,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Most dramatic was the announcement in June by MacMillan Bloedel
Ltd., the province's largest in British Columbia, that it would
stop clear-cutting and come up with plans to increase the
conservation of old-growth, or virgin, forests.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Greenpeace, the environmental group in the
forefront of many of the protests over use of products from
old-growth forests in Canada, South America and Asia, shared a
bottle of champagne with company officials at a press conference
announcing the new policies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, MacMillan Bloedel also agreed to seek
``certification'' for its products by a new environmental group
that audits forest management practices and issues a ``green seal''
of approval if it concludes that a company is following
environmentally sound practices.
</P>
<P>
   Although they haven't reached agreements with organizations like
Greenpeace or the Rainforest Action Network, which staged
demonstrations against Home Depot on Wednesday in Atlanta, other
companies have applied for certification in the hope of giving
their products a greener image with retailers and perhaps blunting
any future boycotts.
</P>
<P>
   The certification plan, in which companies that meet a set of
conservation standards would be allowed to display a green seal of
approval on the door frames, plywood or other products they market,
is being pushed by a Mexico-based group called the Forest
Stewardship Council.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups including the World Wildlife Fund,
Greenpeace, the Natural Resources Defense Council and the
Rainforest Action Network are members of the stewardship council.
</P>
<P>
   So are some industry groups. The council ``audits'' forests to
make sure they are being managed in environmentally sound ways
before issuing its seal of approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studies show that people are not willing to pay more for
their forest products if they have the green seal,'' said Haley,
``but it becomes a question of market share. If the prices are
roughly equal, they will opt for the certified product.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Greenpeace has started opposing efforts by Canadian
forest product companies to obtain environmental certification for
any timber removed from the coastal forest, which environmentalists
have taken to calling the Great Bear Rainforest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also oppose that,'' said Liz Barrat-Brown, a senior
attorney with the Natural Resources Defense Council, a group that
avoids ``direct action'' tactics such as those carried out in
Atlanta on Wednesday in favor of issuing scientific reports and
filing legal actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think no logging is appropriate in the Great Bear
Rainforest until they set aside a much more of the area for
preservation,'' Barrat-Brown added. ``So far only about 6 percent
of that forest has been preserved.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Companies whose products have been targeted by the
demonstrations include West Frazer Timber Co., Western Forest
Products Ltd. and International Forest Products.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth, smaller company, Sawder Industries Ltd., the private
company of the chairman of International Forest Products, also has
been targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Fitzgerald, a spokesman for MacMillan Bloedel, said his
company settled with Greenpeace after years of protests. He said
that the demand that all logging in the old-growth forests cease in
favor of ``second-growth'' trees is not reasonable, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a relatively new industry, mostly having grown up
after World War II,'' he said by telephone, ``so there will be no
mature second-growth trees for another two or three decades.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
