<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Nov. 1,
1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELIMINATE: TAJ-MAHAL-MUSIC.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE Stories
</P>
<P>
   ALANIS-MORISSETTE-MUSIC (Los Angeles) _ The woman who sings
Alanis Morissette's new album sounds like a mess. In the 17 songs
on ``Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie'' (Maverick), which is to
be released on Tuesday, she has been attached to abusive men, she's
been stuffing and starving herself, she has taken too many
antibiotics, and she's been working herself to the point of
collapse. She has felt jealous, misunderstood, worthless; nothing,
from shopping to sex to wealth and worldwide popularity, has made
her happy. And every bit of trauma and frustration comes out in her
voice: in its harried vibrato and sudden yelping breaks, in its
banshee wails and caustic nasal turns. While her litany of
self-doubt is set in the past tense, the wounds still sound raw. By
Jon Pareles. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKERS-PARENTHOOD (Undated) _ In 1998, though, rock and its
sibling genre, hip-hop, seem headed for a different future. On the
MTV Music Video Awards, the rapper and actor Will Smith accepted
his awards accompanied by his 5-year-old son, Justin; Smith's
current single, ``Just the Two of Us,'' is an ebullient ode to the
boy. Billie Joe, of the punk band Green Day, focused his awards
speech on his wife, at home awaiting the birth of their second
child. Performers included two cutting-edge mother figures:
Courtney Love of Hole and the evening's big winner, Madonna, whose
latest album, ``Ray of Light'' describes her spiritual awakening
after the birth of her daughter, Lourdes. Rock-and-roll, the
cultural home of perpetual adolescence, was clearly engaging the
ultimate passage into maturity: parenthood. By Ann Powers. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   FILM AND VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   ARAB-ACTORS (Undated) _ The Arab-American actor Sayed Badreya
has had no problem finding work in Hollywood. With his dark beard
and his accented English, he has had his pick of parts as
terrorists, hijackers, kidnappers and Islamic militants. ``Usually
I play the bad guy role, a terrorist or someone,'' Badreya said by
telephone from Egypt, where he is on a film shoot with Al Pacino,
playing the head of the military wing of Hezbollah. After years of
virtual invisibility, Arab-Americans are finally finding prominence
in Hollywood movies _ as terrorists and villains. They are only the
latest in a long line of ethnic groups and nationalities cast in
sterotypical bad-guy roles, from American Indians to Germans to
Japanese to African Americans to Russians. By Laurie Goodstein.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   HANGING-ROCK-VIDEO (Undated) _ A sweetly knowing look crosses
the face of the lovely young Miranda. ``You must learn to love
someone else apart from me, Sara,'' she says to a schoolmate. ``I
won't be here much longer.'' It never becomes clear how Miranda
knows that, but in Peter Weir's ``Picnic at Hanging Rock,'' as
mysterious as ever in two new video editions, just about everything
keeps us guessing. What we do know is that the year is 1900, that
the location is central Australia and that by sundown on Saint
Valentine's Day, Miranda (Anne Lambert) and two other students at
the brutally proper Appleyard College for young women will have
drifted away during a picnic as if hypnotized, disappearing among
the crags of the 500-foot-high volcanic formation called Hanging
Rock. By Peter M. Nichols. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CATS-VIDEO (Undated) _ Is it a vaudeville show? An oratorio? A
singing and dancing storybook? A live-action cartoon? An
environmental theater piece? A pretentious pop allegory (with
Christian symbolism) that compares the feline condition to the
human one? At various times, ``Cats,'' the indestructible Andrew
Lloyd Webber megahit, is all of the above. Restaged for home video
by David Mallet, does ``Cats,'' which will be shown Monday night at
8 o'clock on PBS, work on the small screen? Yes and no. By Stephen
Holden. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   SCORSESE-SCHRADER-FILM (New York) _ P ERCHED on a director's
chair at Eighth Avenue and 44th Street one recent midnight, Martin
Scorsese is somewhere he never expected to be: directing a movie
again on his native city's mean streets. Nor did he ever expect to
be working again from a script by Paul Schrader, with whom he
collaborated on cinematic landmarks like ``Taxi Driver'' and
``Raging Bull,'' and with whom he believed he would never work
again. How Mr. Scorsese came to be here, shooting ``Bringing Out
the Dead,'' which Mr. Schrader adapted from a recently published
first novel by Joe Connelly, is in part a typical movie-business
tale of switching gears because of logistical delays in the filming
of ``Dino,'' based on the life of Dean Martin. By Jean Nathan.
(Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE
</P>
<P>
   SWAN-LAKE-DANCE (Undated) _ Matthew Bourne'S production of
``Swan Lake'' opened on Broadway as something of an anomaly. Word
from Los Angeles, where the production played last year, was that
the show was touching but campy. Earlier reviews in England, where
the show originated, tended to dwell on what this ``Swan Lake'' was
not, particularly among the older dance critics. By Jennifer
Dunning. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ADAM-COOPER-DANCE (Undated) _ Adam Cooper looks more like a
young club hipster than an elegantly refined ballet prince, despite
his shining pedigree as a principal dancer who played such regal
roles at England's Royal Ballet. He is dancing a lead in ``Swan
Lake'' these days once more, but not as the ballet's lovesick
prince. Instead, Cooper plays a powerful male swan and his
counterpart, a sneering piece of rough trade, in Matthew Bourne's
exuberantly irreverent adaptation of ``Swan Lake,'' now playing on
Broadway at the Neil Simon Theater. By Jennifer Dunning. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER
</P>
<P>
   CANBY-THEATER (Undated) _ Vincent Canby reviews Matthew Bourne's
``Swan Lake''; ``Footloose'' and ``Getting and Spending. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   LITTLE-ME-THEATER (Undated) _ In the early fall of 1962, a group
of New York theater artists ventured down to Philadelphia to try
out a new musical comedy, ``Little Me,'' based on a racy novel by
Patrick Dennis. In terms of comedy and drama, they found, offstage
events sometimes rivaled those in the show: a bathroom sink
untimely ripped from a wall, a police officer commandeered to
arrest the creative team, and a world teetering on the brink of
nuclear annihilation. In recent interviews, Sic Caesar, Cy Coleman,
Cy Feuer and Neil Simon _ who has written about the show in his
1996 memoir, ``Rewrites'' _ remembered the days they spent together
36 years ago in a Manhattan rehearsal hall, at the Erlanger Theater
in Philadelphia and at the Lunt-Fontanne on Broadway. By Mervyn
Rothstein. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MARTIN-SHORT-THEATER (Undated) _ On Broadway, Martin Short has
been lifting off every night in previews of the Roundabout Theater
Company revival of ``Little Me,'' the 1962 musical comedy for which
Neil Simon wrote the book. In the show, which opens on Nov. 12, he
plays not one but seven men in the life of Belle Poitrine, nee
Schlumpfert, the curvaceous beauty turned tell-all memoirist from
Drifter's Row (portrayed by Faith Prince). As those he works with
know, Short is a master at appearing spontaneous in a completely
scripted situation, creating a sense of suspense during a
performance that keeps an audience wondering what will happen next.
By Janny Scott. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   SUSANNAH-OPERA (Undated) _ Quick, name the most often performed
full-length American opera. It's not ``Porgy and Bess,'' which was
banished from the opera house for decades and branded a highbrow
musical. It's not ``West Side Story,'' which was intended for
Broadway despite the fact that Bernstein, late in life, gave it
some operatic trappings. And it's not ``Amahl and the Night
Visitors,'' which, since it was commissioned by a television
network, could not run longer than an hour. It's ``Susannah,'' with
music and libretto by Carlisle Floyd, a native of South Carolina.
By K. Robert Schwarz. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   NUTCRACKER-MUSIC (Undated) _ In a new recording by Valery
Gergiev and the Kirov Orchestra (Philips 289 462 114-2; CD), to be
replicated in a concert at Carnegie Hall on Saturday evening, ``The
Nutcracker'' takes on a symphonic aspect of unsuspected power and
depth. By Lawrence B. Johnson. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-AND-PERFORMER (Undated) _ The delicate dance between
performer and performed has played out in a number of places this
young season. It is a dance in the form of a competition, for what
is it we go to hear? The pianist or the piano sonata? The singer or
the song? By Bernard Holland. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   OPERA-WORDS (Undated) _ Words, words, words: opera finds it hard
to do without them. In the 1950s, the German composer Boris Blacher
wrote a wordless ``abstract opera,'' to which he gave the imposing
title ``Abstract Opera No. 1,'' though he never repeated the
experiment. He left that to Gyorgy Ligeti, who in the next decade
wrote ``Adventures,'' followed by ``New Adventures,'' for three
singers who communicate with one another and with their audience by
nonverbal means: muttering, cajoling, shrieking in surprise. And in
the decade after that, Philip Glass, in ``Einstein on the Beach,''
and Karlheinz Stockhausen, in ``Thursday,'' dispensed for long
stretches not only with words but also with onstage singers, to
create opera as mime. But these will probably remain special cases.
Opera in general needs singers, and singers need words. The
problems start when we come to what the audience needs. By Paul
Griffiths. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   POP MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   ART
</P>
<P>
   NY-CHELSEA-GALLERIES (New York) _ The other day, an artist who
will remain nameless for obvious reasons told me she was worried
about her forthcoming show, not because the work was causing her
more than the usual anxiety but because her gallery happens not to
be in Chelsea. Unfortunately, I knew what she meant. At last count,
around 60 galleries had colonized the area roughly between 17th
Street and 27th Street on the far West Side of Manhattan. I spent a
couple of days recently making the rounds of the neighborhood. I
liked Chelsea very much when it first started to develop as the
un-SoHo, but now, though I still want to like it, I'm not so sure.
By Michael Kimmelman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   CAROL-RAMA-ART (Boston) _ Carol Rama'S remarkable paintings were
last seen here in 1996, in ``Inside the Visible,'' a sprawling
group show of 36 female artists. Featuring such subject matter as
masturbation and bestiality, Ms. Rama's small, delicate watercolors
from the 1930s and 1940s were displayed in quaint, old-fashioned
frames. Now, a comprehensive retrospective called ``Carolrama''
(she prefers the conjoined version of her name) is on view here
through Jan. 3 at the Institute of Contemporary Art. By Ann Wilson
LLoyd.
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-BASEBALL-ART (Undated) _ Memorabilia of Shoeless Joe
Jackson, one of several White Sox players who was accused of
intentionally losing a World Series to the Cincinnati Reds will be
auction on Tuesday at Christie's in New York. Jackson still owns
the third-highest career batting average in baseball history, at
.356. By Ira Berkow. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   ZOOM-TV (Boston) _ Listen up, Zoomers, Ubbi Dubbi linguists of
all stripes, childhood pleasures are coming around again. PBS is
reviving ``Zoom,'' the daily variety series for 6-to-12-year-olds
that was one of the most popular children's show of the 1970s.
Considered a coupling of ``Sesame Street'' and ``Laugh-In,'' the
series was second only to ``Masterpiece Theater'' in its power to
attract public-broadcasting viewers. By Susan Diesenhouse. (Moved).
Photo.
</P>
