u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AIDS29-1STLED     10-28 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AIDS29-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON ANNOUNCES AIDS HELP FOR MINORITIES
 &HT;    Eds: Inserts 2nd graf with Clinton quote.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Warning of a ``severe and ongoing'' AIDS crisis in
minority communities, President Clinton announced a $156 million
program Wednesday to combat the spread of the disease among African
Americans and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is picking on the most vulnerable among us,'' Clinton said
at a news conference. ``The fact is, HIV infection is one of the
most deadly health disparities between African Americans, Hispanics
and White Americans, and just as we have committed to help build
one America by ending the racial and ethnic disparities and infant
mortality and cancer and other diseases, we must use all our power
to end the growing disparities in HIV and AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   The new initiative includes a prevention campaign, improved
access to drug treatments, training for health professionals who
treat the disease and federal ``crisis response teams'' that the
Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) will dispatch to
areas highly affected by AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   While overall AIDS deaths have declined for two years in a row,
AIDS remains the leading killer of African-American men age 25-44
and the second leading killer of African-American women in the same
age group. African Americans account for more than 40 percent of
all new HIV/AIDS cases, and Hispanics represent over 20 percent of
new cases of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In many minority communities, ``there's still a misconception
that this is a gay disease and that other people aren't at risk,''
said Sandy Thurman, director of the White House Office of AIDS
Policy. For that reason, she said, part of the new program will be
to explain the wider dangers of infection to people in these
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be targeted prevention efforts'' to ``raise
awareness and erase the stigma'' sometimes associated with the
disease, Thurman said. ``We be making sure the messages are in
language in that people use and understand and that is culturally
sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, for instance, the program will look ``to the
leadership in the African American church community'' to ``talk
openly to congregations about AIDS,'' explained Thurman, 44, a
Georgia native who headed AIDS Atlanta before joining the 1992
Clinton presidential campaign. The program might enlist volunteers
from the sororities and fraternities at the city's historically
black colleges to help get out its message, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The program will also increase access to new drug therapies at
the city's neighborhood health centers and train the health care
providers there in AIDS prevention and treatment, Thurman said. The
most effective response is community based or ``home-grown,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Personifying this community-based activism, perhaps, is Denise
Stokes, an AIDS educational consultant from Atlanta who introduced
Clinton at Wednesday's announcement. Diagnosed with AIDS 12 years
ago, Stokes ``is one of the first people to put a face on
heterosexual HIV infection,'' said organizers of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the funding for the minority AIDS program was
provided in the Omnibus Appropriations Act that Congress passed and
Clinton signed into law last week. The remainder will come from the
HHS budget.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
