<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-COLOMBIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FIRES BACK AT REPUBLICANS TRYING TO TURN ELECTIONS INTO
SCANDAL REFERENDUM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton fired back Wednesday at
Republicans who are trying to turn the Nov. 3 elections into a
referendum on the Monica Lewinsky scandal, saying that he believes
most Americans accept the fact that he made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the American people have seen in me over the last few
weeks a real commitment to doing what I told them I would do from
the beginning, to try to atone to them for what happened and to try
to redouble my efforts to be a good president,'' Clinton said.
``And I hope they have sensed the inner changes that have been
going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the comments during a joint news conference with
visiting Colombian President Andres Pastrana where he was asked to
respond to a $10 million ad campaign launched by Republicans last
night in an attempt to make the Lewinsky scandal an issues in
congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican ads ask Americans whether they're willing to
``reward'' Clinton for lying about his relationship with Lewinsky
by helping to elect more Democrats to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The president said Republicans are ``free to make the election
about whatever they want to make the election about'' to attract
votes. But he said he thinks Americans will be turned off by the
ads and will end up voting based on ``what's best for them and
their families.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to sugarcoat the fact that I made a mistake and
that I didn't want anybody to know about it,'' the president said.
``I think I've talked about that. The American people have had
quite a decent amount of exposure to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope very much that they have seen that I'm doing my best to
atone for it. I hope they can sense the rededication and the
intensified efforts I am making for the cause of peace around the
world, for the cause of prosperity at home,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP ads also ask Americans to think about what they should
tell their children about Clinton's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The president offered an answer to that one himself, saying the
lesson from his handling of the Lewinsky matters is that ``when
someone makes a mistake they should admit it and try to rectify
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans are hoping the ads will raise questions in
voters minds about whether Clinton can be trusted to carry on in
the job that he has held for nearly six years.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said he believes the verdict is already in on that
question too. That's why he charges that Republicans are trying to
``divert'' attention from important issues like saving Social
Security, modernizing schools and giving patients more rights in
making decisions about their own health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fair for a person to be judged on his whole
record,'' Clinton said. ``If you look at what I said I'd do when I
presented myself to the American people in 1991 and 1992, at the
long list of things we've done ... the American people I think
agree with us and not them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the real issue here. Are we right or are they
right?'' Clinton continued, calling the election ``a clear choice''
for voters on issues that really make a difference in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used his appearance with Pastrana to announce that the
budget surplus for the 1998 fiscal year amounted to $70 billion.
The surplus is the first since 1969, and the Democrats are hopeful
that they can use it to their advantage in the elections next
Tuesday by arguing that Republicans are ready to spend it on tax
cuts rather than shoring up Social Security as Clinton has
advocated.
</P>
<P>
   While most Republicans also favor using the surplus to help save
the Social Security program, many conservative members believe that
can be done while a tax cut. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1900EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
