<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2243 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALTERNATIVE-SCHOOLS-T     10-28 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-SCHOOLS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS' PRIVATE SCHOOL FOR GAYS LETS TEENS BE THEMSELVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Michael Raines didn't know he was gay in high school,
but his classmates sensed something different about him, and they
made him pay.
</P>
<P>
   At band camp during ninth grade, they tied his wrists to a post
and passed a sentence on him ``for being homosexual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was literally held up for ridicule,'' Raines says, sitting
behind a table at Dallas' Walt Whitman Community School, where he
teaches British and American literature. ``I wish I had had the
opportunity to go to a gay and lesbian high school.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Raines now teaches at one and wants to give his
students what he never felt as a teen-ager: a sense of self-worth.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its second year, the country's first private school
explicitly dedicated to that goal finds itself comfortably treading
academic waters _ even taking a few tentative strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Whitman has more than doubled its enrollment, moved into
its own space and, according to co-founder Becky Thompson, forced
the local community to confront the existence of gay and lesbian
teens.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 students registered this year, most identify
themselves as gay or lesbian, but heterosexual students are
welcome. The common denominator is the understanding that tolerance
comes first.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, the students gather in the 1-story office
building's central space, which functions as a classroom, lunchroom
and pseudo-auditorium. The staff members look more like camp
counselors than teachers. Classes are tiny, no more than five or
six students.
</P>
<P>
   A bookcase in a central classroom offers titles most public
school libraries wouldn't dare stock: ``The Penguin Book of
Homosexual Verse,'' ``Contemporary Gay &AMP; Lesbian Plays,'' ``Loving
Someone Gay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very open'' about sexuality, Thompson says. Discussions
of HIV and AIDS and frank talk about sex are part of the Life
Skills course all students take.
</P>
<P>
   DROPOUTS RETURN
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Martinez dropped out of W.T. White High School in Dallas
after several years of abuse by other students. ``I was too scared
to go to class, and I was too scared to tell my teachers,'' says
Martinez, at 21 the oldest Walt Whitman student.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez scrapped the idea of getting a GED because what he
really wants is the high-school experience _ a prom, a graduation
ceremony _ and Walt Whitman can provide that in a safe, supportive
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``In public school, you get harassed if you're out,'' says Amy
McKenna, 16, who attends Walt Whitman with her girlfriend,
Courtney, 18. ``People don't understand it, you don't make real
friends and it lowers your self-esteem. Here, you don't have to
hide it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Amy nor Courtney was officially ``out'' in public
school. Courtney always had boyfriends ``just to cover the fact
that I was gay.'' Amy says teachers complained that she spent too
much time playing sports.
</P>
<P>
   By last spring, Courtney had dropped out of school and was
living with friends. Amy, whose parents are divorced, was averaging
one or two days a week at school when she moved in with her father.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and Pamala Stone created Walt Whitman as a safety net
for teens like Amy and Courtney. A great many fall through the
cracks, according to statistics from the Hetrick-Martin Institute
and the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of gay, lesbian and bisexual teens say they feel
isolated _ from family, peers and information about their
sexuality; half are rejected by their parents; drug and alcohol use
are two to three times more prevalent among them; and their suicide
rates are nearly triple the national figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not saying we want all gay and lesbian kids down here,''
says Thompson. ``That was the first misunderstanding people had
about us. Most of the kids, especially the upperclassmen, who are
here now are saying, `It's either you or nothing. I'm not finishing
school.' ''
</P>
<P>
   OVERCOMING HURDLES
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and Stone met at Walden Preparatory School, an
alternative school in Addison where both were teachers and
administrators. In 1997, they decided to pursue a high school for
gay and lesbian teens and presented the idea to several gay youth
groups. Thompson, who is a lesbian, was not completely out at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Cathedral of Hope, a gay-friendly Metropolitan Community
Church, offered space in its children's center, and school
directors decided to charge $7,000 tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opened with seven kids who couldn't afford it,'' Thompson
says. The school managed to keep its doors open with a fund-raiser,
some budget finagling and the virtual elimination of teacher
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   This year, a development director and board have assumed
responsibility for finding donors. A financial aid committee
estimates how much of the $7,000 each Walt Whitman student will pay
and how much he or she must raise. The remainder is considered a
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson emphasizes that Walt Whitman's priority is to graduate
students and prepare them for the next step, be that college or a
job. (The school is not accredited; it must be open three years
first.)
</P>
<P>
   Students must complete a standard number of credits in math,
English, history, health and science. Each is required to perform
80 hours of community service work per semester with a local
nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers at Walt Whitman also want to give gay teens role
models, and allow them to talk openly about homosexuality in the
context of classes.
</P>
<P>
   Raines' literature lesson plans, for instance, include the
contemporary Tony Kushner play ``Angels in America,'' which focuses
on AIDS, and the documentary film ``The Celluloid Closet,'' about
homosexuality and Hollywood. He opened class by quoting gay
American poet Walt Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Spanish teacher John Lever asks his students to sign a
``Learning Agreement,'' which emphasizes respect for themselves and
others. The unspoken lesson is that you're smart, you're strong and
you're terrific just the way you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish this school didn't exist to some degree,'' Lever adds.
``I wish these kids could go to school with everybody else and be
treated the same way. But that's not a reality right now.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1911EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
