<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTBURSTS AND CHOLESTEROL LINKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not the anger, it's how you express it.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics and neurotics _ hostile types who feel angry but seldom
take it out on others _ are less at risk for high cholesterol than
their upfront-and-in-your-face counterparts, researchers report in
the current issue of ``Annals of Behavioral Medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Hostility has long been linked with cardiovascular disease, but
researchers at Duke University Medical Center recently studied
different types of hostility and found that people who express
their anger verbally and physically are much more likely to have
high cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Antagonistic hostility is a strong predictor of heart disease,
but neurotic hostility is not at all associated with cardiovascular
risks, researchers conclude. In other words, the expression of
anger matters much more than the anger itself.
</P>
<P>
   COPING WITH ADD
</P>
<P>
   Extensive online resources to help parents and teachers identify
attention deficit disorder are available this school year. The new
Web site www.mediconsult.com//add// also provides tools for coping
at home and at school, as well as an online support group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of kids are labeled by teachers, parents and school
administrators as difficult, troublesome and disruptive students,''
says Dr. Ned Hallowell, a Harvard University specialist in
identifying and treating ADD. ``In reality, most classrooms have at
least one student with ADD, and probably several. Providing the
proper diagnosis and treatment can make a world of difference for
these kids, their families, their peers and their teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web site includes 50 tips on managing ADD without medicine,
as well as the latest thinking on medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   BREATH HINT
</P>
<P>
   Lick your hand and take a sniff if you want to check the status
of your breath. Licking is much more reliable than blowing into
your hand because most bacteria in the mouth live on the tongue.
Dentists recommend brushing your tongue as well as your teeth to
protect against bad breath.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1912EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0349 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
