u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-FILMS-ART-1000     10-28 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-FILMS-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: of that.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That said, Israeli films have some enormous advantages as well.
They cover perhaps the most resonant and familiar turf on the globe
and subject matter having to do with borders, conflict, memory and
reconciliation: a world of blood feuds between people so close they
could be brothers, that is at once intensely local and blindingly
universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinema is a very strange medium,'' Gitai said. ``With one
powerful image, you can break through the barriers and stupidity
and oversimplifications that are all around you. So we're still
defining what the face of Israel will be at the beginning of the
century. There's a reality to life in the Middle East that's so
much more complex than the images you see on CNN. It's something we
shouldn't be afraid to look for, and it's why this is one of the
few places in the world where cinema still matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts, like Ms. Shohat, argue that if there is a failing
in Israeli films, it has been more of a constricted esthetic vision
than a political one. The current festival includes two offbeat
classics, ``Hor Balevana'' (``Hole in the Moon'') and ``Ha-Banana
Hashehora'' (``The Black Banana''), both of them wildly fanciful
re-creations of Israeli culture and mythology. But such films
remain rare. And Ms. Shohat says that genuinely opening up the
Israeli film culture means getting more resources to artists who
are not Ashkenazic men, those of Middle and Northern European
descent, a group that includes Gitai.
</P>
<P>
   Gitai, who said he found it odd to be cast suddenly as a poster
boy for Israeli films after years of feeling like a pariah, noted
that providing resources for an art form as expensive as film has
always been an issue in a land fighting for survival. But he said
the nature of Israeli society demanded finding a way to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say you live in a battle zone, which the Middle East
is,'' he said. ``You have to confront two questions. One is you
have to survive. Second, you have to ask yourself what you survive
for. And the second question is no less important than the first
one. The positive thing about Israel is that it's not a Spartan
society. Israelis need to justify for themselves the sense of their
collective existence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
