<SLUG> BC-CLINTON29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON URGES VOTERS TO FOCUS ON ISSUES
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton fired back Wednesday at a blitz
of election-season ads that target his character, casting his
Republican opponents as captives of big business and special
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with polls suggesting that low voter turnout could hurt
Democratic chances next Tuesday, Clinton used the presidential
lectern to make a plea to the nation's civic conscience.
</P>
<P>
   ''Folks should show up and vote,'' Clinton said at a joint White
House news conference with visiting President Andres Pastrana of
Colombia. ''And they should know that the decision not to vote is
also a decision that will affect their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made the remarks the day after Republicans launched a
$10 million television ad campaign focused on Clinton's character,
even as impeachment proceedings loom in the House based on the
president's relationship with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton assailed the ad campaign as an attempt to ''distract''
voters with scandal and ''divert'' their attention away from
bread-and-butter issues such as tobacco legislation, a increase in
the minimum wage and reforms of health insurance and campaign
finance _ all initiatives that Clinton fought but were defeated by
the Republican-led Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are basically saying to the American people ... 'We want
you to, in effect, ratify the decisions we made for the tobacco
companies, the health-insurance companies, the special interests
that didn't want campaign finance reform, all the people that gave
us the money to put this ad on the air,' '' Clinton said. ''It
wouldn't be a very persuasive argument to me if I were a citizen
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as he lambasted Republicans, Clinton asked the nation not
to judge him solely on his belated admission of an intimate
relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's fair for a person to be judged on his whole
record,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not trying to sugar-coat the fact that I made a mistake
and that I didn't want anybody to know about it. I'm doing my best
to atone for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said his job performance should be weighed as he works
to regain the confidence of the American people.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope they can sense the rededication and the intensified
efforts I am making for the cause of peace around the world, for
the cause of prosperity at home,'' he said. ''I'm doing my best to
be a good president.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared in the Rose Garden with Pastrana, who was here
for his first state visit since taking office last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders signed an Alliance Against Drugs accord committing
both nations to step up efforts to combat the illicit trade, and
Clinton said the pact would be backed up in large part by a $280
million U.S. aid package to the South American nation next year.
The money would be spent on a combination of economic development
and anti-crime measures.
</P>
<P>
   Newt week's voting, though, dominated the nationally televised
news conference. Clinton repeatedly tried to rebut GOP efforts to
turn the elections _ certain to bear heavily on the prospects of
looming impeachment proceedings _ into a referendum on his fitness
to serve.
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the 50-minute press conference, Clinton
responded directly to one Republican TV ad now airing in a handful
of closely contested districts. In the ad, two women portray young
mothers troubled over how to discuss the Lewinsky matter with their
children.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what people ought to say to their children is that
when someone
</P>
<P>
   makes a mistake, they should admit it and try to rectify it,''
Clinton said in response to a reporter's question about the ad.
''And this is an illustration of the fact that those rules should
apply to everyone, but that when people do that, if they do it
properly, they can be stronger in their personal lives, in their
family lives and in their work lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said voters concerned about his credibility should
ask whether he has delivered on his promises to help revitalize the
economy and improve educational and job opportunities for the
nation's poor.
</P>
<P>
   ''On whether I've been trustworthy, I think you can look at the
record,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''And the consequences are good,'' he added. ''We have an
economic boom, we
</P>
<P>
   have declining social problems, we are a force for peace in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
