<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2280 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KY-SENATE-ART-725&AMP;ADD     10-28 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KY-SENATE-ART-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KENTUCKY SENATE RACE, TURNOUT SEEN AS THE KEY TO VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moving in ``a'' news file.) 
(th) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAINTSVILLE, Ky. _ Here in the hills of eastern Kentucky, where
Loretta Lynn grew up as a coal miner's daughter, the politicians
are talking this fall about ``a turnout election.''
</P>
<P>
   You hear the same phrase in Louisville and Paducah, and in
Wisconsin, New York and North Carolina _ everywhere there is a
close race for state or federal office.
</P>
<P>
   It is the cliche of the year, like ``Year of the Woman'' in
1992. ``Tell me who's going to show up at the polls next Tuesday,''
said Rep. Jim Bunning, the Republican nominee in this state's
nasty, down-to-the-wire Senate contest, ``and I'll tell you who's
going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Predicting the turnout in midterm elections is never easy, but
the professionals find it harder than ever this time. The
impeachment proceedings against President Clinton provide the added
imponderable. Will Democrats stay home, or will they turn out to
register their anger against Kenneth Starr, the independent
counsel, and the Republicans in Congress?
</P>
<P>
   The importance of those questions was vividly illustrated in a
poll published in Wednesday's Louisville Courier-Journal. It showed
Bunning trailing his Democratic rival, Rep. Scotty Baesler, by 1
percentage point, 44 percent to 43 percent, a statistically
insignificant margin, among registered voters who said they were
likely to go to the polls, but leading him once the sample was
corrected to reflect turnout patterns of recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky's Senate race is one of the half-dozen or so close
contests across the country that will collectively determine
whether the Republicans have the 60 votes they will need in the
next two years to cut off debate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the House seats Bunning and Baesler are giving up
are among the most hotly disputed in the nation. Ken Lucas, a
Democrat, leads in the race for Bunning's seat, although Bunning's
name at the head of the ticket may help the Republican nominee, Gex
Williams, to pull through. Ernest Fletcher, a Republican, is
favored in the contest for Baesler's seat, but turnout is a major
question in that race, too.
</P>
<P>
   At a get-out-the-vote rally Tuesday night in Louisville's old
Union Station, Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., accused the Republicans
of plotting to keep people at home on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're running a negative campaign,'' Biden said, ``because
the more negative, the more visceral the campaign, the more people
turn off, especially women. If only the most motivated voters show
up, the Republicans win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans, of course, deny any attempt to suppress
turnout. Indeed, they blame Baesler for slinging the first mud in a
campaign that has more than lived up to this state's long tradition
of political brawling. But when Bunning's campaign coordinator,
Kyle Simmons, heard the results of the Courier poll, he reacted by
commenting, ``hope it rains.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a Democratic House candidate in the Louisville area has
begun running advertisements criticizing Republicans for
authorizing an open-ended investigation of Clinton, neither of the
Senate candidates has tackled the impeachment issue on television.
One top strategist said it was ``too hot, too volatile and too
unpredictable to touch with a 50-foot pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron McCloud, the state Democratic chairman, said he thought
``the way the Republicans in Washington beat up on Clinton has
energized some of my people, got them stirred up to work and vote,
which is often a problem for us.'' Overwhelmingly Democratic in
registration, Kentucky regularly elects Republicans to top offices
because Democrats break ranks or stay home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's turnout, it's turnout, it's turnout,'' McCloud said. ``I
hope we've learned from 1994. If a few more Democrats in key places
had voted, we might have had Dick Gephardt instead of Newt Gingrich
as speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Mellman, a pollster for Baesler and other Democrats, said
he expected a continuation of the steady decline in turnout across
the country this year, ``with more than likely an equal decline for
both parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Gans, who heads a committee that studies voter
participation, said he expected fewer than four registered voters
in 10 to cast ballots, a new low.
</P>
<P>
   Why? One big reason, Mellman said, is that ``this is not an
issue election, not a referendum on Clinton or the economy or
anything else.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As befits a border state, Kentucky developed a two-party system
earlier than states in the Deep South like Georgia and Mississippi.
John Sherman Cooper and Thruston B. Morton held Senate seats here
as early as the 1950s, taking their places alongside Democratic
icons like A.B. ``Happy'' Chandler and Alben W. Barkley, who was
Harry S. Truman's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But even in the one-party days, the state had a reputation for
particularly quarrelsome politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning and Baesler are both fiercely competitive people, with
backgrounds in sports. Bunning, still lean and fit at 67, spent 17
seasons as a right-handed fireballer in the big leagues. He wears a
Hall of Fame ring on his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Baesler was captain in 1962 and 1963 of one of Adolph Rupp's
legendary University of Kentucky basketball teams. Given
basketball's status in this state as a kind of secular religion, he
is even better known than his rival.
</P>
<P>
   Their personalities could hardly be more different. Baesler is
soft-spoken and seemingly reluctant to work a crowd. Bunning is an
in-your-face sort of campaigner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get along well enough,'' Baesler said in an interview. ``We
see each other on the Hill almost every day and we don't growl at
each other. But he's always been a little strident. In his playing
days, I guess, you knock the other guy down with a baseball if you
didn't like him. In basketball, you can't do that; you have to find
a way to work around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the campaign, Bunning ran a commercial showing Baesler
making an uncharacteristically vehement speech, accompanied by
Wagner's ``Ride of the Valkyries.'' The Democrats denounced the
spot as an attempt to suggest subliminally that their man was a
Nazi, and newspapers and civic leaders joined them in issuing
statements of condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bugs Bunny and Elmer Fudd used that music, and people think
it's funny,'' Bunning replied.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning ran a commercial with actors ``thanking'' Baesler in
comically accented English for having voted for the North American
Free Trade Agreement and preferential trade status for China.
Baesler said it was a ``despicable'' effort to stir prejudice and
xenophobic feelings in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   A hand bill circulated by Bunning attempts to suggest that
Baesler is insufficiently firm in his support of tobacco because he
``accepts campaign help from America's No. 1 Tobacco-Basher'' _
Clinton. Baesler, himself a tobacco farmer, has long championed his
fellow growers.
</P>
<P>
   The two men have spent weeks accusing each other of lying on
subjects like Social Security, health care and education, often
seizing upon narrow differences and magnifying them. Baesler for
example wanted to save 100 percent of the federal surplus for
Social Security, while Bunning settled for saving only 90 percent.
The 10 percent difference is a big issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning has played down issues he has used in the past such as
abortion and flag-burning, leaving the Democrats to accuse him of
stealing their issues. But his slide toward the center has been
uneven.
</P>
<P>
   While he was portraying himself this week as the defender of
Social Security and Medicare, his campaign brought Oliver North, a
symbol of the far right, to Paintsville to campaign for him amid
the Technicolor hillsides of autumn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0362 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ILL-GOV-RACE-800&AMP;ADD-     10-28 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILL-GOV-RACE-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR'S RACE DRAWS LITTLE INTEREST IN CHICAGO, BOOSTING
REPUBLICAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moving in the ``p'' news file.) 
(nk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ In the vast megalopolis known here as Chicagoland,
which stretches 50 miles from the high-rises along Lake Michigan to
suburban cul-de-sacs, it has often been difficult to get voters
interested in the political action in the Illinois Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The capital, Springfield, in the view of many Chicagoans and
suburbanites, is a place to visit Lincoln's tomb or to milk cows at
the state fair.
</P>
<P>
   The lopsided race for governor this year has done little to
change that. George Ryan, Illinois' secretary of state and the
Republican nominee, and Rep. Glenn Poshard, the Democrat _ men who
have never been accused of skating on charisma _ have not managed
to fan the political passions.
</P>
<P>
   Lethargy bodes well for Ryan, whose Republican Party has held
the governor's office for 22 years. Most surveys of likely voters
give Ryan a double-digit lead, except for an anomalous poll
published by The Chicago Sun-Times last week that showed the race
nearly a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Poshard, socially conservative and from Southern Illinois, has
often been at odds with liberals in his party. But his problems, at
least among residents of Northern Illinois, run much deeper than
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people had never heard of him,'' said Peter Nardulli,
head of the political science department at the University of
Illinois in Champaign. ``Even now, he has very little visibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, 64, a former pharmacist from Kankakee, an old railroad
town about 45 miles south of Chicago, could walk down most Illinois
streets without being widely recognized.
</P>
<P>
   But his name is known everywhere. One of the perquisites of the
secretary of state's office, it seems, is the right to have your
signature on everything from driver's licenses to mailings on organ
donation.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan has also used his office to call for stricter laws on
drunken driving. He takes much of the credit for the state's
reducing the maximum blood-alcohol content for drivers to 0.08
percent, from 0.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists have said they expect the race to
tighten. But John Torre, a spokesman for Ryan, said the voter
surveys ``reflect the contentment and satisfaction that people in
Illinois have with Republican leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials note that polls did not predict Poshard's
victory in the primary. ``The polls don't capture the talk in the
fields, the coffee shops and around kitchen tables,'' said Dave
Stricklin, a spokesman for Poshard.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's job has long been regarded here as political
second banana to that of the mayor of Chicago, where City Hall
looms as the real locus of power. (Roman Pucinski left Congress in
the 70s to run for alderman in Chicago.)
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the city has lost plenty of its influence to the
suburbs, which now cast 40 percent of the state's vote. And Ryan
has been able to portray himself as the sort of moderate who plays
well in the suburbs, running television advertisements that
emphasize his support for gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who have been out of the governor's office since
1976, had high hopes coming into this political season. They saw
Ryan, who won the Republican primary without serious opposition, as
a much weaker opponent than Gov. Jim Edgar, a popular moderate who
is retiring from politics, partly for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was seen as vulnerable for his opposition to abortion, as
well as his crucial role as speaker of the Illinois House in 1976
in defeating the Equal Rights Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   But when Democrats nominated Poshard, who has a more
conservative record on social issues than Ryan, the Republican was
able to cast himself as the more enlightened candidate. Ryan, for
example, sent representatives of his campaign to appear at the gay
pride parade in Chicago, while Poshard skipped the event.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of Poshard, who has said he will not accept money
from political action committees, has appeared star-crossed at
every turn. Even a scandal tied to Ryan's state office, involving
workers accused of taking bribes to sell commercial truck-driver
licenses, has failed to help him.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Scott Lassar has said that workers in a driver
license office took $150,000 in bribes to give trucker licenses.
Federal agents also say that some of that money ended up in a
campaign fund for Ryan. The prosecutor has said that Ryan is not a
target of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A television advertisement run by Democrats links the scandal to
an accident involving a van and a truck that killed six children in
1994. But the commercial has provoked widespread criticism as being
unfair, including harsh words from some prominent Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Poshard, a former teacher, also has changed some of his
positions during the campaign, now supporting some gun-control
measures, and justifying his earlier positions as a reflection of
the views in Southern Illinois.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even among blacks, the most loyal part of the traditional
Democratic constituency, the view of Poshard has often been
lukewarm. Some hard feelings might remain among blacks who
supported Roland Burris, a former state attorney general, who is
black, in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   In that race, many black political leaders said Burris, who had
won statewide office by large margins, would probably have faced
little opposition in the primary if he were white. Nardulli, the
University of Illinois professor, said Burris might have given the
Democrats a better chance, since he could have been expected to
rally the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's big lead in the polls, together with the apparent lead of
the Republican candidate for the Senate, Peter Fitzgerald, over
Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, has caused Democrats to worry that
trouble may be in store for Democrats running for the state
Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1936EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0363 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ILL-GOV-RACE-800&AMP;ADD-     10-28 1008
