published by The Chicago Sun-Times last week that showed the race
nearly a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Poshard, socially conservative and from Southern Illinois, has
often been at odds with liberals in his party. But his problems, at
least among residents of Northern Illinois, run much deeper than
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people had never heard of him,'' said Peter Nardulli,
head of the political science department at the University of
Illinois in Champaign. ``Even now, he has very little visibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, 64, a former pharmacist from Kankakee, an old railroad
town about 45 miles south of Chicago, could walk down most Illinois
streets without being widely recognized.
</P>
<P>
   But his name is known everywhere. One of the perquisites of the
secretary of state's office, it seems, is the right to have your
signature on everything from driver's licenses to mailings on organ
donation.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan has also used his office to call for stricter laws on
drunken driving. He takes much of the credit for the state's
reducing the maximum blood-alcohol content for drivers to 0.08
percent, from 0.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists have said they expect the race to
tighten. But John Torre, a spokesman for Ryan, said the voter
surveys ``reflect the contentment and satisfaction that people in
Illinois have with Republican leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials note that polls did not predict Poshard's
victory in the primary. ``The polls don't capture the talk in the
fields, the coffee shops and around kitchen tables,'' said Dave
Stricklin, a spokesman for Poshard.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's job has long been regarded here as political
second banana to that of the mayor of Chicago, where City Hall
looms as the real locus of power. (Roman Pucinski left Congress in
the 70s to run for alderman in Chicago.)
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the city has lost plenty of its influence to the
suburbs, which now cast 40 percent of the state's vote. And Ryan
has been able to portray himself as the sort of moderate who plays
well in the suburbs, running television advertisements that
emphasize his support for gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, who have been out of the governor's office since
1976, had high hopes coming into this political season. They saw
Ryan, who won the Republican primary without serious opposition, as
a much weaker opponent than Gov. Jim Edgar, a popular moderate who
is retiring from politics, partly for health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan was seen as vulnerable for his opposition to abortion, as
well as his crucial role as speaker of the Illinois House in 1976
in defeating the Equal Rights Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   But when Democrats nominated Poshard, who has a more
conservative record on social issues than Ryan, the Republican was
able to cast himself as the more enlightened candidate. Ryan, for
example, sent representatives of his campaign to appear at the gay
pride parade in Chicago, while Poshard skipped the event.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign of Poshard, who has said he will not accept money
from political action committees, has appeared star-crossed at
every turn. Even a scandal tied to Ryan's state office, involving
workers accused of taking bribes to sell commercial truck-driver
licenses, has failed to help him.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Scott Lassar has said that workers in a driver
license office took $150,000 in bribes to give trucker licenses.
Federal agents also say that some of that money ended up in a
campaign fund for Ryan. The prosecutor has said that Ryan is not a
target of the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   A television advertisement run by Democrats links the scandal to
an accident involving a van and a truck that killed six children in
1994. But the commercial has provoked widespread criticism as being
unfair, including harsh words from some prominent Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Poshard, a former teacher, also has changed some of his
positions during the campaign, now supporting some gun-control
measures, and justifying his earlier positions as a reflection of
the views in Southern Illinois.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even among blacks, the most loyal part of the traditional
Democratic constituency, the view of Poshard has often been
lukewarm. Some hard feelings might remain among blacks who
supported Roland Burris, a former state attorney general, who is
black, in the Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   In that race, many black political leaders said Burris, who had
won statewide office by large margins, would probably have faced
little opposition in the primary if he were white. Nardulli, the
University of Illinois professor, said Burris might have given the
Democrats a better chance, since he could have been expected to
rally the black vote.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan's big lead in the polls, together with the apparent lead of
the Republican candidate for the Senate, Peter Fitzgerald, over
Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, has caused Democrats to worry that
trouble may be in store for Democrats running for the state
Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
