<SLUG> BC-ATTIC-TREASURES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUMS HELP SEPARATE FAMILY TRASH AND TREASURES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It could be a Qing Dynasty jade Buddha, worth thousands of
dollars. Or it might be a soapstone replica worth little more than
the memories it evokes.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Casler can't tell from the photograph, although the
accompanying letter contains more information than usual about the
object in question: A woman's uncle found it on a bombed-out street
in China during World War II. It was one of several lying amidst
the rubble. He brought it back to the United States in a diplomatic
pouch.
</P>
<P>
   Casler, the Kimbell Art Museum's curator of Asian and
non-Western art hears countless, similar stories and often doesn't
even have a murky photograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``More often than not, when it's Asian material, it's something
a father or grandfather brought back from Japan or China or
Thailand after World War II,'' she says. ``Or maybe it's from a
missionary in the family, who was in Asia during the early part of
the century, and it has been around the house for three
generations.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer wants to know, is it white jade? Does she have a
legal right to it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' Casler continues, ``someone realizes there's an
Asian curator at the Kimbell who might be willing to look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's only one curator at one museum in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Long before the popular PBS series ``Antiques Road Show'' urged
viewers to cast appraising eyes on their possessions, museums were
helping people learn about the stuff they lived with or picked up
at garage sales.
</P>
<P>
   They still do.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to learn more about the historic and aesthetic
importance of an object or work of art, ``the museum should be one
of the first places you turn,'' says Jane Myers, chief curator of
the Amon Carter Museum and an authority on American prints.
``Museum exhibitions help train the eye and sharpen anyone's
connoisseurship skills. They're a resource. The people are a
resource. The library is a resource, and so is all of the material
we have in the bookstore.''
</P>
<P>
   People phone, FAX and e-mail queries to Carter staff members
daily, Myers says. And, although people sometimes simply walk in
the door, Myers says she and her colleagues would rather first
receive a letter and picture of the item in question.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, you want to learn about how much an object is
worth, don't go to a curator; turn to an appraiser, dealer or
auction house specialist.
</P>
<P>
   What generates real flurries of queries are the special
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Dallas Museum of Art's exhaustive 1994
exhibition on American silver brought ``an avalanche'' of people
calling and asking about grandma's Gorham candlesticks and Towle
bowls, says DMA Acting Director Charles Venable, who also is the
museum's curator of decorative arts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A few pieces entered the collection,'' he adds, not
surprisingly noting that the museum's favorite way of acquiring
works is in the form of a gift. Still, once a work's dollar value
is ascertained, combination gift-purchases or outright purchases
can be negotiated. All, of course, assuming that the curator is
sufficiently interested in the work to get it approved by an
acquisitions committee.
</P>
<P>
   Another DMA show _ its current presentation of ``The Jewels of
Lalique'' _ has stirred up inquiries. Most of its focus is on
unique jewelry, something that few people would have lying around.
But it also features several examples of glass vases, bowls,
perfume bottles and other decorative or functional objects that are
much more common.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Venable says, his decorative arts department fields
the greatest number of questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more liable to call about a class of object, like
silver or glass, because they don't know what they have,'' Venable
says. ``But if someone has, say, a Brice Marden painting, they're
going to know they've got a Brice Marden painting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kimbell's recent display of early modern furnishings brought
in more calls than any other show she knows of, says Patricia Loud,
who was in-house curator for that exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had everything from a doctor's wife who had an Arts and
Crafts basin and ewer similar to one in the show, to a little,
round object someone brought in that was obviously of the Arts and
Crafts period,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Loud told the doctor's wife to contact Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the other piece was of copper and brass, and
featured other characteristics of Arts and Crafts, neither Loud nor
its owner could figure out what it might be.
</P>
<P>
   Myers mentions a couple who approached her in the galleries
during the Carter's ``Inner Spirit'' exhibition of early modern
paintings, prints and sculpture a couple years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pointed to a beautiful color woodcut by B.J.O. Nordfeldt
and said, `You know, we own a print like this. Is it worth
anything?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It had been rolled up in a Japanese scroll they bought at a
garage sale,'' Myers says. ``They thought more highly of the scroll
and were amazed to see this other thing, which they hardly valued
at all, in a museum.''
</P>
<P>
   Queries about personal belongings have brought at least two
important folk-art works to the Carter's collection _ one due to a
lecture, the other to an exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The former piece is a portrait, dated circa 1853, by an
itinerant painter named Jacob Maentel. It had been in the sitter's
family for almost 150 years. When its present owner heard Carter
Director Rick Stewart lecture on Maentel she decided, having no
heirs, to give it to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Curators at the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth regularly field
questions about early modern artworks, including pictures by Fort
Worth School artists. Museum policy doesn't permit them to look at
things, though, so they immediately refer callers to appraisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would be thrilled to hear they have a Picasso,'' says
Modern curatorial assistant Christine Berry, adding that the
possibility of a windfall seems to motivate most of their callers.
</P>
<P>
   Loud, at the Kimbell, sees things somewhat differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a bit of the hidden treasure impulse at
work,'' she says. ``But it's not solely that. For a lot of people,
it just reinforces the sense of value they attach to things at home
_ not just sentimental or monetary, but also artistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very powerful thing for people to open their eyes and
realize that something they own has aesthetic value.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
