<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL a prisoner in Internet browser wars
 &HT;    EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By Andrew J. Glass
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``How much do we need to pay you to screw
Netscape?'' Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates asked key executives of
America OnLine, which has grown into the nation's largest doorway
into the Internet. ``This is your lucky day.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Microsoft paid AOL nothing in January 1996,
when the question was raised. But it gave AOL a highly valued icon
on its Windows 95 desktop and got in return a bargain that vaulted
its then largely untested Internet Explorer into a primary slot for
AOL customers, at the expense of Netscape, which had also sought to
make a deal with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made us an offer we couldn't refuse,'' George Vradenburg,
AOL's general counsel, said on Wednesday. He spoke to a reporter on
the steps of the federal courthouse here, where Microsoft is on
trial, charged by the Justice Department and the attorney generals
of 20 states with having broken the antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' query to AOL, as quoted in court documents, reflects the
bitter battles in the high technology arena which have led the
government to file its most significant antitrust case in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Within the courtroom itself, the browser wars between Microsoft
and Netscape were vented all day long through sheaf upon sheaf of
hitherto secret documents, unearthed for the landmark trial.
</P>
<P>
   And AOL was being cast in the testimony as the swing vote _
first having thrown in with Netscape and then in March 1996
switching its allegiance to Microsoft as it sought to leverage
itself against a threat from the software giant's then-new online
service.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Microsoft lawyers put into the trial record a
draft e-mail written in October 1995 by AOL chief executive Stephen
Case that quoted approvingly from Netscape co-founder Marc
Andreesen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with ju `` the witness, AOL senior vice president
David Colburn, replied evenly. Colburn had been charged with
handling the competitive negotiations with Microsoft and Netscape
that eventually led to Microsoft's victory.
</P>
<P>
   Under fire from Warden, Colburn repeatedly backed the
government's charge that Microsoft won the important 1996 deal as a
result of its Windows monopoly and not, as Warden sought to show,
by virtue of Microsoft's superior browser technology.
</P>
<P>
   Warden also accused AOL of doing precisely what the government
has accused Microsoft of doing: seeking to divide markets. As he
laced into Colburn, the Microsoft attorney put into the record the
terms of a draft agreement calling for AOL and Netscape not to
compete against each other in their respective main lines of
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think there ought to be two sets of rules,''
Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray said into microphones arrayed on
the courthouse steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The antitrust rules make a big distinction between what a
monopolist may do and what a non-monopolist may do,'' David Boies,
the government's lead trustbuster said in the same forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``They only had a tiny fraction of the business each was willing
to stay away from,'' Boies added. ``What Microsoft wanted Netscape
to do was quite a different matter. (Microsoft) would then have had
a browser monopoly on top of its Windows monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
