<HEADER>
A2288 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-9     10-28 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-COALITION-965&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASTORS SAYING NO TO CHRISTIAN COALITION'S VOTER GUIDES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the conservative Christian Coalition prepares to distribute
45 million voter guides in churches this Sunday _ its most
ambitious election-year effort ever _ it is hitting more resistance
than ever before from liberal advocacy groups and even from
conservative and moderate ministers who believe the guides are
biased in favor of Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition maintains that its voter guides are nonpartisan,
educational materials that compare the voting records of
candidates, usually on issues central to the beliefs of
conservative Christians, like abortion, homosexuality and vouchers
for religious schools.
</P>
<P>
   Distributing 45 million voter guides means that the Christian
Coalition would have to put a guide in the hands of nearly one of
every three Americans registered to vote. To reach its goal, the
coalition depends on the cooperation of church pastors, the
gatekeepers to the pews.
</P>
<P>
   But even ministers aligned with the coalition on the issues said
in interviews that they were refusing to distribute its voter
guides this year. Many ministers said the coalition and its guides
were tainted by a perceived affiliation with the Republican Party.
Some said they did not want to appear partisan before their large
and diverse congregations, while others said they did not want to
risk jeopardizing their churches' tax-exempt status by handing out
partisan campaign materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly have nothing against the Christian Coalition,''
said the Rev. Rusty Russell, associate minister of Southeast
Christian Church, a conservative nondenominational ``megachurch''
with 14,000 members in Louisville, Ky. But a committee at his
church decided not to use the coalition's voter guides because,
Russell said, ``We felt like we wanted to stick with something
intended to be a little more unbiased.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it will distribute a candidate survey put out by the
Family Foundation, a statewide group affiliated with Focus on the
Family, a ministry led by James Dobson, the religious broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   In September, at the coalition's convention in Washington,
several coalition volunteers and church liaisons said in interviews
that they had had a difficult time persuading pastors to accept the
guides. Nelida Kuhlman, a volunteer in New Jersey, said none of the
Roman Catholic priests and only half of the Protestant ministers
she contacted in Hackensack and Bergenfield agreed to accept them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really afraid of losing their tax exemption,'' Ms.
Kuhlman said. ``A lot of them don't want to become controversial.
The Christian Coalition also has a connotation of being a political
lobbying group in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   No church has ever lost its tax-exempt status for distributing
coalition voter guides. The coalition itself, however, has been
sued by the Federal Election Commission. The lawsuit contends that
in previous elections the coalition coordinated the use of its
voter guides, telephone banks and mass mailings to promote
Republican candidates, including former President George Bush,
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina and
Oliver North in 1994, when he ran unsuccessfully for a U.S. Senate
seat in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed in 1996 and still pending, contends that even if
the voter guides do not explicitly favor one candidate, they still
violate the law if they are part of a coordinated effort to
mobilize specific voters in a contested district.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that the lawsuit has made the Christian Coalition
vulnerable to accusations of partisanship, two advocacy groups
opposed to the coalition have recently sent ``Dear Pastor'' letters
to tens of thousands of ministers across the country, warning them
away from the coalition's voter guides.
</P>
<P>
   The Interfaith Alliance, a network of Christian, Jewish and
Muslim clergy, most of whom are liberal but some moderate and
conservative, has sent 20,000 letters to fellow clergy members in
25 states, accusing the Christian Coalition of ``seeking to
transform houses of worship into precinct halls for espousing
partisan politics.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Barry W. Lynn, executive director of Americans
United for Separation of Church and State, has written letters to
80,000 pastors alerting them to a memorandum written by two
Washington tax lawyers warning churches against distributing
slanted voters' guides.
</P>
<P>
   The tax lawyers point to several aspects of the Christian
Coalition's guides that potentially violate Federal Election
Commission regulations: They list the candidates' stands on only a
few, select issues of concern to coalition members (in contrast to
the extensive guides issued by the League of Women Voters, for
example); they distort the candidates' voting records, saying, for
example, that the Democrat supports ``special rights for
homosexuals''; and they distribute most of the guides the Sunday
before the election, giving candidates no time to respond to
inaccuracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never seen a guide in all of these years that is
slanted in such a way as to suggest you vote for a Democrat,'' Lynn
said in an interview. ``They are blatantly partisan appendages of
Republican campaign material.''
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Coalition has responded by directing its field
directors and local chapter leaders to give pastors a letter from
Randy Tate, executive director of the coalition, calling Lynn ``the
ACLU's hand-picked mouthpiece'' and telling pastors not to be
``scared off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, there is no risk, because Christian Coalition takes
great care to see that its voter guides are absolutely correct in
accordance with the law,'' Tate wrote to the pastors.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Jay Sekulow, head of the American Center for Law
and Justice, a Virginia-based organization founded by evangelist
Pat Robertson, had offered ``to defend without charge any church
that is sued or threatened because of distributing Christian
Coalition voter guides.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of course, many pastors, especially those in conservative
evangelical, Pentecostal and Southern Baptist churches, say they
are glad to distribute the guides. The coalition says its network
is especially strong in Maine, where 900 churches will take the
guides, and in Dade County, Fla., where 800 churches have accepted
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James Merritt, pastor of First Baptist Church in
Snellville, Ga., said his church inserted the coalition's voter
guides in its bulletins and would make them available at Sunday
services. ``There are a lot of folks out there that don't read,
don't keep up, and they really rely on those guides,'' Merritt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, distributing 45 million of anything is an
extremely ambitious goal. In previous election years, when, the
coalition said, it distributed half that number of voter guides,
pastors hostile to the coalition reported receiving boxes with
hundreds of voter guides dropped on their church doorsteps the
Sunday before the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' Tate, the coalition's executive director, said
in an interview in September. ``In some instances they didn't get
into the right hands. In many instances they didn't get
distributed.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Tate said, the coalition is working to establish 100,000
church liaisons who can calm the fears of the increasing number of
pastors who express concern about involvement with the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have misconceptions,'' Tate said of the pastors. ``The
most common is that somehow it's a violation of church and state to
distribute a voter guide, and that anything that talks about
candidates is illegal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
