<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2299 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1000&AMP;     10-28 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-POLITICS-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S LABOR PARTY HAS AN IDENTITY CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also ISRAEL-LIKUD, ISRAEL-ARAFAT) 
(mk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As the conservative Likud government takes up the
mantle of peace, Labor, Israel's historically dovish party, finds
itself with a conundrum.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-year-old coalition government of Benjamin Netanyahu, the
Likud prime minister who has long been Labor's political enemy, is
wobbly. But to topple it now might threaten the peace effort that
Labor politicians hold so dear _ and even then to risk failure at
recapturing the reins of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a daily dilemma,'' said Yossi Beilin, a Labor member of
Parliament. ``How far are we going to go to support this government
because we don't want it to be toppled against the background of
the Washington agreement? We can't give him a blank check.''
</P>
<P>
   The predicament was crystallized Wednesday morning when
Netanyahu sent a draft of the national budget to Parliament. Labor
strongly opposes the budget, but the vote was turning into a
referendum on the peace agreement negotiated at Wye Plantation in
Maryland and signed last week at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The right wanted to attach a vote of no confidence in the
government to the budget. Netanyahu, in return, wanted a confidence
vote. Labor had promised the prime minister to protect him, but it
was unwilling to go so far as to endorse him or his budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the ultimate trickery and abuse of the good intentions
in our gentlemen's agreement with the prime minister,'' said Ehud
Barak, the Labor Party's leader.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Netanyahu backed down, postponing the budget's
presentation, but the episode made clear to many members of Labor
just how awkward their current role is.
</P>
<P>
   When Netanyahu took a step toward the center by signing the Wye
agreement, he knocked Labor, which has been split by internal
fighting, off its feet. Suddenly the distinctions between the two
major parties _ Labor, the peaceniks, and Likud, the defenders of
Greater Israel _ had blurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Labor has won historically, but what does it mean for
their own future?'' said David Makovsky, diplomatic correspondent
for the newspaper Haaretz. ``Are they rebels without a cause?''
</P>
<P>
   As the only party that could defeat Likud in a national
election, Labor theoretically stands to gain by joining the right's
call for a new vote. But the shakiness of Netanyahu's current
government is no guarantee that he could not maintain power in new
elections by cutting into Labor's centrist constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Also, holding a typically volatile Israeli election campaign
during the 12-week fulfillment period of the fragile peace accord
could create an unstable dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   Even if actual campaigning were delayed, the knowledge that new
elections were on the horizon _ mid-March is the proposed date _
could create a contentious backdrop for the withdrawal of Israeli
troops from an additional 13 percent of the West Bank. And
Netanyahu has threatened to freeze the fulfillment of the agreement
if Labor does force Parliament to dissolve and call new elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an absolutely complicated situation that gives us all a
big headache,'' said Avraham Shochat, a member of Parliament and
influential strategist for Labor.
</P>
<P>
   Labor's identity crisis comes at a critical time for the party,
which held power for most of the 50 years since the state of Israel
was founded. Netanyahu is the third prime minister of Likud, which
was created as a rightist opposition party specifically to stand
against the idea of territorial compromise, the turning over of
land to the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   First, the institutions that sustained Labor, most critically
the labor federation Histadrut and the kibbutzim, are losing their
influence.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Labor has had difficulty reaching down from its elite,
Ashkenazic constituency into the working-class and Orthodox
communities that have been tapped by Likud and by Shas, the growing
third party with a Sephardic, ultra-Orthodox base.
</P>
<P>
   In an embarrassing moment for Labor, its distance from the new
grass-roots Israelis was pointed up this summer when a top party
official, Ori Orr, made disparaging remarks about Moroccan Jews,
questioning their intelligence and terming them a ``problematic
ethnic group.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there have been public tensions between Ehud Barak, the
party leader, and Shimon Peres, the former prime minister who has
been seen to be undercutting him. After one incident, Barak
referred to Peres as ``a saboteur and subversive.''
</P>
<P>
   And epitomizing the party's problems, in the coming municipal
elections, Labor has failed to field a strong candidate to
recapture the mayoralty of Jerusalem from Ehud Olmert, a right-wing
Likudnik, at a time when the future of Jerusalem will move front
and center in the next phase of peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oy, is the Labor Party in trouble,'' Hirsh Goodman, a
columnist, wrote this week in the newsmagazine Jerusalem Report.
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Party is not of one mind, and its present dilemma
highlights that. Some politicians believe that they need Netanyahu
to have access to power and Netanyahu needs them during the final
peace talks that lie ahead. But others do not want to collaborate
at any price with a leader toward whom they feel deep personal
animosity.
</P>
<P>
   Peres has favored a national unity government almost since he
lost the last election to Netanyahu in 1996, because he wants Labor
to have a seat at the negotiating table during the critical and
thorny final talks with the Palestinians. Many say that Peres, who
declined to be interviewed, personally wants that seat.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, on the other hand, rebuffed an offer to join a unity
government that Netanyahu extended this week, Aryeh Deri, the Shas
leader, said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Chaim Ramon, the Labor Party's deputy leader,
caused a stir Wednesday by announcing that he thought Labor should
accept the offer.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Ramon made his comments, three other Labor
members of Parliament called a press conference to denounce the
suggestion, saying it would co-opt the party entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't trust Netanyahu,'' Beilin said. ``It would be very
artificial to enter government and serve as ministers under him.
From the outside we can exert pressure if he tries to do something
like expropriate Palestinian land. But once we're inside, we've
lost the lever.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Last week, Netanyahu called his coalition chairman, Meir
Shitrit, from the negotiating table in Maryland and asked him to
negotiate with the Labor Party for a two-week safety net for his
government. Beyond that, Labor has promised not to touch him during
the three-month fulfillment period, provided that he makes no
aggressive moves counter to the spirit of the accord _ like
expanding settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But Labor members said they would be sitting on their hands with
difficulty, especially when the prime minister spews hostile
rhetoric at them, as he did Wednesday night in a fiery meeting of
Likud's central committee in Tel Aviv, when he railed against
Barak. That, they said, is why they are moving forward to dissolve
Parliament, despite Netanyahu's threat to freeze the agreement with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't mortgage all our political philosophy to this one
issue,'' said Shlomo Ben Ami, a Labor member of Parliament. ``If he
freezes the process, he will cause himself more harm than us. He
will never win back the extreme right, and he will not gain the
support of the center he is courting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1949EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
