<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2301 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-GA-SCHOOLSAFETY     10-28 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-GA-SCHOOLSAFETY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hearing to focus on discipline at schools
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A hearing on student discipline at 7 p.m. at the State
Capitol will wrap up a series of five statewide hearings by a
Senate panel that has found that parents often have a different
perspective on discipline in schools than do teachers and
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents have told the state Senate study committee in
earlier hearings that schools have deliberately shut them out of
efforts by the school to address their children's behavior
problems, according to Suzanne Dion, the Georgia PTA's legislative
chairwoman, who attended the packed hearings in Macon, Ga., and
Athens, Ga., in the past four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When parents come to a school to talk about a discipline
problem, the school makes them feel ``there's no room for
discussion,'' Dion said, summarizing the testimony of many parents.
While some parents and advocacy groups have argued for stronger
due-process protection of accused students and disproportional
administration of punishment against black students, many parents
were more interested in added alternatives for when their children
misbehave and more early notification before suspension or
expulsion becomes necessary.
</P>
<P>
   This is only one of many viewpoints that have been expressed as
various panels, in Georgia and nationally, study the related issues
of school safety and student discipline. A White House summit on
school safety Oct. 15 was linked by satellite to a hearing at North
Atlanta High; two state representatives are also holding hearings
on the issue; the state Board of Education is studying the uneven
state funding of alternative schools and a Department of Education
school safety panel is working on implementing a school-safety
survey that was among its recommendations last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who complained about feeling shut off by the schools
contradicts a common refrain from educators and even some parents
who blame the parents of disruptive students for not being
involved, Dion said. ``The majority of schools do not know what
parent involvement means,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Vincent Fort (D-Atlanta), chairman of the study committee,
said that ``from the testimony we have heard, there seems to be a
genuine concern that there is a need for more teacher training and
focus on class management.'' Additionally, he said, ``And our
minority students are disparately impacted when it comes to
excessive disciplinary actions.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing is 7-9 p.m. in Room 450 of the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1951EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0373 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2303 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-SCHOOLSAFETY-COX     10-28 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SCHOOLSAFETY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hearing to focus on discipline at schools
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A hearing on student discipline at 7 p.m. at the State
