<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENNBAR29-COX     10-28 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENNBAR29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Countdown for Glenn mission `up there with the best of them'
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEDY SPACE CENTER, Fla. _ After a 36-year hiatus, space
pioneer John Glenn on Thursday was set to return to orbit as the
countdown clicked flawlessly toward today's space shuttle launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our countdown is progressing smoothly. This is a pretty good
countdown. It's right up there with the best of them,'' NASA test
director Steve Altemus said.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Mitch no longer posed a threat to the launch, weather
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a zero percent chance of weather prohibiting
launch,'' said Capt. Clif Stargardt, a meteorologist with the Air
Force's 45th weather squadron, which supports space shuttle
launches.
</P>
<P>
   Stargardt said this is a refreshing difference from Glenn's 1962
Mercury flight, when weather caused four of the 10 delays in his
launch. He finally lifted off on Feb. 20 for a four hour, 55-minute
flight that made him the first American to orbit the earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like Mother Nature wants to see John Glenn return to
space just as much as the rest of us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If all continues to go well, space shuttle Discovery will blast
off at 2 p.m. today with nearly 7 million pounds of thrust, sending
the 77-year-old Glenn on an eight day, 22-hour orbital mission that
has drawn worldwide attention. The shuttle is scheduled to land
back here at 11:50 a.m. Saturday, Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   At Pad 34-B, the massive Rotating Service Structure was swung
away from the shuttle at sunset, revealing the white, winged
orbiter Discovery for the first time since it was put on the launch
pad for this mission.
</P>
<P>
   Its seven crew members gathered later in the evening at the foot
of the towering, 184-foot-tall rocket to see their families for the
last time before launch. There were no hugs and kisses. Restricted
by their traditional pre-launch quarantine, astronauts and family
members could only stand apart from each other and wave, Altemus
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling of the shuttle's rust-colored external tank was to begin
at 5:40 a.m. today. Once the liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen
propellants are loaded, the entire shuttle will weigh in at about
4.5 million pounds.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Glenn's Mercury-Atlas vehicle weighed just under
260,000 pounds at the start of his first space flight.
</P>
<P>
   The launch team's biggest challenge appeared to be guessing what
President Clinton will do. Clinton plans to watch the launch, but
Altemus said his specific plans were ``constantly changing.''
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton decides to call the crew, the launch team will have
to figure out how to fit it into the countdown without upsetting
the tightly scheduled sequence of events, launch managers said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Clinton, about 200 politicians are expected to be in a
VIP viewing crowd. That and the high-profile nature of this mission
have prompted NASA support contractor Space Gateway Services Inc.
to boost security at the sprawling space center.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agencies and the Brevard County Sheriff's Office have
loaned extra bomb-sniffing dogs, SWAT teams and law-enforcement
officers for the mission, said Pete Colangel, SGS manager of
protective services.
</P>
<P>
   At the main gate to the launch complex, an electronic ``speed
bump'' takes a digital picture of the underside of each vehicle; a
security guard in a van inspects the image before allowing the
vehicle to pass, Colangel said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's possible presence in the launch control center or the
VIP viewing area has made a favorite photo point off-limits to the
news media for this mission _ the 525-foot-high Vehicle Assembly, a
mammoth sugar-cube shaped structure that looms over the launch
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Insulated from the swirl of reporters and politicians,
Discovery's crew was said to be in high spirits _ especially Glenn,
whose ``attitude is infectious,'' said Charles Precourt, a veteran
space shuttle astronaut who has been keeping close tabs on the crew
as chief of NASA's astronaut office.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very eager, very willing to do the work, and fun to be
around,'' Precourt said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
