<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REED-KY-COX     10-28 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REED-KY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reed doesn't shy from controversy
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Behind some of the more controversial Republican
campaigns in the Southeast is Ralph Reed, the former Christian
Coalition leader who is trying his hand at political consulting.
</P>
<P>
   His first round of candidates since opening Century Strategies
Inc. in Gwinnett County this year includes Mitch Skandalakis, the
GOP nominee for lieutenant governor in Georgia; John Frank Collins,
who is running for labor commissioner; Alabama Gov. Fob James; and
Kentucky state Sen. Gex Williams, running for Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The group is a mix of religious conservatives (James and
Williams), a perennial candidate (Collins) and an ambitious
suburbanite who revels in bare-knuckles politics (Skandalakis).
</P>
<P>
   They share an ability to attract controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I'm rapidly discovering about this business
is that you rarely have a guy who doesn't have any problems. I'm
still looking for Mr. Clean Jeans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Georgia graduate who came to national
prominence as the Christian Coalition's executive director also has
another dozen or so candidates in less competitive races, including
Sen. Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's work for the freshman senator follows the key role the
Christian Coalition played in his election six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell was not the first choice of religious conservatives in
the Republican primary that year, primarily because of his support
for abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than sit out the primary, Reed made sure that the
coalition distributed voter guides that portrayed Coverdell as
acceptable to conservatives, figuring Coverdell would be a strong
general election candidate against Democratic Sen. Wyche Fowler Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Kentucky congressional election features Williams, who is a
perfect match for the Christian Coalition, but who has stumbled
through the campaign over ethical issues and the reluctance of more
moderate Republicans to back him.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, James also faces an uphill fight in an election that
has turned into a referendum on a state lottery.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, the labor commissioner's election is an oddity,
pitting Collins, who has run in the past in both parties, against
Michael Thurmond, an African-American former chief of the
Department of Family and Children Services who is making his first
statewide race.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the lieutenant governor's race that has set the
standard for ugliness this campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   Skandalakis has run a TV ad that suggests opponent Mark Taylor
continues to use drugs (which Taylor vehemently denies) and, in the
view of critics, has sought to make race an issue in order to draw
the votes of conservative whites away from Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, citing an association with Skandalakis that goes back to
college, has a matter-of-fact view of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see either one of those guys winning a lot of Boy
Scout awards,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
