A2308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ART-NYT &LR;      10-28 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVAR TEEN'S DEATH REFLECTS ONGOING DANGER DESPITE CEASE-FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-HOLBROOKE) 
(ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By MIKE O'CONNOR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRAGOBILJE, Yugoslavia _ Hoping that NATO's demand that the
Yugoslav government reduce its forces in Kosovo province would help
keep their village safe, the family returned after three months of
hiding.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday they buried Ali Paqarizi, 19. He was killed Tuesday,
three blocks from home, by a booby trap that police left behind.
</P>
<P>
   There is a cease-fire in Kosovo, but there is still killing and
the likelihood of peace may not be high.
</P>
<P>
   Poking around the edges of a truce demanded and enforced by the
West, both sides in the war seem to be looking for ways to continue
fighting because the mistrust that started the conflict has become,
for some, the deepest hatred.
</P>
<P>
   As people were digging a grave for Ali Paqarizi here, villagers
nearby were digging four graves for elderly men who did not flee
quickly enough when the government attacked their homes this
summer. Their bodies were found by the first of their neighbors to
return Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Though U.S. and European diplomats Wednesday repeated their
strong warnings that peace and negotiations were in great jeopardy
if ethnic Albanian guerrillas reoccupied territory left by
government forces, the guerrillas were doing exactly that
throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Fighters of the rebel group, the Kosovo Liberation Army, bore
Ali Paqarizi's body from his home. Then, his mother followed, held
upright by friends and praying.
</P>
<P>
   In twos, holding hands or arm in arm, a long line of women came
out and turned toward the village square, scarves on their heads,
their long simple dresses reaching to the mud and stones of the
pathway.
</P>
<P>
   Then the men. First, those with the status that comes from age,
each one wearing the brimless white felt cap of Albanian tradition.
Along the way to the military ceremony in the square, other men
waited in groups at the street corners to fall in with the
procession. At the end came three Muslim clerics.
</P>
<P>
   Represented on the streets here were the parts of traditional
rural Albanian society in Kosovo: the family, the clan, the village
and religion.
</P>
<P>
   But the guerrilla army, more of a citizens' militia, these days
is often the part of society that has the most authority. Here,
Wednesday, it was in charge.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrilla army had essentially been in hiding since the
government began a military offensive in late July. But when the
government bowed to NATO threats this week and drastically cut the
number of police and soldiers in Kosovo, the guerrillas came back
as the civilians began to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Some 80 rebel fighters were Ali Paqarizi's pallbearers and honor
guard.
</P>
<P>
   A commander known as Steel, from the rebel headquarters, gave
the eulogy.
</P>
<P>
   He said the death had broken the cease-fire and would be
avenged. ``It is our obligation to those who have fallen to
continue on our sacred road until we have our freedom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The few people returning to Dragobilje on Tuesday and Wednesday
found three booby traps. In other villages, many more have been
found.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a good count yet,'' an international aid worker
said. ``But, mines and booby traps seem to be strewn everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened both by the fact that the government had left and the
rebels could come back, several families left their camps in the
forests and returned here Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Muhament Paqarizi, 48, drove the tractor and wagon with his
family's household goods up to the gate of the family compound and
flung it open. In the courtyard, by the well, there was the hole in
the flagstones left by the artillery round that had sent them
fleeing. On the walls of the buildings were the holes from the
molten metal chunks let loose when the shell exploded.
</P>
<P>
   His family is back, but is very nervous about it, he said. ``We
saw others start back. The last 10 days have been very cold and
wet, so we thought we might take a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   His brother, who said he was a civilian, was killed in his house
by government forces during the offensive. He is now raising his
brother's 10 children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kosovo Liberation Army is here to protect us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the question now is whether the forced retreat of the
government and the very fast advance of the guerrillas will make
renewed combat unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   One set of short hills away from where rebel fighters conducted
the funeral, there are government forces in the town of Malisevo.
With the threats for revenge from the rebel commander Steel fresh
in the air, people in Dragobilje were saying the government
detachment there should be attacked, partly in retribution and
partly because it was impossible for people to return there if the
police were not forced out.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said they have told rebel leaders that more
fighting would be a mistake because it would destroy their chances
for a reasonable political settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been told not to start trouble because we are not
going to bail them out,'' a diplomat said, implying that the West
would not restrain government counter attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such warnings, on the hills around Malisevo, rebel
fighters were occupying not only the land and villages just
abandoned by government forces, but many of the trenches,
observation posts and bunkers as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
