<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HOLBROOKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO ALMOST DECIDED TO BOMB YUGOSLAV FORCES, HOLBROOKE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Richard Holbrooke, the American architect of the
agreement on Kosovo, said Wednesday that NATO had come perilously
close in recent days to a decision to bomb Yugoslav forces to force
them out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us thought that bombing almost certainly was going to
happen,'' he said at a news conference at the State Department to
discuss the situation in the Balkans. ``I judged the chances of
military action _ that is, an aerial war _ at well over 60 percent
when we started. This was not a bluff.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat of NATO air strikes on Yugoslav targets was lifted,
at least for now, when NATO officials announced Tuesday that
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic was in ``substantial
compliance'' with Western demands that he withdraw his forces from
Kosovo and end Yugoslav attacks on ethnic Albanians who make up
most of the population there.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement worked out between Milosevic and Holbrooke,
unarmed Western monitors will now be sent to Kosovo to verify that
the Serbs do not try to resume their crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrooke said the team of monitors would total at least 2,000.
``Two thousand is a floor, not a ceiling,'' Holbrooke said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
