<SLUG> BC-DEPOT-ARREST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    5 environmental protesters arrested
 &HT;    By Chris Reinolds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service ATLANTA _ Five environmental protesters
<TEXT>
who made a pre-dawn climb up a 200-foot construction crane
Wednesday at Home Depot's headquarters in Cobb County were arrested
on charges of criminal trespass, a misdemeanor.
<P>
   Facing charges are John Johnson, 28, of Chattanooga, Tenn.;
Kimba Wolff, 22, of Athens, Ga.; Erin McCulley, 22, of Boone, N.C.;
Anthony Caldetra, 21, of Albany, Ga.; and Matthew Willford, 26, of
Bakersville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Another protester, David Jennings, 46 of Decatur, was arrested
on a charge of simple battery after he pushed a police
photographer, said Cobb County police spokesman Robert Quigley.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainforest Action Network protesters' activity drew looks
from morning rush hour commuters and caused two wrecks on nearby
roads, according to police. The protest ended about 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot said the disruption cost the company about half a day
in construction time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
