<HEADER>
A2314 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALANIS-MORISSETTE-MUS     10-28 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALANIS-MORISSETTE-MUSIC-$ADV01-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALANIS MORISSETTE EXPLORES THE HEALING POWER OF SONG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (For release Sunday, Nov. 1) 
(ART ADV: Photo of Alanis Morissette is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The woman who sings Alanis Morissette's new album
sounds like a mess. In the 17 songs on ``Supposed Former
Infatuation Junkie'' (Maverick), which is to be released on
Tuesday, she has been attached to abusive men, she has been
stuffing and starving herself, she has taken too many antibiotics,
and she has been working herself to the point of collapse. She has
felt jealous, misunderstood, worthless; nothing, from shopping to
sex to wealth and worldwide popularity, has made her happy. And
every bit of trauma and frustration comes out in her voice: in its
harried vibrato and sudden yelping breaks, in its banshee wails and
caustic nasal turns. While her litany of self-doubt is set in the
past tense, the wounds still sound raw.
</P>
<P>
   But in a long talk at the beach house she has rented outside Los
Angeles, the 24-year-old woman who wrote the songs is serene and
cheerful, with an easy laugh that sometimes makes her blush.
``Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie'' is the follow-up to ``Jagged
Little Pill,'' released in 1995, which sold 28 million copies
worldwide with its mixture of fury and resilience. After keeping a
low profile for more than a year, Ms. Morissette is about to face
the public again.
</P>
<P>
   Back from a business meeting, she's wearing a gray pullover and
a black skirt, and she has peach nail polish on her fingers and
toes. Her place is austerely furnished, with an oversize white
couch, a few chairs and a mattress on the floor by the terrace that
overlooks the Pacific. The only obvious personal touches are a pair
of large candles and an amber-colored 1930s Bakelite radio, a
birthday present.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morissette pulls shut a sliding glass door so that the roar
of the waves won't drown her out on an interviewer's tape, curls up
on the couch and explains that, yes, the scenarios she sang are all
pretty much true, with names changed. Writing and performing them,
she says, is a way of resolving things. Maybe it should be called
song therapy; songwriter and audience are determined to master
their problems by naming them aloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more vulnerable and the more confused the song is, the
equal and opposite effect is how I feel after having written it,''
she said. ``Admitting I was bouncing off the walls made it so I
could be calm in my own skin, because I could say it and dissolve
it. And the deeper I go admitting fear, admitting the confusion,
the clearer I usually feel. I don't really feel vulnerable; I feel
empowered by it.''
</P>
<P>
   The therapeutic model has a long rock pedigree. John Lennon made
it official with his primal-scream songs in 1970, but songwriters
from time immemorial have displaced their conflicts, sublimated
their lusts, sought revenge and admitted their upsets within the
confines of verse-chorus-verse.
</P>
<P>
   Few, however, have been as blunt about their therapeutic intent
as Ms. Morissette is on ``Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie.'' The
album includes one song, ``The Couch,'' about convincing her father
to try therapy, and another in which she tells a friend, ``I was
hoping we could heal each other.'' In conversation as well as
lyrics, Ms. Morissette doesn't shy away from psychobabble. ``You've
been nothing but open-hearted and emotionally available and
supportive and nurturing,'' she sings in ``Unsent,'' a series of
affectionate messages to ex-boyfriends. (She says that she called
each one, including men she hadn't spoken to in years, and asked
for permission to sing about him.)
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, not the first time that Ms. Morissette has
wailed her troubles. ``Jagged Little Pill,'' was full of emotional
whiplashes: the furious accusations and sexual bravado of ``You
Oughtta Know,'' the cheerful contradictions in ``Hand in My
Pocket,'' the lapsed-Catholic backlash of ``Forgiven.'' At the
time, Ms. Morissette was unknown outside Canada, where she had been
a child actress and a dance-pop singer and songwriter. But ``Jagged
Little Pill'' reached young women (and some men) around the world,
and Ms. Morissette's concerts almost immediately became fervent
sing-alongs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morissette emerged behind a pack of daring female rockers in
the mid-1990s, among them P.J. Harvey, Liz Phair and Ani DiFranco,
who didn't flinch from sexual candor or extreme emotions. But their
audiences were primarily collegiate-cult followings. Ms. Morissette
was only 21 years old when ``Jagged Little Pill'' came out, and the
songs, some of them written while she was still a teen-ager,
grabbed a mass audience directly by its adolescent angst.
</P>
<P>
   Working with Glen Ballard, who had produced Michael Jackson, Ms.
Morissette came up with clear-cut rock tunes and studded them with
guitar feedback and cutting vocals, a potent commercial combination
of hooks and barbs. She toured like a trouper through 1996,
circling the globe, and ``Jagged Little Pill'' became the
best-selling American debut album ever.
</P>
<P>
   Then she withdrew, exhausted. Recording companies were already
seeking the next Morissette, cultivating the yelps of singers like
Natalie Imbruglia, Chantal Kreviazuk and Tracy Bonham. Meanwhile,
Ms. Morissette stepped away from the music business. ``I had been
overwhelmed with the vast amount of stimuli that is catapulted your
way when you're in the public eye and on tour,'' she said.
``Everything snowballing as it did was a lot to digest, and I
really didn't have the energy or the clarity or the understanding
or the handbook to do that. Now, my handbook would say, `Cry when
you need to cry, talk when you need to talk and stop when you need
to stop.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morissette went through bouts of depression as the tour
stretched on. ``Schedule-wise, my health and my peace of mind
wasn't a priority,'' she said. ``There had been this dissonance in
the midst of all the external success. Because on the one hand, I
was expected to be overjoyed by it, and at the same time I was
disillusioned by it. I wasn't ungrateful, I was just confused and
overwhelmed. So I stopped for what felt like the first time in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
