<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC ALBANIANS RETURN TO KOSOVO, BUT TROUBLE FOLLOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Braving booby traps and sometimes under
the gaze of Yugoslav police, a cautious but steady flow of ethnic
Albanians returned to their abandoned villages in Kosovo, a day
after a Serb pullout led NATO to cancel air raids.
</P>
<P>
   While humanitarian aid groups and Western diplomats took heart
from the returning ethnic Albanians, who had fled into the woods
and hills to escape Serb forces, the US diplomat responsible for
the Serbian province of Kosovo expressed concern that ethnic
Albanian rebels might exploit the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking here late Wednesday afternoon, Christopher Hill, the US
envoy to Kosovo, said he was encouraged by the ``changes on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hill said he worried that the rebels of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, would reestablish checkpoints and posture
provocatively with rifles as they return to the villages from which
they were driven by Serbs over the last nine months. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased that returns are taking place,'' Hill said. But,
he added, ``It is our strong view the KLA should not take advantage
of this reconfiguration, the withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill and his European Union counterpart, Wolfgang Petritsch, the
Austrian ambassador in Belgrade, spoke to reporters outside the US
headquarters here after meeting with the ethnic Albanian delegation
that is supposed to take part in talks with Serbian negotiators,
part of the deal reached two weeks ago by US special envoy Richard
Holbrooke and Yugoslav president Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia is the larger of the two republics that make up
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Hill met with Adem Demaci, a political
representative of the guerrilla group that says it will only stop
fighting when Kosovo is given its independence, to emphasize that
the Kosovo Liberation Army should not taunt Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States does not support Kosovo's independence,''
said Hill. ``It would not be a stabilizing factor in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, US officials were giving the rebels credit for
disarming some of the crude mines and booby traps left behind by
Serb forces. Some of the tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians
displaced by the Serb offensive have refused to return home, citing
fears about booby traps. An ethnic Albanian man who returned to his
home in Dragobilj was killed Tuesday when he tripped a mine.
</P>
<P>
   Hill urged the ethnic Albanians to take advantage of the
breathing space created by the rebel cease-fire and the Serb
withdrawal to begin negotiations on returning Kosovo to the
autonomy it had before Milosevic unilaterally ended it in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``Checkpoints are not going to solve this thing,'' said Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Preparations are being made to accommodate an international
force of 2,000 observers to verify that Milosevic and the rebels
are each keeping their part of the bargain. An equal number of
soldiers from European armies will be deployed to protect the
observers.
</P>
<P>
   Humanitarian groups, meanwhile, were trying to figure out how to
get those who fled the Serb forces to return to their homes, and to
repair many of the homes that were damaged or ruined by Serb troops
and shells.
</P>
<P>
   Of Kosovo's 2 million people, up to 300,000 have fled their
homes in the last nine months, according to humanitarian groups.
The Serbian government puts that figure at closer to 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 700 people, most of them ethnic Albanian civilians,
have been killed since last February, when Serb forces launched a
counter-offensive against the Kosovo Liberation Army after the
separatist group began killing members of the Serb security forces
and publicly asserting control over villages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1955EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2316 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALANIS-MORISSETTE-MUS     10-28 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALANIS-MORISSETTE-MUSIC-$ADV01-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: my life.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She traveled to India and Cuba; she resumed friendships and
reconnected with her family. She got in shape to run, bicycle and
swim in triathlons. She read fiction and psychology books. And for
a while, she contemplated letting ``Jagged Little Pill'' be her
last album.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very thought of my creating another record and having that
sort of craziness that came along with it just didn't seem worth it
to me,'' she said. ``I needed to enter into what I saw as this
terrorizing abyss of letting go of everything that I had been
taught. A lot of preconceived notions that I had about fame and
status and money and joy and pain, and all of these things that I
thought I knew, I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet almost as soon as she decided that she could step away from
her career, she found herself writing songs again. And as 1998
began, she returned to the place where she made ``Jagged Little
Pill,'' Ballard's Aerowave Studio in Encino, Calif. The main studio
is a control room on the second floor of a large house. It's the
size of a master bedroom, with tidy racks of equipment, a small
glassed-in vocal booth and a view of olive trees out the window.
</P>
<P>
   Using guitars, keyboards and computers, Ballard and Ms.
Morissette would work on music together, and then Ms. Morissette
would winnow lyrics from her journals while Ballard built the
backing track. ``She would have this duffel bag full of her
thoughts, poems, ruminations,'' Ballard said. ``Those were all raw
materials. She likes to get a flow going with the music. I'll get a
seed of something, and once she hears it the way she wants to hear
it, she'll go to this computer around the corner and finish the
lyrics.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballard added: ``Every word for her is like giving blood. As she
writes, she eliminates all the things that don't work for her
emotionally. But once she's satisfied that she's said what she had
to say, at that moment, all the lights turn green and she just goes
in and burns it down. She sings it once, maybe twice, and she walks
away from it and says, `That's it.' I don't know anybody else who
can do it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Ballard said they frequently wrote and recorded a song a
day. Ms. Morissette insisted on spontaneity. One song, ``That I
Would Be Good,'' had a buzz in Ballard's guitar part; he
re-recorded it with cleaner sound, but Ms. Morissette insisted that
he keep the original.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morissette shrugs off questions about commercial
expectations. ``I don't think about that,'' she said. ``That wasn't
my mind-set when I wrote `Jagged Little Pill,' or anything before
that, either. I've been surrounded by a lot of people who felt that
external success would result in them feeling good about
themselves. But it just seems extremely unfulfilling to me. You're
almost guaranteed to be disappointed. For me, a life without
expectation results in a life with inspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   Madonna, the co-chief executive officer of Maverick Records,
said in a telephone interview, ``There's nothing predictable about
this record at all, and a lot of it is more experimental than I
expected. She definitely pushes the envelope on this record as well
as delivering some well-written songs. And she uses a lot of
50-cent words on the record. I don't even know what half of those
words mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Does the company anticipate another blockbuster? ``She has a
huge following, and everyone's waiting for this record,'' Madonna
said. ``But 28 million, that's a horrible standard to try to live
up to. She's already proven herself. I won't be disappointed if it
doesn't sell 28 million. I'd be disappointed if it didn't sell 5
million, but I know that won't happen. But for those huge numbers,
it means you're drawing the long straw with the guardian angel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie'' doesn't set out to
re-create ``Jagged Little Pill'' in sound or attitude. Some of Ms.
Morissette's new songs, like the single ``Thank U,'' have clear-cut
choruses; some don't. And rhymes have virtually disappeared from
the lyrics, which can read like unfiltered diary entries. Words,
not melodies, take precedence on most songs, and Ms. Morissette
often delivers them in recitatives, akin to Joni Mitchell and Ani
DiFranco at their most loquacious, and in repeated, incantatory
lines that hint at non-Western music. (Ms. Morissette is to appear
on an album of studio-concocted posthumous duets with the great
Pakistani singer Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan along with Perry Farrell of
Jane's Addiction and the Israeli singer Ofra Haza.)
</P>
<P>
   The tone is different, too. Where ``Jagged Little Pill'' often
lashed out, much of ``Supposed Former Infatuation Junkie'' is about
reconciliation: with parents, with lovers, with the fears and
weaknesses that Ms. Morissette saw in herself. ``I just equated
relationships with pain, and now I don't,'' she said. ``I think of
a lot of those songs on `Jagged Little Pill' as being reactionary.
And they resulted in release but not closure. My rage, in and of
itself, alone and without a level of consciousness and
understanding, wasn't enough.''
</P>
<P>
   In the harrowing ``Sympathetic Character,'' enclosed by a stark,
percussive drone and layers of distorted guitar, Ms. Morissette
recalls an abusive relationship, shifting between memories of
terror _ ``I was afraid you'd hit me if I'd spoken up/I was afraid
of your physical strength'' _ and of dependency: ``You were my best
friend/you were my lover/you were my mentor.'' The song, Ms.
Morissette said, is based on ``a composite of a bunch of people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never abused as such, in the conventional view,'' she
said. ``But I don't think we have to have been beaten up to fear
being beaten up. It's simply being around someone who you don't
trust to be able to deal with their rage. You get used to it, and
that which is familiar is often what we equate with love. I used to
think heart palpitations were love, and really it was fear.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
