<HEADER>
A2320 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALANIS-MORISSETTE-MUS     10-28 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALANIS-MORISSETTE-MUSIC-$ADV01-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOS ANGELES: was fear.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the gentle ``Are You Still Mad,'' Ms. Morissette itemizes the
ways she sabotaged a romance _ ``Are you still mad I had a tendency
to mother you?/Are you still mad that I had one foot out the door''
_ and concludes, ``Of course you are.'' In ``Would Not Come,''
which meshes a modal, Middle Eastern-flavored melody with a
plunging syncopated bass line, Ms. Morissette catalogs misgivings
and chronic dissatisfactions. ``If I take a break it would make me
irresponsible,'' she sings. ``I'd be filthy rich and still it would
not come/I would seduce them and still it would not come.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the songs on ``Jagged Little Pill'' offered a personalized
take on Everygirl's growing pains, ``Supposed Former Infatuation
Junkie'' is more narrowly focused on Ms. Morissette's own situation
as a singular kind of career woman. The songs grapple with
contradictory drives toward success and self-effacement and with
the hollowness of wealth and fame; they wind up, in songs like
``Thank U'' and ``Joining You,'' with a nondenominational
spirituality that insists that people are important for their
essences, not their achievements. The point is not in the
specifics, but in the sound of torment giving way to consolation,
again and again. The volatile strength of Ms. Morissette's voice
promises that candor, no matter what it reveals, will set her free.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Morissette came through New York in late October on a tour
of small halls and theaters before the album's release. At the
Hammerstein Ballroom, her band made the songs pound and seethe,
while Ms. Morissette paced the stage and hurled phrases skyward.
Young women were already singing along on ``Thank U,'' and cheering
its verses of self-help as if they were a pop plebiscite. ``How
'bout no longer being masochistic?,'' Ms. Morissette sang to a wave
of happy shouts. ``How 'bout remembering your divinity?'' got a
more subdued response. But when she sang, ``How 'bout unabashedly
bawling your eyes out?'' the whole room erupted in affirmative
squeals. The therapy was still in progress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
