<HEADER>
A2321 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      10-28 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASKS THAT ELECTION NOT BE REFERENDUM ON HIS PERSONAL
BEHAVIOR  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton asserted Wednesday that he had
undergone ``inner changes'' as a result of the Monica Lewinsky
scandal and said that Tuesday's elections should not be a
referendum on his personal behavior but on his conduct in office.
</P>
<P>
   Answering Republican campaign advertisements that because of his
lies about the Lewinsky scandal he cannot be trusted with the
public's business, Clinton said that he had kept the majority of
his policy promises to the American people and that he should be
held accountable for his public integrity, not his private acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I think that it's fair for a person to be judged on his
whole record,'' the president said in a Rose Garden news conference
with Andres Pastrana, the president of Colombia, who is in
Washington for a state visit. ``I'm not trying to sugarcoat the
fact that I made a mistake and that I didn't want anybody to know
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   At another point in the 50-minute news conference, Clinton
added: ``I hope the American people have seen in me over these last
few weeks a real commitment to doing what I told them I would do
from the beginning _ to try to atone to them for what happened and
to try to redouble my efforts to be a good president. And I hope
they have sensed the inner changes that are going on and the
manifestations and the efforts I've made to help the education of
our children in the budget, to achieve peace in the Middle East
talks.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been the essence of the White House defense in the
Lewinsky affair from the beginning: Clinton's personal behavior
with Ms. Lewinsky was indefensible, but it was private and has no
bearing on how he does his job as president. His actions were
wrong, Clinton's lawyers and political defenders concede, but not
impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   That line of argument has now become a significant part of the
Democrats' strategy in the midterm election. They are happy to
allow Republicans to focus on Clinton's private conduct because
they believe _ and polls tend to support that belief _ that the
American public has rendered a judgment on the president and, by a
large margin, does not favor removing him from office for his
private actions.
</P>
<P>
   In the joint appearance with Pastrana, Clinton returned again
and again to the message he said he believes will benefit
Democratic candidates across the country. He said Republicans are
intent on making the election a referendum on his conduct, while he
is accusing Republicans of squandering the nation's future by
trying to use budget surpluses to finance tax cuts, by refusing to
pass health care and tobacco legislation, and by failing to act on
legislation to revamp campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he had redeemed his promises to the American
people, while Republicans had knuckled under to well-financed
special interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at what I said I'd do when I presented myself to
the American people in 1991 and 1992, at the long list of things
we've done we said we'd do, and at the good results that the
American people have enjoyed, and at the fact that the American
people, I think, agree with us and not them _ I think that's the
real issue here,'' the president said. ``Are we right or are they
right?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's robust defense of his record came in response to
several questions about a new series of Republican television
advertisements questioning his integrity and his trustworthiness.
</P>
<P>
   One portrays two middle-class housewives discussing how to
explain the Lewinsky scandal to their children.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked how he would answer that advertisement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what people ought to say to their children is that,
`When someone makes a mistake, they should admit it and try to
rectify it,' and that this is an illustration of the fact that
those rules should apply to everyone,'' Clinton said. ``But that
when people do that, if they do it properly, they can be stronger
in their personal lives, in their family lives and in their work
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said that he had gone through a period of
self-examination and had grown stronger as a result. ``With a
humble spirit, with the grace of God and with a lot of
determination,'' Clinton said, ``I think that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton received a vote of confidence from Pastrana, who was
inaugurated as president of Colombia three months ago to replace
President Ernesto Samper, whom the administration considered
corrupted by drug money.
</P>
<P>
   Pastrana welcomed the U.S. commitment to his anti-drug efforts
and his attempt to make peace with insurgents. He noted that the
United States had pledged $280 million in new economic assistance
to Colombia, in part to help compensate coca farmers who switch to
less lethal but also less lucrative crops.
</P>
<P>
   And like many other foreign leaders with whom Clinton has
appeared during this year of scandal and investigation, he offered
warm words of support for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allow me to say,'' Pastrana said, ``that my country and my
compatriots feel deep respect for President Clinton and for his
role as a world leader and as a rarity in history.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1956EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
