<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2322 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-POWER-DEREG-COX     10-28 2153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-POWER-DEREG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas braces for another deregulation battle
 &HT;    (With TEX-POWERDEREG-SUMMARY, -CALIF, -PENN. Photos available.
For Sun., Nov. 1. Moving on a and financial wires.)
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When the federal government deregulated the
airline industry in 1978, it changed forever the way people travel,
spurring competition, lowering prices and giving upstart
discounters such as Southwest Airlines a chance to prosper.
</P>
<P>
   When a federal judge approved the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T,
telephone users for the first time were able to choose their
long-distance company.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the state government is considering what could be one of
its most sweeping deregulation actions ever, one that would affect
every consumer and business every time they flick on a light
switch, wash a load of laundry or fire up a factory.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three months from now, the Legislature will begin
debating whether to consider letting Texans shop for their
electricity, just as they can for long-distance telephone service
or the best air fares.
</P>
<P>
   It's a topic so controversial that it has led to protests and
political referendums in other states. It's an issue so big that
the federal government may consider intervening on a national level
next year. And it's so complex that even the legislators who will
decide whether Texas should go through with it are still trying to
understand it.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, both a major producer and a major consumer of energy,
the stakes are enormous.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of deregulation say consumers could save 15 percent
to 30 percent on their monthly electric bills. Given that Texans
pay an average of $88 a month for electricity, that means every
household could have an extra $300 a year to spend on something
else. Moreover, they say, if the state doesn't open up the
electricity business to competition that could bring down prices,
big energy-using employers could move their operations to other
states where they have more choice. Even if they didn't leave, they
might want to expand elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of deregulation point out that Texans already have rates
that are below the national average and the Public Utility
Commission lately has even trimmed rates at some utilities. They
point to other states _ 18 others have begun deregulating their
electric industries _ where competition hasn't worked, at least not
yet. And, they say, deregulation could lead to higher rates, and
will almost undoubtedly lead to more hassles for consumers already
weary of long-distance telephone company pitches and problems.
</P>
<P>
   You'd think such a highly charged issue would be a hot topic
among political candidates and voters.
</P>
<P>
   Think again.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who is running for re-election and favors
competition, said no one asks him about it on the campaign trail:
``It's hard for people to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   His Democratic opponent, Land Commissioner Garry Mauro, said he
considered including electric competition in his announcement
speech, but took it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too complicated for people to understand in an election
year format and it made my speech way too long,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   Enormous impact
</P>
<P>
   Complicated, yes, but incredibly important.
</P>
<P>
   On its surface, the issue of deregulating the electricity
business is simple. Right now, government bodies generally set
electric rates. The Austin City Council sets the rates for the
city-owned utility, Austin Energy. Pedernales Electric Cooperative
Inc., based in Johnson City, sets its own rates, subject to review
by the Public Utility Commission. Rates of big investor-owned
utilities, such as Texas Utilities Electric Co., are set by the
PUC.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, each utility has a monopoly over its service area;
with a few exceptions, no other company can serve its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation would do two things. It would end regulation of the
price charged for generating electricity (but not transporting it),
and it would allow customers to buy it from anyone willing to sell
it to them.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is that if sellers are forced to compete, that will
keep a lid on prices and spur innovative services.
</P>
<P>
   But then the issue of deregulation gets more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Investor-owned utilities typically favor competition_ but only
if it includes a guarantee that they still could bill customers to
recover the billions of dollars they invested in nuclear power
plants _ so called ``stranded costs.'' Right now, those costs are
passed along to consumers in their monthly bills.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that those nuclear plants aren't worth as much
today as the utilities paid to build them. The most recent PUC
report pegged the lost value at $4.5 billion, but its estimates for
individual utilities are generally less than what the utilities
claim.
</P>
<P>
   Also, while Texans have low electric rates, they use a lot of
electricity to cope with the heat by running their air
conditioners.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates, pointing to the fact that Texans have the
third-highest electric bills on average _ only Hawaii and Florida
are higher, according to trade group Edison Electric Institute _
say that Texas needs to do more to encourage conservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the highest bills in the nation for average
consumers,'' said Tom Smith, director of Public Citizen in Texas, a
group founded by consumer crusader Ralph Nader. ``Our power plants
are the largest industrial source of pollution. And we're not
developing new resources we're going to need for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer and environmental groups are not necessarily opposed to
competition in principle, but they want to make sure that programs
to promote energy conservation don't get junked and that air
pollution isn't worsened by competitors making heavier use of
older, less-clean plants.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumer groups also warn against potential ``cost
shifting'' that could occur with deregulation, in which utilities
would cut prices for big customers by trying to collect more money
from residential and small business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, city-owned utilities, such as Austin's, and electric
cooperatives, like Pedernales, remain skeptical. The cooperatives,
which serve mostly rural areas and small towns, fear that big power
suppliers could take away their biggest, most profitable customers,
forcing them to raise the rates of the remaining residential and
small business customers. And the co-ops are in a position to
negotiate, as they showed in the last legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Last session, Bush got behind a bill to allow competition in the
industry, but tripped over the state's electric cooperatives, which
decided at the eleventh hour they were opposed.
</P>
<P>
   The bill didn't even get out of committee.
</P>
<P>
   Big push is on
</P>
<P>
   The issue, however, didn't go away.
</P>
<P>
   Big industrial and commercial customers are convinced that
competition would save them millions of dollars. In Texas, they are
organized as the Texas Coalition for Competitive Electricity, whose
members cover a wide spectrum of businesses, from the Texas
Chemical Council to the Texas Restaurant Association.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Kroger, an attorney for the coalition, said all
customers would save 15 percent to 30 percent on their electric
bills in a fully competitive system. And she said business needs
lawmakers to act in 1999 so that everyone can plot their futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want to know what the landscape's going to look like,''
Kroger said.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's biggest energy companies _ many of which are based
in Texas _ have been plotting strategy for years and are
combat-savvy veterans from deregulation battles in other states.
</P>
<P>
   While the politicians have been silent, the Association of
Electric Companies of Texas has launched a $1.1 million statewide
television ad campaign trumpeting the advantages of competition.
</P>
<P>
   The association's president, John Fainter, argues that if the
Legislature doesn't act, Congress will, and ``Texans may suffer
unpleasant consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Fainter says he isn't trying to scare the Legislature into
passing a bill. But such decisions should be made in Austin, not
Washington, he said, adding that utilities need certainty before
Wall Street and others will invest in new power plants in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The utilities have put their money behind the push for
competition in another way, too.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 1997, campaign contribution reports filed with the
state show, Texas' investor-owned utilities have contributed more
than $652,000 to federal, state and local candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Of that, about $380,000 went to candidates, mostly incumbents,
for state offices, including $58,000 to Bush. At the state Capitol,
the debate over electricity deregulation has already been going on
quietly for months.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Interim Committee on Electric Restructuring and the
House State Affairs Committee have been considering whether the
state should deregulate and give up much of its control over the
rates charged by the utilities.
</P>
<P>
   But the more they learn, the more reluctant lawmakers seem to
tamper with an electric utility system that, they believe, works
well here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pro-competitors have launched a campaign to get into the mind
of consumers that deregulation of electricity means cheaper
electricity,'' complained a member of the House committee, Rep.
Delwin Jones, R-Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Jones said. ``It means that certain people
may get a bargain discount if they are a big (industrial or
commercial) consumer. But we've got to be extremely careful, or
anything we do will cause the residential and small business owner
an increase in his cost for electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   Also cautious is Sen. Troy Fraser, R-Horseshoe Bay, a member of
the special Senate panel: ``If we're not totally assured rates will
go down for residential users, we can't vote for a bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest figures from the federal Energy Information
Administration show why legislators sound so cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Texas residential customers, on average, paid 7.8
cents per kilowatt hour for electricity. The national average was
8.5 cents. California residential customers paid 11.4 cents, while
Pennsylvanians paid 9.8 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In pennies, those differences don't sound like much. But they
add up quickly: a monthly electric bill that would be $100 in Texas
would be $126 in Pennsylvania and $146 in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we have medium-range rates, we still have the
highest electric bills in the United States,'' said Rep. Debra
Danburg, D-Houston, who favors competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not lower those electric bills if we can do so?'' she
said. ``And we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Push for action
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how the battle lines will be drawn will become more
clear over the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   While politicians may be skirting the complex issue now, they'll
be forced to get an education quickly _ if not by consumers, then
by the utilities and others who are trying to force them to make a
stand when the Legislature convenes in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's imminent,'' said Dick Brooks, chairman of Central and
South West Corp., a Dallas-based holding company that owns four
electric utilities, including three operating in Texas. ``It's
about to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Central and South West is merging with a bigger utility,
American Electric Power Inc. of Columbus, Ohio, because of a
conviction that it must get bigger to navigate the coming age of
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Still others see no reason to act: ``I want Texas to wait at
least four years to see what is happening in those pilot programs
in the East and the West,'' said state Rep. Leo Alvarado, D-San
Antonio, a member of the House State Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But like some big utilities, some Wall Street analysts say Texas
cannot afford to wait and see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big customers, if they have choice and if the rates are low,
they'll continue to expand in that area,'' said Edward Tierello, an
investment analyst with Bankers Trust in New York. ``If they don't
have choice, and even if rates are low, they may choose to go
somewhere else where they think there's a possibility of getting a
better deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're jeopardizing the economic future of the state if you
don't put something in place'' to allow competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have watched deregulation in other states _ places
where energy isn't as important as it is in Texas _ agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe you can continue to be the energy center of
the country and not open up your market to retail electric
competition,'' said John Hanger, a former member of the
Pennsylvania Public Utility Commission, whose years as a consumer
advocate convinced him regulation didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Texas continues to protect its local monopolies by not
passing pro-competition legislation, Texas will resign its energy
leadership to other states.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
