<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2323 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-POWERDEREG-CALIF-     10-28 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-POWERDEREG-CALIF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Californians take a wait-and-see attitude
 &HT;    (With TEX-POWERDEREG, TEX-POWERDEREG-SUMMARY,
TEX-POWERDEREG-PENN. Photos available. For Sun., Nov. 1. Moving on
a and financial wires.)
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California consumers' reaction to getting the
right to shop for electricity can be summed up in the word that
perhaps best expresses Californians' laid-back image: ``Whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they have been able to shop for their own power company
since March 31, fewer than 68,000 residential customers _ less than
1 percent _ in California have switched to other electricity
suppliers, according to the California Public Utilities Commission.
Only about 30,000 commercial and industrial customers had made the
switch. That's out of almost 10 million eligible customers.
</P>
<P>
   That indifference in a state where power costs 50 percent more
than the national average perhaps reflects a feeling of comfort
dealing with a well-known local utility and unpleasant experiences
with competition elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   James Forrest, a retired local government official on a recent
visit to the Hillsdale Shopping Center in San Mateo, just south of
San Francisco, said he had not even considered buying power from
someone other than the big local utility, Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric,
``primarily because we're satisfied with the service.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Nadine Forrest, a retired teacher, said she got fed up
with telephone companies calling her for long-distance business.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't she like to have a choice for an electricity supplier?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a nuisance!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some call California's deregulation plan a flop. Others call it
an outrage. Still others say it just needs more time because, like
the breakup of AT&AMP;T in 1984, real competition will evolve slowly,
not explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not try to prejudge what's happened in California,''
said Richard Bilas, president of the California Public Utilities
Commission. ``We didn't start until March 31 ... (but) it is true
that if one were to look at the early results on the residential
side, you would say, `Uh-oh, this is a tremendous failure.'''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, big industrial customers are taking
advantage of their new freedom to shop around.
</P>
<P>
   Bilas said he thinks more vigorous competition for residential
and small business customers will begin after 2002, when the
state's power consumers finish paying off about $28 billion in old
utility investments through a ``competition transition charge'' now
included in every monthly bill.
</P>
<P>
   The transition charge is supposed to compensate utilities for
their investments in nuclear power plants and other long-term
contracts that, in an open market, won't be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer advocates have attacked the transition charge as a
utility bail-out strongly enough that they were able to get a
proposition on the November ballot that could cancel it. If voters
approve it, the issue is likely to end up in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   The transition charge is among the factors cited by California
utility experts on why competition has gotten off to such a slow
start. Other reasons include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Under the California plan, the residential and small business
customers of the state's three biggest investor-owned utilities,
which have most of the market, got 10 percent rate cuts without
doing a thing. Not only did that give customers incentive to stay
with their utility, it made it harder for new competitors to
compete.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not long after competition began, there were a number of media
reports about shady electricity dealers and questionable marketing
practices. That scared a lot of people away.
</P>
<P>
   _ The transition charge can vary from month to month, making it
difficult for a would-be competitor to figure out just what rate to
set for a customer, said Steve Kean, senior vice president for
government affairs at Enron Corp., a Houston-based power marketer.
Enron made national news this spring when it stopped marketing to
residential customers in California. However, it continues to sell
to industrial and commercial customers.
</P>
<P>
   _ The California commission, according to critics, was all too
generous in deciding that the three utilities were entitled to
recover up to $28 billion from the transition charge to make up for
what the industry calls ``stranded costs.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the leading critics of the utilities is Nettie Hoge,
executive director of The Utility Reform Network, a consumer group
that participates in electric rate cases.
</P>
<P>
   TURN officially took a neutral stand in 1996 when the California
General Assembly adopted the pro-competition legislation that, Hoge
says, heavily favored the utilities. Neutrality was a mistake, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have laid down on the track,'' Hoge said.
</P>
<P>
   Other states, including Texas, should not enact similar
legislation just because many say competition is inevitable, Hoge
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does the train have to leave the station?'' she said.
``Especially if your rates are average?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are those who welcome the opportunity to choose _
even, in some cases, choosing to pay more if it means helping the
environment. It's one face of competition that consumer advocates
like.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Baumrucker, of nearby Castro Valley, a city in the San
Francisco Bay area south of Oakland, is one such customer ready to
pay more. He signed up to buy his power from Green Mountain Energy
Resources, a Vermont-based partnership that markets electricity
produced from renewable resources, such as wind turbines, dams,
biomass and geothermal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember what it was,'' Baumrucker said, when asked
how much more he expected to pay. ``I'm willing to pay it.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost ``is not the crucial thing,'' he said. ``The crucial
thing is getting in step with the way I think things ought to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
