NYT-10-28-98 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0391 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-POWERDEREG-PENN-C     10-28 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-POWERDEREG-PENN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Pennsylvania, choice is off to a good start
 &HT;    (With TEX-POWERDEREG, TEX-POWERDEREG-SUMMARY,
TEX-POWERDEREG-CALIF. Photos available. For Sun., Nov. 1. Moving on
a and financial wires.)
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Paul and Marie Curran didn't think their monthly
electric bills from PECO Energy Co. were all that bad, although one
infamously hot summer four years ago they got one for $350.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with three college-age daughters to support, the Currans
_ he's a planner for the Philadelphia Planning Commission, she's a
school nurse _ welcome any opportunity to trim expenses in their
North Philadelphia home, a Dutch colonial with four bedrooms and
about 2,200 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   So when they were offered an opportunity a year ago to join
Pennsylvania's pilot project for opening electric utility
monopolies to competition, the Currans took it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interested in the guaranteed savings that was being
offered by all the companies that were in the program _ 8 to 12
percent,'' said Paul Curran.
</P>
<P>
   After considering numerous offers, they decided to stay with
PECO Energy. But because their power started coming from a new PECO
subsidiary established just to compete with other electricity
providers, their monthly bills nevertheless fell by about 10
percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Currans paid $198.23 for their electricity in July; had they
not been in the program they would have paid $221.08.
</P>
<P>
   The Currans were among 230,000 Pennsylvanians who were in the
pilot project. They will soon be among a much larger group of
Pennsylvania residents who, starting Jan. 1, will be able to choose
their electric company.
</P>
<P>
   Local electric utilities will continue to deliver power to
Pennsylvania customers and take care of such problems as power
outages. Rates for those services are still regulated.
</P>
<P>
   But customers will be charged separately for the electricity
itself. Their bills will state the ``price to beat'' on power so
that they'll know exactly what a competitor must offer to save them
money.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania is not the first state to adopt a plan to allow
competition in the electric utility industry, but observers in
Texas and elsewhere say it appears to have done the best job yet.
</P>
<P>
   So far, almost 2 million of Pennsylvania's 5.2 million
electricity customers have signed up to shop for a power supplier.
About 70 companies have signed up as suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania Legislature enacted pro-competition legislation
in December 1996. It phased in competition so that all customers
are expected to have a choice by January 2000. It also provided for
the pilot project to test the new system.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvanians first began hearing a call for competition in the
mid-1990s, when John Hanger, a member of the state's Public Utility
Commission, decided that competition would be the best way to force
down high electric rates.
</P>
<P>
   Hanger had served for a number of years as a consumer advocate
in utility rate cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating,'' Hanger said. ``We were always arguing
how much rates should go up. We didn't argue about much they should
go down.''
</P>
<P>
   So in 1993, as a new member of the Public Utility Commission, he
began advocating competition as the best way to keep rates down.
</P>
<P>
   Big industrial and commercial customers began to note that while
they were paying rates as high as 6.5 cents per kilowatt hour,
wholesale power was selling for around 3 cents, said David
Kleppinger, an attorney for the Industrial Energy Consumers of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   If utilities could buy power for 3 cents per kilowatt hour, he
said, ``Why not us?''
</P>
<P>
   A Republican governor elected in 1994, Tom Ridge, got
competition rolling.
</P>
<P>
   He saw it as another way to advance his program for countering
what many saw as an anti-business climate in Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   With the chairman of the Public Utility Commission, John Quain,
as his ramrod, Ridge got a bill passed in December 1996. But the
bill did not resolve the question of billions of dollars of
``stranded costs'' _ money the utilities say they will lose from
past investments, especially in nuclear power plants, that will not
be economic in a competitive market for electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The size of stranded costs is important because it determines
how much rates can be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, that problem was turned over to the Pennsylvania
Public Utility Commission, which has been ruling, one utility at a
time, how much each can collect for stranded costs from all
customers over the next decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   The utility usually then sues, other parties intervene and then
talks are held for an out-of-court settlement.
</P>
<P>
   A good example is PECO Energy.
</P>
<P>
   It asked the utility commission for $7.5 billion in stranded
costs; the commission approved $4.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   PECO sued, and in the settlement talks that followed the
compromise was $5.26 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sonny Popowski, Pennsylvania's state consumer advocate, endorsed
the competition plan. But he said the utilities should have been
required to either sell their plants _ and thereby determine their
real market value _ or keep them without recovering stranded costs.
As it is, he said, the utilities want compensation for plants they
say are uneconomical but don't want to have to give them up.
</P>
<P>
   The plants may prove more valuable than initially thought.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cunningham, president of the Pennsylvania Electric
Association, said big industrial customers want to ensure a
reliable source of power by buying it from a company that has its
own power plant.
</P>
<P>
   And utilities, of course, have power plants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
