</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0393 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2326 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-POWERDEREG-SUMMAR     10-28 0304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-POWERDEREG-SUMMARY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas power deregulation: What might happen
 &HT;    (With TEX-POWERDEREG, TEX-POWERDEREG-PENN, TEX-POWERDEREG-CALIF.
Photos available. For Sun., Nov. 1. Moving on a and financial
wires.)
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ No one can predict how the Texas Legislature
could phase out regulation of electric utilities _ or even if it
will. But if Texas follows other states that have deregulated the
power industry, here's what could happen.
</P>
<P>
   What's likely to happen:
</P>
<P>
   _ Consumers and businesses could pick their own power providers
_ much like they do their long-distance telephone service providers
_ within a few years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Electricity prices may come down. In other industries that
went through deregulation, such as the airline industry, prices
dropped dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   _ The government would stop setting the price of power itself.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rules prohibiting practices such as slamming (changing
consumers' power suppliers when they don't want to switch) and
cramming (charging for services consumers don't want).
</P>
<P>
   What's not likely to happen:
</P>
<P>
   _ Choice in power providers probably wouldn't happen soon.
Legislators might well put off consumer choice until 2001, to let
utilities pay down debt on nuclear power plants and develop the
procedures necessary to let consumers switch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consumers and businesses probably wouldn't rush out to change
electricity providers. In many states that have already started to
deregulate their power industry, change has been slow.
</P>
<P>
   _ Utilities will not build new power lines or poles. Companies
would likely deliver electricity using existing lines and poles.
</P>
<P>
   _ State and local taxes would still be levied.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
