<HEADLINE>
ALL PIECES SLIP INTO PLACE FOR GLENN'S TRIUMPHANT RETURN TO SPACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Almost like magic, all of the ingredients
slipped into place Wednesday for the spectacle of John Glenn's
return to space Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of enthusiastic spectators, soon to be joined by
President Clinton, poured into the normally sedate communities of
aerospace workers next to NASA's sprawling Kennedy Space Center and
into the tourist enclaves that line Central Florida's sun-drenched
beaches.
</P>
<P>
   News media jammed into the press facilities, not so taxed since
America launched its first astronauts to the moon in 1969 and in
1988 rebounded from the Challenger tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an unlikely encore flight aboard the shuttle Discovery
by the man who became the first American to orbit the Earth nearly
37 years ago, spaceflight has achieved at least a temporary new
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn,77, is among an otherwise young, international crew of
seven set to blast off from Kennedy aboard the shuttle Discovery at
2 p.m., EST, although the unusually generous launch period spans 2
{ hours.
</P>
<P>
   NASA seemed eager to embrace the spectacle and to spotlight the
nine-day mission of varied experiments it has been patiently
brewing since Glenn was added to the flight crew last January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome the opportunity to showcase this program on the
space shuttle,'' said Bob Sieck, NASA's director of shuttle
operations at Kennedy. ``It's a natural resource, both the hardware
and the people. We're privileged to have the opportunity to
demonstrate these capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn circled the Earth three times in a Mercury capsule on Feb.
20, 1962, after four weather postponements and 11 different launch
dates.
</P>
<P>
   Better luck this time seemed his due.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we couldn't ask for better weather,'' meteorologist
Clif Stargardt said of the sunny skies, light winds and warm
temperatures. ``It looks like mother nature wants to see John Glenn
return to space just as much as the rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``rest of us'' include 21,000 family, friends and assorted
VIPS as well as Clinton and his entourage and at least 70 members
of Congress and their staffs and families, who will watch from
space center grounds. Area tourist agencies expected thousands more
to watch from the roadways, beaches and parks.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's wife, Annie, daughter, Lyn, son, David, and David's two
teen-age sons were to gather in the exclusive realm of the Launch
Control Center for the launch.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dignitaries are some of Glenn's former Mercury
colleagues, Scott Carpenter, Gordon Cooper and Wally Shirra as well
as Apollo 11 moonwalkers Buzz Aldrin, Peter Gordon and Alan Bean
and Baseball Hall of Famer Ted Williams, who served with Glenn as a
Marine Corps aviator during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Would the unusually intense scrutiny tempt NASA's launch and
mission control teams to act rashly? Top agency officials assured
it would not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I firmly believe that when crunch time comes, people in the
launch control center will not know there are 200 politicians, the
president and 3,700 news media people on the site,'' said Tommy
Holloway, NASA's shuttle program manager. ``They will do the same
job they do every day and make the same decisions they make every
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring sign of the flight's significance has been
heightened security. Security officers armed with semi-automatic
weapons checked the credentials of unfamiliar faces once, twice and
three times as they came through the gates with the workforce.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the news media have access to NASA's VIP sites during
the launch. For Glenn's mission they won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due obviously to what is going on in the world you have to be
more heightened with your security precautions,'' said Sieck.
``It's a common sense thing to do considering the environment, the
attention this is getting and what is going on in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Discovery commander Curt Brown and his crew, pilot Steve
Lindsey, flight engineer Scott Parazynski, payload commander Steve
Robinson, European Space Agency astronaut Pedro Duque, Japanese
astronaut Chiaki Mukai and Glenn met family and friends at their
launch pad on Wednesday and reviewed the procedures for boarding
the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Well before sunrise, shuttle managers were to convene to review
countdown preparations. If pleased with the progress and the
weather forecast, they will direct shuttle engineers to load
Discovery's huge fuel tank with a half million gallons of explosive
hydrogen and oxygen propellants.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle astronauts will be awakened shortly before sunrise,
dine and don their bright orange flight suits.
</P>
<P>
   When the fueling operation is complete, the astronauts will be
whisked to the launch pad in a gleaming silver motor home. They
should begin crawling aboard Discovery by midmorning.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect had Glenn and his colleagues in fine fettle on the
eve of lift off. ``They are in very, very good spirits,'' said
NASA's chief astronaut Charles Precourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, they are very relaxed when they get into the
vehicle,'' said Precourt. ``There won't be much in the way of
butterflies until they get within a few minutes of lift off.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 1958EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
