<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-STRAIGHT-TICKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF STRAIGHT-TICKET VOTING MAY BACKFIRE ON ILLINOIS GOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also sent in category `p')  
(See also ILL-GOV-RACE) 
(bl) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It was an old hard-nosed politician, Paddy Bauler, who
crowed defiantly, and accurately, in 1955, ``Chicago ain't ready
for reform.''
</P>
<P>
   But the good-government crowd, not-so-affectionately called
``goo-goos'' in some precincts here, has finally prevailed. One of
the staples of the Democratic machine _ one-punch, straight-ticket
voting _ will be absent on Election Day, after more than a century
of use.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when television advertisements have much more
political power than any precinct captain, the end of
straight-ticket voting illustrates the weakening grip of parties on
the political process.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans here had quite a bit to do with this, as well.
When they briefly controlled the state Legislature, the Republicans
in 1997 pushed through a bill that banned the one-punch system in
Illinois. But now Republicans are wondering whether it might
backfire downstate and in the suburbs, where voters have become
adept at punching the Republican straight-ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The single, straight-ticket punch was perfected by Democratic
Party organizations in big cities, where loyalty to the machine
meant jobs and other favors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was sold as a way for immigrants to make their votes
count,'' said Paul Green, a political science professor at
Governor's State University in Chicago and the author of several
books on Chicago politics. Nearly 20 states still allow voting a
straight-ticket with a single stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Under Mayor Anton Cermak, who brought the fabled Chicago machine
to power in the 1930s, the straight-ticket fostered loyalty among
party workers and voters. Cermak, who adopted a one-for-all
philosophy, would analyze the voter turnout in Chicago
neighborhoods and rank his top ward committeemen _ a rating system
not unlike the Top 20 for college football. A familiar battle cry
of Cermak went: ``Only lazy precinct captains steal.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of single-punch voting saw it as a way to keep voters in
the dark about candidates. David Starrett, a spokesman for the
Independent Voters of Illinois, a nonpartisan group that calls for
election reforms, said voters ``ought to think about individual
candidates and do their homework,'' rather than simply depend on
the party label.
</P>
<P>
   He said the single-punch system made it much easier for party
bosses to punish people who did not tow the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take very long to make a single punch, and if a
voter was in the booth taking his time, the precinct captain would
make note of it,'' Starrett said. ``Questions got asked. Sometimes
garbage didn't get picked up.''
</P>
<P>
   It was part of the tight-fisted control that extended even to
campaign volunteers. Milton Rakove, the late political science
professor at the University of Illinois in Chicago, once used a
familiar political slogan for a book title, ``We Don't Want Nobody
Nobody Sent.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, the rules went, people looking for jobs in city
government or campaigns had to come with an endorsement from
someone on the inside. That power is largely gone.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard M. Daley, son of the legendary boss of the
Democratic machine, ``has not addressed a ward organization in
years,'' said Green, the political science professor.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of straight-ticket voting could mean longer lines at
the polls in Chicago, where voters will encounter a ballot with
more than 100 questions, including 33 political offices, 72 judges
up for retention, a state constitutional issue and, in some
precincts, a referendum on whether to ban alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody has a longer ballot than we do,'' said
Tom Leach, a spokesman for the Board of Elections in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois law requires that voters spend no more than 10 minutes
in the booth, no more than 5 minutes if there is a line. With more
than 100 decisions, voters would need to hurry. But the state
elections board has issued an advisory, Leach said, not to enforce
the time limit, unless someone is intentionally trying to keep
others from voting.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Andrea Moore, a sponsor of the bill to end the
one-punch system, said the old style gave too much power to party
bosses. The change could help some Republicans in strongly
Democratic Cook County, which includes Chicago, but she
acknowledged that some Republicans in other places are not so eager
to see the system changed.
</P>
<P>
   In some suburban counties, she noted, perhaps one-third of
voters have cast a straight-Republican ballot. ``Not all
Republicans thought this was such a good idea,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Brunner, the head of the Better Government Association in
Chicago, said precinct captains years ago sometimes went into the
booth with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``A precinct captain would say, `Hey, Mrs. Jones, remember how I
took care of that ticket?''' Brunner said. ``And then he'd say,
`You're a good Democrat, right? Do you know how to operate this
machine? Let me help you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Brunner, who has long been a champion of election reforms in
Chicago, said the old system, for all its warts, was not without
its merits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, the machines were kind of confusing,'' Brunner
said, ``and somebody like Mrs. Jones really did want to vote for
the Democrats.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 2004EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
