<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-PREPARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE PIONEERS WISH ONE OF THEIR OWN GOOD LUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Three men who taught American
schoolchildren how to count backward gave a confident but
cautionary sendoff to John Glenn, the fourth survivor of their
dwindling band of space legends, as NASA and the astronaut-senator
made final preparatons for Thursday's historic launch.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneering spacemen Scott Carpenter, Walter Schirra, and L.
Gordon Cooper gathered Wednesday at the Astronaut Hall of Fame just
outside John F. Kennedy Space Center to cheer their Project Mercury
colleague and to offer their hard-won perspective on sitting atop
towers of explosive force.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a lot of people don't realize is that those of us who fly
these machines, and this applies also to John Glenn ... feel that
we are expendable in pursuit of a higher purpose,'' said Carpenter,
who in 1962 coined the phrase, ``Godspeed, John Glenn,'' just
before his friend became the first American to orbit Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he or anyone else perishes in this pursuit, we will recover
from that,'' Carpenter added, silencing a crowd of reporters and
tourists. ``We always have, and we always will.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the gates of the space center, NASA officials kept up
their ``all systems go'' optimism and described a nearly flawless
prelaunch regimen, accompanied by calm, clear skies. NASA
meteorologists said there was a ``0 percent'' chance the 2 p.m.
flight would be scrubbed because of weather.
</P>
<P>
   Now and again, though, cracks appeared in the sang-froid of the
men and women who routinely thrust themselves and their colleagues
into space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel an awesome responsibility and apprehension that
everything goes well. This is special,'' NASA Associate
Administrator Joe Rothenberg said after eating lunch with Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg compared the pressure and attention to the 1986
Challenger flight that ended with the deaths of New Hampshire
teacher Christa McAuliffe and six other crew members. Though NASA
officials are loath to say so publicly, looming in the background
is the knowledge that another catastrophe on such a high-profile
effort could threaten future space missions, most notably the
International Space Station.
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible to escape the anticipation here on the Space
Coast, with President Clinton, three-score members of Congress, and
numerous celebrities expected to join an estimated 250,000 other
observers on hand here _ and millions more watching live on
television. Parks were already beginning to fill Wednesday, as
space watchers jockeyed for the best viewing spots.
</P>
<P>
   As preparations reached a fevered pitch, Payload Specialist No.
2, also known as John Glenn, had permission to sleep late this
morning, at least when compared with the last time he blasted into
space.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn and the six other crew members were to be awakened at 7:50
a.m. to begin final preparations. Joining him in space will be
commander Curtis L. Brown; pilot Steven W. Lindsey; mission
specialists Stephen K. Robinson, Pedro Duque of Spain, and Scott E.
Parazynski, the medical officer; and Payload Specialist No. 1,
Chiaki Mukai of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The 77-year-old Glenn's return to space has overshadowed the
mission _ intended to carry out a broad range of scientific
experiments and to release and recapture a satellite _ and has sent
commentators into paroxysms of nostalgia as they try to convey the
uncertainty, excitement, and national pride that accompanied
Glenn's historic first flight, on Feb. 20, 1962.
</P>
<P>
   That day, Glenn awoke at 2:20 a.m., ate a breakfast of steak and
eggs washed down by orange juice and coffee, then proceeded to
board the Mercury capsule Friendship 7 for his brief but momentous
ride.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Glenn and his crewmates were on ``teenagers'
hours,'' said astronaut Charles Precourt, who flew Discovery's last
mission in June and is acting as liaison between Glenn and the news
media. Precourt said the shuttle crew began L-1, space parlance for
launch minus one day, by eating breakfast around 9 a.m., before yet
another preflight briefing session.
</P>
<P>
   They then visited the launch pad, where Glenn and the others
waved, smiled, and gave thumbs-up signals to family members and
busloads of tourists and NASA guests wishing them farewell. The
astronauts stayed some 20 feet from the crowd, in keeping with a
quarantine designed to keep them free of colds and flu.
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, they underwent a training session on donning their
space suits and finding their places in the shuttle, Precourt said.
Glenn has the worst seat for sightseeing, between Robinson and
Mukai in the back row.
</P>
<P>
   Precourt said the crew members were in ``top-notch shape, right
on top of it'' and were joking about the crush of publicity, all of
it focused on their lowest-ranking crew member. Lindsey kidded
Glenn that he would be the next one honored, with a NASA trash bin
named the Lindsey Dumpster, Precourt said.
</P>
<P>
   Prelaunch breakfast was scheduled to be a ``crew's choice''
affair, though Precourt said some or all might skip the meal
because of one of the countless pieces of knowledge gained since
Glenn's first flight: more than half of all space travelers suffer
nausea after blastoff.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast and a weather briefing, the crew will suit up
and walk out to a van that will take them to the launch pad. They
will be guided to their positions, and then the shuttle's hatch
will be closed behind them. They will then have at least 1 1/2
hours to reflect on their missions and their mortality.
</P>
<P>
   Both those subjects were on the minds of Carpenter, Cooper, and
Schirra Wednesday, in part because three other members of the
original Mercury Seven did not live to see their erstwhile leader
return to space.
</P>
<P>
   Virgil ``Gus'' Grissom died in 1967 aboard an Apollo rocket that
caught fire on a NASA launch pad; Donald ``Deke'' Slayton died of
cancer in 1993; and Alan Shepard died of leukemia earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's surviving colleagues said cooly that they had no
particular interest in joining Glenn, but when asked what they
would be feeling during the nine-day mission, the three said almost
simultaneously, ``envy.'' Cooper also offered himself up as a
volunteer for an eventual Mars mission.
</P>
<P>
   In the four decades before his first space flight, as well as
the nearly four decades until Thursday, Glenn has continually
burnished his reputation as an American hero.
</P>
<P>
   A stoic son of Cambridge, Ohio, who married his grammar school
sweetheart, Glenn took his first steps toward glory as a Marine
pilot during World War II, winning three Distinguished Flying
Crosses. He also served in Korea, flying 90 missions and downing
three enemy fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's first taste of celebrity came in 1957, when he became
the first man to fly coast to coast faster than the speed of sound.
He parlayed that triumph into an appearance on a television game
show, during which the guitar-playing pilot won $10,000 by
displaying an uncanny knowledge of pop music.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief flirtation with anonymity, spent designing fighter
jets, Glenn returned to the public eye when the United States began
its full-scale space competition with the Soviet Union. After his
1962 orbits and the ticker-tape parades that followed, it became
clear that his dream of further missions and a moon trip would
never be realized. So he resigned from the astronaut corps. Among
the Mercury Seven, only he and Carpenter were denied a return trip
to space.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn then became a top executive with cola-maker Royal Crown
International before winning election to the US Senate as a
Democrat in 1974. Once there, he worked doggedly to reduce nuclear
proliferation, which he considered the biggest threat to the watery
globe he gazed upon from space.
</P>
<P>
   Never poetically inclined, Glenn has tried countless times to
describe his brief earlier trip to space. The best he could muster
immediately afterward was to call it ``a real fireball of a ride.''
But he may have described his mission best in an interview he gave
before that day in 1962:
</P>
<P>
   ``We are placed here with certain talents and capabilities,''
Glenn said. ``It is up to each one of us to use those talents and
capabilities as best we can. If we do that, I think there is a
power greater than any of us that will place the opportunities in
our way, a power greater than I am that will certainly see that I
am taken care of if I do my part of the bargain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
