<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BARR-ART-NYT &LR;      10-28 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BARR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON NEMESIS VOICES DOUBT ON SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (See also CLINTON-IMPEACH, sent in category `w') 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARIETTA, Ga. _ The humorlessness of Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., the
scowling conservative who started the drive to impeach President
Clinton, was being celebrated by hometown supporters in a political
roast, and Barr agreed that they had a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am smiling,'' he declared in a poker-faced joke on himself
even as he was stoking fresh scorn for an unlikely target: his
Republican colleagues in the Senate who he fears lack the
``backbone'' for an impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``How little interest, how little backbone they have to really
take on tough issues,'' Barr complained in an interview, offering a
concession of sorts from atop the impeachment ramparts that the
campaign might ultimately founder as a one-house effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the Senate, with the current makeup, really
has the stomach for it,'' said Barr, the impeachment stalwart on
the House Judiciary Committee, offering a stark assessment of the
difficulty Republicans anticipate when they resume their effort
after Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton will declare victory no matter what happens,'' Barr
said, finally smiling at what strikes him as the absurdity of the
president's apparent invincibility in opinion polls and the
proclivity of Republicans to ``cave'' and play into his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Clinton magic mystery tour,'' Barr conceded, sounding
as frustrated as Wile E. Coyote in pursuit of the presidential
Roadrunner. ``It's a wonder to behold what this guy can do with
Republicans. We knock him down and then we pull him up and say,
`Sorry, may we dust off your coat?' ''
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday night's fund-raising roast, Barr was celebrated as a
vital patriot by actor Charlton Heston and a host of other
right-wing celebrities who proclaimed the nation's right to ``keep
and bear Bob Barr'' _ a play on Barr's serving as congressional
point man for the National Rifle Association, which Heston heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressman Barr has promised me that I'll get to arrest
Hillary,'' exulted another roaster, Gary Aldrich, the former White
House FBI agent who has been disparaging the Clintons as a book
writer and speaker on the conservative circuit. Dinner guests
guffawed as he brandished handcuffs before Barr, a former federal
prosecutor who first made his anti-corruption reputation here by
bringing down politicians in both parties.
</P>
<P>
   The 49-year-old Barr faces the world with a dark mustache and
steady glare that Clintonites rate villainous but supporters hail
as vigilance personified. He first sampled the intrigues of
Washington as a lobbyist for the Central Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton has abused the office entrusted to him,'' said Barr,
who made the president a target for impeachment well before the
Lewinsky sex scandal, accusing him of abusing campaign finance laws
and the justice system.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the dinner laughter, Barr signaled serious concern that
House Republicans might go through the struggle of impeaching the
president only to see the effort fail because of what he said was
indifference in the GOP-controlled Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we fulfill our duty in the House and the Senate fails to
fulfill theirs, shame on them,'' Barr said, adding that the
Senate's recent rejection of a House-approved tax cut was evidence
of timidity toward contentious issues like impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not to say the votes could not be there if Trent Lott
really worked the issue,'' Barr said of the Senate majority leader,
although he calculated that it would take noticeable Republican
gains in the election on Tuesday to prod greater Senate interest in
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about alternatives to impeachment, like a reprimand of the
president, Barr scoffed at such compromises as ``constitutional
nonsense.'' He dismissed as ``half-baked'' former President Gerald
Ford's proposal that the president stand before the Congress and be
verbally rebuked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Clinton could even keep a straight face,'' Barr
said, grinning at the notion of trying to scold a man who has
lately been gladly embracing every chance at atonement.
</P>
<P>
   As the roasters performed, the difficulty of skewering Clinton _
after all the months of late-night television humor and his
considerable display of resiliency _ became clear. An old chestnut
of a joke, not another risque Lewinsky one-liner, drew one of the
bigger Republican laughs: ``None of this would have happened if Al
Gore were still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating,'' Barr said of his goal to topple the
president, before taking the dais to be teased by sympathetic
partisans. These included a Bill Clinton imitator who fecklessly
grinned upon the pro-impeachment audience and serenaded Barr with
this advice: ``Smile, though you're heart is breaking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
