<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     THE OPRAH BACKLASH
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Oprah Winfrey &LR; 's the most powerful person in show business,
says Entertainment Weekly, with a top-rated talk show, a widely
acclaimed movie and her picture on the cover of Vogue magazine. Now
watch the tables turn:
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so over Oprah,'' wrote New York Post film critic
 &UR; Thelma Adams &LR; , who was quoted in the Times of London.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winfrey should have chosen another theme song this year,
`You're So Vain,''' wrote  &UR; Hal Boedeker &LR;  of the Orlando Sentinel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the way she's promoting herself that's discouraging,''
wrote  &UR; Richard Roeper &LR;  in a  &LR; Winfrey's hometown paper, the Chicago
Sun-Times. ``Can a person do good while constantly drawing
attention to her efforts?''
</P>
<P>
   Under particular fire is Winfrey's revamped talk show, ``Change
Your Life TV,'' described by TV writer  &UR; Jeff MacGregor &LR;  as
``devoted to the mind-numbing cliches of personal improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am defined by the world as a talk-show host,'' she said on
one show. ``But I am spirit, connected to the greater spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   She referred to ``Beloved,'' the movie in which she stars, as
``my `Schindler's List.' I know they're all applauding somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's worrisome about the '99-model Oprah is this,'' wrote
MacGregor: ``She's begun to take herself seriously. Self-reference
is one thing. Self-reverence is another.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; VISUALIZE LETTUCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The secret of  &UR; Alice Waters &LR; ' newfound ease at public
appearances, writes  &UR; Lee Glickstein &LR;  in ``Be Heard Now! Tap Into
Your Inner Speaker and Communicate With Ease'' (Broadway; $20), is
that she imagines her listeners to be heads of lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   The author says he told the restaurateur to treat her audience
the way she treats food she is about to prepare. When facing a head
of lettuce, he said to her, ``I'll bet you place it gently on the
board and honor it with respect and love before you cut into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Glickstein told her that she should ``look at the faceless mass
in the audience as she would regard a roomful of heads of lettuce.
... To take at least 15 seconds of silence'' before speaking ``to
honor those fresh faces, appreciate their beauty and breathe with
them. Then speak to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The technique worked, writes the coach. ``Eventually, any device
that helps you get there, whether it is seeing your audience as
heads of lettuce, hearts of artichoke or souls of sweetness, will
dissolve out when you get comfortable with opening every talk with
just you and them and the silence.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - NASA is so determined to capture the imagination of the public
with the Discovery launch that  &UR; Garth Brooks &LR; ,  &UR; Leonardo &LR; 
 &UR; DiCaprio &LR;  and the members of Aerosmith were invited to a prelaunch
VIP party. ``We're really psyched about this,'' said Aerosmith's
 &UR; Joe Perry  &LR; to the Boston Herald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Nancy Reagan &LR; 's Secret Service men occupied two cubicles, on
either side of her, when she had a facial in New York the other
day. The New York Daily News said they passed the time ``reading
magazines and talking to each other on their hand radios.''
</P>
<P>
   - In answer to Esquire's annual Women We Love feature, the
lesbian magazine Girlfriends is out with ``The Purely Platonic
Lesbian Men We Love'' issue. Among the honorees: ``The San
Francisco 49ers National Football League team. Currently run by ...
 &UR; Denise DeBartolo York &LR;  (who has proven, much to her brother
 &UR; Eddie &LR; 's dismay, that she's more than his corporate puppet), the
49ers are the first -- and only -- National Football League team to
offer domestic-partner benefits to gay employees.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Woody Allen  &LR; didn't let sentiment get in the way when he
talked with Marie- &LR;  Claire magazine about his ex,  &UR; Mia Farrow &LR; . ``I
would challenge Mia's view of herself as a supermother,'' he said.
``She compulsively goes through these manic adoptions even though
she doesn't know where her next job is coming from. ... There are
many horrible things I could say if I wanted to go into detail, but
I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   - Newly former White House spokesman  &UR; Mike McCurry &LR;  will do
election-night analysis for CNN. His counterpart will be  &UR; Tony &LR; 
 &UR; Blankley &LR; , who used to be spokesman for  &UR; Newt Gingrich &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Al Gore has been 50 for at least 30 years. He's someone who &LR; 
 &UR; early on abandoned any pretense of being cool.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Dave Barry &LR; , &LR;  whose new book is ``Dave Barry Turns 50,'' in
New Choices magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
