<HEADLINE>
ALTERNATIVE SCHOOL TAILORS STUDY TO THE STUDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Sporting a shaved head, wire-rim glasses,
faded jeans, T-shirt and feet that would be completely bare if not
for the toe ring, instructor Keven Holt sits at the end of a table,
patiently waiting. The five students seated around him are
pondering ways to prevent terrorists from hunting endangered marine
animals within a mile of their countries' coastline, which has been
designated a no-hunting zone by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Holland Purcell, 13, suggests everything from employing netting
made from plastic six-pack holders to using papier-mache decoys.
Erin Clay, 16, suggests that Navy SEALS handle the situation. Ben
Willeng, 16, takes a more level-headed approach. ``We could just
try to talk with them,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This search for peaceful solutions to worldwide problems may be
atypical at public schools, but it is characteristic of The Tree of
Knowledge, a new Arlington school billed as ``a holistic and
alternative educational approach.'' It's a concept born from the
core of Arlington's holistic community, a group of folks who
believe in soundness of body and mind achieved through
spirituality, herbs, healthful foods and other alternative methods.
Among the community are parents who believe that public schools are
not offering the things they think are vital to education: an
environment of free expression and small classes.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Holt and Mindy Purcell, 38, mother of Holland and
owner of the holistic shop Deep Woods Apothecary, tossed around the
idea of a holistic school for junior high and high school students.
``We thought it would be good to have a school with a more holistic
approach to education, where maybe kids feel good about learning
and good about themselves,'' Purcell says.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, 32, has bachelor's and master's degrees in anthropology
from the University of Texas at Arlington and has taught at UTA and
at Amarillo College in Amarillo, where he grew up. He believes
public schools use a memorize-and-regurgitate method of teaching.
``Thinking is not a part of the curriculum,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Also involved was Jim Koch, 43, Purcell's partner of
four-and-a-half years. The three became the school's board and
began researching ways to bring it to life. They designed
brochures, held fund-raisers and rented space, a small
three-bedroom house in central Arlington that also serves as a
community center for the United Assembly of Unbeaten Paths, a group
that offers spiritual guidance, services and events, such as Friday
night drumming circles.
</P>
<P>
   Spirituality figures prominently in the school's mission. Holt,
whose parents were organic farmers, wants the school to be open to
any religion, but it has so far attracted primarily families with
alternative beliefs. The students ``should have a right to practice
their religions freely. By allowing them that freedom, it will
teach the kids religious tolerance,'' he says. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holt describes his beliefs as ``a nature-based spirituality of
European origins. ... I guess you could probably call me a pagan.''
Purcell, who also grew up in a holistic home and once lived a
peripatetic life with the ``rainbow people,'' describes herself as
``following a path of spiritual light and love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I FELT LIKE A LAB RAT''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Home Education Research Institute,
approximately 1.5 million children in the United States are
home-schooled _ taught by their mothers or fathers. That's five
times the estimated number in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   And although The Tree of Knowledge is technically a private
school, the children aren't taught exclusively at home by their
parents. This type of small, alternative schooling is catching on
in much the same way as home-schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Nagel, National Office Manager for the National Coalition of
Alernative Community Schools, a group that formed in the mid-'70s
to support any type of education that is not publicy funded and now
has 300 member schools, says that thousands of alternative schools
operate in this country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFFORDING ALTERNATIVES
</P>
<P>
   The curriculum is based on a philosophy of ``unschooling,''
which allows students to build their education based on their
interests and curiosities. ``Once you fuel that curiosity and find
out how each student works, we start with an accredited college
prep program, which is more of a classical education system,'' Holt
says.
</P>
<P>
   Students fill out learning objective sheets at the beginning of
the semester, and then their basic skills are evaluated with tests.
Next, textbooks and core curriculum are plotted.
</P>
<P>
   According to the state of Texas, home-schooling has to cover the
three R's, plus civics, or good citizenship. Students at The Tree
of Knowledge are expected to fulfill 100 hours of
volunteer/community work a semester. During the week, the seven
students work on group projects or in workbooks. On Fridays, they
usually have a field trip or activity, such as a trip to the
Arlington Museum of Art, mask making or watching ``Amistad'' and
holding a mock trial based on what they have observed in the movie.
After this particular activity, student Erin Clay became interested
in civil law and said she plans to pursue that course of study.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of families who want to home-school their kids,
but the parents have to work. This will provide that option,'' Holt
says.
</P>
<P>
   Parents pay $100 per month tuition, which pays for rent and
utilities. Holt, who is not paid, supplements his income by waiting
tables at night. At the school, he is counselor, mentor and friend
to his students.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Willeng, a tarot-card reader and owner of Fort Worth's
Timberwolf Construction Co., enrolled her son Issac in The Tree of
Knowledge after three years of home-schooling. ``He couldn't read
or write until I started home-schooling,'' she says. Willeng has
two other children, a son who was salutatorian at Lady Margaret
Roper School at St. Thomas Moore Institute, and a daughter, Lisha,
14, who attends Paschal High School, where she is on the
second-team volleyball squad and was a conscientious objector in
biology class when it came to dissecting a cat. ``Social
interaction was very important to her. She doesn't need'' The Tree
of Knowledge,'' Willeng says.
</P>
<P>
   Issac does need the school, she says. ``Everybody has different
needs, and sometimes alternatives need to be met.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
