<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2387 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-CAPSULES-TEX     10-28 3003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-CAPSULES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL CAPSULES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (6-1) AT GREEN BAY (5-2) Time: 3:15 p.m., Sunday
Site: Lambeau Field, Green Bay, Wis. (60,790) Series: 49ers lead
25-22-1 Last season: At Packers 23, 49ers 10, NFC Championship Game
Line: Green Bay by 3
</P>
<P>
   49ers update: A little history is in order here. In each of the
past three seasons, the 49ers have faced Green Bay in the playoffs,
and each time the 49ers' season ended right then. Think there might
be a little motivation in the San Francisco locker room? Not that
league's most dominating offensive team needs it. QB Steve Young's
20 TD passes are by far the most in the NFL, and WRs Jerry Rice,
Terrell Owens and J.J. Stokes all have more than 30 catches _ Rice
and Owens have already broken the 500-yard mark. And don't forget
the running game, led by Garrison Hearst's 4.7 yards per carry.
Defense was a problem early, but that's changed. DT Bryant Young
leads a unit that has recorded a league-best 31 sacks and allows
opposing passer a skimpy .523 completion percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Packers update: Is the slump over? Hard to tell after last
week's less-than-dominating performance in a 28-10 victory against
Baltimore. QB Brett Favre accounted for three TDs, but he also
threw two more interceptions, giving him 11 in his past four games.
Favre always has been something of a feast-or-famine sort, but for
a guy who threw 16 picks all last year, that's an ugly stretch. One
thing that has hurt the three-time MVP is the Pack's lack of a
running game, which puts the entire offensive load on the shoulders
of Favre and his marvelous WRs, led by Antonio Freeman, the league
leader in receiving yards. On the other side, nobody runs on Green
Bay (except maybe Barry Sanders), but the secondary showed some
vulnerability in shocking back-to-back losses to Minnesota and
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Key matchup: Green Bay's offensive line, led by T Ross Verba and
G Adam Timmerman, will be under the gun against sack artists Roy
Barker, Chris Doleman and Young, who have combined to drop QBs 22
times this year. Given Favre's recent struggles, keeping him
upright and giving him time to scan the field is essential. And
opening up some holes for RB Travis Jervey would be nice, too.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: 49ers 37, Packers 31 ARIZONA (3-4) AT DETROIT (2-5) Time:
Noon, Sunday Site: Pontiac Silverdome, Pontiac, Mich. (80,368)
Series: Lions lead 27-17-5 The line: Detroit by 6
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals update: Take a team nearly devoid of offense and take
away its best defensive players and you've got a mess. You also
have the Cardinals, who are still waiting for QB Jake Plummer to
become the star all the experts said he would be and now have to
play without Pro Bowl DT Eric Swann, who is out indefinitely
following arthroscopic knee surgery. Plummer, who has been sacked
25 times and has thrown 11 interceptions, isn't going to outscore
anyone working behind Arizona's tissue-paper line, and without
Swann, the Cards aren't likely to stop anyone, either.
</P>
<P>
   Lions update: Sure, Barry Sanders leads the NFC in rushing, WR
Herman Moore is the conference's No. 1 receiver and QB Charlie
Batch in rising quickly in the rankings. But the Lions are 2-5 in
large part because they've been penalized 60 times for 542 yards
this year. That's tough to take for coach Bobby Ross, who hasn't
finished a season below .500 since leaving The Citadel in 1977. If
they fall that far this year, it would be a waste of another
spectacular season for Sanders, who last week posted his 72nd
career 100-yard game, five behind all-time leader Walter Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Lions 21, Cardinals 13
DENVER (7-0) AT CINCINNATI (2-5) Time: Noon, Sunday Site: Cinergy
Field, Cincinnati (60,389) Series: Broncos lead 13-6 Line: Denver
by 11
</P>
<P>
   Broncos update: As if they weren't unstoppable enough, the
Broncos last week unveiled another weapon: Howitzer-range field
goals from K Jason Elam. So who needs those Elway and Davis guys,
anyway? OK, so they're pretty good, too, what with Terrell Davis
joining Jim Brown and O.J. Simpson as the only RBs to break 1,000
yards in seven games and QB John Elway cruising along with a sweet
99.6 passer rating. Still, when the Hall of Fame called this week,
it was to request the shoe Elam used to boot his record-tying
63-yarder. Sorry guys. Call back in February. He's still using it
right now.
</P>
<P>
   Bengals update: Time to put a few things in perspective. The
Bengals haven't had a winning season since 1990 and are 38-81 in
that span. Of the 29 October games they've played since '91, they
have won just three, part of a ghastly 11-52 record before the
season's midpoint. They've allowed league-worst 401.9 yards a game,
and their next three opponents _ Denver, Jacksonville and Minnesota
_ are a combined 19-2. Any questions?
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Broncos 49, Bengals 17
</P>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE (5-2) AT BALTIMORE (2-5) Time: Noon, Sunday Site:
Ravens Stadium at Camden Yards, Baltimore (68,400) Series: Jaguars
lead 5-0 Line: Jacksonville by 31/2
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars update: The road is getting long for the Jags, who play
away from home for the third week in a row. Their two previous
trips turned an unbeaten team in control of the AFC Central into a
slumping group that has dropped into a tie with Pittsburgh thanks
to consecutive losses. Now, heading into Baltimore to face the
Ravens isn't exactly as intimidating as last week's trip to Mile
High Stadium, but at this point, the Jags will take nothing for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens update: It didn't take long for things to get ugly for
the Ravens, who are now back to floundering at QB, with Eric Zeier
and Jim Harbaugh trading ineffective performances, while getting
little out of rookie RB Priest Holmes. Nowhere have the Ravens been
as punchless as in the red zone, having scored only 2 TDs in 13
possessions inside the 20. That's 15.4 percent, easily the NFL's
lowest.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Jaguars 30, Ravens 10
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (5-2) AT BUFFALO (4-3) Time: Noon, Sunday Site: Rich
Stadium, Orchard Park, N.Y. (80.024) Series: Dolphins lead 42-22-1
Line: Buffalo by 2
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins update: They've got arguably the greatest passer in
football history. So why are the Dolphins near the bottom in
passing yards? Because the Miami offense has rung up huge numbers
for years without getting to the Super Bowl, so coach Jimmy Johnson
is ready to try something else. That something is defense. Miami
has been immovable, especially at home, where they have allowed
just one touchdown in four games. But to be a championship team,
the Fish are going to have to get it done on the road, where they
have allowed 63 of their league-low 79 points and lost twice.
</P>
<P>
   Bills update: All hail Doug Flutie, who has made believers of us
all. Amazing how when Flutie starts playing like the second coming
of Fran Tarkenton (only better), starting QB Rob Johnson's injury
is suddenly worse than first thought. Coincidence? You decide.
Flutie's renaissance has led the Bills to an improbable four-game
winning streak, putting them into a three-way tie for second in the
AFC East, just a game behind Miami. A win Sunday might shut down
the city of Buffalo for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Bills 17, Dolphins 13
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND (4-3) AT INDIANAPOLIS (1-6) Time: Noon, Sunday Site:
RCA Dome, Indianapolis (60,599) Series: Tied 33-33 Line: No line
</P>
<P>
   Patriots update: There is no question the Patriots are the AFC
East's most talented team. But much of that talent will likely be
on the sidelines again this week. QB Drew Bledsoe is terrific, but
with WRs Terry Glenn, Vincent Brisby and Troy Brown out with
injuries, all that's left to throw to are nonentities like Tony
Simmons and Anthony Ladd. This week, Willie McGinest, Brandon
Mitchell and Chad Eaton could all be missing from the defense.
That's a lot to be without, even against a last-place team.
</P>
<P>
   Colts update: Almost halfway through his first season, QB Peyton
Manning is beginning to remind us why he was the first pick in the
draft. In his last start, he led the Colts to 31 points and a near
upset of mighty San Francisco. And most important, he did not throw
an interception for the first time in his young career. He still
leads the league with 14 picks, but looks more polished every time
out. Behind an offensive line that has allowed just 12 sacks all
year, a maturing Manning could be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Patriots 27, Colts 21
</P>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS (4-3) AT CAROLINA (0-7) Time: Noon, Sunday Site:
Ericsson Stadium, Charlotte, N.C. (73,248) Series: Panthers lead
4-3 Line: Carolina by 3
</P>
<P>
   Saints update: Does anyone know exactly what it is that the
Saints are good at? They're 11th in the NFC in total offense and
27th in the league in total defense. They have no player ranked
among the NFC's top 10 in rushing, passing or receiving. Their best
OL, T William Roaf, is out with a knee injury. But thanks to a
secondary that has pulled in 11 interceptions and reliable K Doug
Brien, the Saints are above .500, even with Billy Joe Tolliver as
the QB du jour. Or will Kerry Collins make his New Orleans debut
against the team he quit on three weeks ago?
</P>
<P>
   Panthers update: Surely the Panthers have to win sooner or
later, don't they? That's what the oddsmakers must have been
thinking when they installed Carolina as a slight favorite at home.
But the law of averages doesn't apply when a team is as banged up
and snakebit and demoralized as the Panthers. Carolina's defense is
in shambles, especially against the run, and the offense has turned
the ball over 18 times. One of these days, the Panthers will
probably win, but until then, the safe pick is against them.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Saints 16, Panthers 6
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA (7-0) AT TAMPA BAY (3-4) Time: Noon, Sunday Site:
Raymond James Stadium, Tampa, Fla. (65,000) Series: Vikings lead
28-13 Line: Minnesota by 6
</P>
<P>
   Vikings update: I know what you're thinking. Maybe if those
Vikings would turn the ball over once in awhile, they'd be
beatable. Forget it. Last Sunday, QB Randall Cunningham threw his
first two interceptions of the season and RB Robert Smith fumbled
for the first time in more than two years, and the Vikes still
drilled Detroit. Even with all that, Minnesota has given the ball
away just nine times this year, fewest in the NFC, and their
plus-seven turnover margin is also the conference's best.
</P>
<P>
   Buccaneers update: On the other hand ... The Bucs' minus-seven
turnover margin among the worst in the NFC, ahead of only
Washington's hideous minus-13, which is only part of their growing
list of offensive problems. Topping that list is QB Trent Dilfer,
who might as well not even be on the field for all the good he does
_ the Bucs average a mere 155.3 passing yards per game, last in the
NFC. The league's No. 3 defense can only take this team so far.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Vikings 34, Buccaneers 9
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK GIANTS (3-4) AT WASHINGTON (0-7) Time: Noon, Sunday
Site: Jack Kent Cooke Stadium, Raljon, Md. (78,600) Series: Giants
lead 75-52-4 Line: New York by 21/2
</P>
<P>
   Giants update: For all their struggles, the Giants are still
just a game behind first-place Dallas in the NFC East, and a
victory Sunday would set up a showdown for the division lead next
week at Texas Stadium. In the meantime, the Giants figure to feast
on Washington's propensity for turnovers, especially since the
fierce New York rush (30 sacks), led by DE Michael Strahan, will
batter whichever QB the Redskins decide to throw out there into
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Redskins update: Trent Green? Gus Frerotte? What's the
difference, really? Both QBs have been awful this year. Not that
that makes them unique among the Redskins, who have had pitiful
performances from much of their roster, most notably the defense.
Not only have they given up more rushing yards than any NFC team,
but they have also taken the ball away just four times in seven
games, by far the league low. By the way, Green starts this week,
as if it matters.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Giants 23, Redskins 17
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (2-5) AT ATLANTA (5-2) Time: Noon, Sunday Site:
Georgia Dome, Atlanta (71,228) Series: Rams lead 39-21-2 Line: No
line
</P>
<P>
   Rams update: The sky is falling in St. Louis, where the home
fans are booing QB Tony Banks, key players such as WR Isaac Bruce,
T Orlando Pace and RB Amp Lee are injured and rookie special-teamer
Leonard Little is up on involuntary manslaughter charges after
slamming his car into that of a woman, killing her. Police said
Little was legally drunk at the time. Amazingly, he is expected to
play Sunday. Not that it will help the Rams, who are more than a
bit wobbly themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons update: What a feel-good story Steve DeBerg was last
week, becoming the world's oldest starting QB at age 44. But it
didn't feel so good to DeBerg, who's still sore after being sacked
five times and throwing for just 114 yards in an ugly loss to the
Jets. The real starter, Chris Chandler, may be back in time for
Sunday, which would make the Falcons look more like the
playoff-bound team they are.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Falcons 26, Rams 13
</P>
<P>
   TENNESSEE (3-4) AT PITTSBURGH (5-2) Time: Noon, Sunday Site:
Three Rivers Stadium, Pittsburgh (59,600) Series: Steelers lead
35-20 Line: None
</P>
<P>
   Oilers update: Hey, can we get a kicker on the field? No, Al Del
Greco, just one. Del Greco's colossal goof last Sunday took away a
realistic chance to kick a game-tying field goal and the Oilers'
two-game winning streak came screeching to a halt. But the reason
for those victories _ a suddenly inspired Eddie George _ was still
there even in defeat, and that suddenly makes Tennessee a much
tougher opponent. After a horrendous start, George has now rushed
for 365 yards in his past three games, rising to fourth in the AFC
and pulling the Oilers along with him.
</P>
<P>
   Steelers update: Talk about doing it with smoke and mirrors. The
Steelers rank a miserable 13th in the AFC in total offense and are
last in the league in passing. Their one-time star QB, Kordell
Stewart, has thrown for just 929 yards and has a chilly 55.9
rating. RB Jerome Bettis has played well but is hardly having his
best year, and the defense ranks in the middle of the pack. How,
then, is Pittsburgh tied for the AFC Central lead? Special teams
have come up big and WR Hines Ward is showing signs of becoming the
new ``Slash,'' the combination runner-receiver-passer Stewart once
was.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Steelers 19, Oilers 14
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK JETS (4-3) AT KANSAS CITY (4-3) Time: 3:05 p.m., Sunday
Site: Arrowhead Stadium, Kansas City, Mo. (79,101) Series: Chiefs
lead 14-12-1 Line: No line
</P>
<P>
   Jets update: Things change quickly in the AFC East, where the
Jets were hurting two weeks ago but now are on a roll, tied for
second, just a game out of first, after blowing away New England
and Atlanta. It's all working these days for the Jets, from QB
Vinny Testaverde's AFC-best 107.0 rating (11 TDs and just one
interception) to WR Keyshawn Johnson's six scoring catches to RB
Curtis Martin's consecutive 100-yard games to LB Mo Lewis' big hits
on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs update: As fast as the Jets have risen, the Chiefs have
fallen, crashing from a perch as a Super Bowl contender to a team
grappling to stay in the AFC West race. The greatest failings have
come on defense. Why, even punchless Pittsburgh, which averages
15.1 points per game, scored 20 on the Chiefs, who are ranked No. 1
against the pass in part because it's so easy to run on them (134.3
yards rushing allowed per game) that opponents don't have to throw.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Jets 30, Chiefs 21
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND (5-2) AT SEATTLE (4-3) Time: 7:20 p.m., Sunday Site:
Kingdome, Seattle (66,400) Series: Raiders lead 21-19 Line: Seattle
by 7
</P>
<P>
   Raiders update: QB Jeff George sits, the passing game withers
and still the Raiders win. Donald Hollas likely will start again
for the ailing George on Seattle's artificial turf, but that hardly
seems to matter, because offense is not why the Raiders have won
four in a row. Oakland's defense, which ranked dead last in 1997,
is now first in the league, allowing less than 250 yards per game.
DTs Russell Maryland and Darrell Russell clog up the inside running
lanes while CBs Charles Woodson and Eric Allen are swooping on
would-be receivers _ Oakland has picked off an AFC-high 12 passes _
and stopping big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks update: The Seahawks found another losing team to beat
up on last week, barely getting by San Diego. All four of their
wins, in which they have scored an average of 30.5 points, have
come against sub-.500 teams. Seattle's only matchups with winning
teams have resulted in losses, in which they averaged 10.7 points.
So what should we expect Sunday, against a 5-2 team with the
league's best defense, and QB Warren Moon still questionable with
cracked ribs? I'll leave that one to you.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Raiders 20, Seahawks 14
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS (4-3) AT PHILADELPHIA (1-6) Time: 7:20 p.m., Monday Site:
Veterans Stadium, Philadelphia (65,352) Series: Cowboys lead 45-29
Line: Dallas by 61/2
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys update: Troy's back! Troy's back! Finally, after five
weeks of thrills and chills with Jason Garrett, QB Troy Aikman is
back in the lineup for the Cowboys, just in time to start the
Cowboys' run at the NFC East title. His presence should improve a
Dallas offense that already ranks third in the NFC, thanks in large
measure to RB Emmitt Smith's resurgence. Not that they'll need much
offense to outscore woeful Philadelphia, which should be easy
pickings for the Dallas D.
</P>
<P>
   Eagles update: Deion Sanders might as well take the night off,
because the Eagles' passing game is no threat. Philly has scored
only twice through the air in seven games, and neither TD went to a
WR. The running game isn't exactly sound, either _ no Eagles RB has
had a 100-yard game this year. In all, the Eagles have scored just
79 points for the season, an average of 11.3 a game. To have a
chance, Philly has to be strong on defense, but they're allowing
nearly 150 yards per game on the ground. Can you say big day for
Emmitt? Sure. I like the way you say that.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Cowboys 27, Eagles 10
</P>
</TEXT>
