<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2394 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KENTUCKY-RACE-COX     10-28 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENTUCKY-RACE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kentucky standing out as hotbed of tight races
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHLAND, Ky. _ J.R. McKenzie, like many in this Ohio River town,
is a registered Democrat. But McKenzie, who owns restaurants and
other local businesses, is voting Republican in this year's
congressional election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family values,'' McKenzie said, explaining his support for
state Sen. Gex Williams, the Republican candidate in Kentucky's 4th
Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   The curious thing about McKenzie's rationale is that the
Democratic candidate, Ken Lucas, shares many of Williams' views on
social issues, including opposition to abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The race to replace Rep. Jim Bunning (R-Ky.), the Republican
nominee for the U.S. Senate, is a contest of who can come across as
more conservative in this district, which hugs the river as it cuts
a swath across northern Kentucky from just east of Louisville
through the suburbs of Cincinnati to Ashland.
</P>
<P>
   In an election year that has relatively few competitive races
and lacks an overarching national theme, Kentucky stands out as a
political hotbed. Campaigns for three House seats and the Senate
are highly competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning is locked in a close campaign with Rep. Scotty Baesler,
who is seeking to keep in Democratic hands the Senate seat that has
been held by Sen. Wendell Ford for the past 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the Louisville area, freshman Republican Rep. Anne Northup is
seeking re-election in a district she won by 1,299 votes in 1996
even as President Clinton carried it handily. She has a large
advantage in campaign cash over former Kentucky Attorney General
Chris Gorman, an anti-abortion Democrat. But Gorman has begun
airing a commercial that says Northup and the Republicans are
obsessed with impeaching Clinton and have neglected important
policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   In Baesler's Lexington-based district, state Sen. Ernesto
Scorsone is trying to shake the ``liberal'' label and hold the seat
for the Democrats. He faces Ernie Fletcher, a physician and former
state lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Fletcher is airing a hard-hitting ad that features a rape victim
who chides Scorsone, a lawyer, for his defense of the rapist, who
received a light sentence. ``The ad doesn't say this happened in
the 1970s, that the rapist was a juvenile or that the most the
judge could give him was six months,'' said Penny Miller, a
University of Kentucky political science professor. ``It's vicious
but effective.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest poll in that race gives Scorsone a 3-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucas-Williams race is among the most closely watched in the
nation, because it follows the model the Democrats said they would
employ to recapture control of the House. Few analysts, or
Democrats for that matter, give the party much chance of gaining a
majority.
</P>
<P>
   But Lucas is the kind of candidate who can draw distinctions
with the national Democratic Party, especially on social issues,
and point to victories in four elections for local and county
offices in the GOP-dominated suburbs of Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Williams defeated a less conservative candidate in the primary,
in part by using his ability to mobilize religious conservatives.
The lawmaker's children are home-schooled, and he appealed for
volunteers for his campaign by noting that he is a ``Christian
father of six.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the campaign has taken on a particularly nasty
tone, with Lucas accusing Williams of lying and the Republican
calling his opponent ``a Clinton liberal right here in Kentucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the Kentucky political scientist, said she doubts that
the charge will stick to Lucas. ``They're both trying to depict
themselves as the best conservative,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas has nettled Williams repeatedly with ads that allege that
the Republican has shoddy ethics, using a Kentucky ethics
commission probe that ultimately cleared Williams but chastised him
for not clearly reporting the details of his sale of farm land to a
political supporter.
</P>
<P>
   And lately, Lucas has gotten under Williams' skin by
intentionally mispronouncing Williams' unusual first name. It is
pronounced Jay, but Lucas says it so that it rhymes with hex.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucas can't win on the issues so he wants to change the
subject to character,'' said Ralph Reed, the former Christian
Coalition executive director who is Williams' political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   But issues have won Lucas the endorsement of the Kentucky Post,
a paper that frequently opts for Republican candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
