<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2395 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNDERGROUND-SALE-COX     10-28 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNDERGROUND-SALE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Owners of Atlanta's Underground mall consider offers
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Underground Atlanta's owners are finalizing a deal to
sell the beleagured downtown landmark to local businessman Dan
O'Leary, who also owns South DeKalb Mall, according to one of the
other bidders.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, managing partner of Atlanta-based Capitalist Ventures
Inc., is one of three finalists bidding on Underground, and the
first choice of Underground Festival Inc.'s committee negotiating a
deal to present to the Atlanta City Council.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's bid to beef up Underground's appeal as a
family-oriented tourist attraction apparently beat out a more
ambitious plan from a joint venture of mall giant Urban Shopping
Centers and local retail consultant George Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality of what we are proposing and what Dan is proposing
is diametrically opposed,'' said Hawthorne, a former retail
operations manager at Underground and owner of Retail Property
Solutions, a consultancy in Atlanta. ``The council needs to look at
both bids.''
</P>
<P>
   UFI's committee wants to present a contract with O'Leary to City
Council for approval by the end of the year. But several council
members have said they want to study all three final offers. ``It's
not over by any means,'' Hawthorne said.
</P>
<P>
   UFI acting president Charlie Battle said the committee was still
negotiating a letter of intent and declined to confirm the bidder.
But Battle's committee may be in for a political fight when they
take their deal to City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne, who was appointed by the mayor to chair this year's
Freaknik celebration, may generate some support for his proposal _
he is encouraging council members to support his effort to get his
bid on the table alongside O'Leary's.
</P>
<P>
   However, he has at least one ``no'' vote on the City Council.
Council President Robb Pitts told Battle and others he would not
approve a deal with which Hawthorne was associated.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorne and Chicago-based Urban are proposing a $100 million
redevelopment of the Five Points area, including a 500-room
convention hotel and 250 condominiums and enclosing Kenny's Alley
at Underground for a nighttime entertainment enclave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Underground has to be the entertainment hub for the city,''
Hawthorne said. ``A family oriented attraction doesn't take care of
your business after 6 p.m. and that's when you make your sales per
square foot.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, a former retail broker who bought the ailing South
DeKalb Mall from the Rouse Co. in 1996, has said he is leaving
nighttime entertainment to Buckhead and Virginia-Highland and
concentrating on tourists and families by bringing new attractions
and shops to Underground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buckhead has emerged as the mecca of nightlife entertainment
and its too difficult to compete against that now,'' O'Leary said
in an earlier interview. ``Underground doesn't have to become a hot
spot for people in metro Atlanta. I see it as a place to showcase
Atlanta rather than a place for Atlantans to hang out at on a
regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary paid about $20 million for South DeKalb and has
successfully signed new retailers and boosted sales. He convinced
DeKalb County this summer to provide a tax break to build a
12-screen Magic Johnson Theaters complex at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   The likely stumbling block for Hawthorne and Urban's bid was not
money or the concept, but a contingency requiring the city to
spruce up the gritty Five Points area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted a commitment from the city to move in the
direction that solves the overall problem,'' Hawthorne said.
O'Leary's plan, he said, ``is a Band-Aid approach to a festering
sore.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
