<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2401 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRUCE-MERCURY     10-28 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUCE-MERCURY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remembering and relishing the excitement, wonder of space
 &HT;    By Jeff Bruce
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ At the guarded entrance to the Kennedy
Space Center, an ancient Redstone rocket rises by the roadside, a
lonely sentry reminiscent of glory days of old.
</P>
<P>
   Atop the seven-story missile sits a Mercury capsule with the
words ``United States'' boldly emblazoned on its thin titanium
hull, white paint on a black spaceship barely large enough to hold
a man.
</P>
<P>
   Alan B. Shepard squeezed into a capsule like this 37 years ago
to begin America's adventure in space. Nine months later, John
Glenn, in a similar capsule but atop the larger and more powerful
Atlas missile, blasted into orbit, the first American to do so.
</P>
<P>
   During the past three decades, many others have followed in
Shepard's and Glenn's trailblazing footsteps. Once there were the
Mercury Seven, household names all. Today, NASA provides a 74-page
catalogue to list all its astronauts, current, retired and
deceased. The space program has 103 astronauts on its active duty
roster. Even more, 105, have retired. Twenty-five astronauts have
died. And another 35 men and women are in the current astronaut
candidate class.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder we don't know their names. No wonder the wonderment is
gone. Heroes don't come by the dozens. But we cherish them when we
find them, which explains the excitement surrounding John Glenn's
return to space.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a hero. In an encore performance, to be sure. But a
genuine hero nonetheless. Finally a chance, too, to relive the
excitement of the days when the space program was young, when men
truly went where no one had gone before.
</P>
<P>
   Tom O'Malley vividly remembers those days. He was the guy in the
blockhouse who pushed the button sending Glenn into orbit the first
time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that he's going up,'' he told reporters.
``It has given the space program a needed lift. Maybe now we'll get
back on track and put an astronaut on Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   George Page was O'Malley's No. 2 on launch day, Feb. 20, 1962.
He recalls the Atlas missile was unsuccessful a third of the time
during launch. ``I think John Glenn had a heck of a lot of courage
to sit on that damned thing.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Malley, too, remembers the danger: ``In the early days, every
other one either failed or fizzled. I don't think there was a
launch pad out there we didn't have one blow up on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public wants a hero...and John Glenn fits that.''
</P>
<P>
   Brave then, brave now. Ask Shirley Franks, she'll tell you.
</P>
<P>
   Franks, 62, works at the Space Shop, the official NASA souvenir
store, and has been around the edge of the space program since its
early years. Back in the '60s she was a waitress at Ramon's, the
hottest eatery in Cocoa Beach and a frequent hangout of the Mercury
astronauts. She remembers John Glenn as a customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very nice man and he had a lovely wife and family,''
she recalls.
</P>
<P>
   And how do you feel about Glenn's return to space?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think its a very brave thing that he's doing''
</P>
<P>
   Franks, along with everyone else at the space center, will stop
what they're doing during the final countdown today. ``When you see
a launch going up, it's a very emotional thing to me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If you had a chance to say something to Glenn before liftoff,
what would it be? I asked her.
</P>
<P>
   She look thoughtful for a moment, then replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``Godspeed John Glenn.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
