<HEADER>
A2402 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-JEFFSIDE29     10-28 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-JEFFSIDE29 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Through time, NASA has grown galaxies more sophisticated
 &HT;    By Jeff Bruce
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ During the past three decades, spaceships
have become far more sophisticated and complex.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask the guys who were in the blockhouse on the day John
Glenn was first launched into orbit:
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we had that was automated in those days was the
coffee machine in the control room,'' recalls Paul Donnelly, a
former NASA test conductor.
</P>
<P>
   The Redstone rocket, which first launched man into space, would
fit into the cargo bay of the Space Shuttle. You could take all the
Mercury capsules ever launched and return them to space in the back
of the shuttle, too _ and still have room for a game of pool if you
could figure out how to play in zero G.
</P>
<P>
   The NASA public relations operation, which also has grown in
sophistication over the years, has compiled a fascinating
comparison of space vehicles, then and now, which illustrates how
much things have changed. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Five computers are on board the space shuttle, helping guide
its flight and re-entry into the Earth's atmosphere. That's five
more computers than John Glenn had aboard Friendship 7.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mercury capsule, designed to hold a single astronaut, had
a mere 36 cubic feet of space. The shuttle, in contrast, can hold
up to 10 people and contains more than 2,300 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   _ While orbiting the planet, John Glenn had to attend to 56
toggle switches, eight push-buttons and 19 event indicators. Aboard
the cockpit of STS 95, the pilots will watch over 856 toggle
switches, 219 push-buttons and 559 event indicators.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Glenn orbited the Earth three times in just under five
hours. The Discovery will remain in space for nearly nine days
orbiting the planet 144 times.
</P>
<P>
   _ Friendship 7 was the ultimate in planned obsolescence, built
to last for only one flight. The Space Shuttle Discovery will be
making its 25th return to space today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 2029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-LOCALS29     10-28 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-LOCALS29 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Those who knew Glenn way back should have known...
 &HT;    By Dale Huffman and Brandon Peterson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Isabel Bowers is proud that ``the jolly
little boy with freckles'' from her hometown of New Concord is the
big news of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Twp. trustee Robert T. Douglass is equally proud _ he's
one of the few people who received an invitation from Sen. John
Glenn's office to watch him go back in orbit today.
</P>
<P>
   And Vivian Walton was so proud she wrote a song for the senator.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's return to orbit has moved people in many different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``From New Concord to space,'' Bowers, 82, said smiling. ``You
know I was older than little John, and we lived about six miles
from his family. John's father had a plumbing business and when my
father went over there to get stuff I would tag along. I got to
play with John. I still find it hard to realize he is the man who
is making all this news.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglass finds it hard to believe he received an invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I talked to John Glenn was in 1996 when we were
at a meeting celebrating the first flight of 1903,'' Douglass said.
``So I wouldn't say we were exactly close.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a close friendship or not, Douglass was one of 100
people, including family members, to get the invitation. The rest
of the group will watch the launch from a designated location.
</P>
<P>
   And he's got his camera too. ``I hope I remember to take
pictures, Douglass said.'' ``I'm like the hunter looking for birds,
gets excited when he sees it, and forgets to shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright State University assistant professor of psychology
Valerie Shalin will also be on hand to watch Glenn's takeoff, but
closer to NASA officials.
</P>
<P>
   Shalin and three Wright State graduate students will be at the
NASA flight control center in Houston observing workplace
activities at mission control as part of a research project to help
NASA improve the design of its software tools.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of design, a Dayton woman has wrote a song
commemorating Glenn's return to space.
</P>
<P>
   Walton, 63, of Dayton, said she was inspired to write ``Pray For
Senator John Glenn and the Crew'' to promote unity and living
longer lives in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in life, and the idea of this song is to encourage
people to live longer,'' Walton said.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers, who works at Wilkie's book store in downtown Dayton,
said she was shocked when Glenn went into orbit in 1962, but in
retrospect had a clue.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to make model airplanes as a kid,'' she said, ''and he
always played with little planes. I guess I should have known.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
