<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPLE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Police show tape second time hoping to find witness to slayings
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler and Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta police had a second world premier movie
showing Wednesday night, hoping to find a murder witness _ a man
caught on video entering the Atlanta Hilton &AMP; Towers the night
three men were shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   After a disappointing first release _ police last week showed a
videotape of the man getting onto an elevator in the hotel with one
of the victims at about 2:10 a.m. _ police now say they hope a
clearer frontal view of the witness will prompt someone to come
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope this additional video will help the public identify
the person we're interested in,'' said Atlanta police spokesman
John Quigley. ``I want to reiterate there is a $30,000 reward
leading to the arrest and conviction of the person or persons
responsible for this crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The earlier video shows 31-year-old Phillip Dover of
Gainesville, Ga., walking into the hotel's elevator bay with a man
dressed in khaki-colored clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Dover, Gerrold Shropshire, 50, of Altamonte Springs, Fla., and
Ronald Gutkowski, 51, of Leesburg, Fla., were found shot to death
``execution style'' in room 2414 of the Hilton on Oct. 18, police
have said.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Eric Kiesel, Fulton County deputy chief medical
examiner, said the men were shot in the head ``more than once.''
</P>
<P>
   California State University at Northridge Criminology Professor
Lewis Yablonsky questioned whether such a shooting could be
considered a cold-blooded execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anger, revenge. This sounds like retribution for being
mistreated in some way,'' said Yablonsky, who has written 16 books
on crime in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone had wanted to kill them, they would have been
killed,'' Yablonsky said. ``But this is overkill, and that would
lead me to believe that there was some enormous, revengeful anger
that came into play.''
</P>
<P>
   Kiesel would not discuss whether the shooting victims had been
beaten or sexually assaulted. The medical examiner collected
evidence from the victims' bodies and said toxicology tests to
determine the presence of drugs or alcohol had not yet been
completed.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery surrounding the triple murder deepened when police
in suburban Orlando, Fla., discovered someone broke into
Shropshire's empty apartment, rifled through papers and ransacked
the place one week after the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta homicide investigators said they are working closely
with police in Altamonte Springs, Fla., to determine whether the
break-in is related to the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law enforcement agencies down there are being very cooperative
with us,'' Sgt. Scott Bennett said Wednesday. ``But it's too early
to tell whether the break-in and the murders are connected yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Chief Mike Deal of the Altamonte Springs Police
Department said his investigators do not know whether anything was
taken from Shropshire's apartment. He said he shared all the
information he had about the burglary with homicide detectives in
Atlanta, but he does not know whether the burglary is related to
the triple murder in the high-rise hotel nearly 400 miles away from
Shropshire's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know a lot about what (the Atlanta police are) doing
and what direction they're going in,'' he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Early in their investigation, Atlanta police ordered the
managers Shropshire's apartment complex to change the lock on his
apartment, Shropshire's relatives said. Five days after the
killings, police officers in the Orlando suburb of about 40,000
people, accompanied Shropshire's daughter and other relatives into
the apartment so they could pick up some clothes for Shropshire's
funeral.
</P>
<P>
   A police report says the apartment was relatively neat and clean
then. On their way out, detectives stuck red tape that says
''EVIDENCE'' on the door.
</P>
<P>
   Two days laters, on Sunday, Oct. 25, someone broke into
Shropshire's apartment, in a complex of beige buildings surrounded
by palm trees. A police report says the burglar or burglars
''pulled out various drawers in the bed room and went through them
scattering articles. Persons went into the living room and pulled
open the drawer and went through some papers.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, written Monday by Officer G.J. Aldrich, said the
burglar or burglars then ''went into the living room and pulled
open the drawer and went through some papers.'' Aldrich said
''there were several papers scattered on the dining room table''
but that valuable items, such as televisions, computers, stereo
speakers and a CD player were ''untouched.''
</P>
<P>
   Aldrich said in his report that ''glove prints'' were recovered
from Shropshire's apartment. Police in Florida said they do not
know whether the glove prints came from the burglar or from a
gloved police officer who accompanied Shropshire's relatives into
the apartment a few days before the burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Maple Bronner, Shropshire's girlfriend, said Wednesday that she
does not know what to make of the burglary.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just getting stranger and stranger and kind of spooky,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bronner said she has ''no idea'' who would have wanted to hurt
Shropshire. She said she is beginning to wonder whether Shropshire
and Gutkowski stumbled onto some information _maybe related to
their trucking jobs _ that was dangerous. If they did, she said,
they certainly did not let on that anything was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just wondering if he found out something or if Ronnie
found out something,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta police are also trying to figure out whether the Hilton
slayings are related to a shooting at a College Park Days Inn on
Oct. 15. For the last few days, police from both agencies have said
the incidents shared a handful of similarities, but they would not
discuss what those were. In that case, 19-year-old Ladaris Hawkins
was found shot in the face inside a room at the motel just after
10:30 p.m. Hawkins was also found in his underwear, and as in the
Hilton incident, there was no forced entry to his room.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday morning Lt. Richard Chromi of the major crimes
division, said he was not as certain that both are connected:
``What we apperared to have at first blush, is not what we have
now. I'm not going to discuss whether that means the cases are not
connected or whether the motive is different, I'm just saying
things may not be the same as what was originally thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said investigators still do not have enough evidence in
the Atlanta case to pin down a motive.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Police Chief Beverly Harvard meanwhile, said she is
staying close to the case: ``I am directing, advising, and making
decisions whenever necessary and as appropriate. I am being brief
around the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
