<HEADLINE>
GRIDLOCK EXPECTED, WELCOMED, FOR VIEWING SPOTS AT GLENN, DISCOVERY
LAUNCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
and PATTI MUCK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ The most enviable spots for viewing
Thursday's liftoff of the shuttle Discovery were claimed by
nightfall Wednesday, but cars, campers and RVs carrying John Glenn
well-wishers were expected to keep on coming, raising the threat of
gridlock before launch time.
</P>
<P>
   Along coastal state highway 528 near here, about a dozen campers
and RVs were wedged into a small, sandy clearing by midafternoon.
They watched the glow of the brightly lit launch pad across several
miles of water as night fell.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Tarsitano of nearby Melbourne, Fla., said she could have
stayed home and gotten a decent view of the shuttle after it
cleared the ground, but that wasn't close enough to suit her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't hear it, you don't see the flames,'' Tarsitano said.
``Here, you get the fire and the vibration.''
</P>
<P>
   The recreational vehicle site featured a hodge-podge of
characters from everywhere. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I was the very first person here _ it's the best spot,'' said
Keith Hilgers, 40, who is unemployed and drove his recreational
vehicle from a Chicago suburb. ``I like the shuttle. I don't care
who's in it, as long as it's safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a few yards away, Australian residents Alec Howie and Jenny
Wingat were settling in to await the launch in the camper they've
used to tour the United States since June.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn is revered in Australia, too, said Howie, 76, and he and
Wingat deliberately planned their trip through Central Florida to
catch the launch.
</P>
<P>
   The way he sees it, Americans must be delighted to have
something to think about other than the ongoing presidential
scandal. ``It's taken all that bad news off the front page,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At nearby Jetty Park, Edward Cooper of Bullhead, Ariz., was
scrambling to raise the colors over his camper Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta get our flag up for this!'' said Cooper. ``This is a
patriotic occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   He and wife Marian tried to make reservations at the campsite
three months ago, she said, but were told it was already booked.
They gratefully squeezed into the overflow section, and plan to
watch the launch from the roof of their camper.
</P>
<P>
   The crush of visitors began affecting traffic days before
launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, the word of the day is gridlock,'' said Titusville Police
Lt. Skip Toney as the 86-member Titusville police force geared up
for crowd and traffic control.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a '60s hero going up in the '90s _ that's pretty
big news.''
</P>
<P>
   So big, in fact, that a lot of Floridians would just as soon
skip the hassle of jockeying for a good spot and watch from the
comfort of their homes along the coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The locals aren't going to be out and about,'' said Charlotte
Leinbach as she and her husband sold souvenirs along U.S. 1 in
Titusville. Most of her customers were home folks, she said, who
bought early to avoid the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just stay home,'' Toney is advising Titusville residents.
``Open your doors and watch it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials predict it will take two to four hours
for traffic to clear after blast-off, scheduled for 2 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how anyone is going to get to work, to be honest
with you,'' said Helen Voltz, Brevard County Commission Chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting earlier this week, she asked that county employees
get a half-day off because of traffic concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody seemed to be a Scrooge this morning _ they all said
no,'' Voltz said. ``They felt we would need a lot of county
services.''
</P>
<P>
   Voltz plans to take time off and has a VIP pass for a close-up
view of the launch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time a launch goes up, I get tears in my eyes,'' she
said ``It's spine-tingling.''
</P>
<P>
   Titusville is just across the the Indian River from the launch
pad and souvenir stands were doing a brisk business.
</P>
<P>
   For vendor Frances Grimm, 67, the excitement went beyond the
money-making opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met John Glenn before he ever went up,'' she gushed. She was
working for Collins Radio in Cedar Rapids, Iowa, she said, and
Glenn toured the plant that would be supplying equipment for his
capsule. ``And he said, `You know girls, our lives are in your
hands,' '' Grimm recalled. ``It was a thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   A few miles west off State Road 50, retiree Betty Reinecke, 76,
proudly wore her volunteer vest heavy with John Glenn pins, patches
and buttons. She worked at a tourist information booth earlier in
the week, but, like many locals, plans to take Thursday off and
watch the launch from her front porch.
</P>
<P>
   While Reinecke believes politics played a role in putting Glenn
on the Discovery, she's not complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The benefit of it is we are going to get a heck of a promotion
by using John Glenn,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of the tourists stopped at the Astronaut Hall of Fame,
many leaving words of encouragement to Discovery's crew in the
visitors book. But the lion's share of the messages were directed
to Glenn _ some making pointed reference to his 77 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Mr. Glenn: Please don't have a heart attack,'' wrote
Elizabeth Snyder, a local elementary school student. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
