<SLUG> BC-GLENN-CHALLENGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN'S COMMENTS ON CHALLENGER DISASTER ARE REVIVED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With GLENN-PREPARE)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The day after the space shuttle Challenger disaster
in 1986, Senator John Glenn blasted NASA's decision to send Christa
McAuliffe on the fatal mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The space program is for basic, fundamental research,'' Glenn
said after McAuliffe, a Concord, N.H., high school teacher, and six
crewmates died in the Challenger tragedy. ``It's not to put the
butcher, the baker, and the candlestick maker up there.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Glenn said, space flight should not be ``a cosmic
carnival ride.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, 12 years later, the 77-year-old Democratic senator
from Ohio is poised to lift off for a shuttle ride in space. And
several critics are using his post-Challenger remarks against him.
</P>
<P>
   Although they praised him as an America hero for his historic
space flight in 1962 and wished him success on the nine-day journey
that is scheduled to start Thursday at 2 p.m., Glenn's critics
asserted Wednesday that his mission on the shuttle Discovery is no
more vital to space science than McAuliffe's education-based
``ultimate field trip'' was to have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a favor for someone who is a favorite son of the space
program and has been loyal to the Clinton administration,'' said
Lon Raines, editor of Space News, a weekly newspaper that covers
the aerospace industry. ``There is no scientific justification for
it.''
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe, who was born in Boston and raised in Framingham, had
been chosen from a field of nearly 11,500 teachers to become the
inaugural astronaut in NASA's civilian-in-space program. She was to
have turned the shuttle into an orbiting classroom, conducting
science experiments and lessons on space history that were to have
been beamed by satellite to millions of American students.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe was 37 when the Challenger exploded 73 seconds after
liftoff, killing the crew and effectively ending the
civilian-in-space program.
</P>
<P>
   Although Glenn expressed ``a profound, personal sense of loss''
over the Challenger tragedy, he questioned the decision to send
civilians into space while the shuttle program was still in ``its
embryonic stage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the taxpayers come to believe that the space program is
becoming a cosmic carnival ride, then we face the very real
prospect that they may withdraw their support,'' Glenn said.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of aggressive lobbying to secure a seat on the
Discovery flight, Glenn is scheduled to act as a human guinea pig
for research on aging in the weightlessness of space.
</P>
<P>
   NASA and some advocates for broader research on aging have
defended Glenn's role on the Discovery flight as a potentially
valuable contribution to science.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn also has responded to the critics. ``If you eliminate the
science benefit,'' he said at a recent news conference, ``then
there's no reason, except I want to go. That's not a justification
for me to go. A lot of people want to go. We are going for science.
That's the reason I am going.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn failed to convince Rick Tomlinson, president of the Space
Frontier Foundation, which promotes opening space travel to
civilians. Tomlinson characterized Glenn's scheduled flight the way
some of McAuliffe's prelaunch critics described her mission. He
called it ``a publicity stunt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 2033EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2414 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN29-COX     10-28 1382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Godspeed, John Glenn
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Launch day for the space shuttle
Discovery will dawn today on Florida's Atlantic coast, but before
the sun clears the horizon, October 29, 1998, will be the day
America sends its first space hero back into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   John Glenn, the senior senator from Ohio, is the lowest ranking
member of Discovery's seven-astronaut crew. Yet it will be his
presence aboard the ship's windowless mid-deck that makes this 92nd
shuttle flight an event of historic proportions.
</P>
<P>
   The first American in space will become, at age 77, the oldest
man ever in space.
</P>
<P>
   A grove of television satellite trucks has sprouted in the flat
grass of the Kennedy Space Center press site. Cocoa Beach's prime
viewing spot, Jetty Park, filled with campers two nights ago, and
just about every business marquee along the beach has spelled out
some variation of ``Godspeed, John Glenn.''
</P>
<P>
   By about 11:15 a.m. today, Glenn will be on his back inching
into position so he can be strapped to his metal seat. Two other
astronauts will be with him, and the remaining four will ride one
floor up on the shuttle's flight deck. The last time Glenn did
this, 36 years ago on a launch pad 12 miles south, the rocket moved
when he did, the capsule fit around him like the trunk of a car,
and he was alone.
</P>
<P>
   The only open question for the day of the launch may be the
evaluations of its importance. The science to which Glenn has been
assigned is in the early stages, and isn't likely to offer
startling new views of aging in the human body. At best, the Glenn
studies will offer future researchers suggestions on where to look
next. But the historical symmetry of sending an original astronaut
back into space, despite drawing intense publicity now, may not
sustain much interest after Glenn's return.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, believes it will.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great thrill,'' said DeWine, who arrived Wednesday for
the launch. ``And I think it's going to reenergize the space
program. When we get to the point where he's back and talking about
it with people and doing interviews about his experience, it will
continue to energize the discussion. And that's good.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Glenn and the rest of the crew has engaged in a mix
of fine-tuning and relaxation. Tuesday night they had a barbecue at
a beach house with family members.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have fabulous cooks there,'' said Lyn Glenn, John Glenn's
daughter. ``We had barbecued chicken, and barbecued beef, and links
and salad, and mixed fruit. One of the cooks out there had brought
in these huge apples and they tasted like they had been covered in
a Heath bar. And I asked where they were from because we wanted to
get more because they were so good. They're from Ohio. Mother wants
to track down where these are from because they were so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving from the training facility in Houston on Monday,
the Discovery crew has spent much of its time with family. For the
Glenns, the time has been valuable because despite John Glenn's
enthusiasm, his wife and children were not thrilled with the
prospect of watching him test the limits of his own aged body with
nine days of weightlessness.
</P>
<P>
   They have since come around, largely in response to his
resilience in training and the radiating effect of his enthusiasm.
The family attended several of Glenn's training sessions, part of
an intense eight-month program in which his mind and body were
strained to capacity. Between learning the shuttles many systems,
and learning the multitude of experiments aboard, Glenn spent more
than 500 hours preparing for space flight. He admitted to being a
bit sore from time to time, and wishing he'd taken up flexibility
training earlier in his life, but otherwise Glenn was invigorated
by the arduous work.
</P>
<P>
   But the heavy lifting ended with the arrrival of launch week,
and Lyn Glenn said her parents have been together every day this
week. She said her mother, Annie, has lately become more
comfortable with the events to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is really good...'' Lyn said, ``...where we're staying, we
can look across at where the pad is, and (Tuesday) morning when I
got up and came out, Mom was just standing out on the balcony and
looking at the launch site. We can see it off in the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   But today will be a day given to nerves with the liftoff,
something Annie Glenn called ``the scary part.'' Even
professionals, such as Discovery Commander Curt Brown, would rather
not have to ride a rocket to get into space.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blasting off is not a good term I like to use. We launch,''
Brown said. ``But it is basically a blast off, and that's very
unforgiving. It's very aggressive and there should be a better
way.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first minute and thirty seconds, while the solid-fueled
rockets drive the shuttle up, computers do all the steering and the
crew has no control. ``The ascent is what you imagine,'' said
Brown, who will make his fifth shuttle flight with Discovery.
``It's some serious stuff happening at the other end of the vehicle
and you're accelerating. It's stressful, the environment, just
because of what you're doing...''
</P>
<P>
   But it's worth remembering that this is not simply something
Glenn wanted to do despite the stresses, it's more than that. He
actually invented this day that will surrender itself to the eyes
of world. Maybe not directly with the media carnival erected around
it, and the postcard-perfect weather, or the press conference and
reception the three surviving Mercury astronauts held Wednesday
night, but it was Glenn's own idea to study the elderly in space
right now, and his relentless determination that found a feasible
plan to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn was just 50, his first flight then a decade behind him,
when he came to grips with the reality that he'd never fly in space
again. America had gone to the moon, Skylab was soon to be
launched, and there seemed no logical way for a Columbus business
executive and soon-to-be U.S. Senator to rejoin the astronaut corps
after leaving in frustration because he never got another flight
back in the early '60s.
</P>
<P>
   It was Glenn's own itching curiosity that turned the fates
around. Many years later, when he noticed that lengthy stays in
weightlessness caused the same debilitating effects as growing old,
he sketched out an idea on a legal pad to send an aged man into
space to see what would happen.
</P>
<P>
   He brought the proposal to NASA, then he lined up the National
Institutes of Health and the National Institute on Aging to hold
the academic conferences necessary to get the project
peer-reviewed. They talked about the way muscles wither, bones turn
brittle, immune systems weaken, and sleep is disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What NIA and NASA want to try and find out is if...'' Glenn
said earlier this month, ``Am I immune to some of the things that
happen to them because I've already had that happen on earth? What
will be my recovery rates? Any different? If so, why? What they're
trying to do is determine within the body what turns these systems
on and off.''
</P>
<P>
   Scientists had noticed all these parallels, too. They just
hadn't thought of sending an elderly man into space. So, of course,
they surely hadn't thought of sending Glenn, which created its own
hurdle. Critics, though they were few, seized upon the simple truth
that this flight would not be happening if Glenn were not the test
subject, and argued that it was a Senator's priviledge or a blatant
play for the nostalgic.
</P>
<P>
   Few thought he shouldn't go; they just called his science
experiments a fig leaf to permit NASA a public relations coup while
giving Glenn, a stalwart supporter of the agency, the second space
ride he never got. But NASA's Administrator diffused some of that
by admitting that science wasn't the sole purpose for sending Glenn
into space. ``I feel that this nation owes Sen. Glenn his second
flight,'' NASA chief Dan Goldin said. ``Science is one aspect,
giving him his second flight is the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn just had to prove a need for the first aspect to create a
day for the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was him! He did it,'' Goldin said. ``He went out and did
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
