<HEADLINE>
RAHAL'S `LAST RIDE' WORTHY OF TRIP TO VICTORY LANE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final 250 laps of Bobby Rahal's ``Last Ride'' through the
CART series will unwind at the California Speedway on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever your particular driver allegiance, feel free to
park it for a few hours and openly root for one of the sport's
gentlemen. We hesitate to use the term ``elder statesman,'' only
because at age 45, Rahal hardly is preparing to slide into a life
of full-fat retirement.
</P>
<P>
   He will remain thoroughly involved in the Championship Auto
Racing Teams FedEx Series as owner of the cars to be driven by
Bryan Herta and Max Papis.
</P>
<P>
   But Rahal will conclude a distinguished 17-year driving career
in the Marlboro 500 on the 2-mile superspeedway in Fontana, Calif.
The race will be the CART-record 264th career start (and 265th
overall) for Rahal, who made his Championship Car debut with
Truesports Racing at Phoenix International Raceway in 1982. The
perfect script this weekend would see Rahal win the thing, complete
with postrace cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is it. I haven't given up yet,'' said Rahal, whose 24
victories are fourth on CART's all-time list. ``I still have one
shot. And in a 500-mile race, I will tell you, anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahal has not won a race since 1992. So more than likely, he
will end the day content that as a three-time champion and the only
owner/driver in the series, he has made a difference to the world
of domestic open-wheel racing. That point has been driven home this
season by CART fans all along the 19-race tour. The fans turned out
en masse at the Mid-Ohio Sports Car Course in Lexington, Ohio, in
early August to bid farewell to their native son and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess because it was Mid-Ohio, you kind of sort of expected
it,'' said Rahal, of New Albany, Ohio, and a prominent business and
civic leader state-wide. ``I think the thing that really hit me
this year, frankly, was Milwaukee after qualifying, when I got a
standing ovation. There were maybe 3,000 or 4,000 people there on a
Saturday, so it's not that many people. But it took me totally
aback. I just never expected that whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the thing that has hit me is the fact that you really
feel like you connected with people after all these years.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact of Rahal's championships probably has been lost by
the fact that the last was registered in 1992. They were preceded
by back-to-back titles in 1986 and 1987. Along with Rick Mears _ a
four-time winner of the Indianapolis 500 when it really was the
world's most prestigious auto race _ Rahal is the only other CART
driver to have won three series championships.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Rahal has amassed 18 poles _ fifth all-time _ on
the series' various oval, permanent road-course and street circuit
layouts. He also has finished in the top five 119 times, or 45
percent of his starts, and in the top 10 in 177 events, or 67
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Your average 45-year-old (and older) NASCAR Winston Cup driver
would kill for those competitive stats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd seen other people do the other _ overstay their welcome,''
said Rahal, who is 10th in series points this year as driver of the
No. 7 Miller Lite Reynard/Ford. ``I don't want people to remember
me, you know, going through the motions. And that we had, I guess,
the good judgment to know when to say when.''
</P>
<P>
   The politics surrounding the split between CART and the rival
Pep Boys Indy Racing League have kept Rahal and his cohorts out of
the Indianapolis Motor Speedway since 1996. But two of the moments
that have defined Rahal's career are tied to the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   Recall the rain-plagued 1986 race, won by Rahal a week after
originally scheduled. What made it special was the fact that Rahal
drove to his first Indy 500 victory with the knowledge that his
team owner and mentor, Jim Trueman, was dying of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won Indy for Jim,'' Rahal said. ``We knew he wasn't going
to be at the Indy 500 next year, and we'd better get with the
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``To realize someone else's dream was something truly special,
not just from my part but everybody on the team. It's a little
unreal, even to this day.''
</P>
<P>
   And recall the final day of qualifications at the Speedway in
May 1993, when former champion Rahal failed to make the big race.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the 77th Indy 500, I can remember walking
toward the main gates of the Speedway. At the side of one of the
tunnels was a cut-out figure of Rahal dressed in his racing suit,
proudly holding his helmet and smiling into space.
</P>
<P>
   And draped around his shoulders was a makeshift cardboard sign
that read, quite ironically, ``Need tickets.''
THE BUZZ NHRA
</P>
<P>
   Pro Stock driver Bruce Allen and the Arlington-based
Reher-Morrison Racing Engines team quietly are completing the 1998
season with heavy hearts. Arlington's Buddy Morrison, a founder of
the famed high-performance company with friend and partner David
Reher, has suffered a setback in his battle against cancer. ``Buddy
is seriously ill and fighting a hard battle,'' said Reher, who
added that Morrison's condition has been deteriorating since June.
At that time, Morrison was heading up Reher-Morrison's involvement
in the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series with driver David Starr. ``The
Friday before the truck race at Texas Motor Speedway, the doctors
told him he was good,'' said Reher, who has known Morrison for 30
years. ``He came in and told us, `You're going to have to put up
with me a while longer.' On the Monday after that race, his doctor
told him he had to see him. And it was like the end of your world.
We were sitting in his office and having a big time and it wasn't a
few weeks later he can't even walk anymore.'' Reher said Morrison
recently returned home from the hospital to be with his wife,
Susan, and friends. ``That's something we wanted to happen very
bad,'' Reher said. ``We're praying for things to get better, for
him to have a little quality time.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Reher-Morrison has been a star-crossed operation. Driver Lee
Shepherd, a native of Fort Worth, won 26 national events and four
consecutive NHRA Pro Stock world championships as a partner with
Reher-Morrison between 1981-84. But Shepherd, whose other specialty
was cylinder head design, was killed during a crash while testing
at Ardmore, Okla., in March 1985. ...
</P>
<P>
   For the first and only time since 1987, Pro Stock Motorcycles
have been scheduled to compete at the Texas Motorplex in Ennis next
year. In addition to Top Fuel, Funny Car and Pro Stock, the Bikes
have been booked for the third annual Castrol Nationals April
22-25. ``That's a class we get tons of calls on around the event _
`Why don't you run Pro Stock Bikes?' '' said Elon Werner, the
Motorplex's director of media services. ``That class, because of
the personalities _ Angelle Seeling, Matt Hines, Dave Schultz _
will add to our presentation.'' And the Pro Stock Trucks that
debuted during the 13th annual Revell Nationals last weekend have
been scheduled to return next Oct. 21-24. ...
</P>
<P>
   Even though he is the reigning NHRA Top Fuel champion, and the
current points leader, some casual fans still have trouble
pronouncing Gary Scelzi's last name. The ``c'' is silent, and it's
pronounced ``sell-zee.'' But Gary's good friends in the NHRA's
media relations department have simplified matters. They refer to
the affable Californian as ``Gary Sleazy.'' And he likes it.
NASCAR
</P>
<P>
   Had Rusty Wallace not won the DuraLube/Kmart 500 at Phoenix
International Raceway Sunday, his winless streak would have hit 60
consecutive races. Wallace is well aware that is just the kind of
round number that gets the vultures in the media circling the
garage area, asking that at age 42, if he still can get it done.
``It's just something that aggravates the hell out of you,'' said
Wallace, the 1989 Cup champion and driver of the No. 2 Miller Lite
Ford Taurus. ``Dale Earnhardt went through a lot of that, I've gone
through it. \RBill\S Elliott's gone through it, Ricky Rudd _ all
the guys that are over 40 years old. They put a bull's eye on our
head and they target us when we're down and having a problem. I've
led a ton of laps this year. I've had four poles and a ton of
top-five finishes. It's enough to really get you aggravated, but
usually those questions come from people that are under-educated
about our sport and really don't understand it.'' And you know who
you are. ...
</P>
<P>
   Dale Jarrett's gallstone condition apparently will not prevent
him from competing in the final two Winston Cup events of the
season. Jarrett, who has a tenuous 36-point lead over fourth-place
Wallace in the standings, may be discharged from John C. Lincoln
Hospital in North Mountain, Phoenix, today. Jarrett plans to
attempt to qualify and start the ACDelco 400 at North Carolina
Speedway this weekend. Jarrett exited the No. 88 Quality Care/Ford
Credit Taurus after 126 laps at PIR. Hut Stricklin will be at The
Rock as Jarrett's relief driver. Dr. James Magary said surgery to
remove Jarrett's gall bladder will be delayed until after the
season-ending NAPA 500 at Atlanta Motor Speedway on Nov. 8.
FAST LAPS
AutoFest on tap at TMS
</P>
<P>
   The first fall edition of the AutoFest featuring Pate Swap Meet
is scheduled to begin today and run through Sunday at Texas Motor
Speedway in Fort Worth. Thousands of automotive parts vendors will
be present for one of the three largest such meets in the country.
</P>
<P>
   AutoFest hours are 7 a.m. through dusk today, tomorrow and
Saturday and 7 a.m. to 3 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with the meet, TMS will play host to the second
annual NASCAR Sale-A-Bration. Officially licensed souvenir items
from leading Winston Cup and Busch Grand National teams will be
offered, many at season-closing discounts. Trailers representing
Dale Earnhardt, Jeff Gordon, Mark Martin, Terry Labonte, Bobby
Labonte, Rusty Wallace and Bill Elliott are among 20 scheduled to
set up.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Lil' Texas Motor Speedway, the one-fifth-mile,
banked track located behind the backstretch, will play host to
Legends and Bandolero racing Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Fan Appreciation night, with fans offered free
admission with an AutoFest ticket. Without an AutoFest ticket,
admission is $2 for adults and children 12-and-under will be
admitted free. Gates open at 4 p.m., with racing starting at 6 p.m.
Nuts and bolts
</P>
<P>
   Pennzoil World of Outlaws rookie Tyler Walker swept last
weekend's 31st annual Western World Sprint Car Championships at
Manzanita Speedway in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Kinser holds a 132-point lead over his cousin, Mark, in
the World of Outlaws driver's championship. With only three races
remaining, Kinser merely has to qualify for each ``A'' Main event
to claim his record 15th title.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace's victory at Phoenix on Sunday was the 48th of his
Cup career, and moved him into a tie for 10th on the all-time list
with Herb Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1971 _ predating NASCAR's ``modern
era'' _ the Wood Brothers (and driver Michael Waltrip) failed to
qualify for a Cup race at PIR.
</P>
<P>
   BFGoodrich will become title sponsor of the Sports Car Club of
America's Trans-Am Series in 1999. It will be called the BFGoodrich
Tires Trans-Am Series.
Last words
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray to Elvis \RPresley\S every run. I know he's listening.
I look up, I look down. Wherever he is.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Seven-time NHRA Funny Car champion John Force, on his rock 'n
roll hero.
</P>
</TEXT>
