<SLUG> BC-GLENN-BEAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-astronaut Bean to help call space shot
 &HT;    By J. Matthew Aldag
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When 77-year-old John Glenn rockets into space again,
the voice of fellow man of the stars Alan Bean will follow him.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the 1969 Apollo 12 lunar mission, Bean will join
Walter Cronkite to do color commentary for CNN's coverage of the
space shuttle Discovery's mission (launch time is 2 p.m. today).
</P>
<P>
   ``(Glenn's mission) is one of the best things NASA has done in
the last 10 or 15 years. It is going to change attitudes,'' says
Bean. The former astronaut knows space travel is going to become
much more common in the near future and he thinks the experience
should be offered more often to people who aren't astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should send Tom Hanks next,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Once a Navy test pilot and commander of the Skylab space
station, Bean has a unique perspective on NASA's space program:
that of an artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like painting just as much as I did flying. It makes me feel
just as good,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   While a test pilot in 1962, Bean started taking night classes at
a Maryland art school. His interest flourished along with his skill
until he retired from the space program in 1981 to devote his time
to painting and motivational public speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bean re-creates on canvas the images he saw 29 years ago and
over 200,000 miles away. The images are more real that one would
expect: Bean sometimes mixes moon dust into his paints.
</P>
<P>
   This perspective can be seen in Bean's recently released book,
``Apollo: An Eyewitness Account by Astronaut/Explorer
Artist/Moonwalker Alan Bean'' (1998, Greenwich Workshop Press,
$45). Illustrated with 17 years of Bean's paintings, the book
recounts his experiences on the moon and describes his astronaut
life.
</P>
<P>
   Bean used models and his memories to help him re-create scenes
from the lunar mission. He also was able to paint images of things
that never happened. On the book's cover is a picture of three
astronauts on the moon side by side: Pete Conrad on the left, Bean
on the right and in the middle Dick Gordon, who never got to walk
on the lunar surface during the mission. Bean titled this work
``The Fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean, 66, lives in Houston with his wife, Lesley, and eight
dogs, spending most of his time painting.
</P>
<P>
   His pieces have sold for $20,000 to $100,000. A 40-foot mural he
painted spans a wall at the Johnson Space Center in Houston and he
was commissioned to paint a mural for the Astronaut Hall of Fame in
Titusville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
