<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-AND-ALZHEIMER'S-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFORMATION CAMPAIGN TARGETS BLACK COMMUNITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joyce Bivens remembers her husband's battle with Alzheimer's as
her ``valley experience.''
</P>
<P>
   It began in 1987 with seemingly small things, like his
forgetting where he was going, and didn't end until January when
the Rev. Roy W. Bivens Sr. died in a local nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd always play (the disease) off with his quick wit,'' she
said. ``As it progressed, though, I knew something was dreadfully
wrong, because the bills began doubling up and he began making
mistakes in the pulpit, mixing biblical characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Such behavior is typical of people stricken with Alzheimer's,
the most common form of dementia. But because the debilitating
disease is still a mystery, particularly to the African-American
community, many do not recognize it. And when they do, because of
the stigma associated with the disease, they often do not seek
help.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to change that, the Alzheimer's Association
recently embarked on a campaign to increase awareness about the
disease in the black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a former case manager for senior citizen services, I knew
there were families experiencing dementia, but who were not making
the connection,'' said Jim Walters, the association's family
assistance coordinator in Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   In September, with funding from the Area Agency on Aging, the
association held its first conference to raise awareness in the
African-American communities, specifically Stop 6 and Polytechnic
Heights. Additional workshops for caregivers are being planned for
early next year. The agency also plans to start a support group at
Sweet Home Baptist Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study published recently by ``The Journal of the
American Medical Association,'' African-Americans and Hispanics are
at greater risk of contracting Alzheimer's disease than Anglos. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. A. Ray Lewis, a local family practice physician and
geriatrics fellow at the University of North Texas Health Science
Center in Fort Worth, said that the tremendous effect on families
and the general well-being of patients need to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The needs are really insidious,'' he said. ``It's like all the
other needs related to medical access in the black community.''
</P>
<P>
   Because bizarre behavior is the cornerstone of Alzheimer's,
Lewis said, many in the black community are afraid of confiding
their concern for fear of being misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you try to share stuff with family, people really aren't
able to accept it,'' said Bivens. ``I think historically and
traditionally, African-Americans have not discussed certain things
outside the confines of the home, and so they are not open for the
help that is available. That's not only true with Alzheimer's; it's
also true with cancer, it's true with everything.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bivens said that not seeking help only adds to the family
pressures. Care-givers often make the mistake of treating patients
as children or try to keep them at home past the point when the
family can care for them.
</P>
<P>
   As Bivens' husband deteriorated, it was no longer possible to
leave him alone. He needed 24-hour supervision. Bivens finally had
to make the tough decision to put her husband in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask yourself, what does the patient need and can
you provide it,'' she said. ``If the answer is no, you're doing
them an injustice by selfishly keeping them at home. And just
because they are not under the same roof doesn't mean you're not
caring for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing you can do is to be godly enough to pray about
your situation and be intelligent enough to get the resources that
are available.''
</P>
<P>
   RESOURCES:
</P>
<P>
   The Alzheimer's Disease Education and Referral (ADEAR) Center,
sponsored by the federal government's National Institute on Aging,
has free brochures covering a variety of topics ranging from risk
factors to new treatment options. ADEAR also provides referrals to
research facilities conducting clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call ADEAR at (800) 438-4380 or visit the
organization's Web site at www.alzheimers.org/adear.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
