<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2431 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTRONAUTS-HEROES-BOS     10-28 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTRONAUTS-HEROES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH WARP SPEED, SPACE TRAVEL (AND TRAVELERS) BECAME ORDINARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The first American in orbit, vaguely worried about
sizzling in space, had slipped into a radio blackout. And in her
classroom on Earth, Sister Mary Karen Kelly asked her
second-graders to summon divine help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the radio on and we were praying that he would survive
the trip,'' Sister Kelly recalled as video images of John Glenn
barreling into space flickered behind her at the John F. Kennedy
Library and Museum in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they lost radio contact, that was nail-biting time and a
time for more intense prayer,'' said Sister Kelly, a Grey Nun of
the Sacred Heart from Philadelphia. ``I remember how relieved and
overjoyed we were. Back then, it was something special. Today,
we're more used to it. We're more sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   The same clock that ticks down to Glenn's scheduled return to
space Thursday measures more distance from an era when derring-do
spacemen were enshrined in the pantheon of genuine American heroes,
and an age in which warp-speed technology has reduced orbital
flight to a routine ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids don't grow up wanting to be astronauts anymore,'' said
professor David Mindell of Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
who teaches the history of technology, ``as much as they want to be
Bill Gates.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the prelude to Glenn's blastoff as one of the Shuttle
Discovery's seven crew members has been more about publicity and
nostalgia than the tension and excitement he evoked on Feb. 20,
1962, when he was strapped into the capsule called Friendship 7 and
shot into space.
</P>
<P>
   He was Colonel John H. Glenn Jr. then, the captain of a
relatively crude and untested rocketship for three orbits around
the Earth, an early leg in the United States's come-from-behind
space race victory against its sworn enemy, the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Now Glenn, a 77-year-old Democratic senator from Ohio, is a
passenger on a complex machine in which he plays a decidedly
supporting _ some say superfluous _ role in the latest in a series
of missions to which the American public has long since stopped
paying rapt attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody cares anymore,'' said Peter B. Crabb, a psychology
professor at the University of Pennsylvania, where he studies
technology and the perception of it. ``Space missions have become
so routine that like other technological wonders, nobody thinks
about them or notices them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing sexy about it. These guys go up. They come
back down. It's about business, not space exploration. It's a
bore.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than 90 launches of the space shuttle since 1981, the
ship has lived up to a name connoting easy access in and out of the
upper atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists say the journey from the Orville Wright of space
travel to blastoffs of boredom on Cape Canaveral is an
extraordinary one whose mileposts are a flag on the moon, a
crumbling wall in Berlin, and silicon computer chips that have made
smaller the world Glenn hurtled over while those who watched and
waited held their breath.
</P>
<P>
   The day Glenn forever became a space-suited icon, President
Kennedy's New Frontier was embryonic, John Volpe was in the
governor's office, and Bob Cousy ran the backcourt for the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   New England, still recovering from a northeaster that had dumped
a foot of snow on the region the night before, walked away from its
work-day machines in such numbers on that fateful Tuesday that the
New England Electric System in Boston recorded a marked reduction
in the demand for electric power.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months after the Soviet Union stunned the world in April
1961 by sending Yuri Gagarin into space for one orbit of the globe,
the United States was belatedly back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in a very real sense a heroic moment,'' said Frank
Rigg, curator of the JFK Library and Museum, which opens a new
Glenn exhibit on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was a person who was literally risking his life for a
purpose that was a good purpose and the continuation of the human
story,'' said Rigg. ``It was absolutely terra incognita. People
were simply amazed. Glenn became a hero in the sense that (aviator
Charles) Lindbergh had been.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most perilous moment of Glenn's voyage arrived when
a warning light at Mission Control erroneously indicated a problem
with the capsule's heat shield. Glenn, whose pulse on liftoff was
an imperturbable 110 beats per minute, later wrote that he was
prepared to die for his country in the 3,000-degree heat of
reentry. Although he was never directly told of the heat-shield
scare, Glenn said later he figured out that his life could be in
danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being scared,'' recalled 47-year-old Micala Jensen
of Utah, who this week was reviewing Glenn memorabilia at the JFK
Library this week. ``But once he was back, it was thrilling. We
were catching up with the Russians. We were actually going to do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And despite setbacks and tragedy, the United States did do it,
winning the race to the moon and achieving unquestioned space-age
superiority. Along the way, communism collapsed, the Berlin Wall
fell, the Cold War thawed.
</P>
<P>
   And that, specialists agree, is precisely why Glenn's return to
space now conjures adjectives like poignant and quaint, not
thrilling or urgent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation's dominant narrative used to be its Cold War
struggle,'' said Ralph Whitehead, who teaches journalism at the
University of Massachusetts at Amherst. ``But space flights are no
longer part of that saga. They simply don't have the national
significance anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   There will doubtless be few schoolchildren petitioning the
heavens when the shuttle lifts off next week _ a mission commanded
by an astronaut almost no one knows, Curtis Brown Jr. of North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few things that can surprise us anymore,'' Rigg
said. ``There is this sense that so much is possible and that we
can do so much. I'm not sure that's an entirely postive thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the days of the space race, said Steven Johnson, editor of
the on-line magazine Feed, the premium on technology has shifted
from the big and the powerful to the small and the fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of physically doing something _ shooting people up
into outer space and those other kind of mechanical, industrial
feats _ is not as captivating as the stuff that happens on our
computer screens,'' Johnson said. ``Today we talk about speed and
how we can connect to another computer server, not how can I move
my body from one place to another.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Beth Adelson, associate professor of psychology at Rutgers
University: ``We are inundated with amazing events. When you go out
into the sunshine, at first it looks dazzling. But then your eyes
adapt to that level of light and it's no longer dazzling.''
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Young, MIT's Apollo professor of astronautics, said
it's not surprising there are few sweaty palms on the days the
launch pads light up in Florida. Most college students weren't yet
born when Neil Armstrong walked on the moon in July 1969 as 500
million watched on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect it to go well. It's no longer seen as
dangerous,'' Young said. ``Students have the sense that the space
program was something that belonged to their fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Young, who heads a consortium preparing for a
distant manned mission to Mars, said Glenn's flight next week is
important even if it has more to do with publicity than science.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wrong with propaganda?'' asked Young. ``We need a
national hero at this point. We need something that says to kids,
`Work hard. Study algebra. Go to space camp because you can be part
of this great adventure.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to believe again that space belongs to all of us.
We're all stockholders. We've all paid for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
