<HEADLINE>
TROJANS HOPING TO LAND BIG MAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC will have its biggest recruiting visit of the
season _ literally _ when 7-foot-3 center Luke Minor of Blue Ridge
High School in Dyke, Va., makes his official visit to the campus
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Minor could give USC coach Henry Bibby his first true center and
answer the one glaring weakness remaining in the Trojans' lineup.
USC does not have a player on its current roster taller than 6-9.
</P>
<P>
   Minor has also made visits to Oregon and Kansas State and is
expected to sign a national letter of intent during the early
signing period next month.
</P>
<P>
   USC has only one scholarship remaining and would like to use it
on Minor. The Trojans have already received a commitment from 6-4
shooting guard Nate Hair of Capistrano Valley High School.
</P>
<P>
   __ Youngsters start quickly: After two weeks of practice, some
underclassmen have been among the most impressive players for the
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore guard Jeff Trepagnier, sophomore forward/center Brian
Scalabrine, sophomore forward Shannon Swillis and freshman point
guard Brandon Granville have all been playing well.
</P>
<P>
   All of those players have the potential to start for the
Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Kevin Augustine, penciled in as the starter at point
guard, has missed several days of practice with a twisted foot, but
it is not considered serious.
</P>
</TEXT>
