<SLUG> BC-DEPOT-CONSUMER29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Issue rarely raised, home builders say
 &HT;    By Gene Tharpe
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Quality and availability _ not age or origin _ are
usually the major concerns when buying lumber, several Atlanta home
builders and remodelers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we need to help protect our environment, but I
personally don't think about it much when I am buying what lumber I
need for a project,'' said Al Capogrossi, a Stone Mountain,
Ga.-based home remodeler.
</P>
<P>
   ``With old-growth wood, I usually am buying to match existing
wood that's already in the house,'' Capogrossi said. ``I'm not
looking at how old it is or where it came from.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Brutera of Homes by Brutera in Snellville, Ga., said he
seldom has any need for old-growth, specialty or rare wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``In building homes, we deal mainly with spruce and fir, and we
look for quality and specific grades of lumber we need to meet
building codes,'' Brutera said. ``In fact, I'm not even sure what
old-growth lumber is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Weidmann of Weidmann &AMP; Associates, an suburban Atlanta
remodeling firm, said the major factor in buying lumber for a
project is to buy whatever wood is specified by the customer or
architect. ``The customer may understand the lumber is now rare or
endangered, but if a customer decides not to use it, it's usually
because he or she did not understand how expensive it is today.''
</P>
<P>
   David Chatham, president of Roswell, Ga.-based Chatham Holding
Corp., a home builder, said most home construction companies use
lumber from new-growth forests, not rare or specialty woods from
old-growth forests.
</P>
<P>
   Many such woods are ``very specialized, hard to find, and most
people don't have any idea where they come from,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chatham said protecting the environment is an important issue to
most home builders, but ``sometimes some of the environmentalists
go overboard about it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
