<HEADER>
A2440 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARAFAT-GAZA-BOS &LR;      10-28 1252
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARAFAT-GAZA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAFAT RETURNS TO CHEERS AND REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  GAZA _ Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat returned
home Wednesday to a well-orchestrated hero's welcome and a
Palestinian population skeptical that the peace agreement he signed
in Washington will ever materialize.
</P>
<P>
   His motorcade whipped along a Palestinian-built coastal road
past schoolchildren waving posters of him, troops standing in
salute, and armored military vehicles draped with the Palestinian
flag.
</P>
<P>
   But just behind the cheering crowds lay the grim realities of
life in Gaza on the edge of peace. Squalid refugee camps abut the
new seaside mansions of Palestinian leaders. The stench of human
refuse wafts over stacks of sewer pipes never installed in one of
many long-delayed public works' projects. These failed promises
fuel the disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   After a tour of Arab states to build support for the
land-for-security-deal signed Friday in Washington, Arafat began
the hard sell to his people. He told them of his confidence that
the plan would be implemented and that it was an important step
toward the creation of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Like Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Arafat will face
fierce political attacks from extremists vowing to derail a process
they view as a sellout. He must also stave off a deep mistrust and
growing impatience among Palestinians about the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Before Arafat left for the Wye summit, a Palestinian poll showed
that more than half of Palestinians supported a return to armed
conflict against Israel. But these challenges, and the means at his
disposal, are profoundly different than those of the Netanyahu
government.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Arafat does not have to deal with the demands of
a functioning democracy. Although democratically elected, his
stature as a symbol of resistance has won him authoritarian rule.
Commonly referred to as ``The Leader,'' Arafat has supressed
criticism of his government and has already begun a crackdown on
militants with little regard to human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists have been arrested in recent days, and Palestinian
security forces shot and killed a 17-year-old activist during a
raid Sunday on a headquarters of the Fatah political party. Both
incidents prompted street riots led by groups opposed to the
Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat must balance the role he has been given with the pressing
need to control militant groups such as the Islamic organization,
Hamas, so that the larger Palestinian population can reap the
benefits of peace. Pursuit of the military wing of Hamas is a
security requirement Palestinians must provide to Israelis under
the agreement if Israeli troops are to withdraw from an additional
13 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But the dismantling of Hamas is also a political necessity for
Arafat. If this agreement is not implemented, many analysts believe
the historic Oslo peace process begun five years ago is doomed,
along with Arafat's enduring dream of an independent Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
   Inaz Ramadan, 31, a mother of three, captured a pervasive
discontent among Palestinians when she said, ``We keep hoping for
more and more and ending up with less and less. The people are fed
up. There is a feeling of depression.''
</P>
<P>
   A construction worker, Said Diyab, 32, who toiled in a hot sun,
said, ``I haven't followed this agreement. We don't have
electricity in our area so we can't see it on TV. But it doesn't
matter. It won't actually be implemented.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, six Palestinian opposition groups in Gaza have publicly
attacked the Wye agreement as ``another retreat in a series of
retreats,'' and warned that it could lead to ``civil war.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement represents a dangerous plot by Washington and
Israel to destroy the power of the Palestinian people,'' said a
newspaper advertisement paid for by Hamas, the Islamic Jihad, the
National Islamic Salvation Party, and the Democratic and Popular
Fronts and the Arab Liberation Front.
</P>
<P>
   Mahmoud Zahar, a physician and a leader of Hamas, said, ``The
majority of Palestinians are not interested in this agreement. They
no longer believe in Oslo. They no longer have trust that it will
be implemented. Ask people about corruption in the Palestinian
Authority, ask them about the violation of human rights by Arafat's
security forces. Arafat has already lost the support of the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   With grass-roots support, Hamas has provided for years a network
of schools, clinics, and Islamic associations for poor
Palestinians. It openly calls for the destruction of Israel and is
reflexively opposed to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   In response to terrorist attacks carried out by Hamas's military
wing, Arafat, at the insistence of Israel and the United States,
attacked what became known as Hamas's ``infrastructure of terror.''
The Palestinian Authority shut down the schools and the clinics.
Now it must prove that it can step up its fight by rooting out
Hamas's armed wing. Zahar says that battling Hamas will ultimately
hurt Arafat politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who was affected by this? The poor. And there are many of us
here. The Palestinian Authority will pay a price for that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   More centrist critics, such as Jihad Alwazir, director of Gaza's
World Trade Center, agree that Arafat has lost political support
and that the implementation of the Wye agreement is urgently
needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oslo has been dead for a while. They tried to resuscitate it.
But we will need to see real improvement on the ground: an airport,
safe passage between Gaza and the West Bank. Then perhaps people
will support the process again,'' said Alwazir. ``We are all a bit
wiser and more cynical now.''
</P>
<P>
   That cynicism has been fueled by Netanyahu's recent announcement
that he would postpone the ratification of the agreement by his
Cabinet until the Palestinians deliver a formal outline of their
security plan. He said the timetable for troop withdrawals would
not take effect until acceptance of the security plan.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will result in Israel ceding a further 13 percent
of the West Bank, the opening of the Palestinian airport, and the
creation of ``safe passage'' between Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the Palestinians must implement:
</P>
<P>
   _A ``systematic and effective combat of terrorist organization
and their infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   _``Apprehend specific individuals suspected of perpetrating
violence and terror.''
</P>
<P>
   _A ``systematic program'' for ``collection of weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   _A formal rewriting of the Palestinian Liberation Organization's
covenant that would annul passages that call for the destruction of
the state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu told reporters in Jerusalem Wednesday, ``There's a
very simple principle here. They do it, they get it. They don't do
it, they don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leaders blasted this rhetoric as a violation of the
agreement and yet another example of foot-dragging by Netanyahu's
government, which is threatened by intense opposition from its
far-right factions. But Arafat remained confident Wednesday,
saying, ``I think that what has been signed will be implemented
accurately.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by television crews what he wanted to tell the Palestinian
people, Arafat responded, ``My message ... is to continue together
until all of us pray in holy Al Quds, the capital of the
Palestinian state.'' Al Quds is Arabic for Jerusalem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
