<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2445 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-MITCH-HNS &LR;      10-28 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-MITCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MITCH STALLS, BATTERS HONDURAS WITH 115 MPH WINDS, RELENTLESS RAIN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EDWARD HEGSTROM 
and ANDREW DOWNIE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELMOPAN, Belize _ Hurricane Mitch stalled off Honduras on
Wednesday, battering it with huge waves and fierce winds while
forcing people in its expected path to stock up on food and hunker
down in shelters.
</P>
<P>
   In Belmopan, the capital of Belize, as many as 10,000 people
settled into shelters and braced themselves for a hurricane that
traveled little during the day. ``They say the hurricane hasn't
moved,'' said Emelia Cayetano, a Belize army official overseeing a
shelter holding 300 people. ``We're the same way _ just sitting
here, not moving.''
</P>
<P>
   To the north, in Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula where Mitch was
expected to strike later in the week, many people took no chances,
buying supplies and filling cupboards. ``A lot of people have been
stocking up,'' said Honorio May, who owns a general store outside
Cancun. ``We've had maybe 800 people in here to buy canned goods,
bread, water and biscuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters at the National Hurricane Center in Miami said Mitch
was likely to remain a threat to the region for the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Although the storm's force diminished since Tuesday when its 180
mph winds cut through the Caribbean, it still thrashed Honduras
with maximum sustained winds of 115 mph and poured up to 25 inches
of rain over a vast region in Central America, the hurricane center
said.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday night, the hurricane's eye stood about 25 miles
north of the coast of Honduras after sitting for several hours atop
Honduras' Bay Islands, a rustic tourist area popular with divers,
fishermen and sun-seekers.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane-force winds from the storm extended outward up to 105
miles, while its tropical storm-force winds spread outward up to
175 miles from the eye, forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   The 350-mile-wide storm was expected to weaken somewhat when it
moves into Belize, but its rains took a toll in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   According to wire service reports, more than 50 rivers
overflowed their banks in Honduras, and authorities there ordered
the evacuations of an estimated 45,000 people. Many towns were cut
off by washed-out roads and downed bridges. Severed phone lines on
the Bay Islands made it difficult to gauge the extent of the damage
there, but ham radio reports indicated it was extensive. President
Carlos Flores Facusse of Honduras declared the country's Caribbean
coast a disaster zone.
</P>
<P>
   Wire services reported at least 35 deaths from the storm _ 23 in
Honduras alone, eight in Nicaragua and one each in Mexico, Costa
Rica, Panama and Jamaica. The toll was expected to increase once
cut-off areas reestablished communications.
</P>
<P>
   Belize City, Belize's capital until 1961 when it was destroyed
by Hurricane Hattie, was virtually deserted Wednesday. The
government had issued a hurricane warning on Tuesday, sending
thousands of residents scurrying away from the coastal city.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus caused bumper-to-bumper traffic on the main road
leaving the city. But once inland, many found little to keep them
occupied Wednesday. Some sunbathed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the government was not willing to suggest that they
return home. ``This hurricane is just so unpredictable,'' said
Godfrey Smith, the Belize prime minister's chief of staff.
``There's nothing to do now, but we're certainly not going to send
people home.''
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline was unavailable throughout most of the former British
colony of nearly 200,000 people. The government acknowledged that
it had cut off supplies to save the fuel for use after the
hurricane moved out of the country. Food and water shortages also
were reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Belmopan, a small town about 40 miles southwest of Belize
City that now serves as the nation's capital, people settled into
shelters, but some tensions began to appear by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not enough room,'' complained Anacleto Martinez, one
of 300 people who was trying to sleep on the floor of a Roman
Catholic Church annex.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez and his 11 relatives squeezed into a 10-square foot
area and shared just one mattress. Children played throughout the
shelter while their parents tried to cook with limited supplies.
One outdoor spigot with a bucket served as the sink for all 300
people.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula, many people said they had little
idea where or when the storm would hit. Rumors abounded, and radio
stations often broadcast conflicting or confusing reports about the
storm's whereabouts and path throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday they said it was going to hit today, and today they
say it is going to hit tomorrow,'' said May, the owner of the small
general store in Akumal, about an hour's drive south of Cancun.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, the weather along Yucatan's Caribbean coast
changed between bright, if clouded, skies and torrential rains. By
late afternoon, the sea was hammering the coast and the rain was
falling steadily.
</P>
<P>
   In Tulum, where expansive Maya temples overlooked the pounding
surf, guides prepared to close the site. The owners of a dozen or
so stalls had packed up and visitors had cleared the area, said the
site's chief, Camilo Kamal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally we get between 700 and 800 people here a day; but
today, because of the weather, there's only been about 30,'' said
Kamal. ``Everybody left yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   A small hotel near the entrance to the ruins was nearly empty,
and owner Felipe Ramirez made final preparations to handle a most
unwelcome guest named Mitch. The bar was taped up with red and blue
plastic sheeting, and the windows were crisscrossed with masking
tape. Ramirez's assistant even moved the bar's refrigerators into a
storeroom, ``so they don't take off'' when the storm blows through.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the hotel, newlyweds Susana and Juan Vaquero from
Barcelona, Spain, sat and watched the rain pour. They came to the
Cancun area for sun and sand and instead got soaked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in Havana and had a ticket for here,'' Susana Vaquero
explained. ``At that time we didn't know if the hurricane was
coming here or going to Cuba, so since we had the ticket, we
decided just to come. We'll probably stay here, especially if it
isn't getting closer.''
</P>
<P>
   And their honeymoon? ``Unforgettable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edward Hegstrom, reporting from Belmopan, Belize, and Andrew
Downie, reporting from Cancun, Mexico, are free-lance journalists.
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
