<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH LIFTS GALVESTON BAY OYSTER BAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CINDY HORSWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Health is lifting a four-month ban on
sale of Galveston Bay oysters intended to be eaten raw.
</P>
<P>
   Effective Sunday, the oysters _ popularly served on-the-shell or
on-the-half-shell _ can be shipped or sold. During the ban they had
to be removed from their shells.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Health Commissioner William R. Archer III said the ban was
lifted because the bacteria ``Vibrio parahaemolyticus,'' which
infected Texas oysters and was blamed for diarrheal illnesses in
416 people, cannot flourish in the cooler water temperatures now
found in the bay.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally occurring in coastal waters worldwide, the bacteria is
more abundant in warm weather.
</P>
<P>
   Also, historical data indicates no oyster-related cases of the
bacterial ailment in Texas after October.
</P>
<P>
   All sale of oysters from Galveston Bay was halted June 26, but
the ban was partially lifted Oct. 3 when the state Health
Department permitted the sale of shucked oysters that were labeled
``For cooked consumption only.''
</P>
<P>
   During the summer months, oysters are only harvested from
private leases where they have been gathered from restricted areas
and allowed to purge themselves of impurities.
</P>
<P>
   The oyster season for the rest of the bay is slated to open
Sunday. However, Archer said elevated levels of harmful bacteria
from floodwater pouring into the coastal waters could delay the
start of the seasons in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Health Department officials are monitoring bacterial counts and
should know Friday which areas will need to be remain closed to
fishermen.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas oyster season runs from Nov. 1 through April 30.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials routinely advise that anyone with liver disease
or immune system problems avoid eating raw shellfish. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
