<SLUG> BC-MITCH-MEXICO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN COAST BRACES FOR DEADLY HURRICANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANCUN, Mexico _ How do you prepare for an unwanted and angry
visitor?
</P>
<P>
   With Hurricane Mitch seemingly stuck in its massive swirl in the
Caribbean just north of the Honduran coast, Belize to Mexico's
Yucatan Peninsula continued guessing about its trajectory and
protecting themselves if the storm takes a northward turn.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the storm's powerful branches pelted regions of
Honduras with 120 m.p.h. winds, killing 32 people
</P>
<P>
   In this resort city about 375 miles north of Honduras and
Mexico's most popular destination for US tourists, government
officials and hotel managers alike expressed optimism that they
would escape the storm's fury. But the hurricane's size and
strength scared about 20,000 US tourists away early, the government
said, and brought back painful memories of Gilbert, an even bigger
storm that devastated the area in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there were 14,470 hotel rooms in Cancun. Now there are
nearly 24,000, according the Hotel Association of Cancun. Another
7,000 rooms will be built over the next few years, said Alejandro
Gongora Vera, the local director of the federal tourism agency
known as Fonatur.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned many serious lessons from Gilbert and as a result,
we believe that our hotels are very well-built,'' Gongora said.
``But the most important lesson was to take hurricane warnings very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Cancun's 125 hotels are required to participate in
coordinated evacuation and protection plans when a hurricane
threatens the narrow strip of land where most of the structures are
located. Newer structures were also forced to be built further back
from the shore because of beach erosion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a tourist area, Cancun is only 30 years old,'' said the
city's mayor, Rafael Lara, who canceled the city's full alert early
in the day but warned residents to be ready if things change. ``We
weren't prepared for Gilbert because we had never experienced
anything like that. But now we know what we need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another post-Gilbert strategy that Cancun and other areas
benefit from today are cable and satellite television and the
Internet, all of which offer hotels and officials up-to-the-minute
advisories of a storm's progress.
</P>
<P>
   But even the best precautions won't keep guests from leaving if
danger seems near. Hundreds of visitors crammed the Cancun airport
Wednesday trying to get a seat on overbooked flights. Many hotel
representatives said they were at about 35-40 percent capacity,
about half the normal rate for this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is usually a pretty busy time for us because of the
colder weather back in the US,'' said Raul Mesa Quinones, a manager
at a three-story waterfront hotel who Wednesday saw a dozen guests
check out early.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak Tuesday, Mitch was classified as the
fourth-strongest Caribbean hurricane this century with 180 m.p.h.
winds. By Wednesday afternoon, the 350-mile-wide storm's sustained
winds were down to 120 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   The US National Weather Service said only three Atlantic storms
were stronger than Mitch at its peak: Gilbert in 1988, Allen in
1980, and the Labor Day hurricane of 1935.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sun shone for most of Wednesday here, clouds, heavy
wind and rain returned by early evening _ a sign for some residents
that Mitch was still on his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not panicking, but we're not thinking that it's over
yet,'' said Carmen Villasantos, 44, as she left a Wal Mart with a
cart full of supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The rainfall _ up to 25 inches in mountainous areas of Honduras
_ began to take a toll. More than 50 rivers had overran their
banks, and the government evacuated more than 45,000 people from
low-lying areas, according to Col. Guillermo Pinel, chief of the
country's National Emergency Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Belize City, Belize's capital until 1961 when it was destroyed
by Hurricane Hattie, was a ghost town. Most of its 75,000 residents
had fled in cars buses commandeered by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Police and soldiers patrolled the streets, and a few people
wandered amid the boarded-up houses. The cable television company
was broadcasting only the weather channel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
