<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2461 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVING-REVIEW-LADN     10-28 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVING-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LIVING OUT LOUD' CONNECTS IN GENUINE WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Living Out Loud'' is a little film about people fighting
loneliness in the Big Apple. The movie marks the directorial debut
of esteemed screenwriter Richard LaGravenese (``The Fisher King,''
``The Horse Whisperer,'' ``Beloved'') and it succeeds in achieving
its modest goals with a tough-minded realism that's typically
absent from romantic movies.
</P>
<P>
   LaGravenese (who also wrote the screenplay) dispenses with the
cutesy-pie dramatics from the outset when we're introduced to
Judith Nelson (Holly Hunter), a woman adrift after her wealthy
doctor husband left her for a younger woman. We're present at the
dumping.
</P>
<P>
   Since Judith has spent so much of her life absorbed in denying
her own dreams to please her husband, she has little identity left
of her own once he walks out. You can feel her emptiness just by
looking at the bare walls of her apartment. This is a solitary soul
who watches and worries over the depressing events on the evening
news simply because the background noise keeps her company.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to reconnect with the outside world, Judith begins
frequenting Jasper's, a downtown jazz club that features a sultry
chanteuse (Queen Latifah) as its featured entertainment. At first,
Judith is more successful fantasizing about meeting people than she
is in actually making contact. But that changes through a
passionate case of mistaken identity. One kiss and Judith is on the
road to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bumpy ride, though. Seeing things as if for the first
time, Judith forms a friendship with her building's elevator
operator, Pat (Danny DeVito). Pat is another dreamer whose life is
on the skids _ terminally ill daughter, terminally absent wife and
a pile of debt owed to underworld loan sharks. While Pat never
stops believing in himself, he realizes his life would be a lot
better if he had someone who shared that belief.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Judith.
</P>
<P>
   LaGravenese, who based his screenplay on two short stories by
Anton Chekhov, ``The Kiss'' and ``Misery,'' has created a sweet,
uplifting movie that never lapses into easy sentimentality or
predictability. The film's basic message _ redemption can come from
the smallest of human connections _ is elegantly stated through
believable characters who never lose their messy foibles just so
we'll like them better.
</P>
<P>
   DeVito gives a charmingly vulnerable performance and Queen
Latifah does some surprisingly credible versions of jazz and pop
standards. But the movie belongs to Hunter, who, in the film's
scant 93-minute running time, conveys a vivid portrait of a woman
in her mid-40s rediscovering what it means to be authentic and
alive.
</P>
<P>
   The findings don't set off any huge emotional fireworks or grand
insights into life's deeper meanings. But they make for a nice
human moment or two, which counts for something when it pertains to
movies and, quite often, everything when it pertains to reality. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 2106EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2465 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLYMPIAN-SUIT-HNS &LR;      10-28 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPIAN-SUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIAN'S COURT VICTORY BRINGS BITTERSWEET LESSON IN ADULT LIFE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ This victory brought Olympic gold-medal gymnast
Dominique Moceanu no joy.
</P>
<P>
   Scarcely acknowledging her parents by her side, Moceanu on
Wednesday ended an ordeal that began when she ran away from home
Oct. 17. In the eyes of the law, she now is an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Dumitru Moceanu, 44, choked back tears and could
barely speak as state District Judge John Montgomery asked him
three times if he agreed with allowing his daughter to be declared
an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a right to have a trial,'' Montgomery said to Dumitru
Moceanu during a tense and silent pause.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Dumitru Moceanu mumbled ``Yes,'' while dejectedly
shaking his head yes to indicate he would acquiesce to his
daughter's wishes and allow her to be declared an adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the hardest thing I've ever done in my life, even harder
than competing in the Olympics,'' the younger Moceanu said, poised
but clearly shaken, after the brief hearing. ``It's a great, but a
sad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, 17, took no questions after her short statement, but
indicated her battles with her parents may not be finished. She
said her lawyer, Roy W. Moore, will help her investigate her
finances to see if the money she has earned in her seven-year
professional career has been squandered by her parents.
</P>
<P>
   In order to demand an accounting of her money, Moceanu first had
to be declared an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Moceanu is not entitled to have access to her trust
account until she is 35. She said she had always assumed the money
would be available when she turned 18, but found out in a newspaper
article last week this wasn't true. Katherine Scardino, the
parents' attorney, said Moceanu should have known about the trust
fund because she signed off on it.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Koenig, an attorney with Fulbright &AMP; Jaworski who
specializes in trusts, said after minors are certified as adults
they can change the terms of a trust set up for them. This is
because they can claim that as minors, they did not realize what
they were doing, Koenig said.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu filed a lawsuit Oct. 19 seeking adult status, alleging
the trust fund set up in her name is all but gone. The next day,
she also said her parents have taken away her childhood by always
pressuring her to compete in gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents have denied the allegations. Dumitru Moceanu has
said all of his daughter's trust fund has been used to build a
70,000-square-foot gym at 6120 Louetta that opened last year, a gym
he says the young Moceanu wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Scardino has said the gym cost $2 million. When it opened, the
family said it cost $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Moceanu parents declined to comment after Wednesday's
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very upset, Camelia is doing better than Dumitru.
It's hard for the father to let go of his little girl,'' Scardino
said after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The Moceanus had said they would oppose their daughter's request
to seek adult status, but changed their mind Tuesday during a
scheduled deposition of Moceanu by the parents' attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Scardino said the parents had a change of heart because they
realized, ``to show her they loved her, they had to let her go.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu said she will not go back to her parents' Spring, Texas,
home, but to an apartment she moved into last week.
</P>
<P>
   After signing the order, Montgomery said, ``I sincerely wish you
all the best of luck on the first day of the rest of your lives.
It's not a pleasant situation to come to court. I sympathize.''
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu spoke briefly with her mother after the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Moore said she plans to stay in the Houston area and
resume training. She is a student at the private Northland
Christian School.
</P>
<P>
   According to Harris County property records, a corporation
listed under Dumitru Moceanu's name, Moceanu Gymnastics Inc. (MGI)
built the gym and is entitled to all the profits from the gym.
Scardino said the gym earned the parents $15,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, Woodforest National Bank issued a $750,000
loan to pay for the gym's construction. The daughter's trust fund
has to pay the loan by November 1999. She will be 18 on Sept. 30,
1999. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
