<HEADER>
A2473 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIGHWAY-PLANE-CRASH-C     10-28 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIGHWAY-PLANE-CRASH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plane crashes into highway at height of rush hour
 &HT;    By Scott Marshall
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A small plane en route from Bessemer, Ala., sputtered
and crashed in flames onto Ga. 400 in Sandy Springs, Ga., at the
height of rush hour Wednesday evening, killing a motorist and
injuring the pilot.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, possibly having an electrical problem, was trying to
reach Peachtree-DeKalb Airport when she crashed into a southbound
lane of Ga. 400 at the Roberts Drive overpass, near the Northridge
Road exit, fire officials and dispatchers said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of motorists on the heavily traveled commuter corridor
watched the 6:25 p.m. crash, but no one else was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot was the only person in the Piper Saratoga, said
Kathleen Bergen, a spokeswoman for the Federal Aviation
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Another plane was seen near the falling plane, witnesses said.
The National Transportation Safety Board was investigating.
</P>
<P>
   After encountering trouble, the pilot of the Saratoga reported
her instruments were failing and officials began clearing airspace
at Peachtree-DeKalb Airport, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   But instead, the plane went down on the highway, striking a
southbound vehicle, which partially overturned.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot was taken to Grady Memorial Hospital with second
degree burns on her upper body and injuries to her back, neck and
pelvis. She was in satisfactory condition an hour after the crash,
said Walter Ingram, a doctor in the burn unit.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot was conscious and talking to doctors. Ingram said he
was surprised to see her burns were not extensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into the ER and saw her,'' Ingram said. ``I said: `Is
this the right person?' I was expecting to see something much
worse.'' Neither the pilot nor the dead motorist was identified.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Beasley of Ball Ground, Ga., was nearly a casualty. She
was driving south on Ga. 400 on her way to work at Scottish Rite
Medical Center, where she is a registered nurse. She had just
checked the rear-view mirror of her Jeep Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of a sudden something hit me and it threw my car forward.
I looked in the rear view and I was losing control.''
</P>
<P>
   She sped up.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw fire and sparks right on the back of my car. I was all
over the road. I could tell it was an airplane.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, she said, she was swerving on the road and
thought she was going to hit the wall and blow up or catch on fire.
She managed to stop her car, got out and she and a woman who had
been driving behind her hugged each other and watched the wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lawson was inside his suburban Atlanta home when he heard
the troubled airplane at 6:25 p.m. ``What made me go outside and
look was I heard the engine and the pilot was revving it,'' he
said. ``I saw the plane pass over and it sounded like it was
running on a couple of cylinders.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawson, who has taken flying lessons, said the pilot was
feathering the engine _ disengaging it _ to build up rpms to gain
more power. ``That's probably what was keeping her going,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the plane was about 300-to-400 feet overhead and a
twin-engine plane was following at about the same altitude just a
few seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   The crash halted traffic in both directions on Ga. 400, blocking
even the emergency lanes and delaying a platoon of emergency
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The southbound lanes of Ga. 400 were expected to be closed for
several hours. All but one northbound lane near the scene were open
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
