<SLUG> BC-POWER-WALLST29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An assessment of Wall Street's power brokers
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wall Street is a six-block strip of Lower Manhattan between a
graveyard and a river. But it's also ``the center of the financial
universe,'' Worth (November) notes in a report that surveys
history, players and trends.
</P>
<P>
   Worth profiles Wall Street's ``20 most powerful people,'' who
``finance our households, lubricate the wheels of industry and fund
entire nations.'' Among them are David H. Komansky, chairman and
chief executive officer of Merrill Lynch; Sanford I. Weill, now
co-chairman and co-chief executive officer at Citigroup; buyout
king Henry Kravis; bullish strategist Abby Joseph Cohen; and media
magnate Michael Bloomberg.
</P>
<P>
   Worth sums up the Street with a quote from etiquette expert
Letitia Baldrige: ``Wall Street has some of the very best and the
very worst types of people in American society.''
</P>
<P>
   Worth's special section is just one of a number of efforts to
help readers deal with today's investment markets and economy:
</P>
<P>
   _ Smart Money (November) offers ``the one investment guide you
really need now,'' which reminds us ``periods of fear and
uncertainty often prove to be the best time to invest.'' This
edition looks at smaller stocks _ which may be the best buys now _
and strategies to adjust an investor's mix of stocks, bonds and
other assets based on age.
</P>
<P>
   _ Individual Investor (November) looks at strategies that enable
some mutual funds to perform well in a bear market. The winners
tend to be funds that invest in futures or use other hedging
techniques to post gains in a down market.
</P>
<P>
   _ Specialty magazines such as Working Woman (November) also
provide practical advice. In this case, when to bail out of a
mutual fund. A clue: If you're losing sleep worrying about your
holdings, it's time to sell.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leave it to The Economist (Oct. 30) to splash the cold water
of reality in our faces, reminding readers ``the world's financial
and economic troubles are not over'' despite the recent stock
market rally. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan gets some
credit for boosting the economy with two interest rate cuts, but
the magazine quips ``even Mr. Greenspan cannot prevent a bear
market with a mere wave of his wand.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Penny-pinching architects
</P>
<P>
   In an era of cost cutting and downsizing, architects contribute
to business by designing attractive structures at minimal expense,
Business Week (Nov. 2) says in its second annual architecture
awards edition, in conjunction with Architectural Record (October).
</P>
<P>
   The winner was the new headquarters of Gap in San Bruno, Calif.,
whose West Coast designers _ William McDonough + Partners and
Gensler _ created a three-section building with grass on the roof
and workstations within 30 feet of daylight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
