A2475 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOFA-SFCHRON &LR;      10-28 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BofA CEO Will Stay 2 Years Longer  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hugh McColl, who heads the new BankAmerica Corp., will stay on the
job until 2002, two years beyond the bank's normal retirement age,
BofA said yesterday.
<P>
   The announcement that McColl, 63, will remain longer as chairman
and chief executive came a month after Charlotte, N.C.'s
NationsBank Corp. bought San Francisco's BofA and adopted its name,
forming the nation's second-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days ago, the North Carolina bank announced the
resignation of David Coulter, the old BofA's CEO who briefly held
the No. 2 job at the combined bank.
</P>
<P>
   McColl forced out the 51-year-old Coulter after the old BofA
recorded steep losses in trading and investment banking, including
a $372 million write-down of a loan to D.E. Shaw &AMP; Co., a New York
investment firm specializing in computer-based securities trading.
</P>
<P>
   When BofA and NationsBank agreed to merge six months ago, McColl
declared it was his ``present intention'' that Coulter eventually
replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts noted at the time that the statement was full of
loopholes and that Coulter was not likely to get the top job.
McColl ``didn't have any intention of turning things over to
Coulter,'' said Sutro &AMP; Co. analyst Michael Abrahams. ``Having
disposed of Coulter, he had a rationale for extending his tenure.''
</P>
<P>
   BofA said McColl agreed to postpone his retirement after the
bank's new board, in its first meeting since the acquisition took
effect, unanimously asked him to remain.
</P>
<P>
   After the merger, the bank's board was made up of 11 directors
from NationsBank and nine from the old BofA. Coulter, a member of
the board, did not attend yesterday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank recently eliminated a rule requiring senior
executives to step down at 65, a bank spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement accepting the board's request, McColl touted the
role of the bank's executive committee, consisting of its six top
managers. The committee includes two executives from the old BofA:
corporate banking chief Michael Murray and investment management
chief Michael O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason I am happy to stay longer is that the other members
of the (committee) all have committed to working together,'' McColl
said. ``This will allow us to keep our team together.''
</P>
<P>
   By highlighting Murray and O'Neill, analysts said, McColl is
trying to boost the morale of the old BofA staff, which was laid
low by NationsBank's lightening moves to seize control of the
combined bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``McColl wants to preserve the illusion that it was a merger as
opposed to an acquisition, which is a pretty tough sell right
now,'' Abrahams said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, BofA's board raised the bank's quarterly dividend 7
cents to 45 cents a share, an 18 percent increase. The dividend is
payable December 23 to shareholders of record on December 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
