<SLUG> BC-SEC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SEC Charges 44 With Fraud Via Internet  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
In what federal authorities call the biggest crackdown on Internet
fraud, the Securities and Exchange Commission yesterday charged 44
individuals and companies with falsely promoting small stocks to
cheat investors.
<P>
   In 23 enforcement actions, the SEC charged the defendants used
unsolicited commercial e-mail, electronic bulletin boards and Web
sites to illegally tout ``microcap'' securities over the Net
without disclosing they received $6.2 million and nearly 2 million
shares of cheap stock and options for their tip services.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants include investment newsletters, Web sites and
other ``touters'' in 11 cities, including Los Angeles, Atlanta,
Boston and New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Microcaps are small-company stocks that are relatively
low-priced, risky and thinly traded.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's clampdown is designed to curb the proliferation of
misleading &UR;  &LR; online stock tips as the Internet increasingly becomes
a major source of financial transactions. SEC officials said they
are concerned the Net is becoming a virtual haven for fly-by-night
businesses and stock shams.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of these cases, the Internet promoters gave ostensibly
independent opinions about microcap companies that in reality were
bought and paid for,'' said Richard Walker, director of the SEC's
enforcement division. ``Not only did they lie about their own
independence, some of them lied about the companies they featured,
then took advantage of any quick spike in price to sell their
shares for a fast and easy profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires people who tout securities for a fee to
disclose the source of their compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the charges in the case:
</P>
<P>
   _ Stockstowatch, based in Sarasota, Fla., endorsed the stocks of
at least five publicly traded microcaps in e-mails to subscribers
and on its Web site. After shares increased sharply in value based
on the recommendations, the company allegedly pocketed more than $1
million in stock sales.
</P>
<P>
   _ An online stock promoter in Southern California, International
Alliance Trading Inc., received more than $64,000 in cash and stock
from several microcap companies it hawked online without revealing
its compensation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  _ An online newsletter, the Future Superstock in Chicago,
received more than $1.6 million in cash and stock from about 25
companies it boosted without disclosing it was paid for the tips.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC did not disclose the name of any of the stocks involved.
</P>
<P>
   The commission set up a special ``cyberforce'' unit this summer
to scour Web sites for illegal promotional arrangements. It has
filed 61 cases since it began patroling the Internet in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC encourages consumers to report suspicious online stock
offers to its toll-free phone number, (800) 732-0330, and e-mail
address,  &LR;  enforcement &LR; sec.gov &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of SEC (99143 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
