<HEADER>
A2483 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEINWINDER-SFCHRON &LR;      10-28 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEINWINDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Jim Steinwinder Provides Databases that Fuel California
Political  Races  By Dan Fost  
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Jim Steinwinder has barely lit his Marlboro when the phone rings,
again.
<P>
   It's another panicked political consultant, wanting to know why
his mailing list has a missing name, or where his labels are, or if
he can get another set of last-minute literature printed and
mailed.
</P>
<P>
   With less than a week to go before election day, Steinwinder
stands at the caffeine-crazed intersection of politics and
technology.
</P>
<P>
   His Santa Clara firm, Computerized Political Services, provides
the databases that fuel many California campaigns, regardless of
ideology. He keeps track of individual voter records going back 10
to 12 years: how often people vote, how they're registered and
whether they vote at the polls or by absentee ballot.
</P>
<P>
   He's constantly massaging, merging and updating the databases
that have become indispensable in modern politics: the statewide
voter file, homeowner files, telephone files and other large
computerized records.
</P>
<P>
   His business also includes a large printing operation, enabling
him to crank out labels and mailers. ``We fine-tune it so we don't
waste a lot on mail to deadwood,'' he said. ``The laser printer
allows for a lot of highly personalized mail pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   He's provided information this year to both candidates for
governor and frequently works both sides of a ballot measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds mercenary,'' he says, ``and in a way, I guess it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   He cares more about software than soft money, more about
mainframes than the political mainstream. If Steinwinder, 50, has
any political opinions, he keeps them to himself. He doesn't even
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to be in the business and serve both sides, it's
best not to leave a trail,'' he says, a curl of smoke leaving his
cigarette, three half-empty bottles of Coca Cola on his desk. ``My
politics are my politics. Nobody knows what they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway,'' he adds, ``I have a far greater impact than a single
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   The political consultants who rely on Steinwinder for their
mailing lists and slate cards verify that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man has touched everybody who votes in the state,'' says
Philip Muller, a San Francisco political consultant. ``Every person
in San Francisco and (most) of California who votes regularly has
received a piece of mail lasered by Jim Steinwinder.''
</P>
<P>
   High-powered consultant Clint Reilly sent Steinwinder a
handwritten note saying that if he runs against San Francisco Mayor
Willie Brown next year, he'll need all the weapons he could &LR;  can
muster _ ``and you are a powerful weapon when loaded and cocked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped create the whole computer targeting technology
that's utilized in practically every campaign in politics today,''
Reilly says.
</P>
<P>
   It was Reilly's brother who first introduced the otherwise
apolitical Steinwinder to the hurly-burly world of elections.
</P>
<P>
   Steinwinder, a San Francisco native, had gone straight to work
for IBM Research when he graduated from Mountain View High School
in 1965. He put in two years there, then two years with a service
bureau, and then took a job with Memorex, where he worked on both
software and hardware. In 1981, after 11 years with Memorex, he
hung out his shingle as a computer consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the worst mistake I'd ever made,'' he says now, not
quite seriously.
</P>
<P>
   A mutual friend introduced Steinwinder to Kevin Reilly, who was
working on an insurance initiative in 1986. ``They came up with a
problem, I came up with a solution, and I haven't been able to get
away from them since,'' Steinwinder says.
</P>
<P>
   He finds it somewhat ironic that he started ``at the top,'' with
the influential Reilly. He continues to maintain a small clientele
of mostly heavy-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do no marketing. I do no sales. I call nobody,'' he says.
``All my work is by referral. I've never had a salesman. I don't
know whether that's good or bad, but it works for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In his office's backshop, people step around stacks of boxes and
reams of paper. The smell of ink pervades the air, while printers
spit out scores of mailers. Steinwinder pokes around a cantankerous
laser printer, jammed again. ``Putting out fires,'' he calls it.
</P>
<P>
   Among the assets Steinwinder brings to the job are proprietary
software systems that sort the voluminous voter records he obtains
from the California secretary of state and others.
</P>
<P>
   He also helped pioneer some of the early vote-by-mail efforts,
in which candidates send out absentee ballots in hopes of gaining
votes from people who would otherwise stay at home.
</P>
<P>
   With Long Beach consultant Jerry Seedborg, Steinwinder produces
sophisticated slate cards that are targeted to voters by region, by
party, by ethnicity, by age.
</P>
<P>
   Seedborg, who was in Steinwinder's office working on a
last-minute mailing this week, proudly showed several cards U.S.
Representative Howard Berman, D-North Hollywood, sent out this
year. One card aimed at Jewish voters touted Berman's toughness
with Saddam Hussein; one aimed at young Hispanics played up
endorsements by Latino politicians; one aimed at conservative
voters showed endorsements from, as Seedborg put it, ``police,
police, police.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the work, though, Steinwinder is anything but a
political junkie. ``Most of the time, I don't know if the campaign
I worked on wins or loses,'' he says. He worked on Assemblyman Don
Perata's bid last month for the Democratic nomination in a state
Senate race, but ``I didn't know Perata won until three days after
the election _ and then because a Republican friend of mine in
Southern California called to congratulate me.''
</P>
<P>
   Perata's victory was credited to an unusually large vote-by-mail
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Steinwinder's willingness to work for either side in the same
campaign sometimes makes consultants uneasy. Gale Kaufman, a
Sacramento consultant, said she won't use him for that reason.
</P>
<P>
   Muller, who is using Steinwinder for vote-by-mail efforts for
the state Democratic Party and for supporters of Proposition 5, the
Indian gaming initiative, said every consultant would prefer that
Steinwinder work exclusively with them _ but very few want to run a
campaign without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have someone like that, you have your hands tied
behind your back,'' Muller says. ``I would prefer that he didn't
(work both sides) but I can't control that, and his integrity is
beyond reproach.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinwinder says the consultants don't even try to wheedle the
other side's strategy out of him. ``They won't get an answer out of
me,'' he says. ``I'm hired to produce. I'm not hired to spy, and
they know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledges, ``It's a very awkward situation to be in
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinwinder isn't the only person providing computer services to
political campaigns. Other notable companies include Political Data
in Los Angeles, and Voter Contact Services, a Hawaii firm whose
mainframes are in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Steinwinder actually owns two companies, both with the initials
CPS: Computerized Political Services and Critical Path Solutions,
the latter handling commercial mailings for businesses like Dolby
Laboratories and Pacific Gas and Electric.
</P>
<P>
   The companies remain private, and Steinwinder says he brings in
$1 million to $2 million in sales each year. He won't divulge
profits.
</P>
<P>
   He employs 11 people in offices in Santa Clara and Los Angeles.
His wife, Myra, a British citizen, works with him, as do two of his
four grown children.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to pictures of his own children, his office wall
features a frame with small photos of children from around the
world. They're all children he sponsors &UR;  &LR; through charities, sending
money and corresponding with them. At any given time, he's
sponsoring five children.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about those kids, the hardened cynic melts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally believe the future of the world is in the
children. The adults have screwed it up. It's going to be the kids
who save it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Although Steinwinder never went to college, he believes that
``the secret there is education. There's a star in there somewhere.
Give them a chance, and they'll blossom.''
</P>
</TEXT>
