<HEADER>
A2485 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEINSIDEBAR-SFCHRON &LR;      10-28 0296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEINSIDEBAR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Data Wizard's Words of Wisdom  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Jim Steinwinder offers pungent views on a variety of topics:
<P>
   _ On using the Internet to target voters: ``There are some
attempts to use the Internet, but I don't think it's ready for
prime time. As soon as you get outside the Santa Clara Valley,
computers are not saturated like they are here. ... The Internet as
a means to replace mail, or television, or radio? Not in our
lifetime. Not gonna happen.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On working on political campaigns: ``You learn how to deal
with a lot of pressure and a lot of unhappy people.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On politicians: ``Of course, when they lose, it's your fault.
They can do no wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On ideology: ``I'm an enigma in politics. I don't care whether
the campaign is Republican or Democrat. I don't care whatever wins.
I care about my job.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On political mudslinging: ``By the time you get hit with 10 or
12 mail pieces and all of these ads attacking the other guy, you
get turned off. I'd like to see campaigns where issues get
discussed, not attacking the other guy all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On why he uses DOS instead of Windows: ``The thing in politics
is, they don't care about technology. They care about speed.
Windows has a nice interface. It's even easy to use _ sometimes.
But it's slow. When you're trying to shove as much data through the
pipeline as you can, Windows slows it down.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On changes in Silicon Valley: ``Technology goes at such a fast
pace, it's becoming more and more impersonal. The Santa Clara
Valley has changed. It's not what I grew up with. I don't mind the
computers _ I get along fine with them. It's this mass of people
... I'd like to have the apricot orchards back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
