<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Teligent to Dish Out Local Phone Service by Using Its Height  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
If you work in a tall building, you could soon have an interesting
alternative to Pacific Bell for local phone service and high-speed
Internet access.
<P>
   Virginia's Teligent Inc. will soon enter the local market,
bypassing Pac Bell's wires with a network of rooftop satellite
dishes capable of delivering voice and data services _ at lower
cost than wire-based options.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  During a recent visit to San Francisco, Teligent chief
executive Alex Mandl explained how his company will get around Pac
Bell's biggest asset: the wires that run to every office and home.
</P>
<P>
   Teligent will mount wireless dishes atop customers' office
buildings in San Francisco and Oakland. Those dishes will transmit
phone calls and high-speed Internet traffic to and from Teligent's
central dish in Oakland, bypassing Pac Bell's wires.
</P>
<P>
   Each dish will tap into the wiring closets in its skyscraper, so
Teligent can reach any office inside _ but only in the building _
via the wires and phone plugs in the walls.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Teligent's central dish will patch into three wire-based
networks: Pac Bell's phone switches for local calls, Frontier's
long-distance lines and the Internet backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Home consumers miss out. So do businesses in short buildings.
Teligent will target businesses in skyscrapers. Blame the
technology. The satellite dishes need a clear line of sight to the
big dish in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Dawson, a telecommunications analyst in New York, said
Winstar Communications of New York is right behind Teligent in
deploying a similar service also aimed at business customers.
</P>
<P>
   Several firms, called competitive local exchange carriers or
CLECs, already offer data and local voice services in California.
But they've mainly focused on data services, and most of them use
Pac Bell's wires to reach their customers, according to Michael
Bloom, a telecommunications analyst in San Ramon.
</P>
<P>
   He said Teligent's wireless network should let it offer phone
service at lower cost than other CLECs or Pac Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell spokesman Paul Cohen noted that all the newcomers focus
on business clients, leaving Pac Bell to serve residential
customers.
</P>
<P>
   And he couldn't resist getting in a word for Pac Bell's
long-sought agenda: selling long-distance. The fact that Teligent
will push phone service, in addition to data, only proves local
competition exists, he said. Therefore, the Baby Bells should be
allowed to enter the long-distance market.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we get into long-distance, then you'll see real
competition at the local level,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; EFF Turnover: &LR;  After less than a year, Barry Steinhardt has
resigned as president of the Electronic Frontier Foundation, a San
Francisco advocacy group. His departure for personal reasons
highlights EFF's growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who think it's never really been an
organization as much as a collection of unique individuals,'' said
one EFF watcher in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Investment banker Giles McNamee, who's been on EFF's board for
over two years, said the group has outgrown its fringe image and
become a mainstream player on free speech and privacy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first joined, we had two weeks' cash on hand,'' he
said. Today, EFF has enough to pay its staff of nine for a year.
</P>
<P>
   EFF co-founder John Gilmore said there are some differences in
style between EFF's long-hairs _ himself and co-founder John Perry
Barlow _ and more buttoned-down board members like Esther Dyson or
Lori Fena, who think ``we need to appeal more to people in suits.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gilmore said EFF's board is united on finding a new
president with the same organizational savvy as Steinhardt, who
learned the nonprofit ropes at the American Civil Liberties Union.
EFF has even asked Isaacson &AMP; Miller, a Boston headhunting firm, to
find its new chief.
</P>
<P>
   EFF also wants to grow its membership, now a paltry 965. But
Gilmore admitted there was some board-level talk about whether EFF,
which has crusaded against spam, should send junk mail to attract
members.
</P>
<P>
   So spare 'em the anguish and visit the Web site  &LR; (www.eff.org &LR; )
to find out how you, too, can become a card-carrying member.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Foreign affairs?  &LR; Want to sell in Europe but don't parlez
vous? For a fee, Protege Software &LR;  (www.protege.co.uk) &LR;  will set up
your office, hire staff, provide a general manager and turn over
the keys.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been lots of horror stories about how companies
have lost their boots in Europe because they didn't understand the
cultural nuances,'' said Protege CEO Larry Levy.
</P>
<P>
   There's a cultural nuance; here we lose our shirts. But Levy
helped NetGravity of San Mateo sell its Internet advertising
software in Europe without shedding anything. ``Other U.S.
companies (should) consider Protege instead of building their
European operation themselves,'' said NetGravity CEO John Danner.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hollenbeck, with H&AMP;Q Venture Associates, said Protege has
helped one of his startups, Vignette, open a European market for
Web management software. For Vignette, it's been great. But
Hollenbeck wonders how long Protege can keep building beachheads
for new companies.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Levy is managing European offices for eight U.S.
startups. Oops. Make that nine. He phoned me from a car phone to
say Virage, the San Mateo firm that sells video search tools, just
hired Protege to keep its boots on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
