<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BELL-TINKLERS TAUNT STRUGGLING STARS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The tinkle of bells on the sidewalk in front of a
midtown hotel Wednesday afternoon appeared to be hurrying the
season. But it was not quite the familiar sound ringing from
soldiers of the Salvation Army seeking alms during Yuletide. There
was indeed a handful of people, not wearing red but black _ black
caps and black-and-white shirts _ and standing beside cardboard
boxes designed for contributions.
</P>
<P>
   They held up placards reading ``NBA Canned Food Drive _ Give
Generously.'' ``Help Feed the Players and Owners.'' ``Bring on the
Ticket Prices Increase.'' And the always ominous, ``Prepare _ The
Sports Apocalypse Is Coming!''
</P>
<P>
   These eleemosynary souls were stationed near the entrance to the
hotel where the National Basketball Association players and owners
were meeting to try to iron out their heart-rending differences
concerning, as David Stern, commissioner of the NBA said, the split
of ``the one-billion-dollar-plus revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   The lockout, as Patrick Ewing, the president of the players
union and a man making the keeping-the-wolf-from-the-door salary of
$18 million a year, had said with a straight face, ``is about
survival, about being able to feed our families.''
</P>
<P>
   The bell tinklers were led by a man named Steve Siegel, who
traveled here from his home in San Diego to try to help the players
and owners out ``from the goodness of my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the president of an organization called Fans Union.
Siegel, a slight, bearded middle-aged man, was, for want of another
figure, the voice and embodiment of the Everyman Fan.
</P>
<P>
   How long has his organization been in existence?
</P>
<P>
   ``About a week,'' Siegel said. ``This lockout inspired it. The
players and owners, after all, are suffering. The owners need to
buy their Cuban cigars and Russian caviar. The players need to make
payments on their nine cars and their 14 gold watches.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said that some people passing by made contributions.
Someone dropped a can of sardines, another a can of Alpo, a third
some cat food. ``Someone wanted to contribute money and had a
nickel,'' he said, ``but he asked for change.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the smile left his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough is enough,'' he said. ``We fans should stand up to both
these ridiculous groups and stop this nonsense.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel is not quite sure how to do it, other than boycott games
and stop watching games on television, which would hurt
advertisers, which would reduce television revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened to some degree in baseball over the last few
years,'' Siegel said. ``The players and owners think their cash cow
can go on forever. But Michael Jordan will be leaving soon, and
then what? You've got Chris Webber and Latrell Sprewell and I see
where Nick Van Exel just found a team. This is what we have to look
forward to, and with higher and higher ticket prices?''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for a fan to sympathize with either side, but in
this corner, the edge goes to the players. The issues of a hard and
soft cap, of revenue sharing, are often lost in the welter of
stupefying utterances, from Kenny Anderson, at $5.8 million a year,
lamenting that ``the more money you make, the more you spend'' to,
well, multimillionaire owners steeling for a war to clutch a
thicker share of the billion-plus.
</P>
<P>
   But Mario Elie, the Houston Rockets' veteran guard, wisely said,
``Guys have to learn how to manage their money.'' He added that
when you're making $2.5 million a year, as he is ``that alone could
set you up.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie could have said the same for the owners. At bottom, the
players have as much right to make as much as they can as do the
owners. And it is the owners who are paying the salaries. Only
because they believe they can make profit from it.
</P>
<P>
   And Stephon Marbury mused about the owners, ``If they're giving
out a hundred million for a player, how much are they making?''
</P>
<P>
   So a few more games _ through November _ were canceled while
negotiations continue. No matter. Even if all the regular-season
games were canceled, the league could still hold a playoffs. The
playoffs are what the NBA is all about anyway, isn't it? Sure, jump
right into the playoffs, and include all the teams, and add a
month, or more, and prorate salaries. And recoup millions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Ewing had come by the Fans Union, and laughed. ``Right
on!'' he said. But he never dipped into his pocket to aid the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Stern. When asked if the league contributed anything to
the charitable group on the street, he smiled kindly from within
his freshly minted gray goatee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave at the office,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
