<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON SAYS SALES SOARED AS QUARTERLY LOSS NARROWED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amazon.com Inc., the leading online bookseller, Wednesday
reported a quadrupling of sales and a narrower-than-expected
third-quarter loss.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon said it also became the leading online music retailer in
the quarter, with sales of $14.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company reported results after the close of the stock
market. In NASDAQ trading, Amazon shares closed at $117.0625, up 75
cents.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Sept. 30, Amazon reported a loss of $45.2
million, compared with a loss of $9.6 million in a year earlier.
Sales soared to $153.7 million from $37.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's third-quarter 1998 earnings included $20.5 million of
costs related to mergers and acquisitions. Excluding those one-time
items, Amazon lost $24.7 million, or 49 cents a diluted share.
Analysts surveyed by the First Call Corp. had expected the company
to lose 57 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very grateful to our customers for choosing Amazon.com
as their online music store so quickly,'' Jeffrey P. Bezos,
Amazon's founder and chief executive, said in a statement. ``Though
pleased with these results, we know our growth initiatives will
continue to require aggressive investment and entail significant
execution challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Although sales quadrupled, the cost of sales nearly did so as
well, at $118.8 million, compared with $30.7 million in the period
a year earlier. Amazon's continued losses despite growing sales
reflect the high cost of acquiring and retaining customers as
traditional book retailers like Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. launch their
own services on the World Wide Web. Moving into music sales pits it
against against online music stores like CDNow Inc., which agreed
to buy a rival, N2K Inc., this month.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon, based in Seattle, said cumulative customer accounts
increased by more than 1.2 million during the third quarter to
nearly 4.5 million. A year earlier, accounts totaled 940,000.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat customers accounted for more than 64 percent of orders
during the quarter, Amazon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the business model continues to work,'' said Lise J.
Buyer, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston. ``For those who
argued that Amazon is just catering to the digerati and Internet
nerds, 4.5 million customers is a pretty big refutation.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Amazon has yet to make money, she said, ``they've
always said that making money early was not their goal; making a
lot of money some time is.''
</P>
<P>
   In August, Amazon.com acquired two companies, Planetall and
Junglee, in stock swaps valued at about $280 million. Planetall
provides a Web-based address book, calendar, and reminder service.
Junglee provides Web-based database technology that can help
shoppers find products on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
