<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-CLINTON29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton doing fly-by fund-raising in Florida
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ President Clinton is scheduled to arrive
at Palm Beach International Airport at the end of rush hour today
for a hurried three-hour, make-up reception and dinner in Palm
Beach to raise money for the state Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be gone again before dessert.
</P>
<P>
   All that assumes once-and-future astronaut John Glenn and the
shuttle Discovery blast off on time at 2 p.m. Clinton, Gov. Lawton
Chiles and gubernatorial candidate Buddy MacKay will watch the
launch at Cape Canaveral.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles will hitch a ride on Air Force One for the trip to Palm
Beach County. For security reasons, officials won't reveal his
route from the airport to Palm Beach but Vice President Al Gore's
motorcade took the Royal Park (middle) Bridge earlier this month,
tying up midday traffic.
</P>
<P>
   While Chiles and MacKay strum a few strings with Jimmy Buffett
at a hastily-scheduled rally in the courtyard of the county
government center, Clinton will meet 100 folks who paid $2,500 for
a handshake at a 7:10 p.m. reception at the Palm Beach condominium
of Democratic donor S. Daniel Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   The reception is to raise money for a Political Action Committee
maintained by U.S. Rep. Peter Deutsch, D-Fort Lauderdale, to help
Democratic congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the reception folks will be ushered out and replaced with
60 or 70 others who paid $5,000 a person for an 8:30 p.m. dinner
with the president. This money will go to the Florida Democratic
Party, which will help MacKay.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham, the founder and chairman of Slim-Fast Foods Co., also
was the host for Gore's lunchtime visit Oct. 13. Clinton had to
cancel his appearance because of federal budget politicking.
</P>
<P>
   It's all very private. Clinton is not scheduled to make any
public appearances here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
