<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE GRANTED A WEEK TO WEIGH YANKEES' OFFER 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Cone's affiliation with the Yankees could have
ended Wednesday. But the pitcher, apparently intent on working out
an agreement that would keep him in pinstripes, agreed to wait an
additional week before deciding whether to accept a $5.5 million
deal for the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Yankees and Cone have until midnight Wednesday to
explore middle ground and possibly negotiate a new deal. There
could be major obstacles to hurdle, however, to prevent the 20-game
winner from becoming a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Cone's future is one of a number of issues that Yankees'
officials are dealing with: others include the remote possibility
of signing the cantankerous slugger Albert Belle; re-signing
center-fielder Bernie Williams in a financial market that rewards
stars with contracts of nearly $100 million; retaining third
baseman Scott Brosius, and investigating the possibility of signing
Kevin Brown or Randy Johnson, star free-agent pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, coming off surgery to correct an aneurysm in 1996 and
shoulder surgery after the 1997 season, earned the right to accept
or reject a $5.5 million option for 1999 when he pitched more than
200 innings this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cone earned his 20th victory in his final start and will most
likely get some secondary consideration for the American League's
Cy Young Award, a performance that would usually be rewarded with
far more than a one-year, $5.5-million deal; that is why Cone
didn't accept the 1999 option immediately.
</P>
<P>
   If Cone were younger than his 35 years and had a clean medical
history, the Yankees would probably be rushing to reach a new
agreement. But Cone generally struggled through the final month of
the regular season, and in two of his four starts in the
post-season, his arm seemingly tired.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the Yankees have not pushed to hammer out a new
agreement; rather, it appears they have been waiting to see if Cone
would accept his one-year option, demonstrating little willingness
to exercise Cone's $5.5 million option for the year 2000, or to
give him money in addition to the $5.5 million for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Cone could almost certainly sign for more money elsewhere. The
Los Angeles Dodgers, now managed by Cone's former manager, Davey
Johnson, could have interest, and the Baltimore Orioles may make an
offer.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone has played most of his career in New York, and his wife
has a business in Greenwich, Conn., and his willingness to wait a
week before making his decision is a strong indication he would
like to stay here.
</P>
<P>
   Cone, who could not be reached for comment, agreed to the
one-week extension Wednesday on a conference call with George
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, Brian Cashman, the
general manager, and Steve Fehr, Cone's agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Cone has been a big part of this organization,'' Cashman
said, ``and this gives both sides a chance to think about the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Yankees will at least look into signing Belle, who has
until Dec. 2 to consider offers from other teams or accept the
remaining three years and $30 million on his current contract with
the Chicago White Sox. Belle is among the game's best hitters, but
has a history of confrontations with reporters and fans and was
disliked by teammates in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner, who presented $200,000 for hurricane victims in
the Dominican Republic and Puerto Rico at the ground-breaking
Wednesday for the 33rd Precinct in Washington Heights, said Belle's
reputation did not concern him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's history scares me _ who came from deeper problems
than Darryl and Doc?'' said Steinbrenner, referring to Darryl
Strawberry and Dwight Gooden. ``We couldn't be crucified any more
than when we signed those two.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will consider all the possibilities when they have
staff meetings in Tampa, Fla., beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   _ The seven-year, $91 million deal signed by the Mets' Mike
Piazza on Monday will very likely drive up the bidding on Williams,
and Steinbrenner tweaked the Mets for their generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that all of baseball has been a bit shocked,''
Steinbrenner said. ``I hear that others are quite upset.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Cashman left a message Wednesday for the agent representing
Kevin Brown, and intends to call the agents representing Randy
Johnson. Cashman also contacted the agent for outfielder Brian
Jordan, whom the Yankees might pursue if Williams signs elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Los Angeles Dodgers offered the reliever Jeff Shaw in
return for Mariano Rivera, the Yankees' closer, but the Yankees
rejected that proposal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
