</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ATLANTA-YOUTH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF COURSE REDEVELOPMENT HELPS REVIVE AN ATLANTA COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Tenn.)  (duplication warning: also sent with `s' code) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The East Lake Meadows housing project was once so
violent that it was nicknamed Little Vietnam. Drug dealers ruled.
Many residents of Atlanta's East Lake section lived in fear during
the 1980s, particularly those in the project.
</P>
<P>
   The deteriorating East Lake Golf Club, where the legendary Bobby
Jones learned to play, was just another casualty of the
neighborhood. Surrounding it was an environment where premature
death was part of the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``About six or seven years ago, the drug dealers started
shooting out, and we started shooting in,'' said Carlos Banda, a
25-year-veteran of the Atlanta police force, who works in the East
Lake area. ``A small child was killed. Even after that, it didn't
get that much better.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the situation facing Tom Cousins, a local real estate
developer and philanthropist, in 1993 when he bought the golf club:
a course in desperate need of restoration, and a community in
desperate need of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Amid East Lake's brush and dirt, Cousins saw an opportunity to
secure a legacy as the man who saved Jones' golfing home and helped
to revive a blighted neighborhood in the process. From his own
charitable foundation, Cousins spun off the East Lake Community
Foundation, and he used it as the linchpin for a complex marriage
involving the golf course, the federal government, city officials
and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   Together they raised $93.5 million, with the goal of reviving
the golf course and the East Lake community _ through new housing,
an after-school academic program, a community center, a golf
academy and a caddie scholarship program that has sent some East
Lake youths on to college.
</P>
<P>
   While there have been many efforts to attract members of
minority groups to golf, this plan was unique in its ambitious
attempt to use the sport as a vehicle for urban restoration. The
undertaking will gain national attention beginning Thursday when
East Lake is host to the Tour Championship, one of professional
golf's most prestigious events.
</P>
<P>
   It is a somewhat odd partnership: golf, a sport with a history
of exclusion, being used to revitalize a troubled, predominantly
African-American neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, many corporate leaders were skeptical. Politicians
disagreed on a course of action. Some within the community
resisted, feeling they were given little voice in the effort;
others were distrustful, having been betrayed in the past by
numerous broken promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, if people asked you where you lived, you better not
say East Lake,'' said Geraldine Lowery, who moved with her
children, Meoshia and Rodriquez, into a new town house last spring.
``When they first started talking about doing this, I thought it
was a joke. Then when they started building the new places, I said,
`They're not really going to let us live over here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm happy, very happy. I wanted something better for my
children, and this is it. And this is how I knew things had
changed: My mother never used to want to have any family
get-togethers at my house. But one day when we were talking about
getting together, my mom said, `Let's do it at your house.' That
made me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowery said that when her children were toddlers, she had taught
them how to roll off the bed and onto the floor when they heard
gunfire, and how to keep their heads low to avoid possible stray
bullets coming through the window. Now, both children attend the
golf academy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they've done is absolutely phenomenal,'' said
Tiger Woods, who will play at East Lake this week. ``It says a lot
for that community. It's just a matter of everyone coming together.
And you don't find that very often. Somebody always has some kind
of agenda, instead of everyone pulling together for a dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative began earlier this decade when federal money from
the Department of Housing and Urban Development was secured. In
1993, Cousins' own charitable organization _ the CF Foundation _
bought the course, and two years later it focused on the East Lake
area and formed the East Lake Community Foundation. Together with
contributions from the Atlanta Housing Authority and private
donations, the money to finance the plan was raised.
</P>
<P>
   What happens to the East Lake community over time will be a
large part of Cousins' legacy. Now 66 years old, he played at East
Lake as a child in the 1940s, and his respect for Jones and the
course was embedded at a young age.
</P>
<P>
   A wealthy developer who is well known in Atlanta, Cousins
developed the downtown Omni complex and NationsBank plaza. He could
have simply renovated East Lake Golf Club and still drawn rave
reviews for restoring a part of golf history. But he chose not to
ignore what was on the other side of East Lake's gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask me all the time why am I doing this,'' Cousins
said. ``It's like they're waiting for the other shoe to drop. We
need to do something about situations like this all over the
country, or we're going to lose our future. If I had grown up the
way a lot of kids had to grow up in East Lake, I would have gone
bad a lot sooner than most of them did.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Cousins hopes the project will serve as a model for
similar efforts elsewhere in the country, and is determined to make
his case to investors nationwide. Of the 100 corporate memberships
at East Lake, 90 have been reserved for corporations outside
Atlanta. Those memberships cost $250,000, with $200,000 of that
earmarked for the East Lake Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to attract 100 of America's best and brightest
corporations so that they see what we do, and take it back to their
cities,'' Cousins said. ``This has been a problem all across the
country. Public housing has been very poorly done and conceived. In
the past, our foundation has donated to hunger programs, school
programs and housing programs, but we were never really satisfied
with the result. This time, we decided to focus on one area, to see
if we could come up with some solutions. We focused on East Lake
Meadows.''
</P>
<P>
   To visit the East Lake community now is to see a rejuvenated
neighborhood. The golf course, restored by the noted architect Rees
Jones, is in immaculate condition, and the picturesque clubhouse
includes personal artifacts belonging to Jones, who won 13 major
championships from 1923 to 1930. The club seeks neighborhood
youngsters and local college students for the caddie program, with
all student caddies eligible for the foundation's college
scholarship program.
</P>
<P>
   But the most impressive restoration has occurred outside the
golf course's black wrought-iron gates. Old housing projects have
been demolished and replaced by new housing called the Villages of
East Lake, where middle-income and low-income families are living
side by side in 182 new units, including single-family homes,
duplexes and apartments. An additional 318 new units are planned,
for a total of 500, with construction to begin sometime next year
on the opposite side of the course.
</P>
<P>
   Working residents are responsible for the rent, which ranges up
to $820 a month for a two-bedroom unit. Unemployed residents are
required to pay what they had been paying at East Lake Meadows, but
under the lease agreement they must also participate in a
self-sufficiency program that focuses on education, job readiness
and life skills training. If unemployed tenants get jobs, their
rents will increase an amount relative to their salaries.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the project, East Lake residents were given
the choice of moving into the new housing or relocating to other
areas of Atlanta. Today, some of the residents who turned down the
opportunity are now trying to get into the new development.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can understand why some people would be leery about
wanting to stay in this neighborhood, no matter how much we talked
about what was going to happen,'' said Scarlet Pressley, the golf
academy's director of community affairs. ``There were so many bad
memories here. People had lost family members to violence here. But
now that they have seen the positive changes in the community, a
lot of them want to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   According to city statistics, the neighborhood has seen a
dramatic drop in crime rate, and a dramatic increase in property
values. Now, instead of moving out, people are looking to move in,
particularly since the area is only about a 10-minute drive from
downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlie Yates Golf Course, a new 18-hole public facility,
has been built in the neighborhood; Woods attending the official
opening last month. Financing is in place to build a YMCA adjacent
to the Yates course. And the East Lake Golf Academy, a golf and
academic after-school program, provides tutoring for neighborhood
youths and regular golf instruction to 115 children who otherwise
might not have any exposure to the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Puryear, a former golf team captain at Tennessee State
University and the director of junior golf at the academy, has seen
first-hand the difference golf has made to the children in the
neighborhood. Asked how many children in the academy had parents
who played golf, Puryear said: ``None of their parents play golf,
not one. And now look at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Erick Poteat, a promising 13-year-old golfer, was about 20 yards
in front of Puryear, painstakingly hitting a bucket of balls on the
same driving range where a month before he had been introduced to
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes you want to study, because you want to be able to
play golf,'' Poteat said. ``I want to be a pro golfer, but if not,
I want to be an architect.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, not everyone is content, which was probably unavoidable,
considering the magnitude of the undertaking around East Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Davis, president of the East Lake Meadows Tenants
Association, has lived in the community for almost 30 years, and
she bristles at the way she feels the plan was pushed onto local
residents. `` Cousins and his group want to do things, but do it
their way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She is also fighting for 28 more families whose apartments are
scheduled to be demolished, asking that they be housed temporarily
in the new village. Organizers have offered a compromise of 15
families, but that has not yet been accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could go back to the bargaining table and work some of
these issues out, I would be the happiest 63-year-old woman in the
world,'' said Davis, who has threatened legal action if some of her
demands are not met. ``I'm proud of what has happened here, and I
had a lot of these same visions before anybody else even cared. But
the residents deserve to have their say in everything, and that
hasn't always happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two former East Lake Golf Club employees, Andy
Portilla and Richard Trent, sued the club in March, saying there
were fired because of discrimination. Portilla is Hispanic, Trent
is African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say anything bad about Cousins, or what he's
trying to do,'' said Portilla, a former assistant caddie master at
East Lake, who caddied last week for Brandel Chamblee at the
National Car Rental Golf Classic. ``In fact, I came to East Lake
because I believed in the program, and I still do. I'm just saying
that not everyone who works for Cousins is like he is, and I wasn't
treated fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at East Lake have vehemently denied Portilla's
charges, and point to the club's strong record in hiring members of
minority groups since Cousins arrived. Sedric Jackson, an
African-American, was recently hired as the head golf professional
for the Yates course.
</P>
<P>
   But whenever Cousins grows weary of the many challenges and
disputes that have accompanied this venture, he can look out the
window at a changed golf course and a changed community to draw
inspiration. To see 30 of golf's greatest players competing at East
Lake this week will be the latest example of how much things have
changed.
</P>
<P>
   When the golfers and the fans depart after this weekend, the
neighborhood and the golf course will be left behind, hoping to
continue the progress that has been made. And golf may be viewed in
a different light, as a vehicle for social change.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure a lot of people thought this was a crazy idea,''
Puryear said. ``Look around this place. This isn't crazy. This is
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
