<SLUG> BC-BBO-RANDY-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG UNIT, NOW A FREE AGENT, HAS A SHORT LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The second Randy Johnson sweepstakes in three months began
Wednesday. Houston won the first; who will win the second? Try the
Yankees, Anaheim, Texas, Houston, San Diego, Los Angeles or
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the teams most likely to appeal to Johnson, who became
a free agent Wednesday. He has some definite ideas about where he
would like to pitch for the next several seasons, but no ideal
situation has presented itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to give Houston a chance because we're very grateful
for what they did for Randy this year,'' said Alan Nero, who, with
Barry Meister, represents Johnson. ``But at the same time we'll
entertain offers from other teams. Randy has a short list of about
six teams that meet his criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   Nero did not want to discuss the criteria, but Johnson
apparently prefers pitching in the American League, wants to play
for a contender and would like to be close to his new home in
Paradise Valley, Ariz. Of the teams thought to be leading
contenders for his services, the Yankees are the farthest away
geographically but fit the other two criteria perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely will call,'' Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general
manager, said when asked about his interest in the 35-year-old
left-hander. ``I'd like to have the opportunity to bring him over
here. We'll be pursuing him _ to what level of years and dollars
remains to be seen.'' Johnson is expected to get a three- or
four-year contract at an average annual salary in the $12 million
to $14 million range.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mariners finally made Johnson available in July, the
Yankees could have had him but chose not to give up the players
that Seattle wanted. Then the Astros swooped in and snatched him
for minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had asked to be traded last winter after the Mariners
said that they would not sign him to a new contract, but they
retained him and he sulked. After he staggered to a 9-10 record and
4.35 earned run average in his four months with the Mariners,
Johnson responded to his new environment and the Astros' presence
in a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   He reeled off 10 victories in 11 starts, losing the other start
while compiling a 1.28 ERA and striking out 116 and allowing a
total of 83 hits and walks in 84-and-a-third innings. He also
performed well in the playoffs, giving up 3 earned runs in 14
innings in two starts against San Diego, but lost both games.
</P>
<P>
   Some baseball people have believed that Johnson would prefer to
play for the Arizona Diamondbacks because he lives only a few miles
from their park. Joe Garagiola, the expansion team's general
manager, said Wednesday that he liked that possibility but conceded
the Diamondbacks had one or two strikes against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he plays for us, he lives at home,'' he said. ``But will we
be in the playoffs next year? Not likely. Then does he want to play
in the American League?''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was one of 12 players who filed for free agency
Wednesday, raising the total to 109. Among the others: Tony
Phillips of the Mets, Mark Clark of the Cubs and Jeff Montgomery of
the Royals. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
