<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC CHIEF MOVES TO ROTHSCHILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER TRUELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raymond W. Smith, the chairman of Bell Atlantic Corp., said
Wednesday that he would become chairman of Rothschild North America
Inc., the Rothschild Group's North American holding company, in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also said that he would leave his post at Bell Atlantic by
the end of this year. As expected, Ivan G. Seidenberg, who became
Bell Atlantic's chief executive in June, will become chairman on
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   During the almost 40 years Smith has been with the telephone
company, he has built it into one of the world's biggest
telecommunications businesses. He most recently oversaw its
purchase of NYNEX and its proposed $52.9 billion acquisition of the
GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring Smith is a considerable coup for the Rothschild Group,
which is seeking to bolster its North American businesses two years
after the British and French Rothschild families _ its owners _
decided to work more closely together. While the Rothschild Group
is well-established in European banking circles, it remains a
financial boutique in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telecom has been a very big area of activity for the firm
worldwide,'' said Wilbur L. Ross Jr., senior managing director at
Rothschild Inc., the group's American broker-dealer. ``This is the
first time we have been able to attract to the firm a very major
CEO respected both in telecom as well as throughout the corporate
sector.''
</P>
<P>
   To start with, even Smith did not take Rothschild too seriously.
``I was engrossed in completing the mergers of NYNEX and GTE at the
beginning _ when I was first contacted by Rothschild, so I didn't
think much of it,'' Smith, who is 62, said in an interview
Wednesday. ``But, the more we talked about it, the more I liked the
idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he decided that he should ``work with some people I
really like. Baron David and Sir Evelyn are marvelous people,'' he
said referring to Baron David de Rothschild, senior partner of
Rothschild &AMP; Cie. Banque in Paris and Sir Evelyn de Rothschild,
chairman of N.M. Rothschild &AMP; Sons in London, the leaders of the
Rothschild Group.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Evelyn and Baron David praised Smith's experience and
business talents in a statement. Smith, they said, would bring them
and their clients ``the perspective of a highly successful CEO who
understands both the U.S. and global markets and who knows how
successful companies operate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will be fun for him and for us,'' Yves-Andre
Istel, vice chairman of Rothschild Inc. said in an interview
Wednesday. Istel, who spoke by telephone from London, added that
Smith's experience and knowledge of business strategy could
particularly benefit Rothschild's investment banking business.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's long experience in the telecommunications industry _ an
area where Rothschild has represented such companies as British
Telecom and Deutsche Telekom _ also is expected to help the
investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   Istel said Smith would also be pursuing ``some venture capital
investing'' interests, but would otherwise spend his time working
for Rothschild. Smith said these interests were an investment fund,
the Arlington Group, that he was setting up with his son, which
would invest in ``information products and services.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
