<SLUG> BC-HUD-INVESTIGATION-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG HUD INQUIRY COMPLETED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Almost 10 years after Congress found the federal
housing agency under President Reagan to be replete with waste,
fraud and abuse, two independent counsels have concluded their
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In a report presented this week to the U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals for the District of Columbia, the counsels said their
eight-and-a-half-year effort _ which led to the convictions of 16
people _ found ``a pervasive pattern of criminal behavior''
involving officials at the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, as well as consultants and others who did business
with the agency.
</P>
<P>
   The counsels _ Arlin M. Adams, who led the investigation from
1990 through May 1995, and Larry D. Thompson, who completed the
work _ said they also determined that Reagan's housing secretary,
Samuel R. Pierce Jr., was the ``central person'' in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But they concluded that Pierce's cooperation through ``full and
public written acceptance of responsibility for his role in the
mismanagement and abuse at HUD in the 1980s'' warranted their
decision not to charge him with any crimes.
</P>
<P>
   While the events covered in the counsels' voluminous report
ended in 1989, their reverberations echoed into the Clinton
administration, under former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros and
the current secretary, Andrew Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, members of Congress outraged by Pierce's stewardship
called for abolishing the housing agency, and Cisneros and Cuomo
embarked on programs to weed out fraud, abuse and other problems.
Both secretaries reduced the number of department employees, and
Cuomo has continued the trimming efforts by reorganizing major
departments. Currently, the department has 9,000 employees, almost
half as many as the 17,000 a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Congress rewarded those efforts this year, by approving the
administration's $25 billion budget request, which included $2
billion for new spending.
</P>
<P>
   The need for an independent counsel grew out of congressional
hearings that determined by November 1990 that the housing agency
under Pierce had engaged in ``widespread abuses, influence
peddling, blatant favoritism, monumental waste and gross
mismanagement.''
</P>
<P>
   But Congress did not determine whether federal crimes were
committed. That fell to an independent counsel. Between 1990 and
1996, indictments led to convictions and plea bargains with an
array of housing officials.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They included Deborah Gore Dean, an executive assistant to
Pierce who was convicted of 12 felony counts in 1993; Catalina
Vasquez Villalpando, U.S. treasurer from 1989 to 1993; Philip Winn,
an assistant housing secretary who became ambassador to
Switzerland; Joseph Strauss, a special assistant to Pierce; and
Thomas Demery, an assistant housing secretary.
</P>
<P>
   All the cases have been resolved except for the one involving
Ms. Dean, who has asked an appeals court to grant her a new trial
based on new evidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
