<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAND-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-28 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAND-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MASTERCARD JOINS CROWD THAT BELIEVES WHAT SELLS HERE
WILL SELL THERE, TOO. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y.)  (af) 
 By GREG FARRELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theodore Levitt may or may not pay for anything with a
Mastercard, but he can certainly use the company to prove his
theories of global marketing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Levitt, a marketing expert at the Harvard Business
School, popularized the idea of the global village in marketing. He
wrote that advances in technology and communications were shrinking
the planet, encouraging consumers everywhere to develop similar
tastes for the same products.
</P>
<P>
   With few notable exceptions, most people ignored his theories,
continuing to believe that what sold in the United States would not
necessarily sell in Japan, France or Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, that has changed. Advertisers have realized that
their greatest asset is the value of their brands and that in an
increasingly interdependent global economy, those brands should
stand for the same things worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, many global marketers have consolidated their
advertising and marketing relationships at single agencies to help
build consistent, globally recognizable personalities for brands,
with Nike's ``swoosh'' the blueprint to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are IBM, which in 1994 consolidated its advertising
at the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of WPP Group PLC, and
Citibank, which last year combined accounts at Young &AMP; Rubicam
Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Mastercard International is following suit.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Mastercard selected McCann-Erickson Worldwide
Advertising in New York to handle its United States advertising. In
recent months, Mastercard's regional partners in Europe and Latin
America have agreed to shift their advertising to McCann, and the
agency is continuing to pitch the business to local partners,
country by country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mastercard is a major global brand,'' said Debra Coughlin,
senior vice president for global advertising and marketing services
at Mastercard in Purchase, N.Y. ``We began searching in the U.S.
for a campaign, but we were looking for a global agency.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann-Erickson, part of the McCann-Erickson World Group unit of
the  &UR; Interpublic Group &LR;  of Companies, came up with a campaign
carrying the theme ``Priceless,'' in which average people use
Mastercard credit cards to pay for all the mundane things that add
up to a special moment.
</P>
<P>
   In one commercial, for instance, two golfers pay for greens fees
and lunch with the card; an announcer supplies the prices for each
transaction. When one golfer gets a hole-in-one, the announcer
describes the moment as ``priceless'' and concludes, ``For
everything else, there's Mastercard.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann-Erickson will use that commercial in the United States,
Canada and Asia. Moreover, it is using the concept of the overall
campaign and localized versions as a drawing card to compete for
and win the Mastercard accounts in other major markets: Asia, Latin
America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most other worldwide account consolidations, Mastercard's
has not been dictated from a chief executive's office; rather, it
has been a gradual process of convincing the regional and local
offices that there are merits to a single approach, and one agency,
to build a unified brand.
</P>
<P>
   Within that unity, however, there is room for customization.
McCann-Erickson has shot extra footage so the commercials can be
re-edited and made more appropriate in local markets. For example,
one spot set at a baseball stadium could be changed to show a
soccer stadium for Europe and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   What does Mastercard consider the advantages of consolidating
its account? ``You want to be a big player with a major agency that
can help you manage your business around the world,'' said Ms.
Coughlin, who joined Mastercard in 1996 after an advertising career
at Y&AMP;R and the J. Walter Thompson unit of WPP.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just a communications partner,'' she added, ``but a
business partner'' that ``can look at your brand the way you look
at your brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Coughlin emphasized the importance of cross-pollination: not
just running American work overseas but also running overseas work
in this country.
</P>
<P>
   For those who have been preaching the gospel of globalization,
moves like Mastercard's only confirm the truth of what they have
been saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these years of ballyhoo, globalization of ad
accounts is finally a reality and here to stay,'' said Kelly O'Dea,
president for client services at Ogilvy, who has helped the agency
manage its worldwide relationships with IBM, Ford and Eastman
Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are finding that old assumptions about how well
brands travel had to be challenged,'' he added. ``Brands can travel
quite well across borders, and you need somebody to help you figure
that out.''
</P>
<P>
   John J. Dooner Jr., chairman and chief executive of
McCann-Erickson World Group, which established its global network
decades ago to serve the Coca-Cola account, said: ``The march
toward globalization is inexorable. It's not just Lever, L'Oreal
and General Motors. The second level of marketers are recognizing
the importance of being global.''
</P>
<P>
   Reckitt &AMP; Colman, a maker of household cleaning products,
consolidated its advertising at McCann-Erickson in 1996. After two
years, Philip Darnton, group director for global marketing, said he
was pleased with the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spend your money in lots of little pieces, things don't
happen,'' he said. ``You can't command the best people on your
account. With a global agency, there's a degree of consistency in
brand position'' because ``the agency starts to be a custodian of
the brand.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward H. Vick, chief operating officer at Y&AMP;R Inc., recalled
that after the Colgate-Palmolive Co. announced in late 1995 that it
was consolidating its account at Y&AMP;R Advertising, his people put
together a study called ``The Big Game.''
</P>
<P>
   By its reckoning, there were about 40 worldwide marketers with
ad budgets of more than $500 million a year. Now, Vick estimated,
that number has grown to 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``As these companies go global,'' Vick said, ``they begin to
realize that as the world gets smaller, the need for a brand to
stand for something is more and more important.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, Dooner said: ``The bigger will get stronger.
That's true not only in the advertising business, but on the client
side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
