<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LABOR-ART-NYT     10-28 1223
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LABOR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRESS REPORTED IN TALKS, WHILE 2 MORE WEEKS' GAMES LOPPED FROM
NBA SCHEDULE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wednesday was the 120th day of the National
Basketball Association lockout and it was unlike any other, with
the owners and the players going face to face for 90 minutes, with
the league deleting two more weeks from the 1998-99 schedule and
with both sides negotiating into the night in the hopes that a deal
can be reached before more damage is done to the season.
</P>
<P>
   The backdrop for the eventful day was the fact the two sides
have at least agreed on an economic framework _ a luxury tax
followed by a modified cap _ that could lead to an agreement to end
the first work stoppage in league history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically filling in the blanks at this point,'' Billy
Hunter, the players union executive director, said optimistically
after he and about 100 players emerged from an unprecedented
90-minute meeting with the owners who sit on the league's labor
relations committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skeleton is there,'' Hunter added, ``but it might take us
a while to get some workable numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   League officials were not as optimistic, however, wondering
aloud whether the union will compromise enough to achieve the
owners' goal of lowering the players' share of overall revenue to
48 percent by the year 2003. Still, NBA Commissioner David Stern
for the first time acknowledged that progress was being made to end
the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure that we are past the label point,'' Stern
said. ``We are talking about share.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel neither optimism nor pessimism,'' Stern added. ``I just
think that we've got to talk. We may have the skeleton of a deal.
But in terms of a hard negotiation on the guts of this deal, I
would say we're no place yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's negotiations began after the league announced it
would cancel the rest of November's games. But straying from its
stance on Oct. 13, when the first two weeks of November were
canceled, the league backed off from its position that all games
that are canceled would not be made up. Instead, Stern said both
sides would discuss the rescheduling of games.
</P>
<P>
   A league official, who asked to remain anonymous, said a
reconfiguration of the season was being worked on so that teams
would end up with the same number of road and home games. As it is,
the league's 82-game schedule has been whittled to 68 games.
</P>
<P>
   Stern estimated that players have lost nearly $200 million in
salaries with the recent cancellations. Union President Patrick
Ewing, whose $18.5 million annual salary is currently the highest
in the NBA, has already lost about $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The cancellations were announced after a meeting of the league's
Board of Governors, at which owners discussed the possibility of
the entire season being lost. Stern said a date for declaring the
season dead was not decided upon for fear of it being perceived as
a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make a deal,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   It was after the owners met, and before negotiations resumed,
that Stern, Deputy Commissioner Russ Granik and members of the
owners' labor relations committee met with about 100 players in a
Sheraton Hotel conference room, with such stars as Michael Jordan,
Scottie Pippen and David Robinson in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting quickly turned into a spirited question-and-answer
session, with players grilling the owners as to why they needed
cost controls. The meeting was intended to be informational, but
both sides used the 90 minutes behind closed door to vent their
frustrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't say it was a heated exchange but it was a very good
exchange,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   According to several participants in the meeting, the Washington
Wizards owner Abe Pollin became visibly upset when Jordan and
others wondered aloud why owners should not consider selling their
franchises if they cannot make them profitable enough. With
Pollin's voice rising, Stern interceded and tried to settle down
the 78-year-old owner.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven owners who were present, Pollin, who has been in
the league for 35 years, is regarded as having a notably hard-line
approach to negotiations. Dave Checketts, the Madison Square Garden
president; Mickey Arison, the managing general partner of the Miami
Heat; the Cleveland Cavaliers' chairman, Gordon Gund; Jerry
Colangelo, the Phoenix Suns president and chief executive officer;
the San Antonio Spurs' owner, Peter Holt, and the Utah Jazz' owner
Larry Miller were also present.
</P>
<P>
   Another member of the committee, the Los Angeles Lakers owner,
Jerry Buss, did not attend. After the 90-minute meeting with the
players ended, the two sides began formal negotiations at 5 p.m. at
an undisclosed midtown sight.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side was expecting a deal to be struck Wednesday night,
but the framework appears to be there, even though there is a wide
gap between the 48 percent of revenues the owners want the players
to receive and the 63 percent the players have proposed. Last
season, the players received 57 percent of the revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're driving a car,'' Ewing said. ``They want us to
go back to horse and buggies. Going back to 48 percent is not
reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   The framework both sides are discussing would run five years and
would involve using the union's proposal for a luxury tax the first
two years, the league's desire for some kind of cap system the next
two years and a moderation of the two plans in the fifth season.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury tax would be on the highest contracts, with the tax
money going to lower-income teams. If that system did not reduce
the amount of revenues being devoted to salaries, a modified hard
cap would be implemented under which players would put 10 percent
of their salaries into an escrow fund.
</P>
<P>
   The sides also need to find a middle ground on the luxury tax.
The players have asked for a tax of 50 percent on the amount of any
annual salary over $18 million, a figure that would only affect
Ewing; owners have asked for tax rates of 50-200 percent on
salaries signed under the Larry Bird exception for more than $2.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we have to do now is agree on the numbers,'' Ewing said.
</P>
<P>
   The league said Wednesday it would not announce further
cancellations of games, preferring instead to say nothing until the
point is reached where it has to announce the entire season has
been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see any point to making further announcements about
our schedule until we either make a deal or cancel the season
entirely,'' Granik said. ``Going forward, the rule of thumb is that
for each week that goes by without a new agreement, we lose one
more week of games.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA season ticket-holders are receiving cash refunds plus 6
percent interest for all preseason and regular-season games that
are canceled. Anyone holding individual game tickets is entitled to
a cash refund of the face value of the tickets or a raincheck to be
used at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an urgency here, but I don't want anyone to
misinterpret the urgency,'' Hunter said. ``The urgency is not one
in which we are going to throw the hat in and accept what anybody
puts on the table. We're just saying time is of the essence. The
longer you wait to put something on the table, it's a missed
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
