<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRAZIL PLANS $80 BILLION IN CUTS AND TAX INCREASES
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian government of President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
detailed a three-year, $80 billion package of spending cuts and tax
increases in a bid to restore the nation's flagging credibility in
world markets and prepare the way for a rescue program led by the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials reacted cautiously, and international investors
warned that the measures could easily stall in the Brazilian
Congress. The blueprint calls for $23.5 billion in savings for
1999, with about $11 billion of that amount coming from tax
increases and $7 billion from federal spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Architects of the IMF rescue hope it will shelter Latin America
from financial turmoil, but their optimism may be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   CRACKDOWN ON INTERNET STOCK FRAUD
</P>
<P>
   Delivering a blunt reminder to investors that the World Wide Web
can be treacherous, federal regulators said they had accused 44
stock promoters of fraudulently promoting more than 235 small
companies on the Internet. The Securities and Exchange Commission,
which created a special enforcement squad to police Internet
frauds, called the enforcement action the first such nationwide
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S OFFICIAL: A $70 BILLION SURPLUS
</P>
<P>
   The government closed the books on the fiscal year that ended on
Sept. 30, saying it ran a $70 billion surplus, the first time since
1969 that Washington spent less than it took in.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ LEADS MILD STOCK ADVANCE
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices resumed their advance in a relatively subdued
session as investors appraised Brazil's fiscal package and awaited
key reports on U.S. wage growth and output. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 5.93 points, to 8,371.97. The Nasdaq
composite index climbed 19.72 points, to 1,737.35, and the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 2.75 points, to 1,068.09.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices fell for the first time in three days as the yield
on the benchmark 30-year bond rose to 5.12 percent from 5.08
percent.
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT DELAYS AN INITIAL OFFERING
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has delayed plans to take its wireless operations public
this year because of the volatility of world financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   DURABLE-GOODS ORDERS UP AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   Orders for big-ticket manufactured goods rose in September for
the fourth consecutive month, pointing to an economy that is
healthier than expected despite a raft of economic problems abroad.
The Commerce Department said that new orders for durable goods rose
nine-tenths of 1 percent, to $192.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   BELL CHIEF TO JOIN ROTHSCHILD
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Smith, who is retiring from his chairman job at Bell
Atlantic at the end of the year, will become chairman of Rothschild
North America Inc., the North American holding company for the
Rothschild Group in January. The Rothschild Group is well
established in European banking circles, but wants to bolster its
North American businesses.
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON LOSS LESS THAN FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, the online book seller, reported much higher sales
and a narrower-than-expected loss for the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Mobil's third-quarter profit fell 45 percent, to $497 million,
because of low crude-oil prices and decreased production.
</P>
<P>
   Anheuser-Busch, the world's largest brewer, said third-quarter
earnings rose 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Revlon reported a decline of 62 percent in third-quarter
earnings, hurt by retailer inventory reductions, product delays and
softness in international demand.
</P>
<P>
   BUILDING BRANDS WITH A SINGLE VOICE
</P>
<P>
   Many global marketers are consolidating their accounts at single
agencies to help build consistent, globally recognizable
personalities for brands. Mastercard is doing that now with with
McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
