<SLUG> BC-CBS-KARMAZIN-PROFILE-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CBS CHIEF IS KNOWN FOR FOCUS ON BOTTOM LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With CBS-CEO-RETIRE) 
(js) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aggressive is the word most often used to describe Mel Karmazin,
the new chief executive officer of CBS Corp., and it is an epithet
as often as it is a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old businessman has no tolerance for excuses or
extravagances, and cares little whether he makes enemies as long as
he makes money. His impressive track record at doing just that has
made him a hero of Wall Street investment firms, which see his
relentless focus on the bottom line as something that will almost
always help his company's stock perform better.
</P>
<P>
   And as the single largest shareholder in CBS, owning about 1.5
percent of its stock, or roughly 10 million shares, Karmazin has a
keen personal interest in that performance along with his
responsibility to investors.
</P>
<P>
   He became a CBS executive as well as its chief shareholder in
1996, when he sold his Infinity Broadcasting Inc., then the largest
radio station group in the country, to Westinghouse Electric Corp.,
then CBS' parent, for $4.9 billion. Given his well-known pugnacious
approach to business, people who knew him predicted he would soon
elbow aside everyone else _ even Michael H. Jordan, the chairman
and chief executive officer _ to run the company the Karmazin way.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, by May of 1997, he had elbowed aside Peter Lund,
the CBS network president, convincing Jordan to let him to take
control of the 14 television stations owned by CBS. ( Lund resigned
as a result.)
</P>
<P>
   Eleven months later, in April of this year, Karmazin was
promoted to president and chief operating officer of the entire
company, leaving Jordan to operate only certain corporate units
like the legal, finance and human resources departments.
</P>
<P>
   Since then Karmazin has overseen the trimming of the news
division's budget by 10 percent, the beginning of company-wide
layoffs that will reach about 300 people by the end of the year,
and the widely publicized dismissal of several longtime television
sales executives.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Karmazin defended those dismissals, saying the
salespeople ``were not doing as good a job as needed to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he had recently told a Goldman Sachs investors'
conference that ``if there is going to be a recession, we aren't
going to participate in it,'' adding: ``If every one of CBS' sales
people sells 10 percent more advertising, our revenues will be up
10 percent. Sometimes it's easier and sometimes it's harder to sell
10 percent more, but it's always possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, advertising sales alone do not make a successful
television network business. Programming must attract enough
viewers to attract the advertisers, and news and sports divisions
are expensive to operate, regardless of the state of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect, this is not Infinity,'' said one
high-level CBS executive, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``Mel is a brilliant radio operator and businessman, but
programming a television network and its owned-and-operated
stations is a trickier enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin said Wednesday that he was pleased with the way the
network's operations were going, under Leslie Moonves, president of
CBS Television. He firmly denied a report that he had told
investors he wanted to sell off the network and keep the stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the network in concert with our television
stations,'' he said Wednesday. ``The network provides over 50
percent of our station's programming. And we are seeing some very,
very encouraging early signs of CBS improving on the network
side.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the network ``will be profitable next year.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And he said he had no regrets about the decision to allow
Eyemark Entertainment, the television syndication unit owned by
CBS, to produce and distribute ``The Howard Stern Radio Show,'' a
late-night television program derived from the notoriously vulgar
radio show hosted by Stern.
</P>
<P>
   Karmazin began his career as an ad salesman for WCBS radio
station in New York, in 1967. He then spent 11 years at Metromedia
before moving to Infinity, also in sales, in 1981. Over the next 15
years, he built it into the largest station group in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, Karmazin approached Westinghouse in 1996 seeking to
buy its CBS and Westinghouse radio stations, to add to his Infinity
stable. He even offered to buy the whole corporation, with the
intention of selling off the non-radio divisions, but Jordan
refused. Karmazin later said he realized the combined strength of
CBS and Infinity radio stations was worth being acquired by another
company, as long as he could stay in charge of the radio
operations.
</P>
<P>
   He did far more than that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
