<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-ARENA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. GETS FOOTBALL TEAM, SORT OF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Professional football is returning to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   And the team doesn't even need an overhauled 70-year-old stadium
or a Spanish-style mall on a toxic dump to play.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it isn't the NFL, either, but L.A. is in no position to
get nit-picky.
</P>
<P>
   The Arena Football League, the quirky, eight-on-eight, ``50-yard
indoor war,'' is returning to this city for the 2000 season. An
as-yet unnamed expansion team will play in the new Staples Center,
joining the Lakers, Clippers and Kings as tenants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are anticipating an announcement early next week,'' said
league spokesman David Cooper. ``We're just really, really, really
excited about getting back to Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Roth, spokesman for Staples Center, confirmed talks with
the Arena league have taken place but said, ``Nothing's been signed
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the ownership group has not been revealed, but
Cooper said the group was ``the linchpin'' in granting L.A. the
franchise. One unconfirmed report had Universal Studios involved,
but a studio spokeswoman said she knew nothing about it.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles will be the league's 17th franchise, following the
addition of New Orleans. But with the Arena league seeking ties to
NFL cities _ Saints owner Tom Benson is the one bringing Arenaball
to New Orleans _ observers had expected the next team to go to an
NFL city, possibly Kansas City or Cleveland. AFL officials hope to
reach 20 teams by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Arena football just completed its 12th season and, like the NFL,
has been operating without an L.A. franchise for some time. The
Arena league's Cobras played one season at the Sports Arena, going
5-6-1 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-paced sport, part football, part soccer, part hockey,
is a high-scoring affair, boasting an average of about 90 points
per game. The league's 15 teams have combined to draw more than 1
million fans for the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose's SabreCats are the only other California franchise.
Other teams play in New York City, East Rutherford (N.J.), Houston,
Tampa Bay, Phoenix, Orlando, Portland (Ore.)., Milwaukee,
Nashville, Grand Rapids, Buffalo, West Palm Beach (Fla.), Albany
(N.Y.) and Des Moines, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Arena league play runs from May through August, culminating in
the ArenaBowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
