<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2563 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENDER-TAX-SURVEY-LAD     10-28 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENDER-TAX-SURVEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN CHARGED MORE FOR HAIR, CLOTHING SERVICES, STUDY FINDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Women are literally being taken to the cleaners
when they're handed the bill at dry cleaners and hairstylists,
according to a new statewide survey.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, released Wednesday by the California Public Interest
Research Group, found that 45 percent of the hair salons, 46
percent of the launderers and 17 percent of the dry cleaners
surveyed in Los Angeles, San Diego, San Francisco and Sacramento
charge women more for similar services than they do men, despite a
1995 law banning the practice.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 59 salons and 56 dry cleaners were investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Among those, women paid $7 more than men for a shampoo, cut and
blow-dry; $1.08 more for each laundered shirt; and $1.04 more for
each dry-cleaned shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the businesses surveyed didn't post their prices or make
written price lists available when asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are being taken to the cleaners by gender pricing,''
said consumer program associate Janee Pelletier of CalPIRG's Los
Angeles office. ``Not only is it unfair, but it's illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   The businesses were investigated in late September and early
October.
</P>
<P>
   On average, women paid $21.51 for a simple haircut, shampoo and
blow-dry, compared with $18.30 for men; $1.82 for a laundered
shirt, compared with $1.31 for men; and $3.32 for a dry-cleaned
shirt, vs. $3.24 for men. These averages include prices at the
businesses that did not discriminate.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Curti of Hollywood, who pays $50 for a shampoo, cut and
blow-dry at a salon in suburban Studio City, wasn't surprised by
the gender-based discrepancy for one simple reason: Women's hair is
much more labor-intensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would charge women more -- they have more hair and it has to
be styled more,'' she said. ``A man just runs his fingers through
his hair and he's done.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend, Tony Cicero of Studio City, pays an acquaintance
only $25 for his short 'do.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a friend of mine, otherwise she'd charge me $35,''
Cicero said. And it's for a styling job that's pretty basic. ``No
blow-drying, just cut and go.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelletier, however, said women are charged more at the salon
even when their hair is shorter than the average man's. And the
same goes with dry cleaners: A woman pays more than a man to clean
a plain white cotton shirt that needs neither special machines nor
special handling.
</P>
<P>
   And that is outlawed by the state's Gender Tax Repeal Act of
1995, which took effect Jan. 1, 1996. The law was passed in the
wake of a 1994 study by the now-closed California Assembly Office
of Research that found 64 percent of dry cleaners and 40 percent of
hair salons in five metropolitan areas charged women more than they
did men for the same services.
</P>
<P>
   That study found that women paid $5 more for a haircut and $1.71
more to have a shirt laundered, according to CalPIRG. Further
studies concluded that each woman in the state annually paid an
average of $1,351 more for those services than men, amounting to
$15 billion each year.
</P>
<P>
   Violators of the law are subject to a minimum $1,000 fine -- if
they're caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law is a good law, but it's not being enforced,''
Pelletier said.
</P>
<P>
   At Hair Sanctuary in suburban Woodland Hills, a woman who would
only identify herself as a manager said the salon charges men with
short hair $30 for a shampoo, cut and blow-dry. For women with
``normal'' hair the price ranges from $40 to $45, or ``a little
more'' if it's ``extra thick.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager said women who opt not to get a blow-dry would pay
$30. She said women's hair takes more time and effort than men's,
accounting for the price difference.
</P>
<P>
   For example, women's hair is blow-dried with a brush. For the
typical man, it's just a few swipes with fingers and dryer, and
they're done.
</P>
<P>
   ``For men, usually they don't blow-dry with the brush. If they
do brush, we would charge (more),'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lester Martinez, assistant manager at Fazio Cleaners in suburban
Sherman Oaks, said the six-store chain charges men and women $1.65
to launder their plain white cotton shirts. Both are charged $4.85
to dry-clean the same garment.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, machines do all the work, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because it's a woman's item, a cleaner doesn't have the
right to charge more,'' Martinez said. ``If it's an item that needs
special handling, they would have to charge that.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's where the price discrepancies start, because many
women's garments can't just go through the machines and need more
handling than men's, calling for extra personnel to do the work, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have your silks, beaded items, rhinestone, leather trims,
and that requires special handling,'' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Fazio doesn't post its prices, but will print them out at the
customer's request, Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Things are actually worse in other parts of the country,
Pelletier said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, 88 percent of dry cleaners in Massachusetts charge
women more for their services. In Illinois, 80 percent of hair
salons charge women more.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is way ahead of the pack because we have the law,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to Diana Horn of suburban Encino and her friend Jane,
who hadn't seen each other in some time and spent part of Wednesday
afternoon relaxing over coffee at a Starbucks in Sherman Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Both say they have noticed that men pay less than women do at
the dry cleaners.
</P>
<P>
   But the first thing each wanted to know of the other when they
met was who had done their hair. Both admit they pay a bundle, or
had paid plenty in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason that Horn, a script supervisor for the NBC
television series ``Jessie,'' no longer pays the $100 a pop she was
charged by a salon in posh Bel-Air is that the hairdresser cuts her
a good deal -- and does a terrific job to boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll cut my hair for me for $35,'' Horn said. ``Otherwise
I'd be spending ($100).''
</P>
<P>
   Jane, an actress and acting coach from Sherman Oaks who would
not give her last name, said she pays $70, plus a $10 tip, to get
her hair done at that same Bel-Air salon, where she has gotten the
only cut she ever really liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I send a lot of people his way,'' she said. ``He charges $100
normally, which is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more outrageous is that her boyfriend, whose hair is
longer than Jane's shoulder-length tresses, gets charged only $65
at that salon.
</P>
<P>
   She once asked the stylist about the discrepancy. ``He would
say, Well, well, that's just the way things are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The solution, according to CalPIRG, is to close loopholes in the
law, increase enforcement and industry oversight, and require
service providers to post their prices in easily visible areas.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
