<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2564 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMPIONSHIP     10-28 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOUR-CHAMPIONSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ Today, a 77-year-old man will sit on a few million pounds
of rocket fuel and get launched into outer space.
<TEXT>
<P>
   So why can't a 49-year-old man win golf's richest event? Tom
Watson wants to know.
</P>
<P>
   When the Tour Championship tees off today at East Lake Golf
Club, it will be nothing if not a celebration of the PGA Tour's
young guns. David Duval, Tiger Woods and Justin Leonard are just a
few of the 20-somethings with legitimate aspirations of winning
this week.
</P>
<P>
   If any of them do, it will continue the onslaught on the tour by
the younger generation in the past couple of seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of those, there is Watson. Or 41-year-old Mark
O'Meara. Or Payne Stewart, Hal Sutton or Fred Couples, all of whom
are closer to the older generation than the younger.
</P>
<P>
   A lot closer.
</P>
<P>
   Watson is the senior member of the 30-man field playing in the
season-ending Tour Championship at East Lake Golf Club. They ought
to call it East Lake Gold Club with all the high finance going on
here. The winner takes home $720,000 nuggets out of a $4 million
pot of gold.
</P>
<P>
   Watson may not be 77 like John Glenn. But he's 49, more than
twice as old as Woods. He isn't in the running for Player of the
Year. Duval and O'Meara will fight that battle. Watson isn't going
to win the money title, either. In fact, at No. 29, he barely
squeezed into this event.
</P>
<P>
   And he risked that spot by not playing last week at Walt Disney
World, opting to spend the weekend with daughter Meg at parents'
weekend at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   That's the sort of thing that puts another space in the
generation gap. Watson, sitting very nearly on the bubble for a
place in golf's richest payday, put his spot in jeopardy for a
family obligation.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Watson, O'Meara and others who remember the '80s
and maybe even the '70s puts this week's tournament in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   While the spotlight is on Duval and Leonard and Woods and the
other new blood, the old-timers aren't exactly fading into the
lush, green background at East Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can play in the tournament like I did today in the
practice round, I have a chance to win this thing,'' Watson said
Wednesday. ``I like to feel like I can win going into a tournament.
I haven't practiced much the past few months. And I worry about not
being tournament-tough, tournament-ready. I worry about my swing
holding up for 72 holes. It might hold up for 18 or 36. But you
never know about 72.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a foreign concept to the whippersnappers. They don't
worry about their swings betraying them. Mostly, they are concerned
with East Lake's glassy greens and the rough that will play havoc
with the occasional stray shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very comparable to Olympic (in San Francisco),'' said
Duval, comparing East Lake to this year's U.S. Open venue. ``The
fairways are narrow, the rough is extremely tough, and the greens
are hard, fast, and have some slope to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course dictates that you hit it in the fairway, knock it
on the green and make a birdie every now and then. Other than that,
you're not going to play golf out of the rough here. There's no
way.''
</P>
<P>
   A reliable swing off the tee truly will be the most valuable
asset this week. East Lake has bermuda grass in the fairways and
rough. It is rare that a marquee PGA Tour event is played on a
course with bermuda grass in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never played a major where we've had bermuda grass, so
it's different,'' said Woods. ``The rough is pretty deep. And being
semi-dormant, the ball goes straight to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be interesting to see how the tournament goes
once it starts. It will be a great test, no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, who has won two major championships, and Duval, who has
four wins for the year, are battling for the tour's Player of the
Year honor. Neither is a clear-cut winner yet. What happens this
week could sew it up for one of them. Or merely muddle the picture
more if neither seriously contends.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus at this point seems to be that Duval is the best
player in the world at the moment but that O'Meara has had the best
full season.
</P>
<P>
   If accuracy is at a premium at East Lake, it could favor
O'Meara. He consistently finds the short grass. Duval has a length
advantage, but at East Lake there is very much a risk/reward gamble
on every tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roughs are unforgiving here,'' said Vijay Singh. ``And
then on the greens, it's almost as bad. You have to hit a lot of
fairways and a lot of greens.''
</P>
<P>
   As Woods added: ``It's going to favor whoever hits it long and
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Watson. After his practice round
Wednesday, he gave an hourlong clinic to Atlanta-area kids who
otherwise would have no contact with a PGA Tour player.
</P>
<P>
   During the clinic, Watson asked how far the kids wanted to see
him hit the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Tiger Woods,'' came the reply, almost in unison.
``I'm twice as old as Tiger,'' Watson explained. ``I can't hit the
ball as far as Tiger.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can hit it straighter than Tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's enough to keep the older generation in step with
the youngsters remains to be seen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
