<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHIPPER-RADIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chipper Jones faces the music on WSB
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves third baseman Chipper Jones went before the
callers Wednesday morning on WSB Radio, spending three hours
responding to questions and comments about his infidelity in what
he hoped would be the first step toward public forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, along with Braves announcers Pete Van Wieren, Don Sutton
and Joe Simpson, were sitting in for the vacationing Neal Boortz, a
commitment that was made before Jones confirmed that he had
fathered a child out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the questions surprised me,'' Jones said afterward.
``All of the questions I had fielded already from family members. I
was prepared for anything, the best and the worst. In Atlanta, if
you are sincere, most people are the forgiving kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was encouraged by what happened, but I know it's going to
take some time.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the calls were supportive. The most critical
call came from a woman about two hours deep into the show.
</P>
<P>
   She said it appeared to her that Jones was getting support
because he was a star athlete, and the fact he was ``willing to
work it out makes it OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones replied, ``All I'm trying to do is ask for forgiveness.
... I'm not using the fact that I'm the third baseman for the
Braves to automatically sweep this under the rug. I'm not using my
authority to weasel my way out of this. I'm genuinely sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Wieren said there were discussions before air time as to how
much of the show would be devoted to Jones' problems off the field.
</P>
<P>
   All three Braves' announcers were candid in their questions to
Jones, with no attempts to play spin doctor. But Simpson leaped
once to Jones' defense after one particularly unforgiving caller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said at the start we did not want the program to be Chipper
Jones at the whipping post,'' Van Wieren said. ``We asked Chipper
if he wanted us to try and move in another direction, but he said
no. He wanted to hear whatever the callers had to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the other notables:
</P>
<P>
   _ On his reaction if his wife had acted the way he did:the
situation was vice versa with his wife: ``I honestly can't say I
would handle it as well as she did. ... I'd like to say I'd have
the grace, faith and hope she displayed, but there's only one Karin
Jones. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the strongest person I've ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On why he went public: ``I've not been blackmailed. It was my
decision and Karin's decision. ... I felt like the people needed to
know. I'd see all those Chipper Jones signs at the ballpark and
felt tremendous, tremendous guilt. I was wondering whether I was
worthy of all that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt if everything was out on the table, then people could
make their judgments. If they were still behind me, that's great.
If they were not, I understand. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was important to do it so that we could start the
process of getting this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
