<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2578 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKO-CADDY29-COX     10-28 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKO-CADDY29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson blames himself for woes
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ On a May night in Gulfport, Miss., a 34-year-old man
who should have known better sat cringing in a casino hotel room,
his arms filled with drug money, a cop's pistol barrel screwed into
his ear, his head spinning, looking across the room at the dealer
who gave him up and asking the same question his friends have asked
for months.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   This week, Greg ``Cadillac'' Anderson, dapper as always in a
gray suit, sat in a conference room in Houston with Tim Johnson,
his attorney, and remembered his desperate words:
</P>
<P>
   ```Why did you do this to me?' That's what I asked him.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the better question would have been: Why did Anderson, a
10-year NBA veteran, do this to himself?
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that Anderson, who pleaded guilty on Oct. 20 to
participating in a drug deal five months ago, can't come up with
one rational explanation for his behavior and can't put the blame
on anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't do it for the money. Anderson never took the $1,000
the dealer offered. He didn't do it for the drugs, either. Anderson
never was a hard-drug user.
</P>
<P>
   Like a character in an Elmore Leonard novel, this man who earned
about $7 million playing basketball was caught in the web of drug
dealers and government agents because he lacked the smarts and the
backbone to walk away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have said I don't want to be affiliated with this,''
he said Tuesday. ``When I knew what they were doing, I could have
said no. But I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Anderson says, he understands the damage was
self-inflicted, that he is guilty of negligence and, worst of all,
participating in a drug deal. That's why he twists in the wind,
awaiting his sentence on Feb. 9 for the crime of possession of
cocaine with intent to distribute. He tries to keep his life
together _ and his relationship with four children who were removed
from his home by a wife who is suing for divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is living, breathing proof that you don't have to be a
bad guy to get in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you sure don't,'' Anderson said. ``I wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He should have known better on the late-winter evening in a
Buckhead nightspot when he first met and drank beers with Anthony
Bates, who turned out to be an FBI informant, and Howard Hill, a
drug dealer Bates was assigned to collar. They were easy to know,
and Hill shared something in common with Anderson _ love of a big,
powerful V8 sedan, the Chevrolet Impala SS. Anderson's was black,
Hill's burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   During weeks that followed, Hill and Bates made frequent trips
from Biloxi to Atlanta, and Anderson ``only tried to show them some
hospitality.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says he wasn't sure at the time why they chose him, but
he later learned that Hill needed a drug connection in Houston and
that Bates was content to let the operation unfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have been suspicious,'' Anderson said. ``I wondered
how they had the money to keep coming up to Atlanta like that, but
I never asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse, he brought them to his teammates, who remember them today
as a couple of guys from Mississippi. ``Those were the guys?'' Ty
Corbin asks, incredulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I introduced them around,'' Anderson said. ``They'd come to
shoot-around, and after that we'd go to eat. They came when we
played Chicago, Charlotte. I didn't see no wrongdoing. We'd laugh,
joke, go eat. After that, they'd go separate ways. It never dawned
on me to have these guys checked out, never dawned on me these guys
were trouble. It was like friends come down see you play, cheer you
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Anderson says, he was made suspicious by the frequency
of their visits. ``I'm beginning to think, you guys keep coming
back; money ain't no object to 'em,'' Anderson said. ``But the
season be ending and the weather be nice, and you don't really
focus in on that.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the season ended, Anderson stopped in Biloxi
with teammate Anthony Miller. When Miller left the group that
night, Anderson learned the truth about his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed us a good time,'' Anderson said. ``We went to a
club, and that's when Hill told me, 'This (selling drugs) is what
we do in Mississippi. We got all this area, and that's what we do.'
Right then and there, I should have said I don't want to be
affiliated. That's what I should have did, but I didn't. You're
laughing and joking. I been driving all day, and your mind don't
click.''
</P>
<P>
   The trap is sprung
</P>
<P>
   A week later, on May 13, Bates and Hill went to visit Anderson
in his hometown of Houston. The two offered Anderson a $1,000
finder's fee if he could assist in helping them set up a drug deal.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson introduced the men to Kevin Blackmon, an old
acquaintance he thought might have drug connections. Anderson
recalls that Blackmon always drove a nice automobile. ``In the
neighborhood where I grew up, if you had a nice car, everyone knew
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Anderson and to FBI reports, here's what happened:
</P>
<P>
   Blackmon put up a kilo of cocaine and gave it to Hill, who left
his Impala in Anderson's driveway as security for the $26,000 cost
of the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Bates informed law enforcement officials on the Gulf Coast of
the transaction, so when Hill and his associate, Kevin Porter,
transported the drugs to Biloxi they were quickly apprehended
during a set-up traffic stop. When the cocaine was found in their
car, Hill agreed to implicate Anderson, just as Anderson later
implicated Blackmon.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, unaware of the drug bust in Biloxi, was called daily
by Hill in an effort to get Anderson to incriminate himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calling me every day, how much he sold, how much he made,
everything all right,'' Anderson explained. ``Calling me every day
to get me to come to Mississippi to pick up (Blackmon's) money;
saying he couldn't come to Houston because his son was diabetic and
in the hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson didn't have to go. It wasn't his business. But he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel I had to do it, but I introduced these two guys,
and the car is sitting at my house, and this guy's asking for his
money, and that guy's saying he can't bring the money, and what I
should have done was let these two guys fight it out,'' Anderson
said. ``I could have asked Blackmon to pick it up. I put it off two
days in a row. Hill called: 'Man, come on down; the casino's
packed.' He's saying, 'Come hang with me.' So I figured I'd get it,
square Blackmon up.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson flew to Mississippi on May 20 and was apprehended an
hour after he arrived in town. The FBI had put Hill in room 870 of
the Grand Casino Bayview in Gulfport. Monitoring equipment was
placed in an adjoining room. Hill set the trap, ``saying a guy
(was) coming to buy this last bit of drugs he had left _ two, three
ounces. I said I don't want to see that; I don't want this around
me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson didn't walk away. ``Soon as (an undercover cop)
buys (the drugs), the guy gives me the money, like 'Here's the
rent.' ``
</P>
<P>
   And that, says Anderson, is why he was holding $26,000 in drug
money when cops crashed into the room and put a gun to his head. He
was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   As Hill handed him over, Anderson agreed to reel in Blackmon.
Anderson was released and sent back to the Grand Casino Bayview to
spend the night in the government's entrapment room.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Anderson and Hill set up Blackmon at a Houston
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up the pieces
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Hawks officials and Anderson's teammates were
unaware of the situation until an FBI agent made references to the
case during a government hearing in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks learned of Anderson's involvement the night of June
24, while they were participating in the NBA draft. A day later, a
startled Miller said, ``I spoke to Caddy last night. He never said
a word.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization was shocked. Anderson just didn't fit the
profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have known better,'' Anderson said. ``I should have
been more careful, more suspicious, but I wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   So, now he tries to figure out what to do with the rest of his
life.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is going to prison, no escaping that. Federal
sentencing guidelines call for 30 to 37 months, but Johnson says he
probably will get less, under a recommendation from the government.
He would like to play in the NBA again, but he knows that it's a
longshot, at best. He could play overseas, if he can get a visa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could work with young players, too,'' he said. ``Tell them
what to look out for, give them some guidance so they don't make
the mistake I made, of trusting everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
