<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anatomy of a deal gone bad
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A summary of Greg ``Cadillac'' Anderson's involvement
in and arrest for drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   _ Late winter 1998: Greg Anderson goes to the Buckhead
nightclub, Atlanta Live, and begins a friendship with two men from
Biloxi, Miss. _ Anthony Bates, an FBI informant, and Howard Hill, a
drug dealer that Bates is stalking. Bates and Hill travel to
Atlanta often during March and April to visit Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   _ May 5, 1998: Anderson and teammate Anthony Miller are
entertained by Bates and Hill in Biloxi, then drive to Houston,
Anderson's hometown, the next day. Anderson knows his estranged
wife and children have moved out of his home but now learns that
most of the furniture also has been taken.
</P>
<P>
   _ May 13: One day after Miller returns to Atlanta, Bates and
Hill visit Anderson in Houston. They tell him they are looking for
a drug deal and offer to cut him in on a finder's fee of $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ May 14: Anderson introduces his new friends to Kevin Blackmon,
an old Houston acquaintance, who has drug connections. The meeting
is successful; the operation is planned.
</P>
<P>
   _ May 15-16: After being supplied with a kilo of cocaine, Bates
and Kevin Porter, Hill's crony, are detained at a set-up traffic
stop in Biloxi. The supply of cocaine, already divided into 16
bags, is discovered. Hill, the deal-maker, has Anderson drive him
to the airport in Houston. He flies home to Gulfport and is quickly
apprehended.
</P>
<P>
   _ May 20: Anderson flies to Gulf Shores to pick up a payment for
Blackmon at the Grand Casino Bayview Hotel. In room 870, an
undercover agent buys the remaining three ounces of cocaine and
hands the money to Anderson. Agents enter the room, put a gun to
Anderson's head and arrest him. Anderson is released, after
promising to cooperate. He is allowed to spend the night in room
869, the room from which the events in 870 were recorded hours
earlier. The government has paid for the room.
</P>
<P>
   _ May 28: Anderson arranges a meeting at a Houston restaurant
with Blackmon, so Hill can pay him $26,000 for the cocaine. As
Anderson goes to the men's room, Blackmon is apprehended with a
total of $28,000, including $1,000 meant for Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   _ Oct. 20: Anderson, Porter and Blackmon plead guilty to one
count each of possession of cocaine with intent to distribute.
Three other counts are dropped. Hill had pleaded guilty one week
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   _ Feb. 9, 1999: Anderson can be sentenced to a maximum of 40
years but really is facing 30 to 37 months, according to sentencing
guidelines. He might draw a lesser sentence at the request of the
government, which promised to intercede, pending his cooperation
and good conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
