<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ACCREPORT29-COX     10-28 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ACCREPORT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clemson to meet N.C. State on Saturday
 &HT;    By Norman Arey and Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEMSON vs. N.C. State, Saturday, noon
</P>
<P>
   Questions about coach Tommy West's job security that began early
in the season reached a peak after the 28-23 loss to Duke. West
says he has not talked or met with athletics director Bobby
Robinson about his job and has already started planning for next
season. Although Robinson has said West and the team will be
evaluated after the season, the AD said last week that West's
one-year contract extension given this summer was not guaranteed
and any buyout was capped at $325,000. ... Despite the team's
struggles on offense, the defense is ranked second in the ACC
heading into Saturday's game against North Carolina State. ...
Freshman running back Travis Zachery, a former All-State player at
Marietta High, leads the Tigers with 441 yards.
</P>
<P>
   DUKE at Vanderbilt, Saturday, 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem strange, but the Blue Devils could be a bowl team
at the end of the season. The 4-4 Devils close out their season
against Vanderbilt, Maryland and North Carolina _ three teams
without a winning record. But don't say that to Duke coach Fred
Goldsmith. ``I haven't been talking about a bowl,'' he said. ``My
gosh, look at our record over the past few years. It hasn't been
that impressive, and it's not that impressive this year. Vanderbilt
has probably chalked us up as a `W' a long time ago.'' Duke has
gotten better, and the turnaround seems to have been most
pronounced when Bobby Campbell replaced Spencer Romine at
quarterback. Campbell has completed 49 of 85 passes for 524 yards
and two TDs and only one interception in his last three games.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA STATE vs. North Carolina, Saturday, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bobby Bowden says he's very familiar with North Carolina
freshman quarterback Ronald Curry, who will face his team for the
first time Saturday. ``We tried our best to recruit Curry out of
high school,'' he said. ``I thought he was the best quarterback,
no, football player, I've ever seen.'' ... Bowden also says he's
aware of Tar Heels All-America cornerback Dre Bly and expects to
see FSU's wideout Peter Warrick go against Bly. ``If I knew where
Bly was going to line up, I'd try to get Pete somewhere else. But
we're going to test him.'' ... Both defensive tackle Jerry Johnson
and cornerback Tay Cody got banged up against Georgia Tech last
week, but Bowden says both will play. Only Lamont Green will miss
the game with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND vs. Georgia Tech, Saturday, noon
</P>
<P>
   The Terrapins, mired in a three-game losing streak, will make
their debut in the new Ravens Stadium in Baltimore. Maryland hopes
to attract 25,000 for the game, held approximately 40 miles from
its College Park campus, although it had only 23,419 for its Oct.
17 homecoming game against Wake Forest. ``It's such a close
proximity to College Park,'' coach Ron Vanderlinden said. ``It's a
win-win for everybody.'' ... The lone bright spot for a Maryland
offense that ranks last in the conference is running back Lamont
Jordan, who posted the fourth 100-yard rushing game of his career
in the 20-10 loss to Wake Forest. Jordan is third in the ACC with
81.7 yards per game. ... The Maryland defense, led by linebackers
Eric Barton and Kendall Ogle, ranks fifth in the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA at FSU, Saturday, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Carl Torbush probably will wait until game time before
making a decision on a starting quarterback. Freshman Ronald Curry
passed for 230 yards and a touchdown in last week's 38-31 victory
over Wake Forest; senior Oscar Davenport returns after serving a
one-game suspension for violating team rules. ... After opening the
season with three losses in a row, the Tar Heels take a three-game
winning streak into Saturday's game at Florida State. UNC, with the
conference's seventh-ranked offense, goes against a defense ranked
No. 1 in the ACC and the nation. ``The key against them is to make
yardage on first down,'' Torbush said. ``If they get you in
second-and-long or third-and-long, that's when they're able to make
the big plays with the sacks, hits, and interceptions.''
</P>
<P>
   N.C. STATE at Clemson, Saturday, noon
</P>
<P>
   Ray Robinson had a career performance in last week's 23-13 loss
to Virginia, and the freshman running back hopes to build on the
effort against the ACC's second-ranked rushing defense. Robinson
rushed for 202 yards on 27 carries against the Cavaliers, an
individual high and the fourth-best single-game rushing total in
school history. ... The Wolfpack are second in the ACC in total
offense and seventh in total defense. ... Junior quarterback Jamie
Barnette holds the school record for total offense (6,104 yards)
and probably will add another pair of records this week. He needs
12 yards to pass Terry Harvey as the all-time leading passer and
one touchdown to break his tie with Harvey for TD passes. ...
Receiver Torry Holt is fourth in the ACC in career touchdown
receptions (26) and fifth in receiving yardage (2,709).
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA at Wake Forest, Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers must play the rest of the season without
All-America safety Anthony Poindexter, out with a torn ligament.
Coach George Welsh says he hasn't decided on Poindexter's
replacement yet. ``We're trying Adrian Bumin and Antwan Harris
there, but I don't want to go into the Wake game, with their
passing attack, with only one cornerback. If we take Harris away
from corner and play him at safety, I'm not sure that's the way to
go.'' ... Virginia is one of only seven teams in the country to
average 200 yards or more both rushing and passing. ... Virginia
tailback Thomas Jones has scored six touchdowns in his last three
games and leads the ACC in rushing and is ninth in the country with
1,229 yards. ... Wake's Desmond Clark has 23 catches against
Virginia over the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   WAKE FOREST vs. Virginia, Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   With injuries throughout the season to seven of its 11 defensive
starters, the Deacons have fallen well short of expectations. ``We
have had a whole rash of injuries,'' coach Jim Caldwell said.
``It's the most I've ever been through except for one year when I
was an assistant at Penn State.'' ... With Virginia leading the ACC
in rushing offense, Caldwell knows what his team's priority is.
``The focal point in this game is to stop the run,'' he said. ``We
can't allow people to run the ball and keep the ball out of our
offense's hands. Virginia's front seven is as fine as you'll see in
the country.'' ... Wake might have a few tricks up its sleeve.
Wideout Desmond Clark lined up at tight end against North Carolina
last week on several sets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
