<HEADER>
A2583 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BLKCOLLEGES29-COX     10-28 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BLKCOLLEGES29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former Div. I coaches vie in Magic City
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two former Division I coaches now guiding programs in
the SWAC will meet Saturday in the Magic City Classic in
Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Former Temple coach Ron Dickerson will lead the Alabama State
Hornets against Alabama A&AMP;M and coach Ron Cooper, the former coach
at Louisville. Both teams are struggling entering the annual match
at Legion Field, which has attracted crowds of more than 40,000
each of the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets (2-5) was idle last week, while Alabama A&AMP;M (4-4)
has two losses in a row to Division II opponents, Tuskegee and
Miles of the SIAC.
</P>
<P>
   _ A blast from the past
</P>
<P>
   The once-powerful ``Big Blue'' of Tennessee State, which has
gone eight years without a winning record, played its last
homecoming game at Hale Stadium last week and mustered the kind of
offensive performance last seen during the heyday of the late
``Big'' John Merritt.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers (5-2), a victory shy of their first winning record
since the 1990 team coached by Joe Gilliam Sr. finished 7-4, routed
Ohio Valley Conference foe Tennessee-Martn 76-0 before an overflow
crowd of 22,046 _ 6,000 more than seating capacity.
</P>
<P>
   The most lopsided victory since TSU routed Kentucky State 83-0
in 1966 came without head coach L.C. Cole and his brother, Johnnie
Cole, the offensive coordinator. The Cole brothers were serving a
university-imposed one-game suspension that resulted from an
in-house investigation of alleged violations of NCAA rules
involving former TSU quarterback Todd Valentine. The NCAA's
investigation is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers, who take their home games to new Tennessee Oilers
stadium in downtown Nashville next season, will play their final
home game Nov. 16 when former Big Blue player and coach Bill Thomas
brings his Texas Southern team to town.
</P>
<P>
   _ No 'D' for Doug
</P>
<P>
   Grambling's Doug Williams, after watching his team get blown out
68-35 at home by Jackson State, fell to within two defeats of a
losing record in his first year as coach at his alma mater. The
Tigers, 3-4, have matched the number of victories recorded last
season under Eddie Robinson. They haven't done it with defense,
though, giving up 40 points or more in three games. In Saturday's
loss, Jackson State wide receiver Sylvester Morris from New Orleans
victimized the G-Men's defense so severely he was named SWAC
``Offensive Player of the Week.'' The 6-2, 210-pound junior caught
eight passes for 201 yards and five TDs.
</P>
<P>
   _ MIghty little, mighty powerful
</P>
<P>
   Livingstone College, the smallest Division II school in the
country, with 650 or so students, continued to roll toward Atlanta
and the Pioneer Bowl for the second year in row. Livingstone
registered the CIAA's most lopsided win of the season, shellacking
Elizabeth City State 59-0 Saturday to reach 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Livingstone's running backs, freshmen Carlton Jones
(849 yards) and Ray Chambers (496), and sophomore Shannon Gainey
(452), have averaged 6 yards or more per carry.
</P>
<P>
   _ Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Anticipated blowout of the week: Florida A&AMP;M, the I-AA scoring
leader at 50 points a game, has had a week to rest for battle-worn
Morgan State (1-6). Morgan coach Stump Mitchell should expect no
mercy in Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
