<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2584 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS29-COX     10-28 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons line focusing on blitzes
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves added an extra period
to practice Wednesday so his offensive line could work on picking
up blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps what the team really could use is extra blockers on
passing downs. The Falcons have surrendered 30 sacks this season,
including 14 on third down and one on fourth down, and are on pace
to allow 69. Opponents are sacking Atlanta quarterbacks once every
7.7 passing attempts, worst in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   So the priority at Suwanee is to improve.
</P>
<P>
   The simple idea of keeping more people in to block isn't always
the answer. Recognition of the defense, however, is part of the
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta didn't anticipate New York coming with an all-out,
eight-man blitz Sunday, such as the one on which quarterback Steve
DeBerg got hit and lost a fumble that New York returned for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   A week earlier, starting quarterback Chris Chandler was knocked
out of the Saints game when all three New Orleans linebackers
criss-crossed up the middle. The Falcons didn't anticipate that
move, either.
</P>
<P>
   The simplest answer in these situations? ``Get rid of the ball
quick,'' Chandler said, even if it means throwing it away.
</P>
<P>
   As Atlanta struggles, opponents continue to blitz. They look at
Chandler, or any quarterback for that matter, and see instant
injury potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not like every team is showing the same blitzes each
week,'' center Robbie Tobeck said. ``We have to get better at
recognizing. The talent is there. We're getting our quarterback hit
too much. We need ... a sense of urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who looked healthy enough in practice Wednesday to
make the team think he'll be the starter Sunday against the Rams
(2-5), would say amen to that.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said that rookie tackle Jose Portilla will split time
with rookie right tackle Ephraim Salaam and that rookie Bob Hallen
will split time with second-year left guard Calvin Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need better recognition (of what defenses are doing),
better film study, watching where the 'backers and safeties line
up,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons rarely involve tight ends in blitz pickups. Starter
O.J. Santiago often leaves the game in passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, there are two running backs in the backfield, and their
first assignment is blitz pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can stop (blitzes) one (game),'' Collins said, ``other
teams won't use it as much.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
