<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2587 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NY     10-28 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA: WITH $4 MILLION, WHY GO FOR MORE?  
 UTAH: LIBERTARIANS TAKING A CRACK AT MORMONS 
IOWA: SENATOR DUMPED FOR MRS. CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also sent in category `p') 
(nk) 
 By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The other night when Sen. John McCain of Arizona debated the
four challengers who are trying to unseat him on Nov. 3, only 40
people showed up to listen, which was as good a measure as any of
the excitement this race has stirred.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a conservative Republican in a state that loves
conservative Republicans, appears to be a shoo-in for a third term,
with the latest poll showing he will probably pull more than 60
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Even one of his challengers, John Zajac, a Libertarian, conceded
during the debate that ``the senator will be easily re-elected.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is McCain, who has raised $4 million for his re-election
effort, a lot of money for a race like this, still out raising even
more money? Why did he send out a fund-raising letter the other day
saying that ``in the next seven days'' he had to come up with
another $80,000 or so?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be prepared,'' he explained in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that earlier this year, when he led the congressional
crusade to increase the tax on cigarettes _ a crusade that enhanced
his already high national profile and increased speculation about
possible presidential ambitions _ the tobacco industry mounted a
$40 million counterattack against him and his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But while the senator may fear a new attack, with less than a
week to go until Election Day, there is no real evidence that the
industry plans one. So the likelihood is that he will not be forced
to make a last-minute defense and will end up with a campaign
surplus of some $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   How will he spend it?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to roll all that money into a presidential fund the
day after the election,'' Ed Ranger, his Democratic challenger,
predicted in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   He can do that. Others have.
</P>
<P>
   But the senator insists he is looking only toward Nov. 3, not
the year 2000. His only concern, he says, is ``personal attacks of
the most vicious nature, as orchestrated by the tobacco industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Libertarians Taking a Crack at Mormons
</P>
<P>
   As in most other states, the Libertarian Party of Utah finds
itself almost perpetually short of members and in an uphill fight.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, two of every three people in Utah are Mormons,
members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, and
Mormons tend to vote Republican. In fact, so many Mormons vote
Republican that a few months back church leaders, concerned that
the church was increasingly being viewed as a political monolith,
urged members to be diverse in their political thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Which gave Libertarian leaders an idea.
</P>
<P>
   They are going hard after the Mormon vote, arguing in Mormon
phrases and words that their party is the party of ``correct
principles'' and ``free agency'' and thus the logical ``righteous''
choice for faithful Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our principles and LDS principles are the same,'' says Jim
Dexter, the Libertarian chairman.
</P>
<P>
   To spread the Libertarian recruiting message as widely as
possible, the party recently ran half-page advertisements in the
Sunday editions of the state's newspapers, under the headline,
``It's OK to be a Mormon and a Libertarian.'' Played prominently
was a reference to the recent plea by Mormon leaders for political
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders have not made public comments on the Libertarian
recruitment effort except to say that the church is generally
``politically neutral'' and does not endorse candidates or parties.
But Republican and Democratic leaders, especially the former, have
criticized the effort as a blatant, offensive and unacceptable
mixing of religion and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religion is a personal matter with people,'' said Spencer
Stokes, the executive director of the Utah Republican Party. ``It
will backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Dumped for Mrs. Clinton
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, a possible Democratic
presidential aspirant in 2000, asked to speak to a big AFL-CIO
rally in neighboring Iowa, home of the first presidential caucuses.
Labor leaders said no: He was out of tune on changing Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Now the senator has had the door slammed on him again.
</P>
<P>
   He was scheduled to speak this weekend at a major
get-out-the-vote rally in Des Moines. But instead, he has been
told, Hillary Rodham Clinton will be in the state that day and,
well, she'll be the headliner.
</P>
<P>
   ``A matter of practicality,'' said Iowa Democratic Chairman John
Norris.
</P>
<P>
   Was it also a matter of the Clinton candidate for 2000 being
Vice President Al Gore, not Kerrey?
</P>
<P>
   Norris wasn't saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the first lady is terrific,'' Kerrey said, gamely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 2223EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0532 </DOCNO>
