WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Canada: Quebec Vote Set for Nov. 30
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of speculation, the date for elections in the
predominantly French-speaking province of Quebec has been set for
Nov. 30. The current Parti Quebecois government, led by Premier
Lucien Bouchard, has vowed to hold a third referendum on Quebec
independence. The primary opposition, the Liberal Party of Jean
Charest, opposes separation and will campaign on economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: General Sentenced to 15 Years
</P>
<P>
   A cashiered Mexican general has been sentenced to 15 years in
prison for collaborating with the Arellano Felix brothers, leaders
of Mexico's most violent narcotics organization. Gen. Alfredo
Navarro Lara was arrested in March 1997 and discharged from the
military after he offered a bribe of $1 million a month on behalf
of the traffickers to the chief of the federal anti-drug police in
the border state of Baja California.
</P>
