<SLUG> BC-FBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES CARSON HAVE THE RIGHT STUFF?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Out of nowhere, Carson, Calif., that little community forever
immersed in the shadow of Long Beach, that obscure hamlet whose
high school once produced mighty football teams, suddenly finds
itself a major player in Los Angeles' attempt to secure an NFL
expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, as Hollywood super agent Michael Ovitz was in Kansas
City unveiling his Carson stadium plan to the NFL owners, I did
something I sheepishly must admit I've never done during my lengthy
encampment in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   I ventured to Carson.
</P>
<P>
   While it doesn't exactly have the magnetic ambiance of the
French Riviera, I have to admit I've never been to a place that had
as many hair salons per square block, nor have I ever been to a
place that had a cleaner trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   With the old Olympic Auditorium fight publicist Van Barbieri
serving as my guide, I drove around the landfill acreage where
Ovitz wants to build his stadium and walked around the strip malls
on Carson St.
</P>
<P>
   I spoke to attorneys, real estate brokers, locksmiths,
restaurateurs, waitresses, legal aides, short order cooks and,
natch, hairdressers and various other types in an attempt to get a
reading on the mood of those who actually work in Carson.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of hours of scouring the gritty area, I
discovered that an overwhelming preponderance of the populace hopes
Michael Ovitz's dream stadium comes to fruition, with only a few
vocal dissenters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it's going to happen,'' says Theron Jackson, a
long-time broker for Realty World and a 1972 Long Beach State
graduate. ``Why not? This is the perfect location. It'll be right
next to the San Diego and Harbor Freeways, and the Long Beach and
91 freeways aren't that far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Coliseum has a chance with the NFL. There
are just too many deterrents in the areas surrounding the Coliseum.
I used to live at 41st Drive and Figueroa, and I'd never live there
now. It's just too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carson to me is the perfect place, halfway between L.A. and
Orange County. I think it would be a huge boost to the area. And
I'm sure a new stadium would increase the real estate values in
Carson.''
</P>
<P>
   But the proprietor of an Italian diner, Domenick Sardisco, is
keeping his fingers solemnly crossed that Carson doesn't go ahead
with its stadium plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be disastrous for this city from a financial
standpoint,'' says Sardisco, whose Domenick's has been a 42-year
fixture in Carson. ``I think this thing is a total joke. Where's
the money going to come from?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're talking about floating a $150 million bond. You can
bet that means they're going to raise our property taxes. Why
should I pay for something that won't help me. The whole idea is
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about freeway access? There'll be traffic jams here that
will disrupt the entire area. And they talk about putting in a new
mall. We already have a mall, a good mall. And it's struggling. Why
do we need another mall? I can't believe our politicians have got
us involved in something like this. It might sound good to some
people. But in reality, it just won't work. We just don't have the
money here in Carson.''
</P>
<P>
   Domenick Sardisco, a man not afraid to give opinions, shakes his
head slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way this is going to happen,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But others have brighter, slightly more positive outlooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a football stadium here would be just great,'' says
Walter Janoff, a UCLA graduate who has practiced law in Carson for
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a big sports fan and I hope it goes through,'' says Tito
Lacorda, a law clerk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually think there is a fifty fifty chance of this stadium
venture making it,'' says Chi Ferrer, as he sits on a barber chair
getting a trim from Mario Rabaino at Gill's Hair Studio. ``I hope
it does. I live right near where the stadium would be, and it would
be so easy for me to go to the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifty fifty?
</P>
<P>
   The New Coliseum people will tell you that Michael Ovitz has a
better chance of joining John Glenn in space than he does of
erecting a stadium in Carson.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe so.
</P>
<P>
   But at least people outside the boundaries of Carson are doing
something that has never been done before in this country actually
holding a conversation about Carson.
</P>
<P>
   I figured the one person who could offer penetrating insights on
Ovitz's stadium proposal would be a palm reader on Carson St. near
Delores.
</P>
<P>
   I rang the buzzer on her front door, and told the lady who
answered that I'd like to know her feelings on the Carson stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm just a helper the palm reader isn't here,'' she said.
``But I'm not sure she can predict the future of a football
stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither can anyone else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
