<HEADLINE>
MAURO'S `DOCTOR CHOICE' ISSUE HAS DISAPPEARED FROM RHETORIC AS HE
AND BUSH NEAR END OF CAMPAIGN TRAIL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
and R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO, Texas _ The issue of doctor choice, an early focus
of Garry Mauro's gubernatorial bid, has practically disappeared
from the stump rhetoric as he and Gov. George W. Bush near the end
of the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Mauro, the state's land commissioner, said Wednesday
that he still supports requiring health maintenance organizations
to allow patients to choose their doctors. He said he has focused
on education issues during this week's campaign blitz through West
and South Texas because public school issues are of greater
concerns to voters there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people in this area don't have access to HMOs so
it's kind of silly to talk about choosing your own doctor when you
don't have an HMO,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Bush also has said little about the issue in the
waning days of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   During appearances Wednesday in Waco, College Station and
Nacogdoches, he pushed his plans for welfare reform, urged voter
turnout and acknowledged that he'd like a landslide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope 50 percent plus one, but if you ask me, I would hope to
get maybe 60 percent of the vote,'' Bush said in Nacogdoches.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Mauro has trailed by double digits in polls taken throughout
the campaign, and hoped to hit a nerve with voters last April when
he launched a $1 million television advertising campaign,
criticizing Bush for vetoing the 1995 Patient Protection Act.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the legislation would have raised health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   It would have required health maintenance organizations to allow
patients to choose their own doctors and to pay for care at
specialty institutions such as Houston's M.D. Anderson Cancer
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro's expensive ad campaign was viewed as a good strategic
gamble, since 84 percent of respondents in a February Houston
Chronicle-Dallas Morning News poll agreed that HMOs should not be
allowed to restrict a patient's choice of doctors.
</P>
<P>
   HMO plans are not required to offer the choice, although some
do. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``I ran the TV ad early to send the message that I was in the
race seriously, that I wasn't going away,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   In the ads, Mauro said, ``To choose your own doctor, you need to
choose a new governor.'' Mauro advocates a constitutional amendment
guaranteeing doctor choice.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has argued that patients can choose their doctors within
their own insurance plans, and he said most insured Texans have the
option of paying more for a full-service insurance plan that will
pay for them to see a doctor of their choice.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has noted that Texas law guarantees every citizen
treatment at cancer centers such as M.D. Anderson, and he said most
health insurance plans will pay for that treatment if it is deemed
medically necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign stops this week, Mauro has only briefly mentioned
doctor choice, and usually only when the issue has been raised by
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said he has not changed his position on doctor choice and
that he is still running a television spot on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But as he campaigned Wednesday in Laredo, San Antonio, Corpus
Christi, McAllen, Edinburg and Brownsville, his speeches focused
almost entirely on his plan to give teachers a $6,000 pay raise and
borrow $2 billion from the Permanent School Fund to reduce class
sizes.
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized Bush's plan to end ``social promotions'' by
requiring students in certain grades to pass the Texas Assessment
of Academic Skills standardized test before advancing to the next
grade.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro says promotions should be based on evaluations by
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the three issues that are going to win the election
for me are teacher pay raise, TAAS and HMOs and I'm choosing to
talk about TAAS and teacher pay raise right now,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a judgment call. It's a political decision. I just happen
to think teacher pay raise and TAAS is a better issue right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, seemed to be sensing a big victory as he
suggested the possibility of claiming 60 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In Nacogdoches, Bush told about 500 cheering students at Stephen
F. Austin State University that voting is their duty: ``In a free
society, a society that relies upon people, it's important to
vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush promoted his welfare reform plans while touring Mission
Waco, a faith-based ministry that uses state funds for job
training. The mission's operations are set up in what used to be an
adult movie house and bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place has gone from a porno theater to a house of love,''
Bush declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government can hand out money,'' Bush said. ``What it can't do
is put hope in our hearts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's welfare plan includes homes for teen-age welfare mothers,
allowing faith-based mentoring of welfare recipients and $100
million in funding for child care for the working poor and for
welfare recipients in job training.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also wants to cut off welfare for people who do not
cooperate in child support enforcement and permanently cut off
people who cheat on welfare. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
