</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOURCHP29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    East Lake course offering test equal to a PGA major
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Considering how tough the neighborhood used to be,
maybe it's fitting that the best players in the world are expecting
a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   After two days of practice rounds at East Lake Golf Club for the
start of today's $4million Tour Championship, members of the top 30
are beginning to wonder if there's an exorbitant price to be paid
for such huge financial rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Playing hard and fast from unseasonably sun-baked fall
conditions, East Lake has become difficult enough to be disguised
as a major championship. Typical of such events, par is about to
become an acceptable score. From what the players are saying, if
you hid the $720,000 winner's check in this clumpy, nasty Bermuda
rough, somebody probably would find it by Thanksgiving. If the
greens get any faster and firmer, those sadistic guys from the USGA
are liable to become jealous.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the pressure and everything, it's set up like a U.S.
Open,'' Masters and British Open winner Mark O'Meara said. ``The
rough is that deep. If you're an inch off the fairway, you're going
to take out your wedge, your 9-iron. ... I think 6-under by the end
of the week is going to be a good score. If you gave me 6-under,
I'd sit in the clubhouse after 72 holes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a choice, I wouldn't be playing these roughs,'' PGA
champion Vijay Singh said. ``It's unbelievable. It's probably the
hardest roughs I've ever played. ... Even if you're 100 yards away,
it's almost impossible to move it sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   If some cooler weather approaches by the weekend and the wind
picks up, said Tiger Woods, the 1997 Masters champion, ``I'd say
anything under par is looking pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If they really want to tuck the pins and get the greens really
hard and fast, even par would be a good score,'' No. 2 money winner
Jim Furyk said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour Championship starts today, with tee times beginning at
11 a.m., five years after Tom Cousins began his $25 million project
to refurbish East Lake as the center of a entire neighborhood
redevelopment exceeding $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   People such as David Duval, who went to school at Georgia Tech,
1989-92, barely recognize the property that once was considered
among the most crime-ravaged in Atlanta. Where muggers once
harrassed club members and a classic Donald Ross course went into
serious disrepair, new cars from Mercedes, a co-sponsor, with the
Southern Co., are parked safely near tee boxes. This week's
security, according to PGA Tour officials, is no tighter than at
any other Tour Championship venue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot different now than it was then,'' Duval said. ``It
doesn't look like the same place coming in. Six, seven years ago it
wasn't the best area to be driving into.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Tour Championship marking a return to the spot that
hosted the 1963 Ryder Cup Matches, many of the PGA Tour's
season-ending awards are to be decided by Sunday, when the winner
through 72 holes will have earned $10,000 per hole.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a highly unlikely scenario, Duval has the money title
all but wrapped up. With $2,470,498, Duval needs to finish 24th to
guarantee the distinction and could be thwarted then only if Furyk,
second with $1,820,334, wins.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, only the second player since 1982 to win two majors in
a season, could see the voting for PGA Tour player of the year
tighten considerably if Duval were to win Sunday and pass $3
million. Duval said he considers the money title ``more significant
than the stardom, personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods leads Duval 69.10 to 69.14 in the race for the
Vardon Trophy, for the lowest scoring average.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the season-ending event, and there's a lot at stake,''
O'Meara said. ``The money title is at stake. The stroke average is
at stake. The player of the year is at stake, a little bit. ... I
think (the Tour Championship) is a great idea. It's kind of like
our World Series, you might say.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the last year the Tour Championship will mark the end of
the official money season. In 1999, the World Golf Championship
American Express Championship will be held the next week in
Valderrama, Spain, and will be counted as official money.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
