<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOURFEA29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods fever slowly breaking
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Is Tigermania over?
</P>
<P>
   The first wave might be ebbing, as the 22-year-old golf
superstar tees up today in the Tour Championship at East Lake Golf
Club.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Tiger Woods failed to win a major golf title, won only
one other time _ at the BellSouth Classic in Duluth in May _ and
this weekend someone else will inherit player-of-the-year honors
from him.
</P>
<P>
   A mellower Tiger showed up Wednesday for an early-morning
practice round, and afterward, about 75 fans stood around the
practice green waiting for his autograph or photos. Twice that many
followed four-time winner David Duval as he teed off on the 10th
hole. Woods looked up from his putting lesson from coach Butch
Harmon and appeared curious that a TV crew was setting up greenside
to film not him but PGA champion Vijay Singh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to win, get a victory under my belt,
considering I haven't won as much as I would like to this year,''
Woods said about this week's event against the tour's 29 other top
players. ``But it's still been a great year, whether I win or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   To those outside the game who love to see him rip mammoth drives
and sink unbelievable putts for a come-from-behind win, Woods'
consistent year might seem boring. But that's what Woods treasures
about this season. In all but four of his 17 PGA events, he
finished in the top 10. It's the biggest change from his erratic
breakout season in which he acknowledges, ``I was either winning
the tournament, or I'd be 20th or 30th. (This year has) just been
one of those years where I've been close, but not quite good
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   A major consolation is that his 69.10 average strokes per round
is the lowest on Tour. If he can hold off Duval (at 69.14), he will
take home the Vardon Trophy, which he sees as a validation of his
growing maturity on the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes to show you haven't shot yourself in the foot with
some 80s, or when conditions are tough, you don't blow up and blow
out of the tournament; you still hang in there,'' Woods said.
``That's what I was able to do this entire year.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's next year to think about. This will be Woods' last
appearance in Georgia before the Masters in the spring. He will
skip his defense of the BellSouth because it didn't fit his
schedule that revolves around the four majors, lucrative
international events and corporate commitments.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how he plays, he still has a gantlet to run every day.
After he finished putting Wednesday, fans chased after him,
thrusting hats, posters and magazines at him. When he reappeared
from the clubhouse and later from the media tent, fans still waited
for him. His life is not that different from when he won the 1997
Masters, and he gets tired of it. ``I still get hassled just as
much,'' he complained.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, his mere entry in a tournament created such a
media frenzy that the tour called a special weekly press conference
just for him. One sign that Tigermania might have peaked appeared
last week, when Woods was finally allowed to skip that obligation.
When asked if he's become just another pro golfer, Woods replied,
``God, I hope so.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
