u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-TOURNOTE29-COX     10-28 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TOURNOTE29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    East Lake's range lives up to its name
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It throws them off a bit at first.
</P>
<P>
   It kind of takes the lob wedge out of warmup preparations.
</P>
<P>
   It's not every day the PGA Tour's elite players have to clear a
water hazard on the practice range.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, those balls they kept plunking in the pond in front of
East Lake's practice range are free, anyway. East Lake members have
to lose their own balls there during the other 51 weeks of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Furyk said he's seen floating driving ranges in Florida, but
never one with about 110 yards of required clearance to hit dry
land and the first flagstick target.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting,'' he said. ``I can't pull the sand wedge out
for the first club of the day unless I want to lose about 10 balls.
First swing of the day, I'm not getting one over that lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara said Wednesday when striking his first ball on the
range, ``What's with the water?'' He finally went to a pitching
wedge to stop the dunking.
</P>
<P>
   Several players turned the strange setup into a competitive
situation. Intentionally hitting low, punch shots into the water,
players such as David Duval, Vijay Singh and Phil Mickelson tried
to skip balls onto the green. Known for his creativity, Mickelson
managed it on his second try.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where's the fairway?
</P>
<P>
   To a man, the players are impressed by East Lake's quality and
the joy of playing a classic, old-style course renovated so
carefully by Rees Jones. Only one area of moderate criticism has
been heard. At the 480-yard fifth hole, which plays as a par-5 for
the members, the fairway is among the most narrow on the course.
``I'm not sure if there is a fairway out there,'' said Furyk. ``I
haven't found it yet. I'm still looking. I walked across the
fairway at one spot and counted 21 yards. ... I guess it's fair
because everyone has to play it. But I would say that hole is
definitely the one I hear the most grumbling about in the locker
room.'' ... Course conditions have been drastically altered by the
warm, dry weather. The zoysia fairways normally are a bit softer
and don't run this swiftly. Packed this tightly, balls are more
prone to find the penalizing bermuda rough. The bermuda is even
tougher because some spots were slightly hit by last week's frost,
creating pockets in the turf. ``Being semi-dormant,'' noted Tiger
Woods, ``every ball goes straight to the bottom. I've hit a couple
wedges just trying to hack the ball out.'' ... Duval said he ``just
flat killed a 2-iron'' on the par-3 18th, which was playing 242
yards to the hole. Joked Duval, ``It's nice to have a driveable
par-4 on every golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   _ O'Meara gets Singh's vote
</P>
<P>
   If you ask Singh, nothing that happens this week should affect
the player of the year voting by the PGA Tour players, which will
be announced Nov. 20. ``Five years from now, nobody's going to know
who won the 1998 money list,'' Singh said, ``but they're all going
to know that O'Meara won two majors.'' ... Commissioner Tim Finchem
made no announcement on future Tour Championship sites Wednesday,
but predicts one in a few weeks. East Lake is expected to get a
return engagement in 2000. Finchem said that when the decision to
play at East Lake was first made, ``somebody said the weather in
Atlanta can be a little iffy at that time of year. If this is iffy,
we can take this all year long.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
