<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA COUNCIL CAN BE MORALE BOOSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Every Friday night, UCLA fullback Craig Walendy
piled the white, wet, chilled french fries on his plate.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't fried but baked, resembling slices of a raw potato.
They were supposed to be a late-night snack, but Walendy never
touched them. He tried salt, he tried ketchup, he tried salt and
ketchup. Yet they remained white, wet and chilled _ and uneaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ate them,'' Walendy said. ``We picked them up and threw
them away, and we didn't get full. I talked to the trainers, and
they said they never ordered them to be baked.''
</P>
<P>
   Walendy had one recourse: the UCLA players' council, a nine-man
elected body that meets regularly with coach Bob Toledo to discuss
everything from team morale and practice times to pregame food and
locker-room towels.
</P>
<P>
   As the running backs' representative, Walendy described the faux
fries. Toledo listened, agreed and decreed that the fries be fried.
It sounds silly, but it meant everything to Walendy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's really important to the team to have the players'
council,'' Walendy said. ``When I first got here, there wasn't one,
and there was a lot of complaining. When your opinions are never
voiced to the coach, it leads to players being unhappy and a
general bad feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Walendy was a freshman in 1995, Terry Donahue's last season as
coach. Donahue had team captains during his 20-year tenure but
never a council or advisory board to hear concerns and complaints
from various limbs of the 105-man team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't think of coach Donahue as someone you couldn't
talk to, but we didn't really have a way to make our complaints
known,'' said one player who requested anonymity. ``It's not easy
for younger guys to walk into the head coach's office and start to
tell him what we think.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo replaced Donahue after the 1995 season and redecorated
the program like a new home. He upgraded the
strength-and-conditioning program. He emphasized national
recruiting. He installed a dynamic offense and he recreated the
player council from his head-coaching tenures at UC Riverside
(1974-75) and Pacific (1979-82).
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a player, there was a head coach, but you never
talked to him, you never knew who he was,'' Toledo said. ``You can
separate yourself as a head coach if you're not careful.'
</P>
<P>
   Each position and the freshman class have a representative on
the council, which complements team captains Cade McNown and Larry
Atkins. Toledo meets with the captains regularly, as well, but two
cannot speak for 105. McNown, a senior quarterback, has different
concerns than a freshman offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The council) helps develop a bond between the players and
coaches,'' said safety Jason Stephens, a redshirt freshman. ``No.
1, it's a vehicle to communicate things. And No. 2, it tells us the
coaches care how we feel. We're not just players on a team. We're
part of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   The council is unique among UCLA teams, and only two Pac-10
football programs have similar bodies. Washington State's panel is
selected by position and class; Oregon uses a senior-loaded,
16-member board that includes one player from the other classes.
</P>
<P>
   For all three teams, councils, not captains, are the most
effective method of communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found that being a captain is a tough situation for
kids,'' Ducks coach Mike Bellotti said. ``It puts them in a role
between the coaches and players. The coaches want them to be team
leaders, the players want them to do player advocacy. They get
caught in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins elect their representatives during training camp. The
current members are Walendy, junior Brad Melsby (receivers), senior
Mike Grieb (tight ends), junior Kris Farris (offensive line),
junior Pete Holland (defensive line), junior Ramogi Huma
(linebackers), senior Tod McBride (defensive backs), junior Chris
Sailer (special teams) and Cory Paus, who represents the freshman
class and the quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo meets with the council each week during training camp and
every two weeks during the season, unless there is a pressing
concern. They gather on Spaulding Field after practice, away from
fans, family and media. Sometimes the meetings last two minutes,
sometimes 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we went to him and said, `We're dog tired,' then if he felt
it was right, sure, he'd cut back practice,'' Farris said. ``But
the reason he respects our input is because we're not going to ask
out of practice because we want to watch TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the requests are mundane _ ranging from bigger towels
and a locker-room clock to pregame Snapple and postgame pizzas _
but Farris says that's the beauty of it. A slew of petty
complaints, if left to fester, can clot player-coach relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's risk vs. reward,'' Farris said. ``The cost of giving us
Snapple is nothing compared to the appreciation we have for him
listening to us. It shows us we're in it together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
