<DOCNO> NYT19981028.0559 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2806 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOV-THIRDPARTY-NYT     10-28 1423
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-THIRDPARTY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 RACE FOR 3rd PLACE PITS GOLISANO AGAINST McCAUGHEY ROSS  
(duplication warning: also sent with `a' code) 
 (bl)  
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although nothing in politics is certain, polls suggest that
Republican incumbent George Pataki will probably win the race for
New York governor on Tuesday, and that Democratic nominee Peter
Vallone will finish a distant second.
</P>
<P>
   The real mystery is who will come in third.
</P>
<P>
   Among the minor-party candidates jostling for that dubious honor
are Thomas Leighton of the Marijuana Reform Party, which advocates
a system of legal distribution of marijuana; the Green Party's Al
Lewis, also known as Grandpa Munster, and Michael Reynolds of the
Right to Life Party.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to carrying the Republican Party standard, Pataki is
the candidate of the Conservative Party. Vallone counts on the
support of the Working Families Party.
</P>
<P>
   But the two leading contenders for also-ran are a millionaire _
B. Thomas Golisano, a Rochester businessman who ran for governor on
the newly formed Independence Party ballot line in 1994 and is
doing so again _ and a millionaire's wife: Betsy McCaughey Ross,
the formerly Republican lieutenant governor whose try for the
Democratic gubernatorial nomination collapsed after her husband,
financier Wilbur Ross, withdrew much of his financial support. Ms.
McCaughey Ross is now on the Liberal Party line.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent New York Times/CBS News Poll shows Golisano with
9 percent of 1,235 registered voters polled, and Ms. McCaughey Ross
with 5 percent, to Vallone's 21 percent. Pataki is in front with 56
percent. Nine percent are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Given Pataki's sizable lead from the start, neither Golisano nor
Ms. McCaughey Ross has exactly shaken up the race. But not
constrained by hope or expectations, they have persisted with their
quixotic campaigns, Golisano with considerably more enthusiasm. For
both candidates, more than mere ego is at stake. Unless they win
50,000 votes, their parties will lose their official lines on the
ballot in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Golisano's campaign strategy is simple: a few news conferences
assailing Pataki's ``borrow-and-spend'' policies, and lots of
money. His most recent financial disclosure form, filed Oct. 20,
showed that he had lent his campaign just over $20 million, and
that it had spent close to $12 million. He estimates that his
spending will total $13 to $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   With paid media doing the work for him, Golisano is free to
continue tending his payroll processing company, Paychex Inc.,
which he founded in Rochester in 1971. He and the political
consultants and media concerns he has hired have papered the
state's buses, trains and billboards with his slightly smiling
visage and blitzed its television stations with witty political
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ads needle Pataki about the state's growing debt. In
1994, Golisano ran on a range of issues, including massive tax
cuts, and won 4 percent of the vote, but this year, he has made
debt reduction the centerpiece of his campaign, saying that Pataki
has irresponsibly increased state spending and ballooned its debt,
particularly through ``back-door borrowing'' that is not approved
by the voters. ``He's trying to create a false sense of euphoria
about our state's economy,'' Golisano says of the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate's focus appears to be paying off. In an attempt to
ride Golisano's financial coattails, aides say, Vallone has begun
hammering the theme of debt reduction much harder. And on Sunday,
The Rochester Democrat &AMP; Chronicle, which endorsed Gov. Mario Cuomo
in 1994, endorsed Golisano, whom it described as ``beating the
drums of fiscal responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the withdrawal of her husband's financial support, Ms.
McCaughey Ross has had no choice but to keep a lower profile. She
devotes most of her time to banging out Op-Ed articles and policy
papers at her Manhattan office. ``She's spending a lot of time
behind her laptop,'' said Cristina Page, an aide at the lieutenant
governor's office. ``She usually spends her day with me in the
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross was plucked from political obscurity by
Pataki in 1994 after writing several highly critical articles about
President Clinton's health care plan. As she put it, ``I'm not a
typical career street politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Her demeanor is not that of a desperate campaigner but of a
beatific crusader. She, too, has adopted only a few issues:
reproductive rights; the expansion of the state's prescription drug
program for the elderly, and explaining to Congress, the public and
anyone who will listen why the Republican Congress should not
impeach Clinton. (``I'm a constitutional scholar,'' she says in
explaining the issue's relevance to her.)
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. McCaughey Ross does venture out, it is often unclear _
even to her own aides _ whether her appearances are as lieutenant
governor or as a candidate. Last week, for instance, she visited a
Chinese-American health care clinic, debated Dick Morris, a former
presidential adviser, on the president's travails and showed up on
a Saturday morning at 8:30 in a black suit and pearls to support a
Brooklyn abortion clinic regularly visited by anti-abortion
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the blurring of lines is a practical matter. As her
campaign spokesman, Kevin Davitt, put it, ``Frankly, she has a
little more oomph as lieutenant governor'' on the issues. ``Our
problem is we're not as _ how shall we put it _ desirable as we
were during the primary,'' Davitt said.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. McCaughey Ross was one of the political dignitaries in
last week's Yankee parade _ riding alone in a convertible _ she did
not share the dais with the governor and Vallone, who is the
speaker of the City Council. (The governor and the lieutenant
governor essentially stopped speaking several years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   Her campaign has fallen to the Liberal Party and its chairman,
Raymond Harding. His party cast its lot with Ms. McCaughey Ross in
part because her husband had pledged several million dollars to her
campaign. When he withdrew the bulk of that support less than two
weeks before the primary, all bets were off, and the pressure was
on Harding to raise enough cash to run something of a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first time the Liberal Party has had the `privilege'
of having to not only run the campaign but worry about the
fund-raising angle of it,'' Harding said. Harding is a close
mayoral ally and a partner in the lobbying firm of Fischbein
Badillo Wagner Harding and among the friends and clients he has
tapped are some, like Donald Trump and David Walentas, the
developers, whose real estate concerns are likely to be affected by
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Harding has raised enough money to get some television ads
featuring Ms. McCaughey Ross on the air, and he says he is
confident that the Liberal Party will win enough votes to secure
its future.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross said she was uncertain about her future past
election day, but she said that another gubernatorial campaign was
possible, although she did not specify a party. Many politicians
and analysts believe it is unlikely, after the events of this year,
that she will ever again be a major party candidate for either
party.
</P>
<P>
   The future of Golisano's party, which he founded about four
years ago, seems assured as well, which he says is partly the
reason he ran. The Independence Party now has 122,172 registered
members. (The Liberal Party has 92,498 members, and the
Conservative Party, 166,985.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We're creating permanent competition with the Independence
Party,'' Golisano said. ``With competition, the consumer wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Consciously or not, Golisano is also building his business:
while he has spent millions of his own money, he and Paychex have
also earned millions in free publicity. But Golisano said that the
attention in New York state would not have a significant impact on
his nationwide business.
</P>
<P>
   Will he run again? ``I'm certainly going to keep an open mind to
it,'' Golisano said, ``and I'm going to be very active in the next
four years. There are some issues I still want to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief among them, he said, is campaign finance reform. If he had
another way of reaching voters, he said, like debates or free air
time or public financing, he would have preferred to give the $13
million or so to charity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could take the money out of the campaigns,''
Golisano said. ``Peter Vallone might have had a better chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
