<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-IRVIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN'S RETURN LEAVES IRVIN GIDDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The man was soaked from the afternoon workouts.
Sweat is flying everywhere with each crazy gyration of his arms,
with each swivel of his hips. Yet you move in closer. You don't
want to miss one word. This is Michael Irvin unplugged.
</P>
<P>
   He's going on and on about his struggles without Troy Aikman:
``I know we lost some of our bravery, some of that `oomph, we can
do it.' '' He's telling you that he still has not learned coach
Chan Gailey's complex offense, ``all we do is run plays ... but I
still don't know it like I'd like to know it.''
</P>
<P>
   He does know this: Philadelphia Eagles cornerback Bobby Taylor
has built his reputation mostly because of his play against Irvin.
This reputation has come even though Taylor often gets double- and
sometimes triple-team help against Irvin. In four head-to-head
regular-season and playoff matchups, Taylor and the Eagles double-
and triple-teaming have held Irvin to an average of 53 yards
receiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young guys come in and they want to play a guy with a name
so they can get their name,'' Irvin said. ``Then they say to
\Rhim\S, `Man, you put it on Michael Irvin.' That's all you need,
and it's off and running.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin might understand this rite of manhood in the NFL. But he's
hardly flattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``How does that flatter me?'' said Irvin, whose matchup against
Taylor will be scrutinized when the Cowboys play at Philadelphia on
Monday Night Football. ``I'm already the big boy. I get no flattery
knowing that he got the big-boy title over me.''
</P>
<P>
   You want to know how Aikman's return from a five-game absence is
supposed to help the mental wherewithal of the Cowboys? Look no
further than the demonstrative Irvin. Not only is the yak back, but
so is the confidence of a man who has caught 45 of his career 61
touchdown passes from Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to play with any quarterback in the history of this
league, there is no one I'd pick over Troy. No one!'' Irvin said.
``I know that he knows the things I'm trying to do on the field. I
know he knows when I'm going to break out, and when I'm going to
break in. And I'm talking about when I have my back to him, even if
the play didn't dictate that. I know if he's on the field and if
there's a chance in the world that I'm one-on-one, the ball is
coming to me. I just know he's throwing it to me. That's our
comfort level.''
</P>
<P>
   Aikman calls it, ``flattering,'' to hear how much he's missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those things that sometimes you get with a
particular player or receiver and sometimes you start seeing the
same things they are seeing,'' Aikman said. ``And they start
thinking the same way that you are thinking. It's fun when you
develop that and play alongside guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But both concede there is still lots of new ground to cover.
Aikman has played just 5 1/2 quarters. And Irvin, though he is
third in the NFL in receiving yards (578) said he feels lost in an
offense that has him running routes from all over the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are ways I run routes in this offense when \Rcoach Chan
Gailey\S tells me \Rcorrecting\S, `No, you've got to go now, you've
got to do this now,' '' Irvin said. ``I don't know the catching
point of every play in this offense, where I should look for the
ball, or how I should expect it coming out.
</P>
<P>
   But Irvin insists that he will get Gailey's offense down soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run so many plays in practice that you can't help but get
better,'' Irvin said. ``We didn't run as many plays before Chan got
here. Before, we had a lot of individual things. Now it's
different. Chan may dress it up, calling it a team drill,
perimeter, red zone, Nickel blitz. But it's all 11-on-11. When you
do that so much you get comfortable with your assignment.''
</P>
<P>
   To Irvin, though, the learning is not coming fast enough. He's
reminded nearly every day about not having scored a touchdown since
Dec. 8 against Carolina, a span of nine games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed because if I'd have scored, maybe those
13-12 games would be wins,'' Irvin said. ``If we were 7-0 it would
not be as disappointing. But losing, knowing I didn't get in the
end zone, that's disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   A few moments after musing about his touchdown drought, Irvin
noticed injured linebacker Broderick Thomas across the locker room.
Thomas shouted to Irvin, ``watch out for the \Rmedia\S traps.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin smiled and flicked some sweat off his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no trap I can't get out of with No. 8,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
