<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 23:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DEBATES-MEDIA-630&AMP;     10-28 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEBATES-MEDIA-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATES: A TRADITION WITH MORE IMPACT ON REPORTERS THAN ON VOTERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Back in the summer of 1982, few people gave Mario
Cuomo, then the lieutenant governor of New York, a real shot at
winning the Democratic primary for governor. By almost any measure
_ financial backing, name recognition _ he stacked up miserably
against the front-runner, Ed Koch, the seemingly indomitable mayor
of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a July morning when the two squared off at a breakfast
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Most voters did not see it. Most probably heard little about it.
But opinion makers were there, and Cuomo's assured and eloquent
performance wowed them. From that moment on, reporters followed his
campaign and sought his comments. And their assessment of his
importance, reflected in that bounty of coverage, registered with
viewers and readers, who chose Cuomo over Koch in the September
primary.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of debates, political analysts and politicians said,
is not so much the reactions of the television viewers watching
them, who generally represent a tiny fraction of voters. The real
impact is the way debates define or explode existing images of
candidates among representatives of news organizations, whose daily
and weekly reporting reaches a much bigger audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debates have a profound impact on the people who cover them,''
said Maurice Carroll, a former political reporter who is now the
director of the Quinnipiac Polling Institute. ``It colors the way
they see candidates and what they broadcast and write the next
morning and every day that follows.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the debates last weekend between Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., and his Democratic challenger, Rep. Charles
Schumer, the impact could be negligible, and that is not because of
the predictably small audiences who watched them. (Television
executives estimated that fewer than 300,000 people saw the first
debate, on Saturday night, and fewer than 250,000 saw the second
one, early Sunday afternoon.)
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the debates came too late in the race to alter
substantially its dynamics, and both candidates are veteran
politicians already well known to opinion makers. Moreover, they
caused no surprises: D'Amato and Schumer merely parroted the
messages they had been repeating in prepared remarks and paid
commercials for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidates' cautious adherence to scripts was a tacit
acknowledgment of how closely reporters were watching, and how
loudly and persistently any miscalculation might echo in their
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say it is not the whole of a debate that
matters; it is the headlines atop newspaper stories and the sound
bites in television news segments that count.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you're really fighting for is not two hours of attention
but 30 seconds on television news,'' said Nelson Warfield, a
Republican political consultant in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Consultants labor mightily to try to influence what those 30
seconds _ or the first several paragraphs of a newspaper story _
will be.
</P>
<P>
   On the front end, they plant pithy gibes and compelling
anecdotes in a candidate's head and then suggest to reporters what
to watch for. On the back end, they instantly offer unsolicited
observations about the salient moments.
</P>
<P>
   In the minutes following the first debate between D'Amato and
Schumer, for example, a reporter for The New York Times who was
writing about the event received telephone messages from eight paid
consultants and political operatives who wanted to share their
thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Warfield and other political consultants said television news
coverage was considered increasingly precious because local
newscasts tended to ignored all but what they considered the high
points of campaigns. And debates always rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``A debate has conflict, and TV loves conflict,'' said Mike
Murphy, a Republican media strategist.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Murphy said enterprising strategists try to stretch a debate
into three or four days of television news stories: the
preparation, the countdown, the big night, the morning after.
</P>
<P>
   In relatively tight races, like the one between D'Amato and
Schumer, debates have become largely tests of poise in which each
thoroughly rehearsed, painstakingly prepared candidate tries to
hammer home one or two essential points while steering clear of
gaffes and rooting for his or her opponent to carom into one.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how scripted each candidate's remarks are, a debate
creates more room, and more chance, for spontaneity than any stump
speech or formal interview.
</P>
<P>
   Consider President Gerald R. Ford's off-the-cuff comment in a
debate with Jimmy Carter in 1976 that Poland was not under Soviet
domination. It was a line repeated endlessly in news reports over
subsequent days, and political analysts said it contributed
considerably to Ford's image as somewhat bumbling _ intellectually,
as well as physically, clumsy.
</P>
<P>
   More often, however, the aftershocks of a debate are subtler.
The first debate of the Senate campaign in New York this year was a
case in point.
</P>
<P>
   It happened back in June, and the three Democrats vying for
their party's nomination _ Schumer, former congresswoman Geraldine
A. Ferraro and Mark Green, the New York City Public Advocate _
trudged all the way to the upstate town of Bolton Landing, N.Y., to
participate in it. News coverage was slim.
</P>
<P>
   But several reporters there said they were struck by how little
zest Ms. Ferraro brought to her performance. And they said that
impression helped to create one of the running themes of the
coverage of Ms. Ferraro that followed: that she was coasting on her
place in history as the only woman to get a major party's vice
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate was way the hell up in the middle of the sticks,''
Andrew Kirtzman, a political reporter for New York 1 News, a cable
news channel, recalled. ``And it wasn't broadcast live anywhere.
But she performed badly, and it wasn't long after that that she was
seen as this kind of giant headed for a fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirtzman and other reporters said that in that same debate,
Green carved out a niche as the election's spirited attack dog,
ignored only at his opponents' peril. Green said he experienced a
bounce in both news coverage and contributions after the debate.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said the sort of bounce that Green felt that
he got _ and that Cuomo clearly did get in 1982 _ was precisely
what Gov. George Pataki, now seeking re-election to a second term,
is trying to deny his Democratic challenger, Peter Vallone, the New
York City Council Speaker. Pataki has repeatedly refused to debate
Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   In a grossly uneven race, a challenger can bridge some of the
gap, analysts said, simply by sharing a stage with a front-runner
or occupying the same visual frame. That tableau, shown on
television newscasts and in newspaper photographs, bestows an
equivalence of stature that voters may not have considered.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki is far enough ahead in the polls that he can afford the
resentments of whatever small number of voters deemed his decision
unsportsmanlike, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
