<SLUG> BC-NY-VACCO-SPITZER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC LEADERS ASSAIL VACCO OVER INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: Also filed in ``a'' category.) 
(mk) 
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Editors of a weekly newspaper say state Attorney
General Dennis Vacco told them early this week that it was hard to
prove the effectiveness of the death penalty because researchers do
not ``stand outside a bodega'' and ask ``the bandito'' if capital
punishment deterred him from crime.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of the remarks, which circulated rapidly Wednesday,
produced strong condemnations of Vacco by many Hispanic civic
leaders and politicians, who said the comments betrayed a bias
against Hispanic New Yorkers. Vacco disputed that contention and
insisted that he had not used the word ``bandito.''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over Vacco's remarks put him on the defensive
Wednesday just as he was trying to take political advantage of an
admission by his Democratic opponent, Eliot Spitzer, that he had
been less than forthright about his campaign financing.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco called a news conference at his midtown campaign
headquarters Wednesday afternoon to raise new questions about
Spitzer's campaign financing. But Vacco, a Republican, faced a
flurry of questions about his remarks on Monday to the editorial
board of the newspaper, The Jewish Week. Reports about the
comments, which are to be published in an issue of the newspaper
due out Thursday, were spread quickly Wednesday by Hispanic civic
leaders and politicians and by Spitzer's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the reinstatement of the death penalty in many states
had not caused murder rates to decline, Vacco told the editorial
board that it was hard to survey criminals, said Rob Goldblum, the
newspaper's managing editor. Then, according to Goldblum, Vacco
said, ``You don't stand outside a bodega and ask the bandito if he
would have killed someone if there was a death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Vacco said at the news conference that he had not used the word
``bandito,'' although he did acknowledge that he had used
``bodega'' and had often used the image in his public remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say it, I didn't say it,'' Vacco told reporters. ``I
was there with a member of my campaign staff. We took copious
notes. I did not use the word bandito. I have never used that word.
I have used that analogy innumerable times over the last four
years, have never used that word.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goldblum said that he and other editors of The Jewish Week,
which is based in Manhattan, stood by their report. He said that
the comments came at the end of the meeting, and that the newspaper
did not have a tape of the final section of the discussion. Vacco
said that a campaign aide had brought a tape recorder to the
session, but that it had malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Some Hispanic civic leaders said they found Vacco's remarks
objectionable, regardless of whether he had merely used bodega or
had also used the word bandito, because they imply that people who
stand outside a Spanish grocery are likely to be criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't even realize the implications of his choice of
words,'' said Lorraine Cortes-Vazquez, president of the Hispanic
Federation, an association of 60 nonprofit agencies. ``The whole
sentiment is a disparaging one. It's such a poor reflection that he
has on the Latino community. You're not cavalier about the death
penalty, and you're not cavalier about 27 percent of the population
that you represent.''
</P>
<P>
   Vacco insisted that his comments were not biased. ``I didn't say
it, I didn't say it,'' he said, referring to the word bandito. ``So
how could it be a slur if I didn't say it?''
</P>
<P>
   He said, too, that bodega carried no ethnic connotations. ``What
is the difference between a bodega and a deli?'' he said. ``I've
used the two phrases interchangeably.''
</P>
<P>
   Vacco was asked what word he had used, if he had not said
bandito, but a campaign aide announced that the news conference was
over. Vacco did not answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Vacco raised several new questions about Spitzer's
campaign finances. Spitzer acknowledged Wednesday that he had
repeatedly misstated facts about his campaign financing. Spitzer,
who has taken out more than $9 million in bank loans to run for
attorney general in 1994 and again this year, has often said he
alone was paying off the loans.
</P>
<P>
   But he said for the first time earlier this week that his father
had lent him money late in 1994 to repay $4.3 million in bank
loans. The loan from his father may not violate state campaign
finance laws, but the acknowledgment represents a political
embarrassment for Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Vacco said Wednesday that Spitzer had reported in disclosure
statements that he received more than $4 million in bank loans
earlier this month for this year's campaign. Vacco asked how
Spitzer had financed his campaign this year before obtaining the
loan.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer, who was campaigning Wednesday in Buffalo, deflected
questions about his financing. ``I have revealed all the facts, and
the issue should be behind us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer tried to turn attention back to questions about Vacco's
fund-raising, particularly to large contributions from a Long
Island car-leasing company made after the attorney general's office
settled charges against the company. ``The question still remains:
Which company under investigation by the attorney general's office
has Dennis Vacco accepted contributions from?'' Spitzer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 2332EST &QL; 
