r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-CLUB-SLUMP-LADN     10-28 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-CLUB-SLUMP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF-CLUB MAKERS AIM FOR GREEN WITH NEW LINES OF BALLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- What's the big deal about golf balls, anyway?
After all, they're all round, white and covered with those cute
little dimples, aren't they?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is: plenty, if you're a golf-club manufacturer
looking for a way to inject some life into your company's revenue
stream.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that most manufacturers have just about reached
the edge of the technological envelope when it comes to clubs. And
today's equipment is so expensive that most players can't afford to
replace their clubs on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Golf balls, though, disappear almost as often as socks in the
laundry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the golf industry, you are at the end of the technology
cycle,'' said Joe Teklits, an analyst at Ferris Baker Watts in
Baltimore. ``When you go through cycles, it's nice to have
something that is a regular seller.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the beauty of the ball industry and why at least three of
the game's most noted club makers -- Cobra Golf, Callaway Golf Co.
and Taylor Made Golf -- are eyeing a new field these days.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the Carlsbad, Calif.-based companies has a ball either
in the research-and-development lab or ready for market in an
attempt to grab a chunk of the annual $1 billion-plus industry.
</P>
<P>
   Cobra and Taylor Made declined to say how much they have
invested in the project, and officials at Callaway, which underwent
a management shake-up this week, could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cobra, it seems, carded a coup of sorts by hitting the market
first with its new line of Dista balls, which this week are being
shipped to retailers in some markets in Southern California and
Arizona. They will be introduced nationally at the golf industry's
big trade show in Orlando, Fla., in January.
</P>
<P>
   Cobra's ball comes in four models, including a women's version,
that all are geared to specific swing speeds. They will be marketed
to recreational golfers, not professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with consumer research to identify some
opportunities in the golf-ball business where there might be a
gap,'' said Fren Haven, Cobra's project manager for the new ball.
``We saw a need for a distance golf ball that would have better
feel and fit a player's swing speed.''
</P>
<P>
   The balls will be priced in the high $30s to low $40s per dozen.
</P>
<P>
   Cobra partnered with the Acushnet Co., maker of the Titleist
ball, which has the biggest market share. Titleist is also used by
more professional players worldwide than any other ball.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, Cobra is not going to try to take market
share from Titleist.
</P>
<P>
   Haven said his company will target Spalding's brands, like the
Top Flite Strata ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view our business as one in which our job is to try and
help the recreational golfer . . . improve the way he plays and
enjoy the game at the end of the day,'' Haven said.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor Made made a big capital bet on securing a share of this
lucrative market in July when it bought the industrial assets of
Hansberger Precision Golf, a Pontotoc, Miss.-based manufacturing
and testing facility that produced the Ram Tour Golf Ball.
</P>
<P>
   Terms were not disclosed, but the deal culminated a two-year
prototyping relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Colburn, Taylor Made's marketing manager for golf balls,
said the company is in the ``tweaking'' phase of development and
hopes to introduce its ball in time for next year's professional
golf season. But that will depend on when the plant is up and
running.
</P>
<P>
   The name and characteristics, though, are still a mystery,
though Colburn said some pros will use it on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice market,'' he said of the ball business. ``People
keep having to replace their balls. We think we have a ball that
creates a consumer benefit they are not getting right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Milne, an analyst at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco,
said the ball projects are important to all three companies,
especially Callaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be much more competitive in the ball market for
Callaway given their amount of capital investment,'' he said. ``And
if you are not first, you had better be coming in with something
that is different and innovative.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
