r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NET-PROVIDER-SURVEY-L     10-28 0274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-PROVIDER-SURVEY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT, AT&AMP;T RATED TOPS AMONG ONLINE PROVIDERS BY J.D. POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- AOL may be the biggest, but Microsoft Network is
the best national Internet service provider, according to a new
J.D. Power and Associates survey.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Power, best known for its annual ranking of automobiles
based on customer satisfaction questionnaires, has turned its
sights in recent years on other industries ranging from airlines to
telecommunications. Wednesday's study is the company's first
examining customer satisfaction in their ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   Based on responses from 5,234 households with Internet access,
the suburban Agoura Hills-based market research firm gave the nod
to Microsoft Network and AT&AMP;T's WorldNet for the No. 1 and No. 2
spots, respectively. Prodigy, Compuserve and America Online rounded
out the list of national providers. Together the companies
represent 52 percent of the online market, J.D. Power reported.
</P>
<P>
   Rankings were based on combined scores in five categories --
access, integrity of connection, value, additional services and
discounts, and technical support.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Power would not release actual scores for each Internet
company, but an AOL official said her company scored a 96, vs.
Microsoft's 106 points. And, not surprisingly, AOL quibbled with
its last-place ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have high customer satisfaction, and all this survey
says is that all five companies are pretty close,'' said Ann
Brackbill, a spokeswoman for the Dulles, Va.-based provider.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
