<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-28 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT &LR;      10-28 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE POLITICS IS NOT ACADEMIC 
AT ARTS AGENCY, PENTAGON DREAMS 
A BIT PART FOR GIULIANI
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAMES BARRON with Judith H. Dobrzynski   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marvin Kalb is moving back to Washington. Kalb was a
correspondent for CBS News and NBC News before he moved to
Cambridge, Mass., and a job with a mouthful of a title: director of
the Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and Public
Policy at the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard
University.
</P>
<P>
   He will step down on July 1, he said Wednesday, and will take a
new job with a shorter title, as executive director of the center's
Washington office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is an extraordinarily interesting place now to
explore the relationship of the presidency and the press,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Back at Harvard, a search committee has been set up to find a
new executive director, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee has decided that his replacement will be a
journalist, a decision Kalb called a ``great victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're at a university and surrounded by faculty, and if the
director is a scholar as opposed to a practitioner, who then speaks
up for journalists?'' he said. ``I found that to be my special
responsibility, and I have enjoyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   At Arts Agency, Pentagon Dreams
</P>
<P>
   They had to strain to hear William J. Ivey, the soft-spoken new
chairman of the National Endowment for the Arts, at a reception on
Tuesday organized by Randall Bourscheidt, the president of the
nonprofit Alliance for the Arts. But the arts administrators,
museum directors and authors liked what they managed to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been quoted as saying the NEA should be as important as
the Department of Defense,'' Ivey said. ``That budget would be
nice.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Pentagon's annual budget is $270 billion and
his agency's is $98 million.
</P>
<P>
   He told an audience that included Glenn D. Lowry, director of
the Museum of Modern Art, and Robert R. MacDonald, the director of
the Museum of the City of New York, that a budget request next year
of $150 million to $200 million ``would not be shocking.'' The next
budget, he said, would ``look different than any NEA budget of the
past.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, at a dinner party given by Mary Sharpe Cronson, a trustee
of the New York State Council on the Arts, Ivey helped celebrate
the 52nd birthday of dancer Peter Martins. Kitty Carlisle Hart
stole the show: After everyone else had sung ``Happy Birthday'' off
key, she delivered a pitch-perfect solo rendition.
</P>
<P>
   A Bit Part For Giuliani
</P>
<P>
   ``What a good job you did of recreating my office,'' Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani said as he walked across the set of ``The Guiding
Light,'' the long-running soap opera. ``What do you want me to
do?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was, stand in front of the make-believe desk and
officiate at a make-believe wedding.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor did not have to say much. The script called for three
or four lines, and they rolled by on a teleprompter just out of
camera range.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani officiated at the groom's fifth marriage and the
bride's third. The bride used to be married to the groom's brother,
who is now married to her sister (who is living happily off camera,
having been written out of the script).
</P>
<P>
   This was probably not news to the mayor. ``I told him about some
of the story lines,'' said his press secretary, Colleen Roche. She
videotapes the hourlong program every day and watches a week's
worth of episodes on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Will the new marriage last?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got the blessing of Giuliani, so it will,'' said Ms.
Roche. To which Renee Young, a CBS executive, added, ``At least
through sweeps week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
