<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-ANTI-SEMITISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINIC IN BUFFALO RESUMES ABORTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Canada)  (Eds: See also ABORTION-VESTS) 
(mk) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ This city's last remaining abortion clinic
resumed performing the procedure Wednesday morning, five days after
its primary doctor was killed by a sniper.
</P>
<P>
   The clinic's staff said they expected to be able to continue
their work through the rest of the week with the assistance of
doctors from around the country who have offered to fill in for Dr.
Barnett Slepian, who was slain at his home in Amherst, a Buffalo
suburb, on Friday night. The staff provided no further details,
citing security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been seeing patients today,'' said Melinda DuBois,
director for Buffalo Women's Gynecological Services, a clinic that
specializes in abortions in one of this city's poorer
neighborhoods. ``Abortions have been performed.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite rumors that anti-abortion protesters would attempt to
halt work at the clinic Wednesday, the authorities reported no
disturbances here. A handful of volunteers, men and women dressed
in bright yellow vests that identified them as ``patient escorts,''
spent much of the day accompanying women in and out of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to help,'' said Jim Heller, a construction worker
who arrived early in the morning to provide protection for the
clinic's staff and clients. ``If you feel strong about this issue,
you should be here to help. That is why I am here.''
</P>
<P>
   Local and federal law enforcement officials reported no progress
Wednesday in their search for the sniper, who fired at Slepian from
a wooded field outside the doctor's home.
</P>
<P>
   The National Abortion Federation, an organization that
represents 350 clinics, and American and Canadian Jewish groups
raised the possibility that anti-Semitism might have motivated the
sniper or snipers responsible for shooting five doctors in Canada
and the United States since 1994. Four of the five doctors, the
federation said, are Jewish, confirming a report in Wednesday's
Buffalo News.
</P>
<P>
   The four are Dr. Garson Romalis, who was wounded on Nov. 8,
1994; a doctor in the Rochester area whose identity has been
concealed and who sustained minor cuts on Oct. 28, 1997; Dr. John
Fainman, who was struck by a bullet in the right shoulder on Nov.
11, 1997, in Winnipeg, Canada, and Slepian, the only fatality. The
fifth victim, Dr. Hugh Short, who was hit in the right elbow on
Nov. 10, 1995, in Ancaster, Ontario, is not Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Britell, the federation's director of government
relations, said the possibility that the doctors' religion was more
than coincidence ``should be looked into,'' particularly because
some anti-abortion groups have equated abortions in America with
the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that that is aimed at those physicians who happen to
be of Jewish descent,'' she said of the comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League,
said that while there was no evidence that the doctors were
attacked because they were Jewish _ there are a disproportionately
large number of Jewish doctors _ he was concerned about a strain of
anti-Semitism in one large anti-abortion group, Human Life
International.
</P>
<P>
   Foxman said that the group, which is based in Front Royal, Va.,
issued a 1993 report suggesting that Jews controlled the abortion
movement.
</P>
<P>
   Don Treshman, a spokesman for Human Life, acknowledged that the
group's founder, the Rev. Paul Marx, a Roman Catholic priest, had
made a statement several years ago that ``for some unknown reasons
a disproportionate number of abortionists are Jewish.'' But
Treshman said the statement was simply a ``startling observation''
and not anti-Semitic. He said his group condemned violence.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the clinic, a dark brown, brick building on Main Street
here, people continued to express frustration and loss. Karen
Jones, a 26-year-old mother of two, said Slepian's death was a huge
loss for the women in this poor end of town. But she said she was
glad to know that the clinic had resumed its work.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have been trying to shut the place down for
years,'' she said of anti-abortion protesters. ``But so long as
women need abortions, there will be abortions. Those can protest
all they want. It's not going to change things.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Clark, 27, expressed similar frustrations. She said women
would continue coming for abortions, as they have for many years,
despite the protests of anti-abortion groups that camp out here
almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women don't come here because they like having abortions,''
she said. ``They are here because they feel that they need to do
it. These people have no right to try and stop them. They should
just mind their own business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
