</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COLUMN-SCALPER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG CITY COLUMN: NEED A RE-ELECTION ISSUE? JUST JAIL A TICKET
SCALPER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jerry Nahay always figured that he, like many of his
fellow ticket scalpers, might one day play a role in the
re-election campaign of a New York state attorney general. But it
never occurred to him that he could be the first to go to prison in
the process.
</P>
<P>
   Nahay, 41, spent more than a decade running a company on West
33rd Street called Tickets on Request. He and his wife, Janet
Rosenblatt, sold tickets to concerts, Broadway shows and sporting
events. They got in trouble for charging whatever the market would
bear, which makes them, depending on your viewpoint, either greedy
outlaws or capitalist martyrs.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most states, which permit consenting adults to buy
tickets the same way they buy anything else, New York forbids
brokers from charging more than 10 percent above a ticket's face
value. The law appalls many economists, who say the price controls
hurt consumers. But it appeals to New Yorkers who blame scalpers
for profiting from inflated prices. And since scalping is one of
the few crimes under the jurisdiction of the attorney general that
attracts press attention, it has long appealed to holders of that
office campaigning for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The last two attorneys general, Robert Abrams and G. Oliver
Koppell, issued a torrent of press releases heralding their
crusades against scalpers, and the current officeholder, Dennis
Vacco, has gone them one better. Besides fining Nahay and other
ticket brokers for the misdemeanor of overcharging, Vacco singled
out Nahay for the first felony prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general used a legal strategy that could be
described, depending on your viewpoint, either as creative or
Kafkaesque. He charged Nahay with a crime no one knew existed.
</P>
<P>
   The ``crime'' was failing to collect the state sales tax on the
surcharges that Nahay added to the tickets. This tax has never been
collected even by law-abiding brokers _ who limit mark-ups to 10
percent _ because the surcharge was considered a service charge
exempt from tax.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general, however, persuaded a judge to apply a
different standard to Nahay. Acting Justice Carol Berkman of State
Supreme Court ruled that a surcharge below 10 percent was exempt,
but a surcharge above that was taxable. Her opinion did not
elucidate how she came to this distinction, or how anyone else
could have been expected to divine it.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Nahay and his wife were convicted on two felony
counts of tax evasion, which carry a maximum sentence of four years
in prison. So far they are still at large _ the prosecution's
request that they be jailed immediately upon conviction was denied
_ while they await sentencing and proceed with appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Their conviction mystified state legislators, who have been
considering a bill to impose sales taxes on ticket surcharges.
Assemblyman Steven Sanders wrote in support of the Nahays.
``Frankly,'' he wrote, ``I was amazed to learn of their conviction
of an offense which has not yet been enacted into law.''
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general says his novel approach is necessary
because mere fines aren't enough to deter criminals like Nahay.
``The resounding verdict in this case,'' he said in a press release
announcing Nahay's conviction, ``signals our increasing success in
pursuing felony charges against ticket chiselers.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Vacco's crusade, Nahay now commutes from his
Upper East Side home to his company's new office in New Jersey,
where dozens of brokers have fled to escape New York's price
controls. Nahay's move to North Bergen, aside from making it more
convenient for New Jerseyans to buy tickets to Broadway shows and
Knicks games, has cost New York six jobs and the corporate taxes
that he formerly paid in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been happy to pay sales taxes in New York, too,
if anybody had told me to,'' Nahay said. ``I knew Vacco was looking
for ink, but I never imagined he'd invent a felony charge to throw
us in jail. In any other industry I'd be considered a good
businessman, but instead I get my life turned upside down by the
government.''
</P>
<P>
   Nahay, who says the case has cost him $250,000, had been looking
forward to revenge next Tuesday: voting against Vacco. But this
week he gave that up. ``My lawyer just told me that I can't legally
vote,'' he said Wednesday. ``I'm now a convicted felon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
