<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USWEST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSING PHONE EQUIPMENT MAY MEAN MILLIONS IN US WEST OVERCHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a federal audit of US West and other Baby Bells is
completed in a few weeks, it will show that telephone equipment is
missing. A lot of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   According to congressional regulators who have seen preliminary
audit results, the five regional Baby Bells have claimed that they
have $5 billion more in telephone equipment than investigators can
find.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how much of that $5 billion is US West's share,
but if it turns out to be even no more than one-fifth of the
federal estimates for all five companies, it could have a sizeable
impact on Arizona's telephone rates.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona sets utility prices by pegging the company's profit to a
fair rate of return on its investment. US West claims $30 billion
in investment, and if it is shown to be claiming $1 billion more
than it has invested, it could mean that Arizona customers had been
overcharged by millions of dollars for years.
</P>
<P>
   US West disputes the audit results that it has seen. Spokesman
Jim Roof says the methodology of the Federal Communications
Commission is flawed.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC investigated 33 switching offices, there are 225 in
Arizona, and determined that 18 percent of the items on the
company's equipment lists is missing, according to Roof.
</P>
<P>
   US West followed up the FCC audit with its own study, but found
that less than 2 percent of the items at more than 1,000 switching
stations didn't turn up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that's a pretty good margin of error,'' Roof said.
</P>
<P>
   US West also is concerned that the FCC hasn't been willing to
accept the additional data the phone company has offered, Roof
said.
</P>
<P>
   An FCC spokeswoman would not comment on the audit, saying it is
confidential until the full commission votes to make it public.
</P>
<P>
   The audit, expected by the end of this month, will be slightly
delayed, sources said. All sides, meanwhile, are anxiously awaiting
the results.
</P>
<P>
   Arizonans for Competition in Telephone Service, a US West
watchdog group of competing telephone firms, has been monitoring
its progress, spokesman Jon Poston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be very concerned if a federal audit showed that any
telephone company serving Arizona was requiring its customers to
pay for non-existent equipment,'' Poston said. ``We don't know
whether that's true or not, but we'll be watching very carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are billions of dollars at stake for ratepayers,'' said
Gene Kimmelman, spokesman for the Consumers Union in Washington,
D.C. ``If there is equipment on the books that doesn't exist or
isn't being used to process phone calls, that needs to be
rectified.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation is particularly ticklish for Arizonans now. US
West is scheduled to request an adjustment of rates by the end of
this year, although the company's not saying whether it will ask
for an increase in any portion of its prices. And because Arizona
is a state that determines prices by setting a fair rate of return,
or profit, on the total dollar amount of a utility company's
investment in providing telephone service, a federal challenge to
the company's investment claims could be disruptive to its rate
request.
</P>
<P>
   US West is allowed to earn 11.4 percent on its investment. If
that total investment amount were inflated by phantom equipment
costs, it would be earning more than the Arizona Corporation
Commission had authorized, all at the expense of its telephone
customers. &QL; 
Adrianne Flynn can be reached at (202) 662-7262 or at
adrianne.flynn(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
