<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-HMO-TAKEOVER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY MOVES TO TAKE REINS OF TROUBLED HMO 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ In a move that highlighted regulatory questions
with health maintenance organizations, New Jersey officials have
moved to take over the operation of HIP Health Plan of New Jersey,
after it appeared to be sliding into insolvency and was
experiencing problems paying its health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   In taking the relatively drastic step to rescue the state's
fourth-largest HMO and to insure that its 194,000 clients would
continue to have health care coverage, Gov. Christie Whitman said
through a spokesman that it was also time for the state to explore
additional measures ``to create a safety net'' for health consumers
in the state.
</P>
<P>
   She said Wednesday that she would soon ask Legislative leaders
to look into the possibility of creating a ``guaranty fund'' for
insolvent health maintenance organizations, similar to funds that
handle claims against automobile and casualty insurers when they go
out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Winnie Comfort, a spokeswoman for the Department of Banking and
Insurance, which along with the state Department of Health and
Senior Services regulates HMOs, said that the move to take over HIP
was the first such move by the state under a year-old law
regulating the companies.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Comfort said that state's concerns about HIP's operations
dated back many years but intensified in June when the quarterly
reports they are required to file showed them running a $9.5
million deficit.
</P>
<P>
   When the next quarter's reports showed the deficit growing to
$20 million, the state stepped in, she said. If approved by a judge
in Middlesex County, the county in which HIP's New Brunswick
headquarters is located, all contracts and assets will be frozen,
giving HIP time to reorganize.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest loser in the state's move to take over the
HMO is Pinnacle Health Enterprises, which last November purchased
HIP's 23 health centers, paid off much of its debt and, with state
approval, entered into a 20-year contract with the insurer to
exclusively provide all of the medical services for its members. In
exchange, Pinnacle was supposed to receive 91.5 percent of the
insurance premium revenue collected by HIP
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth H. Weixel, executive vice president of the PHP
Healthcare Corp., Pinnacle's parent company, said that PHP had
invested $140 million in the arrangement so far and stood to lose
all of it under the proposed takeover because the state was asking
a court to terminate the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at our legal remedies but we are going to fight
this,'' Weixel said.
</P>
<P>
   Pinnacle, which had revenues of $550 million last year, could be
required to continue to provide medical services for at least a
year under terms set by the state, and not by its contract with HIP
</P>
<P>
   Officials at HIP had no comment on the state move to takeover
their operations except to say that they were reviewing their
options.
</P>
<P>
   The state's action seems aimed at new organizations being
spawned by the growing managed care industry _ separate entities
that split medical care and provider recruitment from billing,
marketing and regulatory requirements. In the year since Pinnacle
started doing everything from providing doctors to paying hospitals
for HIP, state regulators have sought to monitor the company. But
under state law, direct authority is limited to the insurer, HIP,
not the health provider, Pinnacle.
</P>
<P>
   Jayne O'Connor, a spokesman for Whitman, said five states _
Alabama, Florida, Illinois, Vermont and West Virginia _ have
separate guaranty funds for HMOs. Nine other states, including New
York and Connecticut, require their health insurers to pool their
money in guaranty funds that cover all regulated insurers,
including casualty and property companies, in those states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
