<SLUG> BC-FBC-FBCCOL-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENTLEMEN, START YOUR GRUMBLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now we know why they waited until late October to release the
first Bowl Championship Series poll: It gives college coaches only
half a season to complain about the results.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches would gratefully take a full season to question the
validity of the rankings, which determine which schools will play
in the Fiesta Bowl for the national championship on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   To no one's surprise, the first complaints came from Kansas
State coach and noted grumbler Bill Snyder. Snyder's Wildcats are
7-0 but fourth in the BCS rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just the formula itself and I guess I just don't
understand what it's all about yet,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder was put off by the power ratings, which include
computerized formulas by the New York Times, USA Today and Seattle
Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seattle Times? I mean, give me a break. Why is it the
Seattle Times as opposed to the Manhattan (Kan.) Mercury? What
makes the Seattle Times capable of selecting opponents for the
national championship?'' Snyder asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. It could be just out of ignorance on my part,
not knowing enough about it that makes it uncertain in my mind
whether it's good or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Snyder forgot to mention that if Kansas State had
played a tougher nonconference schedule, he wouldn't be wondering
why the Seattle Times plays a role in the BCS formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just confusing with all the different places that have a
role in the selection process, and I'm not sure if that's good, bad
or indifferent,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   At Ohio State, coach John Cooper seemed to think ignoring the
poll was the best route. Especially since the Buckeyes were
surprisingly ranked No.2 behind UCLA, although they remain No. 1 in
both top-25 polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have time to sit down and figure out all the rankings,
how they're determined and who's doing them,'' Ohio State coach
John Cooper said. ``I put more stock in the coaches poll and the AP
poll than I do anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody better tell Cooper that Ohio State could win the rest
of its games and conceivably finish out of the top two spots in the
BCS rankings.
</P>
<P>
   It's ironic that the Big Ten is seemingly hurt by the first BCS
poll. The conference sought the strength-of-schedule formula after
Penn State went 12-0 in 1994 and didn't win the national title.
</P>
<P>
   ```I don't believe in second-guessing. We knew it could
happen,'' Big Ten commissioner Jim Delany said. ``The odds were
small. You won't hear a complaint from me, I'll tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ All-Big-Ten Rose Bowl?: How does an Ohio State-Wisconsin Rose
Bowl sound this year?
</P>
<P>
   It's possible. If Wisconsin represents the Big Ten as champion,
and Ohio State should fall out of the top two spots in the BCS
rankings while UCLA stays there, the Rose Bowl conceivably could
pick Ohio State to replace the Pac-10 champs and have an All-Big
Ten matchup, as strange as that would be.
</P>
<P>
   If Ohio State and Wisconsin tie for the Big Ten title, the
Badgers go to Pasadena because they last reached the Rose Bowl in
1993. Ohio State represented the conference in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The teams do not play each other this season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bad timing: Imagine this. San Diego State ends a 12-year
drought and wins the WAC but then is denied an invitation to the
Holiday Bowl in its own backyard because of that game's new
selection procedure.
</P>
<P>
   It will match the Pac-10 Conference No. 2 with the highest
ranking of two choices _ the Big 12 No. 3 or the WAC champion. San
Diego State hasn't even received top-25 consideration while the Big
12 has had five or six teams ranked for most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ground attack: Check out the nation's top three rushing
offense leaders: 1. Air Force. 2. Navy. 3. Army.
</P>
<P>
   __ Two to go: Oklahoma's John Blake probably sealed his fate
with the Sooners' 41-26 loss at Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   It's only the seventh time in history the Sooners have lost to
Oklahoma State and Texas in the same season. The last three
Oklahoma coaches with 0-for-OSU-and-Texas seasons: Snorter Luster
(1944-45), Gomer Jones (1965) and John Blake (1997-98).
</P>
<P>
   Clemson coach Tommy West will probably join Blake out the door,
especially after the Tigers lost to Duke 28-23, assuring Clemson
(2-6) of a losing season.
</P>
<P>
   West is now 34-33 at Clemson, with a 21-17 mark in the ACC. This
will be the second losing season in five years for the Tigers, who
must win their remaining three games in order to avoid their worst
record in 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   One coach who might survive _ believe it or not _ is Hawaii's
Fred vonAppen, 0-7 this season and 5-26 in two years on the island
of Oahu. Apparently he has job security because he was hired by his
old Linfield College teammate, Rainbows athletic director Hugh
Yoshida. And it was Yoshida who, 11 months ago, pushed through a
two-year contract extension for vonAppen, through 2000.
</P>
<P>
   __ Wise move: West Virginia lineman Jeremy Sherman probably made
the prudent decision when he selected the Mountaineers over his
second choice, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman is the great-great grandson of famed Union general
William Tecumseh Sherman, who is a reviled figure in the South, and
especially Georgia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
