<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DANCER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DANCER'S HESITANT PAS DE DEUX WITH CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By MIRTA OJITO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After 24 years with the New York City Ballet, the
last 14 as a principal dancer, Lourdes Lopez knows how to move her
lithe body gracefully. She understands harmony and movement, pacing
and breathing. Yet here she is, painfully stretching her calves,
puffing like a novice, sweat beads dampening her taut chest.
</P>
<P>
   One year into retirement, at 40, Ms. Lopez says her body is out
of shape. But these days, even if she can tame the body and still
arch her back just so, it is her mind that is playing tricks.
</P>
<P>
   For, no matter how hard she tries, she cannot get one thought
out of her mind: In less than a week she will be dancing in Cuba,
the country of her birth and of her adult obsessions. It is also
the country her parents fled in 1959, fearing for their lives. Ms.
Lopez's father had been a captain in the army led by Fulgencio
Batista, the dictator whom Fidel Castro and his bearded rebels
deposed in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lopez, who left Cuba in her mother's arms as a 10-month-old
baby, returned to Cuba for the first time in December as a cultural
reporter for WNBC-TV, Channel 4, for which she has been freelancing
since she left the ballet company. During that visit, she
interviewed Alicia Alonso, the grande dame of Cuban ballet whom Ms.
Lopez had long admired from afar.
</P>
<P>
   After the interview, Ms. Alonso asked her to return to Cuba to
perform during Havana's International Festival of Ballet, set to
begin next week. Ms. Lopez, who in the past had toyed with the idea
of dancing in Cuba but had always decided against it, quickly said
yes. She picked a ballet that she had always liked and that would
be easy on her knees and began rehearsing at Ballet Academy East, a
school on the Upper East Side where she also teaches.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, she says, she is training for the most important
role of her life; not as a dancer, but as a Cuban exile who, she
explains, wants to use her art to help build a bridge between her
two worlds, Cuba and the United States, and between her two
sentimental homes, the Cuba of her imagination and the country Cuba
has truly become.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want them to think of me as a dancer,'' she said,
admitting to insecurity about her audience's reaction. ``If I
wanted that I would have gone seven years ago when I could jump and
leap. Now, I want them to see me as a Cuban with a purpose. If I
were a doctor, I'd go and do surgery. But dancing is what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lopez says she felt a need to contribute in some way the day
she arrived in Havana a year ago. ``For the first time,'' she said,
``I felt I belonged somewhere. Before that trip, the dance
community was my only home. But when I got to Cuba, I said: `This
is it. This is home.' I cried every night in my hotel room. People
said it was stress, but I knew better. I can't tell you what
happened, but it changed my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Ms. Lopez says, she also realized she could not live in
Cuba. A divorced mother of an 8-year-old girl who lives in
Brooklyn, Ms. Lopez says she cannot imagine living with so many
scarcities and restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   She decided to accept Ms. Alonso's invitation now because she no
longer has anything to lose or to prove, she says. In the past, she
had always discarded the idea because she feared that it would
offend her parents and hurt her career. Some artists who have
performed in Cuba have been harshly criticized by exiles who do not
condone travel to the island while Castro is in power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't I at least try to go around it and deal with the
people directly and help them in whatever small ways I can?'' she
asks. ``People like me are the only ones who can do it. We are the
last generation that deeply cares about Cuba and has the means to
actually do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The depth of Ms. Lopez's feelings for Cuba is unusual for a
woman who has lived nearly her entire life outside the island. She
grew up in Miami, where she began studying ballet at 5 because she
had flat feet and her doctor recommended exercise. Her problem was
corrected, but Ms. Lopez, who by then was in love with ballet, kept
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she was 14, Ms. Lopez had moved to New York with an
older sister to pursue her dancing career. Shortly after her 16th
birthday, she began dancing for New York City Ballet, where she
stayed until June of last year. Critics called her a dancer with
flair and intensity.
</P>
<P>
   For her trip to Cuba, she chose ``Pavane for a Dead Princess,''
a ballet created by George Balanchine for Patricia McBride, a
former colleague who has allowed Ms. Lopez to use it. Throughout
the piece, Ms. Lopez fingers a long scarf that sometimes hides her
face, seemingly in tears, as she raises her hands, imploring. Free
of the scarf for part of the performance, she soars, only to end as
she began, her head covered, her hands concealing tears.
</P>
<P>
   After rehearsal one day, Ms. Lopez was asked why she had picked
that ballet. She said that she had always liked it and it seemed
appropriate for this stage in her career. But a few days later Ms.
Lopez called to say that, as she rode in the subway on her way home
one night, the real reason why she had picked the piece all of a
sudden leapt into her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how it begins, a solitary figure center stage,
wrapped in a long veil?'' she asks. ``Well, it occurred to me that,
oddly enough, this ballet is like Cuba. Like Cuba, I'm raising my
hands to whatever, government or God, and I'm imploring. I'm
saying: `Do something. I'm isolated. I'm by myself, buried down
here.' But no one comes, and, in the end, I'm back under the wraps,
crying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-28-98 2359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
